<P>
   CT-POLICE-SHOOTING (New Milford, Conn.) _ Only a couple of
months ago, the future seemed so promising for Officer Scott Smith.
He had been filling in for a detective and showing the brass what
he could do. He had passed the all the tests of the Connecticut
State Police and hoped to become a trooper in training this summer.
But that was before he became the first police officer to be
charged with murder for shooting a criminal suspect.
</P>
<P>
   STEM-CELL-RESEARCH (Undated) _ In a letter, 70 members of
Congress have asked the secretary of Health and Human Services to
rescind a ruling that federal funds may be used for research on
human embryonic stem cells, the primordial cells from which all the
tissues of the body are developed. By Nicholas Wade.
</P>
<P>
   DARTMOUTH-FRATS (Hanover, N.H.) _ The campus of Dartmouth
College is in an uproar over school administrators' plan to
eliminate the traditional fraternity and sorority system. The move
has underscored a vast social gulf that divides the Ivy League
campus. By Carey Goldberg.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Photos [NYT18,19) have been sent to NYT photo
clients.)
</P>
<P>
   CONGRESSMAN-MEETING (Anderson, S.C.) _ Didn't Lindsey Graham get
the memo? Republicans, freed at last from the months-long
impeachment ordeal in Washington, are supposed to be following a
``pivot strategy,'' wherein they shuck the scandal and delve into
real issues that affect real people. But Graham, the folksy
Southerner who soared to national attention on the wings of
impeachment and cable television, is not inclined just yet to move
on. By Katharine Q. Seelye.
</P>
<P>
   BERKELEY-KERR (Berkeley, Calif.) _ The students milling around
the entrance gate at the University of California here take little
notice of Clark Kerr as he passes by on a mild winter afternoon, a
balding emeritus professor in a wool sports jacket and
comfortable-looking black shoes. Three decades ago, he would not
have escaped their attention. In the 1960s, Clark Kerr was at the
center of the cultural hurricane that engulfed virtually every
American campus, and he paid for it with his job. Gov. Ronald
Reagan and the California Board of Regents dismissed him as
president of the university, saying he had been too lenient with
the protesters in the Free Speech Movement at Berkeley. By Karen W.
Arenson.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Photo [NYT13) has been sent to NYT photo clients.)
