A8009 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CAR-DAYTONA-ART-NYT &LR;      02-17 0649
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAR-DAYTONA-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REVVED-UP APPEAL: GORDON WHIRLS INTO TOWN
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(nk) 
 By TARIK EL-BASHIR   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Jeff Gordon's daring pass of Rusty Wallace last
Sunday will be remembered as the defining moment of one of the most
thrilling Daytona 500 races ever. The maneuver, at 190 mph, showed
the fearlessness and talent that has enabled Gordon to win three
Winston Cup championships, including the last two in a row.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've never had so many people say: `Man, what a great race.
That was best race I've ever seen,' '' Gordon said Tuesday in
Manhattan. ``Everyone from David Letterman to the guy who runs the
elevator here at the Waldorf-Astoria has been talking about it. It
was absolutely the biggest win of my career by far.''
</P>
<P>
   Gordon was in Manhattan celebrating his second Daytona 500
victory, his 43rd career Winston Cup victory. On Monday, he made a
guest appearance on Letterman's show and received an ESPY for the
1998 driver of the year at ESPN's award ceremony, where Gordon was
congratulated by George Steinbrenner and Mark McGwire.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was really cool for me to be a part of a race like that,''
Gordon said of holding off his biggest rival, Dale Earnhardt, over
the final laps. ``And especially to be the one to win a race as
exciting as that. This was like Jordan vs. Magic. And Jordan hit a
30-foot jumper to win the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now I've done something like that. This year's win definitely
tops 1997.''
</P>
<P>
   The Nascar season could not have got off to a better start for
Gordon: winning 1999's first race in his sport's biggest event. But
it has also seen the return of the same old questions. Is Gordon's
success a reflection of an outstanding driver, or does he simply
have the best equipment?
</P>
<P>
   It is a question that won't go away, in part, because not
everyone is convinced that Gordon's skill is the biggest factor in
his team's victories.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think he's a better driver than Mark Martin or Dale
Earnhardt,'' Jack Roush, the owner of Martin's Valvoline Ford
Taurus, said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think that his program is better. Jeff may break all of
Richard Petty's records, but the reason Mark isn't beating him more
is because I haven't given Mark a good enough program.''
</P>
<P>
   Roush, who accused Gordon of driving on illegal tires last
season after he outran Martin at Pocono, said: ``I don't think Jeff
has ever been in a bad race car. He's in a great, great position.
If I put Mark in the type of program Jeff has, I think Mark would
beat Jeff more than Jeff would beat Mark. Jeff is not as involved
with the hardware as Mark and Dale have been. So it makes you
wonder.''
</P>
<P>
   Martin, who was involved in a 12-car wreck that eliminated him
from contention last Sunday, was the runner-up to Gordon in 1998.
Martin figures to be there again when this season's championship is
decided this year. Some have called Roush a sore loser. Some agree
with him. Gordon says, ``that's just racing.''
</P>
<P>
   It is no secret that Gordon often has the top car in the field.
He also has the best team, headed by one of the best crew chiefs in
the business, Ray Evernham.
</P>
<P>
   ``I felt like I had one of the best cars,'' Gordon said. ``I had
some problems with the handling. I think because I did not have any
help, I was never in a position to show how good my car was until
the last 10 laps. I had to do it by myself.''
</P>
<P>
   The fact that Gordon did not get any aerodynamic assistance from
his competitors _ it rarely pays to help the fastest car in the
field _ until he got a push from Earnhardt on the final laps,
supports the argument that Gordon does play a major role in getting
the No. 24 DuPont Chevy to Victory Lane, somewhere his car figures
to be parked very often this season.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
