<HEADLINE>
COMMENTARY : HILLARY THINKS, RUDY WAITS, PUNDITS YEARN
</HEADLINE>
  (See related NY-MRSCLINTON) 
 (nk) 
 By GAIL COLLINS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   New York, at least, has figured out how to fill the
post-impeachment political gossip void. Hillary Clinton for Senate!
</P>
<P>
   ``She says, `Charlie, I just want you to know I'm considering
this very, very seriously,''' reported Rep. Charles Rangel of
Manhattan, chief broker of the idea that the first lady might run
for the seat being vacated by Daniel Patrick Moynihan in 2000.
``She says that in all kind of different and charming ways.''
</P>
<P>
   There are probably a number of states in which party regulars
might be offended by the idea of turning over a plum so sweet as a
nomination for an open Senate seat to an outsider. But New York
Democrats have a different mentality. Rangel, in fact, was outraged
when he heard a rumor that Mrs. Clinton might run in Illinois, a
state where she has actually lived.
</P>
<P>
   ``I went to her and said: `You can be senator from Vermont or
Rhode Island or Illinois, but being senator from New York is
different,''' he explained. ``Equal isn't always equal.''
</P>
<P>
   The idea of running Mrs. Clinton for the Senate while her
husband is still in the White House was born of a mixture of great
production values and political desperation. Democrats believe that
New York City's Republican mayor, Rudolph Giuliani, is eyeing
Moynihan's seat. To win statewide races, Democrats generally have
to roll up huge majorities in New York City and avoid getting
beaten too badly in the surrounding suburbs. Giuliani is the
darling of Long Island and Westchester County, and he might be
expected to hold on to at least his core constituency in the city's
white ethnic neighborhoods.
</P>
<P>
   But the one person better known and perhaps better liked than
the fractious Giuliani is the feisty Ms. Clinton. The president and
first lady may be controversial in some parts of the country, but
in New York their approval ratings are at levels normally reserved
for politicians who have won a world war. True, Mrs. Clinton does
not live in New York, but then the first lady, whose voting address
is her mother's home in Arkansas, does not seem to specifically
live anywhere. ``She lives on TV,'' says one local political
consultant. Her endless trips to New York to campaign for Charles
Schumer for Senate (and against her old nemesis Alfonse D'Amato)
have probably involved more overnight stays than Connecticut's
James Buckley logged when he successfully ran for the Senate here,
explaining that his Manhattan office was also his home.
</P>
<P>
   Rangel proudly announced that the contentious and near-bankrupt
New York Democratic Party had ``pulled together an offer that the
first lady can't refuse,'' including a guarantee that the
nomination would be hers for the asking, without a primary. Later
he explained that the party's power to insure Mrs. Clinton a free
ride was based on the theory that ``you can always promise no
primary to an 800-pound gorilla.'' So far, everyone seems to agree,
including the Democrat regarded as the most likely Senate candidate
presently residing within the confines of New York state. ``If the
first lady decides to run, she'll clear the field,'' said Rep. Nita
Lowey of Westchester, demonstrating her own political skills
Tuesday by conducting an interview via cell phone while walking
through airport security.
</P>
<P>
   The idea of a race between Rudolph Giuliani and Hillary Clinton
is so tasty that even the first hints of a speculation of a
possibility created headlines. Now that Mrs. Clinton is officially
considering the idea, political junkies are in a full-blown frenzy.
This is the sort of contest that election aficionados live for. It
could actually overshadow the presidential contest. (Which debate
would you listen to, Clinton-Giuliani or Gore-Bush?)
</P>
<P>
   The cable channels that have been thriving on all-Monica formats
for the last year could easily divert their talking heads to a
discussion of who would have more trouble adjusting to the Senate _
the authoritarian Giuliani or the wife of the man half the senators
voted to toss out of office. On the campaign trail, the first lady
might have to face some embarrassing questions about the state of
her marriage. But Giuliani, whose wife declined to say whom she had
voted for in the last mayoral election, has pretty much broken the
New York press corps of the habit of trying to poke into a
politician's private life.
</P>
<P>
   The mayor, a lifelong New Yorker and the state's best-known
resident, is by no means as assured of his party's nomination as
Mrs. Clinton would be of hers. Allies of Gov. George Pataki, a
Republican, are not necessarily entranced by the idea of having
Giuliani as a candidate, and he might have to run a primary for the
nomination, possibly against the moderate but more housebroken
Republican from Long Island, Rep. Rick Lazio. In fact, the
Clinton-Giuliani race that New Yorkers were imagining Tuesday could
morph very quickly into Lowey vs. Lazio on Wednesday. And then what
will the cable channels do?
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
