<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PUBLIC-LIVES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IMPEACHMENT FADES FAST  
 WILL THE ROLE FIT?  
 THE ART RACKET
</HEADLINE>
   (nk) 
 BY JAMES BARRON with COREY KILGANNON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Being one of President Clinton's personal lawyers was not enough
to get David E. Kendall into Comedy Cellar, a club at 117 Macdougal
Street, less than 12 hours after the Senate trial ended on Friday.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were late,'' said Kendall, who had taken a Metroliner to
New York from Washington on Friday, ``and our reservations were
gone.'' He and the friends with whom he had seen ``Rent'' earlier
in the evening ended up at a nearby club, Cafe Wha.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was good to get out of Washington and not be here,'' he
said Tuesday from his desk at the law firm of Williams &AMP; Connolly,
adding that he was ``blasting through the paper that's piled up.''
</P>
<P>
   The main White House counsel, Charles F.C. Ruff, was also at his
desk Tuesday. ``He's going to see some spring training in March in
Vero Beach,'' a White House spokesman said. ``The only possible
time off.''
</P>
<P>
   With the trial over, what about late-night talk shows that made
the president and Monica Lewinsky a long-running punch line?
</P>
<P>
   ``Unfortunately, we have three months of jokes already on the
cue cards,'' quipped Rob Burnett, the executive producer of ``Late
Show with David Letterman,'' ``so we have to keep going until at
least May.''
</P>
<P>
   Seriously, now: What will Letterman lampoon from now on?
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know,'' Burnett said. ``We have to sit back and wait
until the next bone-headed thing happens. That should only take 24
to 48 hours.''
</P>
<P>
   Will the Role Fit?
</P>
<P>
   Johnnie L. Cochran Jr. has a new client, Annie Dutton.
</P>
<P>
   Cochran, who defended O.J. Simpson and is one of the lawyers
representing the family of Amadou Diallo, the African immigrant
killed by plainclothes officers in the Bronx on Feb. 4, is
scheduled to join Ms. Dutton's legal team at a taping of ``The
Guiding Light'' Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Never mind that she is a soap-opera character charged with
stealing a corpse, among other things. And never mind that some
viewers might say he is blurring the line between fiction and
reality. ``I don't think anybody believes I'm going to be doing
that for any period of time,'' he said. ``I've got so much real
work to do I can't do this very often.''
</P>
<P>
   All he will have to do is follow the script, which is probably a
good thing, considering that he was in Los Angeles on Tuesday and
was scheduled to catch a 10 p.m. flight to New York. ``I'm going to
try to stay awake for the taping,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The Art Racket
</P>
<P>
   The word on the street _ Grand Street, in SoHo _ was that John
McEnroe had decided to shut down his art gallery. But McEnroe says
that is not exactly so. It is not going to be open to the walk-in
trade any longer, which will make it off limits to weekend browsers
who might want to see what a celebrity like McEnroe considers good
art.
</P>
<P>
   ``The problem is, I kept winning on the senior tennis circuit,''
he said yesterday. And, as he noted, ``Art hasn't done
one-thousandth of what tennis has done for me.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, McEnroe said he planned to ``scale down, re-evaluate and
figure out my game plan'' so he could ``level the playing field''
and compete with art dealers who may or may not pepper their
conversations with sports metaphors the way he does.
</P>
<P>
   He was asked, politely, if there had been any tantrums over the
idea that he had been anything less than successful in the art
business.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think I've been unsuccessful,'' he said. ``I just
haven't been able to find the younger artists to bring along like
you'd coach a young tennis player.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-17-99 0015EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
