<DOCNO> NYT19990217.0010 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-17 00:16 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8026 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RIO-SAMBA-920(2TAKES)     02-17 0956
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RIO-SAMBA-920(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CRITIC'S NOTEBOOK: WHEN EVERYONE'S A STAR, IT MUST BE CARNIVAL IN
RIO
</HEADLINE>
 (nk) 
By JON PARELES   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   RIO DE JANEIRO, Brazil _ In the plaza of Largo da Prainha do Sao
Francisco, where slaves were once sold, a huge wall painting shows
a samba singer holding sheet music for the first recorded samba,
``On the Telephone,'' from 1916. It was in downtown neighborhoods
like this, where Africans and Afro-Brazilians from Bahia met Rio
society, that samba took hold in Brazilian culture. On Thursday,
the eve of this year's Carnival, Eliane Costa looked up at the
mural and said: ``Samba is still very similar to when it was born.
In its essence, it has not changed.''
</P>
<P>
   Wearing sunglasses and a headset microphone, she plugged in an
electrified cavaquinho _ the small samba guitar _ and began
strumming and singing with her group, Slaves of Maua. One member
gave out copies of the lyrics. Soon the musicians climbed onto a
sound truck, a dozen drummers fell in line behind them, and a small
parade wound its way through back streets up to the plaza of Maua.
</P>
<P>
   As followers shimmied and strutted and quickstepped, while
people on the sidewalk waved and let loose steps of their own, the
parade snagged traffic on one of downtown Rio's busiest streets,
Rio Branco. ``Whoever thought the fire would go out,'' sang the
Slaves of Maua, ``can still hear our voice.''
</P>
<P>
   During Carnival, which ended Tuesday, the Tuesday before Lent,
the samba takes over Rio on levels great and small. There are
neighborhood groups or blocos, like Slaves of Maua, and casual
brass bands called bandas. There are blocos de enredo, groups that
mount small costumed processions in official all-night parades on
avenues like Rio Branco. And there are the spectacular, gargantuan
sambas de enredo, pageants that play for paying audiences and
television cameras at the Sambodromo, the concrete street flanked
by bleachers that presents the image of Rio's Carnival to the
world. The Sambodromo is near Praca Once, where ``On the
Telephone'' was written.
</P>
<P>
   Four nights after the Slaves of Maua took to the streets,
Mangueira, the oldest and most traditional samba school in Rio,
mounted its parade at the Sambodromo. Its song proclaimed ``A
Century of Samba'' and paid homage to ``On the Telephone.'' Floats
four stories high had towering statues depicting major figures in
Brazilian music, and between them came thousands of shimmying,
costumed dancers in sequins and feathers. The bateria, a group of
hundreds of drummers playing with exact discipline, pounded out the
combination of heartbeat and march and chattering cross-rhythms
that is samba. It might have seemed an odd place for a history
lesson. But samba is as much about historical memory as it is about
spectacle. ``Human intelligence has the capacity to create many
layers,'' said Joaosinho Trinta, the carivalesco _ conceptualizer
and director _ for the Viradouro samba school.
</P>
<P>
   In 1937, as the samba was becoming Brazil's national music, the
revolutionary turned dictator Getulio Vargas decreed that official
carnival sambas should be based on historical, didactic or
patriotic themes. It is a practice that has carried through the
decades: At this year's carnival, there were songs extolling the
state of Minas Gerais and the cities of Natal and Joao Pessoa;
there were also tributes to people, including a communications
magnate and a diplomat.
</P>
<P>
   The samba school Imperatriz Leopoldinense commemorated a Dutch
naturalist who cataloged Brazil's flora and fauna. Rosa Magalhaes,
the group's carnivalesca, summed up her hopes for the audience: ``I
want them to be happy,'' she said. ``I want them to think it was
beautiful. And I want them to know the story.''
</P>
<P>
   When the samba schools parade, pedagogy turns into delirious
spectacle, with images multiplied and repeated by the huge forces
that the samba schools can muster.
</P>
<P>
   Mocidades turned its tribute to the classical composer Heitor
Villa-Lobos, who drew on Brazilian folk and popular music, into a
celebration of Brazil's wildlife and folklore: parrots and leopards
and butterflies, demons and skeletons. And as the samba by
Caprichosos de Pilares praised the plastic surgeon Ivo Pitanguy,
members paraded with giant syringes and oxygen tanks attached to
their shoulders.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever the subject, sambas de enredo are about abundance, with
thousands of dancing people wearing acres of shiny material and so
many feathers it's hard to believe an unplucked peacock survives
anywhere. During the samba parades, there are moments when the
2,000-foot-long parade ground is an uninterrupted sea of people.
Tributes to places invariably celebrate the local resources and
cuisine, from seafood to coffee to guava paste. And the historical
sambas are variations on a complex story: what happened when
indigenous tribes, Europeans and Africans ended up in the same
tropical landscape.
</P>
<P>
   It's not just that Indian costumes are a good excuse for
feathered headdresses. The Viradouro school used a tribute to Anita
Garibaldi, the Brazilian wife of the Italian patriot Giuseppe
Garibaldi, to praise the contributions of native Brazilians,
Africans, Europeans and Asians, with floats depicting everything
from the Hindu deity Ganesh to a Roman colonnade. Viradouro's
carnivalesco, Trinta, said before Carnival, ``We are a culture of
mixing, and this mixing is very positive. The collective
unconscious of Brazil is made of the experiences of all the peoples
that arrived here. Imagine that human DNA is like a memory chip.
Brazil has so many different chips that it is like a
state-of-the-art computer.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Of course, the abundance being celebrated is paradoxical. The
core members of the samba schools are the urban poor who live in
the hillside slums called favelas. Samba is a celebration of their
resilience and energy, and carnival's exuberance presents a spirit
undaunted by Brazil's recent currency devaluation or other crises.
``We rise above these problems,'' Trinta said. ``And we show that a
population without education or technology is capable of producing
a work of art like a samba school.''
</P>
<P>
   The sambas de enredo, nearly a year in preparation, are not
topical like carnival songs are in places like Trinidad or Haiti.
Yet the venerable samba school Portela, paying tribute to the state
of Minas Gerais, had a touch of topicality when a character on a
float brandished a briefcase that read ``Moratorio'' _ a pointed
reference to demands by the governor of Minas Gerais for a
moratorium on his state's debt repayments to Brazil's federal
government, which helped trigger the currency devaluation.
Street-level sambas showed a touch of protest; one group sang about
the national debt, declaring, ``Bring the bill that I won't pay.''
</P>
<P>
   The blocos de enredo, pulling small homemade floats, were more
hopeful; one had a sign that thanked everyone struggling for world
peace. And without television cameras or stadium lights, they still
belted out the songs and danced with pure elation.
</P>
<P>
   When the top carnival groups were moved to the Sambodromo, part
of Rio's carnival was taken out of the streets. But a neighborhood
group can draw the same frenetic, joyful response as the
razzle-dazzle productions in the Sambodromo. Samba demands audience
participation, and a band, a song and a beat can start a street
party almost instantly _ a shouting, singing, dancing mass of
people that spills onto sidewalks and engulfs passers-by. Confetti
and streamers are tossed; spray cans of white foam are spritzed
into the air, and there's the jumble of masquerades everywhere.
</P>
<P>
   Certain groups have themes. Carmelitas' followers, male and
female, danced in the headgear of Carmelite nuns. The Banda de
Ipanema has a large transvestite contingent who this year dressed
like anyone from Carmen Miranda to Monica Lewinsky. Across the
city, many people joined carnival processions dressed as Tiazinha,
a masked, whip-wielding young woman who hosts a variety show on
television. When Tiazinha herself appeared at the Sambodromo with
the school called Tradicao (Tradition), the audience roared.
</P>
<P>
   But in or out of the Sambodromo, carnival wasn't about watching
stars _ it was about being one. In the samba-school parades, masses
of people group themselves by costume, but coexist in happy
anarchy. Without rows or ranks or assigned steps, people strut or
twirl, let loose with fancy footwork or throw kisses to the crowd.
And on the streets, wherever the samba beat started, it was an
invitation to turn tradition and history into pleasure.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
