<SLUG> BC-INSURANCE-ACQUISITION-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BIG BERMUDA INSURER ACQUIRING U.S. INSURER 
</HEADLINE>
 
(ATTN: Conn.) (nk) 
 By JOSEPH B. TREASTER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   HAMILTON, Bermuda _ XL Capital Ltd., one of the leaders in
providing insurance against huge corporate losses, announced here
Tuesday that it was buying the NAC Re Corp., an insurer based in
Greenwich, Conn., greatly expanding its reach into the American
market.
</P>
<P>
   The price, XL Capital officials said, is $1.25 billion,
including $200 million in NAC Re debt.
</P>
<P>
   NAC Re, with big corporate as well as small-business clients,
offers both reinsurance _ insurance that backs up the coverage of
other insurers _ and insurance sold directly to businesses.
</P>
<P>
   XL Capital, a 13-year-old company, has grown rapidly through
acquisitions and offerings of high-level coverage. Its clients
include some of the world's biggest corporations whose executives
either travel to the insurer's Bermuda headquarters to conduct
business or work through subsidiaries in London.
</P>
<P>
   Now, it is buying what Ronald W. Frank, an analyst at Salomon
Smith Barney, called an ``extremely well-run, first-rate company''
that broadens its customer base and enables to it to work more
closely with customers throughout the United States.
</P>
<P>
   Brian M. O'Hara, chief executive of XL Capital, said, ``NAC Re
will become our platform for the United States.''
</P>
<P>
   One of the benefits of operating an insurance company here in
Bermuda is that there is no corporate income tax. NAC Re, which had
revenue from premiums last year of $704 million, will continue to
pay taxes in the United States, O'Hara said, adding that additional
business that the Bermuda corporate parent expected to conduct in
the United States through NAC Re would also qualify for U.S. taxes.
</P>
<P>
   The purchase of NAC Re enables XL Capital to begin dealing with
some smaller but substantial companies in the United States that
have been unwilling to come here to do business _ because of
inconvenience and because they did not need the highest levels of
coverage.
</P>
<P>
   Robert R. Lusardi, XL Capital's chief financial officer, said
the acquisition would enable his company to do more business
involving complex financial arrangements that require close,
day-to-day work with clients, as well as to begin providing some
coverage that can prudently be offered only after detailed studies
of clients and their potential problems.
</P>
<P>
   XL Capital was created in 1986 when other insurers, hurt by big
asbestos-related lawsuits, backed away from offering certain
liability coverage or sharply raised prices. It began to diversify
as competitors re-entered the field, driving premiums down.
</P>
<P>
   Kenneth S. Zuckerberg, an analyst at Keefe, Bruyette &AMP; Woods,
said NAC Re neatly complemented XL Capital and the reinsurance
business it acquired a year ago. While XL specializes in property
and liability coverage that kick in when claims exceed, say, $100
million or when a hurricane destroys great stretches of homes and
businesses, NAC Re has avoided that coverage. It has instead
emphasized reinsurance of liability coverage with frequent, but
less costly claims. And it has been selling direct coverage to
groups of small- and medium-sized businesses like auto dealers and
trucking companies, drugstores and florists.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a great fit, strategically and financially,'' Frank said,
adding that the combination would reduce some overhead costs. And,
as a unit of XL Capital, with $4.8 billion in equity, NAC Re will
be able to reduce the amount of reinsurance it has been buying to
reduce its own risk.
</P>
<P>
   XL Capital plans to issue $1.05 billion in new stock to pay for
NAC Re, not including the $200 million in debt. NAC Re equity
holders will receive 0.915 XL Capital share for each NAC Re share.
XL Capital closed Tuesday at $52, up $2.1875, on the New York Stock
Exchange.
</P>
<P>
   O'Hara, who began trying to expand in the United States with the
purchase of an inactive New York insurer, Folks America, late in
1997, said he had been interested in NAC Re for a couple of years,
but had hung back until negotiations by competitors fell through.
``I didn't want to get into a bidding war,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Jay A. Cohen, an analyst at Merrill Lynch, said XL Capital paid
a ``very fair price'' _ 1.35 times NAC Re's book value at a time
when similar companies were trading at an average of 1.5 times
their book value.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
