<HEADER>
A8035 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKC-UCLA-ANALYSIS-LAD     02-17 0711
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-UCLA-ANALYSIS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DAVIS LACKS SUPPORT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JON WILNER  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &LR; LOS ANGELES _ After four months, 24 games and close to 100
practices, how good is UCLA? It depends on the day.
</P>
<P>
   Last week's Bay Area trip showed the No. 16 Bruins at their best
and their worst. Thursday, in a spirited loss at Stanford, they
displayed the patience and discipline necessary for a furious
finish. It wasn't hard to imagine this UCLA team winning a few
games in the NCAA Tournament.
</P>
<P>
   The 18-point loss Saturday at Cal probably erased any chance of
UCLA earning a No. 3 seed in the tournament and it raised one
important question: Have the Bruins gotten better in the last month
or has only Baron Davis gotten better?
</P>
<P>
   Davis, a sophomore point guard, was masterful in the Bay Area,
combining for 50 points and eight assists and at times playing one
against five. He is averaging 20.5 points in his last five games,
beat Oregon at the buzzer and kept the Bruins breathing at Cal.
</P>
<P>
   Given modest support, Davis is talented enough to carry UCLA in
the stretch run, which begins tonight against USC. But for the
Bruins to flourish in the NCAA Tournament, Davis needs help, and
because of injuries, fatigue and poor play, he isn't getting any.
</P>
<P>
   UCLA (17-7, 8-5) made significant progress in the middle weeks
of January, culminating with the victory at Louisville. Since then,
the Bruins have stayed on a plateau.
</P>
<P>
   The rookie big men, Jerome Moiso and Dan Gadzuric, have
regressed. Moiso is UCLA's most polished interior scorer. Three
weeks ago, he developed tendinitis in his right foot and has lost
confidence, conditioning and timing. He has not scored in double
figures this month, stripping the Bruins of an entire offensive
dimension.
</P>
<P>
   Without Moiso, the frontcourt scoring burden has shifted to
Gadzuric, and he is not ready for it, physically or otherwise. He
cannot practice or play for long durations because of tendinitis in
his knees. Without that foundation _ and considering his fledgling
skill level _ he's ill-equipped to handle the load. The Bruins went
to him early and often against Cal and the Bears pounced with
double teams each time. The result: Gadzuric had seven turnovers in
21 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   The substitution pattern is as inconsistent as the on-court
performance and that lack of stability seemingly has prevented
roles from developing. How can Travis Reed and Matt Barnes, the top
frontcourt reserves, gain rhythm and confidence when they play for
60 or 90 seconds at a time? Not surprisingly, they have stagnated
in recent weeks. Reed has scored two points in his last three
games.
</P>
<P>
   Freshman forward JaRon Rush was improving rapidly until the Cal
game, when his patience and jumper vanished. Rush deserves every
minute he gets; no one plays harder. But he needs guidance. He was
not a 3-point shooter in high school and he isn't one now. He is a
midrange shooter who's best when slashing to the basket. Yet he
continues to launch 3-pointers. The coaches must realign his
offensive priorities.
</P>
<P>
   Last week's mystery was sophomore guard Earl Watson, who made 5
of 15 shots in the Bay Area. Perhaps he has hit a February lull and
is refueling for the stretch. Whatever the reason, Watson must
regain his January production for UCLA to prosper.
</P>
<P>
   Yet for all their injuries and inconsistencies, the Bruins
appear headed for 20 to 22 victories _ a few more than even Lavin
expected. And as they proved last year, two wins in March Madness
can turn questions marks into exclamations points. &QL; 
UCLA REPORT CARD &QL; 
__ Guard: Baron Davis is playing like a pro, with solid defensive
support from Earl Watson. __ Grade: A &QL; 
__ Forward: Bruins would be in great shape if Jerome Moiso and
JaRon Rush ever played well in the same game. __ Grade: B- &QL; 
__ Center: It's Dan Gadzuric against inexperience and tendinitis;
so far, Gadzuric is losing. __ Grade: C- &QL; 
__ Bench: Ray Young, Matt Barnes, Travis Reed and Ryan Bailey have
been as inconsistent as their playing time. __ Grade: C &QL; 
__ Coaching: The good: Bruins are two or three wins ahead of
schedule. The bad: The Bruins have lost three of their past five
games. Final exam is next month. __ Grade: B &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
