<P>
   &UR; TRENDY `OXYGEN BARS': FULL OF HOT AIR? &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (ATTN: California) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   By Andrew Gumbel &QL;
</P>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Feeling lacklustre? Prone to allergies or
headaches? Well, here, at least according to the latest medical
health-kick fad in America, is the reason: you aren't getting
enough oxygen.
</P>
<P>
   Enter a trendy new ``oxygen bar'' on Hollywood's Sunset Strip
where, for $13 a pop, customers are invited to insert a plastic
canula tube up their noses and spend 20 minutes breathing a
cocktail of ``oxygen rich'' air, fruit flavorings and aromatherapy
oils with names like Clarity, Passion and Joy.
</P>
<P>
   To judge from the queues snaking around the corner, the concept
is catching on.
</P>
<P>
   But are oxygen bars a breath of fresh air, or just alot of hot
air?... &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (950 words) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Moved as BC-OXYGEN-BAR-HANGOVER-INDEPENDENT-NYTSF &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; BAKED POTATOES WARD OFF CANCER &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   By Jeremy Laurance &QL;
</P>
<P>
   LONDON _ International medical experts rallied to the cause of
the baked potato as one of the most effective defenses against
cancer, challenging a recent U.S. study that suggested dietary
fiber, found in abundance in potatoes with skins and in other
vegetables, failed to protect against bowel cancer. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (250 words) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Moved as BC-POTATO-CANCER-CURE-INDEPENDENT-NYTSF &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MUZAK, AN UNSTOPPABLE FORCE &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (ATTN: Seattle and Boston) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   By Andrew Marshall &QL;
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ At first I barely noticed it. But it was always
there, somewhere, floating in the air just out of reach.
</P>
<P>
   It is music. Or rather, it is Muzak, for there is a difference.
</P>
<P>
   Since its origins back in the 1920s, Muzak has subliminally _
some would even say sinisterly _ serenaded Americans with
whispering strings in the supermarket, restaurants, motels,
fast-food joints _ even the toilet.
</P>
<P>
   It even accompanied Neil Armstrong to the Moon.
</P>
<P>
   Now, though, there's a new spin on Muzak; the 'ol soundtrack to
the American century is changing its tune... &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (700 words...FOR THOSE DESIRING A SHORTER VERSION, THIS ARTICLE
STANDS IN 700 WORDS; TOTAL UNCUT VERSION IS 850.) &QL;
</P>
<P>
