<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-17 00:32 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8041 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-OLY-TOMJANOVICH-HNS &LR;      02-17 0771
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLY-TOMJANOVICH-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL MURPHY  
 c. 1999, Houston Chronicle  
Rockets coach Rudy Tomjanovich is expected to be named to coach the
next Olympic Dream Team, which will represent the United States in
Sydney, Australia, in 2000.
<TEXT>
<P>
   The announcement could come as soon as this week.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think there's any question that if NBA players are
used, then Rudy is going to be the coach,'' said a source at USA
Basketball.
</P>
<P>
   The USA Senior National Team Committee, headed by Rod Thorn, the
NBA's senior vice president of basketball operations, will meet
today in Chicago to discuss coaching and player candidates. Utah
coach Jerry Sloan, an assistant on the 1996 Olympic Team that won a
gold medal in Atlanta, also is said to be a candidate to coach the
team.
</P>
<P>
   Several NBA players reportedly have been informally contacted
about possibly participating in the qualifying tournament and the
2000 Olympics. Sources say the qualifying team and the Olympic team
will be identical or very close in makeup, ensuring continuity
through the Games.
</P>
<P>
   Should NBA players agree to participate, the selection committee
will establish a list of candidates and send off written agreements
for the players, lawyers and agents to sign and return.
</P>
<P>
   Tomjanovich leads the coaching pack because of the job he did in
leading the United States team to a bronze medal in the World
Championships of Basketball in Athens, Greece, last summer.
Tomjanovich was supposed to coach a team of NBA players, but the
league's labor problems resulted in their honoring a union request
not to participate in the World Championships.
</P>
<P>
   Tomjanovich's team, composed of college and Continental
Basketball Association players, defeated Greece 84-61 to capture
the bronze, even though most experts predicted Team USA would be
quickly eliminated from the competition.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can say that Rudy is the leading candidate,'' said Russ
Granik, president of USA Basketball and deputy commissioner of the
NBA. ``When you look at the job he did with the team he took to
Greece, it was remarkable. While I don't know if you can say that
the committee owes Rudy a spot, there is the consideration that the
team he was originally supposed to coach and the team that he
actually took to Greece were vastly different. There is a lot of
sentiment that Rudy should be rewarded for the time and effort he
put in with that team.''
</P>
<P>
   The selection committee will consist of Thorn, a non-voting
member, and 10 voting members _ seven NBA appointees, one NCAA
appointee and two former athletes. The seven NBA appointees are
Wally Walker of the Seattle SuperSonics; Wes Unseld of the
Washington Wizards; Kevin McHale of the Minnesota Timberwolves;
Ernie Grunfeld of the New York Knicks; John Gabriel of the Orlando
Magic; Wayne Embry of the Cleveland Cavaliers; and C.M. Newton, the
athletic director at the University of Kentucky.
</P>
<P>
   Newton, a past president of USA Basketball, replaced Mike
Dunleavy of the Portland Trail Blazers. The NCAA appointee is Mike
Krzyzewski of Duke. The two former athletes are Billy King, now the
general manager of the Philadelphia 76ers, and former Rocket Clyde
Drexler, now the men's basketball coach at the University of
Houston.
</P>
<P>
   The chief concern of the selection committee is whether the
candidate would be willing to commit to both the Olympic qualifying
tournament, to be held this July in Puerto Rico, and the Olympics,
which will be held in Sydney from Sept. 15 through Oct. 1, 2000.
</P>
<P>
   Sources say Tomjanovich would make himself available to coach
both teams.
</P>
<P>
   NBA players support the idea of Tomjanovich's coaching the team.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would like playing for Rudy, first of all because he has
(championship) rings,'' said the Lakers' Kobe Bryant, an All-Star
last season. ``He has won (NBA titles). But he runs a lot of
isolations, and I really like that. Under any circumstances,
myself, I definitely love to go one-on-one, so I would love to play
for Rudy T.''
</P>
<P>
   Bryant's teammate, Eddie Jones, who also made the 1998 All-Star
team, agreed.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd love to play for Rudy,'' Jones said. ``Rudy is one of
those coaches where he's not like your average NBA coach. He's one
of those guys who lets you do what you do best. He gives you that
green light to do your job. When a coach gives you the green light
to do your job, that's nothing but confidence.
</P>
<P>
   ``You know what I mean? That's confidence for a player, and
confidence that the coach has in you. He puts a lot of trust in his
players, and I think that's what players want in this league.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
