r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HKN-BICKLEY_COLUMN-CO     02-17 0715
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-BICKLEY_COLUMN-COYOTES-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COYOTES FAIL TO MAKE STATEMENT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By DAN BICKLEY  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Silly, isn't it?
</P>
<P>
   A league where a President's Trophy accompanies the highest
score . . . A league that makes it a point to tie . . . A league
where the second-best team can be rewarded with the fourth playoff
seed?
</P>
<P>
   Silly, yes, but no one in the Coyotes organization is very much
amused. Not when all the posturing and point-fishing might land
Ducks and not minnows.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday night, one of those nights when you stick a
thermometer inside your hockey team and gauge the temperature, the
Coyotes came up raw. Manhandled and dwarfed, smothered and stifled.
Swatted away by the team that lives in corners and hits for
distance.
</P>
<P>
   The Flyers and the Coyotes rank No. 2 and 3, respectively, on
the NHL's tote board. On Tuesday night, the difference seemed
profound.
</P>
<P>
   ``At times they dominated us,'' Keith Tkachuk said.
</P>
<P>
   More often than not.
</P>
<P>
   The Flyers looked very much like Stanley Cup material. The
Coyotes looked very much like an over-matched, mistake-prone outfit
that turned over the puck with alarming regularity.
</P>
<P>
   Just as profound as the difference between the two teams could
be the fate awaiting the top two outfits in the Pacific Division.
One likely gets the eighth seed, the other a first-round roll of
the dice. If the postseason started today, the Coyotes would draw
the Mighty Ducks.
</P>
<P>
   A mighty rival full of bad blood, insults and one-sided results.
At least this season, when the Coyotes are 0-2-2.
</P>
<P>
   Not exactly the kind of pairing you envisioned during a 17-3-3
start.
</P>
<P>
   The Ducks have a player, Ruslan Salei, who has delivered a
concussion to Daniel Briere and facial surgery to Mike Stapleton.
They eliminated the Coyotes two years ago. And they have a coach
who has already gotten under the skin of Coyotes boss Jim
Schoenfeld.
</P>
<P>
   After a 5-1 spanking at America West Arena on Sunday, Ducks
Coach Craig Hartsburg claimed the Coyotes may have been too intent
on retribution to focus on winning. That prompted Schoenfeld to
declare that maybe the retribution isn't over, and after
disappearing into the locker room, he popped his head out once
again.
</P>
<P>
   ``Unlike them, we're in a position where we can waste a few
points,'' Schoenfeld said.
</P>
<P>
   No, they're not.
</P>
<P>
   This is the first season that expansion has sprouted three
divisions, and already, there is room for grumbling. The three
champions are assured a 1-3 seeding, even if the Coyotes out-point
everyone but the Stars. Sort of like baseball allowing the wild
card to host three games in a five-game series.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, nothing says the Coyotes can't revert to their
unbeatable ways. Against the Flyers, they were without Dallas Drake
and Jyrki Lumme, and the Coyotes don't have much margin for error.
</P>
<P>
   Given the current trend, there's also a chance both the
Avalanche and the Red Wings will ultimately pass the Coyotes in the
ledger, making the scenario moot.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have to step back a little bit and re-focus,'' Jeremy
Roenick said.
</P>
<P>
   Facing a seven-game tour of the east in the next 14 days, a
victory over the Flyers would've been a wonderful catalyst. Except
the Coyotes never had a chance.
</P>
<P>
   Even as the shot total bulged in the Coyotes' favor during the
first 10 minutes, they were only playing a game of soft toss with
the opposing goalie. And before the period ended, the Flyers simply
muscled away control of the game.
</P>
<P>
   John LeClair scored twice, and has 37 goals. Eric Lindros is
devastating, Dick Butkus on skates. Together, they have combined
for 69 goals. Tkachuk and Roenick have 39.
</P>
<P>
   And so the Coyotes still trail the Dallas Stars by six points in
the race for the Western Conference's top seed, and no ground has
been gained over the past two home games. What was once a two-point
deficit and a race to the finish is beginning to smell like
resignation.
</P>
<P>
   The Stars have played three fewer games. The Coyotes are packing
for a seven-game trip and no one can find their offense. Plenty of
time for another push, but the signs are ominous:
</P>
<P>
   Second place, fourth seed, another first-round fight for
survival. &QL; 
Dan Bickley can be reached at dan.bickley(at)pni.com. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
