<SLUG> BC-BKN-SUNS-ROCKETS-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ROCKETS BURN SLUGGISH SUNS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB YOUNG  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ The Suns could blame their lackluster performance in a
109-92 beating they took Tuesday night from the Houston Rockets on
the NBA schedule makers.
</P>
<P>
   After all, it was their third game in four nights and the
Rockets were coming off four days of rest.
</P>
<P>
   The Suns could say it was inevitable after the energy they spent
Monday night overcoming a 19-point deficit in Denver. Or they could
just chalk it up to a bad night.
</P>
<P>
   But there are no excuses to fully explain their third-quarter
fold, which saw the Rockets turn a four-point lead into a blowout.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were flat at both ends of the court,'' center Luc Longley
said. ``Houston did some good things to keep us out of what we
wanted to do offensively. There are some excuses out there, but
I'll let someone else throw them out and see if they stick.''
</P>
<P>
   Here's what will stick:
</P>
<P>
   The club's starting backcourt of Jason Kidd and Rex Chapman
combined to make only 9 of 33 shots.
</P>
<P>
   Houston's starting frontcourt of Hakeem Olajuwon, Othella
Harrington and Scottie Pippen combined for 55 points and 36
rebounds while limiting Longley, Tom Gugliotta and George McCloud
to a combined 28 points and 17 rebounds.
</P>
<P>
   Pippen finished within one assist of a triple-double for the
Rockets, finishing with 19 points, 12 rebounds and nine assists.
</P>
<P>
   And the Rockets didn't even have Charles Barkley. The league's
leading rebounder and the Rockets' leading scorer through five
games is out after having arthroscopic knee surgery. His
replacement, Othella Harrington, scored 17 points and took down 13
rebounds.
</P>
<P>
   ``Offensively, we just couldn't get going,'' Suns Coach Danny
Ainge said. ``We had some long shots, and we didn't get back in
transition. Offensively, we dug ourselves a hole we couldn't get
out of.''
</P>
<P>
   It doesn't get any easier, either. The Suns close out their
three-games-in-three-nights road trip tonight against the San
Antonio Spurs, who dumped them out of last season's playoffs in the
first round.
</P>
<P>
   Pippen has struggled to find his niche within the Rockets'
offense, but there never has been any question about his defense.
He started on on Kidd, who made only six of his 19 shots after
shooting 47 percent through the first six games.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was all over the place in the second half,'' Houston Coach
Rudy Tomjanovich said. ``On the offensive boards, on the break,
making passes. He is just a versatile player, and he gives me the
opportunity to play so many combinations of players.''
</P>
<P>
   And Chapman, who sat out the victory at Denver because of back
spasms, continued to look for his shooting rhythm. He came into the
game shooting only 26 percent and made three of 14 shots.
</P>
<P>
   ``We got a little frustrated because our shots wouldn't go
down,'' Kidd said. ``We got some good looks, but we couldn't get
them to go. They were coming up short, so maybe our legs were
tired, but you've got to fight through those things. There's
another game (tonight).''
</P>
<P>
   But it was evident the Suns, who beat the Los Angeles Clippers
Saturday night in overtime, then traveled to the Mile High City
Monday, were running on fumes. They had 11 fast-break points at
halftime. They had zero points from the break in the decisive third
quarter, in which the Rockets pushed their 45-41 halftime advantage
to a a 79-62 advantage going to the fourth quarter.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's tough to fast break when the other team is shooting 65
percent (as the Rockets did in the third quarter),'' Ainge noted.
``And a lot of their easy shots were the result of our bad
shooting. They definitely looked like the fresher team.
</P>
<P>
   ``But that's the way it goes. Everybody in the league has to go
through it.''
</P>
<P>
   Kidd said none of the Suns found an offensive rhythm.
</P>
<P>
   ``We didn't get a chance to run like we have,'' he said. ``It
wasn't a typical Suns game. We didn't get going up and down.''
</P>
<P>
   But veteran forward Clifford Robinson said the collapse can't be
blamed on what happened in Denver.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you have a challenge, you better step up and meet it,''
he said. ``If you don't, you're going to get beat.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
