r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN-DIAMONDBACKS-BENE     02-17 0889
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-DIAMONDBACKS-BENES-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BENES  WELCOMES ADDITIONS TO STAFF 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By DON KETCHUM  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   TUCSON _ Say, didn't you used to be Andy Benes?
</P>
<P>
   Weren't you the guy who gutted out 231 innings for the
Diamondbacks in 1998, won seven of your last nine games, including
a near-no-hitter, to record an expansion-record 14 victories?
</P>
<P>
   The one and the same. But there's no ``used to be.''
</P>
<P>
   With the acquisition of starters Randy Johnson, Todd Stottlemyre
and Armando Reynoso via free agency over the winter, it might seem
as if Benes is an afterthought entering the club's second season.
</P>
<P>
   The 6-foot-6, 245-pound right-hander is here to assure everyone
that he is alive and well and ready again to be a valuable member
of the rotation.
</P>
<P>
   He reports today with 28 other pitchers and six catchers to
Tucson Electric Park as spring training officially begins.
</P>
<P>
   After signing a three-year, $18 million free agent contract with
the Diamondbacks on Feb. 3, 1998, Benes barely had time to catch
his breath before reporting to Tucson. He welcomed the challenge of
being the No. 1 man on the staff, but it also brought its share of
uncertainty.
</P>
<P>
   He traditionally had been a slow starter, and he wasn't as
consistent early in 1998 as he would have liked. A loss to Colorado
in the franchise inaugural amid the hoopla at Bank One Ballpark,
followed by the club's first victory after an 0-5 start. Win-loss.
Loss-win. No-decisions thrown into the mix.
</P>
<P>
   ``The first half of the year, and especially any time you come
into a new situation, you feel like you have to prove yourself,''
Benes said.
</P>
<P>
   Diamondbacks pitching coach Mark Connor acknowledged that Benes
probably felt that way, ``even though he had our (manager's and
coaching staff's) confidence. He's the kind of guy where it just
takes him a while to get going.''
</P>
<P>
   Benes admitted his attention may have been diverted somewhat in
the early going.
</P>
<P>
   By advising the young pitchers on the staff, ``I almost felt
like one of the parents. I don't mean that in a negative way
because I wanted to help them, provide encouragement. But it also
can make you lose track a little when you're getting ready.''
</P>
<P>
   By mid-June, Benes had slumped to 4-7. On June 12 at Bank One
Ballpark, he faced his old St. Louis Cardinals teammates and lost
to Stottlemyre as Mark McGwire launched a grand slam.
</P>
<P>
   Benes also began to experience discomfort in his abdominal area.
It later was diagnosed as a hernia.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was some pain. But it was more irritating than
anything,'' Benes said. ``I could have surgery then and miss at
least two or three weeks, or just deal with it. I decided to deal
with it and wait until after the season, unless it got worse.''
</P>
<P>
   Warmer weather and Benes' resolve took over, and he began to
pitch better. He won seven of his last nine, and on Sept. 13 at
Cincinnati's Cinergy Field, he came within two outs of a no-hitter.
</P>
<P>
   ``I pitched better in the second half, but I really couldn't
tell you why,'' he said. ``You just keep going out there and trying
to be consistent, locating your pitches.
</P>
<P>
   ``Something just comes over you. You focus on one spot and
you're just peppering it. You have such a clear focus. There's no
greater feeling than when you're in a groove like that.''
</P>
<P>
   He wished he could have pitched like that earlier in the season,
and he vowed to place more emphasis on conditioning and preparation
in the off-season.
</P>
<P>
   Fellow Diamondbacks pitchers Willie Blair and Omar Daal lamented
the rarity of offensive help in many of their outings. Benes had
similar feelings, but he didn't place all the blame on the offense.
</P>
<P>
   ``We didn't score enough runs on some occasions, but some of the
time I put us in a position where we ``had'' to score a bunch of
runs. I put too much heat on the offense,'' Benes said.
</P>
<P>
   The hernia surgery was done in early October and Benes became
what Manager Buck Showalter called ``a consistent soldier'' in
workouts with strength and conditioning coach Jeff Forney at Bank
One Ballpark. That's in addition to being an important member of
his kids' carpool rotation for school.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think I've done what I set out to do,'' Benes said. ``I've
dropped a lot of body fat, and I feel my arm is in better shape
than it has been and I'm ready.''
</P>
<P>
   Benes is looking forward to working with the new pitchers. He
was a teammate of Johnson's in Seattle for part of the 1995 season
and was Stottlemyre's teammate in St. Louis in 1996 and 1997.
</P>
<P>
   The trio will be housed in a portion of the Bank One Ballpark
clubhouse that could be termed ``Intensity Corner.'' On game days,
enter at your own risk. Cordon it off with yellow police tape.
</P>
<P>
   ``I enjoyed last season, being with the younger guys, but
there's also something to be said of hanging around with guys who
you are closer in age with,'' said Benes, 31. ``We're all pretty
intense. Everybody goes out and pushes the next guy. That's why
Atlanta's so good.
</P>
<P>
   ``With our experience and ability, we'll be capable of throwing
a shutout every night. And though the offense wants to score as
much as it can, it won't feel like it has to score 8 or 9, maybe
only 4 or 5, to have a chance to win. Looking at our division,
we're capable of competing with anybody.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-17-99 0045EST &QL; 
