<HEADLINE>
SLASH ON STAPLETON DOESN'T VEX NHL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB MCMANAMAN  
 and TIM TYERS  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Anaheim's Ruslan Salei escaped Sunday's game against the Coyotes
without getting penalized for a slash to the face of Phoenix center
Mike Stapleton. Two days later, he also managed to escape a
suspension from Colin Campbell, the NHL's chief disciplinarian.
</P>
<P>
   A source in New York said that if Campbell hadn't made a ruling
by Tuesday, it was likely Salei wouldn't be suspended.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was so afraid they were going to give me a penalty on that
play,'' Salei said. ``I was trying to block his shot by hitting him
in the stick, but my stick went up and I saw blood. I wasn't trying
to hit him in the face but I was lucky they didn't give me a
four-minute penalty.''
</P>
<P>
   After slew-footing Daniel Briere in the preseason and then
carving up Stapleton, Salei has become public enemy No. 1 with the
Coyotes.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yes. I don't think those guys like me,'' he said. ``But it's a
game and I try to (tick) them off. Especially guys like (Keith)
Tkachuk and (Jeremy) Roenick. If you (tick) them off, they're going
to take a couple penalties and then you get them off their game.''
</P>
<P>
   Responding to Coach Jim Schoenfeld's post-game comments about
the Coyotes perhaps not being done settling the score with Salei
and the Ducks and how Phoenix can ``waste a few points'' through
possible retaliation, Salei said Schoenfeld can say what he wants.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know what he is thinking. I play for this team and I
don't know what their coach feels,'' Salei said. ``I'm sure they've
got a lot of extra points. They're not worried about those points
like we are.'' &QL;  &QL; 
Close call &QL;  &QL; 
The 27-stitch gash that caused Stapleton to miss Tuesday's meeting
with the Philadelphia Flyers came within a fraction of an inch of
costing his left eye. At that, it's uncertain whether there was
damage to the tear duct. The cut went to the bone.
</P>
<P>
   The swelling effected Stapleton's downward vision, which forced
him to sit out.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have a lot of water around my eye,'' Stapleton said. ``I'm
going to go on the trip and we'll see if the tear duct works and I
can play.''
</P>
<P>
   Stapleton refused comment on the play after that game, but had a
little to say Tuesday night.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's just the nasty part of the game,'' he said. ``Has any
suspension or anything been issued yet? It's unfortunate.'' &QL;  &QL; 
Keith-in-the-box &QL;  &QL; 
Anaheim wing Jim McKenzie, a former Coyote who was traded in the
summer, had several animated moments on the ice during Sunday's
game, including a jawing session with Tkachuk.
</P>
<P>
   McKenzie got the last laugh, though, scoring his third goal of
the season late in the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``Aw, we go back and forth a lot,'' McKenzie said. ``Keith's got
a pretty good endorsement deal going with Jack in the Box. That's
pretty much him with that giant pumpkin for a head.'' &QL;  &QL; 
Star search &QL;  &QL; 
Coyotes General Manager Bobby Smith is in Calgary, where he
attended Tuesday's Top Prospects Game, a scouting combine of sorts
featuring the top 40-rated juniors in North America eligible for
the June entry draft. &QL;  &QL; 
Help on the way &QL;  &QL; 
The Coyotes begin their seven-game trip Friday at Tampa Bay knowing
help is on the way. Right wing Dallas Drake, who has missed the
past seven games because of a shoulder separation, and defenseman
Jyrki Lumme, who has missed the past three games because of a groin
strain, will be making the trip.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
