<SLUG> BC-BKC-ARIZSTATE-NOTES-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IT'S CLEAR UA DIDN'T `STEAL' WIN FROM ASU 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB COHN  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   A statistical oddity in the Sun Devils' 86-80 loss to Arizona in
Tucson last week was that the winning Wildcats did not record a
steal.
</P>
<P>
   It was the first time in 268 games an ASU opponent did not steal
the ball. It last happened against Washington on March 8, 1990, in
the Pac-10 Tournament. Never before in Rob Evans' career as a head
coach, including six seasons at Mississippi, has an opponent gone
steal-less.
</P>
<P>
   It also was the first time the Wildcats have not had a steal
since 1993, despite their career steals leader (and No. 6 in Pac-10
history), Jason Terry, playing all 40 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   ASU, which had 10 steals, has been careful with the ball lately,
averaging only 10.3 turnovers in the past five games. The Sun
Devils are third in the Pac-10 in fewest turnovers at 14.9 a game,
and have a total of 13 in their past two games.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some of that is because they've had a chance to play with each
other for a while,'' Evans said. ``Guys know each other a lot
better. They know where they're gonna be, they know where they like
the basketball. We've gotten a lot more sound offensively and on
the floor in the last five, six, seven ball games.'' &QL; 
Attention, committee &QL; 
Although ASU's chances of getting into the NCAA Tournament remain
slim, Evans would like the selection committee to be aware of the
fact his team played the first eight games without one of its best
players, senior forward Mike Batiste.
</P>
<P>
   ASU was 4-4 with Batiste academically ineligible. Included were
defeats to Northern Arizona and New Orleans at home and to Kansas
State in overtime in the Maui Invitational.
</P>
<P>
   Batiste has averaged 16.8 points and 7.1 rebounds.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think there's any question that if Mike Batiste had
been here the whole year, we'd be very close, if not already in the
NCAA Tournament,'' Evans said.
</P>
<P>
   ASU (13-11, 5-7 Pac-10) must win five of its six remaining games
and finish 10-8 in the conference, 18-10 overall to be considered.
Since 1990, 35 of 36 Pac-10 teams that won 10 conference games and
18 overall have gone to the NCAA Tournament.
</P>
<P>
   Guess which team didn't? ASU, which went 18-9 and 11-7 under
Bill Frieder in 1993. That also was the only Pac-10 team out of 33
this decade to win 11 conference games and not make the NCAA
Tournament.
</P>
<P>
   Then-ASU Athletic Director Charles Harris was on the tournament
selection committee that year.
</P>
<P>
   ``Unbelievable, isn't it?,'' Frieder said. ``But that's ASU.''
</P>
<P>
   Right now, Stanford, Arizona, UCLA are in, and Washington is
close. In the latest Ratings Percentage Index, the Sun Devils were
64th. It hurts that two of their victories were over NCAA Division
II opponents, Chaminade and Alaska-Anchorage, and don't count.
</P>
<P>
   ASU could have avoided playing Chaminade in Maui, had it beaten
Kansas State. But the Alaska-Anchorage game was just bad luck.
Alaska-Anchorage upset Southern Methodist in the first round of
ASU's holiday tournament to earn a date with the Sun Devils in the
championship game. &QL; 
Just ducky
</P>
<P>
   The Sun Devils can forget about the NCAA Tournament and perhaps
even the NIT if they don't beat Oregon on Thursday at Wells Fargo
Arena. This will be the return of Oregon assistant and former ASU
interim head coach Don Newman to Tempe, but that's the last thing
on Evans' mind.
</P>
<P>
   Of more immediate concern is the performance of his team, and
the improvement of the Ducks since they lost to the Sun Devils,
64-60, in Eugene on Jan. 23.
</P>
<P>
   Oregon has won three in a row, including a 94-81 victory
Saturday over Washington, which was the hottest team in the
conference.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're playing with more confidence,'' Evans said.
</P>
<P>
   The Ducks, who have lost seven Pac-10 games by four points or
fewer, or in overtime, don't have a single go-to guy, but they are
balanced. In the Washington game, five players scored in
double-figures.
</P>
<P>
   ``They don't have anybody head and shoulders above anybody
else,'' Evans said, ``but when you get that kind of balance, that's
the best type of basketball team to have.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
