r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HKN-FLYERS-COYOTES-JO     02-17 0641
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-FLYERS-COYOTES-JONES-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FLYERS' UNSUNG HERO  
 ASSISTS BY JONES PROVE KEY AGAIN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By TIM TYERS  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The 42 points Keith Jones has scored for the Philadelphia Flyers
this season would make him the Phoenix Coyotes' No. 2 scorer.
</P>
<P>
   But on the Flyers, Jones is merely known as the right wing who
does all the dirty work for high-scoring John LeClair and Eric
Lindros.
</P>
<P>
   LeClair, the league goal-scoring leader with 37, had two goals
and Lindros added an assist, but Jones' work Tuesday night in the
Flyers' 4-1 win over the Coyotes was a perfect example of what he
adds.
</P>
<P>
   He assisted on the Flyers second, third and fourth goals, but it
was his role on the Flyers first goal in the first period that
typifies his play.
</P>
<P>
   Jones kept the puck alive behind the Coyotes and kept digging
until Lindros was able to pass it to the point to defenseman Chris
Therin, whose slap shot was deflected off LeClair's foot at the
faceoff circle and handcuffed Phoenix goalie Nikolai Khabibulin.
</P>
<P>
   ``Jonesey has been a tremendous help to us,'' said Lindros, who,
combined with LeClair, has produced 150 points this season. ``He's
a fireplug out there. He's always talking and communicating on the
ice. He has fun out there aggravating people.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know we sure are happy to have him on our side. He's always
contributing something.''
</P>
<P>
   Lindros will get no argument from LeClair about Jones' value.
</P>
<P>
   ``He has brought us a lot of grit, especially on the
forecheck,'' LeClair said. ``He has a nose for the puck and has
been a real bonus. He came in, and the chemistry was great right
away.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was the key to the first goal, in there digging hard for
the puck. And on the second goal, he picked off the pass and dug it
out of the corner and fed it to me in front of the net. He's great
down there.''
</P>
<P>
   In fact, it is moves like acquiring Jones from Colorado after 12
games this year that have the Flyers and Lindros thinking this
could be the year that the organization's string of disappointments
in the Stanley Cup playoffs finally ends.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our organization has recommitted itself to going out and
getting great players,'' Lindros said. ``Getting a goaltender like
John Vanbiesbrouck, then going out and getting Mikael Renberg back
and a guy like Daymond Langkow in the same deal has just been a
tremendous boost.
</P>
<P>
   ``The organization has made the moves we needed to get back on
track. Combined with the fact everybody is having fun, it has made
for a lot of success.''
</P>
<P>
   Confidence isn't something the Flyers lack. Perhaps the NHL's
biggest club, they've lost only eight of their past 40 games but
limped into Phoenix with a 1-2-2 record in their past five,
including blowing two-goal leads in Los Angeles and Colorado in
their past two games.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's something every team goes through during a season,''Jones
said. ``You're going to have your ups and downs. Fortunately, we've
had a lot of ups and very few dips.
</P>
<P>
   ``We do feel this is the year the (Stanley Cup) disappointment
can end. We feel real good about our team, but there are a lot of
things to feel good about around here. But to do it we have to keep
focused on what the goal is, and at the same time, make it a fun
experience.''
</P>
<P>
   Jones has been impressed with the leadership Lindros has
displayed this season, despite the fact Lindros has been made the
perennial fall guy in each of the Flyers' playoff collapses in
recent years.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the first time I've played with him, but from what I've
seen, he seems comfortable with where he's at in his career and
wants to establish himself as one of the all-time greats _ and he
is,'' Jones said.
</P>
<P>
   ``In order to do that, he has to win Stanley Cups. Hopefully,
we'll help him do it and achieve all of our goals.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
