<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-17 01:06 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8051 &Cx1f; tic-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HKN-FLYERS-COYOTES-AZ     02-17 0738
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-FLYERS-COYOTES-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FLYERS SPELL DOOM  
 STRENGTH LEAVES COYOTES FEELING DE FENSELESS
 &HT;     FLYERS 4, COYOTES 1 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB MCMANAMAN  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   There were whispers around America West Arena before Tuesday's
clash between the Coyotes and the Philadelphia Flyers that the game
might be a preview of the Stanley Cup Finals in another four
months.
</P>
<P>
   If it was, the NHL could be staring at its fifth straight Finals
sweep, something the suits at the league office must be sweating.
</P>
<P>
   Philadelphia pounded Phoenix, 4-1, to sweep the two-game season
series and drive home the point that they are the Beasts of the
East to contend with in the postseason.
</P>
<P>
   ``They just dominated us,'' Coyotes captain Keith Tkachuk said,
shaking his head.
</P>
<P>
   Someone asked whether they are the best in the league.
</P>
<P>
   ``They sure looked like it tonight,'' Tkachuk said.
</P>
<P>
   Just like his team, Philadelphia's John LeClair continued his
dominance over the Coyotes, scoring two goals, his league-leading
36th and 37th, and adding two assists. During the Flyers' 4-2 win
over Phoenix earlier this season, he had two goals and an assist.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we can skate with anybody, and we proved it tonight,''
said LeClair, who pulled to within one goal of catching former
Flyer Rick Tocchet for ninth place on Philadelphia's career
goal-scoring list (215).
</P>
<P>
   Flyers captain Eric Lindros, meanwhile, extended his
league-leading point-scoring streak to 17 games with a first-period
assist. If he scores a point Thursday at home against Montreal, he
will tie Flyers General Manager Bobby Clarke's franchise record.
</P>
<P>
   Fellow linemate Keith Jones, obtained earlier this season from
Colorado, produced three assists, giving the Flyers' No. 1 line a
total of eight points on the night. They also were a combined
plus-12. A Legion of Doom, indeed.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're a really good team,'' Coyotes center Jeremy Roenick
said. ``That first line of theirs is just sheer power and strength,
and they move the puck very well. The defense is very stable _
they're so big, it's tough to get around them _ and they're all
really strong, which makes it tough to outmuscle them.''
</P>
<P>
   With a win, the Coyotes (29-15-10) could have overtaken the
Flyers (29-12-13) for the second-most points overall in the NHL
with 70. But now Philadelphia, which snapped an 0-2-1 skid, has a
three-point edge on Phoenix, which begins a seven-game, 14-day trip
Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Lindros didn't have to wait long to get his point. Midway
through the opening period, he set up the Flyers' go-ahead goal
with a feed out to Chris Therien at the point. Therien's blast was
deflected and rerouted past an upright Nikolai Khabibulin by
LeClair.
</P>
<P>
   Jones should have received an assist for pinching Coyotes
defenseman Teppo Numminen out of the play, pinning him against the
glass while LeClair set up shop in the slot area.
</P>
<P>
   With Therien in the box for kneeing, the Coyotes momentarily
thought they tied the score at 1. Oleg Tverdovsky sent a pinpoint
pass to the right of John Vanbiesbrouck (32 saves) to Roenick, who
hesitated before firing a shot between the goalie's pads. It
appeared as if he were waiting for rookie Daniel Briere to get out
of the crease.
</P>
<P>
   Briere, making a rare appearance on the first-unit power play
alongside Roenick and Tkachuk, didn't make much of an effort and
the goal correctly was disallowed.
</P>
<P>
   Actually, the Coyotes could have used a few more players in the
crease. Defensively, that is. With little help in front of him,
Khabibulin was tagged for two more goals in the second period as
the Flyers prepared for a rout.
</P>
<P>
   LeClair camped on Khabibulin's doorstep, and with mild
resistence from defenseman Deron Quint, was allowed to take two
easy shots. The second one went in for his second goal of the
night.
</P>
<P>
   Just 56 seconds later, Khabibulin was victimized again. This
time, Dmitri Tertyshny sent in a long shot from the point. It hit
off the right post and went underneath the goalie. When he fell on
it, the puck trickled in behind him. Nobody was there to try to
clear it out before it crossed the line.
</P>
<P>
   Roenick, for one, would love another shot at the Flyers.
</P>
<P>
   ``That would be wonderful,'' he said. ``If that were to be the
case, that would mean we'd be playing for the ultimate goal, and
that would be perfect.''
</P>
<P>
   But would it be a perfect sweep?
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
