<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-17 01:07 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8052 &Cx1f; tic-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-OLY-GUGLIOTTA-CYCLING     02-17 1013
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLY-GUGLIOTTA-CYCLING-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WIFE MAKES OWN MARK  
 NIKKI GUGLIOTTA CONTENDS FOR 2000 TRIALS AS CYCLIST
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By JEFF METCALFE  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   NikkiGugliotta likes being in her husband's athletic shadow, an
ever-lengthening one now that the 6-foot-10 Suns forward is away
from Kevin Garnett and a shared stage with the Minnesota
Timberwolves.
</P>
<P>
   ``Unless someone asks, I don't want the attention, I don't need
it,'' Gugliotta said. ``I'm a mom first, there's no question.''
</P>
<P>
   The mother of a soon-to-be 2-year-old and wife of an NBA
All-Star is a runner turned duathlete turned road cyclist. Those
who have seen her ride say she has potential to make the 2000
Olympic Trials.
</P>
<P>
   While not the highest-paid athlete in the household, the
30-year-old holds her own with husband in ability.
</P>
<P>
   Consider the testimony of Hugh Walton, a 1976 Canadian Olympic
cyclist and general manager of the Hind athletic apparel company,
who befriended Gugliotta when she and Tom lived in Boulder, Colo.,
last summer.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was pretty apparent to me that she had an extraordinary
level of raw talent in terms of her strength and heart-lung
capacity,'' Walton said. ``The only thing holding her back from
winning virtually any race she entered would be experience.''
</P>
<P>
   Experience that Gugliotta hopes to gain beginning this weekend,
when she debuts with the Cox Atlanta Velo team at the Valley of the
Sun Stage Race, Friday through Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   The women's development road team is a new direction for Cox
Atlanta Velo, which formerly focused on men's track cycling. The
team coach, Bobby Livingston, said Gugliotta, Kimberly Bruckner,
Shannon Greenhill, Marjon Marik and others are not seasoned enough
for one of the major cycling teams like Saeco-Timex or Saturn, but
have enough talent to break through in the buildup to the Sydney
Olympics.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody on this team brings something different that will
help the team as a whole,'' Livingston said. ``I was coaching a
girl in Colorado (Bruckner) and wanted to get her on this team, and
Nikki was winning some of the races that she was finishing second
and third in.''
</P>
<P>
   Walton said during the Saturday morning elite rides in Boulder,
Gugliotta had some of the top professionals in the country asking,
``Who's the chick?''
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of these folks are deeply into cycling, and they're
clueless about the NBA and don't know who Tom Gugliotta is. But
they wanted to know who Nikki is.
</P>
<P>
   ``She'd be the only woman in the top 20 (out of 100 in the group
rides), and that's saying something. She'd be sitting at the front,
taking her pulls, and there are only a couple of women around here
who can do that. Plus she'd be kind of popping around, talking a
lot. I told her, `Nikki, when you get in a race, you can't be
talking so much. You've got to mind your business.' ''
</P>
<P>
   So just who is Nikki Gugliotta, and how is she able to move in
one of America's fastest cycling circles and chit-chat at the same
time?
</P>
<P>
   She is the former Nikki Cormack, a perennial state runner-up in
cross country and track while growing up in Grand Junction, Colo.
And partly because of a hamstring injury that became a stress
fracture, she is someone who never fully succeeded at North
Carolina State, where she met her husband 10 years ago when both
were freshmen.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had really peaked out in running, and not peaked out where I
had maybe hoped I would,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   So she gave in to friends, including Jim Kennedy, chairman-CEO
of Cox Enterprises Inc., who had been pestering her to try cycling.
</P>
<P>
   ``It always seemed like there was so much stuff involved,'' she
said. ``Running is so pure. But from the first ride, I thought it
was great.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1994, Gugliotta progressed from a beginning cyclist in April
to the World Duathlon amateur champion in November, winning the
U.S. Duathlon amateur title in between.
</P>
<P>
   Her 10K run, 40K bike, 5K run time at the World Championships in
Tasmania was faster than all the pros, who admittedly competed
later under different weather conditions.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Worlds was awesome,'' said Gugliotta, who was successful
even though receiving the news that Tom had been traded for the
first time from Washington to Golden State 48 hours before her
race. ``It was almost incomprehensible to me that happened.
</P>
<P>
   ``But nationals was almost more emotional because Tom was there,
and I knew I had won. I had never won the big race. It was like,
Wow I did it. It's a small sport, and it's amateur, but I did it.''
</P>
<P>
   Shortly thereafter, motherhood and the Minneapolis winters
intervened.
</P>
<P>
   She gave birth to Cameron Greer, who goes by her middle name, in
March 1997. Gugliotta started back into cycling on an exercise
bike, then progressed to a trainer before the move to Boulder,
where she raced well enough unattached to earn a spot with
Kennedy's recommendation on Cox Atlanta Velo.
</P>
<P>
   ``I need some help,'' Gugliotta said. ``There's a lot to learn
in cycling. Having teammates right there who can tell you don't do
that or go or whatever will be a big help.
</P>
<P>
   ``I still haven't had a full season to where I can judge if I
can reach an elite level. If I can, then I want to continue and
really strive to at least do the races to qualify (for the
Olympics). Then I've thought I want to have another child. Tom's
not ready for that yet, but I am.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a lot of things that you sacrifice, and I'm willing to
do it for a certain goal. But I'm not willing to do it just to go
around and travel every week to these races and drag my bike across
the country. It's a hassle.''
</P>
<P>
   Her mother, who still lives in Grand Junction, and her nanny,
who has moved three times with the Gugliottas, will help
uncomplicate what figures to become a jumbled schedule should
Nikki's career take off like in 1994.
</P>
<P>
   ``If she was to step back in (to duathlon) today, she's be one
of the top Americans competing in the sport,'' Tim Yount of USA
Triathlon said. ``That's how scary her talent is.''
</P>
<P>
   Too great to hide in the shadows. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
