r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-OLY-JOYNER-KERSEE-AZR     02-17 0636
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLY-JOYNER-KERSEE-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SHE'S RUNNING IN NEW DIRECTIONS  
 JOYNER-KERSEE BUSY AS SPEAKER, HELPER TO FLOJO'S DAUGHTER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By JEFF METCALFE  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Did Jackie Joyner-Kersee, gone from track for all of six months,
think we'd actually forget?
</P>
<P>
   That arguably the greatest female athlete of the 20th century
would become a footnote so quickly in this pre-millennium year?
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought there wouldn't be an interest,'' said Joyner-Kersee
of her post-retirement opportunities. ``It's been quite the
opposite.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our society has a way of going with the flow. What I tried to
do when I was competing was to pair it with something bigger and
better when most athletes say they're too tired to do this. That
sacrifice and making those connections, I can see now it's paying
off.''
</P>
<P>
   Free from the consuming rigors of heptathlon training,
Joyner-Kersee is in high demand as a Nike spokeswoman. She will be
in Scottsdale on Sunday for the Lady Foot Locker 5K, the third of a
three-city race series dedicated to helping women break the cycle
of domestic violence.
</P>
<P>
   The event benefits the Chrysalis Shelters for women and
children, many of whom are victims of abandonment or abuse, and the
Arizona Coalition Against Domestic Violence.
</P>
<P>
   Joyner-Kersee has remained physically active, but at a more
relaxed pace.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't have to train, but I find myself giving workouts for
my friends and working out with them,'' said Joyner-Kersee, who
turns 37 on March 3. ``I do biking, I walk, a lot of jump-rope and
lift weights now and then. When it's cold (in her native St.
Louis), I do a lot of walking on the treadmill and sit-ups.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm trying to stay fit and keep my healthy lifestyle going. I
don't have to train to peak at a certain time or be at a certain
level, just a level of happiness.''
</P>
<P>
   The joy of motherhood is another emotion she's hoping to
experience.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hope we have a family,'' said Joyner-Kersee, whose husband
and former coach, Bobby Kersee, continues to train sprinter Gail
Devers, high jumper Amy Acuff and some men in the major
professional sports.
</P>
<P>
   After the Goodwill Games, at which Joyner-Kersee won the
heptathlon with 6,502 points, a score that was second best in the
world in 1998, she announced: ``Anybody wants to start talking to
her about how to make babies, you can do that.''
</P>
<P>
   Joyner-Kersee already is a mother of sorts due to the death in
September of her sister-in-law, Florence Griffith Joyner, a
three-time track gold medalist at the 1988 Olympics.
Joyner-Kersee's brother Al has been raising his daughter,
8-year-old Mary, since FloJo's death.
</P>
<P>
   ``Al is grieving every day, but I think his strength is seeing
his daughter,'' Joyner-Kersee said. ``I knew Al would do everything
he could in his power to make sure his daughter is raised the way
Florence wanted her to be raised.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mary's a bundle of joy for him as well as she was for
Florence. They gain strength from one another, and it's hard for
them to be separated. Every time her dad leaves, she feels he might
not come back.''
</P>
<P>
   Joyner-Kersee said Mary Joyner started in gymnastics when she
was 18 months and now is getting into running. The child is
something of a tomboy yet reflects her mother.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can see the strength of Florence, the creative side and
the nurturing side,'' Joyner-Kersee said. ``At times, Florence was
very shy in a way that was probably misunderstood because of her
flashy uniforms. Sometimes you can see that within Mary, but she
has no problems making friends.
</P>
<P>
   ``To see Mary breaks my heart because one of the things Florence
wanted was to have a child and raise her. I was on the playground
one day and I just broke down thinking this is what Florence would
be doing.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
