<DOCNO> NYT19990217.0031 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-17 01:10 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8057 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-NETS-PISTONS-NYT &LR;      02-17 0839
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-NETS-PISTONS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NETS DEFEAT PISTONS, 97-82 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 By CHRIS BROUSSARD   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   EAST RUTHERFORD, N.J. _ For the third consecutive New Jersey
Nets game there was a noncompetitive fourth quarter filled with
stylish dunks and celebration, second-string ballplayers and
vacating fans. The difference on Tuesday night, however, was that
the Nets were the ones flying toward the rim, exchanging high-fives
and basically partying on the court.
</P>
<P>
   Putting to a halt their humiliating three-game losing streak,
the Nets routed the Detroit Pistons by 97-82 before 15,633 at the
Continental Arena. The blowout came less than 24 hours after an
embarrassing 23-point loss at Miami provoked the team into having a
players-only meeting three hours before the game.
</P>
<P>
   The gist of the discussion centered around returning to what
Coach John Calipari and his players call ``Nets basketball'' _
playing fast, furious and free on both ends of the court. After the
team showed it had returned to its preferred style of play, Keith
Van Horn was one of many Nets (2-4) who made the announcement
afterward in the locker room.
</P>
<P>
   ``Last night we were very down on ourselves and we just needed
to get that loss out of our heads and come out as a new team _ a
team that plays with passion and loves to play,'' Van Horn said.
``And now it's like we feel renewed.''
</P>
<P>
   The revival started with Van Horn, who had his way with
Detroit's Don Reid and Jerome Williams in scoring a career-high 35
points. After averaging 16.3 points in his last three outings, the
Nets' leading scorer looked like the best player on the court on
Tuesday night, even with the superstar Grant Hill, who scored a
lonely 22 points, thrown in the mix.
</P>
<P>
   ``Keith Van Horn is a heck of a ballplayer,'' said Pistons Coach
Alvin Gentry, who watched his team (3-4) drop its fourth straight
from the locker room after being ejected for earning back-to-back
technicals in the third quarter. ``He can be one of the elite
players in this league.''
</P>
<P>
   Supplementing his typical spins and slashes to the basket with
jump shots, the 6-foot-10-inch power forward scored 30 or more
points for the first time this season and the sixth time in his
two-year career. He tied his previous high of 33 (scored on April
12, 1998, at Toronto) within three quarters and even made a rare
3-pointer from 33 feet as the shot clock neared zero.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just heard that the clock was running down so I said, `Oh
well, I'm feeling good tonight,' so I just tried it,'' said Van
Horn, who made 11 of 18 shots and grabbed 6 rebounds.
</P>
<P>
   But Van Horn did not carry the Nets alone. He was aided by four
other players scored in double figures, including the reserves Eric
Murdock (13 points) and the surprising newcomer Damon Jones (10).
</P>
<P>
   Van Horn credited Murdock's solid play on the offensive end with
helping him play his career game. The 6-foot point guard's ability
to run the pick-and-roll enabled Van Horn to break free for open
jump shots, something he had not been able to do without a true
point guard to run the play effectively. Calipari raved about
Murdock's offense and defense, noting that in addition to giving
the Nets a semblance of order he made five steals.
</P>
<P>
   The biggest surprise was Jones, the 6-4 guard who was playing
for the Idaho Stampede of the Continental Basketball Association
less than five days ago. After the Nets had a 69-55 lead chopped to
69-62 heading into the final period, Jones scored 8 straight points
for New Jersey to set the rout in motion.
</P>
<P>
   Nailing two 3-pointers and a 20-footer, Jones bumped the lead
back to 77-64 two minutes into the fourth, and Detroit never
challenged again. The rookie who was playing only his second
National Basketball Association game said Calipari's insistence on
shooting open shots gave him the courage to launch jumpers in a
critical situation.
</P>
<P>
   ``He has made me feel more comfortable than probably any coach
would with a player in my situation,'' Jones said. ``It was just
great to be able to go in there and knock down the shots.''
</P>
<P>
   Kerry Kittles (15 points) and Kendall Gill (11 points) also
added offensive support, but the two starting guards made their
impact on the defensive end. Gill made his fourth and final steal
with 4 minutes 40 seconds to play and capped nicely with a
fashionable reverse dunk that made it 94-72 and kicked off the
parade of second-stringers.
</P>
<P>
   The slam came less than a minute after Kittles had elevated from
the baseline for a thunderous windmill dunk over Jerry Stackhouse,
leading the crowd and his teammates on the bench to rise to their
feet. For the first time since returning from a bruised right knee
three games ago, Kittles was pleased with his performance. Though
he made only 6 of 15 shots, he had 6 assists and 3 steals.
``Tonight I made a conscious effort to have fun,'' Kittles said.
``I've been out of rhythm since coming back and the team has been
out of rhythm, but tonight we just wanted to smile and laugh and
play loose.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
