<DOCNO> NYT19990217.0032 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-17 01:11 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8059 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-ROBERTSON-COLUMN-     02-17 0816
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-ROBERTSON-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
DaleRobertson
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; c. 1999, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
CHARLES who?
</P>
<P>
   Ah, Chuck, just kidding. We love you, and we wish you a speedy
recovery. Get that ol' knee well, fella, and don't you worry about
a thing.
</P>
<P>
   The Rockets, it seems, are in good hands without Charles
Barkley. Soft hands. Confident hands. While nobody relishes losing
a legend who is averaging a mere 19 points and 17 boards per night,
the pain is lessened when you can replace him with somebody capable
of scoring 17 points and hogging a game-high 13 rebounds.
</P>
<P>
   Oh, boy. Oh, my.
</P>
<P>
   Othella.
</P>
<P>
   That's ``O'' as in OK. ``O'' as in offense, too, of course.
Othella Harrington never met a shot he didn't cherish. He thinks he
can score anytime and on anybody. With his sizzling shooting
percentage _ .636 _ through six games, five of which the Rockets
have won with significant contributions from the formerly
unheralded ex-Hoya, he should just keep thinking exactly that.
</P>
<P>
   Nobody can get mad at you when you make 'em.
</P>
<P>
   ```O' didn't do anything different tonight,'' Rudy Tomjanovich
argued, acting surprised that some folks were surprised by
Harrington's multifaceted performance in a 109-92 thrashing of the
Suns at Compaq Center on Tuesday night. ``The guy's always ready.
He's got a great attitude. Does he get mad (when he doesn't play)?
Doggone right he does. But he does it the right way. I don't care
if he sits down for two weeks. `O' is always ready when we need
him.''
</P>
<P>
   Except sitting isn't an option anymore for Harrington. He's in
the Rockets' mix to stay, whether it's pinch hitting for Barkley
over the next three to four weeks or reverting to his role as the
first frontcourt substitute. When Kevin Willis was dispatched to
Toronto after last season, a world of O-pportunity opened up for
Harrington.
</P>
<P>
   Still, in the mad scramble to build a team after the lockout
ended, ``O'' was a late signee. But don't equate that to his being
a low Tomjanovich priority. The delay was the result of the
salary-cap complications, not disinterest on the part of the
Rockets.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was no way he wasn't going to be with us,'' Rudy T said.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's what I was praying for,'' Harrington said. ``Since we
weren't able to talk, I didn't know for sure. But Houston is the
only place I wanted to be.''
</P>
<P>
   He has picked a nice way to show his gratitude.
</P>
<P>
   To date, Harrington's ``worst'' shooting night has been a
5-for-10 against Denver on Feb. 8. Since that game, he's a sizzling
17-for-24, scoring 39 points in 58 minutes. He hit seven of 10 from
the field at Phoenix's expense and ultimately received the highest
of NBA compliments. Danny Ainge ordered the Suns to double down on
him, like he was Hakeem Olajuwon.
</P>
<P>
   His final points came on a six-foot jumper with 2{ minutes left
in the third quarter, and he put his feet up for the game's final
11:29 with the outcome no longer in question. He might be hungry to
play, but he will need his full reserve of energy with the Rockets
embarking today on a 12-day, eight-game wings-over-America ordeal
that will test everyone's fitness.
</P>
<P>
   Barkley, the lucky dog, will miss the trip, a harrowing prospect
if not for Harrington's newfound prominence.
</P>
<P>
   ```O' is as productive as anybody in the league right now,''
Tomjanovich said. ``But we saw it in him coming out of college. He
had his `basic,' a shot we knew he was going to score with no
matter what the level of competition was. We never doubted his
ability.''
</P>
<P>
   All right, so he doesn't pile up a lot of assists (he has two
for the season). They'll come, though, as he learns to cope with
the double teams, which he's going to see more of unless opposing
coaches aren't paying attention to what he's capable of.
</P>
<P>
   Yet you can't double him on the fast break, and he's certain to
get his share of layups and dunks on the run with Scottie Pippen's
textbook outlet passes. Harrington's young legs are made for those
Pippen strikes, which contributed to Scottie's accumulating nine
assists against the Suns.
</P>
<P>
   ``Just get wide and take off _ and always keep your eyes on
Scottie,'' Harrington said his blow-and-go philosophy has become.
``I'm too small to slow down. I've got to get to the basket
first.''
</P>
<P>
   A conditioning regimen over the long, long offseason rid him of
what was left of his baby fat. There's nothing soft or undeveloped
about his 6-9 physique. His arms are sinewy and his midsection
trim. ``O'' has, before our very eyes, acquired the look of a
thoroughbred.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know how much weight he's lost,'' Tomjanovich said.
``All I know is he's moving well and playing at a level we always
thought he could reach. We drafted him believing he'd be a solid
NBA player.''
</P>
<P>
   At this rate, Harrington might become an NBA star. People with
short memories might even take to calling him the Big O.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
