<HEADLINE>
HORRY TAKES A TIMEOUT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By HOWARD BECK  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   INGLEWOOD, Calif. _ For Robert Horry, the diagnosis is now less
troubling than the cure.
</P>
<P>
   The Los Angeles Lakers forward learned Tuesday that his
irregular heartbeat is probably a result of his recent respiratory
infection and should disappear with rest. That was the good news.
But rest meant sitting out another two games, last night's and
tonight's, doctor's orders.
</P>
<P>
   He'll be reevaluated Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yeah, I want to play,'' Horry said. ``I kind of hated lying in
a hospital bed, watching us play Indiana (Sunday).''
</P>
<P>
   Things, of course, could be much worse. Horry's irregular
heartbeat gave him and everyone else a scare, but doctors say the
condition, which was still present Tuesday, is not serious.
</P>
<P>
   ``They say the heart muscles are fine, the blood flow to it is
fine, it's just I've got an extra beat,'' Horry said. ``They said I
have nothing to worry about, I'm healthy. . . . You're dealing with
your heart, so I've got to take it easy.''
</P>
<P>
   Sitting out two more games is a precautionary measure and there
is ``an excellent chance his heart rhythm will return to normal
when he is completely healthy,'' according to a statement from the
team.
</P>
<P>
   Horry began to feel pain and tightness in his chest Saturday
night and was sent to the hospital Sunday when the pain increased
on his way to the Forum.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's very scary,'' he said of the experience. ``You start
thinking about it (mortality), you (think about) what have you
accomplished, what have you done for your family. I tried not to
think about it. I tried to make myself think everything is fine and
that it's just one of those freak situations that will go away.''
</P>
<P>
   The irregular beats continue whenever Horry exerts himself, but
the pain has subsided.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm feeling a whole lot better,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   __ Wormwatch: This should come as no surprise: Dennis Rodman
still is not a Laker.
</P>
<P>
   The Worm was reportedly going to sign a contract Tuesday, just
as he was reportedly going to do for the preceding three days, but
he was instead in Las Vegas. Insiders now say he is waiting until
Thursday, in order to make his Lakers debut in Friday's nationally
televised game against San Antonio.
</P>
<P>
   ``Marketing-wise, that would probably be a good thing to do,''
said Shaquille O'Neal, who has heard the same rumors. ``He has, I
don't want to say negative marketing, but . . . it's
negativity-positivity marketing.''
</P>
<P>
   __ Ouch report: Rick Fox returned to action after recovering
from an upper-respiratory infection.
</P>
<P>
   O'Neal, meanwhile, is showing no sign of being affected by a
groin strain that could be with him for a while.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's never going to go away. I'll have this problem for the
rest of my life,'' O'Neal said.
</P>
<P>
   But he's not heeding advice from his abdominal specialist, Alex
McKechnie, to slow down.
</P>
<P>
   ``Alex told me yesterday, `Don't dunk hard.' Me not dunking hard
is just me playing in my last years. And I can't play like that,''
he said. ``So whenever I step on the court, I go all out.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-17-99 0114EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
