</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-KNICKS-RAPTORS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KNICKS DEFEAT RAPTORS, 95-85 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 By SELENA ROBERTS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ They were giving Marcus Camby grief. The lanky young
fellow was just trying to put his coat on, collect his CD's and
exit discreetly after an emotional night at Madison Square Garden.
</P>
<P>
   But there was the chatty Chris Childs, poking at Camby's bright
yellow suit and ribbing him for mumbling his rap lyrics. And there
was a chuckling Larry Johnson, trying to straighten Camby's rumpled
collar like a father before his son's senior prom.
</P>
<P>
   Nothing but post-game grief. And that's when you knew: Camby has
been accepted by the very teammates who once wondered if he was a
tough enough to replace the scratch-resistant Charles Oakley.
</P>
<P>
   Camby's skin was thick enough to withstand Tuesday night, when
fan sentiment was with a former Knick who was clad like a Crayola
in Raptor purple. The indignity of it all for Oakley. The crowd was
with him and teetering in their opinion of Camby until Camby barged
his way into their hearts by scoring 11 points and grabbing 12
rebound in the Knicks' 95-85 victory.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was a whole lot of hoopla with Charles's return,'' said
Camby, who was acquired for Oakley on draft night last summer.
``I'm glad it's over for now. It felt real good to get the win. I
know Charles was really good for the time he was here. I knew the
crowd would be with him. I was just trying to play my game.''
</P>
<P>
   Oakley (11 points, 7 rebounds) decided on a peaceful
demonstration, and did not extract a pound of flesh from any member
of a Knick organization that makes him percolate with bitterness.
</P>
<P>
   Oakley's former partner, in good times and in bad, would not
allow sentiment to overcome the evening and provide the stage for
an upset by Toronto. Instead, Patrick Ewing shook off the fatigue
of back-to-back games and scored 11 of his 16 points during a tight
fourth quarter. Allan Houston, mired early with faulty aim, also
found his second wind to deliver a team-high 20 points.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was weird seeing him over there,'' Ewing said. ``We chatted
for a minute and then he tried to take my head off.''
</P>
<P>
   As the buzzer sounded, Oakley shuffled off without looking at
his former team. Ewing playfully popped him in the back with a
towel, but Oakley kept walking. Perhaps he expected more. Two hours
earlier, Oakley made a grand entrance by leading his team on the
floor for warm-ups and ran right into the warm embrace of the early
arrivals.
</P>
<P>
   The same hospitality was not offered by the organization.
Instead of playing a minutelong video tribute to Oakley in
appreciation of his decade of plow-horse-type effort before the
game, the Knicks showed the salute at halftime, when Oakley was in
the locker room and half the fans were at the concession stands.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was embarrassing,'' a dejected Oakley said. ``If they
wanted to do it, do it before the game.''
</P>
<P>
   The Knicks' management responded by claiming there was no other
time to show the video. The timing might have had something to do
with Mark Messier's return to the Garden last year. Messier was
moved to tears at the pre-game tribute. The Rangers were
emotionally drained as well and went on to lose that game to
Vancouver.
</P>
<P>
   But Oakley would most likely not have have teared up. He came to
the Garden bitter and angry at the Knicks' president, Ernie
Grunfeld, for his handling of the trade. So there were no
handshakes as he passed Ewing, the player he protected for a
decade. And there was no holding back. In a montage of Oak moments,
he hit the floor, crashed into the baseline seats and launched his
classic 18-foot jumpers. All this in the first half. As a topper,
Oakley defied his vertically challenged body and drove by Camby for
a layup and drew a foul. The fans lighted up.
</P>
<P>
   Camby could have blended into the background. He could have
given in to the pressure to be like Oakley and buckled under the
circumstance. But with a new-found edge, Camby shook off his
fragile wrap and stuck his neck inside the paint.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's finishing his plays around the basket, and that's good,''
Coach Jeff Van Gundy said. ``He tried to finesse a couple in the
last game. This time, he went with strength. We talked about that.
One thing about Marcus, you talk to him about something and he
tries to do it.''
</P>
<P>
   Camby listens well, plays hard. And he has found acceptance from
the toughest crowd of all: his teammates.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know how it is when you face your old team; you want to beat
them so bad,'' Johnson said. ``Marcus, he's coming around. He's
really looking good.''
</P>
<P>
   Well, except for the yellow suit.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-17-99 0124EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
