<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-DODGERS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DODGERS HAVE ANSWERS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BRIAN DOHN  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ There will be no search for a front-line starting
pitcher. Los Angeles Dodgers general Kevin Malone won't be burning
up phone lines in an attempt to add a bat to the middle of the
lineup.
</P>
<P>
   No, there won't be much drama in Dodgertown this spring. Panic?
Only if one of the offseason acquisitions _ Kevin Brown, Todd
Hundley or Devon White _ pulls up lame.
</P>
<P>
   The Dodgers don't have questions. They have answers.
</P>
<P>
   Pitchers and catchers voluntarily report Thursday, signaling six
weeks of soul-searching and gap-plugging at many major-league
camps.
</P>
<P>
   That's not the case with the Dodgers, however, installed here as
favorites to win the National League West and battle the Atlanta
Braves (who else would it be?) for a trip to the World Series.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe we're getting ahead of ourselves, but that's what the
Dodgers did in the offseason, getting ahead of nearly everyone in
the National League.
</P>
<P>
   ``The questions don't have to do with whether a guy can play at
this level or not,'' said first baseman Eric Karros. ``You know
Devon White can play center field. You know Jeff Shaw is a
major-league closer.''
</P>
<P>
   None of the issues facing the team seem daunting, but there are
a few things that need to be ironed out before the Dodgers face the
Arizona Diamondbacks in the April 5 season opener.
</P>
<P>
   __ The shortstop situation: The Dodgers want to know if Mark
Grudzielanek has improved enough defensively to play in the middle
of a championship team, or whether Jose Vizcaino's glove is enough
to offset his weak bat.
</P>
<P>
   __ A fifth starter: Figure Brown, Darren Dreifort, Chan Ho Park
and Carlos Perez as the top four. But will it be Dave Mlicki or
Ismael Valdes as the fifth starter? Or will one of the two be
traded or moved to the bullpen?
</P>
<P>
   ``That'll work itself out,'' Malone said. ``I don't have to do
anything at any time. I think it's better to be safe than to making
a deal and then someone gets injured.''
</P>
<P>
   __ Raul Mondesi: Reports are that he is not in great shape, but
he has the ability to drop weight quickly. And will the acquisition
of White, reunited with former Florida Marlins teammate Gary
Sheffield in the outfield, be a positive influence on Mondesi?
</P>
<P>
   __ Future of Dodgertown: Dodgertown has been the club's
spring-training home since 1948, but it's looking more and more
like the team will be headed to Arizona next season. Not only would
it be fiscally advantageous for the Dodgers to leave Vero Beach, it
would allow them a better opportunity to scout divisional teams
during spring training.
</P>
<P>
   However, don't expect an announcement regarding future plans
until after spring training. Many people close to the Dodgers
expect the change, but it could turn into a public relations fiasco
if it were announced with the team still in town.
</P>
<P>
   __ Todd Hundley's elbow: The former Mets catcher's surgically
repaired right elbow will be monitored closely. How it responds to
the rigors of catching can't be determined in six weeks of
Grapefruit League play. Consider it an ongoing situation that won't
have a resolution until July or August.
</P>
<P>
   Malone, and the Fox group, constructed the Dodgers so questions
wouldn't be prevalent in spring training, and they've succeeded.
Even to the point where Malone admits there's not a lot of
shuffling to be done.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's some things I would definitely like to continue to
improve,'' Malone said. ``We have to emphasize our defense. We have
to improve there. Other than that, we have to stay healthy and get
everyone on the same page.''
</P>
<P>
   In other words, it's about fine-tuning and not a major overhaul
or rebuilding.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's different from years past, but you can't compare it to
years past because you're comparing apples and oranges,'' Karros
said. ``You're comparing a club with a $90-million payroll to a
club that had some fiscal parameters. To compare this ownership
group to previous ownership groups, it's an injustice. It's not
fair.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
