<SLUG> BC-ANGLO-IRISH-PLAYS-$ADV21-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THIS SPRING, THE SEASON SPEAKS WITH AN ENGLISH ACCENT  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, FEB. 21) 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By ANDREA STEVENS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   In the 10 weeks between now and the cutoff date at the end of
April for Tony Award nominations, a crowd of visitors from the
British Isles will be taking their places on New York stages.
</P>
<P>
   Last season around this time, theatergoers were anticipating a
similar Anglo-Irish delivery of plays, performers and directors.
And next season is already shaping up as a busy one for London
imports.
</P>
<P>
   Is it all one way? Not quite. Currently on the boards in London
are some familiar-sounding shows: ``Annie,'' ``Chicago,'' ``Beauty
and the Beast'' and ``Rent.'' The productions incorporate the
American creative teams to some degree, while in the case of the
National Theater's acclaimed ``Oklahoma!,'' the American material
gets a British gloss.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the path to New York this season has already been
taken by Harold Pinter's ``Ashes to Ashes'' and David Hare's ``Blue
Room,'' among others. The first of the newer arrivals opens this
Thursday:
</P>
<P>
   `NOT ABOUT NIGHTINGALES' The story of how this recently
discovered early play by Tennessee Williams found its way to the
stage is a drama in itself. A cooperative effort by the Royal
National Theater in London, the Moving Theater (founded by Vanessa
Redgrave and her brother, Corin Redgrave) and the Alley Theater in
Houston, the drama is set in a brutal American prison in 1938.
</P>
<P>
   Redgrave, as the corrupt warden, leads a company of 18 British
and American actors, directed by Trevor Nunn, the artistic chief of
the National Theater. Now in previews at Circle in the Square on
Broadway, it opens on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   `VIA DOLOROSA' This is so much the playwright David Hare's
season on Broadway that he will be performing himself. The author
of the current ``Blue Room'' and the arriving ``Amy's View'' made
his acting debut in London in this one-man examination of the
Mideast.
</P>
<P>
   Inspired by a first-time visit to Israel in 1997, Hare's story
of his journey received very favorable reviews in London. The play,
directed by Stephen Daldry, begins previews on March 5 at the Booth
Theater, where it opens on March 18.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   `CLOSER' Several seasons ago, Patrick Marber's dark comedy
``Dealer's Choice,'' about poker, competition and fathers and sons,
made an appearance in New York. This time, the playwright, who
again directs, examines sexual competition (and jealousy) among men
and women.
</P>
<P>
   The four people involved are portrayed by Natasha Richardson,
Rupert Graves, Anna Friel and Ciaran Hinds. ``Closer,'' which won
the 1998 Olivier Award for best play (the British equivalent of the
Tony), begins previews at the Music Box Theater on March 9 and
opens on March 25. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   `THE WEIR' The young Irish playwright Conor McPherson arrived
Off Broadway last season with his quirky one-man narrative ``St.
Nicholas,'' about a theater critic amid a houseful of vampires.
Performed by Brian Cox, it won a handful of glowing reviews.
</P>
<P>
   This season, McPherson's tale of five people in a rural Irish
pub opens on Broadway at the Walter Kerr Theater on April 1. The
all-Irish cast includes Brendan Coyle, who just won an Olivier
Award for best supporting performance as the bartender. ``The
Weir'' itself took the Olivier for best play. Previews begin on
March 23.
</P>
<P>
   `THE ICEMAN COMETH' Kevin Spacey, the star, and Howard Davies,
the director, have won the triple crown for this four-hour-plus
visit to Harry Hope's bar by Eugene O'Neill. The two recently
walked away with the Oliviers for best actor and best director.
They had already won the Evening Standard and London Critics Circle
awards.
</P>
<P>
   In New York, the cast will include a number of actors from the
Almeida Theater production in London, as well as such new arrivals
as Robert Sean Leonard, Tony Danza, Paul Giamatti and Jeff Weiss.
Previews begin March 29 at the Brooks Atkinson Theater, where the
play opens on April 8.
</P>
<P>
   `MARLENE' Sian Phillips will be repeating her London role as
Marlene Dietrich in Pam Gems' musical play. Backstage in a Paris
concert hall in 1969, Dietrich prepares for her final farewell
concert tour. If that means scrubbing the floor herself, so be it.
Directed by Sean Mathias. Previews begin March 30 at the Cort
Theater. The show opens on April 11. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   `AMY'S VIEW' David Hare's play about the disjunction between
what life should be and what it is brings Judi Dench back to
Broadway after 40 years. In this valentine to the stage, Dame Judi
plays an actress who is passionate about the theater, and the
mother of Amy, portrayed by Samantha Bond. Directed by Richard
Eyre, the play begins previews on April 3 at the Ethel Barrymore
Theater and opens on April 15. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Off Broadway, McPherson's play ``This Lime Tree Bower'' opens in
May at Primary Stages, the same month that the New Group presents
Ayub Khan-Din's bittersweet comedy ``East Is East,'' about growing
up in an Asian family in the north of England. This summer, Lincoln
Center Festival will present a lineup of Irish theater.
</P>
<P>
   And what of next season? ``Saturday Night Fever,'' the stage
version of the 1977 movie and a hit in London, is heading to
Broadway, as is Peter Hall's current revival of ``Amadeus'' by
Peter Shaffer.
</P>
<P>
   Yasmina Reza, the author of ``Art,'' will be back in New York
with ``The Unexpected Man.'' The hope is that Michael Gambon and
Eileen Atkins will repeat their London roles.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
