<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-17 01:35 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8071 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CORIN-REDGRAVE-THEATE     02-17 0664
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CORIN-REDGRAVE-THEATER-2TAKES-$ADV21-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A REDGRAVE MOVES UP IN THE FAMILY BUSINESS  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, FEB. 21) 
</HEADLINE>
   (Eds: Please note subslug for NIGHTINGALES-THEATER)  
 (af)  
 Matt Wolf is the London theater critic for Variety and a regular
writer on the arts from Europe.  
 By MATT WOLF   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON _ There will be two unfamiliar entities onstage when
``Not About Nightingales'' opens on Thursday at Circle in the
Square on Broadway.
</P>
<P>
   First, of course, will be Tennessee Williams' fierce, lyrical
prison play, having its belated New York premiere 61 years after it
was written. And second, playing the central role of the warden,
will be Corin Redgrave, who has not been on Broadway since 1963 and
who is the least known of the famous acting Redgraves.
</P>
<P>
   With the imposing demeanor of the politician he has often played
and might have been, Redgrave, 59, is the middle brother to Lynn
and Vanessa, the son of the late Sir Michael.
</P>
<P>
   Redgrave made his initial trip to Broadway as an aristocratic
young pilot in ``Chips With Everything,'' Arnold Wesker's play
about class divisions among a group of Royal Air Force cadets.
After that transfer from the Royal Court Theater in London, he
dropped from the view of New York theatergoers, devoting much time
at home to left-wing politics.
</P>
<P>
   He was often joined in his crusades by Vanessa, who is two years
his senior. But whereas Vanessa Redgrave has fought to advance both
her political views and her eminent career, Redgrave could for many
years be found beating the drum for the Socialist Labor League or
the Workers' Revolutionary Party, rather than playing Hamlet,
Antony, Vanya or any of his distinguished father's other signature
roles.
</P>
<P>
   Only recently has his acting elicited more attention than his
activism. In addition to what Ben Brantley, writing in The New York
Times, called an ``outsize, satanic'' performance as Boss Whalen in
``Not About Nightingales,'' Redgrave has been acclaimed in
productions of plays by Martin Sherman (``Some Sunny Day''),
Richard Nelson (``The General From America'') and Noel Coward (``A
Song at Twilight''), as well as onscreen as Sir Walter Elliot in
``Persuasion.''
</P>
<P>
   As Redgrave describes it, chatting amiably in the front room of
his South London home, the uptick in his career has more to do with
external factors than with any change in himself. ``I would have a
lot of complaints if I ever sat down and thought about it too
much,'' he said, sounding less angry than regretful about all the
work he has never been offered. ``There are parts for a long time
in your life you can play, and then suddenly you know you're not
going to play them.''
</P>
<P>
   Redgrave did what he could to create his own opportunities,
founding the Moving Theater with his older sister. (It was the
Moving Theater that co-produced the world premiere of ``Not About
Nightingales'' at the Royal National Theater last year, in
association with the Alley Theater in Houston.) But, he said, for
24 years, ``I didn't work in BBC television, which is one of the
major employers then and now.''
</P>
<P>
   Then, in 1994, he drove into a BBC parking lot, on the way to
film a production of ``Measure for Measure'': ``I remember saying
to myself, `How strange: here I am again, and it's 1994, and I was
last here in 1970.' I had one or two avenues like the Young Vic,
doing usually one play a year. But even there, the theater got a
little bit of a backlash for employing people like me. They were
told, `You've got to stop being so political a theater.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Still, others see in his recent success an actor newly
invigorated in his art. ``Corin is like a man who has suddenly
decided to cultivate his garden, having let it run down,'' said
Simon Callow, who appeared with Redgrave in the film ``Four
Weddings and a Funeral'' in 1994 and then directed him on the West
End last year in ``HRH,'' a play by Snoo Wilson about the Duke and
Duchess of Windsor.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   `It's not that Corin has mellowed,'' Callow said. ``He's still a
very clear and convinced Trotskyist. But whatever it is that has
relaxed in him, has enabled him to release all these
possibilities.''
</P>
<P>
   Peter Hall, the veteran theater director who has known the
Redgrave family more than 30 years, said about Redgrave: ``He was
always a very sound actor; he has become a great one. What has
happened now is that he seems to have inherited the mantle of his
father in a major way.''
</P>
<P>
   That inheritance, paradoxically, may result in part from
Redgrave's ability at last to step away from the shadow of his
father, who died in 1985. (The son has movingly examined his
father's legacy in a 1995 book, ``Michael Redgrave _ My Father''
and a subsequent television documentary.)
</P>
<P>
   ``Now there's a power in knowing that what Corin does onstage is
his own thing,'' said his sister Lynn. Four years younger than he,
she has herself recently re-energized her career, winning an Oscar
nomination for her performance in the film ``Gods and Monsters.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I went to see him as Rosmer,'' Ms. Redgrave said, about a
Young Vic production of Ibsen's ``Rosmersholm'' in 1992, ``and
there were all those things again that he was wonderfully as a
young actor; suddenly, he was free.''
</P>
<P>
   Roger Michell, who has directed Redgrave in three different
disciplines in as many years _ the play ``Some Sunny Day,'' the
film ``Persuasion'' and the television documentary about Michael
Redgrave _ favors a political explanation.
</P>
<P>
   ``I see the renaissance of Corin's career coinciding with the
fall of the Berlin Wall,'' Michell said. ``I don't think the battle
was lost, but the dogmatism was put to bed perhaps. Corin is
flexing different muscles, and I'm thrilled for him.''
</P>
<P>
   Vanessa Redgrave also spoke about the toll politics took on her
brother's career. ``There was a period when Corin was
blacklisted,'' she said. ``There was a period when I was
blacklisted. It's very frustrating if you can't get work and you're
out of work. How do you pay your bills? It's not a question of
frustration; it's a question of being demented.''
</P>
<P>
   Redgrave said that the instability of his career had caused
periods of financial difficulty. Yet there was some respite in the
fact that because of the varying ages of his four children from two
marriages, he was never responsible for all of them at the same
time.
</P>
<P>
   For 22 years, he has lived on an unprepossessing street in an
area known as Balham. The actor said dryly that the neighborhood
``has virtually no distinguishing marks at all.'' He first moved
there to join Kika Markham, an actress he married 13 years ago.
Their older son, Harvey, 20, is in his first year at Manchester
University; the younger, Arden, 15, attends a nearby high school.
</P>
<P>
   Redgrave's daughter, Jemma, 33, is an actress; his oldest son,
Luke, 30, works on movie sets as a focus-puller. Redgrave and their
mother, Deirdre Hamilton-Hill, who died just over a year ago of
cancer, were divorced in 1980.
</P>
<P>
   In her 1986 memoir, ``A Family and Its Fortunes,'' Redgrave's
mother, the actress Rachel Kempson, who is 89, suggested that the
intensity of Redgrave's political life contributed to the
dissolution of his first marriage.
</P>
<P>
   In conversation, Redgrave is still more passionate when riffing
on the privatization of Britain's railroads or on the Clinton
impeachment hearings (``that ghastly and absurd trial'') than when
he is reflecting upon, say, a past movie role.
</P>
<P>
   But he will allow himself some gratified murmurings about the
current state of his professional life. And, indeed, that evening
he would be taking the stage in ``A Song at Twilight,'' for which
he received excellent reviews.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you get to a certain time in your life,'' Redgrave said,
``which is probably the most productive and creative time in your
life, nevertheless it's also a time when you have to both make
opportunities and seize them because you know they're not
necessarily going to happen again.''
</P>
<P>
   So is he in his prime?
</P>
<P>
   ``We shall see,'' Redgrave said, ``whether, after all, this is
one of those plateaus where you've climbed a great height, and yet
there's always something beyond. Hopefully, there's always
something beyond.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-17-99 0135EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990217.0041 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-17 01:36 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8073 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SHAPERO-CLASSICAL-SYM     02-17 1063
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SHAPERO-CLASSICAL-SYMPHONY-2TAKES-$ADV21-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A WORK TWICE LOST, NOW TWICE FOUND?  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, FEB. 21) 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Mass.)   (af)  
 By ANTHONY TOMMASINI   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The history of music is filled with accounts of major new works
that received prominent premieres only to languish thereafter and
sometimes virtually disappear.
</P>
<P>
   Even when everything breaks right in the beginning, it is
difficult for a work to achieve wide exposure, let alone repertory
status. Take the Symphony for Classical Orchestra by the respected
American Neo-Classical composer Harold Shapero.
</P>
<P>
   Shapero was 27 when he completed this 45-minute work, which was
given its promising first performance in January 1948 by the Boston
Symphony Orchestra and Leonard Bernstein, who was then 29. Two
months later, George Szell conducted it with the Cleveland
Orchestra.
</P>
<P>
   And on one hectic day in 1953, Bernstein and the Columbia
Symphony Orchestra recorded the piece in New York, producing a
remarkable performance that circulated for years and won the
symphony admirers among musicians and composers sympathetic to
Neo-Classicism. That recording, long unavailable, has now been
reissued by Sony Classical in its Bernstein Century series (SMK
60725; CD).
</P>
<P>
   The symphony, meanwhile, gradually fell into oblivion, until
Andre Previn and the Los Angeles Philharmonic performed it to
acclaim in 1986. They brought it back the next season in another
critical and audience triumph, but the piece has since been
languishing again.
</P>
<P>
   How can a major work, introduced so auspiciously, get lost for
more than three decades, then come back and get lost again? The
answers speak to the difficulty all new music faces in gaining an
audience, and whatever the reasons, this is a dismaying and
cautionary tale.
</P>
<P>
   Shapero, who was born in Lynn, Mass., in 1920, studied piano as
a young man. He played jazz for fun and for profit, and later did
arrangements for Benny Goodman's band. One of his first composition
teachers, Ernst Krenek, tutored him in 12-tone technique, but at
Harvard University Shapero fell strongly under the influence of
Igor Stravinsky, who presented the Norton Lectures there in the
1939-40 academic year.
</P>
<P>
   Aaron Copland, too, became an important mentor and friend to
Shapero. Impressed with the young composer's early Woodwind
Quintet, Copland sent a teasing note to Bernstein, who was two
years ahead of Shapero at Harvard: ``Look to your laurels! There
may be another composer in your neighborhood!''
</P>
<P>
   When Shapero started composing his symphony, he thought he was
writing a divertimento of, say, 20 minutes. ``But I had wildly
miscalculated my materials,'' he said recently from his home in
Natick, Mass. ``When I measured out the slow movement, I was
shocked. It was 15 minutes. I stopped working for a month. Then I
tried to cut the thing. But it fought me and won. Slowly I became
aware, with horror, of what I was writing: a long and difficult
symphony. I thought I'd never get it performed.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, Shapero received a modest award from the Koussevitzky
Foundation. ``When my friend Copland heard the news,'' Shapero
said, ``he kidded me: `You're the only jerk who would write a piece
like that for $500.''' But it was enough to make a difference.
</P>
<P>
   Then Bernstein got interested. He and Shapero had become good
friends at Harvard. In 1947, Bernstein had a guest stint with the
Boston Symphony, and seeing the newly completed manuscript of the
symphony one day, ``he kind of scooped it up and took it away,''
Shapero said.
</P>
<P>
   The work is indeed long and difficult. But it has many admirers,
including the critic Alan Rich, who, after Previn's performance,
called it ``the greatest American symphony.''
</P>
<P>
   In the late 1940s, Neo-Classicism, an attempt to reinvigorate
Classical forms and procedures with innovative harmonic and
rhythmic techniques, was a vital movement in American composition,
and Shapero believed intensely in the creative value of looking
back.
</P>
<P>
   The imitation of a model, he argued in a 1946 article in the
journal Modern Music, could bring about the discovery of personal
materials in a musician's own voice. Stravinsky, he noted, was fond
of repeating a remark of his own teacher, Rimsky-Korsakov: ``I
don't like that which resembles nothing.''
</P>
<P>
   The models for Shapero, in this work and in general, were
Stravinsky, who was then in his prolonged Neo-Classical period, and
Beethoven, who remains Shapero's hero. Indeed, the Symphony for
Classical Orchestra is in some ways a soul mate of Beethoven's
Seventh Symphony, which it slyly quotes.
</P>
<P>
   As in the Beethoven, the first of its four movements opens with
an Adagio that shimmers with flickering colors and sustained
harmonies, leading to a long, bustling, contrapuntal Allegro. The
second movement is a wistfully lyrical yet rhythmically restless
Adagietto; then comes a misbehaving Scherzo, which hurtles toward
the imposingly structured but spirited Finale.
</P>
<P>
   Shapero, however, fractures the Classical models while paying
homage. The piece is essentially tonal, with the outer movements
hewing to B flat; but the harmonic language contains elements of
polytonality, and the music is spiky with dissonance, rhythmically
shifty and utterly fresh. Phrases are filled with surprising
asymmetries.
</P>
<P>
   There is a youthful challenge in Shapero's tribute, as if he
were saying, ``Take that, Beethoven!'' It's the same quality that
you hear in early Beethoven: ``I'll show you, my revered teacher
Haydn, how to write a piano sonata.'' Or that you see in early
Picasso: ``Take that, Cezanne!''
</P>
<P>
   Bernstein's premiere performance received mixed reviews, and an
unfavorable one from Cyrus Durgin, of the Boston Globe, who was
still fighting modern music, Shapero said. ``He once wrote that
Stravinsky should study Rachmaninoff to learn how to write for the
orchestra.'' But there was a buzz about the piece among musicians.
</P>
<P>
   The experience with Szell in Cleveland was exasperating. ``Szell
was a fabulous musician who hated modern music,'' Shapero said.
``He summoned me, asked me to play the piece on the piano, then
told me I didn't know how to modulate and should study Richard
Strauss.'' Under pressure to perform works by Americans, Szell
agreed to present the symphony. The reviews were equivocal at best,
hostile at worst.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   With further support from the Koussevitzky Foundation, Bernstein
recorded the work in New York with the Columbia Symphony, a
freelance ensemble drawn for recording purposes from the best
musicians of the area. On the day of the recording, Bernstein had a
temperature of 102, Shapero said. ``During one break, he took a cab
uptown to get his doctor to shoot him full of penicillin.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet the performance is bracing, rhythmically vivid and full of
character. It spread the gospel of the work for the moment. But
performances failed to materialize.
</P>
<P>
   As years went by, the symphony fell victim to the polemical
battles that flared in the 1960s and 70s between atonal and
Serialist composers, on one hand, and Neo-Classicists like Shapero,
who adhered to some semblance of tonality, on the other. Many of
Shapero's works were deemed conservative by those who advocated
12-tone procedures and claimed the intellectual high ground.
</P>
<P>
   Shapero, who had been teaching at Brandeis University since
1950, was stung by the criticism, and his compositional output
declined severely in the 1960s and after. Asked about the falloff,
he answers only with self-deprecating barbs.
</P>
<P>
   Yet it remains curious that Bernstein, who had been such a
champion of the symphony, later neglected it, since he continued to
conduct Neo-Classical and neo-Romantic symphonies of less merit by
composers like Roy Harris, David Diamond and others. Occasionally
Bernstein would perform the slow movement on a program. But all in
all, it was discouraging, Shapero said. ``Once he told me, `I could
play the whole thing, but why should I knock myself out for you?'
Was he kidding? I couldn't figure it out.''
</P>
<P>
   Then, in 1986, John Harbison, an admirer of Shapero's music and
at the time composer-in-residence at the Los Angles Philharmonic,
brought the symphony to Previn's attention. The conductor was
completely taken with it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Out of the blue one day,'' Shapero recalled, ``I got a call,
saying: `This is Andre Previn. I want to perform your symphony.' I
thought it was a hoax and nearly hung up.''
</P>
<P>
   Martin Bernheimer, then the critic of The Los Angeles Times and
never one to mollycoddle contemporary works, made a point of
shaking Shapero's hand after the performance and wrote a glowing
review. The response was so enthusiastic that Previn brought the
work back in 1988. A recording, drawn from two of the performances
that year, was released by New World Records and is still
available.
</P>
<P>
   Previn took the work on guest-conducting appearances over the
next two years with the major orchestras in Pittsburgh, Cleveland
and Boston. He was scheduled to perform it with the Chicago
Symphony as well, but took ill. The concert was covered on short
notice by Christopher Keene.
</P>
<P>
   ``Poor fellow,'' Shapero said of Keene, who died in 1995. ``He
was so scared by it, he could not be talked out of taking the outer
movements at almost half the proper tempos.''
</P>
<P>
   It remains a challenging work for players, as was clear when
Previn conducted the work with the Boston Symphony in 1990. The
shape and character of the piece came through, and the audience
gave it a prolonged ovation. But the playing was tentative and
rough.
</P>
<P>
   Shapero is indebted to Previn, whom he calls ``the most
excellent and self-effacing conductor imaginable.'' Since those
performances, apart from a few in 1994 and 1995 by Roger Nierenberg
and the Jacksonville Symphony in Florida, the symphony has again
disappeared from major concert halls.
</P>
<P>
   When contacted for this article, Shapero was not aware that Sony
had reissued the Bernstein recording, which he had not heard in
years. He recalled it as being a bit driven and hyperactive. He
admires Previn's recording greatly.
</P>
<P>
   That account is strong and clear, to be sure. But Previn tends
to milk the patches of sweet lyricism, the moments that recall the
bucolic quietude of Copland in his Americana vein. Bernstein lets
the lyricism of those passages take care of itself and concentrates
on rendering the rhythms with crispness and energy. And he projects
a visceral sense of the work as an architectonic whole.
</P>
<P>
   The Bernstein recording, called ``Modern Masters,'' also offers
shorter works by Luigi Dallapiccola and Nikolai Lopatnikoff in
stirring performances that indicate how involved Bernstein was with
new music in this important first stage of his career.
</P>
<P>
   Shapero, who has been retired from Brandeis for 10 years, does
not discount the degree to which a certain lack of initiative may
have contributed to the neglect to his symphony and his other
works. ``I'm not good at pushing, or at cultivating people,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Previn has been an invaluable champion. But it is time for
someone else of his stature to take up the fight. Maybe it will
happen, especially now that the contemporary-music scene has become
less fractious and more open-minded. And the historic and
electrifying Bernstein recording, again available, could make a big
difference.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
