<HEADER>
A8078 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MORELL-PHOTOGS-ART-$A     02-17 1188
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MORELL-PHOTOGS-ART-$ADV21-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHERE CHILD'S PLAY AND JUST PLAIN FACTS RENDEZVOUS ON FILM 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Mass., N.Y., Maine)   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.)  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, FEB. 21)  
 (af)  
 Deborah Weisgall's most recent article for Arts and Leisure was on
the biennial exhibition at the Portland Museum in Maine.  
 By DEBORAH WEISGALL   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Until 1986, Abelardo Morell worked as a street
photographer. He stalked the quick shot, a fleeting conjunction of
action, form and light. But when his son, Brady, was born, he says,
``I started taking pictures from the point of view of a child.''
</P>
<P>
   Morell stayed home and played, photographing what he
encountered: a playground slide, a paper bag, pots and pans
refracted through the lenses of a pair of eyeglasses. His notion of
time slowed, and he made exposures lasting for several minutes.
Like a child, he explored the world around him, but his abrupt
change of focus served as a means to reveal an interior world of
emotion.
</P>
<P>
   The exhibition ``Abelardo Morell and the Camera Eye,'' at the
Museum of Fine Arts through April 11, documents these
investigations with 70 images. It was organized by Diana Gaston,
curator at the Museum of Photographic Arts in San Diego.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had wanted to do this show for several years,'' Ms. Gaston
said. ``Abe Morell is one of the most important photographers in
the country and has been in lots of group exhibitions, but he has
never had a one-person show.''
</P>
<P>
   Over the next three years the show is to travel to eight
museums. In the spring, Morell's work will also be shown at the
Fogg Art Museum in Cambridge, and last month, Dutton published an
edition of ``Alice's Adventures in Wonderland'' illustrated with
Morell's photographs, which juxtapose Tenniel's original drawings
with real objects: playing cards, books and water.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, he was artist-in-residence at the Isabella Stewart
Gardner Museum here, and some of his witty views of the museum's
paintings hang in the current show.
</P>
<P>
   Although all this visibility seems sudden, Morell has been
emerging, like a slow exposure, for much of this decade. The Museum
of Modern Art first bought his work in 1991, and now he is
represented in the collections of more than 40 American museums,
including the Metropolitan, the Whitney and the Art Institute of
Chicago.
</P>
<P>
   ``He has accumulated enough work so that people really know
him,'' says Anne Havinga, assistant curator of prints, drawings and
photography at the Boston Museum of Fine Arts. ``It's appropriate
to have a retrospective now. Abe takes pictures of the everyday
world, yet they're full of fantasy. With a straightforward
technique, he achieves special effects of magic and wonder.''
</P>
<P>
   Success at the age of 50 perplexes him, Morell said in a recent
interview. His hair is turning gray, but his unlined face makes him
look young. ``Maybe it's my need to work hard, coupled with a sense
of urgency,'' he says. ``I had angioplasty last year and realized
I'm not a little boy any longer.''
</P>
<P>
   He chooses his words precisely and speaks with a barely
perceptible Cuban accent. Morell was born in Cuba in 1948; in 1962,
his parents fled to New York. His father found a job as
superintendent of an apartment building, where the family lived in
a basement unit.
</P>
<P>
   Morell learned English, he says, by reading Hemingway. At
Bowdoin College in Brunswick, Maine, which he attended on a full
scholarship, he set out to study engineering.
</P>
<P>
   ``But I was failing physics, so I dropped it and took a
photography course,'' he said, smiling. ``That was much better.''
He pauses. ``From Cuba to New York to Maine. What a change: all
that gray light.'' He works only in black and white.
</P>
<P>
   Some images _ ``Slide,'' for example, dating from 1988 _ are,
like Hemingway's sentences, deceptively simple. Below its top step,
where the embossed name of the manufacturer has been erased by
generations of children's feet and bottoms, the metal slide
shimmers like a waterfall spilling forever in dread and delight.
But an awareness of gravity, of how short the drop really is,
haunts the photograph.
</P>
<P>
   In Morell's work, the intersection of the playful mind and plain
facts seems almost a physical place, an image achieved by simple
means: light, length of exposure and sometimes the old magic trick
underlying the physics of photography. After he received a master's
degree from Yale, he joined the Bowdoin faculty; a year later he
became a professor of photography at the Massachusetts College of
Art in Boston.
</P>
<P>
   For his students, he constructed a camera obscura, a device
invented over four centuries ago, literally a dark room, or box,
with only a pinhole. Light entering through the pinhole projects on
the inner walls of the box an inverted image of what lies outside
it.
</P>
<P>
   In 1991, Morell decided to photograph those illusions. He
started at home, using his bedroom in Brookline. The photograph,
resulting from an eight-hour exposure, shows neighbors' houses
hanging upside down over the bed and shadowy leaves dappling the
spread.
</P>
<P>
   Then Morell took his camera on the road. In a Times Square hotel
room, cars on Broadway streak along the ceiling, and signs
advertising musicals and credit cards blaze upside down and
backward on the walls. The spire of the Empire State Building
drapes like a silver robe across a quilt in a friend's midtown
apartment.
</P>
<P>
   During a 1997 vacation in Wyoming, Morell revealed outdoor
furniture and the Tetons hovering like ghostly stalactites in his
motel; the tip of the Grand Teton tickles a souvenir plastic elk
standing on a table. Translucent exteriors, hazy as memory, settle
over the rooms. The elk, bed posts, a coffee mug: long exposures
have burned these presences into the film, intensifying their stark
solidity. The space is both crowded and empty.
</P>
<P>
   ``These photographs show that even when you are alone in a room,
you are not alone,'' Morell says.
</P>
<P>
   The mystery of place, the tension between affection and
detachment, informs Morell's work. He left his childhood home
behind at 14, and his early efforts reflected, he says, this lack
of connection.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was an anonymous person looking at an anonymous situation.
But you can't be anonymous with your family. You can't give babies
baths without touching them.'' His photographs express this sense
of tender surprise, a pure astonishment at connection. ``Now, what
I'm feeling and what I'm seeing are one,'' Morell said. ``I've got
a lot of inventive energy now, but I won't have it forever.'' And
every photograph also records the short span of the conjuction of
eye and heart.
</P>
<P>
   ``Brady Looking at His Shadow,'' from 1990, shows his son, in
silhouette, facing his shadow on a wall. The source of light is
low, in angle and in wattage; both the boy and his tall shadow are
blurred, both equally insubstantial. Brady could not keep still for
the long exposure. Only a child's chair against the wall emerges
clear and immutable, immune to time.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
