<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-17 01:48 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8082 &Cx1f; taf-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-WOMENS-FASHION-ART-NY     02-17 1313
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WOMENS-FASHION-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WARMTH AND WEARABILITY, BUT WHERE'S THE SURPRISE 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photos have been sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(sw) 
 By ANNE-MARIE SCHIRO   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Remember the scene in ``Jurassic Park'' when the T.
rex is chasing the car and the side mirror carries the warning
about reflected objects being closer than they look? Some designers
seem to be riding along oblivious to how close and how fast the new
millennium is approaching.
</P>
<P>
   How else to explain why Marc Jacobs, one of the brightest and
most lauded American fashion stars, should troll the 1970s and
beyond for the fall 1999/winter 2000 collection he showed Monday
night?
</P>
<P>
   Not that the clothes didn't look great. There were cozy
hand-knit cashmere sweaters, graceful calf-length skirts worn with
glossy leather boots, well-cut coats, and capes with a military
air. But they represented a style that might have been worn a
generation ago by the mothers of the young fashion editors seated
at the show. Even the men's clothes, classy and classic styles like
cashmere sweat shirts, corduroy jeans and double-face cashmere
coats, looked familiar.
</P>
<P>
   Jacobs, however, must get credit for showing more variety than
he has in some past seasons. Skirts were cut like aprons or had low
pleats or ruffles at the hem attached with cartridge pleats. Tops
with tucklike folds were worn over thin wool camisoles or cashmere
T-shirts. A wide stole was held closed with a large button. And
there were alternatives to trousers and jeans in the form of
cropped pants that Jacobs called breeches.
</P>
<P>
   The pretty cerulean blue of last season gave way to muted
heathery shades and earth tones, with deep purple and black velvet,
and metallic tulle for evening.
</P>
<P>
   And Jacobs can certainly not be faulted for concentrating on
knitwear, which has dominated fashion for the last year. Hand-knit
turtlenecks and chunky fishermen's knits have turned up on many
runways and are sure to make even more appearances before the fall
show season ends in Paris next month.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the best knits seen so far were in the Tse New York show
designed by Hussein Chalayan. He called the collection the Bed and
presented it on a large square runway with a cube suspended from
the ceiling, like a fireplace in a modern winter cabin, with
simulated blazes crackling and the scent of a homey hearth
permeating the air.
</P>
<P>
   Big labels like those on blankets were prominently placed on
some skirts and dresses, and hems were sometimes finished with
blanket stitching, to stress the notion of warm clothes for a cold
winter. Fabrics were mainly cashmere, boiled wool or felted wool in
white, black or neutral grays and shades of brown from beige to
chocolate.
</P>
<P>
   Neat, simple shapes were made interesting with hand-knit cables
or novelty stitches, with tiny knot prints, with blocks of
contrasting fabric or color, or with connect-the-dot embroidery.
Mr. Chalayan also showed jackets and coats with modifications of
the asymmetric necklines and closures he featured in his signature
collection last season. This provocative, much-scrutinized designer
has succeeded in adapting some of his extreme notions for a more
commercial client, and giving the results a signature that sets Tse
New York apart from just another knit collection.
</P>
<P>
   Stephen DiGeronimo also concentrated on knits for fall, in a
collection that included similar styles for men and women. Both
sexes sported rugby-striped cashmeres in yellow and camel,
loose-fitting fishermen's knits, hooded pullovers with kangaroo
pockets, and pea coats. The collection wasn't one to break new
ground, but it was also nothing for the designer to be ashamed of.
It worked just fine.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the cowboy boots, gaucho pants and square-dance music at
the BCBG Max Azria show, the clothes were not gimmicky in the
least. Azria showed hand-knit sweaters (what else is new?), long
skirts and wide-leg pants of wool felt or mohair plaid, hooded
coats of shearling or mohair, and sheer evening dresses accented
with sparkling beads.
</P>
<P>
   There were apron dresses with cutouts in back, including one in
black leather, and jackets and coats with invisible closures and
unexpected touches like bright red shearling. From a purely
commercial line that in past seasons has adapted all the trends of
the moment, BCBG has developed into a line with character.
</P>
<P>
   Mary McFadden has always had a signature look that includes
embroidered and beaded tunic jackets, pleating and references to
exotic cultures that only someone as steeped in research as Ms.
McFadden herself could differentiate. But no matter. She has a
following that appreciates the timelessness of her designs, the
flattery of the colors and decorations, and the beauty of the
clothes.
</P>
<P>
   This time, she looked to ancient Mongolia, adapting 13th-century
block prints and 17th-century Buddhist paintings, opening her show
with a Mongolian wedding coat of white with an intricate design in
red and black, and ending it with a bride in a coat covered with
green and gold embroidery and topped with a towering gold hat.
</P>
<P>
   Oscar de la Renta may be best known for extravagant evening
creations, but he keeps up with the times and the preferences of
his customers, who now range from the likes of the elegant Judy
Peabody to the young Aerin Lauder. So, in addition to satin ball
gowns that can be adorned with a woman's precious jewels, he also
provides beaded cashmere twin sets and turtlenecks with a row of
discreet beading at the hem, and satin anoraks and parkas. For day,
there are brushed wool coats and jackets, some in blousy shapes
with zippers, to team with camel wool pants and cashmere
turtlenecks. Some of the day clothes have couture touches like
crewel embroidery, which adds dimension and texture to tweed skirts
and cardigans.
</P>
<P>
   Vivienne Westwood brought her Red Label collection to Seventh
Avenue for the first time on Tuesday, to celebrate the opening of
her New York boutique. The show was held in the Celeste Bartos
Forum at the Public Library on 42nd Street, which Ms. Westwood had
decked out with a stage set of a gray brick wall covered with
flowering vines. Models entered by ducking through a too-low Gothic
archway and descending a few steps to a red-carpeted runway.
</P>
<P>
   The iconoclastic designer has obviously decided she wants to
sell clothes seriously, so most of the styles were quite normal,
running to patterned knit dresses, plaid jackets, kilts and even a
ladylike gray princess-shaped coat. But the accouterments tended to
the outrageous, with models' faces painted blue or red, and with an
abundance of accessories like leg warmers, blankets worn as shawls,
scarves, hats, bags, gloves and oversize jewelry, with some
necklaces made of beads the size of Christmas ornaments.
</P>
<P>
   It was all good fun, and so was Betsey Johnson's show Monday
evening in a Mercedes-Benz warehouse in mid-Manhattan. The green
neon sign with the designer's name and the three cars on display
where the models came out were just background for a wacky show
that she called ``7 Sisters.''
</P>
<P>
   Her program notes defined them as spooky sisters ``with very
witchy lives.'' They included Morbida the oddity, who wore florals
and flounces; Infantina the baby, who wore baby doll dresses;
Lascivia the sybarite, in muslin and gauze, and Urchina the
wanderer, whose get-ups included sequined ski vests and corsets.
</P>
<P>
   Not all the action was on the runway, however. Before the show,
photographers were in a frenzy over Steven Tyler of Aerosmith, Lou
Reed, Tia and Tamera Mowry of ``Sister, Sister,'' Debbie Harry,
Dylan McDermott of ``The Practice '' and Amanda Lepore, a
transsexual with flaming red hair and lips, who was totally nude
except for multiple strands of gold beads.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
