<HEADER>
A8084 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-SUNS-ROCKETS-HNS &LR;      02-17 0929
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-SUNS-ROCKETS-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JONATHAN FEIGEN  
 c. 1999, Houston Chronicle  
Scottie Pippen, goofing through a particularly entertaining run,
made a sleight-of-hand, three-card-monte fake for a layup. Matt
Bullard went up for an Air Jordan-logo dunk. Othella Harrington was
so unstoppable, the Suns gave him the Hakeem Olajuwon defensive
treatment.
<TEXT>
<P>
   If the Rockets tried it in Tuesday night's second half at Compaq
Center, it worked. They laughed when Bullard went up for his
ridiculous dunk attempt. They were in awe of Pippen's mastery of
the open court. They were relieved by Harrington and Olajuwon's
combined excellence inside in the absence of Charles Barkley.
</P>
<P>
   The Rockets whipped the Suns in the second half to begin the
toughest part of their schedule with a 109-92 rout and even got
some rest for their regulars in their most complete performance of
the season.
</P>
<P>
   The Rockets had five players in double figures, made 51.9
percent of their shots, outrebounded the Suns by 10 and made up for
the absence of the injured Barkley with huge games from Olajuwon
and Harrington.
</P>
<P>
   And Pippen dominated everywhere, coming within an assist of a
triple double. He finished with 19 points, 12 rebounds and nine
assists.
</P>
<P>
   As the Rockets (5-1) head off to the road portion of a stretch
that will have them playing five games in six days, there are just
two concerns that will come along for the ride. With Barkley and
Antoine Carr already out with injuries, the Rockets lost backup
center Stanley Roberts for two weeks with a strained right
hamstring. And when Phoenix hit an early wall, the Rockets had to
wonder if by the weekend they would end up looking as worn as the
Suns did Tuesday, when they played the second game of a
back-to-back.
</P>
<P>
   But those things aside, the Rockets had a locker room full of
contributors and their first runaway win of the season.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had a great time tonight,'' Bullard said. ``I really love
our team this year. All the guys get along great, and we play well
together.''
</P>
<P>
   They had never played as well as in Tuesday's second half, when
they took a tied game and turned it into a chance to save strength
for games to come. And unlike previous wins when Barkley was forced
to carry them for key stretches, the Rockets had more scorers than
the Suns knew what to do with.
</P>
<P>
   That became most obvious when, filling the wing on a fast break,
Bullard found his path to the basket blocked and decided to leap
for a be-like-Mike dunk. ``I was flying,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   He never got to the rim, Chris Morris having come over to pull
him back down. Bullard got up to hit both free throws, then 16
seconds later took a fast-break pass from Pippen to nail a 26-foot
3-pointer for a 79-62 lead.
</P>
<P>
   Bullard added a fourth-quarter 3 and finished with 14 points in
21 minutes off the bench.
</P>
<P>
   But his scoring, as well as Michael Dickerson's 18 points and
Cuttino Mobley's seven, was actually set up long before when the
Suns could not begin to stop Harrington and Olajuwon inside.
</P>
<P>
   Harrington, starting for the three to four weeks of Barkley's
knee rehabilitation, made seven of 10 shots for a season-high 17
points and added a career-high 13 rebounds. He had been second in
the NBA in field-goal percentage before the game but had taken on
enough added responsibility for Barkley to tell him, ``Now, we'll
see what kind of a player you really are.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I made my first couple of shots, and Rudy (Tomjanovich) kept
calling my plays,'' Harrington said. ``But I was surprised when
they finally decided to double-team me. When I hit Mike for an open
jumper, that felt so good.''
</P>
<P>
   The Suns had already given up on the plan to defend Olajuwon
with Luc Longley. And when Joe Kleine had even less success,
Olajuwon was on his way to 19 points on 7-of-11 shooting to go with
11 rebounds.
</P>
<P>
   The Suns were then forced to double-team the post in every
half-court set. That left shooters open, and they and Pippen,
playing perhaps his most complete game of the season, blew the game
open.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is probably our best shooting team,'' Tomjanovich said.
``A lot of guys are just now getting their rhythm. We've got
Michael, Cuttino, Matt (Maloney), Brent (Price), Bull. Those things
just break the game wide open. I liked the way things were going
when they weren't doubling, because `O' (Harrington) was scoring at
a very high rate.''
</P>
<P>
   To all that, Pippen added a dominant second half in which he
practically toyed with the Suns. Pippen had 13 points, including
his full-speed fake to Dickerson to open the lane for a layup. He
added five assists and 11 rebounds in the second half, while
leading the Rockets' suddenly effective fast break.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel much more comfortable offensively now,'' Pippen said.
``We are trying to focus on distributing the ball well on offense,
and we are doing a good job of passing out of the double team. I
never thought I would play with such a dominant center. This is
such a great team to play for.''
</P>
<P>
   It certainly was Tuesday. Tomjanovich was quick to point out
that his team had four days of rest while the Suns played in Denver
on Monday night. The Rockets will face a similar hardship the next
two nights, but they did provide themselves a particularly amusing
send-off.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought it was a great start for a real tough stretch in our
schedule,'' Tomjanovich said. ``Our defense carried us, and
everybody played really, really well.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm still learning about this team. I had a real good feeling
after that game.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
