</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SIMPSON-AUCTION-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SIMPSON ITEMS ARE AUCTIONED FOR $382,075 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Two years after the courtroom drama ended, the
O.J. Simpson case moved to the auction block on Tuesday as dozens
of Simpson's belongings, including his Heisman Trophy, were sold to
help pay the wrongful-death verdict against him.
</P>
<P>
   The auction brought $382,075 for the families of Simpson's
ex-wife wife Nicole Brown Simpson and her friend Ronald L. Goldman.
Simpson was acquitted of their 1994 slayings, but in 1997 he was
found liable for their deaths. Their estates were awarded $33.5
million. The sale on Tuesday night of about 70 items, including
sports trophies, jerseys and art work, will hardly put a dent in
the judgment.
</P>
<P>
   Simpson's Heisman Trophy, which he won in 1968, brought
$230,000. The winning bidder was an East Coast collector who
entered his bid by telephone and asked the auction house,
Butterfield &AMP; Butterfield, to keep his identity confidential.
</P>
<P>
   A lawyer for Goldman, Gary Caris, said Simpson had been making
small payments on the verdict but, citing a confidentiality
agreement, declined to be specific. Caris said the Goldman family
would get about two-thirds of the auction's proceeds and the Brown
family would receive one-third.
</P>
<P>
   Bids on most items were well over maximum offers anticipated by
the auction house. A commemorative football given to Simpson when
he was inducted into the Pro Football Hall of Fame in 1985, for
example, which was expected to attract a bid of no more than $300,
was sold for $2,500, and two autographed jerseys from when Simpson
played with the University of Southern California and with the
Buffalo Bills, valued at a maximum of $900, went for $4,750.
</P>
<P>
   Ghoulish paradox seemed to drive the price up on many items,
including six golf bags embossed with Simpson's name, which sold
for as much as $2,250. On the night of the deaths, he brought golf
clubs with him on a plane flight.
</P>
<P>
   Two trophies other than the Heisman, a plaque Simpson got when
he was inducted into the Hall of Fame, which was sold for $10,000,
and a pair of jerseys were bought by a Denver group that runs a Web
site called Shadowgov.com. The group said it would destroy the
items at a Los Angeles courthouse on Wednesday. ``We're here to let
our criminal justice system know it is a complete failure,'' said
Bob Enyart, who said he was a leader of the group.
</P>
<P>
   Simpson lives with his two children in Pacific Palisades and is
fighting with Mrs. Simpson's parents for their custody.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
