A8122 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ORO-MERGER-LADN     02-17 0330
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ORO-MERGER-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JEWELRY GIANTS MERGER REJECTED
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
BY ENRIQUE RIVERO  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES -- Jewelry maker OroAmerica Inc. was rebuffed
Tuesday in its attempt to acquire Michael Anthony Jewelers Inc.,
based in Mount Vernon, N.Y., in an all-cash transaction that would
have been worth more than $41 million.
</P>
<P>
   OroAmerica officials said early Tuesday that they had sent the
Michael Anthony board an unsolicited offer five days earlier to
purchase all the company's 6.86 million common shares at $6 each.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Anthony's board unanimously rejected the offer Tuesday,
according to a written statement issued after U.S. stock markets
closed.
</P>
<P>
   Company officials could not be reached for further comment.
</P>
<P>
   OroAmerica officials would not comment on the rejection.
</P>
<P>
   According to OroAmerica officials and analysts, however, the
company could have realized a host of cost savings and
substantially boosted its annual revenues if the acquisition had
succeeded.
</P>
<P>
   OroAmerica stock closed up 25 cents at $9.75. Michael Anthony
closed at $4.8125, up $1.3125.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Anthony is the nation's second-largest jewelry maker,
just behind top-ranked OroAmerica, according to Bill Gibson, a
senior analyst with Crittendon Roth Inc. in Santa Barbara.
</P>
<P>
   Gibson expects OroAmerica to end its fiscal year with $180
million in revenues. Michael Anthony officials say that, when they
release their company's year-end results, they expect them to be
``substantially better'' than the previous year's $130 million in
revenues.
</P>
<P>
   This wasn't the first time a merger of the two companies had
been proposed. About three years ago, Michael Anthony failed in its
bid to acquire OroAmerica, said Sheldon Grodsky, director of
research for Grodsky and Associates in South Orange, N.J.
</P>
<P>
   ``These two companies danced together before and went home from
the dance alone,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   X X X &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-17-99 0217EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990217.0067 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-17 02:40 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8134 &Cx1f; tth-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-THIEL-COLUMN-SPI &LR;      02-17 1128
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-THIEL-COLUMN-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JAZZ REMAIN NBA CONSTANT UNDER SLOAN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ART THIEL  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ Since we last rested eyes upon the Jazz, back when the
NBA still had a shred of dignity, a number of things have changed.
</P>
<P>
   The club's once-virtuous home state has suddenly become a hotbed
of inequity that may someday challenge the other sin capital of the
desert, Las Vegas.
</P>
<P>
   The Winter Olympics scheduled for Salt Lake City in 2002 has
brought with it more corruption than a Republican or Democratic
national convention. At one time or another, it seems like every
Utah resident has been accused of being either a geisha or a pool
boy for Juan Antonio Samaranch.
</P>
<P>
   Then one of the Jazz heroes, Bryon Russell, had the unfortunate
experience of becoming part of the world's most widely distributed
poster _ the flailing victim of the final game-winning jumper of
Michael Jordan's career.
</P>
<P>
   Didn't matter that he was big part of a valiant Jazz effort
against the Chicago Bulls for two straight Finals. All that any kid
from Rome to Nome will remember is Russell falling and Jordan
lingering, making sure the humiliation was complete.
</P>
<P>
   And then some wise guy in the front office decided to change the
primary road uniform color to oh-so-trendy black, with some
side-panel splash of colors not found in nature. Aside from the
choices being a screaming fashion cliche, the attempt to make the
Jazz hip is like putting tail fins on a potato.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, the more things change, as they like to say in the
valley of the Wasatch, the more they stay Jerry Sloan.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever tumult occurs in the NBA, around the Jazz, or the
surrounding environs, the Utah coach is as steadily relentless as a
dial tone. Some would say about as colorful, too. But entertainment
value in a coach can be overrated, as some University of Washington
football fans might be prone to saying these days.
</P>
<P>
   As a coach who has been twice denied the NBA pinnacle, thanks
largely to the bad timing of having Michael Jordan already at the
summit, Sloan would be entitled to feel a bit torqued over what
fate has dealt him. In the same position, ex-Sonic coach George
Karl would have offered up unending months of his tortured soul for
public display, so much so that more squeamish observers would feel
compelled to request that he put it away.
</P>
<P>
   But Sloan has a hard time even wondering what any fuss might be
about being twice denied.
</P>
<P>
   ``Doesn't bother me,'' he said before Tuesday night's game.
``Oh, sometimes you think about a mistake here and there, where you
could have done something different. But I can't do anything about
it now. You coach, or you play, and you go home.
</P>
<P>
   ``After all, it's really not important. Just basketball.''
</P>
<P>
   Just basketball. Boy, wait until Commissioner David Stern hears
about this. Sloan will be staying after class for weeks, writing
thousands of times ``I love this game'' on the blackboard.
</P>
<P>
   Actually, Sloan does love the game, as anyone who has played
with or against him (they're the ones with the broken noses), or
played under him will attest. He has an intense working
relationship with the game, not a marriage.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not much around people who care about this,'' Sloan said.
``I go back to Southern Illinois (where he has a farm) every
summer.
</P>
<P>
   ``They don't bring it up.''
</P>
<P>
   The approach is part of why Sloan is the longest tenured coach
in the NBA by a wide margin, while his more neurotic rivals such as
Karl and Chicago's Phil Jackson require change. Sloan is the NBA
master at concerning himself with only those things he can
influence, and letting the rest go either to hell or the Knicks.
</P>
<P>
   A recent example was over the summer, when the franchise
bulwark, Karl Malone, suddenly starting talking as if he spent July
going forehead-to-bumper with his semi-trailer truck. Malone's
chief looniness was his claim that he would never again play with
the Jazz, for reasons that are still not known even to NASA
researchers.
</P>
<P>
   Obviously, Malone recanted his statement, as well as numerous
others that drove many Jazz fans to distraction.
</P>
<P>
   What did Sloan think about all of this? Nothing.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know what his motive was,'' Sloan said. ``Karl always
says things in the summer that he wishes he hadn't said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The only thing I care about is whether he comes to play. And
he always comes to play. I have no gripe about anything else he
does. A lot of times the coach has it the other way around: He has
to deal with the player's problems with management. But Karl has
never brought it to the court.''
</P>
<P>
   Sloan was tested again Tuesday night. While it looked like
almost the same team that has been coming to Seattle for what is a
decade-long rivalry, it's doubtful the Jazz have ever played worse
here.
</P>
<P>
   In a somewhat anticipated meeting between the winners of the
last three Western Conference championships, the two unbeatens
pulled a Clippers-Kings stagger-a-thon that was the NBA's worst
nightmare in a lockout-shortened season.
</P>
<P>
   The Sonics' 71-56 win was a scar across the heart of basketball
_ the fourth-lowest combined score in NBA history. Because it was
Utah's fourth game in six nights, including an overtime win the
night before against Sacramento, the Jazz missed 13 of its 17 shots
in the first quarter, and remained inert.
</P>
<P>
   True to Sloanian form, however, the Jazz, while embarrassed, was
neither distraught nor whiny, even though they were missing starter
Jeff Hornacek (funeral) and reserve Thurl Bailey (injury).
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh, really?'' said Malone, when told of the four-games-in-six
business. ``I didn't know that. I promise you, I didn't know that.
Hey, it doesn't make a difference. I felt fine, and I prepare for
each game the same way.
</P>
<P>
   ``I mean, it sounds nice, playing that many games. You can say
that, if you want to. But we're not that kind of team. In sports,
you see that excuse used all the time.
</P>
<P>
   ``In truth, nobody really cares.''
</P>
<P>
   Malone's thoughts were the only clear moment in an otherwise
absurd evening.
</P>
<P>
   Well, there was another one, also in the Jazz quarters, when an
irked Sloan addressed the fact that in the second half he benched
his all-stars, Malone and John Stockton.
</P>
<P>
   ``They weren't playing very well,'' he said. ``My job is to win.
If that hurts their feelings, I'm sorry.''
</P>
<P>
   That's how it works for the steadiest franchise in sports. Check
your feelings, and your excuses, at the locker room door.
</P>
<P>
   The Jazz play. Sloan coaches. They go home.
</P>
<P>
   And one other thing.
</P>
<P>
   They come back.
</P>
<P>
   The rematch is Saturday in Salt Lake. Bring a lunch, Sonics. And
a snack. And a good dental plan.
</P>
<P>
   Art Thiel is a P-I columnist.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
