<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-17 02:41 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8135 &Cx1f; tth-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-SONICS-SPI &LR;      02-17 0782
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-SONICS-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SONICS HOLD JAZZ TO NEAR-RECORD LOW SCORE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By RONALD TILLERY  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ The Sonics are the last undefeated team in the NBA,
and the Utah Jazz are squirming under their feet.
</P>
<P>
   Although the Sonics were hardly dominant in many aspects of
Tuesday night's game, this much has become abundantly clear: If all
else fails _ and just about everything did for both teams _ these
Sonics apparently will flatten you with defense.
</P>
<P>
   In trampling the Jazz 71-56 at KeyArena, the Sonics improved to
6-0 and handed Utah its first defeat of the season while holding
the Jazz to the second-lowest point total by any team in an NBA
regular-season game.
</P>
<P>
   It was also the lowest point total ever by any team against
Sonics, who are off to their best start since the 1993-94 season.
That year, they won their first 10 games.
</P>
<P>
   ``It just wasn't their night,'' Sonics coach Paul Westphal said
of the Jazz. ``But we won't give back the win. We're glad we got
it.''
</P>
<P>
   Gary Payton led all scorers with 17 points, 11 rebounds and
eight assists. The only other Sonic to score in double figures was
Dale Ellis, who added 11 points off the bench.
</P>
<P>
   The Sonics shot just 40 percent from the field, but they held
Utah to 30-percent shooting. Karl Malone had 15 points and was the
only Jazz player to score in double digits.
</P>
<P>
   ``We looked like we never played a basketball game together,''
Utah coach Jerry Sloan said. ``They did a great job of taking us
out of our offense, which they've done before. Every time we would
try to figure out something to do, they had an answer for it. They
were all over us like a dirty shirt.''
</P>
<P>
   The Sonics were fortunate to catch a weakened Utah team. The
Jazz, coming off an overtime win against Sacramento on Monday
night, was playing its fourth game in six days.
</P>
<P>
   Utah also was without starting shooting guard Jeff Hornacek, who
was attending the funeral of a family friend.
</P>
<P>
   The Sonics, meanwhile, had two days' rest, and were fired up.
</P>
<P>
   They pounced on the Jazz in the first quarter, and never let up.
Although both teams shot poorly from the outside, the Sonics got to
the basket relatively easily. They led 19-12 after the first
quarter and went ahead 39-25 at halftime.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not going to give us all the credit,'' Westphal said.
``Utah was flat.''
</P>
<P>
   The Sonics took the Jazz out of its patented pick-and-roll. The
most effective strategy was pressuring the ball at half court to
eat away at the shot clock. The Jazz operated with less than 10
seconds by the time it managed to run its offense.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not a team that uses excuses. They just won the game,''
Malone said. ``They throw a lot of different defenses at you. Even
though they have new coaches, they still throw good defenses.''
</P>
<P>
   The Sonics never gave up an easy basket and finished with nine
block shots. Center Olden Polynice rejected three shots and grabbed
10 rebounds.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't want to give up anything easy,'' Polynice said.
``We're going to make everybody work for what they get. It starts
with me on down. I was pumped up for the game because I knew I had
to guard Karl.''
</P>
<P>
   Polynice defended Malone most of the game, a move the Sonics
tried so that Vin Baker could expend more energy on offense. Baker
is still looking for a breakout game after finishing with six
points on 3-for-9 shooting and, for the second straight game, no
trips to the free-throw line.
</P>
<P>
   Payton, though, continues to carry the load. He scored seven
straight points during a run midway in the third quarter that put
the Sonics ahead 51-31 _ their biggest lead of the night.
</P>
<P>
   ``He makes plays, and he makes it tough for the other teams to
make plays,'' Westphal said.
</P>
<P>
   Utah made a run at the Sonics and cut the deficit to 11 points
with 5:43 left in the game. But Payton responded with a layup and
fed Polynice for a score under the basket. The sequence eventually
put the Sonics ahead 67-51 with less than three minutes left.
</P>
<P>
   Payton has led the Sonics in scoring in every game so far.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's nice to know we can play bad and still win,'' Ellis said.
``It was nice to see Gary come alive in that third quarter.
</P>
<P>
   ``We just want to take care of our home. We wanted to take
advantage of a weak schedule early, and now we've gotten off to a
good start to a tough week.''
</P>
<P>
   The schedule presents plenty of challenges this week.
</P>
<P>
   After tonight's game against Sacramento, the Sonics play at Utah
on Saturday before returning home to face Los Angeles on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not complaining about anything right now,'' Westphal said.
``Our balance is good.''
</P>
</TEXT>
