<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ULSTER-BUDGET-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORS: 
  
</HEADLINE>
  
 Wednesday, Feb. 17, 1999
<TEXT>
<P>
   Death is part of the landscape of Northern Ireland, the
British-ruled province where a fragile peace agreement has tempered
longstanding sectarian differences.
</P>
<P>
   Across the region, and in Belfast in particular, a generation of
violence has claimed 3,600 lives since 1969. About 2 percent of
Northern Ireland's 1.6 million people have been killed _ which
statistically compares to 500,000 deaths in the United States,
nearly 10 times the number of American soldiers who died in
Vietnam.
</P>
<P>
   After three decades of fighting, the Good Friday peace agreement
signed last year has brought a halt to violence and has inspired
hope for the future.
</P>
<P>
   In stories written by Paul Grondahl, the Albany Times Union
explores the death, the destruction and the promise of peace in
Northern Ireland.
</P>
<P>
   The Hearst News Service will move the following stories in the
International news (``i'') category for release Sunday, Feb. 21.
The accompanying photographs by Steve Jacobs are available through
the Wieck database.
</P>
<P>
   For questions or resends, call Tim Spence at 202-298-6920.
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   NIRELAND-LANDSCAPE (Belfast, Northern Ireland) _ Death is deeply
embedded in the landscape of Northern Ireland and the psyche of its
people, as ever-present as pubs, grazing sheep and ocean views. And
nowhere better symbolizes the sectarian divide than Belfast, a city
split into Catholic and Protestant neighborhoods now made peaceful
by a fragile peace accord.
</P>
<P>
   NIRELAND-BOMBING (Omagh, Northern Ireland) _ It killed 29 people
and wounded 400, many of them women and children. The bomb blast in
the peaceful town of Omagh last August was the deadliest single
episode of sectarian violence in 30 years in Northern Ireland. It
also was a terrifying watershed that spurred the peace process in
the British-ruled province.
</P>
<P>
   NIRELAND-TITANIC (Belfast, Northern Ireland) _ It isn't much to
look at nowadays, this forlorn patch of asphalt. But this is the
birthplace of the RMS Titanic, the mythic ship that became the
subject of a blockbuster movie. Now some of the workers here see
capitalizing on the movie as the only way to save what remains of
the shipyard and its crucial jobs.
</P>
<P>
   NIRELAND-McALEESE (Belfast, Northern Ireland) _ Mary McAleese
returned to her old neighborhood as president of the Irish
Republic, north Belfast's most famous native daughter. Remembering
the pain of the past, she sees the promise of peace in
British-ruled Northern Ireland.
</P>
<P>
   NIRELAND-AID (Colonie, N.Y.) _ Paul and Jean Murray live in a
plain ranch house in a plain suburban subdivision. They are members
of the Shaker Ridge Country Club, but they also were leaders
helping members of the militant Irish Republican Army in Northern
Ireland. ``We were known as the terrorists at the club,'' Paul
Murray recalls of his days as head of Irish Northern Aid.
</P>
<P>
   (END)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
