<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-17 08:04 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8219 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NIRELAND-LANDSCAPE-2T     02-17 0896
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NIRELAND-LANDSCAPE-2TAKES-$ADV21-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DEATH HAUNTS THE UNEASY PEACE IN NORTHERN IRELAND 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For release Sunday, Feb. 21)   (Photo vailable on the Wieck database)  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By PAUL GRONDAHL  
 c.1999 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   BELFAST, Northern Ireland _ Death is deeply embedded in the
landscape of Northern Ireland and the psyche of its people, as
ever-present as pubs, grazing sheep and ocean views.
</P>
<P>
   Gravedigger David McDonnell, up to his armpits, shoveled sopping
mounds of soil as fast as he could, each thrust making slurping
sounds as water quickly seeped into the hole.
</P>
<P>
   ``Typical Irish weather,'' McDonnell said with a grunt on this
gray and raw November morning. Howling winds drove sheets of cold
rain across the crumbling, working-class Catholic Milltown
Cemetery.
</P>
<P>
   ``They don't bury ya here in Ireland,'' McDonnell said. ``They
drown ya.''
</P>
<P>
   The fabled hunger striker Bobby Sands is buried here. So are
nine of his Irish Republican Army compatriots. They starved
themselves to death in 1981 in the notorious Maze Prison _ known
locally as Long Kesh _ for the right to call themselves political
prisoners and to wear their street clothes instead of prison
uniforms.
</P>
<P>
   The Milltown is the final resting place for the most hardcore of
IRA families, for whom death through armed struggle is preferable
to living under British rule.
</P>
<P>
   At the peak of violence and retaliatory killings in the early
1970s, soldiers filled a British Army post at the entrance to the
cemetery. Today, the post remains lightly staffed but on alert,
ringed by concertina wire and bristling with surveillance cameras
and high-tech listening devices.
</P>
<P>
   Across Northern Ireland, and Belfast in particular, a generation
of sectarian violence has claimed 3,600 lives since 1969. About 2
percent of Northern Ireland's 1.6 million people have been killed,
which statistically compares to 500,000 deaths in the United
States, or nearly 10 times the number of American soldiers who died
in Vietnam.
</P>
<P>
   After three decades of fighting, the Good Friday peace agreement
signed last April has brought a fragile cessation of violence and
hope for the future, despite sporadic outbursts. In August, the
deadliest episode of the sectarian violence _ known here as ``the
Troubles'' _ took place when a car bomb planted by an IRA splinter
group killed 29 and wounded 400 in Omagh.
</P>
<P>
   In this austere landscape of death and myth, history often has a
stronger pull than the present. People know the undertow of past
hatreds could pull the province into a vortex of violence once
again.
</P>
<P>
   The militants are increasingly relegated to the margins of
Northern Ireland society. Today, in Belfast _ a city of 500,000
where Protestants are soon to be at equal numbers with Catholics _
there are prosperous communities from downtown to Queens University
and in the suburbs ringing the city core. The fight has gone out of
those middle-of-the-road masses who see a better future, a chance
at a good education and a decent career.
</P>
<P>
   Those who want to continue to live by the gun and the bomb as a
way of making political change are growing more isolated, their
paramilitary groups ranging from a few hundred to a few thousand
members. They are confined mostly to a patchwork of urban ghettos.
</P>
<P>
   In one of those neighborhoods of Belfast _ a 10-block Catholic
district known as New Lodge, a center of IRA activity _
battle-scarred red brick walls separating welfare tenements from
streets are pocked with bullet holes. Firebombed rowhouses here
were never rebuilt, leaving rubble-strewn vacant lots like so many
missing teeth.
</P>
<P>
   Since 1969, 62 residents of New Lodge have died. Many were
civilians, simply in the wrong place at the wrong time.
</P>
<P>
   The Shankill, the Loyalist Protestant district that abuts the
New Lodge, has known its share of death, about three dozen
residents since 1969. Those who live in the Shankill bury their
relatives and loved ones right across Falls Road from the Milltown,
in the Protestant City Cemetery.
</P>
<P>
   J. Bowyer Bell, who has studied political turmoil around the
world, concluded that Northern Ireland was unlike any traditional
battle zone because the violence was sporadic and chaotic without a
recognized front and no rules of engagement. It was gang versus
gang in a style of urban guerrilla warfare.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sadly, so sadly, even the decent have rarely accomplished much
good and have at times contributed to the turmoil,'' Bell concluded
in his monumental 872-page history ``The Irish Troubles.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I was more scared stationed in the farmland of south Armagh (a
county of Northern Ireland) than the time I served in the Gulf
War,'' said Lee Lavis, 27, a former British Army soldier who now
lives in Belfast and works as a department store security guard.
``In the Gulf, we attacked trenches and we knew where the enemy was
coming from. In Northern Ireland, an attack can come from anywhere,
anytime.''
</P>
<P>
   Lavis lives in a Loyalist Protestant district he wouldn't name
for fear his past would be discovered.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were stuck in the middle trying to keep peace and neither
side liked the British Army,'' Lavis said. ``It's a frustrating,
Catch-22 situation. I just go day to day now, watching where I go,
what I say. You live in Belfast, you learn to keep your mouth
shut.''
</P>
<P>
   (MORE ... MORE)
</P>
<P>
   More than half of those killed during the Troubles were
civilians. They had no allegiance to the stew of acronyms of
Loyalist and Republican paramilitary groups who painted murals and
slogans and graffiti across Belfast celebrating their desire to
destroy one another.
</P>
<P>
   ``You need a scorecard to keep track of all the groups,'' said
George Mitchell, the former senator from Maine who spent three
years brokering the historic Good Friday accord.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.) &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Loyalist Protestants and Republican Catholics live tightly
packed, separated by corrugated iron and concrete ``peace walls''
that keep opposing sides apart.
</P>
<P>
   Julie Dean, a 14-year-old from the Shankill, a Loyalist
Protestant district, lives along the peace walls in a brick
rowhouse and has no contact with Catholic youths, save for furtive
whispers after dark through heavy-duty swinging entryways known as
``peace gates'' that are locked at 9:30 p.m. and reopened at 7 a.m.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're afraid to come over to our side, but the ones I've
talked to at the gate seem all right,'' said Dean, whose dream is
to become an archaeologist and live in Washington, D.C. But her
neighborhood is mired in poverty and higher education is not a
common path. Recruitment by paramilitaries, teen pregnancy, a life
of unemployment and welfare: those are the norm.
</P>
<P>
   More common than the conversations that might reconcile the
warring sides are the epithets, stones and the occasional Molotov
cocktail hurled over the peace walls _ violence akin to a child's
low-grade fever. Dean's friends have never met their enemy
face-to-face, cannot see who they are battling, and yet the
conflict continues as if on auto-pilot.
</P>
<P>
   Tom Winstone is a celebrated former Loyalist paramilitary leader
who spent 17 years in Long Kesh prison for killing an IRA member in
1974. He's now involved in efforts to prevent violence between the
paramilitary groups. He may be a peacemaker, but he still hasn't
made peace with his former enemy.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's definitely a class struggle, an economic fight, and I
don't regret what I've done,'' Winstone said. ``For me, I chose to
be a Loyalist because I'm British, I have a right to remain here
and I won't be run off by the IRA. They killed three dozen people
with a dozen bombs on the Shankill Road but didn't scare us off.
</P>
<P>
   ``Americans mostly just hear one side, that old downtrodden
Catholic story,'' Winstone said. ``They're professional victims.
They're good at making excuses.''
</P>
<P>
   The IRA slogans and tri-color Irish flags of Catholic New Lodge
give way just across a street to the Loyalist graffiti and British
Union Jacks of Protestant Shankill. Otherwise, neighborhoods are
the same depressing brick slums, and the future promises continued
high unemployment, chronic poverty and a cycle of welfare
pathologies _ peace accord or not.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's all a kind of madness, isn't it?'' said the Rev. Des
Wilson, 73, a Catholic priest in west Belfast who has gone to the
United States numerous times to raise funds for his Springhill
Community House programs for job training and continuing education.
Unemployment in his district fluctuates between 40 and 70 percent.
</P>
<P>
   The easy shorthand of Catholics versus Protestants is not what
The Troubles are all about, according to Wilson, a
cleric-without-parish censured by the Roman Catholic Church for his
outspoken criticism of its hierarchy.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's an economic struggle, not a religious one,'' Wilson said.
``The Protestant ghettos have the same problems as the Catholic
ones. It's unemployment and poverty and a lack of hope they're
fighting against. The British government and the Church on both
sides are the problem. Ireland has a brutal and bloody past, but
the people will not give up to make a better future for their
children.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-17-99 0804EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990217.0073 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-17 08:05 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8221 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NIRELAND-BOMBING-$ADV     02-17 0991
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NIRELAND-BOMBING-$ADV21-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OMAGH BOMBING: A TRAGIC WATERSHED IN PEACE PROCESS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For release Sunday, Feb. 21)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By PAUL GRONDAHL  
 c.1999 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   OMAGH, Northern Ireland _ The bandages are gone, and her eyes
are painful to look at. The bridge of her nose is scarred, and the
eyes themselves are watery and bloody and adrift.
</P>
<P>
   The bomb that stole 15-year-old Claire Gallagher's sight also
drained the color from her eyes. Operations to repair her vision
haven't worked. ``I'm hoping with technology, maybe they'll be able
to do something for me in 30 years or so,'' she said quietly,
fidgeting with her brown-and-yellow school uniform.
</P>
<P>
   Omagh is a sleepy town of 20,000, largely apolitical, and
well-mixed with Protestants and Catholics who coexist relatively
peacefully 60 miles west of Belfast.
</P>
<P>
   It has a postcard quaintness to it, with church steeples on a
hillside overlooking the placid Strule River. It was along this
river, at the foot of Market Street, a two-block commercial
corridor, that a car bomb parked across from the Cozy Corner Pub
and a row of shops ripped into the heart of the town, and of the
country.
</P>
<P>
   When the bomb _ planted by a splinter group of the Irish
Republican Army called the Real IRA _ exploded on Aug. 15, it
killed 29 people and wounded 400, among them Claire Gallagher. It
was the deadliest single episode of the sectarian violence that has
claimed 3,600 lives in 30 years in Northern Ireland.
</P>
<P>
   It also was a terrifying watershed that spurred all the parties
in the simmering political war to renew their commitment to the
Good Friday peace accord, signed just four months before the bomb
blast in Omagh.
</P>
<P>
   ``The people do not want to go back to the bitterness and the
violence of the past'' as a result of Omagh, Northern Ireland peace
broker George Mitchell said at an Oct. 20 speech at the College of
Saint Rose in Albany, N.Y.
</P>
<P>
   He movingly described Gallagher in that speech as a ``tall,
gangly and lovely'' girl who ``poignantly trying to be courageous,
spoke of peace.'' Mitchell, the former U.S. senator from Maine, and
President Clinton had met her during a visit to comfort the victims
of the terrorist attack.
</P>
<P>
   In Omagh, it is difficult to find someone who hadn't been
touched by the bombing. The bomb exploded at mid-afternoon on a
Saturday. The shops were packed with mothers and daughters doing
their last back-to-school shopping, buying backpacks and skirts and
colored pencils.
</P>
<P>
   Claire was shopping with two girlfriends from school. At
5-feet-9-inches, she stood a head taller than her friends. ``They
managed to escape without injury, but Claire was struck in the eyes
from the side with shrapnel that whizzed right over the heads of
her friends,'' said Colm O'Neill, principal of the Loreto Grammar
School, a Catholic school for girls. ``Her friends are dealing with
a lot of survivor guilt.''
</P>
<P>
   O'Neill had one student killed and 11 others wounded.
</P>
<P>
   ``It just devastated this school as it did everything else in
town,'' O'Neill said.
</P>
<P>
   Claire's parents, Marie and Seamus Gallagher, were flown by
helicopter with their daughter to a hospital in Belfast for
emergency eye surgery.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was the first time we'd flown, and I don't remember
anything about it,'' Marie Gallagher said. ``From that moment, life
changed completely and nothing has been the same since.''
</P>
<P>
   The entire Omagh landscape was altered irrevocably.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our loss was so deep and indiscriminate, women and children
and people from all sides were killed,'' said Paddy Cullen, editor
of Omagh's weekly newspaper, the Ulster Herald. ``Analysts
speculated at first that this bomb would split this community and
derail the peace process. The people of Omagh vowed that would not
happen. If anything, it has brought us all closer together and
we're more determined than ever that we will not go back to the
violence of the past.''
</P>
<P>
   For now, Claire Gallagher is getting around school with the help
of an aide and looking to the future by learning Braille and how to
operate a voice-activated computer. She continues to do the things
she likes best, singing soprano in the school choir and playing
piano, going to discos and the movies with friends, studying Gaelic
as a way of deepening her Irish cultural heritage.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's more important than ever that we have peace in Ireland,''
Gallagher said. ``Hopefully, what happened in Omagh will make
people stop and think and it will bring us around to peace.''
</P>
<P>
   The oldest of five children, Gallagher hopes to earn a college
degree in music, with a dream of returning to teach music at Loreto
Grammar School.
</P>
<P>
   R. Mark Sullivan, president of The College of Saint Rose, has
offered Claire a four-year scholarship in music as a contribution
to the future of Northern Ireland.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is totally overwhelming,'' Gallagher's mother said.
``It's the ultimate opportunity. Claire has always had in her mind
she wants to go to New York. She's never been to the States. Here I
was trying to get used to the idea of her going to Belfast and now
she may be going off to America. It's fabulous.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.) &QR;  &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   On a clear, crisp November day, Omagh's Strule River glinted in
the noontime sun. The idyllic scene was interrupted by the rumble
of two backhoes that removed the twisted rubble that had been the
pub and shops on Market Street destroyed by the August bomb blast.
</P>
<P>
   ``From the evil and misery of the Omagh bombing, something
positive and good can come,'' somebody wrote on a sign outside the
fenced-in demolition site.
</P>
<P>
   But the hole in the heart of Omagh at the bottom of Market
Street won't soon be healed. ``Someone described the bomb site as
an open grave,'' said Cullen, the newspaper editor. ``It's a scar
that will always remind us of what happened, even as we try to move
on.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
