<HEADLINE>
OMAGH BOMBING: A TRAGIC WATERSHED IN PEACE PROCESS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For release Sunday, Feb. 21)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By PAUL GRONDAHL  
 c.1999 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   OMAGH, Northern Ireland _ The bandages are gone, and her eyes
are painful to look at. The bridge of her nose is scarred, and the
eyes themselves are watery and bloody and adrift.
</P>
<P>
   The bomb that stole 15-year-old Claire Gallagher's sight also
drained the color from her eyes. Operations to repair her vision
haven't worked. ``I'm hoping with technology, maybe they'll be able
to do something for me in 30 years or so,'' she said quietly,
fidgeting with her brown-and-yellow school uniform.
</P>
<P>
   Omagh is a sleepy town of 20,000, largely apolitical, and
well-mixed with Protestants and Catholics who coexist relatively
peacefully 60 miles west of Belfast.
</P>
<P>
   It has a postcard quaintness to it, with church steeples on a
hillside overlooking the placid Strule River. It was along this
river, at the foot of Market Street, a two-block commercial
corridor, that a car bomb parked across from the Cozy Corner Pub
and a row of shops ripped into the heart of the town, and of the
country.
</P>
<P>
   When the bomb _ planted by a splinter group of the Irish
Republican Army called the Real IRA _ exploded on Aug. 15, it
killed 29 people and wounded 400, among them Claire Gallagher. It
was the deadliest single episode of the sectarian violence that has
claimed 3,600 lives in 30 years in Northern Ireland.
</P>
<P>
   It also was a terrifying watershed that spurred all the parties
in the simmering political war to renew their commitment to the
Good Friday peace accord, signed just four months before the bomb
blast in Omagh.
</P>
<P>
   ``The people do not want to go back to the bitterness and the
violence of the past'' as a result of Omagh, Northern Ireland peace
broker George Mitchell said at an Oct. 20 speech at the College of
Saint Rose in Albany, N.Y.
</P>
<P>
   He movingly described Gallagher in that speech as a ``tall,
gangly and lovely'' girl who ``poignantly trying to be courageous,
spoke of peace.'' Mitchell, the former U.S. senator from Maine, and
President Clinton had met her during a visit to comfort the victims
of the terrorist attack.
</P>
<P>
   In Omagh, it is difficult to find someone who hadn't been
touched by the bombing. The bomb exploded at mid-afternoon on a
Saturday. The shops were packed with mothers and daughters doing
their last back-to-school shopping, buying backpacks and skirts and
colored pencils.
</P>
<P>
   Claire was shopping with two girlfriends from school. At
5-feet-9-inches, she stood a head taller than her friends. ``They
managed to escape without injury, but Claire was struck in the eyes
from the side with shrapnel that whizzed right over the heads of
her friends,'' said Colm O'Neill, principal of the Loreto Grammar
School, a Catholic school for girls. ``Her friends are dealing with
a lot of survivor guilt.''
</P>
<P>
   O'Neill had one student killed and 11 others wounded.
</P>
<P>
   ``It just devastated this school as it did everything else in
town,'' O'Neill said.
</P>
<P>
   Claire's parents, Marie and Seamus Gallagher, were flown by
helicopter with their daughter to a hospital in Belfast for
emergency eye surgery.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was the first time we'd flown, and I don't remember
anything about it,'' Marie Gallagher said. ``From that moment, life
changed completely and nothing has been the same since.''
</P>
<P>
   The entire Omagh landscape was altered irrevocably.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our loss was so deep and indiscriminate, women and children
and people from all sides were killed,'' said Paddy Cullen, editor
of Omagh's weekly newspaper, the Ulster Herald. ``Analysts
speculated at first that this bomb would split this community and
derail the peace process. The people of Omagh vowed that would not
happen. If anything, it has brought us all closer together and
we're more determined than ever that we will not go back to the
violence of the past.''
</P>
<P>
   For now, Claire Gallagher is getting around school with the help
of an aide and looking to the future by learning Braille and how to
operate a voice-activated computer. She continues to do the things
she likes best, singing soprano in the school choir and playing
piano, going to discos and the movies with friends, studying Gaelic
as a way of deepening her Irish cultural heritage.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's more important than ever that we have peace in Ireland,''
Gallagher said. ``Hopefully, what happened in Omagh will make
people stop and think and it will bring us around to peace.''
</P>
<P>
   The oldest of five children, Gallagher hopes to earn a college
degree in music, with a dream of returning to teach music at Loreto
Grammar School.
</P>
<P>
   R. Mark Sullivan, president of The College of Saint Rose, has
offered Claire a four-year scholarship in music as a contribution
to the future of Northern Ireland.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is totally overwhelming,'' Gallagher's mother said.
``It's the ultimate opportunity. Claire has always had in her mind
she wants to go to New York. She's never been to the States. Here I
was trying to get used to the idea of her going to Belfast and now
she may be going off to America. It's fabulous.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
