<SLUG> BC-NIRELAND-TITANIC-$ADV21-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BIRTHPLACE OF RMS TITANIC SINKS INTO DESPAIR 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For release Sunday, Feb. 21)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By PAUL GRONDAHL  
 c.1999 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   BELFAST, Northern Ireland _ It isn't much to look at nowadays,
this weedy and forlorn patch of asphalt with a scattering of rusted
steel beams and a view of the Belfast skyline across a muddy river.
</P>
<P>
   That's all that remains of the sloped slip at the Harland &AMP;
Wolff shipyard where the mythic RMS Titanic was launched into the
placid confluence of the River Lagan and Belfast Lough on May 31,
1911.
</P>
<P>
   At 882 feet, 8 inches long; 92 feet, 6 inches wide; and 46,329
tons of iron stacked across eight decks, the luxurious White Star
liner was the largest and most extravagantly appointed ship ever
built _ a powerful symbol of British maritime might.
</P>
<P>
   Chris Maxwell, a plumber and 25-year veteran of the shipyard,
whose grandfather worked as a riveter on Titanic, walked up the few
yards of crumbling concrete incline that remain of the 1911 slip.
He scoffed at the busloads of gullible American tourists who drive
by each day, straining to touch history beyond the shipyard's metal
fence.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some fella down the road was selling chunks of rock to the
American tourists, telling them they were pieces of the Titanic
slip,'' Maxwell said. ``Ever since that movie, it's been crazy
around here.''
</P>
<P>
   That movie would be director James Cameron's Oscar-winning epic
of the doomed liner starring Leonard DiCaprio and Kate Winslet,
which became the highest-grossing movie in America at more than
$600 million. Cameron's ``Titanic'' grew into an international
blockbuster with $2 billion in sales worldwide and achieved that
rare pop culture phenomenon, global mania.
</P>
<P>
   Maxwell's review of the movie: ``A love story with a boat. It
was a big disappointment that Belfast and our shipyard never got a
mention.''
</P>
<P>
   Maxwell's buddy, Bobby Moore, a pipefitter and a 25-year veteran
of the shipyard, was not thrilled with the film version either.
``Ach, just a piece of fluff. At least the ending wasn't spoiled.
You knew she was going to sink.''
</P>
<P>
   Maxwell interjected, ``Aye, but that had nothing to do with the
ship we built here. She was well-made. It was a freak of nature
that sunk her.''
</P>
<P>
   On its maiden voyage from Southampton to New York, shortly
before midnight on April 14, 1912, the Titanic struck an iceberg
off the banks of Newfoundland. Two hours and 40 minutes after
impact, the ship sank to the bottom and more than 1,500 people
died.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Titanic is our claim to fame, and it ended badly,'' Moore
said. ``That's what we're known for, the only ship we built that
sunk.''
</P>
<P>
   The two men are large, beefy fellows who wear oil-stained denim
coveralls and feed wide pessimistic streaks. It's a natural
response after working through the long decline of what was once
one of the world's largest and most prosperous shipyards.
</P>
<P>
   In its heyday of the late-1950s, Harland &AMP; Wolff employed 33,000
people who churned out luxury liners, cargo ships, British naval
ships, oil tankers and ferries.
</P>
<P>
   Today, just 1,400 workers remain and the shipyard hasn't
actually built a ship in three years. Cheap steel in Korea,
low-paid workers in Asia and subsidies for German shipmakers have
sucked the work out of Belfast.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not getting a fair kick at the ball,'' Maxwell said.
</P>
<P>
   The vast dry dock, bracketed by two massive 800-ton cranes
visible all over the city, is a shadow of its former self. Unlike
in the time of Titanic, when ships were built on braces and rolled
into the water, vessels are completed in this cement dry dock
chamber, which is flooded and the finished product is floated out
into the river.
</P>
<P>
   The dry dock on this day contained a mammoth offshore oil rig in
for refurbishing and a boxy drilling ship being built.
</P>
<P>
   For the past two decades, repair and construction of oil rig
platforms have been the primary market for Harland &AMP; Wolff. Once
the dominant builder of oil supertankers, the company hasn't
received a contract to build one of those in many years.
</P>
<P>
   The mood in the shipyard seemed grim. Workers sounded resigned
to further shrinkage of markets and layoffs.
</P>
<P>
   Still, in Northern Ireland's tight economy, these are
sought-after jobs with long waiting lists. Many are second- and
third-generation Harland &AMP; Wolff workers. Although it has gradually
become integrated in recent decades, Harland &AMP; Wolff was long known
as Protestant domain: Catholics need not apply.
</P>
<P>
   Despite automation and computerized assembly lines, it remains
heavy labor with hard-earned wages. Maxwell and Moore, approaching
retirement, have topped out on the salary scale at about $575 a
week gross pay. ``At the end of the day, computers don't build
ships,'' Moore said. ``Men do.''
</P>
<P>
   But with their obsolescence looming over them as surely as the
massive cranes, Maxwell and Moore have a notion that might rescue
the sinking shipyard: Tap into Titanic fever.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's what we're famous for and they're not exploiting it at
all,'' Maxwell said. There are no signs, no archives, no displays
of Titanic memorabilia at the shipyard. And, the most grievous
oversight of all in Maxwell's mind, no Titanic souvenirs for sale.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.) &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The only thing tourists can buy at the shipyard is a
black-and-white poster of the launch. Post-movie demand drove the
poster price up from $7.50 to $17.50.
</P>
<P>
   But think of the possibilities, Maxwell mused. Instead of giving
the busloads of tourists the brushoff and treating them like
intruders on private property as they are now, why not turn acres
of derelict buildings and land into a Titanic theme park?
</P>
<P>
   ``Just a lot of talk so far,'' Moore said. ``Some developers
have mentioned building a museum, creating a replica of Titanic on
the old slip as a hotel and restaurant and making the shipyard a
tourist attraction.''
</P>
<P>
   The two men looked at each other, hitched up their coveralls and
shrugged in unison.``Same old story,'' Moore said.``No money to do
it,'' Maxwell added.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
