<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NIRELAND-McALEESE-$ADV21-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NATIVE DAUGHTER FINDS HOPE IN DIVIVED CITY 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For release Sunday, Feb. 21)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By PAUL GRONDAHL  
 c.1999 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   BELFAST, Northern Ireland _ She was just Mary McAleese then,
growing up in the 1960s in the violent and segregated New Lodge
district, a poor and forlorn patch of hardscrabble north Belfast
where sectarian violence exacted a terrible cost in death and
destruction.
</P>
<P>
   McAleese, a Catholic, experienced the violence in many
terrifying ways: the bombing of her father's pub, the severe
beating of her deaf brother by a Loyalist gang, the murders of two
close friends on her wedding day.
</P>
<P>
   The harassment and intimidation from Loyalist Protestant gangs
grew so frightening, her family fled its north Belfast home to a
quiet, predominantly Catholic village south of the city.
</P>
<P>
   McAleese returned to her old neighborhood Nov. 17 as president
of the Irish Republic, north Belfast's most famous native daughter.
In a speech, she remembered the pain of the past, but carried a
message of hope.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know this place well and I know it is a place that has
suffered just extraordinary levels of pain, levels of pain that are
almost unimaginable unless you have lived right inside them,''
McAleese said.
</P>
<P>
   ``But we are so fortunate that we have the fair wind behind us
of the Good Friday agreement and the referendum of the north and
south, which said that there was a huge yes-ness in the hearts of
all our people. It really is up to us now to unpack all that
yes-ness and to put it at the service of our children.''
</P>
<P>
   McAleese, whose role as president is largely ceremonial with
very little political power attached, spoke at the launch of the
New Start Millennium Awards. During the next three years, about 100
awards averaging $6,000 each will be given out across Northern
Ireland for training, education and community support in New Lodge
and the other hardest-hit communities of north Belfast.
</P>
<P>
   The money is being provided by corporations as well as the
British government, which controls Northern Ireland, and the Irish
government. The cooperation is a result of the peace agreement
reached last year on Good Friday between the region's factions.
</P>
<P>
   McAleese said she was particularly interested in seeing the
money go toward parenting courses for teen parents, to fund
literacy mentoring, to create conflict resolution alternatives and
to bolster programs between children and senior citizens.
</P>
<P>
   McAleese spoke at the Ashton Community Hall, where in contrast
to the dark and menacing murals of the neighborhood streets,
student artwork on the walls depicted a place of clean parks, safe
playgrounds, rainbows and laughter.
</P>
<P>
   ``I take such pride and joy representing Ireland abroad and
being able to tell the many, many Irish and friends of Ireland all
over the world about this new, smart, self-confident Ireland so
deeply in its stride, so culturally confident, so economically
confident,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   McAleese described an ongoing legacy of violence in north
Belfast stretching from her youth to the Oct. 31 murder of Brian
Service, a Catholic man shot by a Protestant Loyalist death squad
as he was walking home.
</P>
<P>
   ``None of us can do anything about the past, unfortunately,''
McAleese said. ``We could apologize for it and receive apologies
for it, but we can't undo it. The best we can do is to use this
moment that we have to make something better out of today and build
something much better for the future.''
</P>
<P>
   McAleese described the grim reminders of the remaining ``peace
walls'' and how they separate Protestant from Catholic in Belfast.
She said she prays that one day such walls will be torn down,
replaced by a community of sharing across the sectarian divide.
</P>
<P>
   ``I look forward to the day when the landscape of this place and
the landscape of the heart and the political landscape will be
transformed and we will have here again a place of happy children
running around without the awful burden of hatred and violence that
has hung over this place for so long. Please God, those days will
soon be over.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
