u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NIRELAND-AID-$ADV21-H     02-17 0747
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NIRELAND-AID-$ADV21-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COUNTRY CLUB COUPLE EARNED REPUTATION FOR AIDING IRA 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For release Sunday, Feb. 21)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By PAUL GRONDAHL  
 c.1999 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   COLONIE, N.Y. _ He lives in a plain ranch house in a plain
suburban subdivision. He has a round, soft face, with wisps of
thinning hair slicked straight back above wire-rimmed spectacles.
</P>
<P>
   Everything about Paul Murray says insurance man, which is what
he is. Nothing says terrorist, which is what he has been accused of
being.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was investigated and harassed at home. I lost a lot of
business and many friends over the years,'' he said. ``It
ultimately cost me my health. But I don't have a single regret. I
played my part for the Republican cause.''
</P>
<P>
   Murray, 59, a native of the Albany suburb of Colonie, was the
first and only American national director of Irish Northern Aid
(NORAID). He held that position for five years beginning in 1989 _
traveling to New York City weekly, making weekend trips around the
United States and extended visits abroad _ until vertigo and other
stress-related symptoms compelled him to resign. Murray handed over
leadership of the NORAID group to his wife, Jean, who has since
passed it on to Paul's brother, Dave Murray.
</P>
<P>
   Murray was not to the militancy born.
</P>
<P>
   Growing up in Colonie, Murray's only memory of feeling connected
to Ireland was marching in the St. Patrick's Day parade. Paul
graduated from Colonie Central High School and Hudson Valley
Community College. He and his wife later joined Shaker Ridge
Country Club.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were known as the terrorists at the club,'' Murray said.
</P>
<P>
   The snide whispers did not dissuade the couple.
</P>
<P>
   His wife's family believed armed struggle was the only way to
force the British and its imperial government out of Northern
Ireland.
</P>
<P>
   ``For years, my cousins wouldn't talk to my grandmother and aunt
because of their pro-IRA position,'' Jean Murray said, referring to
the militant Irish Republican Army that has fought British rule.
</P>
<P>
   Paul Murray opened an Irish pub, The Sand Creek Inn, in Colonie
in 1974 and talk around the bar often turned to the political
troubles in Northern Ireland. It wasn't hard to determine which
side Murray was on.
</P>
<P>
   Murray said he always operated on this philosophy: ``Deep inside
every Irish man and woman is a vein of Republicanism, but they're
afraid to let it out until they perceive it is acceptable.''
</P>
<P>
   On St. Patrick's Day in 1976, Murray made a chance encounter
with a north Belfast man at the Starry Plough, a defunct Irish pub
in another upstate New York town, Rensselaer. It changed his life
and steered him into his involvement in the Republican cause of
Northern Ireland.
</P>
<P>
   The Belfast man was Geordie Pierce, the only one of 10 siblings
in his family to escape Belfast, who would become another pillar of
the Irish aid community in upstate New York.
</P>
<P>
   ``He became like a brother to me,'' Pierce said, noting Murray
helped him make contacts and assisted him in getting a job.
</P>
<P>
   For two decades the two men have tried to meet every Saturday
morning at Murray's Colonie house to discuss Northern Ireland
politics.
</P>
<P>
   Belfast was a war zone in 1980 when the Murrays first visited
the Northern Ireland city as guests of the Pierce family. The
couple witnessed firsthand the IRA and the British Army in violent,
explosive clashes.
</P>
<P>
   The Murrays returned every year between 1980 and 1996. In August
1992, during a Catholic party, the Murrays recalled seeing officers
of the Royal Ulster Constabulary, unprovoked, firing plastic
bullets into the crowd. The hard rubber projectiles hit the chins
and elbows of children playing at the party.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a frightening environment for an American,'' Paul
Murray said. ``But our fear turned to outrage and we decided we'd
do our part in the struggle, no matter how unpopular it was here.''
</P>
<P>
   The Murrays didn't heed criticism for inviting convicted IRA
leader Brendan Hughes to their house after his release from prison.
Hughes stayed with the Murrays twice in the late 1980s.
</P>
<P>
   Hughes was one of the beneficiaries of the Murrays' fund-raising
efforts.
</P>
<P>
   ``The money goes to prisoners' families and not for guns.
Period,'' Murray said. ``We've been investigated over and over
again by many different agencies. We've never been charged with
anything. The British government uses the accusation that we run
guns as a red herring. It's not true.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
