<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-COWBOYS-RAISES-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COWBOYS TO GIVE RAISES TO AIKMAN, SANDERS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By CLARENCE E. HILL JR. 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   IRVING, Texas _ If it seems that the Cowboys have been
spectators since the free-agent signing period began Friday, it's
because they have been.
</P>
<P>
   Much of the early movement has been to sign high-profile and
high-dollar free agents, said Cowboys owner Jerry Jones. He said
such moves aren'tnecessary for the Cowboys to achieve their
off-season goals, which in free agency are to find a speed
receiver, a center and a strong-side linebacker at reasonable
prices.
</P>
<P>
   However, that doesn't mean Jones won't be reaching deep into his
pockets, as new contracts are planned for quarterback Troy Aikman
and cornerback Deion Sanders.
</P>
<P>
   ``I anticipate doing something with Aikman and Deion this
year,'' Jones said. ``I'm not talking about restructuring for
salary-cap reasons. I'm talking about new negotiations. I think it
will likely happen this off-season.''
</P>
<P>
   Jones declined to get into dollar amounts, but both contracts
could approach $8 million per season.
</P>
<P>
   Aikman, whose current contract averages $5.8 million a year, has
three years left on his deal, which pays him $8.5 million in 1999,
$9.3 million in 2000 and $8.8 million in 2001. Sanders, who will
make $8.2 million in 1999, has three years remaining on his
contract; however he will reach incentives that will void the final
two years of the contract. His original deal averages $5 million
per year.
</P>
<P>
   Sanders has already said that he wants a new deal before the
start of next season. Aikman and his agent, Leigh Steinberg, agree
that it's probably time for them to revisit his contract as well.
</P>
<P>
   Aikman is looking for a deal that will take him to the end of
his career, while also bringing him back in line with the market
value for top quarterbacks. He is currently the sixth highest-paid
quarterback behind Steve Young, Brett Favre, Jake Plummer, Drew
Bledsoe and Mark Brunnell. The top three make more than $7 million
per season.
</P>
<P>
   Giving Aikman and Sanders new deals could help the Cowboys'
tight salary cap situation for 1999, as they would likely include
heavy bonuses and low initial base salaries. However, Jones said
the cap is not part of his motivation for giving them new
contracts.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's something we need to get done,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   What the Cowboys also need is to reduce fullback Daryl
Johnston's salary _ which is $1.65 million in 1999. Jones said
Johnston is valuable, but not at that price. He said they are
working on redoing Johnston's contract, but has not set a timetable
for its completion.
</P>
<P>
   Jones also said the Cowboys are planning to bring back most of
their own unrestricted free agents, including receiver Ernie Mills,
linebacker Broderick Thomas and guard Nate Newton. Their in-house
priority, however, is unrestricted free-agent linebacker Randall
Godfrey, who is expected to replace Fred Strickland at middle
linebacker.
</P>
<P>
   Jones said that the Cowboys gambled a bit by tendering Godfrey a
qualifying offer of $429,000. That could result in Godfrey's
getting higher offers from other teams, who would only have to give
the Cowboys a second-round pick as compensation if they chose not
to match the offer.
</P>
<P>
   But Jones said that Godfrey's off-season shoulder surgery might
temper the offers. Jones speculates that Godfrey will want to come
back and have a good 1999 season to put him position for even
bigger money as an unrestricted free-agent next season.
</P>
<P>
   Though Jones won't discuss specific players they are targeting
in free agency, the Cowboys have made many contacts with players
outside the organization. There is no question a speed receiver is
their primary focus.
</P>
<P>
   Unrestricted free agent Raghib Ismail of the Carolina Panthers
and restricted free agent Derrick Mayes of the Green Bay Packers
are among the players the Cowboys are evaluating. Ismail is being
targeted by several teams, and the competition could put him out of
the Cowboys' price range. They also could find a receiver via a
trade. One possibility is St. Louis receiver Eddie Kennison.
</P>
<P>
   Former Colts linebacker Quentin Coryatt is still the Cowboys'
main target at outside linebacker. However, he is being pursued by
several other teams, and his agent, Steve Zucker, said Coryatt
won't visit any teams until early March.
</P>
<P>
   At center, the Cowboys could be going back to Mark Stepnoski, a
former Cowboys player who has been with the Oilers the past four
seasons. Stepnoski's agent, Ralph Cindrich, said his client would
like to come back and is looking for a multiyear contract. However,
Cindrich said Stepnoski probably won't make a decision on where he
will play for another month or so.
</P>
</TEXT>
