<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MCCARTY-COLUMN18-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Art immitating life
 &HT;    By Mary McCarty
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _ ``Tell me about your families,'' child therapist
Karen McQueary tells her young clients at the Artemis Center for
Alternatives to Domestic Violence. They often say, ``I don't want
to,'' or ``Pass.'' ``It's too scary,'' they explain. ``It makes me
sad.''
</P>
<P>
   Many of the children, too traumatized to trust adults, initially
reveal themselves only through their artwork. For McQueary, a pad
of paper and a pencil can be the ``Open Sesame'' to their souls.
``I feel glad and sad and frightened,'' one 8-year-old captioned
his drawing of a father and a child crying purple tears. ``I feel
upset that Dad had to go to jale. I feel lonely.''
</P>
<P>
   This child's-eye view of domestic violence will be displayed
Saturday night at Sinclair Community College at the ninth annual
Artemis gala as part of an exhibit, ``Expressions,'' featuring
original artwork by Artemis clients, children and adults.
</P>
<P>
   None of the books or articles I've read on domestic violence
come as close to capturing the child's experience as this exhibit.
In one drawing, an oversized judge looms over drawings of ``daddy
and lawyer'' and ``mommy and lawyer.''
</P>
<P>
   Another drawing depicts the picture-perfect home, complete with
picket fence, dog house, chirping birds, a tree swing and a little
girl. Balloon messages relate, ``You deserve to be safe'' and ``We
wish for Chris to go to a counselor.'' The bird chirps, ``You are
OK, domestic violence is not your fault.''
</P>
<P>
   A little girl drew a heart and a picture of her mother in a
flowered hat: ``I would like my life to be full of love,'' she
wrote.
</P>
<P>
   A child captioned another drawing: ``I don't trust my daddy
because he hurted my mom. I trust my mom because she never hurted
me; I trust my teacher because she is nice to me and my class.''
</P>
<P>
   Other drawings are more cryptic. McQueary was particularly
puzzled by one until the artist explained that, in the drawing, God
had turned his father into macaroni and cheese ``so he can't hurt
people any more.'' Using art's magic wand, children transform
batterers into frogs, marshmallows, you name it _ always for the
same reason: ``Then he can't hurt people.''
</P>
<P>
   How does such an exhibit fly at a glitzy, festive event?
Wouldn't they rather be noshing hors d'oeuvres or boogieing to the
Arnette Howard Creole Funk Band? ``We've been pleasantly surprised
to see that most of the guests visit the exhibit, and spend a fair
amount of time there,'' said Artemis director Nancy Grigsby, who
founded the agency in 1985.
</P>
<P>
   The gala has always mixed fun and flair with a serious message _
usually, in past years, with a national photography or art exhibit.
This year, for the first time, the exhibit will be local, featuring
works by current and former Artemis clients. ``This year, we wanted
to make it more local and more personal, to show people what we're
dealing with at Artemis,'' said Jill Bishop, community relations
coordinator. (Tickets are still available by calling Artemis at
461-5091.)
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps most telling is a drawing a child made of the ``place I
feel most safe.'' At first it appears to be a nondescript red brick
building, until you look in the corner where the numbers ``301'' _
the street address for the Artemis Center _ are faintly drawn.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's bittersweet,'' Grigsby said of the drawing. ``I'm glad
kids trust us and feel safe, but it's very tragic this is the only
place they feel safe and can trust people. We want a community that
holds offenders accountable so the rest of world can be a safe
place, too.''
</P>
<P>
   For 14 years, the Artemis Center has been doing its part.
</P>
<P>
   Mary McCarty writes for the Dayton Daily News, Dayton, Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
