<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NETHAWAY-COLUMN18-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Military pomp takes back seat to display of language mastery
 &HT;    By Rowland Nethaway
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   PRESIDIO OF MONTEREY, Calif. _ During afternoon tea at
Monterey's elegant Spindrift Inn, a fellow guest politely asked the
reason for my visit.
</P>
<P>
   ``My mother and I are here to attend the graduation ceremony of
my brother's daughter from the Defense Language Institute at the
Presidio,'' I replied.
</P>
<P>
   I started to say ``from spy school'' because I rather like the
way that sounds even though I know it's not accurate. It's good
that I didn't.
</P>
<P>
   ``Their studies and training are long and difficult,'' said the
prosperous-looking man. ``I'm sure she will appreciate having
family members see her graduate. What is her language?''
</P>
<P>
   ``Arabic,'' I said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yes, we've seen the need for that language recently. I was a
graduate there in Hmong before leaving for Vietnam,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``My brother, who will be arriving a little later, was a
graduate there in Russian at about the same time,'' I said. ``But
he was sent to Europe rather than Southeast Asia.''
</P>
<P>
   The man was the first of several people to comment on the family
legacy aspect of having both father and daughter graduate from the
same military language school, albeit in different languages.
</P>
<P>
   The Defense Language Institute Foreign Language Center traces
its origins back to Nov. 1, 1941 _ weeks before the bombing of
Pearl Harbor _ when the Army established a secret language school
in the Presidio of San Francisco to teach the Japanese language.
</P>
<P>
   After the war, the school was moved to the Presidio of Monterey
and was called the Army Language School. In 1963, the military
consolidated all foreign language programs at the Presidio of
Monterey with the mission to train military linguists to meet
Department of Defense requirements and sustain those capabilities
worldwide.
</P>
<P>
   ``Presidio'' is Spanish. The Spanish founded this presidio in
1770 to defend the bay area from the Russians. With better military
intelligence, they would have known they were looking in the wrong
direction.
</P>
<P>
   Presidio can refer to ``prison,'' ``hard labor'' and
``garrison'' as well as a military installation. Those terms seem
out of place on this scenic peninsula that has some of the nation's
greatest golf courses, swankest homes and best scenery.
</P>
<P>
   Enough relatives came to celebrate young Alpha Nethaway's
graduation that we arrived at the base in a three-car caravan, with
one more soon to follow.
</P>
<P>
   I expected a ceremony that included precision marching past a
high grandstand on a huge parade ground. I envisioned gleaming
swords, colorful pennants and flags and perhaps a military band,
cannon salutes and fly-over of military jets trailing red, white
and blue smoke.
</P>
<P>
   My military training was of a different era. It also was
considerably less subtle and cerebral. The language I learned in
military training cannot be printed in newspapers or repeated
outside of outlaw motorcycle gangs.
</P>
<P>
   I also expected to see a graduation class numbering in the
hundreds, if not thousands.
</P>
<P>
   As it turned out, the ceremony had no marching, swords,
pennants, flags, music or cannon fire. And there was no fly-over.
</P>
<P>
   Only 22 people were in the graduation class. They included men
and women, officers and enlisted. They represented most branches of
the military.
</P>
<P>
   A good portion of the ceremony would have been incomprehensible
had not my niece given the English interpretation of her
classmate's speech in Arabic.
</P>
<P>
   An officer with 24 years of military service, much of it in the
Middle East, was the guest speaker. He reminded the graduates how
important their training and skills are for the nation. It was all
low-key but enough to choke you up.
</P>
<P>
   Still, a fly-over of F-16s doing victory rolls would have been
nice.
</P>
<P>
   Rowland Nethaway is senior editor of the Waco Tribune-Herald,
Waco, Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
