<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-17 10:28 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8328 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-AUSCHWITZ-LASTDAYS18-     02-17 1097
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AUSCHWITZ-LASTDAYS18-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Nazis took away everything but her soul
 &HT;    (EDS: Photos available.)
 &HT;    By Hap Erstein
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ In the Auschwitz death camp and for the
following 50 years, Irene Zis-blatt kept silent about the horrors
she saw and lived through.
</P>
<P>
   ``I knew that silence was very, very important to our survival,
because if you weren't silent they took you right away,'' says
Zisblatt, 68, sitting in the living room of her apartment in
Pembroke Pines, Fla.
</P>
<P>
   Persuaded finally to tell her story to the Survivors of the
Shoah Visual History Foundation, the nonprofit organization founded
by filmmaker Steven Spielberg, Zisblatt discovered a new wave of
liberation.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was like inside me, this second life, an inner life that I
didn't release,'' she said. ``When I broke my silence, all these
memories that I suppressed for all these years, they just popped
right back. The pain was not important anymore. What was important
to me was I needed to share my pain with the world, so they cannot
let anybody be painful like this again.''
</P>
<P>
   And now, Zisblatt's story is a key part of the Oscar-nominated
documentary feature, The Last Days, which opens Friday.
</P>
<P>
   The film concentrates on the end of World War II, when Germany
realized defeat was inevitable, but continued exterminating the
Jews. Specifically, it focuses on the Hungarian Jews, who were
forced into ghettos, herded onto boxcars and transported to Poland.
</P>
<P>
   Zisblatt was born in the lush resort town of Poleno,
Czechoslovakia, which was later annexed into Hungary. A handful of
Nazi officers occupied the town, but her family was able to hide
for two weeks in their home, which had been sealed to suggest it
had been vacated. Eventually, they were betrayed by neighbors, sent
to the ghetto and then to Auschwitz.
</P>
<P>
   Thirteen-year-old Irene was transported to the camp with her
mother, brother and sisters, all of whom would be killed soon after
arrival.
</P>
<P>
   In the film's most memorable sequence, Zisblatt talks of her
mother sewing diamonds into her daughter's skirt, telling her to
use them when necessary to buy bread. But the detainees were
stripped of their clothes, so Zisblatt quickly hid the gems in her
mouth. When she saw others being examined for gold fillings,
Zisblatt swallowed the diamonds. Throughout her many months in the
camp, she would retrieve them from her excrement and swallow the
diamonds again.
</P>
<P>
   ``Because that was the only connection to my mother,'' Zisblatt
explains. ``By not giving up the diamonds it was holding on to a
past, holding on to a strength and (to) my mother's wish to buy
bread so I could be strong and work.''
</P>
<P>
   Zisblatt was determined not to be broken by her Nazi captors.
``I felt that there was something that they wanted from us,'' she
says softly. ``They already took our possessions, they already took
my family, they already took my freedom, they already branded me
with a number and took my name away. So there was something they
needed to take away in order to kill us.
</P>
<P>
   ``I figured the only thing that's left is my soul and they're
not going to take that.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, there were many times when Zisblatt's will to live ebbed.
``When I was ready to die _ like on a death march, where they were
shooting the ones that couldn't keep up with the march, they left
them on the road _ and I was ready for that,'' she says. At those
times, she recalls an older teenage girl pulling her back on her
feet, repeating their joint pledge, ``Now remember, we're not going
to be ashes.''
</P>
<P>
   Zisblatt eluded the crematoriums and was freed by U.S. troops,
but she soon landed in another camp for displaced persons. A
soldier being shipped home took her name and background particulars
and placed them in an ad in a New York newspaper. There it was read
by her deceased father's oldest brother, who sent her a letter
asking her plans and enclosing a check for $500.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was overwhelmed,'' says Zisblatt. ``I sent back the check,
because I couldn't buy anything, I had no use for it.'' But she
wrote that she wanted to be with family, to rebuild her life and
start a new family.
</P>
<P>
   She moved to New Jersey, attended night school to learn English,
worked for RCA on a filament assembly line and eventually was sent
to Rutgers University to be able to work with the company's
engineers. ``I kissed the ground that I walked on where I was, that
I was given the opportunity to be in this country and be free and
not to ever be afraid again.''
</P>
<P>
   Zisblatt married, had two children and moved to South Florida in
1989 to alleviate her Krone's disease, which doctors said is
aggravated by conditions in the North. It is unclear whether the
disease is related to her confinement in Auschwitz, but she feels
that is likely.
</P>
<P>
   Pictures of her grandchildren fill many frames in Zisblatt's
kitchen, but the inscribed photograph that dominates her living
room is of The Last Days' executive producer _ Spielberg.
</P>
<P>
   All through her interviews in Los Angeles, she hoped to
encounter the director of Schindler's List. ``I didn't know what to
expect, but I figured, well, if we're going to work on this for so
long, I'm sure to meet him, right?''
</P>
<P>
   But it was not to be, until the documentary premiered. ``At the
screening, I figured, `Well, he's going to come for a few minutes.
He's going to run in, he's going to say ``hello,'' he's going to
take a picture and then be on his way, out the back door.'''
</P>
<P>
   However, Spielberg stayed to watch the film and spend time with
Zisblatt and the other four featured interview subjects.
</P>
<P>
   ``He is the most compassionate, the most wonderful, caring
person,'' she says. ``To meet him and to touch him, it was like
touching an angel.''
</P>
<P>
   Spielberg had only one request. He knew she had the diamonds
from the concentration camp made into a tear-shaped pendant. She
had only worn it twice, at her children's weddings. But she wore it
to the premiere and Spielberg asked to touch it, to connect with
the triumph and the loss that it represents.
</P>
<P>
   ``And he took these diamonds and he kissed them like it was a
mezuzah,'' an ornamental scroll holder proclaiming one's Judaism,
says Zisblatt. ``And I cried for 24 hours after that.''
</P>
<P>
   As to watching the film that night, well, ``Half of the film, I
didn't even see, because I was crying so hard,'' she says.
</P>
<P>
   And a new tear forms in her eye.
</P>
<P>
   Hap Erstein writes for the Palm Beach Post, West Palm Beach,
Fla.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
