<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Masseur has magic touch, but here's the rub: He treats your pets
 &HT;    By Jeff Houck
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ When you're a pioneer in medicine, you
stick your neck out a little. And when your job involves
therapeutic massage of dogs and cats, well, you become easy prey
for jokesters.
</P>
<P>
   Pet masseur and animal behavior expert Michael Holloway knows
this. After he was quoted in a recent article in Time, he was
invited on a morning radio show.
</P>
<P>
   ``They wanted to poke a little fun,'' Holloway says. ``They made
a few jokes.''
</P>
<P>
   But it's clear no matter how odd his line of work sounds, his
Boca Raton, Fla. business, Pet Massage Rehabilitation Services, has
found a niche in a booming market. More and more owners who
contribute to the $21 billion pet-care industry are willing to pay
extra dough for alternative treatments: Acupuncture, herbal mood
enhancers and, yes, pet massage.
</P>
<P>
   In the past two years, business for Holloway _ who is a licensed
massage therapist (for humans) and former veterinary assistant _
has grown sevenfold.
</P>
<P>
   Holloway uses deep-tissue massage to facilitate recovery from
surgery and treat physical problems such as hip dysplasia. Therapy
is intended to work in tandem with whatever is prescribed by the
animal's veterinarian, much the way a physical therapist might
rehabilitate a human patient who had knee surgery.
</P>
<P>
   But massage also heals behavioral problems, such as ``contact
phobia'' experienced by dogs who become fearful when approached by
strangers.
</P>
<P>
   Judy and Michael Odsess of Boca Raton turned to Holloway to help
their Old English sheepdog, Nathan.
</P>
<P>
   Nathan, now 6, suffered as a puppy from a shoulder disorder
caused by his rapid growth. After he underwent surgery to remove
damaged cartilage, the Odsesses hired Holloway, who began weekly
massage sessions. He also added 2- to 4-mile walks three times a
week.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Odsess said that when Nathan's veterinarian recommended
massage therapy, ``I thought it was insane. But it made sense.
Massage does work.''
</P>
<P>
   And the several hundred dollars they spend a month for the
treatments?
</P>
<P>
   ``I totally think it's worth it,'' Judy Odsess said. ``He's a
happier dog. He feels better. If Nathan needed acupuncture I'd get
that too.''
</P>
<P>
   Jeff Houck writes for the Palm Beach Post, West Palm Beach, Fla.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
