<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-17 10:29 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8332 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NEWS-QUESTIONS18-TAKE     02-17 1458
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NEWS-QUESTIONS18-TAKE2-COX </SLUG>

<TEXT>
<P>
   News Questions
</P>
<P>
   (Eds: continued)
</P>
<P>
   Q: Can you list the names and addresses of the House managers
involved in the impeachment trial of President Clinton so we can
write to express our opinions?
</P>
<P>
   A: Indeed we can. There are 13, all Republicans, and their
offices are in three buildings in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   Reps. Bob Barr of Georgia, Lindsey Graham of South Carolina and
Asa Hutchinson of Arkansas can be reached at: Longworth House
Office Building, Washington, DC 20515.
</P>
<P>
   Reps. Ed Bryant of Tennessee, Steve Buyer of Indiana,
Christopher Cannon of Utah, Steve Chabot of Ohio and James Rogan of
California maintain offices at: Cannon House Office Building,
Washington, DC 20515.
</P>
<P>
   Reps. Charles Canady of Florida, George Gekas of Pennsylvania,
Henry Hyde of Illinois, Bill McCollum of Florida and James
Sensenbrenner of Wisconsin are at: Rayburn House Office Building,
Washington DC 20515.
</P>
<P>
   Q: What is the relationship, if any, between George Clooney, the
actor, and Rosemary Clooney, the singer? What are their ages?
</P>
<P>
   A: George Clooney is Rosemary's nephew. George's father, Nick
Clooney of American Movie Classics, is Rosemary's brother. George
was born May 5, 1961, in Lexington, Ky.; his aunt (``Come on-a My
House'') was born May 23, 1928, in Maysville, Ky.
</P>
<P>
   Q: A recent article mentioned that Max Cleland received a Silver
Star. What heroic act did he do to receive that award?
</P>
<P>
   A: Cleland (D-Ga.) was awarded the Silver Star and Soldier's
Medal in connection with his Vietnam War service. According to Army
citations, he won the Silver Star for crawling out of his foxhole
during a rocket attack to tend to wounded men. The Soldier's Medal
was awarded for shielding other men from the grenade blast that
wounded him. But in his autobiography, ``Strong at the Broken
Places,'' Cleland wrote that he hadn't really earned either of the
awards for heroism. ``There were no heroics on which to base the
Soldier's Medal. And it had been my men who took care of the
wounded during the rocket attack, not me,'' he wrote. ``Some
compassionate military men had obviously recommended me for the
Silver Star, but I did not deserve it.''
</P>
<P>
   Cleland, then an Army captain, lost both legs and an arm in the
explosion of an M-26 fragmentation grenade on April 8, 1968.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Why does Charles Ruff, one of the key members of President
Clinton's defense team, use a wheelchair?
</P>
<P>
   A: He contracted a polio-type virus while teaching in Liberia in
the 1960s, and has been using a wheelchair ever since.
</P>
<P>
   Q: I understand that the amount of an estate that is not subject
to taxation will increase over the next several years to $1
million. Can you give me a breakdown by year and amount until that
maximum is reached?
</P>
<P>
   A: These are the years and the corresponding Applicable
Exclusion Amounts, the term used by the Internal Revenue Service:
1999, $650,000; 2000 and 2001, $675,000; 2002 and 2003, $700,000;
2004, $850,000; 2005, $950,000; and after 2005, $1 million.
</P>
<P>
   Q: A recent newspaper article said someone ``had stumbled onto
the Lascaux Cave of the computer industry.'' What does that mean?
I'm a spelunker and am interested in caves, and haven't been able
to find any information in my resources.
</P>
<P>
   A: The Lascaux Cave, situated above the Vezere Valley near
Montignac in southwestern France's Dordogne, is famous because of
art believed to have been placed there by Cro-Magnon man beginning
about 17,000 years ago. The cave consists of a main cavern and
several steep galleries, all magnificently decorated with engraved,
drawn and painted animals in shades of red, yellow, brown and black
on a light background. Painting at Lascaux continued over several
thousand years.
</P>
<P>
   After being sealed off since the last Ice Age, Lascaux was
discovered by accident in 1940. Soon after World War II, people
began flooding into the cave to see the paintings. The public has
been kept out since 1963 because the passage of so many visitors
was causing microscopic mosses and algae to grow on the walls,
damaging the art.
</P>
<P>
   Since you're a spelunker, if you visit there you still can see a
re-creation of the Lascaux Cave, with paintings of bison and
flying-hooved antelopes. It's at Lascaux II, near
Beynac-et-Cazenac.
</P>
<P>
   Q: What is the derivation of the expression ``salad days''?
</P>
<P>
   A: It refers to naive and inexperienced youth, and it comes to
us from Shakespeare's ``Antony and Cleopatra.'' Cleopatra, kidded
by Charmian about her old love for Julius Caesar, joked that those
were her ``salad days'' when she was ``green in judgment, cold in
blood.'' In other words, she loved Caesar unskillfully and without
much compassion, compared to the way she loved Mark Antony.
</P>
<P>
   The reality is quite different, however. According to the Facts
on File Encyclopedia of Word and Phrase Origins, the real Cleopatra
actually was a trained and artful lover before her adolescence, and
the salad days that Shakespeare has her admit to were distant
memories long before she married her brother at 17.
</P>
<P>
   Q: What do the initials R.E.M. stand for in the rock band?
</P>
<P>
   A: Many fans contend that the initials don't stand for anything.
Others have various versions, some not printable. But several
sources say there's no mystery at all. This is what The New Rolling
Stone Encyclopedia of Rock &AMP; Roll reports: ``In April 1980, the
four (Michael Stipe, Peter Buck, Mike Mills and Bill Berry) formed
R.E.M. (named for the dream-state rapid eye movement) and began
rehearsing in a converted Episcopal church.''
</P>
<P>
   Internet sites dealing with the origin of band names repeat the
``rapid eye movement'' story, saying it's the state of sleep in
which dreams occur, while one, The Heathen World Homepage, adds
that ``some say R.E.M. means Rightous Energetic Music.'' So take
your pick, or make up an explanation of your own.
</P>
<P>
   Q: What was the religion of Queen Noor of Jordan when she was
living in the United States, before she converted to Islam?
</P>
<P>
   A: Current Biography says she was a ``nominal Protestant'' _
denomination not specified _ who had never been baptized. Several
days before she married King Hussein on June 15, 1978, Lisa Halaby
expressed her adherence to Islam, which entailed her declaring
before an Islamic court that there is only one God, that God is
Allah, and that the Messenger of Allah is Muhammed the Prophet. In
accordance with the Jordanian tradition that the king's bride take
an Arabic name, Halaby became Noor al-Hussein.
</P>
<P>
   Q: What is the significance of Feb. 14 being designated
Valentine's Day? Is this a holiday created by some company for
commercial reasons?
</P>
<P>
   A: Don't blame (or credit) greeting card and candy companies, or
the florists of America, although they all enjoy mopping up the
cash flow associated with the day. Some people trace the beginning
of the Valentine's Day observance to an ancient Roman festival,
Lupercalia. It was held in mid-February to ensure protection from
wolves. There's a fertility rite involved, but we won't get into
that.
</P>
<P>
   Other experts associate the event with one or more saints of the
early Christian church, while still others link it with an old
English belief that birds choose their mates on Feb. 14. World Book
Encyclopedia concludes that Valentine's Day, as it's observed now,
probably came from a combination of all three sources, plus the
belief that spring is a time for lovers.
</P>
<P>
   Shakespeare even got into the act in ``A Midsummer Night's
Dream,'' in which a character discovers two lovers in the woods and
asks, ``St. Valentine's Day is past;/ Begin these woodbirds but to
couple now?''
</P>
<P>
   Q: While I was going through an old scrapbook of my mother's, I
came across an envelope with a 1 1/2-cent stamp. The postmark date
isn't clear, but I'm guessing it's around 1939. I've never heard of
a stamp that cost an uneven amount. Do you know anything about
this?
</P>
<P>
   A: Half-cent stamps, usually based on zones, were common in the
late 1930s, said Barry Ziehl of the Postal Service in Washington.
They varied in value and could be used for books or second- or
third-class material. In 1938, the post office issued a 1 1/2-cent
Martha Washington stamp, a half-cent Benjamin Franklin stamp, and a
4 1/2-cent White House stamp, Ziehl said. In 1939, a half-cent coil
stamp also was issued.
</P>
<P>
   Decimal stamps were issued by the Postal Service as recently as
1988, Ziehl said, such as 5.3 cents, 7.6 cents and 8.4 cents, and
were used primarily by nonprofit and small business mailers. But
those weren't the same as the half-centers, and even those have
been discontinued.
</P>
<P>
   Endit.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
