<HEADER>
A8333 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NEWS-QUESTIONS18-TAKE     02-17 1621
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NEWS-QUESTIONS18-TAKE1-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Q &AMP; A ON THE NEWS
 &HT;    (EDS: In two takes _ take 1)
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Have a question about the news? Colin Bessonette will try to get
an answer. Call 404-222-2002, or write him at The Atlanta
Journal-Constitution, P.O. Box 4689, Atlanta, Ga. 30302, or e-mail
him at
</P>
<P>
   q&AMP;(AT)ajc.com
</P>
<P>
   Q: What can you tell us about the background and whereabouts of
the mother of King Abdullah of Jordan?
</P>
<P>
   A: Antoinette ``Toni'' Gardiner was born in Chelmondiston,
England, near Ipswich. Educated at a convent school in Canterbury,
England, she started her working life as a typist and wage clerk.
She met Jordan's King Hussein at a party while she was visiting her
father, Lt. Col. Walter Gardiner, who was then serving at the
British Military Mission in Amman, Jordan. When she married Hussein
in 1961, taking the name Muna, she converted to Islam. It is said
that her personal modesty prevented her from adopting the title
queen. Abdullah was born Jan. 30, 1962, and when his parents
divorced 10 years later, Muna chose to remain in Amman, where she
lives in relative seclusion in an elegant villa. She never
remarried.
</P>
<P>
   After Muna's marriage, her parents moved to Amman, where her
mother died five years ago. Her father still lives there. Muna, now
58, also maintains a small home in London.
</P>
<P>
   Q: If you served in the Army during the Vietnam War era, but
didn't actually serve in Vietnam, are you still considered a
Vietnam veteran?
</P>
<P>
   A: Not by the definition used by the Department of Veterans
Affairs. Obviously it's a matter of semantics, VA spokesman Tom
Thomas said. The VA distinguishes between a Vietnam veteran (one
who actually served in-country in Vietnam) and a Vietnam-era
veteran (one who served during the defined period of the Vietnam
conflict: Aug. 5, 1964, through May 7, 1975).
</P>
<P>
   Q: What does the word ``pops'' mean in describing an orchestra?
</P>
<P>
   A: It comes from ``popular'' and means an orchestra specializing
in popular or light classical music, such as the Boston Pops.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Can you give us some information about the headdresses worn
by Arabic men, such as those we saw during TV coverage of the
funeral of Jordanian King Hussein and in frequent published photos
of Yasser Arafat?
</P>
<P>
   A: The kaffiyeh, the characteristic masculine Arab headdress, is
a square of cotton, linen, wool or silk, and can be either plain or
patterned. It is folded into a triangle and placed on the head so
that one point falls onto each shoulder and the third down the
back. It's held in place on the head by an agal, a corded band
decorated with beads or metallic threads. Originally cream-colored
or white, it now is seen in varying colors, with green, purple,
even red stitching.
</P>
<P>
   Designed more than a thousand years ago, the kaffiyeh protected
wandering Bedouins from the harsh desert climate of lethal sun and
sand storms. Eventually Arab workers in all but North Africa
started wearing it as a head cover, and more recently it made the
leap to Europe and the United States as a fashionable scarf. But in
the Middle East, the kaffiyeh is much more than an item of fashion.
It's an emblem of masculinity, maturity and nationalism, almost a
substitute flag, and can be viewed in some cases as a political
statement. Having crossed many eras and cultures, the kaffiyeh is
worn by Muslims, Christians and Druse, as well as by tourists and
even street vendors in Manhattan and other cities.
</P>
<P>
   Q: If a U.S. president were impeached and forced to leave
office, he would lose certain benefits and privileges, such as his
pension. But would he also lose his lifetime Secret Service
protection?
</P>
<P>
   A: No. Secret Service protection is an open-ended entitlement to
any and all former presidents, said Pete Sepp of the National
Taxpayers Union. It's accorded to them regardless of whether they
simply serve out their term, resign or are impeached and convicted.
``The law treats them all the same,'' Sepp said. Such protection is
governed by a part of the U.S. Code pertaining to the Treasury
Department. The only limitation is that presidents elected after
Clinton will be limited to 10 years of Secret Service protection.
That was passed several years ago.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton's pension will start at about $151,800 a year,
Sepp said, with additional office and staff allowances budgeted at
$450,000 to $650,000 a year. A presidential pension and other
allowances would be stripped in their entirety only if a president
were both impeached and convicted.
</P>
<P>
   Q: What has become of Spencer Christian, the wise-cracking,
cheerful weatherman on ABC's ``Good Morning America''? We miss him.
</P>
<P>
   A: It was reported last July that the network was not offering
Christian a new contract, but was extending his previous contract
by six months. So, after a dozen years of reporting on sun, rain
and snow, mixed with trademark witty repartee with his coworkers,
he left New York Jan. 1 for KGO-TV in San Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   Q: I'm interested in the mascot names of two schools. What is a
wahoo, and what is a hokie? I need to know the schools, and what
the names mean.
</P>
<P>
   A: A wahoo is the informal mascot of the University of Virginia
at Charlottesville. It refers to a UVA student; an under-hoo is an
undergraduate. According to UVA's Internet site, it's derived from
a fish that can drink twice its weight daily. We'll leave the
interpretation up to you.
</P>
<P>
   Hokie is associated with Virginia Tech. It dates to the late
1800s, when the school, at Blacksburg, changed its name from
Virginia Agriculture and Mechanical College to Virginia Polytechnic
Institute. The original college cheer, which referred to the
school's original name, no longer made sense. So a spirit contest
was held, and O.M. Stull (class of 1896) came up with a new cheer,
known as Old Hokie, for which he won $5. Stull said he made up the
word hokie _ no explanation for spelling it with and without the
``e'' _ just to attract attention, and it had no hidden or symbolic
meaning. The words:
</P>
<P>
   Hoki, Hoki, Hoki Hy!/
</P>
<P>
   Tech! Tech! V.P.I./
</P>
<P>
   Sola-Rex Sola-Rah/
</P>
<P>
   Polytech-Vir-gin-i-a/
</P>
<P>
   Rae, Ri, V.P.I./
</P>
<P>
   Team! Team! Team!
</P>
<P>
   Q: How many known American veterans of World War I are still
alive? And when did the last American veteran of the
Spanish-American War die?
</P>
<P>
   A. The population of American World War I veterans is declining
rapidly and is now estimated at 3,200, said Tom Thomas of the
Department of Veterans Affairs. The last American veteran of the
Spanish-American War, Nathan E. Cook, died at age 106 on Sept. 10,
1992.
</P>
<P>
   A footnote: As of July 1, 1998, the VA's compensation and
pension rolls showed that 46,311 spouses of World War I veterans,
and 694 spouses of the Spanish-American War, were living.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Republican Rep. Matt Salmon of Arizona is proposing a bill to
add Ronald Reagan's image to Mount Rushmore. What House committee
is handling this legislation, and whom can we contact on that
committee from Georgia to express our concern?
</P>
<P>
   A: The bill will be introduced Feb. 23, said Michael Paranzino
of Salmon's Washington office. What happens after that isn't known,
so there's no one to contact at this point. You're always welcome
to sound off to your representative about any concern you have, of
course.
</P>
<P>
   Salmon proposes to create a foundation that would raise
voluntary contributions _ ``no tax dollars involved,'' Paranzino
emphasized _ to finance the Reagan addition to Rushmore, which is
famous for its giant images of Presidents George Washington, Thomas
Jefferson, Abraham Lincoln and Theodore Roosevelt. The proposal
would establish a commission of experts, Paranzino said, adding
that the project wouldn't go forward if the commission determined
it would harm the existing sculpture.
</P>
<P>
   When he announced his plan Feb. 1, this was Salmon's explanation
for his proposal: ``Ronald Reagan won the Cold War and began the
unprecedented economic growth we have been enjoying for more than
15 years now. He also restored America's hope and faith in the
future. As the 20th century's greatest president, he should be on
Mount Rushmore.''
</P>
<P>
   Salmon's idea isn't expected to go far. The reaction of the
Mount Rushmore memorial is that sculptor Gutzon Borglum decided
long ago there's no more room on the mountain for another face.
</P>
<P>
   Q: What is the timetable for the United States to turn the
Panama Canal over to the Panamanians? Several of us are debating
it.
</P>
<P>
   A: It's scheduled to happen in about 10 1/2 months. The canal
was completed in 1917, with the United States taking control of the
canal and the Panama Canal Zone, a special area bordering the
canal. In 1977, Panama and the United States signed a treaty that
resulted in the transfer of the zone to Panama in 1979. The treaty
also provided for the transfer of the canal to Panama on Dec. 31.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Is a transcript available of Rep. Bob Barr's speech to the
Council of Conservative Citizens?
</P>
<P>
   A: Apparently not. Barr (R-Ga.), who spoke to the controversial
group in Charleston, S.C., in June, didn't have a speech prepared
in advance, said spokesman Brad Alexander in Washington. No
transcript is available from the group, either, said Gordon Baum at
its St. Louis headquarters. Baum said he thought Barr had some
notes scribbled on the back of an envelope, but he wasn't sure.
Barr has distanced himself from the council, saying he disagrees
with its racial views, which he finds ``repugnant.'' He said he
merely spoke to the group because he was invited to do so. Both
Alexander and Baum said Barr's topic was presidential impeachment.
</P>
<P>
   MORE
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
