<HEADER>
A8344 &Cx1f; tad-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BYRON18-COX     02-17 0798
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BYRON18-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Don Byron's colors of the clarinetBy Michael Point
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ ``People have a preconceived notion of what a
clarinetist is supposed to play,'' Don Byron says. ``It's like
there's some unwritten rule about what you can do with the
instrument and what you can't, despite all its possibilities.''
</P>
<P>
   Few have explored the clarinet's potential with more consistent
creativity than Byron, whose unpredictable arc through modern music
has redefined the instrument's role while using it to open ears to
forgotten wonders of the past. Byron, classically trained at the
New England Conservatory of Music and jazz experienced, via
ground-breaking work with Bill Frisell, Bobby Previte and Ralph
Peterson, is an omnivorous music consumer who believes in using all
the colors available, as well as occasionally coloring outside the
lines.
</P>
<P>
   ``I like to take the whole culture and use it,'' Byron says.
``There's so much out there that goes ignored, and so many ways of
interconnecting things, that I can never understand why musicians
ever have trouble finding something to inspire them.''
</P>
<P>
   The 40-year-old New Yorker has spent less than a decade in the
spotlight but he's already created a body of work adventurous and
wide-ranging enough to serve as complete careers for less eclectic
musicians. ``Tuskeegee Experiments,'' his stunning 1992 debut as a
leader, presented his personalized takes on everyone from Ellington
to Schuman, while ``Music for Six Musicians'' shifted the focus to
Latin jazz and ``No Vibe Zone'' emphasized a more modern jazz
approach.
</P>
<P>
   Had Byron recorded only these albums his identity as the best
and brightest clarinetist on the contemporary jazz scene would have
been a clear one. But he muddied the waters by tackling other
musical forms, beginning with a controversial album of klezmer
music.
</P>
<P>
   Byron's tribute to klezmer cutup Mickey Katz caught the music
world off guard, despite the fact he had performed with a klezmer
repertory band for a decade. Jewish scholars were outraged, jazz
fans were perplexed and Byron was amazed.
</P>
<P>
   ``No one seemed to hear the music,'' Byron says. ``People were
writing editorials and giving lectures about how I wasn't treating
the music properly, yet no one else was even bothering to play
it.''
</P>
<P>
   If Byron had just played straight-ahead traditional klezmer he
would have been proclaimed a musical hero. But by opting for an
esoteric approach, he upset many listeners, even while making the
best neo-klezmer album to date. That approach is a constant in
Byron's career, and it's spectacularly showcased in the live show
he's bringing to town Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bug Music,'' named after Byron's favorite episode of ``The
Flintstones,'' remains one of his most popular musical personas.
The mirthful music is nominally jazz, but it's jazz caught at an
intersection of classical and cartoon music. The approach was the
creation of composers such as Raymond Scott, John Kirby and the
early Duke Ellington. Full of elastic adaptability, the music swung
in a manner regular swing didn't and, like the music of Katz, it
proudly included comic overtones.
</P>
<P>
   Byron performs the unusual ``Bug Music'' repertoire with wit and
respect, and his emphasis on Scott and Kirby, innovative stylists
and synthesists whose accomplishments have been downplayed, if not
actually ignored, by modern critics, graphically illustrates his
decidedly different sort of repertory jazz approach.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most repertory bands always stress the obvious and the
overexposed and miss the material that really deserves to be heard
by more people,'' Byron says.
</P>
<P>
   It's not enough that Byron confused jazz fans with an
off-the-wall klezmer album, or that he mixed cartoon music with the
classics. Even those who thought they were ready for anything were
surprised at last year's ``Nu Blaxploitation,'' a fun and funky
fusion effort featuring the tunes of Mandrill, Byron's favorite
band as a teen-ager.
</P>
<P>
   Once Byron fans have fully absorbed Mandrill, they'll be able to
move on to classical composer Igor Stravinsky, another recording
project Byron is involved with.
</P>
<P>
   ``I never have to go out and search for new ideas or concepts,''
Byron says. ``There's a whole universe full of great music that
deserves to be heard.''
</P>
<P>
   So whether it's Mickey Katz or Mandrill, Raymond Scott or
Schuman, Byron is on the beat.
</P>
<P>
   ``I dream of the day when people won't care what type of music I
play,'' Byron says. ``I just want to be able to follow my heart and
soul and hopefully take some like-minded fans with me on the
journey.''
</P>
<P>
   Michael Point writes for the Austin American-Statesman, Austin,
Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
