<HEADER>
A8345 &Cx1f; tad-z
u d &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-JUICY-ROAST18-COX     02-17 0447
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JUICY-ROAST18-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Salt-and-water blend pours waves of tenderness into the driest
roasts
 &HT;    By Ann Heller
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _ If you're too young to remember the good old
days, think of this as a legend. Once upon a time, a Sunday pork
roast was a tender, succulent treat.
</P>
<P>
   That was before farmers bred most of the fat from the pig,
leaving us with a rather svelte porker. And a skinny pig produces a
dry roast. Sure, some cuts still retain a little internal fat, but
the pork loin of today is closing in on chicken breast as a low-fat
choice.
</P>
<P>
   And boneless pork loin is the way most Americans want their meat
these days _ easy to slice and with no bones to remind them of the
origins of the meat.
</P>
<P>
   What's a cook to do? A few chefs and cooking experts say the
answer is easy: brine it.
</P>
<P>
   Remember the new approach to Thanksgiving turkey? Lots of cooks
have adopted brining the bird as a way to ensure a moist and tender
breast. The technique works on roast chicken as well.
</P>
<P>
   So listen up if you're tired of dry, rather flavorless, pork
roasts and chops. The cure is a cure.
</P>
<P>
   The brine is simple; just a mixture of coarse salt and sugar
dissolved in water with added seasonings. Because the brine
penetrates the meat, so does whatever flavoring is used. That's a
bonus because traditional marinades just stay on the surface.
</P>
<P>
   Doesn't the brine make all pork taste like ham, one skeptic
asked? No, because the brine bath is short, just four to six hours
for chops and a day or two for a roast.
</P>
<P>
   Obviously, this does requires a little planning but the amount
of work is minimal. Making the brine takes at most five minutes.
Add the meat and let the brine do its work for the allotted time.
Then proceed with your recipe, which can be as simple as grilled
chops.
</P>
<P>
   An explanation of why this works? Scientists understand that
better than those of us who just cook. Harold McGee, the
much-quoted California specialist in the science of cooking, says
it's osmosis. ``The meat absorbs the salt water. The salt begins to
denature the meat proteins, causing them to unwind and form a
matrix that traps the water.''
</P>
<P>
   Another way of saying that comes from Gourmet magazine: ``The
salt is the key element. Its electrically charged ions make the
muscle fibers plump up and absorb more water. The structure of the
protein changes as well, preventing water from escaping during
cooking.''
</P>
<P>
   See, I told you the scientists would understand.
</P>
<P>
   I just know that it works.
</P>
<P>
   Ann Heller writes for the Dayton Daily News, Dayton, Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
