</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GOODSTUFF18-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Good stuff
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   While some of us have gone to the no-soak method of preparing
dried beans, the Bean Education &AMP; Awareness Network says there's
still one good reason to soak. A new study says soaking helps
dissolve oligosaccharides, the indigestible sugars that cause gas.
The quick hot-soak method is more effective in reducing those
sugars than the traditional overnight soak.
</P>
<P>
   One good reminder
</P>
<P>
   Just in case you missed the point that baking soda has uses
beyond cooking, Arm &AMP; Hammer is introducing a blue Fridge-n-Freezer
box specially designed to deodorize the refrigerator. Tear-off
panels and cloth filters make the new box more effective than the
familiar yellow box we all tuck inside our refrigerators.
</P>
<P>
   Sneaky sugar hides in some food
</P>
<P>
   Wonder where the pounds come from?
</P>
<P>
   Experts say the sugar Americans consume adds to the problem _
about 20 teaspoons, or 320 calories a day. Not you, you say? Well,
look where it's hiding: 13 teaspoons in a cup of Dannon French
Vanilla Low Fat Yogurt with Raspberries, and six teaspoons in a
half-cup of Mott's applesauce _ more than is in a Hershey's milk
chocolate bar.
</P>
<P>
   Sugar hides in such disguises as high-fructose corn syrup,
honey, molasses, sorghum syrup and even fruit juice concentrate,
notes the Tufts University Health &AMP; Nutrition Letter.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
