<HEADER>
A8347 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-REDS-BELINDA18-COX     02-17 1018
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-REDS-BELINDA18-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Belinda playing baseball again, despite MS
 &HT;    By Hal McCoy
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   SARASOTA, Fla. _ A brown cardboard box stuffed with baseball
equipment was in front of him and Stan Belinda slowly, almost
lovingly, sorted through it, touching each sock, each sweat shirt,
each shoe as if they were gold.
</P>
<P>
   To Belinda, they are better than gold. They are life
re-incarnate.
</P>
<P>
   A few months ago he was diagnosed with multiple sclerosis and
feared he might never again use the baseball equipment and clothing
he'll put on today to work out with the Cincinnati Reds.
</P>
<P>
   It was last Sept. 21 at the Mayo Clinic when Dr. John Noseworthy
confirmed that the 32-year-old relief pitcher had MS, a diagnosis
first made by Cincinnati's Dr. Robert Reed with a spinal tap on
Aug. 25.
</P>
<P>
   ``A tough, tough day,'' Belinda said Tuesday, his eyes reddening
as he fought tears, both from joy at being back and from the
unpleasant memories. ``I'd gone through so many tests, then a
nine-day waiting period to confirm the diagnosis. I was in la-la
land after I was told. I was sitting on the doctor's table and I
broke down in tears. My wife (Lori) broke down and my (two) kids
were in the room and they didn't understand what was happening.''
</P>
<P>
   Cincinnati Reds medical consultant Dr. Tim Kremchek implored
Belinda not to give up, not to quit the game and retreat to his
Huntingdon, Pa., home. Dr. Noseworthy told Kremchek, without naming
names, that there are 10 to 20 active professional athletes with MS
and many more have participated while carrying the incurable
disease.
</P>
<P>
   And Belinda has been helped by Copaxane, a new drug approved by
the Food and Drug Administration just last year that minimizes the
symptoms.
</P>
<P>
   ``Coming in here to this clubhouse today is a big boost and a
jolt,'' Belinda said. ``It all came together for me. I did come
back.''
</P>
<P>
   Belinda has been without symptoms for several months, which is
extremely encouraging, but May 15, 1998, is indelibly etched in his
mind.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've marked down the date . . . it hit me overnight like a
Mike Tyson punch to the head,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   His left leg had a tingling feeling. It went away for three or
four weeks, then the tingling was back in his leg, his foot, the
bottom of his foot and moved up to his back, stomach, neck and
cheeks.
</P>
<P>
   ``When it went to my cheeks and the side of my head, I threw up
the red flag,'' he said. ``I was performing well, but I had to put
myself ahead of the team, which is something real hard for me, one
of the hardest things I've ever done.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, Belinda made five appearances over six innings in August
and hadn't given up a run. But he knew his body was shouting at him
that all systems were not go.
</P>
<P>
   Then came the crushing diagnosis.
</P>
<P>
   ``My career has been a roller coaster ride,'' Belinda said.
``Some very low points. Everybody brings up the Francisco Cabrera
hit. That haunted me for years.''
</P>
<P>
   In Game 7 of the 1992 National League Championship Series,
Belinda, then pitching for Pittsburgh, had a tie game on his hands
in the ninth inning in Atlanta. Pinch-hitter Cabrera scorched a hit
down the left field line and slow-footed Sid Bream slid across home
plate with the winning run, sending the Braves to the World Series,
the Pirates home and Belinda into Pittsburgh's Hall of Infamy. To
this day, heartless Pittsburgh fans boo whenever Belinda sticks his
head out of a dugout.
</P>
<P>
   And it bothered him. No more.
</P>
<P>
   ``No hit can happen that hits you like this (MS),'' Belinda
said. ``In baseball, I knew I'd always get another chance. With
this you don't know. I thank God I'm sitting here, able to make
another run. In fact, it might make me a better player. I won't
worry what my stats are going to be at end of the year. This is not
an everyday task; this is an every-minute task and mentally, it
drains you.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now, though, if I give up a home run and lose a game, it won't
be the end of the world to me, like it used to be,'' he said.
``That's not what life is all about. Life is about trying your
best, giving it your all and being good and kind to people.''
</P>
<P>
   The Reds are giving him a chance to resume his career, but
Belinda can't deliver a prognosis on his future.
</P>
<P>
   ``You've asked a question I can't answer,'' he said. ``Every
case is different. It's one of those things where time will tell
everything. They gave me a good bill of health and I'll go day by
day, put it in the Lord's hands, put my life in God's hands.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been throwing for five or six weeks, working out, running
2 miles every three or four days. The main thing is not to get
over-fatigued and to gradually build my body system up . . . and
just hope symptoms don't pop up.''
</P>
<P>
   Belinda self-injects the Copaxane once a day, even though a year
ago he would rather face Mark McGwire with a game on the line than
stare at the sharp end of a needle.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was deathly afraid of needles,'' he said. ``That was a major
mental hurdle. I took at least an hour before I could do the first
one. By the fourth or fifth one, it became part of my life. It's
worth 15 minutes a day if it makes me feel better, and it does.
There are a lot of things I don't understand about this disease,
but I've come to grips with it. And I don't dwell on it. The more
you dwell on it mentally, the worse the symptoms get.''
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Kremchek said symptoms may not show up again, ``for many,
many years. He may finish his career and his life symptom-free. We
know it is not hereditary or contagious and it is suspected to be
viral.''
</P>
<P>
   Belinda, of course, was frightened after the diagnosis. Calls in
late September from teammates and players on other teams comforted
him as he slowly pieced together his shattered mental state.
</P>
<P>
   ``I tried to set up a game plan all winter, to work at it
mentally,'' he said. ``The mental part is the toughest thing.
Physically, I was able to deal my entire career with groin injuries
and other stuff because I knew they'd heal. This is different.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
