<HEADER>
A8348 &Cx1f; tad-z
u d &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ROAST-TEMPERATURE18-C     02-17 0237
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ROAST-TEMPERATURE18-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Juices run dry when roast cooks too long
 &HT;    By Ann Heller
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   There's more than one secret to putting a tender, juicy pork
roast on the dinner table. Brining the roast before cooking is one.
The other one , and it is just as important, is this: Don't
overcook it.
</P>
<P>
   Disregard recipes that say to cook pork to 180 degrees or even
170 degrees. They're as out of date as lard.
</P>
<P>
   As Merle Ellis says in The Great American Meat Book, ``To cook
today's pork to those temperatures would be akin to cremation.''
Experts agree that the absolute maximum internal temperature is 160
degrees, and they recommend pulling the roast out of the oven at
150 to 155 degrees because the temperature will continue to rise.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, you will see a faint blush. And that's OK. The bacteria
responsible for trichinosis are killed at 137 degrees.
</P>
<P>
   Measuring the temperature is easiest with a roast. Use an
instant-read thermometer. Be sure to insert it at least two inches
into the roast. That's harder to do with chops, even thick ones,
though it can be done from the side. A better bet may be the old
checkpoint: Cut into the pork with a sharp knife to make sure the
chop is done but still retains that slight blush.
</P>
<P>
   Ann Heller writes for the Dayton Daily News, Dayton, Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
