 &HT;    COX NEWS SERVICE COMMENTARY BUDGET
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   These columns for release Thursday, February 18, 1999 are moving
today to clients of the New York Times News Service.
</P>
<P>
   All columns have moved, in the commentary (k) category. If you
have questions or need a resend, please call CoxNet, the Cox News
Service, at 404-526-5456.
</P>
<P>
   NETHAWAY-COLUMN _ PRESIDIO OF MONTEREY, Calif. _ Enough
relatives came to celebrate young Alpha Nethaway's graduation rom
the Defense Language Institute at the Presidio that we arrived at
the base in a three-car caravan, with one more soon to follow. I
expected a ceremony that included precision marching past a high
grandstand on a huge parade ground, gleaming swords, colorful
pennants and flags and perhaps a military band, cannon salutes and
fly-over of military jets trailing red, white and blue smoke. My
military training was of a different era. It also was considerably
less subtle and cerebral. I also expected to see a graduation class
numbering in the hundreds, if not thousands. As it turned out, the
ceremony had no marching, swords, pennants, flags, music or cannon
fire. And there was no fly-over. (Nethaway, Waco Tribune-Herald)
MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   MCCARTY-COLUMN _ DAYTON, Ohio _ ``Tell me about your families,''
child therapist Karen McQueary tells her young clients at the
Artemis Center for Alternatives to Domestic Violence. They often
say, ``I don't want to,'' or ``Pass.'' ``It's too scary,'' they
explain. ``It makes me sad.'' Many of the children, too traumatized
to trust adults, initially reveal themselves only through their
artwork. For McQueary, a pad of paper and a pencil can be the
``Open Sesame'' to their souls. ``I feel glad and sad and
frightened,'' one 8-year-old captioned his drawing of a father and
a child crying purple tears. ``I feel upset that Dad had to go to
jale. I feel lonely.'' This child's-eye view of domestic violence
will be displayed Saturday night at Sinclair Community College at
the ninth annual Artemis gala as part of an exhibit,
``Expressions,'' featuring original artwork by Artemis clients,
children and adults. (McCarty, Dayton Daily News) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
