<P>
   FOOD
</P>
<P>
   FOOD FROM ATLANTA
</P>
<P>
   FOOD-AFRICAN _ ``You can trace a whole history in a bean
fritter,'' said noted African food scholar Jessica Harris to a
handful of folks who'd gathered at the Shrine of the Black Madonna
on Abernathy Boulevard in late January. Harris described how the
bean fritter (akara) of Nigeria gave way to the black-eyed pea
fritter (acarage) in Brazil and then to the corn fritters of the
American south. That's the way it is with African food -- it
flavors so many different cuisines. And yet we tend to know so
little about it. We cooked and talked with Harris, author of The
Africa Cookbook: Tastes of a Continent, as well as some Atlantans
for a survey of African food, from orange radish salad of Morocco
to the sizzling sosaties of South Africa. (Walker, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution) WITH COLOR PHOTO.
</P>
<P>
   FOOD-AFRICAN-RECIPES _ Recipe page to go with African story
centerpieced on AJC weekly food section. (Walker, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   FOOD-RECIPESWAP _A weekly recipe exchange column. This week:
German Chocolate pie. (Langhenry, Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   FOOD-SKUBE-BEERCOLUMN _ A weekly beer column by the Michael
Skube of the Atlanta Journal-Constitution. This week: Brewing with
hemp seed. (Skube, Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   FOOD-CYBERSPICE _ A weekly column looking at the plethora of
recipes on the Internet. (Parham, Atlanta Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   FOOD/FROM DAYTON
</P>
