 ENTERTAINMENT SUMMARY No 421 - February 17, 1999   ENTERTAINMENT
SUMMARY -- No. 421 -- Feb. 17, 1999 We are offering the following
articles for sale. Please contact us for availability your country.
Best regards, Karl Horwitz
<TEXT>
<P>
   1. RACHEL GRIFFITHS' VIRTUOSO SCREEN DUET Oscar-nominated
actress Rachel Griffiths shares on and off-screen experiences in
the making of the film about cellist Jacqueline du Pre, ``Hilary
and Jackie.'' By Louise Farr. From Women's Wear Daily. 800 words +
photo. 2. RETURN OF THE MAGNIFICENT SEVEN Seven strapping young
males with guns in the Wild West? Sounds like a series with the
right demographic appeal. Based on the 1960 big-screen classic
starring Yul Brynner and Steve McQueen, ``The Magnificent Seven''
TV series is an unapologetic throwback to the western shoot-'em-up
and has a devoted fan base. By Tamara Conniff. BPI. 700 words +
photo. 3. JULIA SWEENEY BATTLES CANCER WITH COMEDY Comedian Julia
Sweeney went from the top TV show ``Saturday Night Live'' to the
worst year of her life. Her brother became ill with cancer and
moved in with her. Her parents got worried and moved in too. Her
little house was soon full and her daily routine was derailed. And
that was just the beginning. For the icing on this horrible cake,
Sweeney herself contracted cancer. Like many artists she did the
only thing she could in the face of adversity and channeled it into
her work. She has turned her harrowing, real-life experiences into
an acclaimed one-woman stage show, ``God Said,Ha!'' And now she's
made a film version of it - a moving and funny look at what it's
like when everything goes wrong. By Joshua Mooney. BPI. 1,200 words
+ photo. 4. IF ONLY WE COULD ALL BE 'FRIENDS' In many ways,
``Friends'' is like a fast-and-funny soap opera. All of the cast
are attractive, have interesting lives, great clothes and
apartments. In its sixth season, the slick formula still works and
has propelled the show to its highest ratings ever. This interview
with the cast shows how level-headed they are about their success.
By Andrew Ryan. From TV Guide Canada. 1,300 words + photo
____________________________________________________________ 5.
GENE WILDER RETURNS TO THE SMALL SCREEN Comic actor Gene Wilder may
be open, talkative and friendly, but he is a distinctly serious
man. That's understandable, since he has known his share of
unhappiness along with the laughter, most notably the 1989 death
from ovarian cancer of his wife, comedian Gilda Radner. ``My early
life was a combination of sadness and hilarity,'' the 63-year-old
Wilder says in this interview. ``My mother was so ill, I was told
not to ever argue with her, because it might kill her. But I was
told to make her laugh.'' Wilder will turn up as the Mock Turtle in
a three-hour-long movie of Lewis Carroll's ``Alice's Adventures in
Wonderland.'' By Ian Spelling. 1,300 words + photo. 6. MARK
WAHLBERG BIDS FOR ACTION STARDOM Alma Wahlberg wants to see less of
her son Mark. It was bad enough when he was modeling Calvin Klein
underwear, but in ``Boogie Nights'' (1997) he often wore nothing at
all. And for the past few months, the movie has been playing around
the clock on cable TV. In this interview Wahlberg talks about fame,
embarassing questions about his career, breaking the rules and his
stint in jail. By Cindy Pearlman. 1,300 words + photo.
____________________________________________________________ 7.
BACK TO BASICS, VINCE GILL LOOKS FOR HIS COUNTRY ROOTS He may be a
poster boy for today's emerging traditional country music, but
don't say that to Vince Gill. The singer/songwriter, whose personal
artistic style has run from bluegrass to country/pop, looked back
to his country roots for his latest studio album, ``The Key,'' a
salute to the style of classic country. Gill insists that he
recorded this particular set of songs for himself, not intending to
lead any parade back to what he interprets country music to be.
Interview by Beth Torroll. 1,300 words + photo.
