<HEADLINE>
EDITORS:
</HEADLINE>
  
 Wednesday, Feb. 17, 1999      The Hearst News Service will file the following stories for
Thursday If you have questions, please call Tim Spence at
202-298-6920.  
    (Slugline includes the ``HNS'' tag.)
   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NATIONAL NEWS (``a'' category)
</P>
<P>
   SCHOOLS-RACE (San Francisco) _ Faced with the end of a
race-based admissions system, San Francisco Unified School District
may adopt a less controversial form of affirmative action:
preferences for kids who face personal and economic hardship. A
tentative settlement reached Tuesday would topple the school
district's 15-year-old race-conscious admissions policy. By JULIAN
GUTHRIE.
</P>
<P>
   JASPER-REBEL (Jasper, Texas) _ Call it the scout manual from
hell. When lawmen investigating the brutal dragging death of James
Byrd Jr. searched the apartment of murder defendant Bill King, they
found handwritten outlines, bylaws and recruiting letters for what
he called the Confederate Knights of America's Texas Rebel
Soldiers. By RICHARD STEWART.
</P>
<P>
   INDIAN-SITE (Rotterdam, N.Y.) _ A group of Native American in
upstate New York plan a gathering place for expatriates of various
Native American nations who, far from their reservations, have made
their homes in cities and suburbs. By JAY JOCHNOWITZ.
</P>
<P>
   Y2K-ELECTRICAL (Clifton Park, N.Y.) _ New York's power companies
say they expect few, if any, blackouts because of Y2K. But many New
Yorkers aren't buying it. They are, however, buying generators to
supply backup power in the event things don't work as well as
officials say. Sales of power generators and other equipment in New
York state are skyrocketing. By ALAN WECHSLER.
</P>
<P>
   SF-MAYOR (San Francisco) _ Clint Reilly, the former campaign
consultant-turned-businessman, plans to announce his candidacy for
the upcoming mayoral election. With his announcement, Reilly steps
out from behind the scenes where for years her served as a player
in San Francisco and state politics, running campaigns for other
people and causes. By RACHEL GORDON.
</P>
<P>
   BUSINESS/FINANCIAL NEWS (``f'' category)
</P>
<P>
   CAREERS (San Francisco) _ The man who built his career around
selling envelopes has come out with another mixed bag. Bestselling
author Harvey Mackay's latest motivational book, ``Pushing the
Envelope All the Way to the Top,'' doesn't fit neatly into any sort
of career category. He warns CEOs about why companies fail,
explains how he has attracted workers to his Mackay Envelope Corp.
in Minneapolis and describes the traits that help people rise to
the top. By DAVE MURPHY.
</P>
<P>
   WOMEN-INVESTORS (San Francisco) _ Linda Pei, a San Francisco
banker, wanted to make a strong statement about male dominence in
the business world. So she and a former co-worker pooled $50,000
from friends in 1993 to start the Pro-Conscience Women's Equity
Mutual Fund, which invests in companies with pro-women policies.
Today, the fund manages $8.7 million in assets and holds stock in
50 large-cap companies. By EDWARD IWATA.
</P>
<P>
   LEVI'S-COMPETITION (San Francisco) _ Dickies. JNCO. Fubu. Pelle
Pelle. If you've never heard of them, you're showing your age.
Those are some of the labels responsible for Levi Strauss &AMP; Co.'s
13 percent sales slide in 1998, the 146-year-old jeans maker's
largest percentage decline in at least 50 years. By VICTORIA
COLLIVER.
</P>
<P>
   ENTERTAINMENT (``e'' category)
</P>
<P>
   BOOKS-THRILLERS (Undated) _ Two of the best writers of the
historical thriller genre are Robert Harris and Joseph Kanon.
Harris' latest, ``Archangel'' tells of four days in the life of a
former Oxford historian who travels to Moscow to attend a
conference on the recently opened Soviet archives. In the ``The
Prodigal Spy,'' Kanon pegs his second historical thriller to the
witch hunts of the House Un-American Activities Committee of the
1950s. By BOBBIE HESS.
</P>
<P>
   LIFESTYLE/FEATURES (``l'' category)
</P>
<P>
   SEEING-RED (Albany, N.Y.) _ Throughout history, the color red
has carried many different connotations _ from aggression and
destruction to vibrant emotion to love and the celebration of life.
Yet it also is a color favored historically in interior design for
its warmth and intimacy. By FRANCES INGRAHAM.
</P>
<P>
   MAILBOXES (Albany, N.Y.) _ Door-to-door city mail delivery began
in the mid-1860s. Ever since then, the mailbox has become a
decorative necessity that we place at the entrance to our homes and
apartments. By FRANCES INGRAHAM.
</P>
<P>
   GARDEN-COLUMN (Undated) _ A reader wants to know what she can do
to help her star cactus bloom again. A Q&AMP;A. By KATHY HUBER
</P>
<P>
   SPORTS (``s'' category) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   SNOWBOARDING (Undated) _ On any given slope in North America, it
appears that snowboarders out number skiers. While statistics
indicate that isn't true, snowboarders are proliferating. Once
dominated by teen-age boys rebelling against their skiing parents,
the sport is attracting children, young girls, Generation Xers and
people over the age of 40 in record numbers. By KIM McHUGH.
</P>
<P>
   OLY-RATTO (San Francisco) _ Salt Lake City is quiet these days,
perhaps because the city finally ran out of things to give to the
International Olympic Committee's Directorate of Graft. Of course,
it's easy for outlanders to crack smug about Salt Lake's scandal of
the century. It wanted to be a player at the world's game and found
out face-first that the seat at the table costs way too much, both
in cash and self-esteem. By RAY RATTO.
</P>
<P>
   TRAVEL (``t'' category)
</P>
<P>
   TRAVEL-COLUMN (Undated) _ Some international travelers are
experiencing problems using credit cards whose expiration dates are
2000 and beyond. A cooperative effort among major credit card
companies is ongoing but the State Department is concerned enough
to issue an announcement alerting travelers about potential
problems. By HARRY SHATTUCK.
</P>
<P>
   FOOD (``d'' category)
</P>
<P>
   CREPES (Undated) _ With all the ado about ``wraps'' these days,
you'd think enveloping food in a pancake was something new. It's
not. Remember crepes? Those light, feathery French pancakes that
used to appear on fancy restaurant menus in the '60s. They were
filled with cheeses, fruit, seafood and chicken. They were drenched
in newburg sauce, cheese sauce or spirits. And they were a pain to
make. Not anymore. By RUTH FANTASIA.
</P>
<P>
   COMMENTARY (``k'' category)
</P>
<P>
   LYNCH-COLUMN (Albany, N.Y.) _ We were sitting around one night
not too long ago _ me, Henry Zwack and a bunch of farmers from
Rensselaer County, N.Y. We were all thinking pretty much the same
thing: Wouldn't it be great if Fidel Castro died? Everything would
be so much simpler. By DAN LYNCH.
</P>
