A8395 &Cx1f; tad-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-VIDEO-MINIS18-COX     02-17 0341
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VIDEO-MINIS18-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Mini reviews of movies released on video
 &HT;    By Steve Murray and Eleanor Ringel
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QR;  ``Snake Eyes'' (R) _ The best thing you can say about this
movie? Well, at least Brian De Palma can only go up from here. In
his very unpredictable career _ from his early Hitchcock rip-offs
to slick Hollywood fare (``The Untouchables'') _ this would-be
thriller has to be his worst work yet. Nicolas Cage plays a crooked
cop at an Atlantic City prize fight _ during which, the secretary
of state is shot and killed. So it's up to Cage (and the
secretary's security chief) to find the killer among the tens of
thousands of ringside fans. You get what you expect from the
director: lots of look-at-me camera angles, tracking shots and
women in dumb wigs. What you don't get is a remotely plausible
story or an ounce of real suspense. It's like De Palma, ripping off
De Palma. Badly. Grade: D
</P>
<P>
   _ Steve Murray
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``The Governess'' (R) _ Where's Mary Poppins when you need
her? In the 1840s a young Jewish woman (Minnie Driver) poses as a
Christian to secure a job with a wealthy family on a remote
Scottish island and help her own debt-stricken family. The film
tries to deliver a treatise on religious bigotry plus a dollop of
feminism within the context of a fevered bodice-ripper. What
evolves is an overbusy movie with under-realized potential. Grade:
C
</P>
<P>
   _ Steve Murray
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``Beyond Silence'' (PG-13) _ A film worth listening to.
Germany's Oscar nominee for best foreign-language film concerns a
musical prodigy who is also her hearing-impaired parents' crucial
link to the rest of the world. Sensitive and well-acted, the film
uses a specific situation to explore a universal one: how children
must learn to separate from their parents without cutting them off.
In German with subtitles. Grade: B +
</P>
<P>
   _ Eleanor Ringel
</P>
<P>
   Steve Murray and Eleanor Ringel write for the Atlanta
Journal-Constitutions.
</P>
