<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VIDOE-MAGIC18-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Sibling witches find love casts a powerful spell
 &HT;    By Steve Murray
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``Practical Magic'' (PG-13)
</P>
<P>
   Raised to adulthood by their witchy, spell-teaching aunts Jet
(Dianne Wiest) and Frances (Stockard Channing), flame-haired
Gillian (Nicole Kidman) moves away to live a poolside party life of
tequila and sexy-dangerous fellows, while quiet sis Sally (Sandra
Bullock) stays home. Sure she's a witch, but all Sally wants is
``normalcy.'' Which is hard to achieve, when every man who falls in
love with you is doomed, by an old family curse, to die.
</P>
<P>
   The movie may look like another lightweight romantic vehicle for
Bullock: a ``Hope Floats'' with brooms. Well, it is lightweight,
but the movie has a bite to it, throwing demon lovers and spiritual
possession into its mix. But director Griffin Dunne manages to keep
the blend coherent; his flick is a charming piffle that celebrates
the powers of love, and especially sisterhood.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: B +
</P>
<P>
   _ Steve Murray writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
