<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-17 12:23 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8461 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CPT-CHEAP-PCS-BOS &LR;      02-17 1567
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CPT-CHEAP-PCS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PRICE-BUSTING PCS BRING COMPUTERS TO THE MASSES 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)   By HIAWATHA BRAY   
 c.1999 The Boston Globe   
<TEXT>
<P>
   To judge by all the attention it has garnered, Apple Computer
Inc.'s sleek, colorful iMac might seem to be the most significant
high-tech hit of 1998.
</P>
<P>
   Not necessarily. Another computer, introduced late last year
with almost no fanfare, is selling almost as quickly as the iMac
and may wind up playing a bigger role in the history of computing.
</P>
<P>
   It's called an eMachine. It's everything the iMac isn't:
bland-looking, technically unsophisticated, and cheap. Very cheap.
Some models cost just $500, including monitor. That's half the
price of the least expensive iMac.
</P>
<P>
   And that has made all the difference. Solely on the strength of
Sunday newspaper circulars and word of mouth, eMachine has become
one of the nation's best-selling computer brands, and a harbinger
of an era when personal computers will be as cheap and commonplace
as television sets.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're seeing the beginning of what I'll call a structural
change in what PCs cost,'' said Stephen Dukker, chief executive of
eMachines Inc., the US-based, Korean-owned company that makes the
computer. ``There's a whole area of $800 to $1,500 machines that
are going to disappear.''
</P>
<P>
   A dramatic cut in the cost of a computer could finally transform
the PC from a luxury into just another home appliance, making it
affordable to nearly everyone. That was Microsoft Corp.'s goal when
it bought WebTV, a company that makes a $300 box that pumps the
Internet into a TV set. Oracle Corp. also took a swing with its
Network Computer for the home. Neither product is a full-fledged
personal computer, and neither has been embraced by consumers.
</P>
<P>
   But prices of computer parts such as processors, hard drives,
and memory chips have plunged in recent years, even as these
components become much more powerful. As a result, it is now
possible to make a true personal computer that is about as cheap as
a WebTV unit, but powerful enough to meet the needs of the average
user.
</P>
<P>
   That's eMachine's market, and by going after it, Dukker thinks
his company is helping to slice the computer industry into two
sharply defined segments: costly high-performance machines and
mass-market models.
</P>
<P>
   Mass-market PCs could also change the face of the Internet,
allowing users with lower incomes to join the mostly affluent
denizens of cyberspace.
</P>
<P>
   Industry giants such as IBM Corp., Compaq Computer Corp., and
Dell Computer Corp. have long competed on price. But all have
costly sales and distribution channels to support, so they don't
want prices to fall too far, too fast.
</P>
<P>
   Companies have offered PCs at similar prices as promotional
gimmicks. IBM had a $599 computer available in limited quantities
last Christmas. Other firms, such as PrecisionTec LLC of Costa
Mesa, Calif., offer ultracheap machines by mail order. But
eMachines' sole focus is the low-end market, and it has succeeded
in getting shelf space in many of the nation's leading electronics
retailers, including Circuit City and Best Buy. America Online, the
world's largest on-line computer network with 15 million members,
also features eMachines in its computer retailing forum.
</P>
<P>
   The company that makes eMachines was founded just five months
ago and expects to turn a profit this quarter. It hopes to sell as
many as 2 million computers this year and rake in $1 billion, which
would make it one of the fastest-growing companies in history.
</P>
<P>
   It all started with a long distance phone call. Dukker, a former
executive at retailer CompUSA, had moved to a rival firm, Computer
City. In June, when CompUSA announced it would purchase Computer
City for $275 million, Dukker's career prospects seemed dim.
Apparently the same thought occurred to Jung Koh, chief executive
of Korea Data Systems, a leading maker of computer monitors and an
old friend.
</P>
<P>
   Koh phoned Dukker and asked if he was interested in a possible
business venture. Why not? Dukker figured. ``I went off to Korea
and had some discussions.''
</P>
<P>
   Dukker served up an idea that had come to him a few months
earlier as the result of an experiment at Computer City. The
company ran a sale of ultracheap personal computers at $599 each,
for a limited time. Dukker wasn't surprised that the computers sold
quickly. But something else happened.
</P>
<P>
   ``The behavior of these buyers was very different,'' he
recalled. When Computer City sold a typical $2,000 computer, 10
percent to 12 percent of the customers brought them back. But the
return rate on the cheap machines was much lower, 4 percent to 5
percent.
</P>
<P>
   ``The principal reason for the lower return rate,'' Dukker said,
``was the customer could afford the purchase.'' Time and again,
customers who had spent two grand would return a machine when they
saw it down the street for $100 less. Some would exchange an
expensive machine the week after they bought it, because an even
faster one was now available.
</P>
<P>
   But the buyers of cheap machines tended to be satisfied with
what they had. They didn't expect state-of-the-art performance, and
they knew they had a good price. So they kept the computers.
</P>
<P>
   ``The whole behavior toward the machine became a whole lot more
like an appliance,'' said Dukker.
</P>
<P>
   That gave him an idea, one which Koh quickly embraced. Dukker
and Koh began discussions with TriGem, a Korean maker of computers
and computer parts, and drew up a business plan. Dukker believed
that if they could make the machines both cheap and reliable, the
low return rate would ensure a slim but acceptable profit margin.
</P>
<P>
   Incorporated in the United States, eMachines started business on
Sept. 1. By October, the company had begun making 150,000 computers
at a TriGem plant in Korea, with monitors supplied by KDS.
</P>
<P>
   Dukker worked his retail-industry contacts and persuaded the
Best Buy, Office Depot, Fry's, and MicroCenter chains to carry the
computers, but he was terrified. ``I was waking up in a sweat and
saying, `Oh, my God, I've got to sell 150,000 computers in the next
two months.' ''
</P>
<P>
   He needn't have worried. By year's end, consumers had purchased
180,000 of them. This quarter, eMachines aims to sell 300,000 more.
Market research firm Ziff Davis Infobeads of La Jolla, Calif.,
found that eMachine was the sixth-best-selling computer brand at US
retail stores in December.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're doing it with price,'' said Infobeads analyst Matt
Sargent. While ``eMachine's average price for the month of December
was just over $400 . . .the average price for the market was over
$1,000,'' Sargent said.
</P>
<P>
   Customers love the low price of the eMachines, but retailers
also love them because they sell so fast, Sargent said. PCs have
almost as short a shelf life as hamburger, and dealers lose money
unless they can move the merchandise quickly.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, cheap is not enough. The eMachines have to work, and
work they do. They're far from state-of-the-art machines, but the
various models contain reliable low-end processors from National
Semiconductor Corp. and Advanced Micro Devices Inc., as well as
Intel Corp.'s cut-rate Celeron chips. A built-in graphics chip
comes from ATI Technology Inc., one of the industry leaders, and
hard drives are supplied by Seagate Technology Inc. and Korea's
Samsung Electronics Co.
</P>
<P>
   The eMachines haven't been on the market long enough to assess
their long-term reliability. But some early customers say they're
delighted with their purchases.
</P>
<P>
   ``Would I buy another one? You bet!'' said Ruth Sams, a senior
programmer at Florida State University. Sams beefed up the memory
of her eMachine to 96 megabytes from the standard 32 megabytes and
put in a better graphics card, but figures she still saved money on
the deal.
</P>
<P>
   Her eMachine will soon be obsolete, but so what? ``For $499,
I'll just keep upgrading every year,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Mark Freeman, an IBM employee in Longmont, Colo., picked an
eMachine when he needed a second computer at home. ``No system that
IBM offers can touch the price,'' Freeman said.
</P>
<P>
   Yet these computer-savvy buyers aren't the only customers.
Dukker says that 56 percent of eMachine buyers have never before
owned a computer, and 35 percent of them have household incomes
below $30,000. In his view, the eMachine is tapping a whole new
market, made up of people who could never before afford a computer.
</P>
<P>
   Not everybody is convinced there's a future in supercheap
machines. Brian Connors, IBM's general manager of consumer systems,
said his company would continue to stress overall product value,
rather than just a low sticker price.
</P>
<P>
   He noted that eMachines isn't even a year old yet. ``What
happens if eMachines goes away a month from now, two months from
now, a year from now? With IBM, you know we're here.''
</P>
<P>
   IBM made the same argument in the 1980s when an unknown startup
called Compaq began offering knockoffs of IBM's then-dominant
desktop machines. Soon hundreds of other firms leaped into the
market for ``cloned'' PCs, savaging IBM's profit margins.
</P>
<P>
   Nobody thinks eMachines alone will have a vast impact on the
market. But if the company can sell $500 computers at a profit,
others will certainly follow. And that would permanently reshape
the computer industry, whether the big boys like it or not.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
NYT-02-11-99 1330EST &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
