<SLUG> BC-CPT-COMPUTERS-CYBERSPACE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`HOMICIDE' WEB SITE LINKS FANS TO CYBER PLOT 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PATTI HARTIGAN   c.1999 The Boston Globe  
<TEXT>
<P>
   It's late, round midnight. You're scrolling through your
favorite news group, alt.newageritual, and you notice a posting
inviting you to an on-line spiritual revival. You click over to the
Webcast and witness what appears to be a human sacrifice: Right
there on your computer screen, a woman is bound, gagged, and
stabbed by some virtual shaman. What to do? Call the police? E-mail
your service provider? Run anti-voodoo software?
</P>
<P>
   We've seen a baby born on the Internet, witnessed open-heart
surgery, and, gasp, seen Victoria's Secret models walk the runway
in their scanties. Now ``Homicide,'' the NBC police drama set in
the streets of Baltimore, is introducing a serial cyber killer.
It's something of a first in entertainment: Tonight's episode has
been preceded with an on-line counterpart on the Web site,
homicide.com. Earlier this week, the site laid out the plot as part
of its innovative ``Second Shift'' series, an on-line drama
featuring the officers who work at the homicide unit when the
television cops are off duty. On the Web, the ``murder'' appears to
be virtual performance art, as if shock artist Chris Burden
performed his mutilation antics on line.
</P>
<P>
   But in this television episode, it turns out that the murder is,
in fact, real. There is what one detective calls a ``temporal
being'' _ that is, a dead body. When one voyeuristic witness finds
out that it wasn't a hoax, he stammers, ``Oh man, oh man, that's so
. . .'' _ a long pause _ ``it's so cool.''
</P>
<P>
   Precisely.
</P>
<P>
   The ``Homicide'' folks are on their way to a skillful merger of
the two media. The prelude on the Web serves as a sly appetizer,
with a few neat tricks that draw you into the story and leave you
hungry for more. The payoff comes in the television episode, where
the images from the Web site become clues to solving the murder.
The criminal is a hacker in more ways than one, spoofing the
investigators with fake e-mail addresses and other cyber-jinks.
Some of the detectives are savvy to cyberspace (Bayliss has his own
home page, but Giardello can't even use a calculator). As the
suspense grows, they learn to navigate what one character refers to
as the realm of the ``Internuts.''
</P>
<P>
   The hard-boiled detectives become hard-wired, and that's a good
thing. It's also exactly the kind of merger that executives in both
the television and Internet industries have been scrambling to
achieve. In Net speak, they call it convergence. Plenty of TV shows
have complementary Web sites, but for the most part, they're
digital fan clubs where folks can buy T-shirts and read bios of the
stars. ``Homicide'' goes a step further. ``I'd like the viewer at
home to see that NBC shows do not just begin and end with the
television tube,'' says Tom Hjelm, director of interactive
programming and executive producer for NBC Digital Productions.
``In the early days, we were seen as a pretty alien bunch,'' he
adds, referring to the on-line group. ``But now I'd like to see an
interactive writer or producer sitting down at the table when the
shows are conceived.''
</P>
<P>
   There are, of course, limits to convergence. ``It's hard to do a
chase scene on line,'' says Ayelet Sela, ``Second Shift'' writer
and producer. ``But you can break down the fourth wall on line,
which you can't do on television.'' In past ``Second Shift''
stories, users could read the detectives' notes, search for clues,
play desktop sleuth.
</P>
<P>
   But ``Homicide'' has a loyal _ perhaps even obsessive _ fan
base, and viewers don't necessarily need streaming audio and video
as an incentive to watch the show. So what's the value for the
viewer? It makes the experience more immediate, giving you the
feeling that you have inside information before the show starts.
Interactive theater productions like ``Nicholas Nickleby'' were the
rage back in the '80s, precisely because they made audience members
feel as if they mattered. And early users of the Internet (back in
the days when you had to type in commands on a phosphorescent
screen) remember feeling as if they were members of a secret club
every time they logged on. It gives everyday Judys and Joes the
sense that they're a part of the program.
</P>
<P>
   But what about the networks? Why is convergence the Next Big
Thing? ``I would like to see us continue to build a business around
this,'' says Hjelm. ``Second Shift,'' after all, has a corporate
sponsor. Take a guess who it is. Think hard. Consider: You have to
use the Windows Media Player to access the video version on line,
and Macintosh users can only view a text version of the ``Second
Shift'' script.
</P>
<P>
   Did I hear you say Microsoft? You're a genius.
</P>
<P>
   Convergence, as the witness said, is cool _ unless you're one of
those stubborn folks who continue to polish their Apple at home. Oh
well. The television episode was designed to stand on its own, but
the on-line segment certainly enhances the plot and it wraps up on
line next week. Will they do it again?
</P>
<P>
   Probably, says ``Homicide'' coproducer Sara Charno, adding,
``When eight-track tapes came out, everyone thought that was the
wave of the future. No matter what the medium, whether it's a movie
or television or the Internet, it's still about telling a story.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC;  Ah, the wave of the future. Remember time capsules, those
quaint collections of memorabilia folks would bury in the ground to
be uncovered in the next millennium? Well, the folks at MIT's Sloan
School of Management have created a time capsule of their own,
which they say they are ``sealing in the cornerstone'' of the
school's updated Web site. (It's actually an icon on the site, and
the information is stored in the server.) The goal is to capture a
digital snapshot of the Internet as it exists today and have a few
laughs (and gasps) five years from now when the capsule is
reopened. The capsule covers a broad sociopolitical range, with Web
sites about e-commerce and merger mania, the impeachment
proceedings and anti-pornography campaigns, women's empowerment and
Victoria's Secret.
</P>
<P>
   MIT has also solicited predictions from folks like UN Secretary
General Kofi Annan and Governor Paul Cellucci (who makes obligatory
comments about education). For the rest of the year, browsers can
add their own prophecies to the capsule, which is at
mitsloan.mit.edu.
</P>
<P>
   Predictions by the likes of Martha Stewart and Bill Gates will
not be divulged until 2004, when the capsule is opened, and we're
holding our breath to learn what they have to say about wallpaper
and world dominance.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
NYT-02-11-99 1329EST &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
