<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GOODYKOONTZ-COLUMN-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CONE MY EARS? I MUST BE WAXY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BILL GOODYKOONTZ  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - John Rosegard lay curled on his side on a table, the
picture of relaxation, except for the foot-long flaming cone
sticking in his ear.
</P>
<P>
   Not to worry _ he wasn't the victim of some medieval torture. He
was having his ears cleaned and had paid $30 for the privilege.
</P>
<P>
   It's called ear coning, and the basic idea has been around for
centuries. It's fairly simple: The shape of the cone forms a vacuum
with the ear; the heat of the flame draws out earwax and other
debris. Some wax is good, but too much can cause all sorts of
problems.
</P>
<P>
   But no matter how sound the idea behind it, there is still
something daunting about sticking a flaming cone in your ear.
</P>
<P>
   Even though it was his first time, however, Rosegard wasn't
worried. He was lying on a table outside Phoenix Civic Plaza, where
the Phoenix Holistic Health Expo was held last weekend. Dieter
Gould, owner of King Cone International, was holding the cone,
fretting that the fire marshal wouldn't allow him to demonstrate
the cones inside, where he was selling them (business is growing
rapidly, he said). Open flame and all that.
</P>
<P>
   After about 10 minutes, half the cone had burned down, so Gould
pulled it out of Rosegard's ear, took a wooden skewer and scraped
out the inside. A fine, off-white powder dumped out, along with
what looked like small pieces of caramel. In a word, yuck. &QL; 
 &QL; 
What's in a color?
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``It all looks weird,'' Gould said of what comes out of people's
ears after they've been coned. ``I've seen many different colors.
I've seen olive drab, which indicates infection. I've seen
shoe-polish black, which may indicate nicotine in a heavy smoker.''
</P>
<P>
   Mind you, you can't tell everything about a person by what's in
his ears. Gould carefully kept claims sufficiently vague _ so don't
expect companies to substitute ear coning for urine tests to find
out if you've been using drugs. The point is to make you feel
better, not to reveal innermost secrets.
</P>
<P>
   After cleaning the cone, Gould lighted it again and stuck it
back into Rosegard's ear. After 10 more minutes, he repeated the
process in the other ear. He finished by dabbing a cotton swab in
olive oil and wiping Rosegard's ears with it.
</P>
<P>
   Gould, who lives in Redondo Beach, Calif., started his
ear-coning business six years ago. He's a nice guy but occasionally
a little hard to get a straight answer out of. He's one of those
people who can't talk about earwax without getting into its
harmonic relationship with the body's organs and the 4,000 pores in
the ear and the healing effect of this and that; somehow the liver
and kidneys were involved, but it was hard to follow.
</P>
<P>
   But he explained away the biggest worry people have about ear
coning _ other than, presumably, immolation _ with ease.
</P>
<P>
   ``If there's any dripping at all, it'll drip onto the candle,
not into the ear,'' he said. ``It's the design of the candle, the
way it's shaped. It's the way I'm holding it, too . . . at about
the 1 o'clock position.'' &QL; 
 &QL; 
Earwax exonerated
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   That's important to note _ Gould sells the cones for people to
use themselves.
</P>
<P>
   Afterward, Rosegard liked the results. So did I _ after watching
Rosegard, I paid my $30 and had Gould cone my ears. When he lighted
the cone and stuck it _ gently _ into my ear, it was like listening
to a seashell _ I could hear the ocean.
</P>
<P>
   That gave way, once the flame burned a bit, to a gentle white
noise. There was some warmth, but no painful burning.
</P>
<P>
   Happily, my earwax got a clean bill of health _ just the
remnants of an older infection, Gould said.
</P>
<P>
   Although to my untrained eye, what came out of my ears looked an
awful lot like what came out of Rosegard's, and he was apparently
loaded down with candida, older wax and open to a virus.
</P>
<P>
   That's the thing about many holistic remedies _ you can't tell
if they work. Yes, my ears were cleaner, but Gould could have told
me my wax showed I had been bitten by a tsetse fly and I couldn't
have disproved him. No matter the treatment, it's all harmony and
healing _ in this case, the whole ball of wax. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
Bill Goodykoontz can be reached at bill.goodykoontz(at)pni.com via
e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-17-99 1234EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
