<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CPT-COMPUTING-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)  
 The Snag in Lycos' MP3 Jukebox  
 By David Einstein   
 c. 1999 San Francisco Chronicle   
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; Question: &LR;  What's with the new MP3 search engine on Lycos? When
I click on a song to download it, I get the same message every
time: ``Internet Explorer could not open the site because the
server returned extended information.`' Please help. The MP3
revolution is passing me by!
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Answer: &LR;  Most likely, the server that hosts the songs you are
trying to get is crowded and not letting anyone on. ``Most MP3
servers reach their maximum number of users during peak hours of
the day,'' says my 17-year-old son, who's quickly turning into an
expert on the subject. ``You just have to keep hammering at them.''
A spokesman for Lycos acknowledged that in its first full day, the
new MP3 search engine generated more than 1 million hits.
</P>
<P>
   Another possible cause for the message you're getting is that
some sites use ``ratios,'' letting you download stuff only if you
first upload something. It's an easy way for a site to increase its
content. You can avoid this particular problem by using an audio
search engine such as MediaFind (formerly Chaos MP3), which lets
you block ratio sites from search responses. You'll find it at
search.mp3.de /index.html.
</P>
<P>
   Insomniac Compaq
</P>
<P>
   Q: My Compaq Presario home PC will not stay asleep. It wakes up
by itself during the night. This happens without any programs left
open, and it makes no difference how we put it into ``sleep'' mode.
What's going on?
</P>
<P>
   A: Most Presarios are programmed to wake up at midnight, or
whenever the phone rings, if the PC also is being used as a fax
machine. But you can change the default and eliminate the problem.
Here's how: Restart your PC, and when the Compaq logo appears,
immediately press the F10 key. That will take you into the Setup
program. Now go the Power section, where you can change the wake-up
settings.
</P>
<P>
   Pandora's Box
</P>
<P>
   Q: Recently, a gray box has been appearing in the middle of my
screen for no apparent reason. The top left corner contains
``Waol,'' and the text in the box says, ``This program has
performed an illegal operation and will be shut down. If the
problem persists, contact the program vendor.'' Any suggestions on
how I can get rid of this pesky problem?
</P>
<P>
   A: My guess is that the America Online program on your PC has
become corrupted _ ``Waol'' stands for Windows America Online. So
what you should do is delete AOL from the computer and install a
fresh copy. Of course, you should download the new copy from AOL
(keyword: Upgrade) before deleting the old one because once you
delete it, you won't be able to get online. And it would make you
feel like a fool.
</P>
<P>
   When Your Click Sticks
</P>
<P>
   Q: When I click on Microsoft Internet Explorer, I get a message
that it cannot connect to the server. Yet when I click on AOL,
which uses Internet Explorer, everything works fine. What is wrong?
</P>
<P>
   COL. 1 of COMPUTIN () &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A: AOL is an online service that connects you to the Internet.
Once you log on, you can use AOL's built-in Internet Explorer
browser (as well as another version of IE or Netscape Navigator) to
browse the Web. When you open the browser, it goes out and connects
with the server for the browser's home page. After that, every time
you go to a new site on the Web, the browser will seek out the
server for each site's address.
</P>
<P>
   If you're not actually online, however, the browser is basically
worthless. It only works if it can connect to a server. And the
message you're getting indicates that you haven't yet gone online.
So log onto AOL first, and then open the browser.
</P>
<P>
   Folder Foul Up
</P>
<P>
   Q: I use Windows 95 for my business. I prefer to view the
contents of my folders in list form rather than icons. Every time
Windows crashes, all my folders revert to showing files as large
icons. I've been using My Computer to change them back to list form
one folder at a time, using each folder's View menu. Is there a way
to set a global preference for viewing the content of all folders
and sub-folders as lists?
</P>
<P>
   A: I don't know of any global options for My Computer, but you
can make life easier on yourself by managing your files instead
with Windows Explorer. When you choose List from its View menu, all
the folders are displayed that way. FYI, the easiest way to start
Windows Explorer is by right-clicking the Windows Start button and
choosing Explore.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; TIP OF THE WEEK &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Readers often ask how to access previous Computing Q&AMP;A columns
online. Here's how: Go to The Chronicle's Web site at sfgate.com.
Scroll down and click Search under Resources at the left side of
the window. In the Article Search box, choose the first option to
search for Chronicle and Examiner articles. In the Search form that
appears, choose the year you want, enter David Einstein in the
byline box, and Q: in the keywords box.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Got a question about computing? E-mail it to computers(at
sign)sfgate.com
</P>
