<HEADER>
A8512 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CPT-WOLFF-INTERNET-CO     02-17 0953
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CPT-WOLFF-INTERNET-COX </SLUG>
  
 (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)  
Author tells tale of how to lose money in a hurry 
By Mark Clothier  
c. 1999 Cox News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Michael Wolff wrote one of the first ``how not to''
books about the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   ``Burn Rate: How I survived the Gold Rush Years on the
Internet,'' is about Wolff's experience as an unlikely Internet
entrepreneur.
</P>
<P>
   The former journalist turned screenwriter turned American
expatriate and would-be novelist turned media consultant staked an
early claim _ 1994 _ in the Internet gold rush. Wolff New Media
compiled, published and sold NetGuide, a book that tried to be the
TV Guide of the Internet. Burn Rate tells the story of how Wolff
turned a profitable publishing company into a money-sucking
Internet black hole.
</P>
<P>
   Wolff traded outside cash for control and grew his new media
company exponentially. In four months in 1996, his company shot
from 8 employees to 70. Wolff took a profitable business making 15
percent to 20 percent profit margins into a company that in one
year lost $7 million.
</P>
<P>
   In the end, Wolff was smacked: Unable to cover the bills, he
allowed his company to be taken over by some of its investors. The
book, finished in March 1998 and released in June, is Wolff's smack
back. Part diary, part gossip column, part cautionary tale, Wolff
describes Burn Rate as ``an incredibly sweet revenge.''
</P>
<P>
   Burn Rate has sold close to 100,000 copies. Wolff, 45, said he
is starting to think about a new book. In the meantime, he writes a
weekly, 2,000-word media column for New York magazine.
</P>
<P>
   Wolff will speak in Atlanta at a Wednesday night dinner
sponsored by the Association for Interactive Media.
</P>
<P>
   Q: How did you end up an Internet entrepreneur?
</P>
<P>
   A: ``I started consulting on the future of media for some
friends on Wall Street. Then I got involved with people wanting to
do some media deals. I got gradually more and more in this world of
deals and media and entrepreneurship, and I liked it. I liked being
around business people. I'd been around writers for a long time.
And you know, writers, are a lot of _ they're a group with a lot of
homogeneity, let's say. I got into the business world and said,
where'd these people come from? It was fun.''
</P>
<P>
   Q: How did that lead you to the Internet?
</P>
<P>
   A: ``I got more interested in desktop publishing technology. I
was always looking for ways to compete with larger media
organizations and that lead me to the Internet. Around 1990, I
started getting this inchoate sense that there was a relationship
between information and technology. That sounds ridiculous now, but
in 1990 not a lot of people I knew were thinking like that. The
Internet just got into my horizon, in subtle ways. A guy I knew
knew a guy who said there was lots of free information out there,
stuff you pay Lexis/Nexis for. I told an intern to find out about
it for me.
</P>
<P>
   Gradually it was just there. It was a presence. I remember
trying to explain this to people in the early 90s, and it was
impossible. You sounded like a crazy person at that point. You were
trying to describe the indescribable, and no one ever got it. I
thought then that there's got to be a book here. I came up with
NetGuide. I saw it as a TV Guide for the Net. Describing the
Internet as a new kind of TV, a new kind of media, which no one was
doing at that point. The book came out in Jan. 1994, within a week,
knew my life had changed. The response to the book was
overwhelming.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Is it too late for regional cities like Atlanta to get
involved in the technology industry in in a big, Silicon Valley
way?
</P>
<P>
   A: It's too late and too early still. I still don't know what's
going to work in this industry. Everybody assumes this certainty,
but it lasts for a limited period. Like electronic commerce. Yeah,
well, e-commerce doesn't work. All the people know is they can sell
products while losing money on them. No one has figured out how to
sell products that make money.
</P>
<P>
   Q: What advice do you have for people running start-ups?
</P>
<P>
   A: It's all a matter of your individual goals. If you want to
trade up into a company that you don't control, there's one way. In
my own career, I traded up and shouldn't have. I did not want to be
beholden and under the thumb of other people, even if it meant the
possibility of unlimited wealth.
</P>
<P>
   Q: What would you do differently?
</P>
<P>
   A: I shouldn't have expanded as fast. We grew twentyfold. We
went, in four months, from eight employees to 70. Revenue went up,
but losses did too. I took a profitable company making 15 percent
to 20 percent margins into a company that, in a year, lost $7
million.
</P>
<P>
   Q: What reaction did you get from the subjects of your book?
</P>
<P>
   A: These guys were so shocked by the book. Never in their
wildest imaginations did they think that this would happen, that
someone would hold them up to the kind of ridicule I held them up
to. It was and is an incredibly sweet revenge. Of all the kinds of
things business people think, they don't think there are people who
will write about them in a completely honest, open and unexpurgated
way. It's quite possibly never happened before in the annals of
business.
</P>
<P>
   Q: What was the biggest surprise?
</P>
<P>
   A: How much you could make and how much you could lose. And that
I would have been able to turn myself into a business guy. Really,
for me, to be a business guy, to have been able to step forward and
create the industry, meant that no one knew anything.
</P>
<P>
   Mark Clothier writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
