<SLUG> BC-CPT-TICKETMASTER-MICROSOFT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TICKETMASTER AND MICROSOFT SETTLE SUIT ON INTERNET LINKING 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)   By BOB TEDESCHI   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Ticketmaster, a unit of Barry Diller's USA Networks Inc., has
settled its two-year-old lawsuit against Microsoft.
</P>
<P>
   Although the parties agreed not to disclose the terms of the
settlement, executives said the agreement did resolve the suit's
central issue _ whether Microsoft's Sidewalk online city guides
could bypass many of Ticketmaster's advertising-laden Web pages and
link Sidewalk users directly to the ticket-purchase portions of
Ticketmaster's site.
</P>
<P>
   Charles Conn, chief executive of Ticketmaster's Ticketmaster
Online-Citysearch business, said that Microsoft had agreed to no
longer link Sidewalk to pages deep within the Ticketmaster site,
where visitors might not even realize they were using
Ticketmaster's services.
</P>
<P>
   As a result of the settlement, the Sidewalk guides will now
point visitors who want to purchase tickets directly to the
Ticketmaster home page _ where Ticketmaster will have ample
opportunity to bathe them in advertising.
</P>
<P>
   The two sides came to terms on Jan. 22, but had not announced
the settlement. Conn disclosed the deal in an interview late last
week.
</P>
<P>
   The case had been widely watched for its potential to establish
a legal precedent on the intellectual property rights of Internet
companies. But with an out-of-court settlement, the online industry
remains without legal guidelines on the practice of so-called deep
linking, of which Microsoft was by no means the only practitioner.
</P>
<P>
   Ticketmaster filed suit in April 1997 in a federal court in
California, arguing that Microsoft had ``pilfered'' its content and
therefore diluted its value. At the time, Ticketmaster had recently
signed a deal with Citysearch, which, like Microsoft's Sidewalk
guides, provides information about local news, merchants and
entertainment in various cities. In that deal Citysearch was
essentially paying Ticketmaster for the right to do what Microsoft
was doing free.
</P>
<P>
   Ticketmaster, which was acquired by Diller's company in 1997,
merged its online division with Citysearch last September to create
Ticketmaster Online-Citysearch.
</P>
<P>
   In its legal defense, Microsoft had argued that Ticketmaster's
stance breached an unwritten Internet code in which any Web site
operator has the right to link to anyone else's site. Microsoft
also based its defense on what it said was its First Amendment
right to publish public information.
</P>
<P>
   But with the settlement, those in the industry looking for the
federal court's guidance were disappointed.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm sure it's in the best interest of the parties, but for the
purpose of providing meaningful guidance to the Internet community,
this is the worst news I've heard all day,'' Jeffrey Kuester, an
Internet law specialist and a partner in the Atlanta law firm
Thomas, Kayden, Horstemeyer &AMP; Risley, said when told of the
settlement.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were hoping to hear some good, broad, general language from
the court,'' Kuester said. ``Now, do we know if deep linking is
bad? Is linking to a main home page OK? Is it just not OK to link?
We don't know.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
NYT-02-14-99 1808EST &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-17-99 1245EST &QL; 
