</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CPT-MICROSOFT-LANGUAGE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MICROSOFT DENIES RUMORS THAT IT IS CRAFTING A LANGUAGE LIKE JAVA
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)  By LAWRENCE M. FISHER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Microsoft Corp. is playing down a report in Monday's PC
Week, a trade magazine, that the software giant has been briefing
software developers on a new programming language that would be
similar to Sun Microsystems Inc.'s Java software, but free of
technological or licensing obligations to Sun.
</P>
<P>
   Sun recently won a court order blocking Microsoft from shipping
products containing Microsoft's own version of Java, which Sun
claims has been altered to work only with Microsoft Windows, thus
thwarting the so-called cross-platform capability designed into the
language. Cross platform means that a developer can write one
version of a program in Java, which can then run on Windows,
Macintosh, Unix and other software operating systems. Microsoft is
appealing the ruling.
</P>
<P>
   It is not clear why software developers, who have embraced Java
enthusiastically, would be interested in a new programming
language. But analysts predicted that Microsoft would work hard to
win the role of intellectual leadership that a dominant programming
language confers within the developer community. And it is Java and
its steaming coffee cup logo _ not Windows _ that are synonymous
with the World Wide Web.
</P>
<P>
   The PC Week article quoted unnamed software developers who said
they had been briefed on a Java language alternative code-named
``Cool.''
</P>
<P>
   However, none of the developers offered any details about the
nature of such a program, not even whether or not it would be
cross-platform. The article, which was heavily promoted by PC
Week's public relations staff late last week, offered no clue as to
what the product really is, who would use it or when it would ship.
</P>
<P>
   ``It seems Microsoft at this point is not willing to give more
than a broad outline,'' said Eric Lundquist, PC Week's editor in
chief. ``It may be it is something they're working on in their labs
and they're trying to get feedback.''
</P>
<P>
   Michael Risse, Microsoft's product manager for application
development tools, said Cool was simply one of a number of new
ideas under discussion.
</P>
<P>
   ``Have we discussed something like this? Yes. Are we developing
anything? No, we are not,'' he said in a telephone interview.
</P>
<P>
   Of 800 employees in the development tools unit, ``not one _
zero, nada _ is working on or developing any new language,'' he
said. ``That's the case today and for the foreseeable future.''
</P>
<P>
   Lisa Poulson, a spokeswoman for Sun, said that rumors had been
circulating for two years that Microsoft was at work on a so-called
universal virtual machine that would conceivably enable its
operating systems or applications to run Java programs without
employing any Java technology themselves. Such a piece of code
would fall far short of a new language, but Microsoft already has
two programming languages, C++ and Visual Basic.
</P>
<P>
   ``Separately, they did ask the judge if they could build
independently developed works, and they were specific in their
court papers about a compiler,'' Ms. Poulson said. A compiler is a
programming tool that converts high-level languages, like C++ or
Java, into the machine code of ones and zeros that computers
understand.
</P>
<P>
   Judge Ronald Whyte, of United States District Court in San Jose,
Calif., has not yet ruled on Microsoft's request. But at any rate,
Risse said the concept called Cool is unconnected to the lawsuit.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
NYT-02-14-99 1613EST &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-17-99 1245EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
