</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MICH-GOP-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MICHIGAN SENATOR REFLECTS GOP DESIRE TO MOVE ON 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ANNE E. KORNBLUT  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DETROIT _ He blended into the background of impeachment, most
notable for his alphabetical role of being the first to vote. But
the minute the trial was over, Senator Spencer Abraham seemed
poised to become a star of the next Republican cause.
</P>
<P>
   Because by Saturday, Abraham was talking issues _ specifically,
tax cuts _ and uttering the now-ubiquitous phrase ``time to move
on.'' And as he waited to board a plane back to Detroit he acted as
though business had already returned to normal _ co-opting, it
seemed, the political strategy of President Clinton himself.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our goal, I think, really, is just to get some debate going in
Michigan about tax issues,'' said Abraham, 46, as he sat in a
terminal at Reagan National Airport. ``We've actually got a budget
surplus, not just because of Social Security but also because of
the so-called operating budget as well. So I think it's a real fair
time to talk about how we handle that.''
</P>
<P>
   Republican leaders, after watching their members suffer in the
polls and in last November's elections as a result of impeachment,
have made no secret of their determination to move on to other
things. During a weekend retreat in Williamsburg, Va., earlier this
month, Republican House members were admonished for lacking a
strategy on anything but impeachment. On Saturday, at a conference
in Miami, New Jersey Governor Christine Todd Whitman told other
Republicans that the public views the party as ``mean-spirited,
vindictive, not attending to the American public.''
</P>
<P>
   And if there is a party identity crisis, Republicans seem to
fear its effects will be felt in Michigan, particularly by Abraham,
who as a one-term Republican has no guarantee of a solid future in
the Senate. Clinton is quite popular, winning Michigan with 52
percent of the vote in 1996. Impeachment, on the other hand, is not
popular: 64 percent were opposed to the process, according to a
poll taken last November.
</P>
<P>
   Abraham, the first Republican senator elected in Michigan in two
decades, already faces some formidable Democratic opponents in his
2000 race.
</P>
<P>
   Geoffrey Feiger, best known as the lawyer for Jack Kevorkian,
the assisted suicide doctor, and for his own failed gubernatorial
bid, has said he will ``of course'' turn impeachment into a
campaign issue against Abraham. Any raising of impeachment might
help other potential candidates, including Detroit Mayor Dennis
Archer and former governor Jim Blanchard, simply because they are
Democrats.
</P>
<P>
   And yet, according to a January poll taken in Lansing,
impeachment would play a marginal role in an election at best, and
42 percent of those polled said they would not consider impeachment
a deciding factor if Abraham voted to convict and remove Clinton,
as he did last Friday on both articles of impeachment.
</P>
<P>
   Even in working-class areas around Detroit, where most voters
are Democrats, several people said impeachment would be irrelevant
in the next race. Tom McGee, 60, a retired phone splicer and former
union president, said he ``wouldn't have voted for Abraham no
matter what he did with impeachment.''
</P>
<P>
   Another Democrat, Candida Davis, 44, a nurse, said she ``would
have to focus on what his character is, outside of what he did on
impeachment.''
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, Jen VanDusen, 28, a marketing services
specialist at the Ford Motor Co., said she would never consider
voting against Abraham in favor of a Democrat, and certainly ``not
specifically'' because of impeachment.
</P>
<P>
   ``It wouldn't affect the way I vote,'' said VanDusen, a
Republican who voted for Abraham in the last election. ``Although I
did like that he voted guilty. I would support him.''
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, there are signs Republican leaders are concerned
about the 2000 elections, including Abraham's. Chief among them:
Majority leader Trent Lott flew to Michigan for a town meeting, the
first of several dozen Republican gatherings planned in the coming
weeks. Michigan Governor John Engler, who is popular and a close
friend of Abraham's, is also scheduled to attend.
</P>
<P>
   Abraham did not seek out the town meeting: He has other genuine
concerns now that impeachment is over, including a set of
5-year-old twins and a 2-year-old. He also has a legitimate claim
to discussing taxes instead of the trial. Although he attended
Harvard Law School, where he founded the conservative Federalist
Society, Abraham is known in the Senate for his work on the Budget
Committee. These days, that role is the one he would prefer to
emphasize.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I ran for Senate, I made a lot of pledges about getting
the budget balanced, and was met with the cynicism one might
expect,'' he said. ``But I got a seat on the Budget Committee. The
budget's balanced.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Clearly,'' he added, ``the impeachment trial is over, so we
have to move on. I haven't met anyone on either side of the aisle
who says, `Let's rehash impeachment.' So the question is: Do we
move ahead legislatively or not?''
</P>
<P>
   Abraham's legislative battles may be as fierce as impeachment.
He is given credit for suggesting a 15 percent across-the-board tax
cut to Bob Dole, who used it in his unsuccessful 1996 presidential
bid. Now that Republicans are promoting a similar across-the-board
cut, there appears to be plenty of room for political attacks on
Republicans, including Abraham, over issues alone. Lott also backs
the plan, which is seen by Democrats as favoring the rich.
</P>
<P>
   Guests on the Sunday talk shows made that clear. White House
Chief of Staff John Podesta, appearing on ABC's ``This Week with
Sam Donaldson and Cokie Roberts,'' said Clinton planned to address
the issue of tax cuts with congressional leaders when they return
from a one-week recess.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think there will be plenty of things to fight about,''
Podesta said.
</P>
<P>
   Abraham seemed eager to get to those battles, almost denying the
possibility that constituents would ask him about impeachment
today. If the question does arise, he said he would be ``obviously
happy to talk about the vote, if that comes up.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Really, I think this is more of a tax focus,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
