u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-IMMIGRATE-BOS &LR;      02-17 1158
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-IMMIGRATE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WORRY ON KOSOVO REFUGEES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KEVIN CULLEN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   PARIS _ Before he began these latest peace talks, President
Jacques Chirac told the warring factions in Kosovo that their
barbarity against each other was anti-European.
</P>
<P>
   Chirac told the ethnic Albanians and Serbs that war had taught
the rest of Europe that compromise with one's historical enemies
was not only more courageous than waging war, but was also more
beneficial to Europeans.
</P>
<P>
   But another reason why the European governments are determined
to resolve the conflict in Kosovo was to be found outside the
wrought iron gates of the chateau at Rambouillet, where the talks
are being held.
</P>
<P>
   Hundreds of ethnic Albanians, many of them wrapped in the
blood-red flag of the separatist Kosovo Liberation Army, milled
around the streets, shouting slogans in support of the guerrillas,
unnerving locals in village cafes. Some of the protesters said they
were living in France, while others, asked where they lived,
shouted out several other European countries.
</P>
<P>
   The fighting in Kosovo has forced or encouraged hundreds of
thousands of ethnic Albanians to flee Kosovo in the last year,
either for sanctuary or a better way of life. Every European
country has seen a surge in the number of Kosovars seeking asylum,
especially Germany and Switzerland, where established Albanian
communities have swelled with refugees from the rebellious
province.
</P>
<P>
   According to the UN High Commissioner for Refugees, more than
300,000 people have been displaced in Kosovo in the year that has
passed since Serbian authorities crushed an uprising by the Kosovo
Liberation Army. About 2,000 civilians have been killed in the
conflict, most of them ethnic Albanians, and mostly at the hands of
Serbian authorities.
</P>
<P>
   About two-thirds of those displaced, about 210,000, are still in
Kosovo, living with family or friends. Another 45,000 have
resettled in other parts of Serbia and Montenegro, the two
republics that make up what is left of Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
   About 100,000 are scattered throughout Europe, more than half of
them in Germany, where about 35,250 have applied for asylum, and in
Switzerland, where 21,520 are seeking shelter.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the applications for asylum are in countries that have
long been havens for political refugees, such as Germany,
Switzerland, and Britain, which also have established Albanian
communities with an informal support system. But the conflict in
Kosovo has also badly stretched the resources of countries not used
to large influxes of refugees.
</P>
<P>
   The number of asylum applications in Hungary, for example, went
from 1,100 in 1997 to 7,400 last year, nearly half of that total
coming from Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   In an attempt to accommodate the surge of asylum seekers from
Kosovo, officials in the Netherlands have been forced to limit the
number of countries from which they will consider applications.
Last year, the number of asylum seekers there rose from 34,000 to
48,000, with refugees from Kosovo accounting for almost a third of
the increase.
</P>
<P>
   The Dutch were embarrassed last year when they were forced to
house hundreds of asylum seekers in tents because they ran out of
indoor accommodations. But they and other European governments fear
they will be forced to implement similar stopgap measures unless a
settlement is reached.
</P>
<P>
   Because they are fleeing persecution at the hands of Serbian
authorities, widely viewed as the aggressors in the conflict,
Kosovo Albanians are presumed to be entitled to asylum in most
European countrie, even though the Kosovo Liberation Army has
promoted conflict with the Serb authorities.
</P>
<P>
   Maki Shinohara, a spokeswoman for the UN High Commissioner for
Refugees in Geneva, said refugees from Kosovo ``are being
tolerated'' throughout Europe.
</P>
<P>
   ``We appealed to governments in Western Europe to deal with
asylum requests from Kosovo individually, and that even if they are
rejected not to send them back,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Shinohara said those deported to Serbia would face persecution.
Kosovo Albanians say they would face death.
</P>
<P>
   Shinohara said there is no guarantee that the fate of Kosovo
refugees will be part of any agreement, should one emerge from
Rambouillet. Although the UN is not represented at the
negotiations, Shinohara's office gave its position after it was
provided an advance copy of the framework document that US envoy
Christopher Hill drafted for the negotiations.
</P>
<P>
   ``The biggest issue for us is amnesty,'' she said. ``In
principle, most refugees could go home if there was a settlement.
But many of them fear persecution when they return.''
</P>
<P>
   In Bosnia, more than three years after the Dayton agreement
ended the war there, getting refugees to return to areas that
became ethnically homogenous remains one of the biggest challenges.
Kosovo, however, could be easier because its population of 2
million is 90 percent ethnically Albanian.
</P>
<P>
   But, diplomats and humanitarian groups agree, safeguards for
refugees must be part of a final deal if there is a realistic
chance of luring back many of the 100,000 refugees who have left
the Balkans for continental Europe.
</P>
<P>
   While the armed conflict has accelerated the flight of refugees
from Kosovo, there has been a steady exodus from there since 1989,
when Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic ended Kosovo's autonomy.
Thousands of ethnic Albanians were thrown out of work, others
thrown into prison as suspected subversives. Many decided to seek a
better life abroad.
</P>
<P>
   Britain is an example of the larger picture. Only 10 years ago,
government figures show there were only about 30 Albanians living
in London. Today, there are as many as 30,000.
</P>
<P>
   At night, Albanians crowd into the Lisi restaurant in Maida
Vale, northwest London, to catch the news from Tirana beamed in via
a satellite dish.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to know what's going on back home,'' said Ilir, 23, a
refugee who said he was from near Pristina, the Kosovo capital, but
refused to give more information, saying he feared Serbian
authorities, not to mention the British, who are still
investigating his asylum application.
</P>
<P>
   Albania, which borders on the Serbian province of Kosovo, is the
poorest country in Europe. A growing number of native Albanians
have begun to falsely claim they are from Kosovo in an attempt to
win asylum, say officials at the British government's Home Office.
</P>
<P>
   Shinohara said the Albanian dialect spoken by Kosovars is
different from that in Albania. ``A language test would identify
the fakers pretty quickly,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Ilir, who spoke authoritatively about Pristina, naming cafes and
characters there, said he found it incomprehensible that people
would falsely claim to be from Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you are from Kosovo,'' he said, his head down, ``that means
someone in your family or your friends have been killed.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
