<SLUG> BC-JACKSON-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GUN MAKERS TAKE A HIT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DERRICK JACKSON  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   It was not a blast through its heart, but anytime a wounded
handgun industry hops on one leg, it makes my day.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, a federal jury in New York City found that 15 of 25
gun makers had marketing and distribution practices that fueled
illegal trade from states with weak gun laws to states that are
much more strict. The jury further found that 9 of those 15 were
liable in at least one street shooting.
</P>
<P>
   One could easily be confused by the reaction to the ruling. The
gun industry acted as if it had won. The lawsuit had been brought
forward by the families of victims of seven shootings. The jury
found that gun makers were liable in three of the shootings and
awarded money in only one, a sum that will probably end up being
about $500,000.
</P>
<P>
   With damages awarded in only one of the seven shootings, gun
lawyers immediately said the verdict was so weak, the judge should
throw it out. ``There's no rhyme or reason to this jury's
verdict,'' said gun lawyer John Renzulli. ``It makes no sense.''
</P>
<P>
   The plaintiffs were almost ecstatic. It was the first time gun
makers were ever found the least bit liable for putting a product
onto the streets that could easily end up in the hands of a killer.
``It was never about the money,'' said one of the plaintiffs, Diane
Zaretsky, who lost her husband to gunfire five years ago. ``It was
about shared responsibility.''
</P>
<P>
   The fact that a jury finally forced the gun makers to share
responsibility for the crippling and fatal results of their
products is one of the most encouraging breakthroughs in the
gun-control debate to date. Until now, gun makers have been as
invulnerable as Big Tobacco from lawsuits, hiding behind its
antiquated interpretation of the right to bear arms.
</P>
<P>
   But the science that links cigarettes with cancer, the
statistics that connect guns to blood on the streets, and the
common sense that marketing them as instruments of glamour and
power makes them all the more alluring has begun to win juries
over.
</P>
<P>
   On the same front page last Friday in which The New York Times
reported the gun verdict, there was also a feature about the
stunning $51.5 million verdict against Philip Morris in a lawsuit
brought by a woman who developed lung cancer.
</P>
<P>
   ``And it is not just happening in the juror room, but in the
general way people think about the industry,'' said Stanford
University law professor Robert Rabin.
</P>
<P>
   Rabin meant that about cigarettes, but the same could be applied
to guns. A Harris poll last year found that 69 percent of all
Americans and even 57 percent of gun owners want tighter laws on
gun control. Several cities, such as Chicago, New Orleans, Miami
and Bridgeport, Conn., have filed suits against gun makers. Cities
such as Boston, San Francisco, and Philadelphia are on the verge of
filing suits, charging gun makers with negligence in either
marketing or manufacture. The cities want to recoup medical and
police costs costs due to gun violence.
</P>
<P>
   The defiant Make My Day gun lobby, a lobby that once could stop
serious gun control with political contributions and sheer voting
strength, has been forced to scramble. Last week, the lobby
succeeded in getting Georgia to enact a law preventing its cities
from suing gun makers. Atlanta had filed such a suit.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the next year, I think we can probably get 25 or 30 more
states to do the same thing,'' said James Baker, director of the
National Rifle Association's Institute for Legislative Action.
</P>
<P>
   But Baker admitted that Georgia, where the NRA claims 93,000
members, is one of its stronger states. The prospects for getting
much more urbanized states to do the same thing are much more
uncertain unless governors like Paul Cellucci of Massachusetts and
John Rowland of Connecticut cave in to the sure-to-come ploy of
lost jobs at Smith and Wesson and Colt (what are lost jobs compared
to lost lives?).
</P>
<P>
   Just as uncertain is how gun makers will be able to handle
either sustained multiple litigations, let alone substantial jury
awards.
</P>
<P>
   The American gun industry is nowhere as solvent as Big Tobacco.
Despite their annual carnage (35,000 homicides, suicides and
accidents involve a gun), yearly US gun sales are between $2
billion and $3 billion, which pales next to the $72 billion by
Philip Morris and RJR Nabisco.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike the two cooperative cigarette makers, gun makers are
historically preoccupied with outdueling each other's firepower.
Robert Ricker, a top aide of the American Shooting Sports Council,
frets that such an uncoordinated industry may not have the
``horsepower to deal with national litigation.''
</P>
<P>
   Never before have handgun makers hopped this hard. Never before
do they seem so afraid of being knocked off their feet. A few more
wounds like this, and they just might be convinced not to be so
eager to contribute to the nation's carnage.
</P>
<P>
   It is a good day when the gun industry is forced to consider
that the person saying ``Make My Day'' is not Charles Bronson, but
a woman like Diane Zaretsky, who will take the killing no more.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Derrick Z. Jackson is a Globe columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
