<SLUG> BC-HKN-BRUINS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ROBITAILLE GETS HIS SHOT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JIM GREENIDGE  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   There's never been any doubt about Randy Robitaille's offense.
The center scores in bunches, and this season for Providence, he is
leading the American Hockey League with 72 points (21 goals, 51
assists).
</P>
<P>
   In the last 15 games, Robitaille had 28 points (8 goals), and he
was the AHL's Player of the Week with 10 points in four games last
week.
</P>
<P>
   Hoping he can bring some of that offense with him from
Providence, the struggling Bruins have called up Robitaille (and
forward Landon Wilson) as they prepare to play the Senators in
Ottawa Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is where I want to be and I'm happy to get the
opportunity, and hopefully I can make the best of it,'' said
Robitaille, who was up for four games with Boston last season. ``I
can't be nervous playing my game. I want to make the best of it.''
</P>
<P>
   Robitaille is a native of Ottawa and will have plenty of family
members and friends at the Corel Centre in Ottawa.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll try to make as few mistakes as possible,'' he said, ``but
if I do make a mistake, I won't get down on myself. Hopefully, I'll
have the confidence to go back out there.''
</P>
<P>
   The Bruins could use a spark. They are in ninth place in the
Eastern Conference _ 1 point from eighth, the final playoff spot _
with 28 games remaining. Ottawa is first in the Northeast Division,
second in the Eastern Conference.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ottawa is a great team, but we've got guys here who can get
the job done,'' said Robitaille, who scored a team-record five
goals for the Baby B's in a 14-2 rout of Syracuse Nov. 25. ``I'm
just trying to carry over what's going on down in Providence, by
coming here with a good attitude.
</P>
<P>
   Last season, Robitaille missed the final 29 games of the AHL
season after breaking his leg. After a so-so training camp, he
seems to have gotten better with experience this year.
</P>
<P>
   ``They were waiting for my game to come along and we're up at
the right time, my game is feeling good,'' he said. ``I'm getting
stronger and I've worked on my defensive game.''
</P>
<P>
   Robitaille, who will skate on a line between Cameron Mann and
Ken Baumgartner, doesn't think there will be a great deal of
pressure on him.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think the older guys are looking to the younger guys
to lead this team, they're just expecting us to chip in and work
hard for them,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday will be his sixth NHL game; his first was against the
New York Islanders in 1996-97, when, on his first shift, he was
belted behind the net by Ken Belanger. Robitaille separated his
shoulder and missed the rest of the season.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm glad he's on my team now,'' Robitaille said. ``It's just
the way it happened, on my first shift. I'm sure we'll joke about
it later.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Wilson's status may be in doubt. He did not practice Tuesday and
was being examined for an ailment that may be appendicitis . . .
Defenseman Kyle McLaren is ready to get back to work after missing
14 games with a separated left shoulder. ``There's been no problem
the last week and a half,'' said McLaren. ``I've just been
strengthening it. Thursday it should be 100 percent. If I go out
and if I don't hit, I'm not going to be successful, worrying about
my shoulder.'' . . . P.J. Axelsson's right thumb is sprained, not
broken. He'll play against Ottawa. ``It hurts a bit but it's
nothing more than that,'' he said. Sergei Samsonov, who has a thigh
contusion, also will play. ``It was tight at practice, but I
started slowly to see how it went,'' Samsonov said. ``It felt tight
and sore but it's fine.'' . . . Steve Heinze, who has a groin
injury, left practice early. He has missed two games and hopes to
get back next weekend.
</P>
</TEXT>
