<SLUG> BC-RELIGION-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GROUPS UNITE FOR STRONGER VOICE IN WELFARE DEBATE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DIEGO RIBADENEIRA  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Even as the drama of President Clinton's impeachment limped to a
close, a different and potentially significant moral tale was
unfolding in another corner of the nation's capital.
</P>
<P>
   More than 800 people from 40 states gathered in Washington last
week to grapple with the question of what religious congregations,
in the uncharted era of welfare reform, can do to help the poor
lift themselves out of poverty.
</P>
<P>
   The National Summit on the Churches and Welfare Reform, the
first meeting of its kind, attracted more than 500 faith-based
organizations that provide dozens of services, from child care to
job training to health care.
</P>
<P>
   As the country embarks on a historic and controversial effort to
curb guaranteed government aid to needy families, churches,
synagogues, and mosques are likely to play a huge role in helping
the poor enter the working world.
</P>
<P>
   But summit organizers say that while congregations certainly are
capable and willing, they also are obliged to hold governments
accountable so they will not completely abandon the poor.
</P>
<P>
   ``Before politicians start patting themselves on the back for
welfare reform, they need to understand exactly what is
happening,'' said Jim Wallis, an organizer of the summit and a
Washington-based Christian activist who is spending a year as a
fellow at the Center for the Study of Values in Public Life at
Harvard Divinity School.
</P>
<P>
   ``Politicians are asking the wrong question,'' said Wallis,
editor of Sojourners Magazine and founder of Call to Renewal, a
national faith-based organization working to overcome poverty.
``The question isn't how many people are getting off welfare. The
question is how many people are getting jobs. And right now, the
data show that half the people are getting jobs and the other half
aren't.''
</P>
<P>
   Many who are able to get jobs are earning wages too low to
significantly improve their economic situation, Wallis argued.
</P>
<P>
   At a forum last week on churches and welfare reform at Harvard
Divinity School, Mary Jo Bane, a professor of public policy and
management at Harvard's Kennedy School of Government, said many
people being pushed off welfare are landing minimum-wage jobs that
make it inevitable that they will remain poor.
</P>
<P>
   ``The welfare poor have become the working poor,'' said Bane,
who quit her job as an assistant secretary for health and human
services in the Clinton administration in protest after the
president signed the federal welfare reform law in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   A main goal of the church summit, Wallis said, was to catalyze
an organized movement of religious congregations that could have an
influential voice in public policy involving the plight of poor
people.
</P>
<P>
   The idea would be to mimic the success the religious right has
enjoyed in having its voice heard in Washington and in state
capitals on moral issues such as abortion and homosexuality.
</P>
<P>
   Building on what Wallis said was a successful summit, key
organizers will meet next month to decide what steps to take to
build a national association of congregations working on poverty
issues.
</P>
<P>
   Already, Wallis said, it is clear that welfare reform will fail
unless government at all levels deals better with three key
weaknesses: a lack of affordable health and child care, and jobs
that pay too little to support families.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have a real potential for advocacy,'' said Wallis, who is
completing a book on the connection between spirituality and social
action. ``There are no political action committees for poor people;
no highly paid lobbyist on Capitol Hill. Well, that's what churches
are supposed to do.
</P>
<P>
   ``But a lot of churches have been doing their own things
individually and staying away from politics,'' he said. ``There's a
major untapped force here.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite the great changes in welfare laws, Wallis said he is
encouraged by the response of religious groups. A growing number no
longer are simply interested in operating traditional charities
such as soup kitchens, clothing closets, and homeless shelters.
They want to provide permanent solutions to poverty.
</P>
<P>
   ``Running food pantries and the like in the end can be very
demoralizing for churches and clients, because nothing ever seems
to change,'' Wallis said. ``Working on what it takes to move out of
poverty can be more energizing. We want to end poverty, not service
it.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Diego Ribadeneira receives comments and ideas at Box 2378, Boston,
MA 02107-2378, or via e-mail at religion(at)globe.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
