<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FASHION-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JUST SHOWING IS WINNING FOR NEW DESIGNERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SUZANNE C. RYAN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ For his fall fashion show here on Sunday, designer
Mark Montano paid his 14 models barter-style: one outfit each for
several trips down the runway. He couldn't afford a makeup artist
or a DJ, so friends volunteered. And the champagne party afterward?
It's on hold _ indefinitely.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you have no money as a young designer, this is exactly
what it takes,'' says Montano, 32.
</P>
<P>
   This is fashion week. For the industry, no period is more
important. It's when virtually every major American designer
unveils his or her all-important fall collection. Fashion trends
are launched here, and industry heavyweights such as Ralph Lauren
and Calvin Klein get lots of press coverage and retail orders _
which boost the reputation of American designers worldwide.
</P>
<P>
   But fashion week isn't just about household names. Up-and-coming
designers such as Montano play a big role as well. For one thing,
they bring fresh perspectives and ideas, something the industry
can't survive without. Also, they're often more willing to take
chances with their clothes than old hands are. And such risks can
lead to breakthroughs in design. Last, their presence creates an
atmosphere of competition, which spurs designers to do better work.
</P>
<P>
   To be sure, new designers on the scene face an uphill battle, no
matter how enthusiastic and enterprising they may be. With more
than 80 shows running this week, attracting harried retailers and
journalists can be tough. New York-based Montano says his show
Sunday _ his first on the official fashion-week calendar _ was
``totally a dream come true. . . . Ever since I was little, I've
been sewing and looking at fashion magazines. . . . It's wild'' to
be here.
</P>
<P>
   Still, even with the unveiling of his 36-piece collection
scheduled a strategic two hours before renowned Donna Karan's show,
Montano obviously couldn't come close to matching the scale. His
show (located in the smallest venue available) drew a respectable
340 people. But Karan's show, for her 87-piece DKNY line, attracted
almost 800 to a larger nearby facility, including celebrities such
as actress Jennifer Esposito of ``Spin City,'' singer Debra Cox,
and actor Cameron Mathison. Guests for Karan's show had to line up
an hour before start time. Among them, providing all-important
publicity, was CNN reporter Elsa Klench (who was let in early).
</P>
<P>
   Booking experienced models in a competitive environment like
this can be almost impossible when you can't pay them the going
rate of $5,000 to $10,000 per show. No problem for Karan, of
course. DKNY _ celebrating its 10th anniversary _ hired some of the
hottest, including Esther Canadas and Kiara Kabukuru. What about
Montano? Rather than name names, let's just say that one of his
volunteer models tripped on the runway and another couldn't stop
shaking.
</P>
<P>
   Certainly Montano doesn't need a supermodel to have an impact.
The fact that he showed on the calendar speaks volumes. His venue
cost $7,800 to rent, paid for by Cotton Inc., a nonprofit industry
trade group, after the Denver native won a national contest in
which he described how he uses cotton in his designs. The grant for
the show wasn't part of the contest prize, but Cotton sponsored it
anyway, says Montano spokesman Patrick Hughes: ``If alcohol
companies can sponsor fashion shows, why not Cotton Inc.?''
</P>
<P>
   Montano's latest collection is geared toward ``a really
hard-edged woman with a lot of style,'' Montano says. ``My customer
is a woman who has an attitude about life. She's a very strong
woman who is happy with herself no matter what she weighs'' or
looks like. ``My colors are bright, my patterns bold. They're happy
clothes.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, the show included sexy, bold, unexpected elements, like
shoulders that pointed sharply into horn shapes and a collar that
unzipped and jutted out into two long points. One dress was long in
the front and miniskirt length in the back. A few skirt waistlines
were asymmetrical.
</P>
<P>
   Like Karan, Montano studied design in New York. (Karan attended
Parsons School of Design; Montano graduated from the Fashion
Institute of Technology.) Using $5,000 saved from an internship at
Oscar de la Renta, Montano opened a store in Jersey City, N.J.,
after graduation.
</P>
<P>
   Sewing all of his goods himself, he cultivated a following and
eventually moved his store to Manhattan's East Village in 1991. Now
some of his clients include LeAnn Rimes, Demi Moore, and Melanie
Griffith. (Montano's casual wear ranges from $75 to $400. His ball
gowns start at $500.)
</P>
<P>
   Montano _ who says his ``company car'' is a bike and who lives
in an apartment above his store _ is quick to agree that the
fashion business is tough. But he also points out it could be
worse. His first show, in 1993, was in a public park. ``I wheeled
the clothes 15 blocks'' to get there, he says, shaking his head.
``It was outside and it was cold. It sounded like a good idea at
the time.''
</P>
<P>
   And Sunday's show was the first time in three years in which the
music didn't cut off while Montano's models were still on the
runway. ``I've learned that at a certain point, you don't have
control over a show. You have to relinquish it.``
</P>
<P>
   Montano says his ultimate goal isn't necessarily to become the
next Donna Karan, who is creative director of a publicly traded
company. ``I want to be able to design and create without worrying
about money. That's what my life is about _ creation.''
</P>
<P>
   Montano, who has seven volunteer assistants, says that every day
at 2:30 p.m. they all order sandwiches and sit around, discussing
fashion, relationships, and life in general. ``I love it,'' he
says. ``I never want to lose that.''
</P>
<P>
   So what if a Montano show never attracts 800 people? ``In a lot
of ways, I feel I've reached the goal I set long ago,'' he says.
``They painted my name out front! Whatever else happens, I made it
here.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
