<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-17 13:08 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8573 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MUSIC-MARTIN-BOS &LR;      02-17 1065
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MUSIC-MARTIN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SIR GEORGE TRAVELS THE LONG AND WINDING ROAD 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVE MORSE  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ He's now called Sir George Martin, having been knighted
three years ago. He'll forever be known to the public, though, as
the professorial producer of the Beatles. He worked on all of their
albums _ including the popular ``Beatles Anthology'' series of the
past few years, which reunited him with Paul McCartney, George
Harrison, and Ringo Starr at Abbey Road studio in London.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Abbey Road staff was amazed to see these old codgers
reminiscing about old times,'' says Martin, who will be inducted
into the Rock Hall of Fame next month.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was astonishing to do the anthology series _ to relive all
your moments of joy and fun and sadness and anger,'' adds Martin by
phone from England. ``I'm very glad we did it.''
</P>
<P>
   Martin, 72, will relive another aspect of his Beatles experience
on a multimedia lecture tour, ``The Making of Sgt. Pepper,'' which
comes to the Berklee Performance Center Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   ``Multimedia is a rather grand term,'' says Martin. ``It's kind
of a talk, really. I do use one or two bits of video to illustrate
what we're talking about, which wakes people up and gives me a
chance to have a glass of water. I speak for up to an hour and 15
minutes. It's an explanation of `Sgt. Pepper' and why and how it
came to be made. I wrote a book about it some years ago and I also
had a TV program based on it. It's the kind of thing I've been
doing for a while, but people seem interested in it and everywhere
I go, they receive it very warmly.''
</P>
<P>
   Even though ``Sgt. Pepper's Lonely Hearts Club Band'' is not
Martin's favorite Beatles album (he'll instead name ``Rubber Soul''
or ``Abbey Road''), he says that ``it took on a shape of its own''
once the Beatles settled into the concept.
</P>
<P>
   ``Its significance is that it was a breakthrough, a kind of
watershed,'' Martin says. ``It was something that I'd always
nurtured in my mind _ to get a little more programmy about what we
were doing and a little more symphonic. I was lecturing Paul and
John (Lennon) always to think in classical terms, not necessarily
to write classical music, but to think about form a bit more. John
wouldn't have any of it. He said, `I'm a rock 'n' roller. What are
you on about? I'm a Teddy Boy (term that roughly means tough guy).'
Paul took some of it.''
</P>
<P>
   Martin says that in later years, he and the Beatles eventually
went too far. He says he was a ``little pretentious'' in the
classical overtones he brought to ``Abbey Road.'' He admits to
other second thoughts, though he's proud of the body of work.
</P>
<P>
   ``Many years ago, before John died, we spent some time in his
flat and he said he'd like to do everything again,'' recalls
Martin. ``I was appalled by this and I couldn't really believe he
meant that. I said, `You mean you'd like to record everything
again?' And he said, `Yes, I would.' I said, `You know, I think
some of those records were great.' I couldn't understand what he
was on about. I was just saying to myself, `Well, his imagination
is always much better than real life,' which I think was true. I
think his dreams were much more vivid than reality.
</P>
<P>
   ``But when I went through the anthology, there were cases where
I said to myself: I think we should have left it there and not done
any more. I would have liked to be a little more minimalist. That
was my only criticism. I think what we did wasn't bad, but some of
the innocence of the demos was incredibly charming. When you hear
the first time a song had ever been heard in the studio, and we put
a mic on it _ some of those, warts and all, were better than the
masters.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked what he thought of Lennon's and McCartney's post-Beatles
solo work, Martin is equally honest. ``They wrote some smashing
songs during that time and they also wrote some rubbish. I don't
think either of them ever achieved the Olympian heights they
achieved together. I think they missed each other very much.''
</P>
<P>
   Did you ever tell them that?
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh, sure. Sometimes I would say things that weren't very
welcome and I would get rapped over the knuckles. But I think they
knew that too. I'm sure they knew it.''
</P>
<P>
   Although principally known for his Beatles work (he's often been
called ``the fifth Beatle''), Martin has been a prolific producer,
with more than 700 records to his credit. Outside of the Beatles,
he's proudest of his productions with the band America, Jeff Beck,
and the Mahavishnu Orchestra.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are so many people I enjoyed working with. And even
before the Beatles, I enjoyed my work in the comedy field with
Peter Sellers,'' says Martin, who began his career in 1950 as a
classical producer for the Parlephone label, which he eventually
headed and to which he signed the Beatles in 1962.
</P>
<P>
   Martin, who is now losing his hearing (he originally offered to
do this interview on the Internet rather than by phone), had
another career highlight when he produced Elton John's tribute to
Princess Diana, ``Candle in the Wind.'' Martin then retired from
making records after releasing last year's ``It's My Life,'' a
compilation of Beatles songs done by artists from Celine Dion to
comedian Jim Carrey.
</P>
<P>
   But it's not a typical retirement. He's now on his lecture tour,
then will arrange Beatles songs and other compositions for
orchestras in Canada this spring. He hopes to get back to
Montserrat (where he had the world-famous Air Studio, which was
recently damaged by a hurricane) to help rebuild that island.
</P>
<P>
   ``Life is very full, so retirement is not exactly the word,'' he
says.
</P>
<P>
   As for today's producers, he likes the self-produced techno
group the Prodigy, but doesn't like the way that many modern
records are made. ``Producing today is such a different art. It's
very technical and it's very computerized. You've got to be a
master of many things in the studio. It's less to do with musicians
and orchestration and more to do with sound bites and Pro Tools and
those kinds of things.''
</P>
<P>
   Nor does he miss the record business. ``First of all, records
are very hard to sell now. The record business is not very good.
Secondly, most of the corporations seem to be run by people who
don't know a great deal about what we're trying to do. It's not as
happy as it was in our day.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
