<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-17 13:10 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8579 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RETIREMENT-CAMPUS-2ND     02-17 0995
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RETIREMENT-CAMPUS-2ND </SLUG>
   TAKE-ART-BOS  
 HANOVER, N.H.: ... to $3,604.  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Residents say they identify closely with both the Kendal and
Hanover communities. ``I have a life within Kendal, but I also have
a life outside of it,'' says 77-year-old Joan Birnbaum. ``I take
part in all sorts of activities in town, and I have a lot of
younger friends outside of Kendal.'' A former investment counselor
for the United Methodist Church, Birnbaum moved to Kendal from
Greenwich, Conn. in 1991, when the retirement community opened.
</P>
<P>
   Birnbaum serves on several retirement community committees and
is active in a couple of area women's organizations, the local
Wellesley College alumnae club, a bridge group in Hanover, and a
Congregational church in Norwich, Vt. And she keeps on learning.
</P>
<P>
   One of Hanover's top assets for many Kendal residents such as
Birnbaum is the Institute for Lifelong Education at Dartmouth.
Staffed by volunteers, the institute offers about 30
adult-education courses on a wide range of subjects each semester
as well as a summer lecture series.
</P>
<P>
   The institute's classes are held at Dartmouth and in various
venues around Hanover, including the retirement community. Nearly
40 percent of Kendal community residents are enrolled in the ILEAD
program. Birnbaum says she has taken 25 ILEAD courses on subjects
as varied as the history of Yugoslavia, how to predict weather, and
the art of story telling. ``It's whatever interests me,'' she
explains.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the college towns that have attracted retirement
communities are, like Hanover, serene, safe, and in beautiful rural
settings. Also appealing (and reassuring) to elderly retirees is
the presence of medical schools and the teaching hospitals usually
affiliated with them. The Dartmouth-Hitchcock Medical Center, for
instance, is considered one of the best in New England.
</P>
<P>
   Conversely, the presence of a population of vigorous elders also
gives specialists in the growing field of gerontology an
opportunity to study the long-term effects of aging. ``The
Dartmouth Medical Center looks on Kendal as a big laboratory,''
says 77-year-old Robert Stambaugh, a Midwesterner with a degree
from Purdue University who was a Union Carbide Co. executive. ``A
lot of people here have volunteered for studies.''
</P>
<P>
   Kendal is nondenominational, though it was developed by the
Kendal Corporation of Kennett Square, Pa., a nonprofit company with
a Quaker affiliation. The corporation has developed 10 such
retirement comunities around the country, including several in
college towns. The one in Ithaca, N.Y., for example, is on the
Cornell University campus.
</P>
<P>
   Only about 10 percent of Kendal at Hanover residents are
Quakers, says administrator Leonard Cadwallader, ``but the
operating philosphy is Quaker.'' Among other things, Cadwallader
says, this means decision-making by consensus and an emphasis on
community service and volunteerism.
</P>
<P>
   One active Kendal volunteer is Walter Frank, who chaired the New
York Stock Exchange in the mid 1960s. ``I like to sing,'' explains
Frank, who leads sing-alongs to entertain infirm and bedridden
patients in the community nursing center. Asked about his own
health, the 90-year-old Frank cheerfully replies, ``I'm bullish.''
</P>
<P>
   George Graham, 77, a Kendal resident and Dartmouth alumnus,
says, ``I audit classes at the college, go to plays and concerts
there, and take part in a Dartmouth fitness program. And, quite a
few of my classmates are also in the area and I see them.''
</P>
<P>
   While the presence of Dartmouth alumni such as Graham is
understandable, the community might at first seem an odd retirement
choice for 90-year-old Olin J. Stephens. ``People always ask me
what I'm doing so far inland,'' says Stephens, the legendary
designer of boats that have defended the America's Cup eight times.
</P>
<P>
   Known in yachting circles as ``the ancient mariner,'' Stephens,
who did not attend Dartmouth, dropped anchor at Kendal shortly
after it opened. ``I've always liked the country, had sons living
in the area, and my wife wasn't in good health at the time and
needed a place like this,'' he explains.
</P>
<P>
   His wife died in 1993 but Stephens has no plans to ship out. ``I
don't feel stranded here,'' he says. He says he spends most of the
year in New Hampshire, with occasional forays to Maine and
California to visit friends and do some sailing, often in restored
old wooden boats he designed.
</P>
<P>
   Stephens says he has taken several courses at Dartmouth and
makes use of the library and other facilities. ``I'm now working
with a Dartmouth professor studying the effect of wind on sails,''
he says. ``I have a pretty fast PC with a good memory that I use to
work on mathematical problems, and the project keeps me busy.''
</P>
<P>
   Besides all the activities at the college, the retirement
community itself has about 70 resident-organized special interest
groups, from book and bridge clubs to woodworking and weaving
groups. It was the absence of just this sort of intense
intellectual and social activity that made Charles and Shirley
Boren decide last year to exchange their retirement home in New
Mexico for an apartment in Kendal.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were in a beautiful spot in a canyon along the Pecos River,
but it was lonely and isolated; you had to drive two hours just to
go to a movie,'' says Shirley Boren. ``Being here is stimulating
and a relief _ we don't plan ever to move again.''
</P>
<P>
   The couple, both in their mid-60s, lived in Hartford for 30
years before moving to the Southwest five years ago. A
psychiatrist, Charles Boren was a consultant to the National
Basketball Association and now lectures part time at Dartmouth
Medical School. He says he's impressed _ and inspired _ by the way
Kendal residents care for each other.
</P>
<P>
   ``The issues at the end of life are loneliness, making your life
count for something, and facing death,'' says Borens. ``We never
lose the need for role models, and these people are models for
aging.''
</P>
</TEXT>
