<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-17 13:11 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8581 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TV-SPORTS-COLUMN-BOS &LR;      02-17 0919
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-SPORTS-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ESPYS ARE PRIME-TIME 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By HOWARD MANLY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Dick Vitale was backstage Monday night at Radio City
Music Hall, waiting to present an ESPY award, when he struck up a
conversation with actor Christian Slater. They chatted like old
pals, shook hands, and went their separate ways _ Vitale to his
wife and daughters, Slater to schmooze with other Hollywood
celebrities.
</P>
<P>
   The only problem was that Vitale didn't know who Slater was.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yeah, I told my daughter that I just met some guy, uh, a
Christian Slater and she went, `Oh my God, Christian Slater . . .
Christian Slater,' '' said a slightly embarrassed Vitale said.
</P>
<P>
   There are worse things in life, and given that ESPN considers
itself the center of the sports universe, it's only natural that
one of the network's most recognizable personalities wouldn't know
each person who makes a splash in Hollywood.
</P>
<P>
   The funny part is that Slater also didn't know to whom he was
talking.
</P>
<P>
   When Vitale made it onstage to present an award, Slater was
backstage watching on television.
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh, there's that guy I just met,'' he told a friend.
</P>
<P>
   The ESPYs are more than just an annual celebration of athletic
achievement. No other sports awards show brings athletes from
different professions together for mutual praise. That alone
qualifies it as a one-of-a-kind event.
</P>
<P>
   But the ESPYs are much bigger, bigger than simply having Jeff
Gordon, fresh off his Daytona 500 victory, and Sammy Sosa under the
same roof. That's easy. But Hollywood celebrities and sports? Now
that, as ESPN likes to describe it, is ``the greatest night in
sports.''
</P>
<P>
   The ESPYs weren't always so great. Seven years ago, Steve
Bornstein, then president of ESPN, approved an idea that one of his
editors, John Walsh, had been kicking around for years. Walsh had
been managing editor at Inside Sports magazine and dreamed up a
sports award show as a way to create publicity to save the
publication. Inside Sports went out of business before the show
came to be, but Walsh held on to the idea.
</P>
<P>
   Bornstein liked it, and the rest is history.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is show biz,'' said ESPN executive producer Jeff Ruhe.
``This isn't like live sports, where you just turn on the cameras.
We devote a lot of time and attention to the ESPYs and we have seen
a real payback in terms of awareness of the show. More and more big
names are excited about and look forward to participating every
year.''
</P>
<P>
   Comedian Dennis Miller hosted the first show, held at the Felt
Forum in Madison Square Garden, and while some of the presenters
were stars, they didn't always know what they were doing. Raquel
Welch, for instance, gave the college basketball player of the year
to ``Christine'' Laettner.
</P>
<P>
   But from the beginning, the show had its moments, such as the
time a cancer-stricken Jim Valvano accepted the Arthur Ashe ESPY
for courage. ``Don't give up, don't ever give up,'' Valvano told
the audience.
</P>
<P>
   Jim Allegro was executive producer of the first show and he
remembered Bornstein telling him it could run no longer than two
hours.
</P>
<P>
   Allegro and Walsh tried to cut back the highlights, but it
turned into three hours. An annoyed Bornstein restated the two-hour
rule and Allegro and Walsh went back to the editing room. They
finally got it to two hours and 40 minutes and, according to some
critics, the show was still too long.
</P>
<P>
   ESPN stayed with it, though, encouraged by the support of such
stars as Emmitt Smith and Jimmy Johnson and the worthiness of its
contribution to cancer research through the V Foundation. Its
ratings were better than those the cable network received from most
of its college basketball games. The live audience grew from about
2,000 to 5,000 after the show moved to the bigger Radio City Music
Hall.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can tell it's catching on,'' said ESPN's Charley Steiner.
``Everywhere I go, someone invariably tells me that a play should
be considered for an ESPY.''
</P>
<P>
   Now ESPN turns down offers from stars to participate. Not that
anyone could tell from the crowded scene backstage Monday night.
</P>
<P>
   Samuel L. Jackson hosted this year's show, which was filled with
tributes to the incredible baseball season. Talk-show host Rosie
O'Donnell held court in one corner. Actor Jeff Daniels talked with
Cal Ripken in another. Mark McGwire and David Wells traded jokes.
</P>
<P>
   Darryl Strawberry and his wife stood in the middle of the room
and posed for photographs with stars, including actors Matthew
Broderick and Sarah Jessica Parker.
</P>
<P>
   A Yankees fan, Parker inched her way over to Strawberry and got
to shake his hand. She tried to coax her husband but he was a
little torn.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm a Mets fan,'' Broderick said. ``And I'm still struggling
with Yankee fever. And besides, what do you say to Darryl
Strawberry? `Hi, it's nice to meet you.' I don't know. I'm a little
nervous.''
</P>
<P>
   Broderick eventually went over and sheepishly had a picture
taken.
</P>
<P>
   Comedian Al Franken stayed in the background. He liked the idea
of having entertainers mix with athletes but was a little concerned
about comparing his own athletic prowess with those in attendance.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm from Minnesota and I wrestled in high school,'' Franken
said. ``You don't see any awards for professional wrestlers, now do
you?''
</P>
<P>
   Becoming governor of Minnesota is one thing, but no one could
imagine Jesse Ventura winning an ESPY.
</P>
<P>
   Not even in ``The Body's'' prime.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
