<HEADER>
A8582 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u d &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FOOD-COLUMN-RECIPES-B     02-17 0841
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FOOD-COLUMN-RECIPES-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MELISSA KELLY SHARES HER RECIPES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Here are some recipes created by Melissa Kelly, executive chef
of the Old Chatham Sheepherding Company Inn.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL; 
OLD CHATHAM CAMEMBERT CRISP
</P>
<P>
   2 pieces fresh sheep's milk Camembert cheese
</P>
<P>
   3 sheets phyllo dough
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons melted butter plus 1 tablespoon unmelted
</P>
<P>
   For the egg wash:
</P>
<P>
   1 egg
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons milk
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Cut each Camembert from corner to corner into 2 triangle shapes.
</P>
<P>
   Lay a sheet of phyllo in front of you, butter it lightly with
the melted butter, and lay another sheet over the top. Repeat.
</P>
<P>
   Place the Camembert triangles in a row at the bottom of the
sheet (you should have 4 triangles). Cut the phyllo between each
piece from the top to the bottom.
</P>
<P>
   Beginning at the bottom, fold the phyllo ``flag-fold style''
over the cheese and roll the cheese until you get to the top. Make
the egg wash by beating together the egg and milk, then brush a
little on the final fold.
</P>
<P>
   When ready to serve, heat a skillet over a medium-high flame,
add 1 tablespoon of unmelted butter and brown the phyllo on all
sides until golden. This should take less than 1 minute on each
side.
</P>
<P>
   Serve warm with a fruit chutney, toasted bread, and a tossed
salad.
</P>
<P>
   Serves 4.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL; 
FIELD GREENS WITH ROASTED BEETS AND FRESH SHEEP'S CHEESE
</P>
<P>
   Goat cheese can be substituted for the sheep's cheese. Both
cheeses are sharp and play off the sweetness of the beets.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   2 shallots, minced
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup red wine vinegar
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon balsamic vinegar
</P>
<P>
   Salt and freshly cracked black pepper to taste
</P>
<P>
   3/4 cup olive oil (medium-bodied pure)
</P>
<P>
   3 to 4 beets
</P>
<P>
   Mesclun greens (field mix)
</P>
<P>
   2 sprigs basil (torn into bite-size pieces)
</P>
<P>
   2 sprigs flat-leaf Italian parsley (pick leaves from stem)
</P>
<P>
   1/2 bunch chives (snipped into 1-inch lengths)
</P>
<P>
   2 heads Belgian endive, separated into spears
</P>
<P>
   1/4 pound cheese (fresh sheep or goat)
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Prepare the vinaigrette by mincing the shallots and placing them
in a bowl with the vinegars. Season with salt and pepper, then let
sit 15 to 20 minutes. Whisk in the olive oil and adjust the
seasonings to taste. Set aside.
</P>
<P>
   Set the oven to 400 degrees. Wrap the beets in foil and roast
for about 1 hour or until a knife slides in with ease. Remove from
the oven and let them cool. Then peel the beets and cut into
wedges. Set aside.
</P>
<P>
   In a bowl, toss the greens and herbs with half the vinaigrette.
</P>
<P>
   To serve, lay the endive spears on a platter or plates. Place
the greens in the center of the endive and arrange the beets around
the greens. Drizzle the beets with the remaining vinaigrette.
Crumble the cheese over the top and then sprinkle with cracked
black pepper. Enjoy with crusty bread.
</P>
<P>
   Serves 4.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL; 
RICOTTA CHEESECAKE
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   For the crust:
</P>
<P>
   12 tablespoons unsalted butter
</P>
<P>
   3/4 cup sugar
</P>
<P>
   1 egg
</P>
<P>
   1/4 teaspoon vanilla extract
</P>
<P>
   1 1/2 cups all-purpose flour
</P>
<P>
   3/4 teaspoon baking soda
</P>
<P>
   Salt to taste
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   For the filling:
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup golden raisins
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup Marsala
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup pine nuts
</P>
<P>
   4 cups whole milk ricotta
</P>
<P>
   3/4 cup heavy cream
</P>
<P>
   4 large eggs
</P>
<P>
   9 tablespoons sugar
</P>
<P>
   Pinch of cinnamon
</P>
<P>
   1/2 teaspoon vanilla extract
</P>
<P>
   1/4 teaspoon almond extract
</P>
<P>
   5 tablespoons all-purpose flour
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Set the oven to 350 degrees.
</P>
<P>
   For the crust: Cream together 8 tablespoons of butter with the
sugar until light and fluffy. Mix in the egg and vanilla, and beat
until smooth. Set aside.
</P>
<P>
   Sift together the flour, baking soda, and salt. Stir the dry
mixture into the butter mixture until combined. Wrap and chill at
least 2 hours or overnight.
</P>
<P>
   Split the chilled dough into 2 pieces. Roll out each into a
rectangle 1/8 inch thick. Place on a baking sheet and bake in the
oven for 10 to 15 minutes, until golden. Remove from the oven and
then crumble both. Place the crumbs in a bowl.
</P>
<P>
   Melt the remaining 4 tablespoons of butter and stir into the
crumbs. Butter an 8 1/2-inch round springform pan and press the
crumb mixture on the bottom and sides of the pan to form an even
crust.
</P>
<P>
   For the filling: Place the raisins in a bowl. Heat the Marsala
in a saute pan. When hot, pour it over the raisins. Let stand for
20 minutes to plump up the raisins.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, spread the pine nuts on a baking sheet and toast in
the oven for 2 to 3 minutes, until golden but not dark. Set aside.
</P>
<P>
   Place the ricotta, cream, eggs, sugar, cinnamon, and extracts in
a bowl, then sift the flour over them. Whisk together for 4 minutes
until well combined. Add the plumped raisins and toasted pine nuts,
and mix well. Spoon the batter into the prepared crust. Bake on a
cookie sheet 1 1/4 to 1 1/2 hours, until the top is golden brown
and has puffed.
</P>
<P>
   Cool on a rack for at least 20 minutes, then chill in the
refrigerator for 1 hour. Run a spatula around the sides and unmold.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
