<DOCNO> NYT19990217.0144 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-17 13:14 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8584 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u d &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FOOD-COLUMN-BOS &LR;      02-17 1612
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FOOD-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHEF MELISSA KELLY MAKES IT FROM SCRATCH 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ALISON ARNETT  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   OLD CHATHAM, N.Y. _ The rolling hills around the Old Chatham
Sheepherding Company Inn are frosted with snow. The January
vacation is over, along with the annual refurbishing of the
antique-filled main house. The chef is back in residence,
developing her winter menus. And the first lambs of the season's
expected 1,600 are trying out their spindly legs.
</P>
<P>
   A stay at a country inn spells romance to most of us, and this
one, tucked into a 500-acre working sheep farmjust over the
Massachusetts border, hits every high note. Its draw, though, isn't
just as a bucolic hideaway for well-to-do New Yorkers. The Old
Chatham Sheepherding Company Inn is a mecca for food lovers,
because of Melissa Kelly, executive chef and co-manager.
</P>
<P>
   On this wintry day, she greets me in a cozy sitting room of the
1790 Georgian-style house. Wearing overalls and a little T-shirt
under a long white apron, with her dark brown hair slicked back
into a ponytail, she looks like an 11-year-old who had wandered in
from school.
</P>
<P>
   Kelly, at 33, is an undisputed culinary star, acclaimed by
national food magazines and writers since graduating first in her
1988 class at the Culinary Institute of America. Her food, which I
had sampled the previous evening, ranges across the new American
palate. Its clearest impetus is not a regional style such as
Mediterranean or a look such as vertical. The impetus for
everything Kelly makes is taste.
</P>
<P>
   One can be assured of being fed well here. That stems not only
from Kelly's talent but also from her life philosophy. The French
talk about ``terroir'' _ being able to taste the soil, the very
essence of the land, in wine and food. That's what you get in
Kelly's cooking at the inn.
</P>
<P>
   This morning, Kelly's conversation illuminates the way she puts
that exquisite food on the table. Basically she starts at the
beginning. She uses the lamb raised on the farm to create highly
flavorful dishes such as grilled lamb chops with a ragout of
flageolet beans, tomatoes, portobello mushrooms, and eggplant on a
bed of mustard greens. The Camembert _ layered with phyllo sheets
and fashioned into a crisp to be served with cherry-gooseberry
chutney and venison prosciutto _ is made down the road at the
farm's creamery from milk from the sheep.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the vegetables are grown in the kitchen garden next to
the inn in the warmer months. Kelly stores root vegetables in a
cellar for the colder months. Year-round, she and a gardener grow
salad materials in a greenhouse next to the garden. The breads,
biscuits, and desserts are made by her fiance, Price Kushner, in a
bakery next to the inn.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the beginning, I studied the Shaker philosophy'' of doing
everything from scratch, Kelly says of her first days creating a
cuisine for the inn, which opened 3 1/2 years ago. The Shaker
Museum and Library across the road lent inspiration, and she was an
eager student. After all, she grew up in an extended
Italian-American family on Long Island that had a tradition of
gardening, fishing, and putting up vegetables for the winter. ``It
was almost embarrassing that we were so peasant,'' Kelly says with
a wry grin.
</P>
<P>
   The peasant orientation, ``the things I learned as a child from
my grandmother,'' gave Kelly a foundation when she moved from
working in restaurants for pocket money during high school to
deciding that cooking was what she wanted to do with her life.
</P>
<P>
   Her dedication to her craft is limitless. ``Everything is my
concern,'' she says of her job as executive chef and co-manager
with innkeeper George Shattuck III. ``The first three months that
we were open,'' Kelly says, ``I literally didn't get off this
road.'' Even now, as the inn's fame has grown, Kelly finds it hard
to stay out of the kitchen on Tuesdays, her day off. She lives on
the edge of the property and her schedule stretches from 10 a.m. to
the wee hours of the morning six days a week, planning, managing a
staff of five to six cooks, and cooking alongside them. ``It's very
intense,'' she says.
</P>
<P>
   Firmly believing in using only what is fresh and seasonal, Kelly
has developed local sources for game birds and for vegetables she
can't grow, and she has found a fish purveyor she trusts. She
writes the menu daily, changing it four or five times ``up until 5
o'clock.'' Kelly checks on the Camembert production, makes sure the
guests have sheep-shaped cookies on their turned-down beds in the
evenings, and tries to find time to plan restarting the smokehouse
on the property.
</P>
<P>
   She became interested in smoking food several years ago. While
researching regional cooking, she began reading about Native
American methods. The farm raises six pigs at a time for the
restaurant and she and her staff butcher sides of pork, cure hams
and other pork products, and make sausages and headcheese. The
bacon is cured here but smoked off the premises, and Kelly would
like to add that chore to her repertoire. ``The pork is delicious
because (the pigs) eat so well,'' she says.
</P>
<P>
   One might suppose, from the back-to-basics approach, that
Kelly's food would be rustic, but that's not the case. Her dishes
are as evolved as those in fine New York City and Boston
restaurants, the presentation as exquisitely mannered. Truffles and
caviar, foie gras and lobster grace the menu. And the desserts by
Kushner are works of art. It's also true that lamb grown near the
kitchen, or sheep's milk ice cream made from milk only hours old,
or green tomato pickles and tomatillo chutney canned at the peak of
ripeness in the summer make indelible taste impressions.
</P>
<P>
   Customers come from all over the country, with the strongest
contingent from New York City. Many diners travel down from Albany,
only 20 minutes away, or over the Berkshires from Massachusetts,
about 40 minutes east. In the summer months, the inn and the
restaurant are ``consistently busy,'' Kelly says. March and April
are slower months.
</P>
<P>
   Kelly previously worked for restaurateur Larry Forgione at
Beekman 1776 Tavern farther down the Hudson River and for Alice
Waters at Chez Panisse in Berkeley, Calif. She first came to the
farm to give advice to owners Tom and Nancy Clark, who had started
raising sheep on the property and were thinking of creating a bed
and breakfast. At that time, Kelly says, the inn was just an
``empty, dark, drab house.'' Kelly told them they needed a full
restaurant and less than a year later began the intense work to
open one.
</P>
<P>
   Nancy Clark finds the antiques that furnish the house,
supervises all the decorative elements, and even hunts out the
delightful antique china that is mixed and matched with new pieces
for the dining room. Tom Clark is in charge of the financial
operation.
</P>
<P>
   The inn consists of five rooms in the main house, two guest
cottages with three rooms, a carriage house with two rooms. Four
suites are being built and will be ready for the summer high
season. All are luxuriously appointed and the rooms go for $185 to
$450 a night. But both Kelly and innkeeper Shattuck stress that
it's not formal.
</P>
<P>
   ``We try to keep it cozy and family-style,'' Kelly says. Guests
are encouraged to wander down to the dairy barns to watch the lambs
being fed and the sheep being milked, to watch through glass
windows the yogurt and cheesemaking operations, and to hike the
paths around the property. There are afternoon lectures on
gardening, talks and demonstrations by local artists, and cooking
classes in the bakery. And the 70 staff members are unfailingly
gracious.
</P>
<P>
   The life is ``very consuming,'' says Kelly, who serves 70 to 100
meals a night, works in a small kitchen with only three other cooks
at a time, and rarely sees her fiance during the week.
</P>
<P>
   ``I always thought I'd have my own place,'' Kelly says. But the
inn's resources and the latitude the Clarks give her are
fulfilling. ``I don't make all the final decisions,'' she says,
``so sometimes it's hard. But they have a lot of confidence in
me.''
</P>
<P>
   Now in midwinter, Kelly and the gardener, Jo Ann Regan, are
poring over seed catalogs to begin next summer's garden. It's been
a system of trial and error, Kelly says, but also rewarding. She
rattles off what grew last year: raspberries, strawberries, green
garlic, spring onions, purslane, squashes, fava beans, Romano
beans, filet beans, baby carrots, turnips, broccoli rabe, edible
flowers of all kinds, and the list goes on. ``Every year it gets
better,'' she says with a smile.
</P>
<P>
   The smile and the sentiment could refer to it all _ Kelly's
belief that going for the pure, elemental taste in good ingredients
gives great results. The diner can taste the terroir of the farm in
her food.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
HOW TO GET THERE &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Old Chatham Sheepherding Inn is in Old Chatham, N.Y., off
Route 90 (New York extension of the Massachusetts Turnpike), about
4 hours from Boston. The inn, open all year except for three weeks
in January, is on the National Historic Register and a member of
the Relais &AMP; Chateaux association.
</P>
<P>
   The restaurant, which is open to the public, serves dinner every
night except Tuesday and also serves Sunday brunch. Prices for
entrees range from $19 to $29.
</P>
<P>
   Cooking classes, held in the spring, are open to the public with
reservations, as are afternoon lectures. The bakery sells bread,
scones, cinnamon rolls, and other pastries as well as Camembert,
sheep's milk cheeses, ricotta, and yogurt made on the farm, frozen
lamb chops and shanks.
</P>
<P>
   For information, call 518-794-9774 or e-mail
oldsheepinn(at)worldnet.att.net.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
