<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VENTURE-INSURANCE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INSURERS HOLD THEIR OWN, RECEIVE $80M IN QUARTER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JERRY ACKERMAN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Seemingly running against a high-tech tide, three New England
insurance companies received a total of almost $80 million in
venture fund financing during the last quarter of 1998, accounting
for 14 percent of all investment in the region.
</P>
<P>
   One, Insurance Holdings of America Inc., of Beverly, Mass.,
which got $24.75 million from a consortium of venture funds, is in
fact built around the presence of the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   Representing several life and property insurance underwriters,
it uses the Internet to provide franchised field agents the ability
to offer quotations and write insurance policies almost instantly,
drawing on data stored in a computer bank at company headquarters.
</P>
<P>
   Brian McCarthy, founder and chief executive, said its agent
network includes 82 who now work in Sam's Club stores, operated by
Wal-Mart Stores Inc., in New Hampshire, Michigan, Illinois, and
Arizona.
</P>
<P>
   Nine more states, including Massachusetts, are expected to be
added by June, and most other states by the end of the year.
Insurance Holdings also plans to launch a World Wide Web site this
summer where consumers can order insurance directly.
</P>
<P>
   The others, Connecticut Reinsurance Corp. and Target Capital
Partners Inc., are more traditional insurers, with business plans
that aim to acquire smaller companies over several years.
</P>
<P>
   Executives of both companies said they chose Connecticut because
of an economic development program that exempts them from all state
corporate taxes for 10 years.
</P>
<P>
   Enacted in 1995, the Connecticut Insurance Reinvestment Act was
designed to stimulate a revival of the state's traditional
insurance industry, decimated in recent years by mergers,
acquisitions, and automation.
</P>
<P>
   Participants must have at least 25 percent of their employees in
the state and remain in Connecticut for 10 years. The first company
to take advantage of it, Zurich Reinsurance Centre Holdings Inc.,
moved 400 employees to Stamford from New York in 1997, with its
projected tax break estimated at $190 million.
</P>
<P>
   Connecticut Reinsurance and Target Capital each received $25
million in start-up funding from Northington Connecticut Insurance
Reinvestment Partners LLC, funded mostly by the insurance industry.
Connecticut Reinsurance chief executive David Harris said his
company also got $5 million from other sources.
</P>
<P>
   Harris, also chief executive of Harris Insurance Holdings of
Houston, a group that includes Central United Life Insurance Co.,
Christian Life, and Unum Life, said Connecticut Reinsurance is
negotiating to acquire other life underwriters being offered for
sale by large financial institutions, following major mergers and
acquisitions in the industry.
</P>
<P>
   ``The industry is restructuring right now,'' he said, ``and is
looking at what they now have and repositioning again.''
</P>
<P>
   Target Capital Partners chief executive Mark Kottler, who is
based in Boca Raton, Fla., said his company plans to buy up to 20
smaller general managing agency companies now underwriting and
issuing policies to niche markets, such as liability insurance for
lawyers, architects, and nonprofit groups.
</P>
<P>
   The first acquisition, last month, was an Illinois company that
insures architects, engineers, home inspectors, educators, and
public officials, among others.
</P>
<P>
   Kottler said such firms typically have about $50 million in
annual premium revenues, and while profitable, are managed by
owners who are nearing retirement age and don't have succession
plans. ``A changing of the guard is occurring,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Harris and Kottler said they both plan to locate their corporate
offices in the Hartford area, where, Harris said, a sizable work
force that knows the insurance business appears to be available.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
