<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-17 13:16 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8593 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-WEATHERVANE-REVAMP-BO     02-17 0967
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WEATHERVANE-REVAMP-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THIS IS NOT YOUR MOTHER'S WEATHERVANE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CHRIS REIDY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   His stores abandoned by middle-age women, Larry Davidson Jr. is
hoping teenage girls can save his family's clothing business.
</P>
<P>
   Not long ago, the Weathervane Retail Corp. of New Britain,
Conn., stocked its chain of small New England stores with wardrobes
for women in their 30s, 40s, and 50s.
</P>
<P>
   But as these women reached middle age, fashion became less of a
priority, and a drop in sales forced a chain that traces its roots
to 1911 to seek bankruptcy protection in early 1998.
</P>
<P>
   Weathervane isn't the only retailer hurt by such changes. Look
at any clothing chain that targets baby-boomer women, and most have
recently posted ``lackluster results,'' says Davidson,
Weathervane's president and a grandson of a company cofounder.
</P>
<P>
   Women who were once Weathervane customers have ``migrated to
T.J. Maxx,'' he says. ``Or else they wait until department stores
have a big sale.''
</P>
<P>
   In an effort to reinvent itself as it prepares to emerge from
Chapter 11 next month, Weathervane has shifted its focus from its
former customers to their teenage daughters. That younger
demographic group is rapidly growing in size and has seen its
spending power surge in the strong economy of the late 1990s.
</P>
<P>
   Matronly merchandise has been banished from Weathervane.
Instead, shelves groan under sporty denim and youthful styles.
</P>
<P>
   ``We now have a somewhat similar mentality to Abercrombie &AMP;
Fitch _ only cheaper,'' says Davidson.
</P>
<P>
   Davidson's family is no stranger to change and retail
reinvention. Founded 88 years ago by Samuel Davidson and his
brother-in-law, Alexander Leventhal, the business long operated a
string of junior department stores under the D&AMP;L nameplate,
competing with the likes of G. Fox &AMP; Co. and Sage-Allen &AMP; Co.
</P>
<P>
   D&AMP;L closed its doors in 1994, and many of its small family-owned
rivals are gone too, casualties of consolidation in an industry
dominated by a few department store giants.
</P>
<P>
   Fortunately for the Davidsons and Leventhals, they had branched
out in 1969, opening boutique-size stores called Weathervane that
catered to baby boomers in their teens.
</P>
<P>
   As these girls grew into women, Weathervane aged with them,
updating the merchandise to keep pace with their customers'
evolving wardrobe needs.
</P>
<P>
   This strategy worked fine for more than 20 years.
</P>
<P>
   But by the early 1990s, many Weathervane customers had reached
middle age, a time when fashion becomes less of a priority and
shopping rarely qualifies as a leisure activity.
</P>
<P>
   As they juggle career and family, time-squeezed middle-age women
tend to buy new clothing for themselves only when their old
clothing wears out, Davidson says.
</P>
<P>
   And when they do shop, they want low prices and stores like T.J.
Maxx they can zip in and out of.
</P>
<P>
   ``Middle-age women no longer shop the whole mall,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   That was bad news for Weathervane. With its small stores rarely
producing more than $1.8 million each in annual sales, it couldn't
compete on price with the likes of a T.J. Maxx, whose Framingham
parent has annual sales of nearly $8 billion.
</P>
<P>
   So Weathervane decided to return to the teen market, in part
because just as their mothers had started stinting on fashion,
their teenage daughters were splurging on it in a big way.
</P>
<P>
   That splurge could continue for a decade.
</P>
<P>
   According to Teen Research Unlimited, a consulting firm that
tracks spending patterns, US teenagers accounted for an estimated
$141 billion in purchases last year, and the numbers of a group
sometimes labeled ``Generation Y'' and ``echo boomers'' is expected
to grow until the year 2010.
</P>
<P>
   Better still, teenage girls now spend about the same as boys,
about $83 per week of either their own money or their family's
money, the group says, while as recently as 1994, girls spent much
less than boys, partly because girls with jobs earned less.
</P>
<P>
   But having demographics on your side doesn't guarantee success
for a cash-poor retailer trying to reinvent itself.
</P>
<P>
   That's where Paragon Capital LLC of Needham came in, extending
loans to Weathervane after it filed for bankruptcy.
</P>
<P>
   Weathervane had operated 86 stores, many of them in strip malls
and community shopping centers. Their chief virtue? They offered
convenience to the older, time-pressed shopper.
</P>
<P>
   But teenagers still prefer to shop in big malls such as South
Shore Plaza and Natick Mall. That left Weathervane with a lot of
stores in places teenagers rarely venture.
</P>
<P>
   One advantage of Chapter 11 is that it lets a retailer break
leases at unprofitable locations. Weathervane closed 32 stores; 54
remain open.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, the increased buying power of teens hasn't gone
unnoticed by other retailers. Even in its new lean-and-mean
condition, Weathervane will have to fight Abercrombie &AMP; Fitch, the
Gap, and Gap's sister chain Old Navy for its share of the teen
dollar.
</P>
<P>
   One Weathervane strength is its long-term relationships with
clothing manufacturers. By drawing on these relationships,
Weathervane can stock its stores almost entirely with private-label
merchandise that is comparable in quality to brand-name goods but
at a much lower price, says Paragon chief executive Stewart Cohen.
</P>
<P>
   ``My teenage daughters would buy everything they could from
Abercrombie &AMP; Fitch if I let them,'' he says. ``So I'll buy them
one pair of $60 jeans from Abercrombie, but for the second and
third pair, that's when you go to Weathervane.''
</P>
<P>
   Privately owned Weathervane doesn't disclose financial
information, but Davidson says sales at stores restocked with teen
apparel are up smartly, and the company will report an operating
profit for the year it spent in Chapter 11.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
