<HEADER>
A8598 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-PRIESTS-ADS-BOS &LR;      02-17 1066
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PRIESTS-ADS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHURCH TRIES ADS TO AMPLIFY CALL FOR PRIESTS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DIEGO RIBADENEIRA  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   It may not seem like a match made in heaven, the Roman Catholic
Church turning to savvy advertising professionals for help.
</P>
<P>
   But on billboards, radio spots and television ads, the church
has joined forces with marketing gurus to send the message that
it's looking for a few good men.
</P>
<P>
   Sandwiched often jarringly between car and beer commercials on
TV channels such as Comedy Central, church ads are asking male
viewers to consider the priesthood.
</P>
<P>
   Jarring it may be, but church leaders say they must be more
aggressive if they are to overcome a significant plunge in the
number of priests over three decades.
</P>
<P>
   In 1975, the United States had about 59,000 priests. Two years
ago, there were just over 48,000. More telling, the number of
parishes without a resident priest is at 2,393, up from 549 in the
mid-1960s. And this at a time when the number of Catholics _ 61.2
million _ is more than 12 million higher than in 1975.
</P>
<P>
   So, in Milwaukee, billboards declare, ``Work with the World's
Greatest Boss,'' or, ``Enjoy the Ultimate Benefits Package.'' The
small print urges the reader to call St. Francis Seminary.
</P>
<P>
   The campaign started in November, and Milwaukee church officials
said it's too early to tell if it will produce new seminary
students, but they say they have gotten several phone calls from
men interested.
</P>
<P>
   Last month, the Diocese of Providence, R.I. ran ads on channels
that are popular among young men _ MTV, ESPN, the Comedy Channel.
</P>
<P>
   One ad shows a telephone ringing incessantly and ends with the
message: ``Christ calling you to the priesthood.'' Since the ads
started running, three men have applied to study for the
priesthood, including a police officer and a lawyer.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've gotten many, many calls from Catholics praising us for
even doing this,'' said the Rev. Marcel Taillon, director of
vocations for the Providence diocese. ``I think people are just
happy that the church is trying to get this message out and to have
something positive about the priesthood.''
</P>
<P>
   While the Archdiocese of Boston is not relying on ad campaigns
to draw more priests, officials are trying new outreach strategies
to attract candidates.
</P>
<P>
   This weekend, for example, Cardinal Bernard Law is hosting a
retreat at St. John's Seminary in Brighton for 47 men who have
expressed interest in the priesthood.
</P>
<P>
   Law first held the retreat in 1997. That year 23 men attended;
last year it was 29. Of the 52 who went on the retreat, 14 have
applied to enter St. John's Seminary.
</P>
<P>
   ``Being able spend that much quality time with the cardinal
really confirmed for me that this was the route I wanted to take,''
said Michael Drea, 32, who went on last year's retreat and is in
his first year at St. John's.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the cardinal's willingness to do this really gives a
lot of encouragement to people who may be sitting on the fence and
not quite sure if they want to do this,'' said Drea, who worked at
St. Sebastian's School in Needham, Mass. before entering the
seminary. ``It's really impressive to have someone like him doing
this and challenging people to consider the priesthood.''
</P>
<P>
   Chip Hines, 30, another first-year student at St. John's who
left a job to pursue the priesthood, said the 45-minute
conversation he had with Law at last year's retreat ultimately made
him decide to become a priest.
</P>
<P>
   ``By the time we were done he said to me, `I think you have the
call,' '' said Hines, who had been considering the priesthood for
years. ``I don't think I would be here if he had not said that.''
</P>
<P>
   Law's three-day commitment to the retreat underscores the
church's new attitude toward the recruitment of priests, church
officials said.
</P>
<P>
   No longer can the church, they said, simply sit back and expect
young men to flock to seminaries. Fewer priests means that they are
less visible in society today, making it harder to persuade young
men that the priesthood is a viable vocational option, church
officials said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Kids grow up thinking about becoming a doctor, a lawyer, but
not many grow up thinking about becoming a priest,'' said Owen
Phelps, editor of The Observer, the newspaper of the Diocese of
Rockford, Ill. ``When I was growing up you saw priests not only
saying Mass but teaching school or coaching the basketball team.
Now, you might see a priest for an hour at Mass on Sunday. Becoming
a priest doesn't register on people's radar like it used to 30 or
40 years ago.''
</P>
<P>
   Last year, the Rockford Diocese spent $50,000 on a media
campaign that included billboards and radio and TV commercials.
``God is still calling men to religious vocations, but this is a
media age and we have to be able to work in this new culture,''
Phelps said. ``That means turning up the volume and amplifying
God's call using mass media.''
</P>
<P>
   Some liberal critics of the church say the church could more
quickly ease its priest shortage if it opened the priesthood to
married men and to women, something the Vatican shows no intention
of doing.
</P>
<P>
   ``We support doing whatever it takes to make the Mass as widely
available as possible,'' said Sister Christine Schenk, president of
FutureChurch, a liberal national Catholic organization based in
Cleveland.
</P>
<P>
   In the meantime, the often high-profile marketing campaigns
appear to be paying dividends by yielding at least a slight uptick
in the number of men entering the seminary.
</P>
<P>
   The Rockford Diocese two years ago had eight men studying for
the priesthood. Right now there are 31. The Diocese of Kansas
City-St. Joseph, Mo., has seen its number of seminary students jump
from three to 20 in five years. In Milwaukee, church officials say
they expect their advertising campaign to generate 30 new
seminarians by next year.
</P>
<P>
   Nationally, after years of steep declines, the number of
students entering seminaries has stabilized in recent years at
about 500 a year.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the church needs to be out in the marketplace speaking
not in churchspeak but in the language that people understand,''
said the Rev. Robert Stiefvater, director of vocations for the
Archdiocese of Milwaukee. ``At the very least we have people
talking about the priesthood, which is not something that maybe was
happening before.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-17-99 1319EST &QL; 
