<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-17 13:20 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8600 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-STUDENT-PROTESTS-BOS &LR;      02-17 1359
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STUDENT-PROTESTS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COLLEGE ACTIVISM, '90S STYLE, UNITES TWO SIDES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KATE ZERNIKE  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The events of the past two weeks are reminding university
administrators of their salad days: students staging sit-ins in
presidents' offices, presenting them with lists of demands,
chanting about moral imperatives in foreign lands.
</P>
<P>
   This time, the issues are fair wages and better conditions in
the sweatshops that turn out billions of dollars in logo-emblazoned
college gear. Across the country, they have set off a wave of
student activism among a generation that has been labeled
apathetic.
</P>
<P>
   But this is a very different pack of protesters from the
long-haired, antiestablishment dissenters of the past. Entering the
presidents' offices, they carry cell phones and laptops so they can
do their homework (and get into good graduate schools). At
Georgetown University, students brought Dustbusters, figuring that
if they were going to occupy the president's office, they had best
clean up after themselves.
</P>
<P>
   And in a decade when each year registers another record low in
student concern for anything but their future earnings,
administrators are responding differently, too. They're not
annoyed, outraged, or polarized; they're charmed, proud _ and
relieved.
</P>
<P>
   ``Thank God students are getting passionate about something
other than basketball and bonfires,'' said John Burness, an
administrator who helped negotiate the end to a 31-hour standoff at
Duke University last week. ``But the tone is definitely different.
In the old days, we used to have to scramble to cut off phone lines
when they took over the president's office, but we didn't have to
worry about that here. They just bring their laptops and they do
work.''
</P>
<P>
   The protests began at Duke the first weekend of the month and
spread to Georgetown, where a four-day sit-in in President Leo
O'Donovan's office ended in Tuesday's wee hours. Students at the
University of Wisconsin-Madison entered a fifth day of protest
Friday, and as at the other campuses, they have been strategizing
daily via conference calls with student groups coordinating
protests at 50 other schools.
</P>
<P>
   ``The last big thing on campuses was divestment from South
Africa in the '80s,'' said Tico Almeida, a Duke senior. ``This
could turn out to be the next big thing.''
</P>
<P>
   The seeds of the protest were planted in the summer of 1997,
when Almeida and a core group of other students were working as
interns at labor unions and law firms, and learned about a plan by
14 universities to force a code of conduct on the Collegiate
Licensing Co., which manufactures logo wear for about 160 schools.
The code would set minimum wages and working conditions for the
factories that make the sweatshirts, caps, and other items sold in
university book stores.
</P>
<P>
   The students wanted a stricter code that would also force the
company to make public the location of its factories. But last
March, the universities signed a code that did not include that
provision, after the company said it didn't want its competitors to
know that information.
</P>
<P>
   After several months of trying to persuade the universities with
petitions, the students decided it was time to get pushier. More
than 100 students marched across the Duke campus to the president's
office. And with an e-mail update spreading across the country,
other campuses planned protests of their own.
</P>
<P>
   It may not be a return to the spirit of the '60s, but it is a
significant blip. Each year of the past five, the annual survey of
national freshman attitudes conducted by the University of
California at Los Angeles has hit a new record low with students
who say it is important to ``keep up with political affairs.'' At
26 percent this year, it was down from 58 percent when the survey
was first done in 1966. By contrast, the interest in being well-off
financially rose to 74 percent this year from 44 percent in 1966.
</P>
<P>
   ``The period during which we grew up, we remember Iran-Contra,
but we also remember presidents who were pretty popular, an economy
that's been strong the last several years,'' said Alex Zwerdling, a
Middlebury College junior who delivered students' demands to the
administration late last week. ``At this campus you have a pretty
solidly upper-middle class bunch of people, kids have a lot of
self-interest to worry about. Not in a negative way, but they're
worried about what they're going to do when they get out of here.
It's a very personal outlook as far as betterment goes, it's
focusing on yourself.''
</P>
<P>
   Without the threat of being sent overseas to fight, students and
researchers say, political issues seem remote, unimportant.
</P>
<P>
   But working conditions in sweatshops _ where college-age
students and younger earn about $2 an hour, and may endure
poisonous air and sexual and physical abuse _ have hit a nerve.
Many of the students admit that they wear clothing made in
sweatshops, so slipping a sweatshirt over their heads in their cozy
dorm rooms, they say, reminds them of the less fortunate whose only
opportunities are in the factories where they are made.
</P>
<P>
   ``These are people who are our age, even younger than us,'' said
Eric Brakken, a 21-year-old senior at Wisconsin. ``We're seeing a
lot of people who've never been involved, because this is such a
close issue for them.''
</P>
<P>
   But while today's protesters are employing phrases like Moral
Power, Solidarity, and The Principle of the Matter, they're not
carting unwilling administrators out of their offices, shoving the
finger in photographers' faces, or smoking pot in the president's
chair.
</P>
<P>
   There was a smattering of graffiti on the Georgetown campus the
weekend of the protest there. But for the most part, students sat
quietly, eating bagels while they did homework in the president's
office. When administrators asked if they might say a Mass
together, the students said, ``Sure.'' At Duke, students agreed to
let a chaperone stay with them during their occupation-sleepover in
President Nan Keohane's office, and agreed to an administration
request that they clean up after themselves. (They did that, too.)
Their version of protest music was love-happy Dave Matthews Band
songs blaring from a boombox.
</P>
<P>
   Budding activism hasn't made them abandon their academics. The
protesters include Truman and Rhodes scholars. Their numbers rose
and dwindled as they ran off to attend class or turn in papers.
</P>
<P>
   Hate the establishment? They wanted to work with it. And the
establishment was happy to go along.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm very, very proud of our students,'' said James A. Donahue,
dean of students at Georgetown. ``This is not just about their
self-interest, that's why the commitment and the passion is just
remarkable.''
</P>
<P>
   Students were not only more civil than past protesters, they
were more focused on accomplishing a goal _ and less on simply
making noise.
</P>
<P>
   Students say that reflects how they've learned from the mistakes
of the past.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the '60s, from what I've read anyway, there was a real
distrust of authority, but frankly, this is a business issue and
we've got some pretty damn smart people in the front office who can
work with us and help,'' Zwerdling said.
</P>
<P>
   The establishment, too, has changed. Many administrators were
among the longhairs, their sentences still laced with barnyard
epithets and ``cool.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We have a general sympathy and empathy with this as a way of
realizing social change,'' Donahue said. ``In the '60s you had a
generation of decision-makers and faculty who didn't have that
history. Now we're in the position of trying to help institutions
find responsible answers to these challenges.''
</P>
<P>
   Students and administrators at Duke and Georgetown settled the
protests by agreeing to revisit the code of conduct after a year's
trial period, and to push the company to make its factory locations
public if conditions don't improve. The students say they'll be
watching, and ready to strike again.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, at Wisconsin, often a more radical campus, students
were already upping the ante. Next up? A hunger strike.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-17-99 1320EST &QL; 
