<HEADLINE>
DARTMOUTH PLAN RELIES ON MYTH 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By EILEEN MCNAMARA  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Does anyone else remember the hoax perpetrated a few years back
by a group calling itself the Barbie Liberation Organization? It
bought up hundreds of talking GI Joe and Barbie dolls and then
switched the voice boxes before restocking the toy store shelves.
</P>
<P>
   The hilarious result? Buxom Barbies that bellowed: ``Vengeance
is mine!'' and camouflaged soldiers that fretted: ``Will we ever
have enough clothes?''
</P>
<P>
   I was reminded of that clever illustration of gender caricature
by news of Dartmouth College's stealth campaign to civilize its
frat boys by sending women to live among them.
</P>
<P>
   To his credit, Dartmouth president James Wright is trying to
solve some serious problems, from social isolation to alcohol
abuse, on the Hanover, N.H., campus. To his embarrassment, he is
banking on the transforming power of female virtue to do it.
</P>
<P>
   Times have changed more than he must realize since Dartmouth
admitted women in 1972. It's true more than 95 percent of corporate
executives are still men, that more than two-thirds of adults
living in poverty are still women. It's true more than 85 percent
of elected officials are still men, that more than 95 percent of
child care workers are still women.
</P>
<P>
   But women are gaining fast on men in unanticipated venues. Equal
opportunity too often means an equal chance to engage in
self-destructive behavior. Witness women's advancing rates of lung
cancer and heart disease.
</P>
<P>
   While Wright couched the changes to be instituted next fall in
terms of general concerns that ``single-sex organizations play far
too dominant a role in social life,'' it is clear that alcohol is
the heart of the problem at Dartmouth, as it is at most colleges
where the party scene revolves around Fraternity Row.
</P>
<P>
   How to bring unsupervised drinking by underage students under
control in unregulated fraternity houses is a major preoccupation
of administrators from MIT, where a fatal alcohol poisoning in 1997
forced the school to rexamine its student housing policies; to
Boston University, where an underage co-ed charged last fall that
she was raped after being served alcohol at a fraternity party.
</P>
<P>
   The 34 alcohol-related deaths estimated to have occurred on
American campuses last year only hint at the number of students
injured, assaulted or raped because of the consumption of too much
liquor. Last September, a study by the Harvard School of Public
Health reported that more than 42 percent of college students
surveyed in 1997 identified themselves as binge drinkers _ that's
five drinks at one time for a man, four for a woman. More than 52
percent said they drank expressly to get drunk.
</P>
<P>
   The number of students abusing alcohol is much higher among frat
members, says the author of the study, Dr. Henry Wechsler, adding
that members of sororities are catching up fast to their male
counterparts.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nationally, there is not that much difference in alcohol
consumption between sororities and fraternities on co-ed
campuses,'' says Wechsler. ``I wish I could say women are
different, but they binge drink, too.''
</P>
<P>
   So much for the myth of the inherent moral superiority of women.
</P>
<P>
   It has always been a double-edged sword. The Seven Sisters
schools were founded more than a century ago to educate women
turned away from colleges like Dartmouth because of notions about
female delicacy, including ``scientific'' evidence that
intellectual pursuits could cause permanent sterility in women.
</P>
<P>
   The suffragists tried to turn prevailing myths about women to
their advantage, arguing that granting women the vote would
``purify'' politics. Well, we've all seen how that's worked out.
</P>
<P>
   President Wright has his work cut out for him at Dartmouth,
where students canceled Winter Carnival parties last weekend to
protest his threat to the fraternity system. ``My sympathies are
with him,'' says Dr. Wechsler. ``There is no simple answer to this.
He should get credit for trying to do something.''
</P>
<P>
   If Dartmouth women do integrate the fraternities next fall, they
should take their cue not from their new frat brothers but from
their sisters at all-women colleges. There, Wechsler says, binge
drinking is far less frequent.
</P>
<P>
   At Wellesley, they know that when William Allen White advised
women ``to raise more hell and fewer dahlias,'' he did not have a
frat party in mind.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Eileen McNamara's e-mail address is mcnamara(at)globe.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
