<HEADLINE>
HERE'S TO ROBERT DUVALL, AN ACTOR, NOT A MOVIE STAR 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARTIN F. NOLAN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ With the approach of the Academy Awards, it is
time to root for Robert Duvall. No matter what the outcome, this is
a worthwhile investment, a bankable emotion. After his portrayal of
a Boston lawyer, Jerome Facher, stole ``A Civil Action'' from the
rest of an excellent cast, Duvall received another Oscar
nomination, his third for best supporting actor.
</P>
<P>
   He is an actor, not a movie star, a crucial difference. In a
lifetime of covering politics, I've met many stars who were
campaigning for or against some politician: Bob Hope, Jimmy
Stewart, Gregory Peck, Warren Beatty, Angie Dickinson and others.
</P>
<P>
   For conversation, it's useful to compliment a star on a lesser
work, as John F. Kennedy did when he met Norman Mailer. ``I've read
`The Deer Park,' '' JFK deadpanned to the novelist, ``and the
others.'' When I complimented Paul Newman on ``The Helen Morgan
Story,'' he raised an eyebrow, but took it well.
</P>
<P>
   Hey, Shirley MacLaine, you were great in ``Two Mules for Sister
Sarah.'' Her dazzlingly elfin smile showed she could be a good
sport about it. When I raved about his performance in ``Inside
Daisy Clover,'' Robert Redford grinned, kept the conversation
going, and eventually invited me to lunch. (With this churlish
gambit, ink-stained wretches fear no retaliation; few respondents
have the time or patience to research our multitudinous lesser
works.)
</P>
<P>
   Movie stars are instinctively polite to anyone with a press
card, but when I encountered Robert Duvall, I was on my own time
and my own nickel. He, too, was on vacation last year at a pleasant
spot far from Broadway or Hollywood. As he crossed the garden of
the hotel, his gait was unmistakable, evoking what Katharine
Hepburn said of John Wayne's ``light dancer's steps.''
</P>
<P>
   As Duvall approached, I stalled in a too-familiar wasteland
between tongue-tied and garrulous. Figuring that most artists savor
appreciation based on some knowledge, I blurted out the
compliments.
</P>
<P>
   Mr. Duvall, I loved every frame of ``The Apostle.'' You captured
the Southern Baptists I got to know when I pulled guard duty at the
US Army Chaplains School. I played football against them and
discussed scripture with them. You portrayed the uncomplicated
simplicity of Southern clergy, so different from today's media
portrait.
</P>
<P>
   Duvall appeared genuinely interested. ``Was that in the South,
sir?'' (Sir?) No, it was actually on a post in Long Island Sound.
It was surreal, protecting the choir practice of the padres with my
M-1 rifle against a flotilla of godless Bolsheviks bent on
interrupting ``Bringing in the Sheaves.''
</P>
<P>
   Duvall's eyes narrowed as though he were enduring a feckless
pitch for a lame screenplay. I returned to my principal mission.
</P>
<P>
   But of course, I loved many of your roles, from Boo Radley to
Frank Burns and Frank Hackett. Tom Hagen, of course, and Mack
Sledge, Bull Meechum, Colonel Kilgore, and Doctor Watson, Tom
Spellacy, and Lucky Ned Pepper.
</P>
<P>
   Remembering his roles rather than acknowledging his celebrity
was an offer he could not refuse. He said a fervent thank you and
we wished each other good day.
</P>
<P>
   He made it possible and easy to remember ``To Kill A
Mockingbird,'' ``MASH,'' ``Network,'' ``The Godfather,'' ``Tender
Mercies,'' ``The Great Santini,'' ``Apocalypse Now, ``The Seven
Percent Solution,'' ``True Confessions'' and ``True Grit.''
</P>
<P>
   He was the star in only two, winning the best-actor Oscar for
``Tender Mercies'' and a best-actor nomination for ``The Great
Santini.'' He has been in some turkeys, too. ``The Betsy'' and
``The Eagle Has Landed'' were awful, but Duvall's performances were
not.
</P>
<P>
   He's no matinee idol, but he had stage training in New York,
where his pals were Gene Hackman and Dustin Hoffman. His politics
and personality? Who cares? Jay Carr, a critic's critic, calls him
an American Alec Guinness, high and proper praise for Robert
Duvall, an actor's actor.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Martin F. Nolan is a Globe columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
