<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-REDSOX-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FRYE GETS BACK INTO THE FIRE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By GORDON EDES  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT MYERS, Fla. _ As the ball sailed over the left-field fence,
becoming as small as a snowflake against a cloudless sky, the
batting-practice slugger couldn't resist taking a shot at his
victim.
</P>
<P>
   ``You should be depressed,'' Jeff Frye taunted Joe Kerrigan, the
pitching coach who was muttering to himself on the mound. ``I've
been on a couch for 12 months, and I take you deep.''
</P>
<P>
   To borrow Pedro Martinez's favorite phrase, Jeff Frye is back in
the house, nearly a full year after his left knee disintegrated
during a rundown drill in camp. He arrived here more than a week
ago, well ahead of Tuesday's reporting date for position players,
and there was no mistaking his pleasure as he took his swings with
catcher Scott Hatteberg, another early arrival.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I can't do what I did before,'' said Frye, ``I won't be the
second baseman. That's why I came early, to be ready when the rest
of the guys get here.''
</P>
<P>
   Even if he is fully recovered from surgery that left him with a
matching set of repaired anterior cruciate ligaments, one in each
knee, Frye admits he'll be concerned that the signing of
high-priced Jose Offerman means he may be dealt before the season.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hope I'm here, but yeah, I have doubts,'' said Frye, who
made a successful comeback from surgery on his right knee six years
ago, but will be 33 on Aug. 31.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've heard a lot of rumors that they're shopping me around.
Nobody's stupid enough to make a deal when there are question marks
about a guy's health, but we'll find out pretty early how things
are going to work out.''
</P>
<P>
   Frye was wearing shorts and a T-shirt left over from his 1996
collection. On the back, it read: ``Mo gets a $50,000 bonus and
didn't bring us any T-shirts back. So we bought our own. Thanks for
nothing.''
</P>
<P>
   That was a reference to the bonus Mo Vaughn received after
winning the MVP award in 1995. Frye thought of designing a new
model.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was thinking of making one that said `B.C./A.M.,' '' Frye
said. `` `Before Christ and After Mo,' but I didn't want anybody to
take it wrong.''
</P>
<P>
   When Frye came to camp last February, there could not have been
more things right in his universe. Coming off his best season in
the big leagues, one in which he batted .312 and appeared in a
career-high 127 games, Frye had been rewarded with a three-year, $7
million contract. A favorite of manager Jimy Williams, who loved
Frye's fearlessness, he figured to be the team's leadoff man.
</P>
<P>
   ``I felt like I was at a point where my career was taking off,''
Frye said. ``Instead, I wound up sitting at home.''
</P>
<P>
   While attempting to tag Darren Bragg between third and home
during a routine drill, Frye's spikes caught and his left knee
buckled, making a sound that turned his heart to dust. Frye had
torn not only the ACL but also some cartilage, sending the Sox on a
season-long scramble for a second baseman.
</P>
<P>
   Four players started games at second last season _ Mike
Benjamin, Mark Lemke, Donnie Sadler, and Lou Merloni. Frye,
meanwhile, returned home to Texas, rehabilitated relentlessly, and
watched every game he could on TV, while his team went to the
playoffs without him.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was tough,'' he said. ``I wanted so much to be a part of
it. Not taking away anything from anybody who played second _
Sadler did a great job, so did Merloni, and Benjamin did an
unbelievable job _ but I kept feeling like the guy who was supposed
to be there.''
</P>
<P>
   Frye remained in touch with his teammates, appearing in the
visitors' clubhouse on both Red Sox visits to Arlington, Texas, and
coming to Boston for surgery to repair torn ligaments in his right
thumb, which he had jammed while sliding on the next-to-last day of
last season. The severity of the injury went undetected at the
time.
</P>
<P>
   ``I came to spring training and thought it was all right,'' Frye
said. ``I could play with it. But later, my physical therapist
noticed how weak it was, and that's when we discovered the ligament
was torn.''
</P>
<P>
   Even though he needed crutches for two weeks, Frye was on an
exercise bike the day after his knee surgery, which was done by
Richard Steadman, doctor for the US Olympic ski team. Frye wore a
brace for a couple of months and says he has been running and
jogging for the last several months. He has been hitting for the
last few weeks.
</P>
<P>
   He was surprised at first to hear last December that the Sox had
signed Offerman.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody assumed, including me, that we were going to sign
another first baseman,'' Frye said, ``and he's been pretty much a
second baseman.
</P>
<P>
   ``But I think the Red Sox, after losing Mo, felt like they had
to get somebody, so they got a guy who was coming off a great
season who they think can help the team win.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've got no animosity toward him. I'm happy he got $26
million.''
</P>
<P>
   Frye said he talked to Williams several times this winter, and
was told by the manager that he is the second baseman coming into
camp. The manager's word is good enough for him.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's honest with you,'' Frye said.
</P>
<P>
   But he also knows that unless Offerman winds up at first base, a
position he played part-time just one season in Kansas City, Frye
could be odd man out. There are two reasons, he said, that he won't
be kept in a Benjamin-type utility role. He had a terrible time
playing third base as a fill-in in '97, and he's overmatched at
short as well.
</P>
<P>
   ``Plus, they're not going to pay me what they're paying me to be
a part-time player.''
</P>
<P>
   Frye has spent most of his career uncertain whether he had a
job, both in Texas and Boston. As recently as '97, he was forced to
the bench when Nomar Garciaparra arrived and John Valentin moved to
second, until Tim Naehring's elbow injury forced another
reshuffling. He thought his suspenseful springs had ended a year
ago, but here he is again, feet planted on ever-shifting sand.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hope on April 5 I'll be playing second base for the Red Sox,
playing for Jimy,'' Frye said. ``I can't think of anybody I'd
rather play for. But we'll just have to see.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
