<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-17 13:30 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8616 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-WOM-MILLER-BOS &LR;      02-17 1348
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WOM-MILLER-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A GOLD MEDAL _ AND A BABY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BARBARA HUEBNER  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WHITE LAKE TOWNSHIP, Mich. _ Not long after Lisa Brown-Miller
returned home from Nagano with her Olympic gold medal last winter,
she found a message on her answering machine from coach Ben Smith.
There was a women's ice hockey camp for younger players coming up
in the summer. Would she like to help out?
</P>
<P>
   Brown-Miller hemmed. Hawed. Talked it over with her husband,
John. Called Smith back, only to get his machine. There's sort of a
circumstance, she said. We'll talk.
</P>
<P>
   When they did, she told him she was sorry but she couldn't
accept his offer. Let me put it this way, she explained, back in
Nagano, ``we're lucky we didn't get called for too many players on
the ice.''
</P>
<P>
   Pregnant. The veteran forward who had talked longingly before
the Games of retiring immediately afterward to settle down, spend
more time with John, think about starting a family, was _ much to
her surprise _ already six weeks pregnant when she stood at center
ice one year ago to receive her gold medal.
</P>
<P>
   ``When we found out, I'm like wh . . . wh . . . what?''
Brown-Miller said. ``He's going to have bragging rights when he
goes to preschool.''
</P>
<P>
   Since the US women's ice hockey team defeated Canada, 3-1,
exactly one year ago today (Feb. 17, 1998), the lives of all 20
players have changed in ways they could only have imagined _ and,
often, in ways they couldn't. They've seen their faces on
supermarket cereal shelves, and watched tapes of themselves doing
the Top 10 List with David Letterman. The team's captain, Cammi
Granato, is a radio commentator for the Los Angeles Kings. Katie
King and Tricia Dunn have co-authored a book. Everyone, from Chris
Bailey to Sandra Whyte, were greeted back home as heroes.
</P>
<P>
   But it's doubtful anyone's life has changed more than that of
Brown-Miller, whose days are filled with the obligations brought
not by a medal, but by a baby born on Aug. 25, three weeks early
and even more beautiful than a balletic Granato breakaway.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had no idea what life would be like after, but I wouldn't
want it to be any different,'' said Brown-Miller one recent
afternoon, feeding Alex his sweet potatoes and barley cereal in the
kitchen of a new home virtually within cooing distance of all his
grandparents. ``It's like a complete 180. I'm going in the totally
opposite direction. He's my complete focus now. When we won the
gold medal, I couldn't think of any better feeling in the world,
and then Alex was born.''
</P>
<P>
   Now 32, Brown-Miller was the oldest player on the US squad that
went to Nagano, and the only one who was married. A member of the
national team since its inception in 1990, Brown-Miller saw 1998 _
in which the sport of women's ice hockey made its Olympic debut _
as her first, last, and only chance, and resigned in the summer of
1996 as Princeton's hockey coach to train full-time.
</P>
<P>
   While Smith says ``there wouldn't have been any sense fielding a
team if she wasn't on it,'' the 5-foot, 1-inch Brown-Miller doubted
up until the last minute that she would survive the final cut. On
the mid-December night in Lake Placid when Smith was to announce
the Olympic roster, Brown-Miller had arranged for John to be ready
to get her out of town immediately after the meeting. ``When my
name isn't read off, I don't want to be around here,'' she said she
told him. ``I was convinced I was not going to be on that team.''
</P>
<P>
   Brown-Miller played in all six games in Nagano, scoring a goal
and an assist. She also took some powerful hits, including a
drilling by Canada's Karen Nystrom with just over a minute to go in
the final game that sent her slamming to the ice.
</P>
<P>
   ``You look back on that and you think, oh my god, little Alex
got rocked,'' said Brown-Miller, acknowledging that it's just as
well she didn't know she was pregnant.
</P>
<P>
   But after all the sacrifices, the training, the time away from
her automotive-engineer husband, she thinks she would have played
even if she had known, given her doctor's OK. ``It would have been
tough,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Although Brown-Miller's situation is unusual, it is not a first.
In the 1996 Olympics, Michele Granger pitched the first 5 1/3
innings of the gold-medal softball game while two months pregnant,
while kayaker DeAnne Hemmens was also expecting. But while the
contact in ice hockey adds an extra dimension, Brown-Miller was not
on especially-thin ice in playing during the early stages of
pregnancy.
</P>
<P>
   ``Certainly early on, I don't think there would be too much
danger,'' said Dr. Sandra Glasson, who served as the team's
physician. ``At that stage, the fetus is well-protected in the
uterus.'' And Brown-Miller's fitness and skill level played in her
favor. ``Basically what we tell patients is to continue the
activities that you have been participating in all along. If you've
been running two or three miles a day, it's OK to run two or three
miles a day, but it's not a good idea to take up running if your
body was not accustomed to it when you became pregnant. Most of us
couldn't go out there and play even a portion of a hockey game, but
her body was used to it.'' (Brown-Miller told the story that upon
learning she was pregnant, she asked her doctor if she could still
work out. ``You just played hockey in the Olympics,'' the physician
replied. ``Feel free.'')
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, asked if knowing of the pregnancy would have made
him nervous, Smith gasped: ``Oh, god, yeah. As if we had a lot of
other easy decisions to make.'' Karyn Bye, for years her roommate,
agreed. ``Brownie is such a physical and intense player, and a
small player, she can get banged around a little bit,'' said Bye,
the assistant captain. ``Overall, I think it was a good thing none
of us knew, in the best interests of the entire team.''
</P>
<P>
   But once they did find out? ``I was thrilled,'' Smith said. ``I
was pretty choked up, to tell you the truth.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, her teammates sprung into action. A ceremony in
Colorado Springs brought the team together; a baby shower followed.
You name it, if it was tiny and had anything to do with hockey or
the Olympics, Alex got it either then or after he was born.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think Brownie looks at all of us as Alex having 19 aunts,''
said Bye.
</P>
<P>
   ``We haven't had to buy a lot of clothes,'' said Brown-Miller's
husband, John, of those 19 aunts. But more important, with the team
now scattered, ``Alex is sort of a conduit to keep in touch. Lisa
talks to them a lot. It's good for Lisa, good for us, good for
Alex.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   For now, Brown-Miller had decided to concentrate on home and
motherhood. Having moved from an apartment into a new three-bedroom
contemporary house late last fall (``It's the one with no grass,''
said Brown-Miller in giving directions), she still has furniture to
buy and boxes of Olympic memorabilia to unpack. Although she
remains on the board of directors at USA Hockey, she recently
turned down an offer to start up and coach a women's Division I
hockey program at nearby Wayne State University in Detroit.
</P>
<P>
   ``At first I was excited about the challenge,'' she said, but
quickly nodded toward the baby. ``He's only five months old. We
think all the time I spend with him right now is real important.''
As for competition, she occasionally plays with a women's senior A
team based about an hour away, but mostly considers herself ``on
sabbatical. When I said I was ready to retire, I was ready to
retire. There are certain things I miss: I miss being around my
friends, I miss the competitive side of things. I'm sure (that as
Alex gets older) that in some way, shape or form I'll be involved
in women's hockey.''
</P>
<P>
   But for now her favorite workout is trying to coax a smile from
Alex. It's one that doesn't take much effort.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's kind of sad to see '98 go, because it's been so good,''
said the woman described by Smith as ``a great player, a great
coach and an all-world mom.''
</P>
<P>
   ``How,'' asked Brown-Miller, ``do you top it?''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-17-99 1330EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
