<DOCNO> NYT19990217.0157 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-17 13:31 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8617 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SHAUGHNESSY-COLUMN-BO     02-17 1059
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SHAUGHNESSY-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A LOW BLOW ON MARCIANO 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAN SHAUGHNESSY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The folks at ESPN are smart. They know how to generate barroom
arguments. It's easy. Just create a ``best ever'' list and watch
the spittle fly.
</P>
<P>
   So now we have ESPN's top 100 athletes of the 20th century.
Numbers 51-100 have been revealed and the countdown from 50 to 1 is
a weekly television event featuring one of the greats of the
century. Already we've revisited the lives and times of Chris Evert
(No. 50), O.J. Simpson (49), Pete Sampras (48), and Edwin Moses
(47), with Eric Heiden (46) coming Friday. No doubt we'll get to a
top 10 that includes Babe Ruth, Muhammad Ali, and Michael Jordan.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, folks in Brockton, Mass. are wondering how homeboy
Rocky Marciano _ the one and only undefeated heavyweight champ in
history _ came in at No. 51, missing the cut for the weekly
festival accorded members of the top 50.
</P>
<P>
   Peter Marciano, Rocky's 32-year-old nephew, says, ``When you
talk about great athletes in this country in the 20th century,
Rocky has to be somewhere in the top 25. He represents everything
good about athletes _ on and off the field. I think he deserves a
place in there. There's only a few records that have lasted and
Rocky's record continues to flourish.''
</P>
<P>
   At age 45, Rocky Marciano died in a plane crash in Iowa 30 years
ago. But he's still a huge presence in Brockton, where scores of
relatives (there's a Marciano or a Colombo on just about every New
England coaching or playing roster) still live. The Rock also lives
in the minds of those who have little and fight for a better life.
He lives every time the mighty Brockton Boxers take to the gridiron
at Rocky Marciano Stadium. And he lives every time time you put
Rocky or Rocky II, III, or IV in your VCR.
</P>
<P>
   Forget Rocky Balboa. Marciano was the real thing. The true
Rocky.
</P>
<P>
   He was born Rocco Marchegiano, the oldest of six children of
Pasqualena and Pierino Marchegiano. He was a high school catcher
and linebacker, and when he was 15 he intercepted a pass and ran it
back 67 yards for a touchdown. After school he was a coal-truck
loader, a candy mixer, a brush cutter, and a shoe factory worker
before he was drafted into the army. At Fort Lewis in Washington
state, he tried boxing for the first time.
</P>
<P>
   He fought under the name of Rocky Mack in his first pro bout in
Holyoke, Mass. in 1947. The Chicago Cubs gave him a baseball tryout
that spring, but he couldn't throw or run well enough and returned
to the ring. He was a serious contender by 1951 and knocked out
37-year-old Joe Louis in New York on Oct. 26, 1951. In September of
'52, he knocked out Jersey Joe Walcott in Philadelphia to win the
heavyweight championship. He defended his title only six times and
retired in 1955 after knocking out Archie Moore.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was one of my heroes,'' says Massachusetts Auditor Joe
DeNucci, who had 86 professional fights and was once ranked fifth
among middleweights. ``I still remember the night I boxed Joey
Giardello at the Boston Garden in December of '61. I was 21 years
old and Rocky was sitting in the front row with my father. He
looked like an ordinary working guy, wearing boots and a winter
jacket. Giardello and I boxed to a draw and I still remember Rocky
cheering me on and saying I got robbed.
</P>
<P>
   ``I still remember being a kid watching him on closed circuit TV
at the Paramount Theater in (a Boston suburb). I saw when he
knocked out Joe Walcott for the heavyweight championship of the
world. There's no question he has to rank certainly in the top 50.
He never lost a fight. How can you not be in the top 50? I don't
get it. I don't know how they meausre issues of greatness.''
</P>
<P>
   Marciano is more than a local legend. In a sport populated by
men who always hang around too long, Rocky knew when it was time to
stop. Can we think of any other boxer who left on top? Marciano is
boxing's equivalent of Sandy Koufax, Jim Brown, and Michael Jordan.
</P>
<P>
   So how can ESPN rank him behind Eric Heiden? Edwin Moses? Chris
Evert?
</P>
<P>
   All of the above were fine performers, but Marciano would seem
to belong ahead of them _ closer to Ali and Louis in the top half
of the all-time 100.
</P>
<P>
   ESPN's selection process was thorough. A panel of 48
journalists, historians, observers, and administrators cast votes.
Panelists included the likes of Roone Arledge, Chris Berman, Bob
Costas, Harry Edwards, Curt Gowdy, Bryant Gumbel, David Halberstam,
Lesley Visser, George Will, and the Globe's Bob Ryan.
</P>
<P>
   Ryan is a naysayer when it comes to Rocky:
</P>
<P>
   ``The three most famous fights of his career were against
37-year-old Joe Louis, Walcott, who was about that old, and Archie
Moore, who was over 40. The rest of those guys he fought were
ham-and-eggers. Rocky's a convenient local myth and it's as simple
as that. We voted for 50 people and it never occurred to me to vote
for Rocky. It never entered my mind.''
</P>
<P>
   Peter Marciano, who played in the 1986 Rose Bowl for Iowa and
now works for the Massachusetts lottery, says, ``It's lousy. The
people of Brockton still hold Rocky so dear to them. It's almost an
embarrassment to the city. They take it personally.''
</P>
<P>
   Marciano may have been dissed by ESPN, but he's going to be on a
US postage stamp this summer. And his name will come up again every
time a heavyweight champ tastes his first defeat.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like with Roger Maris,'' says Peter Marciano. ``People
forgot about how great he was until last summer when his record was
challenged. You might go years without hearing Rocky's name. Then
when someone like Larry Holmes goes for his record, Rocky comes
back.
</P>
<P>
   ``I went to the University of Iowa. Rocky was killed in Iowa. I
remember when Holmes got to 48-0 all my college buddies were
ragging on me, telling me Rocky's record was going down. At that
same time, people there invited me to Newton, Iowa, where Rocky's
plane crashed. I saw the one big oak tree in the cornfield and I
knelt down and said a prayer. I prayed that his record would stand
forever. Holmes lost the fight that night. Rocky answered my
prayer.''
</P>
<P>
   If Rocky is indeed Up There jabbing in the big ring in the sky,
you know he must be asking himself one question.
</P>
<P>
   Eric Heiden?
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Dan Shaughnessy is a Globe columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
