<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WOM-NOTEBOOK-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TEAMS SET SIGHTS ON TOURNEY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JUDY VAN HANDLE  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   With the regular season evaporating into its final few games and
the start of conference tournaments only a few days away, less than
three weeks remain until the field for the NCAA women's basketball
tournament is announced.
</P>
<P>
   Selection Sunday is March 7, when 64 teams will learn where
they're seeded and who they'll be playing as the always-emotional
chase for a national title begins to take shape.
</P>
<P>
   How many New England teams shape up as NCAA worthy? While the
high of six teams probably won't be reached, it's a good bet that
the following will be extending their seasons:
</P>
<P>
   Connecticut (21-4): From the time practice began in October, the
Huskies were a shoo-in to make their 11th consecutive NCAA
appearance. The path to the postseason hasn't been as smooth as in
the past _ the Huskies may not even win their sixth straight Big
East postseason title, given that tournament host Rutgers is tied
for first with UConn and lost by only a point in their only
regular-season meeting. Even so, the Huskies' reality is different
than that of any other New England team. One question their fans
want answered: will their two-year Final Four drought end?
</P>
<P>
   Boston College (18-6): Emphatic victories over Notre Dame and
UConn helped guarantee the Eagles their first appearance in the
tourney, negating a third straight midseason slump. At any rate,
losing to UConn, Rutgers, and Notre Dame is far less injurious than
being defeated by Syracuse, Providence, and Villanova. Finishing
the regular season with two wins will give BC the 20 victories that
coach Cathy Inglese so covets; coupling that with a decent showing
in the Big East tourney would seem to ensure at least a seventh or
eighth seed.
</P>
<P>
   Maine (18-5): The Black Bears did nothing this season if not
show that theirs was more than a one-woman team. If America East
opponents thought the graduation of All-American Cindy Blodgett was
going to open doors for them, a three-headed offensive attack
slammed it shut. Methuen's Jamie Cassidy (23.3 points per game),
Medford's Kristen McCormick (45.9 3-point percentage), and Amy
Vachon (8.2 assists per game) all rank among the nation's top 10 in
their categories as the Black Bears try for a fifth consecutive
conference title (and automatic bid).
</P>
<P>
   Other America East contenders include New Hampshire, which
counts on Orsi Farkas to lead it to a postseason surprise, as does
Vermont with Karalyn Church. Northeastern has its best team in
years, led by Tesha Tinsley and Betsy Palacek, and is certainly
capable of repeating its regular-season upset of Maine.
</P>
<P>
   Holy Cross (18-7): Amy O'Brien is in the last few weeks of a
wonderful four years with the Crusaders, and the school's all-time
leading scorer would like nothing better than to cap her career
with a third Patriot League championship and subsequent NCAA berth.
The Crusaders have lost just one league game, so it would take a
monumental effort to deny them a second straight bid and sixth
overall (second only to UConn among New England schools).
</P>
<P>
   In the Ivy League, which does not conduct a postseason tourney,
Dartmouth is a game behind first-place Princeton with five games
left and plays the Tigers this weekend. Harvard and Brown also are
still in the running but need help from other teams.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
A thousand welcomes
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Northeast-10 Conference's 1,000-point club welcomed two more
members last Saturday: Assumption's Stacy Mattioli, a junior from
Sturbridge, and Stonehill senior Becky Barrett of Needham each
reached the milestone. For Barrett, the feat was even more
impressive since she's the NE-10's reigning defensive player of the
year . . . Jillian Danker, one of New England's most highly
sought-after players as a senior at Minnechaug Regional in
Wilbraham last year, led Vanderbilt with 15 points in a Feb. 7 loss
to No. 1 Tennessee. Danker, a 6-foot-1-inch guard/forward, is
averaging 4.5 points per game as one of the Commodores' top
reserves . . . UConn has scored 100 or more points in 12 games,
three shy of Long Beach State's 1987 record . . . If Massachusetts
wins one of its final two regular-season games, it will ensure a
fifth straight .500 or better season under Joanie O'Brien. It's
worth nothing that, three years before O'Brien took the job, UMass
was 0-27 . . . The latest strange polling twist: Virginia Tech has
the nation's sixth-best ratings power index, a 23-1 record, and is
ranked 10th. Rutgers (eighth in RPI), Duke (ninth), and Old
Dominion (10th) all are deemed better teams by the AP voters . . .
Coaches have been known to make some peculiar promises if their
team achieves certain goals, but it's doubtful any can rival these:
If No. 20 Santa Barbara makes the Sweet 16, coach Mark French says
he'll go sky-diving. And should the Gauchos go further, assistant
Cori Close has agreed to go on ``The Dating Game.''
</P>
</TEXT>
