<SLUG> BC-RETIREMENT-CAMPUS-2 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE NEW SCHOOL OF RETIREMENT 
</HEADLINE>
 TAKES-ART-BOS  
 (ART ADV.: A photo is being sent to NYTNS clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchases by calling 212-556-4204 or -1927.)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By WILLIAM A. DAVIS  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HANOVER, N.H. _ It's a sunny and brisk winter day, and Dartmouth
College students by the dozens are hurrying across the town green
on their way to classes.
</P>
<P>
   And keeping right up with them is Betty Tuttle, 81, who is still
working on her learning curve. ``We have so many advantages because
of Dartmouth,'' says Tuttle. ``It's like a Utopian kingdom here.''
</P>
<P>
   A retired librarian, Tuttle is among the growing number of older
people who, instead of moving to a Sun Belt ``leisure village''
built around a golf course, have opted for retirement communities
built close to major colleges and universities such as Dartmouth.
</P>
<P>
   In such communities, residents are able to lead stimulating,
active lives largely based on taking advantage of opportunities on
campus, from auditing classes and lectures to attending concerts
and sporting events. At Dartmouth, such options extend outdoors and
include skiing at the college-owned downhill area or on a superb
network of cross-country trails, as well as participating in
organized hikes, nature walks, and canoe trips.
</P>
<P>
   Formerly of Rockport, ``Bee Gee'' Tuttle and her husband,
Irving, a Dartmouth alumnus, are among the 370 residents of Kendal
at Hanover, a retirement community situated two miles from the
Dartmouth campus and linked to it by shuttle bus. This is not the
kind of retirement community where rocking on the veranda is the
most exciting option _ or even a probable one.
</P>
<P>
   The residents (who range in age from their mid-60s to their
mid-90s) tend to be a high-powered lot, including about 40 retired
professors, two former college presidents, doctors, lawyers,
Fortune 500 executives, a leading yacht designer, and a former
chairman of the New York Stock Exchange. In most cases, they bring
to retirement the same determination to excel that they did to
their careers.
</P>
<P>
   ``I love the combination of being able to enjoy the beauty of
the outdoors and also go to wonderful concerts, exhibitions, and
programs at the college,'' says Tuttle.
</P>
<P>
   Tuttle recently attended a Dartmouth function that showed the
advantages of being where she is. Called ``A Feast of Song,'' it
was a lavish 17th-century-style banquet at which costumed Dartmouth
students served the meal, played baroque music, and put on period
skits. ``Where else but someplace like this would I get a chance to
go to something like that?'' she asks.
</P>
<P>
   There are more than 100 campus-oriented retirement communities
around the country, including several in Massachusetts, with dozens
more in the planning or discussion stages.
</P>
<P>
   Reed's Landing is on the campus of Springfield College and was a
joint venture of the college and a local hospital group, Bay State
Health Systems. Loomis House in Holyoke and Loomis Village in South
Hadley are close to Mount Holyoke College and a short ride from the
rest of the Five College Area. Applewood in Amherst is directly
across from Hampshire College and has a stop on the free bus route
that serves the five schools.
</P>
<P>
   ``The presence of the colleges was a major consideration in
placing the community here,'' says Applewood director Robert
Woolrich. ``There are tremendous learning opportunities.'' Tuttle
believes that the stimulation retirees find in Hanover is
rejuvenating. ``People seem to get younger here,'' she says. ``I
was cross-country skiing not long ago and a 90-year-old woman from
Kendal came up and passed me. And my 96-year-old neighbor has just
started rereading `War and Peace,' but this time she's doing it in
Italian.''
</P>
<P>
   Communities such as Kendal attract retirees who are more
concerned with expanding their mental horizons than in improving
their tan or golf swing, says James Armstrong, former president of
Middlebury College. ``There is a vigorous quality about life here
that helps us maintain our health, and I don't feel the least bit
old,'' says the 79-year-old Armstrong.
</P>
<P>
   Armstrong has a daily routine that, he says, leaves little time
for boredom. A typical day includes a couple of hours working at
his desk, followed by exercise such as tennis or cross-country
skiing. In the afternoon he usually participates in committee work
and then has cocktails with friends before dinner. The after-dinner
program often includes attending a class or an event at the
retirement community or on the Dartmouth campus.
</P>
<P>
   Dartmouth College does not have a direct tie to Kendal, but
according to John Hennessey, chairman of the retirement community's
board of trustees and former dean of the college's Amos Tuck School
of Business Administration, ``There has always been a bond between
us.'' Professors often allow Kendal residents, many of them
Dartmouth alumni, to audit courses. And residents avidly
participate in an expansive adult-learning program offered through
the town.
</P>
<P>
   Occupying a 65-acre site, a former farm at a bend in the
Connecticut River, Kendal looks more like an upscale condominium
complex than the popular image of a retirement community. Most of
the residents are independent and live in their own apartments. But
Kendal also is a ``continuing care'' community and has an
assisted-living program and a nursing unit providing skilled care
to residents who are infirm, bedridden, or have cognitive
disabilities. Amenities include three restaurants, a health clinic,
a beauty parlor, a bank, hobby workshops, a gift shop, meeting
rooms, a 7,000-volume library, an exercise room, and a large heated
lap pool.
</P>
<P>
   Although Kendal is considered moderately priced for a community
of its type, all this doesn't come cheap. Entry fees, nonrefundable
after a trial period, range from $80,962 to $287,864, depending on
the size of a unit and whether a single person or a couple occupy
it. Monthly fees, which include one meal a day, run from $1,539 to
$3,604.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MORE &LR;  &QC;
</P>
</TEXT>
