<SLUG> BC-CREPES-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MAKING CREPES DOESN'T HAVE TO BE TRYING 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By RUTH FANTASIA  
 c.1998 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   With all the ado about ``wraps'' these days, you'd think
enveloping food in a pancake was something new. It's not.
</P>
<P>
   Remember crepes? Those light, feathery French pancakes that used
to appear on fancy restaurant menus in the '60s. They were filled
with cheeses, fruit, seafood and chicken. They were drenched in
newburg sauce, cheese sauce or spirits. And they were a pain to
make. Not anymore.
</P>
<P>
   Technological advances such as nonstick saute pans that really
don't stick have made crepe cooking easier. And instant-blending
flour means you can whip out a batch of crepes in half the time it
used to take. Another reason to make crepes: They freeze perfectly
so you can pull them out and heat them up whenever you need a quick
appetizer, entree or dessert.
</P>
<P>
   There are, generally, two types of crepes: sweet and savory. And
about all the two kinds have in common is the method for making
them. Sweet crepes can contain sugar in the batter, but they don't
have to. They're usually made from white flour and cooked in
clarified butter or an unflavored oil such as corn. Dessert crepes
are filled with sweet cheeses, chocolate, fruit and other things
that make sugar-lovers swoon.
</P>
<P>
   Savory crepes, on the other hand, can be made with buckwheat or
whole wheat flours, in addition to white flour. They can be cooked
in olive oil and filled with meats, sharp cheeses, spices and
topped with gravies and sauces. Some chefs are even adding
vegetables or vegetable puree to the crepe batter. A technique
that's reminiscent of those green (spinach) or red (pepper)
tortillas.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can find a crepe recipe in any good French cookbook,''
says Sophie Parker, owner of Chez Sophie in Malta, N.Y., ``but be
sure to make the dough and let it rest for an hour or two,
sometimes even overnight.''
</P>
<P>
   Crepe batters need a good rest to help the flour fully dissolve
into the liquid. However, if you use an instant-blending flour
(like those sold for making gravy) you can cut the resting time
down from at least an hour to 10 minutes, according to ``The Way to
Cook,'' by Julia Child (Knopf, 1989).
</P>
<P>
   Another key to making crepes is the amount of oil or butter in
the pan, Parker says.
</P>
<P>
   ``Oil the pan very lightly,'' Parker says. ``Take a clean piece
of paper towel and rub the oil on the pan. You don't want to pour
it in and have a pool.''
</P>
<P>
   When Parker makes crepes for special occasions, she uses corn
oil. ``It doesn't have any taste and it's very light,'' she says.
</P>
<P>
   Since the crepe batter must coat the bottom of the pan quickly,
the most important thing to remember is to keep the pan at the
proper temperature, Parker says.
</P>
<P>
   ``If it's too hot, the batter will dry out too quickly and not
coat the pan.''
</P>
<P>
   Parker recommends cooking crepes over a medium flame. Another
trick, especially when using an electric stove, is to lift the pan
off the heat when you pour in the batter then swirl the batter
around the bottom of the pan.
</P>
<P>
   Cook the crepe until the top is set and the bottom is lightly
browned. Then, turn it for a few seconds and slide it off onto a
plate. Accomplished crepe makers simply flip the crepe in the pan
without a spatula.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is superstition in France,'' says Parker, who grew up in
Northern France, ``that on Mardi Gras, if you can flip a crepe with
one hand while you hold a coin behind your back with the other
hand, you'll have money the rest of the year. But you can't use any
utensils.''
</P>
<P>
   As for what you fill them or top them with, that's up to you.
</P>
<P>
   Or, you don't even have to bother.
</P>
<P>
   ``I like them just sprinkled with sugar and rolled up like a
cigar,'' Parker says. ``The contrast between the hard sugar and the
soft crepe is delicious.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
