<SLUG> BC-MAGAZINE-REVIEW-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
POLITICS WITH BRAINS, BODY; BRIGHT `FUTURAMA' 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DON AUCOIN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Strange but true: John F. Kennedy Jr., having lived the most
atypical life imaginable, may actually be more in touch with the
thinking of regular folks than your average Beltway pundit is.
</P>
<P>
   This conviction emerges from a reading of Abigail Pogrebin's
profile of the scion of Camelot-turned-magazine editor in the March
issue of Brill's Content, along with an interview of Kennedy by
Pogrebin and the relentless Steven Brill.
</P>
<P>
   Washington insiders have either yawned or sneered at George ever
since Kennedy launched it four years ago as a ``lifestyle magazine
grounded in politics,'' and Pogrebin reports that they continue to
do so. But Pogrebin also takes the extra, revealing step of talking
to actual readers of George, and they describe it as a magazine
that puts politics in its proper place: comfortably on the
periphery of their lives, not at the center of the universe.
</P>
<P>
   In creating George along those lines, it could be argued that
Kennedy has a firmer grip on the public pulse than most pundits do.
We have, as Kennedy notes, entered a ``postpartisan'' and
nonideological age, opening up plenty of room for George's
evenhanded approach. Sure, George (circ. 420,000) goes overboard on
the show-biz stuff and gives too many celebrity airheads a
platform, but it's a better mag than its detractors claim. It
succeeds because it recognizes how completely the boundaries
between pop culture and politics have blurred, and how utterly the
traditional, eat-your-peas approach to political journalism turns
off young readers.
</P>
<P>
   Kennedy says George is aimed at people who want to ``talk about
politics with the same sort of informed casualness that they might
talk about the new movie coming out, or a new record, or the NBA.''
</P>
<P>
   That might not be the democratic ideal, but it sure describes a
lot of people I know. So why shouldn't George's personality-driven
journalism be one avenue into public affairs for apolitical Gen
Xers and their younger siblings of Generation Y? In any case, it's
hard to argue with either half of this Kennedy assertion: ``There
were a lot of people that would have loved to see this be a farce,
and it hasn't been.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Speaking of farces: It's not easy to express dismay at the
election of Jesse (The Body) Ventura as governor of Minnesota
without coming off like a stuffed shirt, but Dennis Cass manages it
splendidly in this month's Harper's.
</P>
<P>
   Cass, a Minnesotan, followed the former pro wrestler's campaign
of ``celebrity, inexperience and issue-avoidance'' and was present
at Ventura's election-night party, where frat boys, bikers, and
punk-rockers gathered to celebrate the triumph of a candidate
``whose campaign refrain was `I don't know.' ''
</P>
<P>
   In Cass's view, Ventura's victory represents _ among other
disquieting things _ the further erosion of an already dubious
tradition: the election of former entertainers to political office.
From Ronald Reagan and Clint Eastwood _ ``the top of the food
chain'' _ the trend has moved to encompass Sonny Bono and former
``Love Boat'' actor Fred Grandy. Now a major state has a governor
best known for ``prancing around in shiny panties and a feather
boa'' as one of the designated villains of wrestling.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ventura is not only television, he's Saturday morning
television,'' laments Cass. ``He's cable, he's pay-per-view, he's
direct-to-video. . . . Minnesota is about to become like Italy,
where porn stars win parliamentary seats, and I wonder what is
next, whether somewhere in America there is a birthday-party
magician destined to be president.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   One of these days, it will finally be universally acknowledged
that ``The Simpsons,'' rather than ``Seinfeld,'' has been the best
TV show of the 1990s.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Simpsons'' ' creator Matt Groening does not pound that
drum during an interview in the new issue of Wired magazine, but he
does say enough about his upcoming midseason show for Fox,
``Futurama,'' to whet the appetite of anyone who has ever fallen
off the couch laughing at Homer, Marge, Bart, and Lisa.
</P>
<P>
   ``Futurama'' is set in the year 3000, and it features, in the
words of Wired executive editor Kevin Kelly, ``celebrity talking
heads in jars, narcotic soft drinks, while-you-sleep advertising,
one-eyed she aliens, jet-powered scooters, beer-drinking robots,
and a corrupt megacorporation run by a despotic mom.'' The robot
looks especially promising, a cyborg screw-up to rival Homer
Simpson.
</P>
<P>
   With mordant wit, Groening delivers his opinions on pop culture,
advertising, cartooning, merchandising spinoffs, the Web sites
devoted to Simpsonia, the appropriations of his characters' images
by groups ranging from vegetarians to neo-Nazi skinheads, and why
he retains his belief that the one key thing to remember at all
times is that ``the authorities don't have your best interests at
heart.''
</P>
<P>
   Best news of all: Groening says that `` `The Simpsons' are still
on the air in the year 3000.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   By the year 3000, maybe media moguls will have figured out how
to combine the Net and TV, a hoped-for convergence that is their
consuming obsession these days. Everyone wants to do it, but no one
is quite sure how, or what it will look like.
</P>
<P>
   If anyone can mastermind the Net-TV marriage, it just might be
Geraldine Laybourne, the subject of stories in both Forbes and
Wired. Laybourne is the odds-bucking woman who, armed with only a
master's degree in early childhood education, transformed an
obscure cable network called Nickelodeon into the reigning
powerhouse of children's television. ``She turned what was a
`spinach' channel, something kids should eat, into a `pizza'
channel, something kids wanted to eat,'' her first boss at Nick
tells Forbes author Tom Post.
</P>
<P>
   Now Laybourne has teamed up with Oprah Winfrey and the creative
team behind ``Roseanne'' and ``Third Rock From the Sun'' to create
Oxygen, a TV channel aimed at women. Laybourne already seems to be
looking beyond the immediate competition from the existing women's
channel, Lifetime, toward a larger goal of creating a multimedia
company that combines ``the entertainment power of television with
the interactivity and specificity of the Internet,'' according to
Post.
</P>
<P>
   The author makes clear just how difficult it will be to
integrate the two media _ and how foolish it would be to bet
against Laybourne.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
