<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SEEING-RED-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOR DECORATING, IT'S RED ALL OVER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By FRANCES INGRAHAM  
 c.1999 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ Throughout history, the color red has carried
many different connotations _ from aggression and destruction to
vibrant emotion to love and the celebration of life.
</P>
<P>
   A color favored historically in interior design, it provided
backgrounds for figural work on the frescoed walls of the ancient
city of Pompeii, for the throne rooms of royal palaces, for many of
the great literary and artistic salons of Europe and on down to the
chambers in ``red-light'' districts.
</P>
<P>
   In China, red was considered the symbol of pleasure, joy and
festivity, and it was the symbol for blazing love in the Eastern
Orthodox Church, according to Frank H. Mahnke in the book ``Color:
Environment &AMP; Human Response'' ($64.95, Van Nostrand Reinhold,
1996).
</P>
<P>
   Red can raise the blood pressure. It is popular for sports cars
and barns. It's the first color that babies see.
</P>
<P>
   Mahnke, founder and director of the American Information Center
for Color and Environment in San Diego, an environmental designer
and consultant for architectural projects, noted that red is an
arousing, exciting, stimulating color with positive associations of
passion, strength, activity and warmth.
</P>
<P>
   Red is the boldest of all the colors in the spectrum and has the
greatest emotional impact, wrote Bonnie Rosser Krims in ``The
Perfect Palette: Fifty Inspired Color Plans for Painting Every Room
in Your House'' ($30, Warner Books).
</P>
<P>
   Red is a warm color, said Margaret Walch, director of the Color
Association of the United States in New York City.
</P>
<P>
   ``Because the color red is associated with warmth and comfort,
you often see it in the dining and living room,'' Walch said. ``You
often see red used in public rooms, because it's also invigorating
and stimulating. The architect Frank Lloyd Wright used red rooms in
several of his homes.''
</P>
<P>
   In the 19th century, red was a very popular color for dining
rooms, according to preservation architect Doug Bucher, of John G.
Waite Associates in Albany.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was also used occasionally in the library in the second
half of the 19th century,'' Bucher said.
</P>
<P>
   In the 19th century, red was popular for public buildings as
well, as it reiterated the old notion of being associated with
prestige and royalty.
</P>
<P>
   The Assembly Chamber in the New York state Capitol was done in
red with red stenciling on the stone walls. The two legislative
chambers in state capitals were often in either red, the most
popular, or green or blue, also associated with royalty, according
to Bucher.
</P>
<P>
   The color red also is said to stimulate the appetite, which is
why it was so popular for dining rooms and restaurants. However,
because red is considered such a stimulus, you may not want it in
the kitchen if you are trying to diet, or in the bedroom if you
have trouble getting to sleep.
</P>
<P>
   Red rooms fell from favor during the Colonial Revival, Classical
and Art Deco period of the early 20th century, Bucher said. It
wasn't until World War II, when dark colors became the vogue, that
red came back into fashion.
</P>
<P>
   ``Although red is a popular room color today, you never found
much of it in American houses, except for in fabrics,'' he said.
``It would be relatively rare to find a room in red, except for in
upper-class houses, especially those in Europe. Red pigment was
expensive, which put it out of reach for many working-class homes.
</P>
<P>
   ``Today, it's become very popular for the dining room, library
and living room. Works of art, especially those in gold frames,
look good against a red wall. You often see red walls in galleries
and museums for this very reason.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.) &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Some people simply select red walls for a room in their homes
because it's their favorite color.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had actually seen red used in a dining room in another house
and decided to use it in mine, as it's also my favorite color,''
said Maria Winans of Latham, N.Y. ``We even used the same shade of
red for the inset of our tray ceiling in the dining room. So it
wasn't too much red, we used white wainscoting below the chair
rail, the cornice and window and door trim.''
</P>
<P>
   The window treatments are salmon, gold and green. ``It's all
very striking,'' she said, ``and we love it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
