<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ONJOBS-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHEN CUPID VISITS THE OFFICE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DIANE E. LEWIS.  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Blame William Agee and Mary Cunningham.
</P>
<P>
   Her rapid rise from company neophyte to a vice president of
Bendix Corp. in the early 1980s fueled rumors that they were
engaged in an office romance _ gossip that not only led to a flood
of publicity but, for the first time, focused attention on love on
the job.
</P>
<P>
   Agee was chairman of Bendix. Cunningham was a newly minted 1979
Harvard Business School graduate whose MBA had led to more than 30
job offers, including one from Bendix. He was 49; she, 29.
</P>
<P>
   ``Theirs was the classic case,'' Joseph Weintraub, a management
professor at Babson College in Wellesley, Mass., says of the
Agee-Cunningham romance. ``That was where all the debate over the
office romance actually began, with Bill Agee and Mary
Cunningham.''
</P>
<P>
   Flash forward nearly 20 years and the debate continues, but the
parameters of the discussion certainly have changed. No longer
taboo, the office romance has bloomed as the definition of the
workplace has expanded to include social meeting ground.
</P>
<P>
   Seeking to prevent messy entanglements that could affect
productivity, employers had previously adopted antidating policies
and regulations banning fraternization on _ and sometimes off _ the
job.
</P>
<P>
   Increasingly, however, the pendulum has swung away from such
policies toward more lenient guidelines or no rules at all. The
general consensus seems to be that any attempt to legislate
morality at work might infringe on employees' privacy, or even
worse, result in a lawsuit.
</P>
<P>
   According to a recent survey of 600 US firms by the Society for
Human Resource Management in Alexandria, Va., 72 percent did not
have policies governing employee relationships or office romances.
But most US firms, 90 percent, have instituted sexual harassment
policies.
</P>
<P>
   ``The whole thing is a mine field,'' said David Blankenhorn,
president of the Institute for American Values, an academic think
tank in New York that focuses on children and family matters.
``Historically, the policies companies adopted reflected shared
cultural values. No one was going to sue because everybody thought
the company was doing the right thing. Secondly, it was in the
interest of workplace productivity and harmony. But the cultural
consensus has become fractured and conflicted. There may not even
be a consensus about this issue anymore.''
</P>
<P>
   According to a 1999 Roper Starch Worldwide survey of 1,000 men
and women, 38 percent have dated a co-worker and 72 percent know of
employees who date each other. The survey suggests that Americans
are somewhat concerned about the problems inherent in such
relationships, but think it is inevitable that people who work
together will become involved. And, of those who have dated
co-workers, 23 percent said the relationship led to marriage. The
participants had some misgivings, however. When asked what they
thought about office romances, 72 percent said employees ``should
never date the boss.''
</P>
<P>
   Attorney Dennis Powers, author of ``The Office Romance: Playing
with Fire without Getting Burned'' (Amacom Books, New York, N.Y.),
says employees who are dating would do well to follow certain
guidelines.
</P>
<P>
   To prevent problems, Powers suggests, the couple should identify
a top-ranking person who will be more likely to support their
liaison, inform the employer of the relationship, and be willing to
accept, or even suggest, a transfer to another department,
especially if the relationship is between a supervisor and
subordinate. Powers also suggests that couples who work together
consider bringing a third party to meetings to prevent gossip and
make sure discussions are conducted in an appropriate manner.
</P>
<P>
   Where corporate policies do exist, they tend to focus on the
manager-subordinate romance, with reason: The Agee-Cunningham love
connection not only upbraided lives, it raised questions about fair
play in the office. When Agee was asked by the Bendix board of
directors to describe his relationship with Cunningham, he
reportedly said he and she were simply ``very, very good friends.''
</P>
<P>
   The board didn't buy it. Shortly after Cunningham's promotion to
vice president, the Bendix board fired her, sending a message that
such alliances would not be tolerated primarily because any
appearance of impropriety or favoritism can wreak havoc in the
office.
</P>
<P>
   ``Whenever there is an imbalance of power, a situation where a
manager or chief executive is involved with a subordinate, the
relationship can create issues of equity and fairness,'' noted
Babson's Weintraub. ``Even if the person is not getting favored
treatment, other people may think so. It usually turns out to be a
no-win situation.''
</P>
<P>
   At AT&AMP;T, company supervisors or managers are required to report
personal relationships with subordinates. ``Today, the only
restriction we have about the office romance is we do not want
married couples or boyfriends and girlfriends reporting to each
other,'' said AT&AMP;T spokesman Burke Stinson.
</P>
<P>
   As for dating between co-workers, Stinson said, ``I guess you
could say we treat that with benign neglect. Of the 108,000 people
employed by the telecommunications giant worldwide, approximately
8,000 are married couples who met on the job.''
</P>
<P>
   At Sears, Roebuck &AMP; Co, workplace romances are generally
accepted, but relationships between the boss and underlings are
verboten. ``With a company as large as Sears, workplace romances
are something we see a lot,'' said spokeswoman Paula Davis. ``It
seems logical today that the more time you spend at work the more
likely it will become a social outlet.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the early 1990s, (Sears) had 29 pages of policies and
procedures, but we found that the more rules and regulations we
created, the more ambiguities cropped up,'' Davis said. The
company, which employs 300,000 people nationwide, tossed out its
regs and substituted a set of guidelines, and a 1-800-ethics assist
line to help Sears associates who are unsure or uncomfortable about
a situation related to an office romance.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Problems on the job, questions, story ideas? Contact Diane Lewis
at work(at)globe.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
