<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MAILBOXES-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MAILBOXES COME IN ALL STYLES AND TYPES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By FRANCES INGRAHAM  
 c.1999 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ The mailbox has become a decorative necessity
that we place at the entrance to our homes and apartments.
</P>
<P>
   Wall-mounted mailboxes come in a variety of styles _ an economy
vertical box, 11-by-11 1/2 inches, in black or white metal costs
$5.48 at Home Depot, for example. A brass version costs $26.97, and
a horizontal plastic model can cost from $6.97 to $9.99. A solid
brass mailbox 15 1/2 inches wide by 7 inches high will cost
approximately $99.
</P>
<P>
   Mail slots are also popular for the door or installed to the
side of the door. These usually come in sizes of seven or 11
inches. The cost for solid brass is approximately $19.93 for the
small letter size, or $29.99 for the larger size. Brass-coated and
aluminum cost less.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike post-mounted mailboxes, frequently found in the country
and at the end of suburban driveways, wall-mounted boxes do not
feature a flag to alert the postal carrier that there is a pickup.
But they do offer the option of a newspaper or magazine holder
under the box and a lock on the upright models. Among decorative
options are solid brass boxes from mail-order catalogs that can be
personalized with your name, address or house number.
</P>
<P>
   Some are large enough to receive packages through a door on the
side of the mailbox and mail through a hinged flap on the front.
The cost is of such a box from Lillian Vernon is around $90.
</P>
<P>
   Many of the new brass mailboxes are treated with a weather- and
tarnish-resistant lacquer.
</P>
<P>
   Mailboxes also come in oversize (17 3/4-by-16 1/2 inches by 7
1/2 inches high) weather-resistant plastic that never needs to be
painted and won't leak, for $24.99, from Improvements catalog. A
magnetic catch makes sure the door stays shut even when the box is
stuffed.
</P>
<P>
   Door-to-door city mail delivery began in the mid-1860s,
according to Paula Rabkin, research associate on postal history for
the U.S. Postal Service headquarters in Washington, D.C.
</P>
<P>
   Patent designs for mailboxes and mail slots were in abundance by
the 1890s. A commission was formed by the postal service to set
guidelines for all mailboxes. They must fit the minimum dimensions,
be weatherproof, feature a signal for pickup on rural boxes,
security such as a lock, and be relatively inexpensive to
manufacture, Rabkin said.
</P>
<P>
   By the 1950s and '60s many contemporary versions began to
appear. But they still must be acceptable to the postmaster, so as
not to hamper the delivery of mail.
</P>
<P>
   ``In early rural delivery, prior to urban delivery, people put
just about anything out to catch the mail,'' Rabkin said. ``They
used everything from cigar boxes to used flue pipes from stoves.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-17-99 1337EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
