<DOCNO> NYT19990217.0166 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-17 13:39 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8629 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-VENTURE-INTERNET-ART-     02-17 1469
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VENTURE-INTERNET-ART-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TWO GOLDEN WORDS: INTERNET RELATED 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ART ADV.: A photo is being sent to NYTNS clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchases by calling 212-556-4204 or -1927.)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JERRY ACKERMAN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The I's had it _ Internet-related companies, that is _ as
venture fund managers poured $561.2 million into New England
start-ups during the final three months of 1998.
</P>
<P>
   This rush of investment pushed total funding to promising
entrepreneurs in the region to over $2 billion for the year, spread
among 407 companies in all six states. Total New England investment
for 1997 was $1.36 billion.
</P>
<P>
   Both the quarterly figure and annual total were records for the
Boston Globe/PricewaterhouseCoopers LLC survey of venture capital
funding, which began in 1993.
</P>
<P>
   The number of New England companies getting financing from
venture funds during the final quarter _ 99 _ was down from the 114
counted during the fall. But the average deal, $5.7 million, was up
19 percent, as these funds had little trouble raising new money
from their investors, which include pension funds, college
endowments, insurance portfolios, and wealthy individuals.
</P>
<P>
   According to Patrick M. Gray of PricewaterhouseCoopers, the
bigger deals are the result of huge profits made during the past
three years by these money sources. A separate survey by Venture
Economics of Newark found 364 venture funds nationally raised $88.4
billion last year to be put into these high-risk but highly
enticing enterprises. That was 25 percent more than in 1997, and
more than double the amount raised in 1995.
</P>
<P>
   Venture investment also continued to set records nationally,
with $3.7 billion pumped into 713 companies from coast to coast
during the quarter, and $14.3 billion shared by 2,856 companies for
the year. That year-end figure was up $2.8 billion from 1997.
</P>
<P>
   Software and information systems and communications companies
again led the pack, receiving about half of all investment for both
the quarter and the year, both regionally and nationally.
</P>
<P>
   But increasingly, lines between traditional industry sectors
blurred, as consumer-oriented communications companies claimed
space in the Internet realm, and enterprises engaged in
business-to-business commerce over the Internet categorized
themselves as either communications or software firms.
</P>
<P>
   One Boston company, Virtual Ink Inc., which has developed an
electronic device that uses the Internet to transmit images from
office or school ``white boards'' to distant points as they are
being drawn, said it had trouble convincing potential investors why
it wanted to be seen as an Internet-related company.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some saw this as just a computer hardware peripheral, which it
is not,'' Greg McHale, the company's chief executive, said. In the
end, Virtual Ink got the $5 million it wanted to launch a national
marketing campaign from CMG AtVentures Fund, an affiliate of CMGI
Inc., the founding investor in Lycos Inc. and other Internet
start-ups that became Wall Street superstars.
</P>
<P>
   Of the 99 New England companies receiving venture financing
during the last quarter, at least 41 were Internet related,
according to the PricewaterhouseCoopers/Boston Globe survey, also
known as the Money Tree Survey.
</P>
<P>
   This first attempt to make such a distinction relied on the
companies themselves for information, and venture fund managers
said many candidates probably were overlooked.
</P>
<P>
   ``To me the Internet is like electrification _ it drives all
business today,'' said Stephen J. Ricci, a partner at OneLiberty
Ventures in Boston. Michael Frank, a partner at Advanced Technology
Ventures in Waltham, added: ``Almost 100 percent of what we do is
somehow related to, or touches, the Internet.''
</P>
<P>
   Companies that fell into the Internet category in the survey
ranged from on-line retailers _ such as Furniture.com Inc. of
Worcester, toysmart.com of Waltham, MASS., and MotherNature.com
Inc. of Acton, Mass. _ to firms that make switches and software
that allow data to move faster, with telecommunications carriers as
their prospective customers.
</P>
<P>
   But they also included marketing, publishing, health care, and a
variety of service companies _ sectors that also are trying to
realign themselves to do business in an on-line age.
</P>
<P>
   Some venture fund managers see this second group as perhaps more
promising than those focused on on-line commerce, which in spite of
high interest on Wall Street has yet to prove itself able to
deliver profits based on sales of goods and services.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you can, you want to build a company that has real revenues
and real profits,'' said Robert Fleming, a partner at Prism Venture
Partners in Westwood.
</P>
<P>
   Although the Internet was perhaps the strongest force in venture
funding last year, other sectors, including drug development,
medical devices, health care management and services, and
traditional retailing, all continued to attract investor interest.
</P>
<P>
   ``Venture investment was up almost all across the board,'' said
Gray, a partner in PricewaterhouseCooper's Boston office who
oversees the New England portion of the survey.
</P>
<P>
   Nine biotechnology and pharmaceutical companies in the region
received $87.5 million during the fourth quarter, $10 million more
than the same number of companies in these sectors got during the
third quarter.
</P>
<P>
   The single largest fourth-quarter venture-fund investment in the
region was, in fact, a $31.4 million mezzanine financing to Dyax
Corp. of Cambridge, Mass., which has developed a specialized
technology to search molecular databases for proteins that can be
used in drug development.
</P>
<P>
   Dyax planned to go public last year but postponed its initial
stock offering as market conditions wavered.
</P>
<P>
   As a percentage of all investment in New England, however, these
sectors remained flat compared with earlier years, when they
sometimes captured up to 40 percent of all financing during a
quarter.
</P>
<P>
   In a twist away from electronics, two insurance companies
setting up shop in Connecticut _ Connecticut Reinssurance Corp. and
Target Capital Partners Inc. _ ranked second and fourth in dollars
received in the region during the fourth quarter.
</P>
<P>
   Connecticut Reinsurance received $30 million and Target $25
million. Both said they plan to take advantage of big tax breaks
Connecticut is offering to try to revive its insurance industry.
</P>
<P>
   Third place went to another biotech company, Ontogeny Inc. of
Cambridge, which received $28 million in late-stage funding that
could precede an initial public offering. The company has developed
protein compounds that have promise for treating bone fractures and
cartilage and skeletal disorders.
</P>
<P>
   By region, California's Silicon Valley region continued to lead
the nation for 1998 in both number of investment deals, 787, and
dollars invested, $4.55 billion. That amount was about 31.9 percent
of all venture money invested nationally.
</P>
<P>
   New England's investment dollar share for the year was 14.2
percent, up from 11.8 percent in 1997. The Southeast, with $1.12
billion invested during the year, held its third-place position in
the Money Tree Survey, but the region's share of the national total
slipped to 7.9 percent from 9.4 percent in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   Gray sees a continued high level of investment across the nation
as venture fund managers, under some pressure to put the growing
amounts of investor money they are raising to work as soon as
possible, increase the amounts they pledge in each funding round.
</P>
<P>
   ``Fund managers are raising $100 million and more for their
investment funds regularly now,'' he said. ``Ten years ago they
were raising $30 million to $50 million.''
</P>
<P>
   Venture fund companies say they have no trouble raising these
amounts, either, citing other surveys that document high returns in
recent years. Several said their institutional investors have
raised the ratio of funds going into these higher-risk accounts, to
7.5 percent and sometimes 10 percent, from a traditional level of 5
percent.
</P>
<P>
   Venture Economics reported last month the average US venture
fund delivered an annualized return of 32.2 percent over the
three-year period ended Sept. 30. However, last summer's market
slump resulted in an average loss of 3.6 percent in venture funds,
the first quarterly loss since 1992.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps the biggest obstacle facing start-ups now, fund managers
said, is a shortage of personnel that now reaches beyond technical
skills and into managerial fields.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a huge dearth of such talent,'' said Frank, of
Advanced Technology Ventures, leading to the risk that chief
executives who are hired to run start-ups will have too little
experience, and the people they hire will also be less qualified.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
