<SLUG> BC-BOOKS-THRILLERS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TWO TOP WRITERS PRODUCE MASTERFUL HISTORICAL THRILLERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By BOBBIE HESS  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Two of the best writers of the historical thriller genre are
Robert Harris and Joseph Kanon. And each has a new book out.
</P>
<P>
   Harris' latest, ``Archangel'' (Random House, $24.95, 373 pages),
tells of four days in the life of Fluke Kelso, a former Oxford
historian who travels to Moscow to attend a conference on the
recently opened Soviet archives.
</P>
<P>
   Kelso gets a visit one night from Papu Rapava, who says he was
on the security detail of Secret Police Chief Lavenry Beria. He
claims he was with Beria on the night Stalin suffered his fateful
stroke and he helped Beria steal Stalin's papers and a notebook.
</P>
<P>
   After Beria's death, Rapava was sentenced to the Gulag for 15
years. Now he says he knows where the notebook is hidden and wants
Kelso to help him get money for it. Unexpectedly, Rapava takes off
without leaving an address or a phone number. The only thing he
leaves behind is a book of matches from a Moscow bar.
</P>
<P>
   The next morning Kelso skips out of the conference and goes to
the Lenin Library to see if any of Rapava's story checks out. He
finds a book by a Red Army general that states that Stalin kept a
``black oilskin exercise book in which he would make occasional
notes and that for some time he kept letters. .. All efforts to
discover either the notebook or these letters have failed. ...''
</P>
<P>
   Next Kelso goes to the bar named on the book of matches and
meets a television reporter named O'Brian and Rapava's estranged
daughter, Zinaida. For $300, she agrees to drive Kelso to her
father's apartment. When they get there, Zinaida flees and he finds
the old man murdered. Kelso is questioned, released and told not to
miss his flight the next morning.
</P>
<P>
   But he spots Zinaida at the airport and takes off with her when
she tells him that her father left her something in a toolbox. She
drives to an old shed, and they find the toolbox just as O'Brian
shows up with a camera. Inside the toolbox is a black oilskin
notebook that turns out not to be Stalin's but that of Anna
Safanova, a young comrade from Archangel who worked at Stalin's
dacha outside Moscow.
</P>
<P>
   Deciding to try to find out what happened to Anna, O'Brian and
Kelso drive to Archangel and interview her aged mother. What they
discover in a forest outside the city could rewrite history and
change the world forever.
</P>
<P>
   ``Archangel'' is creative and filled with enough plot spins to
keep you reeling.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In ``The Prodigal Spy'' (Broadway Books. $25. 409 pages), Kanon
pegs his second historical thriller to the witch hunts of the House
Un-American Activities Committee of the 1950s.
</P>
<P>
   Imagine you are 10-year-old Nick Kotlar and your world is
perfect. Your father is Walter Kotlar, an undersecretary of State,
your parents are in love and they treat you wonderfully. Then
suddenly, your father stops going to work and heads for Capitol
Hill to testify before the committee because a young department
store clerk has accused him of treason.
</P>
<P>
   The reporters wait outside your house every morning and walk
your father to the hearings. They leave you alone, but when
classmates start making snide comments, your parents take you out
of school.
</P>
<P>
   One night Walter Kotlar vanishes and his accuser plunges from a
hotel window. Just imagine young Nick's anguish when he has to
admit that his father is a traitor and willing to give up his
family for his cause.
</P>
<P>
   Nick's mother moves them to New York and marries Walter's best
friend, Larry Warren, a career diplomat. Adopted by Larry, Nick
changes his last name and life goes on. Having served in Vietnam,
Nick is now in London as a graduate student. During an anti-war
rally outside the U.S. Embassy, he meets a beautiful blonde
freelance journalist named Molly, who tells him Walter Kotlar is
living in Prague and wants to see him.
</P>
<P>
   Using Molly as his cover, Nick heads for Prague and the
long-overdue meeting with his father. Walter Kotlar wants to get to
know his son, but he also wants Nick to help him to go home; he
says he's willing to unmask a long-time mole still in Washington.
But Walter is murdered before he can give any details of the spy
code-named Silver.
</P>
<P>
   It's left to Nick to uncover years and years of deceit and to
learn the hard way that almost everyone has something to hide.
</P>
<P>
   The strength of ``The Prodigal Spy'' is its point of view: The
entire story is told through Nick's eyes, first as that scared
young boy and then as an adult trying to make sense of a
clandestine world he doesn't understand. Kanon lets the action
progress at a natural speed, building his characters bit by bit.
</P>
<P>
   Kanon has set out to show how the crimes of the father can
affect the child _ a task he masterfully pulls off.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
