<SLUG> BC-WOMEN-INVESTORS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MUTUAL FUND INVESTS IN COMPANIES THAT SUPPORT WOMEN 
</HEADLINE>
   (EDs: Note optional trim)  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By EDWARD IWATA  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Not long ago, Wall Street mocked socially
responsible funds. No more.
</P>
<P>
   After a slow start, baby boomers have started pouring more money
into the nation's 144 socially responsible mutual funds, with
assets hitting a record $529 billion last year, according to the
Social Investment Forum, a nonprofit organization in Washington
D.C.
</P>
<P>
   In the performance arena, these stock funds gained 18.5 percent
in 1998, compared to 14.3 percent for the average domestic stock
fund, according to Morningstar Inc.
</P>
<P>
   Yet another sign of success: about 40 percent of socially
responsible funds have earned top 5-star and 4-star ratings from
Morningstar Inc., compared to 30 percent of funds in other groups.
</P>
<P>
   ``They've made a very good showing overall,'' said Jon Hale, a
Morningstar analyst who follows socially responsible funds.
``People were skeptical of them as investment vehicles, but now
there's a growing respect and recognition. As an investment
approach, it's here to stay.''
</P>
<P>
   These funds often specialize, carefully sorting out companies
that have exceptional environmental and human rights records or, in
the case of one fund, invest in companies that are deemed good for
women.
</P>
<P>
   Linda Pei, a San Francisco banker, and a former co-worker pooled
$50,000 from friends in 1993 to start the Pro-Conscience Women's
Equity Mutual Fund, which invests in companies that the fund
managers believe have pro-women policies.
</P>
<P>
   Today, the fund manages $8.7 million in assets and holds stock
in 50 large-cap companies.
</P>
<P>
   Run by portfolio managers Heidi Soumerai and Bill Apfel at U.S.
Trust Company Boston, the fund enjoyed a 28.76 percent gain last
year, edging the Standard &AMP; Poor 500's 28.72 percent return.
</P>
<P>
   ``When we started, we were told the social criteria for our
investments would limit us, and we couldn't possibly outperform
other funds,'' said Pei, 54, the president of the fund. ``Now, so
many socially responsible funds are doing well.''
</P>
<P>
   Pei is betting that clients will continue to invest with their
financial minds, and their hearts.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you can make money while following your heart, why not?''
Pei said.
</P>
<P>
   Pei and Leslie Christian, a former Salomon Brothers executive
who is now managing director at Progressive Securities in Portland,
Ore., began the fund in part because they believed that
businesswomen had made little progress in breaking the glass
ceiling in corporate boardrooms.
</P>
<P>
   ``We looked at each other and said, `What happened?' In the '70s
and '80s, we thought we'd be at the forefront, a new vanguard of
businesswomen,'' Pei said.
</P>
<P>
   The two decided to start a mutual fund, using money as a voice
for women. Pei registered the fund with the Securities and Exchange
Commission. They hosted a wine-and-cheese party for 100 friends,
who pitched in $50,000 to start the fund.
</P>
<P>
   They also started hunting for good stocks, large-cap companies
that treat women well in the workplace. Among their criteria: Women
in executive ranks; equal pay for women; career development
programs; pro-family benefits, including child care and maternity
leave; contracts with women-owned companies; and positive images of
women in advertising.
</P>
<P>
   Financially, the companies must be top performers in their
industries, with well-run management, strong market share and high
earnings potential.
</P>
<P>
   Today, most of the fund's holdings are in technology (19
percent), health care (17 percent) and financial services (15
percent). Top holdings include Lucent Technologies, Johnson &AMP;
Johnson, Sanmina and Cisco Systems.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.) &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   One tough decision Pei and her fund managers must make soon:
whether to hold or dump 180,000 shares of BankAmerica, the San
Francisco corporate institution taken over last year by NationsBank
of Charlotte, N.C.
</P>
<P>
   Some departing BankAmerica women executives have accused the
NationsBank management of discrimination, charges denied by the
company.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're in touch with bank executives to find out what's going
on there,'' Pei said. ``Were these disputes involving employees, or
part of corporatewide practices?''
</P>
<P>
   While lacking the raw clout of giant mutual funds and pension
plans, Pei hopes her fund will show that women are a force in
finance.
</P>
<P>
   ``Collectively, we have a lot of power,'' Pei said. ``That's an
important message to get out.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Information on the Pro-Conscience Women's Equity Mutual Fund is
available at 415-547-9135; on the Web: www.womens-equity.com.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
