<SLUG> BC-ADULT-SPIRITUALITY-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MID-LIFE SPIRITUALITY SHUNS `QUESTION-AND-ANSWER' RELIGION 
</HEADLINE>
   (Commentary)  
 &HT;    
 &HT;    (To purchase this ``separate buy'' article from the New York
Times Syndicate please contact syndicate sales representative DEBRA
WEYDERT at 732-390-4480)  
 &HT;    
 By DIANA BUTLER BASS  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
 &HT;    
 &HT;    Long before the Y2K computer glitch, 1999 filled me with fear.
On New Year's 1969, my mother commented, ``Imagine that: thirty
years from now you'll celebrate a new millennium and your fortieth
birthday.''
 &HT;    At ten years old, both sounded apocalyptic. I convinced myself
neither would ever arrive.
 &HT;    The long-dreaded day has come. This month, I turn forty.
 &HT;    Forty? The ``old age of youth and the youth of old age'' is upon
me. Friends who have already passed the mid-life milestone grin
knowingly, ``It's tough. You'll see.''
 &HT;    They are right. Over the last months, a gnawing sense of
mortality keeps me awake nights. My career dissatisfies me. I am
trying to eat better and work out. I even want to buy a
convertible.
 &HT;    A by-the-numbers mid-life crisis.
 &HT;    Recently, I saw a book about spirituality for life's ``second
half.'' Thumbing through the pages, the prospect of the ``second
half'' irritated. Not for me, I mused. I am still young. After all,
I just had a baby.
 &HT;    In many ways, forty is young -- especially now as people live
longer. However, as the distance between my students and me
increases, I know that forty is not youthful. That twenty-year gap
constantly reminds me that I'm not of their generation. They are
growing up; I already have.
 &HT;    The spirituality of growing up and being grown-up is not the
same. Youthful spirituality seeks answers for big questions: Who is
God? Who am I? Who will be my life partner? What am I to do in the
world?
 &HT;    A quest for order engulfs the young as they become independent
persons. As a result, religions with strict moral boundaries and
clear-cut beliefs appeal to teen-agers and young adults, providing
direction to those otherwise adrift.
 &HT;    By forty, spirituality is no longer about order. Rather, it is
about meaning. For most of us, those ``big questions'' have been
resolved. There may or may not be a God. I may or may not ever
figure out who I am. Partners may or may not be for life. My career
may or may not provide meaning or fulfillment. The twenty years
between college and mid-life reveal the messiness of life -- very
little is as we expected it to be. Is there any meaning in the
mess?
 &HT;    Mid-life spirituality seeks to make sense of messiness. There
will always questions. Instead of answers, faith turns to finding
meaning through telling stories. Through story, patterns emerge
that give form to the chaos of adulthood.
 &HT;    Story-telling is an ancient -- and profoundly human -- way of
expressing faith. Every culture told stories of creation,
recreation, and death. A tribe's self-understanding and explanation
of God came from campfire tales -- and were eventually gathered
into sacred books and systematic theologies.
 &HT;    Sadly, in America, we treat the dominant religious book -- the
Bible -- as an answer book. This is an adolescent approach to the
text. The Bible is primarily a storybook -- tales whose collective
narrative shapes us spiritually. Its main story-line is that of a
God who creates and loves a people who, in turn, love God and serve
the world.
 &HT;    This story provides meaning for generations of Jews, Christians
and Muslims. Anyone who has spent time in its pages knows the Book
is riddled with ambiguity and paradox. Even it provides no
clear-cut answers. If so, how could there be so many conflicting
interpretations of its message? The Bible is, after all, a
collection of stories. And story must be experienced as living text
-- not simply memorized as a cheat sheet for God's final exam.
 &HT;    At forty, I find myself living in multiple stories: my own
story, my family's story, my church's story, history's story, and
biblical story. Meaning is multi-layered; truth is textured. Life
experience enriches each interpretation as stories are told and
retold. In the process, both humanity and divinity speak.
 &HT;    Perhaps story-telling as adult spirituality accounts for the
current popularity of spiritual autobiographies. As the last
baby-boomers turn forty, an entire generation is moving away from
question-and-answer religion to narrative faith -- a shift likely
to produce profound consequences for America's religious
institutions and political landscape. We should expect a higher
degree of religious and moral flexibility with an aging population
-- as already evinced by the Clinton scandal.
 &HT;    Life is messy and that's okay. Our stories tell us so.
 &HT;    Contemplating the years ahead, I may never be rich enough to buy
that red Mercedes convertible. But I trust the story will become
richer. Looking back on life's narrative seems fundamentally more
satisfying than finding the answers -- and even makes the prospect
of 2029 interesting rather than fearful.
 &HT;    Imagine that: my daughter will be thirty!
 &HT;    
 &HT;    ----
 &HT;    c.1999 Diana Butler Bass
<TEXT>
<P>
   (Diana Butler Bass, Ph.D., writes a religion column for the
Santa Barbara News-Press and is associate professor of religious
studies at Rhodes College in Memphis, Tenn. Her latest book is
``Standing Against the Whirlwind: Evangelical Episcopalians in 19th
Century America,'' published by Oxford University Press.)
</P>
