<HEADLINE>
Y2K PROBLEM HITS CREDIT CARDS EARLY 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By HARRY SHATTUCK 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   You browse through a small shop on the island of Gibraltar,
select a souvenir and hand your credit card to the cashier.
</P>
<P>
   He utters a thank-you, places the card through a swipe machine
for verification, then frowns and gives the card back.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sorry, your card is expired,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   ``But it was just renewed through 2001,'' you explain.
</P>
<P>
   He shrugs. And politely asks you to pay cash or return your
purchase.
</P>
<P>
   Some travelers to foreign countries have experienced such an
uncomfortable situation over the past few weeks. Primarily in small
establishments off the beaten path. And especially when a credit
card _ or ATM card _ carries an expiration date beyond 1999.
</P>
<P>
   And we thought all that Y2K talk was baloney.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
DIGIT DILEMMA &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   What's happening is this:
</P>
<P>
   Computer programmers have commonly used the last two digits,
rather than all four, to represent the year. With these programs,
the first two digits are presumed to be 19. Thus, 99 is programmed
as 1999. But 00 is programmed as 1900, not 2000.
</P>
<P>
   While most businesses in the United States already have
addressed changes required to advance computer systems into the
next millennium, a small minority of merchants in other countries
has been slow to respond. Not every card-swipe machine is outfitted
with new software. And if the machine reads the expiration date as
being in 1900, not 2000 ... you guessed it: Your card has been
invalid for 99 years. Or so the merchant is led to believe.
</P>
<P>
   The State Department is concerned enough to issue an
announcement two weeks ago that reads in part, ``U.S. citizens
abroad should not assume that credit cards, ATM machines,
international banking transactions, etc., will operate normally in
all locations throughout the world.''
</P>
<P>
   But a cooperative effort by major credit card companies is
dedicated to limiting international traveler inconveniences. And,
says John McCarthy, vice president of Visa International's 2000
Project, ``Our data shows that more than 99.4 percent of merchants
worldwide have accepted 2000-expiration cards without a problem.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are monitoring this situation closely. We want cardholders
to feel confident in using their cards. Visa, American Express,
MasterCard and other companies recognized some time ago that this
was a potential problem. We established a Payment Card Council and
got together and discussed the issue. We've traveled all over the
world since 1996 working with merchants (on the necessary
changes).''
</P>
<P>
   It's a massive undertaking. ``We've got 15 million locations
worldwide directly connected to Visa,'' says McCarthy. ``We've been
in contact with each of them. We created 300,000 test cards with
expiration dates in 2000.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
DEALING WITH REJECTION &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Rest assured that the vast majority of businesses overseas _ and
certainly all major airlines, hotels and other leading
travel-service providers _ will gladly accept our credit cards.
You'll likely encounter few if any problems at the most popular
destinations. And card companies will continue to address any
trouble spots; they certainly don't want us resorting to cash
payments.
</P>
<P>
   But what do we do if a merchant rejects a credit card that we
know is valid? McCarthy urges travelers to ask for a voice
authorization. ``All merchants have telephone numbers they can call
to check expiration dates,'' he says. ``Then the transaction can be
completed.''
</P>
<P>
   That's assuming the cardholder and merchant can overcome any
language barrier.
</P>
<P>
   I recommend that any international traveler also formulate a
backup plan for spending and exchanging money, especially when
venturing beyond large cities, resort areas and other regions
accustomed to dealing with tourists. Take a few travelers checks
(though I experienced occasional difficulty cashing these last year
in small European towns except at banks). And carry enough cash
(securely) in case you get in a pinch.
</P>
<P>
   If you do encounter a problem, inform the card-issuer when you
return home so that it can take steps to protect subsequent
travelers.
</P>
<P>
   The State Department announcement can be accessed in full on the
Internet at travel.state.gov.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
