<SLUG> BC-GARDEN-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CACTUS FLOWERS BEST WHEN POT-BOUND 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By KATHY HUBER 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q: Last spring my husband gave me a beautiful flowering cactus.
The flowers were almost iridescent. I believe the name was star
cactus. It is still alive and doing well. What do I need to get it
to bloom again? Is it similar to the Christmas cactus?
</P>
<P>
   A: One plant commonly called star cactus is ``Astrophytum
ornatum'' and is native to Mexico. It is shaped like a stocky,
deeply ribbed ball and slowly becomes more cylindrical or columnar
with age. This cactus bears long spines and large, bright yellow
flowers at the plant crown on older plants in spring and summer. It
is a relative of the spineless cactus known as bishop's cap. Does
this sound like your cactus?
</P>
<P>
   Most cactuses flower on new growth. Give the plant care during
the warm season, but don't be too fussy with it in winter. It may
flower best when slightly pot-bound. The plants generally are
slow-growing, so frequent transplanting is unnecessary.
</P>
<P>
   Star cactus likes sun, but be careful of exposure to a full day
of unrelenting full hot sun. Some filtration is best. A daily dose
of some sun or an abundance of bright light will encourage blooms.
</P>
<P>
   Give the plant fresh air. Increase watering in spring and
summer. Water well, and allow the water to drain. If draining into
a saucer, empty it. Let the plant go dry between waterings, and
water infrequently during winter. Don't allow the soil to remain
dry so long that the plant shrivels.
</P>
<P>
   The planting mix should provide rapid drainage. A commercial
cactus mix should be fine. Some advocate adding ground limestone to
the mix to boost root development and plant vigor.
</P>
<P>
   You can apply a diluted fertilizer every second or third time
you water during the growing season. A 20-20-20 houseplant
fertilizer will do. Some boost bloom with a diluted African violet
fertilizer.
</P>
<P>
   The Christmas cactus, ``Schlumbergera bridgesii,'' needs short
days and cooler temperatures to produce midwinter 3-inch tubular
blooms in bright pink, red, fuchsia or white. This cactus is a
sprawling, jointed, spineless plant.
</P>
<P>
   Q: About 23 years ago we planted a boxwood hedge along the front
of our house. This area did not receive much sun, but the hedge
grew thick and healthy. Once in a while we would notice a few brown
leaves, but the bushes continued to grow. Recently we have noticed
two bushes next to each other have turned brown and died. We would
like to replace these but feel we should first find out the
possible cause.
</P>
<P>
   A: When a boxwood dies and then one next to it does, too, it is
possible that root knot nematodes are at work. These are
microscopic worms in the soil. The plant may wilt during the day
and recover at night. It will gradually decline, and branches or
the entire plant may die. Remove the dead plants and examine the
roots for galls or swellings. The roots may look gnarled.
Sometimes, too, disease organisms, such as root rot, attack
infected roots.
</P>
<P>
   Have your county extension service help you with a diagnosis if
you're not sure.
</P>
<P>
   Boost the organic matter in the soil to introduce beneficial
soil microorganisms and encourage those already present. Keep the
area clean. Remove any weeds, which can be hosts to the pests.
Water remaining boxwood as needed to avoid drought stress and
reduce root knot damage. This will not decrease the pest
population, however. Don't let runoff from suspected infected areas
spill into other garden areas. And don't transfer any soil from a
suspected area elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
   Soil solarization using a clear (not black) plastic spread over
bare soil for several weeks during hot weather can reduce nematode
populations, at least temporarily.
</P>
<P>
   There are nematicides that sometimes can be applied around
established plants. Contact your extension service for information.
</P>
<P>
   Dwarf yaupon, an evergreen often used as a foundation plant,
would be a good substitute if it becomes necessary to replace your
boxwood. Apparently it is resistant to root knot nematodes and is
shade-tolerant.
</P>
<P>
   Other possibilities: Fungal problems can occur when drainage is
less than ideal. Portions of plants may die, but it is possible an
entire shrub will die. When portions of a boxwood turn yellow or
brown, and there is a brownish discoloration in the wood at the
base of the trunk (you'll need to cut the wood to check), cotton
root rot could be the problem. If the entire plant is not dead,
prune affected branches, improve the drainage in the bed or replant
the boxwood in another area. You may want to lift the plants, work
some sand into the soil to improve drainage, then replant.
</P>
<P>
   If a shrub turns yellow or brown and some leaves brown only on
the leaf margins, it could be drought or winter injury. But other
fungal diseases can result in these symptoms, so diagnosis can be
tricky. Prune affected branches and improve drainage to see if
plant health improves.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Mail garden questions to Kathy Huber, garden editor, Houston
Chronicle, P.O. Box 4260, Houston 77210. The bulk of mail prevents
individual replies to all unpublished letters.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
