<HEADER>
A8647 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-JASPER-REBEL-HNS &LR;      02-17 0919
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JASPER-REBEL-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SUSPECT'S WRITINGS POINT TO ROLE IN LEADERSHIP OF `AYRIAN' GROUP 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  (Note: ``Mein Kampf'' is Hitler's political manifesto) 
 
By RICHARD STEWART 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   JASPER, Texas _ Call it the scout manual from hell _ or maybe
``Mein Kampf'' _ East Texas Style.
</P>
<P>
   When lawmen investigating the brutal dragging death of James
Byrd Jr. searched the apartment of capital murder defendant John
William ``Bill'' King, they found handwritten outlines, bylaws and
recruiting letters for what he called the Confederate Knights of
America's Texas Rebel Soldiers.
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes calling himself the president of the organization,
sometimes a captain, he called himself and his followers ``a
relative handful of Aryans dedicated to fighting on the behalf of a
world that often fears and hates us.''
</P>
<P>
   King clearly considered his ``Aryan'' heritage far superior to
other races _ ``a race of individuals who have found themselves
existing on humanity's evolutionary plateau. Born with the genetic
capacity for great power, leadership and knowledge; we have chosen
the added burden of responsibility, to defend those who have not
the power nor resources to protect themselves.''
</P>
<P>
   While that might sound like the Rebel Soldiers would protect
other races, theirs was clearly the only race they felt needed
protecting. ``At times this will mean coming to the aid of our
fellow kindred _ providing a defense against those races who feel
their powers allow them to dominate others. Just as often, we will
be called on to safeguard our Aryan race against those individuals
and organizations who fear and hate them simply because we are
`different'! All to (sic) often, we will defend Aryans against
their own kind _ as the unfortunate quest for supremacy continues
... ''
</P>
<P>
   Many of the writings found in King's apartment listed rules and
codes his Rebel Soldiers were expected to follow. ``The possession
of any contraband or consumption of any illegal drugs and/or
alcohol at organizational functions is strictly prohibited.''
</P>
<P>
   Investigators said King and his companions spent several hours
drinking beer before they picked up James Byrd Jr. for the last
ride of his life.
</P>
<P>
   ``Act nobly and courageously, always carefully considering the
consequences,'' another list of rules said, ``as the effect of your
deeds live on after you pass.''
</P>
<P>
   Another rule tells Rebel Soldiers to ``love, protect, reproduce
and advance your folk.'' Almost two months after his arrest on
murder charges, King's girlfriend gave birth to their son.
</P>
<P>
   King was clearly looking toward the future in his writings. In
what he titled ``Introduction to the Texas Rebel Soldiers,'' King
said the organization ``was started on July 4, 1998, in memory of
all Aryan kindred who led a courageous fight throughout the dawn of
time towards the advancement of our beautiful and great race.''
</P>
<P>
   Byrd was killed early June 7, and King had been in jail for
almost a month by the time Independence Day came that year.
</P>
<P>
   He wrote that ``no leader will ever ask you to break any law,''
but in other parts of his writings, he made dire predictions of
racial war.
</P>
<P>
   ``It has been my fervent wish, long before the formation of the
T.R.S., that hostilities be avoided at all cost, be it race vs.
race or kind vs. kind. In recent years, however, I have become
painfully aware that a war is being waged across the planet earth _
and that we (the Aryan race) are the first, quite possibly the
final, line of defense.''
</P>
<P>
   That war, he claimed, called for extreme measures: ``While it
may appear unseemly and disturbing that we are engaged in sometimes
illegal activities, it must be stressed that these activities have
proven vital to our survival on many occasions. We live in
difficult times and moral choices of questionable nature are
unfortunately the result.''
</P>
<P>
   King's writings make it clear that his Texas Rebel Soldiers had
its start while he was previously in prison on a burglary
conviction. Texas prison officials said King and Lawrence Russell
Brewer, also charged in the Byrd slaying, were members of a very
small group, which existed only at the Beto I Unit, called
Confederate Knights of America.
</P>
<P>
   Prison officials monitor 11 major racial gangs or groups within
the giant Texas prison system and keep tabs on about 20 other minor
groups that seem to come and go. The Confederate Knights were one
of those minor groups, said Sam Buentello, who keeps tabs on such
prison groups.
</P>
<P>
   Buentello wouldn't talk about King's case because he is due to
be a witness in the capital murder trial, but he said prisoners
often get Klan propaganda and build their own groups around what
they read.
</P>
<P>
   If so, King may have based his Texas Rebel Solders on an older
group that is no longer active.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the material found in King's apartment bore the name of
the Confederate Knights of the Ku Klux Klan of Huntersville, N.C.
</P>
<P>
   That group was active in the late 1980s but has been inactive
since 1992, said Joseph Roy Sr., director of the Intelligence
Project of the Southern Poverty Law Center of Montgomery, Ala. The
center keeps tabs of hate groups throughout the nation.
</P>
<P>
   Such groups are constantly forming and dying, Roy said. Groups
like the Texas Rebel Soldiers are far from rare, he said. There are
more than 5,000 white supremacy groups in the United States, he
said. Only about 500 are active at any one time.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
