<SLUG> BC-FOOD-AFRICAN-RECIPES2ndTAKE18- </SLUG>

<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA: 2 bay leaves
</P>
<P>
   Salt and freshly ground black pepper to taste
</P>
<P>
   Heat the oil in a heavy saucepan. Add onion and cook over medium
heat until it is translucent. Add meat and continue to cook,
stirring occasionally, until it is lightly browned on all sides. In
a small bowl, mix the peanut butter with cold water and pour it
over the meat. Dilute the tomato paste with the hot water, pour the
liquid over the stew and stir well to make sure all the ingredients
are well-mixed. Add the carrots, thyme, bay leaves, salt and
pepper; lower the heat, cover and cook, stirring occasionally, for
45 minutes, then uncover and cook for another 15 minutes or until
the meat is tender. Remove the thyme sprigs and bay leaves. Serve
hot over white rice.
</P>
<P>
   Per serving: 552 calories, 41 grams protein, 35 grams fat
(percent calories from fat, 57), 22 grams carbohydrates, 105
milligrams cholesterol, 290 milligrams sodium, 6 grams fiber.
</P>
<P>
   GHANA
</P>
<P>
   Eartha Whitfield is known for cooking for her son, Atlanta
Falcon Bob Whitfield, and his teammates. Along with traditional
home-style dishes like lasagna, she's added some African dishes.
This palaver, taught to her by a friend from Ghana, is a big hit.
It can be adapted to any meat, poultry or smoked fish, and we've
adapted her version to serve four.
</P>
<P>
   MAIN DISH
</P>
<P>
   Palaver
</P>
<P>
   Makes 4 servings Preparation time: 30 minutes Cooking time: 30
minutes
</P>
<P>
   1 1/2 tablespoons vegetable oil
</P>
<P>
   1/2 pound ground turkey or beef
</P>
<P>
   1/2 pound diced smoked turkey or beef
</P>
<P>
   1/2 pound chopped or sliced turkey sausage
</P>
<P>
   1/2 to 1 small jalapeno pepper, seeded and diced
</P>
<P>
   1 small onion, diced
</P>
<P>
   1 1/4-inch piece fresh ginger, diced
</P>
<P>
   1 clove garlic, diced
</P>
<P>
   1/8 teaspoon each dried basil, rosemary, cumin seed and celery
seed
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup water
</P>
<P>
   3 tablespoons tomato paste
</P>
<P>
   1 large tomato, diced
</P>
<P>
   1 10-ounce bag prewashed fresh spinach
</P>
<P>
   Salt to taste
</P>
<P>
   In a Dutch oven over medium heat, add oil, ground turkey or
beef, smoked turkey or beef and turkey sausage. Add chopped pepper,
onion, ginger, garlic, basil, rosemary, cumin seed and celery seed.
Cook and stir for 10 minutes. Add water and tomato paste; cover and
cook for 10 minutes on low heat. Add diced tomato and spinach;
cover and cook 10 minutes on medium heat, stirring to incorporate
spinach. Add salt to taste. Serve hot.
</P>
<P>
   Per serving: 340 calories, 30 grams protein, 21 grams fat
(percent calories from fat, 54), 10 grams carbohydrates, 102
milligrams cholesterol, 497 milligrams sodium, 3 grams fiber.
</P>
<P>
   NIGERIA
</P>
<P>
   Jessica Harris explains that the whole-bean fritter defines
Nigerian cooking for many people. There are many variations, but
this white bean and palm oil version is the most common. Palm oil
is a wonderfully flavorful red oil that also happens to be high in
saturated fat. It can be found at ethnic grocery stores and
markets. You may choose to fry these fritters in an alternative oil
_ but we're glad we took Harris' recommendation and tried them once
in palm oil for a unique taste.
</P>
<P>
   SIDE DISH
</P>
<P>
   Bean Fritters (Akara)
</P>
<P>
   Makes 24 fritters
</P>
<P>
   Preparation time: 30-45 minutes Soaking time: overnight Cooking
time: 20-25 minutes
</P>
<P>
   2 cups dried Great Northern beans
</P>
<P>
   Oil for deep frying, preferably red palm oil
</P>
<P>
   1 1/2 cups cold water
</P>
<P>
   1/2 teaspoon finely minced habanero chile, or to taste
</P>
<P>
   1 small onion, finely minced
</P>
<P>
   Salt, to taste
</P>
<P>
   Prepare the beans by picking over them to remove any impurities
and broken or bad beans and soak them overnight in water to cover.
The next day, remove the skins from the beans by rubbing them
between your hands. (This can be a time-consuming step, so find a
partner.) Heat the oil for frying to 375 degrees in a heavy Dutch
oven or a deep fryer. Place the prepared beans in a meat grinder or
food processor and pulse until you have a smooth paste. Place the
paste in a large bowl. Beat the bean paste with a wooden spoon to
aerate it, and gradually add the water. Continue to beat while
adding the water. Use only enough water to make a mixture that will
fall easily from the spoon (too soupy and it will break apart in
the oil). Add the chile and onion and season to taste with salt.
Continue to stir so that all ingredients are well-mixed. When
ready, spoon the akara up by the tablespoonful and drop a few at a
time into the hot oil. Fry for 2 minutes on each side, or until
golden brown. Drain on absorbent paper. Serve hot.
</P>
<P>
   Per fritter: 133 calories, 4 grams protein, 9 grams fat (percent
calories from fat, 64), 9 grams carbohydrates, no cholesterol, 1
milligram sodium, 3 grams fiber.
</P>
<P>
   CAMEROON
</P>
<P>
   Like many cuisines, African food evolved as new folks and new
technologies arrived on its shores. But simplicity _ even when
combining local ingredients with more European techniques _ has
endured. Give this elegant mango cream a try. From ``The Africa
Cookbook,'' it's a dreamy end to any exotic meal.
</P>
<P>
   DESSERT
</P>
<P>
   Mango Cream
</P>
<P>
   Makes 6 servings
</P>
<P>
   Preparation time: 30 minutes Chilling time: 1 hour Cooking time:
10 minutes
</P>
<P>
   4 large mangoes
</P>
<P>
   1 cup heavy whipping cream
</P>
<P>
   3 tablespoons confectioners' sugar
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons freshly toasted Coconut Crisps (see note)
</P>
<P>
   Fresh mint, for garnish
</P>
<P>
   Peel the mangoes and cut in pieces. Place pieces in a medium
saucepan with water to cover and cook over low heat for 10 minutes,
or until very tender. When cooked, put through a food mill until it
is a thick pulp. Place pulp in a small bowl, cover with plastic
wrap and chill for 1 hour.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, whip the cream with an electric mixer or wire whisk,
slowly sprinkling in the sugar. When the mango pulp is chilled,
slowly fold in the sweetened cream, stirring only enough to make
sure that the ingredients are well-mixed. Pour the mango cream into
individual sherbet glasses, sprinkle each serving with some of the
toasted coconut, garnish with mint and serve.
</P>
<P>
   Note: To make Coconut Crisps, open a brown coconut by baking it
in a 350-degree oven for 10 minutes, then whacking it soundly with
a hammer on its ``fault line.'' Take out the coconut meat,
reserving liquid for other uses. Remove the brown rind from the
meat and pare the coconut into long, thin strips with a potato
peeler or paring knife. Place pieces on a cookie sheet and brown
them under the broiler for about 5 minutes, or until they are
lightly toasted. Watch them carefully, as they go from lightly
toasted to charred black in the blink of an eye. May also serve
warm with drinks.
</P>
<P>
   Per serving: 294 calories, 2 grams protein, 16 grams fat
(percent calories from fat, 49), 40 grams carbohydrates, 55
milligrams cholesterol, 20 milligrams sodium, 4 grams fiber.
</P>
<P>
   MOROCCO
</P>
<P>
   The foods of North Africa are heavily influenced by other
Mediterranean cuisines, so olive oils, couscous and flat breads are
common. Small vegetable salads are very popular, and this one from
``The Africa Cookbook'' shows how the foods of Africa often are
familiar foods with a twist _ such as the pairing of oranges and
radishes. It's a cool, tangy, sweet union. The orange flower water
can be found in many ethnic and gourmet groceries.
</P>
<P>
   SALAD
</P>
<P>
   Orange and Radish Salad
</P>
<P>
   Makes 6 servings Preparation time: 10 minutes Cooking time: 30
minutes
</P>
<P>
   1 bunch large red globe radishes (4 or 5 radishes)
</P>
<P>
   4 large navel oranges
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons fresh orange juice
</P>
<P>
   1 1/2 teaspoons orange flower water
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon
</P>
<P>
   confectioners'
</P>
<P>
   sugar
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon freshly
</P>
<P>
   squeezed
</P>
<P>
   lemon juice
</P>
<P>
   Wash the radishes. Cut off the green tops and the roots and
grate the radishes into a glass salad bowl. Peel the oranges and
segment them, reserving 2 tablespoons juice. Place the orange
segments in the bowl with the grated radish. Mix the orange flower
water, confectioners' sugar, lemon juice and reserved orange juice
together in a small bowl and pour the marinade over the
radish-and-orange mixture. Cover with plastic wrap and set aside
for 30 minutes so that the flavors mix. Serve at room temperature.
</P>
<P>
   Per serving: 52 calories, 1 gram protein, less than 1 gram fat
(percent calories from fat, 6), 13 grams carbohydrates, no
cholesterol, 9 milligrams sodium, 3 grams fiber.
</P>
<P>
   SOUTH AFRICA
</P>
<P>
   The southern tip of the continent is known for pickled fish,
ostrich filets and heady curries. Stews and such are popular here,
but the grilling can be sublime. Justin Anthony, owner of 10
Degrees South, shared this recipe for sosaties, succulent beef
kebabs.
</P>
<P>
   MAIN DISH
</P>
<P>
   Sosaties
</P>
<P>
   Makes 8 servings
</P>
<P>
   Preparation time: 45 minutes Marinating time: overnight Cooking
time: 7-10 minutes
</P>
<P>
   2 large onions, diced
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons oil
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon curry powder
</P>
<P>
   1/2 tablespoon salt
</P>
<P>
   1/2 tablespoon turmeric
</P>
<P>
   3 tablespoons granulated sugar
</P>
<P>
   3 tablespoons apricot jam
</P>
<P>
   4 bay leaves
</P>
<P>
   Pinch black pepper
</P>
<P>
   2 1/2 to 2 3/4 cups white vinegar
</P>
<P>
   3 pounds beef filet, cut in squares
</P>
<P>
   Saute onions in heated cooking oil until transparent. Add curry
powder and cook for 2 minutes. Add salt, turmeric, sugar, jam, bay
leaves and pepper. Stir constantly for 5 minutes. Add vinegar and
let simmer for 10 minutes. Remove saucepan from heat and allow to
cool. Skewer meat and arrange sosaties in a deep dish and cover
with cooled marinade. Allow the dish to marinate overnight in the
refrigerator before grilling. Grill over hot coals or fairly high
heat about 5 minutes on each side or to desired doneness.
</P>
<P>
   Per serving: 306 calories, 37 grams protein, 14 grams fat
(percent calories from fat, 40), 7 grams carbohydrates, 107
milligrams cholesterol, 119 milligrams sodium, 1 gram fiber.
</P>
<P>
   Reagan Walker writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
