<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-17 13:50 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8649 &Cx1f; tad-z
u d &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FOOD-AFRICAN18-COX     02-17 1380
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FOOD-AFRICAN18-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Just a few `riffs' of improvisation lets you trace, taste
continent's history with dishes both familiar and exotic
 &HT;    By Reagan Walker
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Jessica Harris pops a compact disc into the stereo. To
the sway and beat of African tunes, she tosses a cut-up chicken
with her bare hands in a bath of peanut oil, fresh lemon juice and
translucent-thin onion slices. Then she adds an extra flavor burst
_ a fork-pricked, orange-hot habanero pepper.
</P>
<P>
   This is just the beginning of the Senegalese classic, Chicken
Yassa, and of an afternoon of cooking with the renowned African
food scholar and cookbook author.
</P>
<P>
   ``I consider Chicken Yassa my good luck dish,'' says Harris, who
is touring the country promoting her latest effort, ``The Africa
Cookbook: Tastes of a Continent'' (Simon &AMP; Schuster, $25.) ``It was
my first taste that let me know what it is.''
</P>
<P>
   That is to say, this dish defines African food _ at once
familiar and exotic.
</P>
<P>
   That defining moment came to Harris on her first trip to Africa
in the early '70s. She and her mother ventured off the beaten path
in Dakar, Senegal, and into a small restaurant, where the tables
were set with tie-dyed fabric and lampshades made from woven
baskets. One bite of the Chicken Yassa and, ``it's been love ever
since.''
</P>
<P>
   In the decades that have followed, she has traversed the
continent, seeking out exotic spices in the open-air markets of
North Africa, eating blood sausage on a dare in Kenya. Her research
has resulted in a collection of cookbooks on African foods and the
cuisines it has inspired, including Caribbean, Brazilian and
African-American.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can trace a whole history in a bean fritter,'' says the
51-year-old Harris, a New York native and English professor at
Queens College. The akara, or white bean fritter, is the definitive
dish of Nigeria, she explains. But that fritter gives way to the
porridge fritter in East Africa, the black-eyed pea fritter in
Brazil, the bean fritters of the Caribbean and the corn fritters of
the United States.
</P>
<P>
   Getting to ``the matrix'' of so many cuisines was the goal of
``The Africa Cookbook,'' Harris says. From Africa come radishes,
onions, okra, watermelon, black-eyed peas and coffee. And foods
such as tomatoes, potatoes and chiles arrived there from other
continents so long ago _ the early 16th century _ that most
Africans would be hard-pressed to acknowledge they are not
indigenous, Harris explains.
</P>
<P>
   But while those foods, and the stewing, grilling and frying of
them, are so prevalent in other cultures, including ours, African
cuisine remains a mystery to most Americans. Harris says that's
because we tend to ignore Africa _ which is oceans away
geographically and culturally.
</P>
<P>
   ``It can be hard for us to understand Africa since we live in
the country of the TV set, the Big Gulp and the wide highway,''
Harris says. ``One way to learn is through something everyone is
intimately connected with. That's the food.''
</P>
<P>
   Interest in African food has grown steadily since she began her
work years ago, Harris says. Immigration has increased, and so has
cultural and business exchange with the continent.
</P>
<P>
   One sign of the growing interest is the slew of cookbooks
released in recent years focusing on African and African-inspired
cuisines, such as ``Soul and Spice: African Cooking in the
Americas'' and ``Mother Africa's Table''.
</P>
<P>
   Growing participation in Kwanzaa, held annually from Dec. 26 to
Jan. 1, also is fueling interest, especially in the
African-American community, she says. Several cookbooks offering
menus based on traditional African and African-American dishes have
been written in the past five years to help guide the estimated 13
million participants in the holiday.
</P>
<P>
   Harris says immigration has played a key role. First, because
friendships formed on a personal level open culinary doors.
</P>
<P>
   That was the case with Eartha Whitfield, mother of Atlanta
Falcons player Bob Whitfield. She learned how to make a dish called
palaver from a recent Ghanian immigrant. It's now a favorite among
some Falcons such as Jamal Anderson and Morten Andersen.
</P>
<P>
   More often, immigrants open restaurants, Harris says, and they
attract not only other immigrants but adventurous eaters as well.
</P>
<P>
   ``In D.C., you see a lot of Ethiopian restaurants, in New York
it's Senegalese. It all depends on who migrates into a neighborhood
or a community,'' she says. In Atlanta, at least three new African
restaurants have opened in the past year, joining a handful of
existing ones.
</P>
<P>
   At Queen of Sheba, you can scoop up spicy beef tips with the
spongy bread called injera. At the Moroccan-themed Casbah, you can
use your hands to dig into mounds of couscous with grilled lamb or
fish. And at 10 Degrees South, you can sample South African
specialties such as ostrich filets or sosaties _ tangy kebabs
seared on a grill.
</P>
<P>
   The diversity among the restaurants and cuisines illustrates the
wide array of foods from the continent. That also is apparent in
the kitchen with Harris, who can be authoritarian and exact or
loose and relaxed, depending on what the moment _ and the dish _
requires.
</P>
<P>
   Harris demonstrates how to segment oranges with great precision.
Then she mixes the wedges with grated radishes and a splash of
orange flower water. One taste and you greet Morocco.
</P>
<P>
   In more free-form fashion, she blanches tomatoes and okra and
douses them with a little vinaigrette for a simple taste of popular
African staples.
</P>
<P>
   For a dreamy dessert, Harris cooks mango chunks slightly, then
forces them through a strainer. She then folds this mush into
sweetened whipped cream and tops it with toasted coconut _ a dish
from Cameroon that blends European traditions with local
ingredients.
</P>
<P>
   And, of course, the yassa. After allowing it to marinate for
several hours, Harris sears the chicken on a hot grill for a few
minutes. Then she dumps it into an iron stewpot with carrots,
pimento-stuffed olives, a touch of Dijon mustard and that sassy
habanero. Sounds simple, but the three stages _ marinating,
grilling and stewing _ give the dish a fabulously complex flavor.
</P>
<P>
   Harris admits that, with the mustard and the olives, it's a
jazzier version than that first taste in Dakar. But variation on a
theme is how African cuisine became so influential _ it can be
adapted to the times, the place, the person.
</P>
<P>
   ``We improvise everything we put our hands on,'' Harris says.
``We have riffs in clothes, in music, in writing and in food.''
</P>
<P>
   EXPERIENCING AFRICA AT HOME
</P>
<P>
   Whether you're looking for a place to sample some African
cuisine, are hunting for that red palm oil to fry up some bean
fritters or want to cook more African recipes, this list of
resources should get you started.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  NOTEWORTHY COOKBOOKS WITH AFRICAN RECIPES:
</P>
<P>
   The Africa Cookbook: Tastes of a Continent, Jessica B. Harris,
Simon &AMP; Schuster, $25.
</P>
<P>
   Mother Africa's Table, National Council of Negro Women, Main
Street Books, $18.95.
</P>
<P>
   Flavors of Africa Cookbook, DeWitt/Wilan/Stock, Prima
Publishing, $16.
</P>
<P>
   The Dishes of Africa, Princess Ngozi Kachikwu, Wimmer Companies,
$19.95.
</P>
<P>
   The African-American Kitchen, Angela Shelf Medearis, Plume
Paperbacks, $14.95.
</P>
<P>
   Soul and Spice, Heidi Haughy Cusick, Chronicle Books, $16.95.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  A SAMPLING OF ATLANTA AREA AFRICAN RESTAURANTS:
</P>
