<HEADER>
A8650 &Cx1f; tad-z
u d &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FOOD-AFRICAN-RECIPES1     02-17 1796
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FOOD-AFRICAN-RECIPES1stTAKE18- </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Experience the diverse tastes of a continent
 &HT;    By Reagan Walker
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ If we are guided by pervasive images in the media, we
might believe that there is no such thing as African food.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you watch TV, you see Africans starving to death. We
think they don't eat at all,'' said Eartha Whitfield, mother of
Atlanta Falcons player Bob Whitfield. ``In fact, they eat very
healthy, very delicious food.''
</P>
<P>
   Whitfield discovered this when she struck up a friendship with
an immigrant from Ghana, who introduced her to palaver, a spicy
mixture of meat and spinach. She's made it for many of the Falcons
and it's become a favorite.
</P>
<P>
   The palaver is best when cooked in a cast-iron pot or Dutch
oven, as are many African dishes. Major culinary techniques derive
from the traditional three-rock stove, which is an open fire inside
a border of three large rocks.
</P>
<P>
   With that as the principle source of heat, recipes were
developed around boiling in water, steaming in leaves, frying in
deep oil, grilling beside the fire, roasting in the fire and baking
in the ashes. That's why in traditional African cooking stews are
so popular, baked breads not so.
</P>
<P>
   Today, those traditional techniques cross with modern means and
indigenous foods meet intercontinental influences.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our cuisine is largely Portuguese and Malaysian, with a French
influence,'' said Justin Anthony, owner of 10 Degrees South, a
South African restaurant in Atlanta. ``People in Atlanta have been
surprised to learn that South Africa is such a melting pot.''
</P>
<P>
   That's the story across the continent. We offer here a culinary
tour of Africa intended to pique your interest and please the taste
buds.
</P>
<P>
   ETHIOPIA AND EAST AFRICA
</P>
<P>
   The traditional way to eat in Ethiopia is from a large communal
platter lined with injera, a spongy, pancakelike bread. Instead of
utensils, more injera is torn and used to scoop up savory stews and
vegetables. Our recipe is adapted, coming close in texture. Serve
it with a national favorite, Doro We't, a rich, spicy chicken stew
with whole boiled eggs. Another favorite along the eastern coast of
Africa is fish curry. Here we offer a simple version combining
curry, coconut and black pepper.
</P>
<P>
   MAIN DISH
</P>
<P>
   Chicken Doro We't
</P>
<P>
   Makes 4 servings Preparation time: 20 minutes Marinating time:
30 minutes Cooking time: 1 hour
</P>
<P>
   1 chicken (about 3 pounds), cut in small pieces
</P>
<P>
   3 tablespoons lemon juice
</P>
<P>
   1 large onion, chopped
</P>
<P>
   2 cloves garlic, chopped
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons butter or margarine
</P>
<P>
   2 teaspoons ground ginger
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon ground black pepper
</P>
<P>
   1/4 teaspoon ground cardamom
</P>
<P>
   1/4 teaspoon ground nutmeg
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup Berbere Paste (recipe below)
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons paprika
</P>
<P>
   Water as needed
</P>
<P>
   4 hard-cooked eggs, peeled, whole
</P>
<P>
   Remove the skin and score the chicken so the sauce will
penetrate the meat. Rub the chicken with the lemon juice and let it
marinate for 30 minutes at room temperature.
</P>
<P>
   In a five-quart Dutch oven over medium heat, saute the onion and
garlic in the butter until browned. Add the ginger, pepper,
cardamom, nutmeg, Berbere Paste and paprika and cook for 2 to 3
minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Add the chicken to the pan and toss to coat. Stir in enough
water to form a thick sauce. Bring to a boil, reduce the heat,
cover and simmer for 30 minutes or until the meat starts to fall
off the bone. Using a fork, poke holes all over the eggs, then add
them to the stew. Simmer for an additional 15 minutes. Serve with
injera (recipe at left). _ From ``Flavors of Africa Cookbook''
(Prima Publishing, $16)
</P>
<P>
   Per serving: 475 calories, 49 grams protein, 25 grams fat
(percent calories from fat, 48), 12 grams carbohydrates, 338
milligrams cholesterol, 268 milligrams sodium, 3 grams fiber.
</P>
<P>
   SAUCE
</P>
<P>
   Berbere Paste
</P>
<P>
   Makes 1 cup Preparation time: 10 minutes Cooking time: 20
minutes
</P>
<P>
   4 whole cardamom pods
</P>
<P>
   2 teaspoons cumin seed
</P>
<P>
   1/2 teaspoon black peppercorns
</P>
<P>
   1/2 teaspoon fenugreek seed
</P>
<P>
   1 small onion, coarsely chopped
</P>
<P>
   4 cloves garlic
</P>
<P>
   1 cup water
</P>
<P>
   15 dried piquin chiles, stems removed
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon ground cayenne
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons ground paprika
</P>
<P>
   1/2 teaspoon ground ginger
</P>
<P>
   1/4 teaspoon ground allspice
</P>
<P>
   1/2 teaspoon ground nutmeg
</P>
<P>
   1/4 teaspoon ground cloves
</P>
<P>
   3 tablespoons vegetable oil
</P>
<P>
   In a hot skillet, toast the cardamom pods, cumin seeds,
peppercorns and fenugreek seeds, shaking constantly for a couple of
minutes until they start to crackle and ``pop.'' In a spice mill,
grind these spices to form a powder.
</P>
<P>
   In a blender container, combine the onion, garlic and 1/2 cup
water and puree until smooth. Add the chiles, cayenne, paprika,
ground toasted spices, ginger, allspice, nutmeg and cloves and
continue to blend. Slowly add the remaining water and the oil and
blend until smooth. Remove to a saucepan and simmer the sauce for
15-20 minutes to blend the flavors and thicken. This very spicy
sauce will keep for 2 months in the refrigerator. Serve as a
condiment to grilled meats and poultry or add to soups and stews. _
From ``Flavors of Africa Cookbook'' (Prima Publishing, $16)
</P>
<P>
   Per tablespoon: 41 calories, 1 gram protein, 3 grams fat
(percent calories from fat, 64), 4 grams carbohydrates, no
cholesterol, 3 milligrams sodium, 1 gram fiber.
</P>
<P>
   BREAD
</P>
<P>
   Injera
</P>
<P>
   Makes 6 servings Preparation time: 10 minutes Cooking time:
about 4 minutes per pancake
</P>
<P>
   4 1/2 cups self-rising flour
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup whole-wheat flour
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon baking powder
</P>
<P>
   2 cups unflavored club soda
</P>
<P>
   4 cups water
</P>
<P>
   In a large mixing bowl, combine the self-rising flour,
whole-wheat flour and baking powder. Add the club soda and water
and stir until the batter is smooth. It will be thin. Heat a large
nonstick skillet over medium heat until a drop of water bounces in
the bottom of the pan. Measure out 1/2 cup of the batter and pour
into pan like a pancake. Allow to cook until small holes appear on
the surface and it is set. Remove from pan. Injera is cooked on one
side only. The bread will appear slightly moist when done. Stack
the bread rounds on top of each other and cover with a light towel
until serving. Tear the bread and use to scoop up tastes. _ From
``Flavors of Africa Cookbook'' (Prima Publishing, $16)
</P>
<P>
   Per serving: 360 calories, 10 grams protein, 1 gram fat (percent
calories from fat, 3), 76 grams carbohydrates, no cholesterol,
1,300 milligrams sodium, 4 grams fiber.
</P>
<P>
   MAIN DISH
</P>
<P>
   Fresh Fish in Coconut Cream of Curry
</P>
<P>
   Makes 6 servings Preparation time: 10 minutes Cooking time: 30
minutes
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons butter
</P>
<P>
   1 onion, thinly sliced
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon salt
</P>
<P>
   2 teaspoons black pepper
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon crushed red pepper
</P>
<P>
   4 pounds whole fresh fish (bass, snapper, halibut or any fish,
heads removed, and filleted) or 2 pounds fillets
</P>
<P>
   3 cups coconut cream or milk
</P>
<P>
   4 tablespoons curry powder
</P>
<P>
   Preheat oven to 400 degrees. In a saucepan, melt butter and add
onion, salt, black pepper and red pepper. Add fish and saute for 3
minutes on each side. Pour the coconut milk and curry powder over
the fish. Put fish in a baking pan and pour mixture over it. Cover
with foil and bake for 30 minutes. _ From ``The Dishes of Africa''
(Wimmer Companies, $19.95)
</P>
<P>
   Per serving (with coconut cream): 485 calories, 35 grams
protein, 35 grams fat (percent calories from fat, 65), 11 grams
carbohydrates, 66 milligrams cholesterol, 552 milligrams sodium, 5
grams fiber.
</P>
<P>
   SENEGAL
</P>
<P>
   A traditional Chicken Yassa combines three steps _ marinating,
broiling/grilling and stewing. Some are as simple as chicken and
onions; others, like this version that is a favorite of Jessica
Harris, has carrots and olives. It is well worth the three-step
process. Also from Senegal, we include peanut butter stew made with
lamb. Peanut (or groundnut) stews are widely popular in Africa,
with many variations. We found this one rich and wonderful _
reminding us of some of our favorite Thai dishes. More proof that
you just can't go wrong with peanut butter. The stew also can be
made with beef or chicken. Both come from Jessica Harris' ``The
Africa Cookbook: Tastes of a Continent.''
</P>
<P>
   MAIN DISH
</P>
<P>
   Chicken Yassa
</P>
<P>
   Makes 6 servings
</P>
<P>
   Preparation time: 25 minutes Marinating time: 3 hours to
overnight Cooking time: 45-55 minutes
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup freshly squeezed lemon juice
</P>
<P>
   4 large onions, thinly sliced
</P>
<P>
   Salt and freshly ground black pepper, to taste
</P>
<P>
   1/8 teaspoon minced fresh habanero chile, or to taste
</P>
<P>
   5 tablespoons peanut oil, divided
</P>
<P>
   1 frying chicken (2 1/2 to 3 1/2 pounds), cut in serving pieces
</P>
<P>
   1 habanero chile, pricked with a fork
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup pimento-stuffed olives
</P>
<P>
   4 carrots, scraped and thinly sliced
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon Dijon-style mustard
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup water
</P>
<P>
   In a large nonreactive bowl, prepare a marinade by mixing the
lemon juice, onions, salt, pepper, minced chile and 4 tablespoons
of the peanut oil. Place the chicken pieces in the marinade, making
sure they are all well-covered. Cover the bowl with plastic wrap
and allow the chicken to marinate for at least 3 hours in the
refrigerator.
</P>
<P>
   Preheat the broiler. Remove the chicken pieces, reserving the
marinade and onions, and place the chicken in a shallow pan. Broil
the chicken until it is lightly browned on both sides.
(Alternately, you can grill until chicken is seared on each side.)
</P>
<P>
   Remove the onions from the marinade. Heat the remaining
tablespoon of oil in a flameproof 5-quart casserole or Dutch oven
and cook the onions slowly until tender and translucent. Add the
reserved marinade. When the liquid is thoroughly heated, add the
chicken pieces, pricked chile, olives, carrots, mustard and water.
When the dish has reached the desired degree of hotness, remove the
chile and reserve (it can be served separately to the
``chileheads''). Stir to mix well, then bring the yassa slowly to a
boil. Lower the heat and simmer, covered, for about 30 minutes, or
until the chicken is cooked through. Serve hot over white rice.
</P>
<P>
   Per serving: 364 calories, 31 grams protein, 20 grams fat
(percent calories from fat, 50), 14 grams carbohydrates, 93
milligrams cholesterol, 211 milligrams sodium, 3 grams fiber.
</P>
<P>
   MAIN DISH
</P>
<P>
   Mafe (Peanut Butter Stew)
</P>
<P>
   Makes 4 servings Preparation time: 10 minutes Cooking time: 1
hour
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons peanut oil
</P>
<P>
   1 large onion, minced
</P>
<P>
   2 pounds lamb stew meat, cut in 1 1/2-inch pieces
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup creamy peanut butter
</P>
<P>
   1 1/2 cups cold water
</P>
<P>
   1/3 cup tomato paste
</P>
<P>
   2 cups hot water
</P>
<P>
   4 large carrots, scraped and cut in 1-inch pieces
</P>
<P>
   3 sprigs fresh thyme
</P>
<P>
   2 bay leaves
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
