<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Kitchen counter on cutting edge of curative cuisine
 &HT;    By Betty Parham
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   New technology and cutting-edge nutritional research have led
many medical and scientific experts to conclude what everybody and
their great-grandmother have known forever _ that real and
substantial relief can come from over the counter _ the kitchen
counter, that is.
</P>
<P>
   People from all cultures have always known that curative
cuisine, from chicken soup (they don't call it Jewish penicillin
for nothing) to soups and teas made with curry, chile peppers,
ginger, garlic, citrus, horseradish and a host of other foods often
provide real relief for the ills of mankind.
</P>
<P>
   What we call ``feeling better,'' scientific researchers are
calling the effects of phytochemicals. Medical science has begun to
test and recognize that substances called phytochemicals, which are
neither vitamins nor minerals but are found in most fruits and
vegetables by the tens of thousands, contain potent therapeutic
properties that often dramatically relieve and sometimes even
eliminate certain illnesses.
</P>
<P>
   There is so much interest in these ``nutraceuticals'' that
public and private laboratories, including the National Cancer
Institute, are stepping up research by spending millions of dollars
to see how best to identify, extract and use phytochemicals to
create new drugs that in coming decades may be used to fight
diseases from the common cold to cancer.
</P>
<P>
   At
http://www.phys.com/bnutrition/01selfanalysis/05colds/colds.html, a
site sponsored by Conde Nast in collaboration with Tufts
University, you can find the latest in this exciting field of
nutritional research. But the best part of the site is how we can
use what is known now in our own kitchens to whip up culinary
curatives when the need arises.
</P>
<P>
   In a section called ``The Culinary Chemist,'' you will find
detailed information on phytochemically rich foods along with
recipes that can help relieve debilitating symptoms of a number of
ailments.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Symptom Advisor'' asks you to check off certain symptoms
you may be experiencing, from congestion to nausea to diarrhea to
headaches, and then ``prescribes'' a dish that may help. It also
advises, of course, that under certain circumstances you should see
a physician.
</P>
<P>
   Here are other interesting sites to visit:
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  At ``Flu Food,'' at
http://www.ab.sympatico.ca/Contents/Health/HEALTHYWAY/recflu.html,
you will find informative articles from various sources including
Better Homes and Gardens, CNN, Redbook and others concerning
kitchen remedies. There also are lots of recipes.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Http://www.naturalland.com/ is an interactive site where you
chat and pick up tips about healing foods, fitness and nutrition.
It changes daily. A recent tip of the day: ``Celery juice has a
mild diuretic effect, similar to many drugs that are prescribed for
high blood pressure. The juice is highly nutritious and can be
helpful for people who need to balance their blood pressure.''
Another imparted this bit of nutritional wisdom: ``For optimum skin
repair and healing, increase intake of foods rich in vitamin A and
zinc. Good sources for vitamin A are carrots, sweet potatoes,
butternut squash and mangoes. Zinc is found in wheat germ, lima
beans, legumes and nuts.'' Good stuff here.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  At
http://www.ivillage.com/food/articles/0,3035,221(tilde)77,00.html,
you will find an excellent article entitled ``Cures in Your
Cupboard'' by nutritionist Sue Gilbert, who, while she doesn't go
into phytochemical research, does gi/ve sound nutritional
information about different foods.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  And, finally, at
http://www.betterbaking.com/baker2/delisou.html you will find the
classic, Jewish penicillin.
</P>
<P>
   SOUP
</P>
<P>
   Bronchitis Broth
</P>
<P>
   Makes 15 servings of broth and vegetables; may be served
separately Preparation time: 40 minutes Cooking time: 1 hour, 10
minutes
</P>
<P>
   Pulmonary specialist Dr. Irwin Ziment at the University of
California-Los Angeles faxed the recipe he gives his patients, and
we started from there. After cooking the chopped vegetables for 30
minutes, you can refrigerate the broth and complete it up to two
days later. For a light broth, strain out the vegetables before
adding the garlic and other ingredients. (Don't discard the
vegetables; they're terrific over brown rice or couscous.) By the
way, this soup is delicious even if your breathing is fine.
</P>
<P>
   2 1/2 tablespoons olive oil
</P>
<P>
   1 medium onion, peeled and chopped
</P>
<P>
   1 pound carrots (6 or 7 medium), peeled, scraped and chopped
</P>
<P>
   1 bunch (1 1/4 pounds) celery with leafy tops, chopped
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon curry powder
</P>
<P>
   1 or 2 teaspoons ground cayenne pepper, or to taste
</P>
<P>
   12 cups low-sodium canned chicken broth, or water or half of
each
</P>
<P>
   2 heads garlic, cloves lightly smashed, peeled and sliced
</P>
<P>
   5 dried whole red chile peppers (finger-size peppers)
</P>
<P>
   1 bunch fresh cilantro, chopped medium
</P>
<P>
   1 bunch fresh mint, chopped medium
</P>
<P>
   1 bunch fresh basil, chopped medium (optional)
</P>
<P>
   1 bunch fresh parsley, chopped medium (optional)
</P>
<P>
   Squirt of fresh lemon juice
</P>
<P>
   2 teaspoons each kosher salt and pepper, or to taste
</P>
<P>
   Heat the oil in a Dutch oven over medium heat. Stir in onion,
carrots, celery, curry powder and cayenne pepper and cook for 20
minutes, stirring occasionally, until vegetables are soft. Add
broth or water and bring to a boil on high heat. Reduce heat to
medium and simmer 30 minutes. Add garlic, chile peppers, cilantro,
mint, basil and parsley; cover and bring to a boil on high heat.
Reduce heat to medium-low and simmer 20 minutes. Remove peppers
with a slotted spoon and discard. Add lemon juice and salt and
pepper to taste. Strain, if desired, and serve vegetables over
brown rice or couscous. Serve hot. _ From ``Tonics'' by Robert A.
Barnett
</P>
<P>
   Per serving (broth and vegetables): 43 calories, 1 gram protein,
2 grams fat (percent calories from fat, 43), 6 grams carbohydrates,
no cholesterol, 290 milligrams sodium, 2 grams fiber.
</P>
<P>
   DESSERT
</P>
<P>
   Minted Pink Grapefruit Sorbet
</P>
<P>
   Makes 9 servings Preparation time: 20 minutes Cooking time: 15
minutes Cooling time: 20 minutes Freezing time: 4 hours
</P>
<P>
   If you can find ruby-fleshed grapefruit for this light,
refreshing dessert, snap it up. The sorbet is undiluted, so it's an
appealing tea-rose color. If you like a sweet sorbet, add more
sugar. And if you use yellow-fleshed grapefruit, you might want to
add even more sugar, as they can be bitter.
</P>
<P>
   4 1/2 pounds ruby- or pink-fleshed grapefruit (4 to 6, depending
on size)
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup granulated sugar, or more to taste
</P>
<P>
   1/2 bunch fresh mint,
</P>
<P>
   washed and stemmed, divided and several leaves reserved for
garnish; remainder chopped
</P>
<P>
   16 whole cloves
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon fresh lemon juice
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon vanilla extract
</P>
<P>
   Juice grapefruit to yield 4 to 4 1/2 cups juice. Collect pulp
from juicer and add it to the juice. In a saucepan, combine 1 cup
juice with sugar, chopped mint and cloves. Bring to a boil over
medium-high heat, stirring occasionally. Reduce heat to medium and
cook until sugar dissolves, about 5 minutes. Reduce heat to low and
simmer, stirring occasionally, for 10 minutes. Set aside to cool,
about 15 minutes. Strain the cooled liquid through a fine sieve
into the remaining juice, pressing down with a spoon to extract
liquid. Stir in lemon juice and vanilla. Pour into an ice cream
maker and process according to manufacturer's instructions. If you
don't have an ice cream maker, pour mixture into two 9-inch pie
pans or 4 ice cube trays and freeze until hard, about 4 hours. When
ready to serve, let sit at room temperature about 5 minutes to
loosen up. If using pie pans, break sorbet into chunks and process
in a food processor in two batches until smooth and light in color,
about 3 minutes per batch. Serve topped with the reserved mint
leaves. The sorbet can be packed into tightly covered plastic
containers and frozen. Since it doesn't contain a lot of sugar,
which acts as a preservative, it should be used within 3 or 4 days.
_ From ``Tonics'' by Robert A. Barnett
</P>
<P>
   Per serving: 87 calories, 1 gram protein, no fat, 22 grams
carbohydrates, no cholesterol, 8 milligrams sodium, 1 gram fiber.
</P>
<P>
   Betty Parham writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
