<SLUG> BC-FOOD-RECIPESWAP18-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    German chocolate in a crust
 &HT;    By Marcia Langhenry
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Dorothy Phillips of Dallas, Ga., sent this German
Chocolate Pie in response to an e-mail plea from Tiffany Kramer,
who said she'd had one 25 years ago. She remembers a pie that's
closer to a brownie than a pie and is not at all cakelike. The one
she remembered called for cocoa, while this one uses baking
chocolate. It is crunchy on top and mousselike in the center.
</P>
<P>
   DESSERT
</P>
<P>
   German Chocolate Pie
</P>
<P>
   Makes 8 servings Preparation time: 15 minutes Cooking time:
50-60 minutes
</P>
<P>
   4 ounces ( 1/2 cup) German sweet cooking chocolate
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup butter
</P>
<P>
   2 large eggs
</P>
<P>
   1 1/2 cups granulated sugar
</P>
<P>
   3 tablespoons cornstarch
</P>
<P>
   1/8 teaspoon salt
</P>
<P>
   1 can (12 ounces) evaporated milk
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon vanilla extract
</P>
<P>
   1 10-inch unbaked deep-dish pie shell
</P>
<P>
   1 can (3 1/2 ounces) flaked coconut
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup coarsely chopped pecans
</P>
<P>
   Preheat oven to 350 degrees. Melt chocolate and butter in small
saucepan over low heat, stirring occasionally. Remove from heat and
set aside. In medium bowl, beat eggs until light and fluffy. Add
sugar, cornstarch and salt, beating until smooth. Blend in
chocolate mixture. Gradually add milk and vanilla, mixing until
smooth. Pour into pie shell; set aside. In small bowl, mix coconut
and pecans; sprinkle over filling. Bake 50 to 60 minutes, until
puffed and lightly browned. If top browns too quickly, cover
loosely with foil the last 15 minutes of baking.
</P>
<P>
   Per serving: 589 calories, 8 grams protein, 32 grams fat
(percent calories from fat, 49), 70 grams carbohydrates, 108
milligrams cholesterol, 294 milligrams sodium, 2 grams fiber.
</P>
<P>
   Requests
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``Does anyone remember the Russian Tea Cakes at the old
Manhattan Bakery on Cheshire Bridge?'' asks Judy Merlin (e-mail).
``Is there a recipe for these floating around? I loved these as a
child and would love to make them again.''
</P>
<P>
   See ``Where to Write,'' .
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``I had my first boiled custard this past Christmas but was
unable to purchase this product after the holiday,'' says Nina
Whitfield of Roswell (Ga.). ``Does anyone have a recipe for this
wonderful drink _ which I would imagine is very high in calories?''
</P>
<P>
   Marcia Langhenry writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
