<HEADER>
A8653 &Cx1f; tad-z
u d &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FOOD-SKUBE-BEERCOLUMN     02-17 0774
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FOOD-SKUBE-BEERCOLUMN18-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Making a mark of distinction a matter of basics not gimmicks
 &HT;    By Michael Skube
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The heyday of hemp and hashish has long since faded,
as distant from the here and now as Woodstock or Jefferson
Airplane. But hemp had been around, in many uses, long before the
'60s. It's what we made rope from, after all.
</P>
<P>
   But beer?
</P>
<P>
   Over the centuries, people have made beer from whatever
indigenous materials were at hand, whether they be cassava root or
cactus, and no doubt hemp was pressed into service for brewing as
well as smoking. But today the science of brewing is
well-established, its basic ingredients fairly standard around the
world: malted barley (sometimes with additions of wheat, oat or
rye), lager or ale yeast, hops and water. It's the art that varies,
from style to style and brewer to brewer. What malts and in what
proportions? Which hops and at what stage of the brewing process?
Which yeast strains? How long the fermentation?
</P>
<P>
   It is both art and science.
</P>
<P>
   Which is why Frederick Brewing Co. had nothing hallucinogenic in
mind when it decided to add crushed hemp seed to the grist. It was
looking for something to set its Hempen Ale apart from so many
other brown ales.
</P>
<P>
   If it piques the curiosity, so much the better. But, as
brewmaster Tim Keck says, it wasn't something just tossed in for
the fun of it. ``Hemp,'' he says, ``can be hard to work with. You
don't always get the clarity you want, so you have to be careful.''
</P>
<P>
   Done well, brewing with hemp seed can impart a subtle earthiness
to the flavor. Rye _ also difficult to work with _ is used for
similar reasons, although its effect is different.
</P>
<P>
   ``The aim was to make a brown ale, but one that was a little
spicier than most,'' Keck says.
</P>
<P>
   Hempen Ale is certainly that, not spicy in the manner of winter
seasonal beers but noticeable enough that you know it's not the
usual brown ale. This is, in fact, quite a good one, fuller bodied
than most (but not heavy) and more complex in taste.
</P>
<P>
   As an accompaniment to food, a brown ale is usually relegated to
the nuts and the side dishes. But this is a brown ale that can
stand up to steaks and to slathery burgers.
</P>
<P>
   Hemp makes up about 10 percent of the grist, the rest being
barley, and the Cascade hops in the finish give it a robustness
seldom found in a brown ale. English-style brown ales are typically
a beginner's ale, soft on the palate but with nothing much in the
way of complexity. Of late, American craft brewers have been
redefining the category in innovative ways, and what could be newer
_ or older _ than hemp?
</P>
<P>
   What works in one beer, though, doesn't always work in another.
Hempen Gold, a companion beer from the Frederick, Md., brewery, is
called a cream ale, meaning a light-bodied, very pale brew of low
alcohol content and almost no hop character.
</P>
<P>
   Cream ales have a long history in the United States and have had
their devotees. At one time, they were enjoyed as alternatives to
the growing dominance of mass-market lagers. But some cream ales
were ales in name only, and others were odd mixtures of ale and
lager.
</P>
<P>
   Hempen Gold, with hemp constituting 20 percent of the grist, is
top-fermented like all ales, but it is a beer whose flavor _ what
there is of it _ is entirely in the foretaste. It hits you and
almost evaporates. A real beer will unfold its character in the
mid-taste and leave its signature in the aftertaste.
</P>
<P>
   This beer was designed for other purposes. ``We were aiming for
more of a mass audience,'' Keck concedes.
</P>
<P>
   If you're intent on using hemp, a better way to reach that
audience might have been the way Lexington Brewing of Lexington,
Ky., has. Instead of trying to make an extremely light ale, it
brewed a Coors-like lager and even used rice (10 percent), the
ingredient that gives mass-market beers their crispness but also
their blandness.
</P>
<P>
   Kentucky Hemp Beer is different in another way, too. Hemp is
used in the hopping process rather than as part of the grist, the
aim being to give the aroma a slight earthiness. But in a beer so
lightly hopped to begin with, the effect goes all but undetected.
</P>
<P>
   You wonder what the point really was. The best way to set your
beer apart is still the old-fashioned way, choosing your malts with
care and balancing the hops like a painter with his colors. Do it
well and you don't need the odd, eye-catching ingredient. The beer
will speak for itself.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Skube writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
