<SLUG> BC-CAREERS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MINNESOTA ENVELOPE MAVERICK OFFERS WISDOM ON SUCCESS 
</HEADLINE>
   (EDs: Note optional trim)  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By DAVE MURPHY  
 c.1998 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ The man who built his career around selling
envelopes has come out with another mixed bag.
</P>
<P>
   Bestselling author Harvey Mackay's latest motivational book,
``Pushing the Envelope All the Way to the Top,'' doesn't fit neatly
into any sort of career category. He warns executives about why
companies fail, explains how he has attracted workers to his Mackay
Envelope Corp. in Minneapolis and describes the traits that help
people rise to the top.
</P>
<P>
   Mackay is the author of such other books as ``Swim With the
Sharks Without Being Eaten Alive'' and ``Beware the Naked Man Who
Offers You His Shirt.'' Here are some of his observations, taken
from the new book and an interview earlier this month:
</P>
<P>
   _ Companies get in trouble for three main reasons: arrogance,
arrogance and arrogance.
</P>
<P>
   In the interview, Mackay recalled how a friend named Don Burr
sat with him and scribbled ideas on a napkin about the airline that
Burr wanted to create. ``Fifteen months later, his picture is on
the cover of Time magazine.''
</P>
<P>
   Burr's airline, Peoples Express, became a huge success _ and
then a huge failure. Mackay said Burr later attributed much of the
failure to arrogance; company leaders were so pleased with their
success that they didn't think about how larger competitors could
move into their routes and clobber them.
</P>
<P>
   Workers run into the same sort of complacency, Mackay said. They
think a job will be theirs forever, so they don't work as hard as
they can to keep it, or worry about networking to set up other job
possibilities.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you go to work, it's a boundaryless company,'' Mackay
said. ``You don't fall in love with your corporation because the
corporation may not love you back.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Many times determination makes the difference.
</P>
<P>
   ``I remember when I was first starting out,'' Mackay writes,
``and asking a colleague I respected how many calls he would make
on a prospect before giving up. He told me: `It depends on which
one of us dies first.'''
</P>
<P>
   Job hunters can benefit from the same sort of determination. In
the book, Mackay describes how a recent college graduate dealt with
getting rejected.
</P>
<P>
   ``One busy personnel manager, flooded with applications,
suggested the hopeful applicant check back in 10 years. `No
problem,' the young woman responded. `Would a morning or afternoon
interview work best for you?'''
</P>
<P>
   Determination also helps people keep jobs while their colleagues
are being laid off, Mackay said in the interview. ``There will
always be a place in this world for anyone who says, `I'll take
care of that,' and then performs.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Don't stifle creativity.
</P>
<P>
   One chapter lists 25 things people say that kills creativity,
including ``Great idea! Let's form a committee to tackle it.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Know how to recruit and hire good people.
</P>
<P>
   Mackay has been heavily involved in hiring Mackay Envelope
employees. The two he makes sure he always hires are the president
and the receptionist, the latter because the person who answers the
phone can do an awful lot to encourage or drive away business.
</P>
<P>
   When hiring, Mackay said he makes sure to meet the prospect's
spouse so that the spouse can understand the corporate culture, and
he uses an industrial psychologist to advise him on which
candidates are particularly attractive or unattractive. He also
looks for a good sense of humor.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to walk the factory, I want to walk the offices and I
want to hear laughter.''
</P>
<P>
   When people are hired, the company and the employee put together
an agreement for the next several years, Mackay said, outlining
what is expected of the worker and what the employee can expect to
receive for achieving those goals. ``Our whole philosophy is this:
Agreements prevent disagreements.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.) &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   He said the company rewards employees frequently with perks like
tickets to sporting events, and stresses the attitude of not only
succeeding on your own, but helping co-workers to succeed. In the
book, he mentions how important it is to share the company's values
with employees, including how valuable time is for everyone.
</P>
<P>
   The book describes Mackay's shock as he interviewed a
prospective sales representative named Jane for the Chicago area.
</P>
<P>
   ``During my interview with Jane, I popped one of my favorite
questions, `Jane, how many hours a week do you work?'
</P>
<P>
   ``I was expecting a `sound barrier' number. Instead she blurted,
`Oh, about 20 hours.'
</P>
<P>
   ```Twenty hours? Wait a minute, what did you say your dollar
volume was last year in Chicago?'
</P>
<P>
   ```$2 million.'
</P>
<P>
   ```We can check, you know.'
</P>
<P>
   ```So check. That's what I did, and I can do it for your
company, too, and even better.'
</P>
<P>
   ``It checked. I hired her. I don't ask her how many hours she
works. I don't care. This year her W2 form will be six figures.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
