<SLUG> BC-LYNCH-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW YORK FARMERS WAIT FOR END OF CASTRO REGIME 
</HEADLINE>
   Commentary  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By DAN LYNCH  
 c.1998 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ We were sitting around one night not too long ago
_ me, Henry Zwack and a bunch of farmers from Rensselaer County,
N.Y. We were all thinking pretty much the same thing: Wouldn't it
be great if Fidel Castro died? Everything would be so much simpler.
</P>
<P>
   The scene was the Tavern at Sterup Square, a top-drawer
restaurant in the heart of this suburban Albany county of 154,000
souls. Zwack is a shrewd, calculating, bespectacled lawyer of 45
who serves as the Rensselaer County executive. He was throwing a
fancy dinner for a couple of Cuban diplomats from Washington. The
idea was to interest Cuba in buying food from Rensselaer County
farmers.
</P>
<P>
   The county has a gritty little city, Troy, and some gracious
suburbs. But much of Rensselaer County is farmland populated by
people who vote Republican. Coincidentally, Zwack is a Republican.
His idea of a creative American foreign policy would be to wean the
Cubans away from communism on a diet of Rensselaer County beef,
mutton, apples and vegetables _ not to mention processed dairy
products.
</P>
<P>
   The Cubans would be delighted with that, actually. Things got so
bad in Havana a few years back that family cats were scrambling to
avoid a closer association with rice and black beans than cats
usually find congenial.
</P>
<P>
   For about a century now, ever since we Americans threw the
Spanish out, Cuba has been even less stable politically than
Zwack's Rensselaer County. And, believe me, that's going some. The
Cubans never really got the idea of democracy. Every time one side
won an election, the other side picked up guns.
</P>
<P>
   When Zwack was 5 years old, Castro was a hot-blooded communist
lawyer who raised an army and chased out Fulgencio Batista, a
tyrant who'd staged his own military coup some years earlier. All
green fatigues and gray beard, Castro turns 73 this year as the
only major remaining communist leader in the hemisphere. Recurrent
rumors of his physical ailments bring bright smiles to the lips of
South Florida's prosperous expatriate Cuban community, which has
demonstrated an impressive gift for nursing a grudge for four
decades now.
</P>
<P>
   Castro has suffered a stroke. Big grin. Did you hear? Fidel has
Alzheimer's disease. Champagne, anyone?
</P>
<P>
   But the champagne has been on ice for a while now as Castro has
clung selfishly to life. His country is a shambles, thanks to
communism's shortcomings as an economic system, to general
mismanagement and to a strict trade embargo imposed by the United
States, which classifies Cuba as ``a terrorist nation.''
</P>
<P>
   As Castro hangs on, the U.S. government pretty much sticks to
its embargo, despite pleas from the pope and even from aggressive
Republican politicians like Zwack.
</P>
<P>
   Sure, Zwack and his farmers despise communists every bit as much
as anybody else might despise communists. They would love the
opportunity to feed them, though. They would love to sell them
apples, for example, at a better price than the Cubans can buy them
now from China. One Rensselaer County farmer, George Messick, would
be thrilled at the chance to sell the Cubans meat from bisons. He
raises the huge things, and he figures buffalo steaks would be a
treat for them.
</P>
<P>
   Agriculture is a tough business. Farmers everywhere are always
looking for new mouths to feed. This market is a natural for
Rensselaer County farmers. Cuba is just 200 miles in a straight
line from downtown Miami _ a suburb, really. And it's much closer
to the Port of Albany than to the Port of Shanghai.
</P>
<P>
   The problem is that, so far, the U.S. government hasn't given
Zwack and his farmers permission to go there and even talk,
although the Cubans are even more eager to buy food at decent
prices than the Rensselaer County farmers are to sell it.
</P>
<P>
   The complication is that the victims of the Cuban Diaspora wield
great political power in Florida, a key state in presidential
elections. They want no U.S. trade with Cuba for as long as Fidel
Castro draws breath.
</P>
<P>
   Even so, Zwack hopes to land with a trade delegation at Jose
Marti International Airport as early as next month. If he's lucky,
he'll get to represent Rensselaer County at Castro's funeral.
</P>
<P>
   And the champagne finally will flow.
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Dan Lynch is a columnist for the Albany Times Union, P.O. Box
15000, Albany, NY 12212.)
</P>
</TEXT>
