<SLUG> BC-SF-MAYOR-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CAMPAIGN OPERATIVE EXPECTED TO RUN FOR SAN FRANCISCO MAYOR 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By RACHEL GORDON  
 c.1998 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Clint Reilly, a millionaire real estate investor
who previously worked as a campaign consultant, is expected to
announce his candidacy for mayor of San Francisco on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Reilly has hinted at his ambition to take on Mayor Willie Brown
for more than a year, and recently put together a campaign team.
With his announcement, Reilly steps out from behind the scenes
where for years he served as a player in city and state politics,
running campaigns for other people and causes.
</P>
<P>
   Although Brown has been busy getting endorsements from key
political groups such as labor and the Democratic Party in
preparation for the November election, Reilly is considered his
first viable challenger. Board of Supervisors President Tom Ammiano
and Supervisor Leland Yee have not ruled out mayoral campaigns.
</P>
<P>
   Reilly does not hide his dislike for Brown. He ran incumbent
Frank Jordan's unsuccessful campaign for re-election against Brown
in the race four years ago. More recently, he fought Brown over the
ballot measures for a new 49ers football stadium and sponsored
another ballot drive to strip Brown's control over the development
of Treasure Island.
</P>
<P>
   Flamboyant and outspoken, Reilly has made his own headlines over
the years. He's been sued for sexual harassment by a former
employee and in 1993 he sued the San Francisco Examiner, alleging
that Executive Editor Phil Bronstein assaulted him during a meeting
in the newspaper's editorial offices. Bronstein never conceded
culpability. The lawsuit was settled out of court for an
undisclosed sum.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
