<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOME-BUDGET-NYT </SLUG>
  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Home Section stories from The N.Y. Times News Service for
Thursday, Feb. 18:
</P>
<P>
   RENOVATE (Undated) _ Okay, so it's not a palace. Maybe you just
bought it. Maybe you just looked around and, as if for the first
time, spotted the cracked plaster, the 20 or 30 coats of paint, the
dark stains on the floors, the exposed electrical conduit and the
unmentionable kitchen. Maybe it's time for a renovation. If you
have neither the inclination nor the budget for a large-scale,
architect-designed renovation _ a project that could easily run to
$75,000 or $100,000 for a one-bedroom apartment _ you'll probably
turn to a general contractor, someone experienced ed to handle the
whole job, including plumbing, wiring, tiling and carpentry. How to
weigh the widely varying _ and often impenetrable _ bids when they
arrive? The questions are as nervewracking as finding the apartment
or house in the first place. By Tracie Rozhon.
</P>
<P>
   With photo.
</P>
<P>
   KITCHEN-TECH (Cambridge, Mass.) _ Maybe Mr. Java is just shy.
But when asked to produce a cup of coffee for a stranger last
Thursday, he sat as still as a child frozen on stage. ``I don't
understand,'' said Kristin Hall, a project coordinator at the Media
Laboratory at MIT, founded 14 years ago to, in the phrase of its
director, Nicholas Negroponte, ``invent the future.'' Mr. Java is
an Acorto 2000s automatic expresso machine wired to a personal
computer _ a kind of HAL for latte, when he works. He is also the
first piece created by Counter Intelligence, a new five-year
research program inaugurated in October to invent a technological
future for the home kitchen. By William L. Hamilton.
</P>
<P>
   With photo.
</P>
<P>
   VISIONAIRE (New York) _ ``It's our dream,'' Stephen Gan said,
surveying the vast, gleaming-white new home of Visionaire, the
avant-garde quarterly that changes format with each issue and which
has developed an international cult following among the
increasingly entwined worlds of art and fashion. By Christopher
Mason
</P>
<P>
   IKEA-SPACE (New York) _ She's always organizing, but her house
is a mess. He leaves his running shoes all over the apartment. Her
heel-less pumps multiply on the closet floor. The children are
having turf wars over their toys. Disputes over space _ especially
the lack of it _ can turn a happy marriage into the bitter,
chandelier-swinging finale from the divorce film, ``War of the
Roses.'' With that in mind, on the eve of Valentine's Day, Ikea in
Elizabeth, N.J., brought together two psychotherapists and an
interior designer to help customers sort out, or maybe even shelve,
their issues. By Julie Iovine.
</P>
<P>
   With photo.
</P>
<P>
   GARDEN-Q&AMP;A (Undated) _ Garden questions answered. By Leslie
Land.
</P>
<P>
   GUEST-HOUSE (Undated) _ A 3,000-square-foot guest house on a
20-acre property, across the lawn from a tiny 1840 weekend cottage.
It was built as a retreat for guests who might stay longer than a
weekend as well as a gathering place during large family events. An
80-foot-long dormitory wing sleeps 25. By Julie Iovine.
</P>
<P>
   QUILTS-DECODED (Undated) _ One scholar compared it to the
``Rosetta stone,'' said Jacqueline L. Tobin, the author, with
Raymond G. Dobard, of ``Hidden in Plain View,'' a new book that
makes a startling claim about quilts: that some quilts were
patterned as a code to direct escaping slaves. A quilt with
monkey-wrench pattern hung in a cabin window signaled slaves to
gather tools for the escape. Tumbling blocks indicated imminent
departure. The number and placement of knots represented dates. The
book, just published by Doubleday, has become a surprise hot
seller. The story of its origin is as intriguing as its theory. By
Phil Patton.
</P>
<P>
   HOME-IMPROVEMENT (Undated) _ The Home Improvement column. By
Edward Lipinski.
</P>
<P>
   With howto drawing.
</P>
<P>
   For information and repeats call the News Service at (888)
346-9867 or (212) 556-1927. And be sure to look for other stories
from our partners: Bloomberg News, The Boston Globe, Cox News
Service, Hearst Newspapers, The Houston Chronicle, The Arizona
Republic, Kansas City Star, Fort Worth Star-Telegram, Los Angeles
Daily News, San Francisco Chronicle and Seattle Post-Intelligencer.
</P>
