<DOCNO> NYT19990217.0195 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-17 15:14 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8780 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-Y2K-ELECTRICITY-HNS &LR;      02-17 0503
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Y2K-ELECTRICITY-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Y2K PROBLEM SPARKS BRISK SALES OF GENERATORS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ALAN WECHSLER  
 c.1998 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   CLIFTON PARK, N.Y. _ New York's power companies say they expect
few, if any, blackouts because of the millennium computer glitch.
But some New Yorkers aren't buying it.
</P>
<P>
   They are, however, buying generators to supply backup power in
the event things don't work as well as officials say.
</P>
<P>
   Sales of power generators and other equipment in New York state
are skyrocketing. Manufacturers are churning out popular models at
record rates, and customers are waiting months for some models.
</P>
<P>
   ``It just makes sense to be prepared,'' said David Triller of
the upstate New York town of Clifton Park. ``All I keep reading is
nobody really knows what's going to happen. That's kind of scary.''
</P>
<P>
   Triller waited three months to get a 5,000-watt Honda for his
house. He also ordered two more _ one for a friend, and one for his
guitar store to keep the fragile wooden instruments from freezing
if the power dies.
</P>
<P>
   Computer specialists fear that many computers originally
programmed to recognize only the last two digits of a year will
fail or malfunction on Jan. 1, 2000, when the machines will assume
it is 1900.
</P>
<P>
   For those who worry about the year 2000 computer glitch, or
``Y2K problem,'' the biggest concern is that the electricity will
go out for a long time. Power companies say they are well aware of
the problem and expect to be Y2K-compliant before the end of this
year.
</P>
<P>
   Specialists who have been following the Y2K problem say they
expect, at the worst, temporary outages in a few places that won't
last more than a couple of days.
</P>
<P>
   Y2K isn't the only reason to buy a generator. Headlines about
natural disasters during the last two years _ hurricanes in the
southern United States and Central America, landslides in
California and floods in the Midwest _ get people worried.
</P>
<P>
   Bad weather news means good business for Joe Farina, manager of
Albany Honda. ``There's been a tremendous increase,'' he said.
``It's like buying fire insurance on your house.''
</P>
<P>
   Honda, one of the bigger generator sellers in the United States,
has doubled its sales in the past year, according to a Jan. 1
letter sent to its dealers. The company has given up producing a
wide selection, concentrating instead on the more popular models in
an effort to produce more. And despite that, there's still a
months-long waiting list.
</P>
<P>
   Y2K has been an especially powerful sales incentive because of
all the advance publicity and speculation about impending doom.
</P>
<P>
   All the fuss and worry may be for naught. At a recent New York
Assembly committee hearing, officials from power companies around
the state testified that their computers would be Y2K-compliant by
the end of June. Other power experts say they believe the worst
problem that will occur the first week of January is a few spotty
outages that will not take long to repair.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
