<HEADER>
A8783 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r d &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CHINESENEWYEAR-960(2T     02-17 0815
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHINESENEWYEAR-960(2Takes)-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GOOD FOOD, GOOD FORTUNE IN THE YEAR TO COME
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BEVERLY BUNDY 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Our neighbors in the Far East know how to celebrate.
</P>
<P>
   The lunar new year kicked off Tuesday. People will be partying
for the next couple of weeks.
</P>
<P>
   For the Chinese and Koreans, this will be the Year of the
Rabbit; for the Vietnamese, the Year of the Cat. For all concerned,
it's a season of eating, gift-giving and symbolism.
</P>
<P>
   Houses are cleaned to rid them of bad fortune. New clothes in
bright colors (particularly red) are readied. Homes are stocked
with food and flowers.
</P>
<P>
   ``No matter where you are,'' says Chinese master chef Martin
Yan, ``you try to go home for the new year.''
</P>
<P>
   And one of the main reasons for going home again is to get some
of the dishes that foster good fortune and prosperity.
</P>
<P>
   ``The food for New Year's has a long history of symbolism and
superstition,'' Yan says. ``Even Chinese menus will change names of
dishes during New Year's. A lobster becomes a `dragon' on a menu
because it looks like a dragon, which is a symbol of power and
vitality. A chicken on a menu becomes a phoenix because it's a
bird. Fish are important because the word for fish is a homophone
for the word for abundance.
</P>
<P>
   ``Red is the most important color because it is the color of
blood and symbolizes vitality. That's why parents give their
children money at New Year's in a red envelope, and poems are
written on red scrolls. And sweet and sour dishes are red.''
</P>
<P>
   Shapes also have importance at the holiday table.
</P>
<P>
   Round shapes, symbolizing coins, denote prosperity. Long, uncut
noodles promote a long life. Duck, chicken and fish are served
complete, again meaning affluence. (Even if a fish or chicken is to
be divided at the table, it is presented assembled.)
</P>
<P>
   As with all holiday fare _ here or abroad _ the meal plan is in
the memories. Following are typical New Year's dishes from ``Martin
Yan's Feast: The Best of Yan Can Cook'' (Bay Books, $34.95).
</P>
<P>
   LION'S HEAD MEATBALLS
</P>
<P>
   Serves 4-6
</P>
<P>
   6 dried black mushrooms
</P>
<P>
   Meatballs:
</P>
<P>
   1/4 pound regular-firm tofu, drained
</P>
<P>
   3/4 pound ground pork OR ground beef
</P>
<P>
   1 egg, lightly beaten
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons oyster-flavored sauce
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons cornstarch
</P>
<P>
   2 teaspoons minced ginger
</P>
<P>
   2 teaspoons minced cilantro
</P>
<P>
   Soak mushrooms in warm water to cover until softened, about 20
minutes; drain. Discard stems and quarter the caps.
</P>
<P>
   Mash tofu in bowl. Place in a clean towel and squeeze to remove
excess liquid. Return to bowl and add remaining meatball
ingredients; mix well. Divide mixture into 12 equal portions. Roll
each portion into a ball.
</P>
<P>
   Cooking oil for deep-frying
</P>
<P>
   1 1/2 cups chicken broth
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons Chinese rice wine or dry sherry
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon soy sauce
</P>
<P>
   3/4 pound napa cabbage, cut into 3-inch sections
</P>
<P>
   1 small carrot, thinly sliced diagonally
</P>
<P>
   16 snow peas, trimmed and cut in half diagonally
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon sesame oil
</P>
<P>
   In wok or 2-quart saucepan, heat oil for deep-frying to 350
degrees. Fry meatballs, half at a time, turning frequently, until
browned on all sides, 3 to 4 minutes. Remove with slotted
spoon/spatula; drain on paper towels.
</P>
<P>
   Place meatball in 2-quart pan. Add broth, wine and soy sauce.
Heat to simmering. Cover and simmer for 10 minutes. Add mushrooms,
cabbage and carrot. Cover and cook for 10 minutes. Add snow peas
and cook until all vegetables are tender-crisp, about 2 minutes
longer. Stir in sesame oil.
</P>
<P>
   Nutritional analysis per serving: 288 calories, 21 grams fat, 7
grams carbohydrates, 18 grams protein, 79 milligrams cholesterol,
594 milligrams sodium, 64 percent of calories from fat.
</P>
<P>
   GOLDEN MEAT-FILLED COINS
</P>
<P>
   Serves 18
</P>
<P>
   2 1/4 cups flour
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup boiling water
</P>
<P>
   1/3 cup cold water
</P>
<P>
   Place flour in bowl. Add boiling water, stirring with fork or
chopsticks. Gradually stir in cold water, mixing until dough holds
together. On a lightly floured board, knead dough until smooth and
satiny, about 5 minutes. Cover and let rest for 30 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Filling:
</P>
<P>
   1/2 pound ground chicken, beef OR pork
</P>
<P>
   3 tablespoons chopped green onions
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon minced ginger
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup chicken broth
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon soy sauce
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon oyster-flavored sauce
</P>
<P>
   2 teaspoons sesame oil
</P>
<P>
   1/2 teaspoon sugar
</P>
<P>
   1/4 teaspoon white pepper
</P>
<P>
   Combine filling ingredients in bowl; mix well.
</P>
<P>
   On lightly floured board, roll dough into 9-inch-long cylinder.
Cut cylinder into 18 pieces.
</P>
<P>
   Roll a portion of dough into 3 1/2-inch circle about 1/2 inch
thick; keep remaining dough covered to prevent drying. Place
rounded tablespoon of filling in center of dough. Gather edges of
dough around filling; pinch to seal. Roll filled dough into a ball;
flatten with palm of hand to make a disk 1/2 inch thick.
</P>
<P>
   MORE
</P>
</TEXT>
