<HEADER>
A8798 &Cx1f; tab-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BRAZELTON-SAMPLE-1-NY     02-17 1052
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BRAZELTON-SAMPLE-1-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FAMILIES TODAY 
 THE GREAT TOILET-TRAINING DEBATE
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   ------------------------------------------------------
</P>
<P>
   EDITOR'S NOTE: What follows is a sample of Dr. T. Berry
Brazelton's column ``Families Today,'' which is distributed by The
New York Times Syndicate. Dr. Brazelton is America's most respected
pediatrician and a tireless advocate for children and families. He
is Professor Emeritus at Harvard Medical School, which recently
named a chair in his honor. In his weekly column ``Families
Today,'' Dr. Brazelton guides readers through a child's
development, from teething to the terrible twos and beyond, in
essays and Q&AMP;As.
</P>
<P>
   The following essay is about the hot-button topic of potty
training, which has been in the news lately _ including a front
page New York Times article featuring Dr. Brazelton. Another sample
column can be found in your system under the slug
BC-BRAZELTON-SAMPLE-2-NYTSF. For information about subscribing to
``Families Today,'' call 888-269-8796 to connect to a New York
Times Syndicate sales executive nearest you.
</P>
<P>
   ------------------------------------------------------
</P>
<P>
   &UR; By T. BERRY BRAZELTON, M.D. &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) &LR;  &QC;
</P>
<P>
   ``When should we begin to teach our child to use the potty?''
</P>
<P>
   This is one of the most common questions I am asked by parents _
especially lately, since this issue has been in the news.
</P>
<P>
   I still offer the same advice I've always given: Only a child
can decide when the time for toilet training has come. Any pressure
parents may feel from grandparents, nursery schools or friends
should be ignored. It's got to be the child's achievement, not
theirs.
</P>
<P>
   There are certain signs of readiness that parents can look for
to know when it's time to begin training. These include a good
understanding of words, concepts and instructions; a desire to
imitate important adults; an urge to put things where they belong;
and the waning of negativism. This will probably happen sometime
during the third year. I like to start at the age of 2 to show
children what we expect of them. Each step can then be theirs, if
parents watch their signals.
</P>
<P>
   When the time is right, here's what I recommend:
</P>
<P>
   1. Give the child a potty chair on the floor, so he can take it
wherever he wants. Call it his and let him get used to it as his.
</P>
<P>
   2. After a week, take him to sit on his toilet, in his clothes,
while you sit on yours. Read to him or give him a cookie to keep
him there momentarily. This is just to establish the daily routine
of sitting on it. If you take his clothes off, it's too invasive
and may frighten him.
</P>
<P>
   3. The next week, ask him if it's OK to take his diaper off so
he can sit on the potty, once a day. You sit on your potty, he sits
on his. Tell him: ``This is what Mommy and Daddy do every day.''
</P>
<P>
   4. The third week, take him to his pot with his dirty diaper,
undo it, then drop it in the toilet. Meanwhile, say something like:
``This is where you can go someday to do your b.m. This is what
Mommy and Daddy do. This is your pot. This is mine.''
</P>
<P>
   Don't flush his b.m. away while he watches. The child feels it
is part of him and wonders where it goes when it disappears. Don't
get rid of it until he loses interest and walks away.
</P>
<P>
   5. The next step is completely at the discretion of the toddler.
In fact, if at any time he resists a step, forget training for a
while.
</P>
<P>
   If he's been interested in the previous steps, however, you can
offer to take his clothes off and let him run around with a bare
bottom. Offer to put the potty in his room so he can go to it
himself when he wants to. Then, offer to remind him every hour to
try to go.
</P>
<P>
   If he's ready, he will be able to cooperate on the pot. If he
does produce something, congratulate him, but don't overdo it. Too
much praise can take away his own excitement about his achievement.
</P>
<P>
   6. If he's really ready, you can leave his pants off for longer
periods. If he has an accident on the floor, go right back to
diapers. Don't make a fuss. Simply say, ``We'll try again. There's
no hurry. Someday you'll do it like Mommy and Daddy.'' You are
depending on his desire to imitate and identify with you.
</P>
<P>
   Each step must be at his timing. If he gets worried or
resistant, pull back quickly. Offer him back his diapers, and try
to forget training for a while. He knows now what you are expecting
of him, and he'll do it when he's ready.
</P>
<P>
   7. Night training shouldn't begin until he's dry at his nap and
until he gives some signal that he wants to stay dry at night. Wait
until he has dry diapers or no urine for at least four to six hours
a day.
</P>
<P>
   A child will have to be really ready to cooperate to make night
training worthwhile. Unless he asks you to help _ or does it
spontaneously _ I'd eliminate nighttime as a project until he's at
least 3. Most children aren't ready until 4 or 5.
</P>
<P>
   As a society, we are far too uptight about pushing children to
be trained. The incidence of failures _ including children
withholding b.m.s and urine _ is rising today. Perhaps this is due
to the pressure on busy parents to have children trained by 3 for
nursery school. Fight that pressure.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe it's due to confusion children feel when their parents
share the training steps with day-care providers. Don't do this.
For the best chance of success, toilet training should be something
personal between you and your child.
</P>
<P>
   In future columns Dr. Brazelton will answer selected questions
from readers. Questions or comments should be addressed to Dr. T.
Berry Brazelton, care of The New York Times Syndication Sales
Corp., 122 E. 42nd St., New York, N.Y. 10168. Questions of general
interest will be answered in this column; Dr. Brazelton regrets
that unpublished letters cannot be answered individually. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Copyright 1999 by T. Berry Brazelton, M.D. &QL; 
 &UR; Adapted from ``Touchpoints,'' by T. Berry Brazelton, M.D. &QL; 
 &UR; A Merloyd Lawrence Book &QL; 
 &UR; Published by Perseus Books Publishing, LLC &QL;
</P>
<P>
   For information about subscribing to ``Families Today,'' call
888-269-8796 to connect to a New York Times Syndicate sales
executive nearest you.
</P>
<P>
   ---
</P>
