A8818 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-INDIAN-SITE-HNS &LR;      02-17 0499
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INDIAN-SITE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INDIAN GROUP PLANS MEETING PLACE FOR EXPATRIATES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JAY JOCHNOWITZ  
 c.1999 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ROTTERDAM, N.Y. _ On a derelict farm with crumbling barns and
rusted tractors, a Native American dream is growing along the
Mohawk River.
</P>
<P>
   The vision of the Keepers of the Circle is a gathering place for
expatriates of various Native American nations who, far from their
reservations, have made their homes in the cities and suburbs of
the Albany area.
</P>
<P>
   When completed at a projected cost of $10 million, the 29-acre
site will preserve the languages, rituals and food of the Indian
nations. It would serve as a focal point for Native Americans, a
public education center and, possibly, a magnet for tourists.
</P>
<P>
   But unlike the roadside souvenir stands that dot highways around
the country, ``This isn't the 10-cent tourist trap where you go by
a plastic teepee and not a Native American in sight,'' said Vince
Dwyer, a Tonawanda Seneca and chairman of Keepers of the Circle.
``The whole purpose of it is for Native Americans to have a place
where they can come and congregate.''
</P>
<P>
   Based now in Albany, the Keepers, an 8-year-old nonprofit group
formed to promote the culture of Native Americans, has been looking
for a home for years. It rejected sites in urban areas, unsuitable
for a group that, for reasons both practical and spiritual, wanted
a location that would express the Native-American concepts of
living in balance, harmony and interdependence with Earth.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, Schenectady County authorized the $170,000 purchase
of the 29-acre tract in Rotterdam Junction. The land includes a
house that will be rehabilitated for offices.
</P>
<P>
   The land, set in a river valley that was home to Mohawks long
before the Europeans came, has some strong connections to its
proposed use. A 1714 deed conveying a portion of the property to
Jan Mabee, written on sheepskin, bore what appears to be the
upside-down wolf seal of a Native American.
</P>
<P>
   The site, Dwyer said, also featured a trading post that was the
last stop for hunters and trappers headed along the Mohawk River
into what was then a vast western wilderness. ``It's just really
rich in history,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   For the county, the idea was a good fit, said Joe Ryan, the
deputy public works commissioner. The site includes 13 acres of the
Great Flats Aquifer, a source of drinking water. Plans are to carve
trails through the lowlands over the aquifer, protecting it from
development. Dwyer has been collecting wildflowers to seed the
land.
</P>
<P>
   The property is also next to the historic Mabee farm, owned by
the Schenectady County Historical Society and scheduled to open
fully as a museum in 2001, Ryan said. The two sites could serve as
a joint attraction, perhaps incorporating programs on the
interaction between the early Dutch and Native Americans who, in
peaceful periods, taught settlers survival techniques for the New
World.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-17-99 1526EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
