<HEADER>
A8850 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ONLINE-TIPS-$ADV21-CO     02-17 0314
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ONLINE-TIPS-$ADV21-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    TIPS FOR TRYING TO PROTECT YOUR PRIVACY
 &HT;    With ONLINE-PRIVACY. For release Sunday, Feb. 21.
 &HT;    Eds: This is an added graphic element for a package of stories
that moved Tuesday.
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Experts say it's difficult to protect your privacy
in the computer age. But there are some preventive measures you can
take to reduce the amount of personal information that makes its
way into databases.
</P>
<P>
   You can take extreme measures, as outlined by California author
Don Ray on his Web site (http://www.privacyrights.org/donray.htm).
He offers more than 100 tips to privacy fanatics, including
everything from ``get married overseas'' to ``don't drop business
cards in the 'Free Lunch' bowl.''
</P>
<P>
   The Rhode Island-based ``Privacy Journal'' newsletter suggests
less aggressive measures, including:
</P>
<P>
   _ Protect the confidentiality of your Social Security number.
Don't provide it unless you have to.
</P>
<P>
   _ Attach conditions to sensitive information you provide to
companies or organizations. Insist in writing that it not be
disclosed or that it be erased after a set number of years.
</P>
<P>
   _ Never provide personal information over the telephone unless
you initiated the call and know to whom you're speaking.
</P>
<P>
   _ List your telephone number but not your address in the
telephone book. This makes it harder for those who compile data to
produce consumer profiles.
</P>
<P>
   _ If a telemarketing company calls you, tell them: ``Under the
federal Telephone Consumer Protection Act, I want to be on your 'do
not call' list.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Ask the post office not to disclose your change of address to
commercial mailers.
</P>
<P>
   _ Be discreet in filling out application forms. Don't feel an
obligation to fill in every blank.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
