<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOUNT-BLACKS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PORTRAYING BLACKS, FROM MOUNT'S PERSPECTIVE
</HEADLINE>
 
(EDS: Accompanies MOUNT-EXHIBIT) (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JANET TYSON 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT WORTH, Texas _ From where I sit _ white, middle-class,
female _ both the best and worst of William Sidney Mount's pictures
are representations of black people.
</P>
<P>
   I'd stand by that opinion under any circumstance. But right now,
I want to put it out there because it's Black History Month, and
the Amon Carter Museum is presenting the most comprehensive Mount
exhibition to date.
</P>
<P>
   Mount painted pictures of everyday life in the mid-19th century
_ in the North, before, during and after the Civil War. For him,
that meant representing African-Americans, as well as
European-Americans. His perspective is that of a white man who
opposed abolition. Nonetheless, almost all of Mount's pictures of
black men, women and children stand in direct opposition to typical
(for the times) representations of them as carefree, childlike
creatures or craven idiots.
</P>
<P>
   That said, his pictures consistently communicate the
marginalization of blacks in 19th-century Northern society. He does
not gloss over the situation, which makes his sensitive portrayals
all the more poignant.
</P>
<P>
   But, regardless of the reality of that world and Mount's
interpretation of said reality, those viewing his pictures today
will see them differently. There are two or three exceptions _
early works, crudely rendered _ that harshly caricature blacks and,
to a lesser degree, whites. Virtually anyone would agree with that
assessment.
</P>
<P>
   But the rest are up for grabs, which is where each of us applies
our own experiences to viewing them.
</P>
<P>
   I look for whatever little positive evidence I can find of
racial good will.
</P>
<P>
   So I dwell endlessly on ``Eel Spearing at Setauket,'' in which a
black woman is joined in her labors by a white boy. Powerfully
built, she is the dominant figure in terms of the classical,
triangular composition. She also has strength, secure footing and
the requisite keen eye and quick reflexes.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, this is one of the most beautiful, masterfully
composed pictures in American art. The sense of serenity, the
subtle layering of landscape and reflections of landscape, figures
in boats and other elements are magical and compel us to conclude
that this is an important subject, indeed.
</P>
<P>
   Then there is ``Dance of the Haymakers.'' This is a
heartbreaking picture, because the little boy beating out the time
cannot be inside the barn with the white dancers and the white
musician. But there is another black youth, a girl, in the company
of a white girl: Both are viewing the scene from the hayloft,
sharing that perch with what seems to be comfortable intimacy.
</P>
<P>
   Other Mount pictures include individual portraits of black
musicians that are a far cry from minstrel-show caricature. Based
on Dutch baroque compositions, they sparkle with individuality,
warmth and intelligence.
</P>
<P>
   Still, there is the ambiguity of the work considered Mount's
masterpiece _ ``Farmers Nooning,'' in which a black field hand has
fallen asleep after a morning's labor.
</P>
<P>
   He lies, vulnerable, in the midst of a handful of white men and
youths, while the youngest boy tickles his ear with a bit of hay.
Is the sleeping man the butt of a joke, unwitting entertainment for
his white companions? Is he a symbol of African-Americans being
cynically (in Mount's view) roused by abolitionists? Or is he among
friends who would do the same to any other of that company?
</P>
<P>
   We can learn as much as we can about this picture but, in the
long run, we read it according to our own experiences.
</P>
<P>
   The Carter presents other opportunities to interpret historical
black experience, however. It owns other pictures on that theme,
and two have been added as a coda to the Mount exhibition.
</P>
<P>
   One is Thomas Hovenden's ``Chloe and Sam'' (1882); the other is
Francis William Edmonds' ``The Flute'' (circa 1859). Both are by
white Northern artists who were influenced by Mount.
</P>
<P>
   ``Chloe and Sam'' represents an elderly couple who were the
artist's neighbors in rural eastern Pennsylvania. This is a tender
depiction that, like the historic European works that inform it,
represents poverty almost as a state of grace.
</P>
<P>
   In its turn, ``The Flute,'' at first glance, reverses the
blacks-entertaining-whites cliche. Here, the flutist is a young
white man, while his audience is composed of two black boys. But
the boys are not taking this music as entertainment. Instead, it
seems to come to them almost as a revelation _ and their demeanor
is almost reverent. Arguably, then, the flutist plays a superior
role in this picture. But, even so, he is sharing directly and
without apparent condescension.
</P>
<P>
   But ... those are only my readings. They are not the final truth
about any of these pictures. Not that any final truth about art is
possible.
</P>
<P>
   (Janet Tyson is arts critic for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram.
Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
