<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-YAN-COOKBOOK-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHEF MARTIN YAN'S MISSION IS TO BRING THE EAST TO THE WEST
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BEVERLY BUNDY 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Martin Yan is not a comedian, but he plays one on TV.
</P>
<P>
   For more than 20 years and 1,500 episodes of ``Yan Can Cook,''
he has been telling jokes that verge on the lame. He makes faces
while dancing his cleaver over carrots and rehydrated black
mushrooms. Every show features at least one rat-tat-tat of knife
work that brings applause from his studio audience.
</P>
<P>
   In town to promote his new book, ``Martin Yan's Feast: The Best
of Yan Can Cook,'' (Bay Books, $34.95), Yan is nothing like his TV
persona. He is intense and serious. He explains the dual
personality succinctly.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even on a serious show like `60 Minutes,' they end with
something funny like Andy Rooney,'' Yan says.
</P>
<P>
   He's earned the right to find humor where he may.
</P>
<P>
   He was born in Canton a year after the communist takeover; his
father's restaurant was nationalized, and his mother worked at a
grocery. ``We didn't have much food or much to eat,'' Yan says.
</P>
<P>
   At 13, he moved to Hong Kong, where he learned and slept in a
hotel kitchen until he was 18. That's when he emigrated.
</P>
<P>
   Immigration led to the University of California, Davis, where he
earned bachelor's and master's degrees in food science and got a
start on the road to teaching. To afford college, he taught cooking
classes for the university's extension service.
</P>
<P>
   This is a far different route than most food celebrities take.
Yan is quick to compliment trained chefs (Emeril Lagasse and
Wolfgang Puck get high marks), but he sayd that today's chefs too
often think of themselves as artists, without being grounded in the
fundamentals.
</P>
<P>
   And fusion cuisine (which Yan calls the cuisine of the future),
the palette for a lot of these young artists, can suffer from a
lack of training.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you do it incorrectly, it is confusion cuisine,'' Yan says.
``If you're making a French sauce, it's fine to add something like
oyster sauce, because it is velvety and savory. But it's not right
to use hoisin sauce in that sort of sauce, because it's coarse and
spicy.''
</P>
<P>
   Yan is quick to point up the strengths of Chinese cooking _
widely acknowledged as one of the world's great cuisines, along
with Italian and French.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are 13 to 15 techniques in Chinese cooking. There's
stir-frying, deep-frying, pan-frying, braising, stewing, poaching,
barbecuing, smoking. In Peking duck, you use three different
techniques.''
</P>
<P>
   Yan lives in San Mateo, Calif., with his wife and 6 1/2-year-old
twin sons.
</P>
<P>
   He gives two months of his year to his TV show and cookbooks. He
records 52 shows in 13 days and calls it the ``fun part'' of his
year. The rest of his time is devoted to the moneymaking enterprise
of consulting with food companies such as Libbys, Tyson, Nestle and
Kikkoman. He is also a consultant for restaurant projects such as
the Empress Court in Caesars Palace. On that project, as well as
giving input on design and menu, he recruited and hired chefs from
locations as diverse as Hong Kong and Toronto.
</P>
<P>
   For the TV audience, it may look like fun and games. To Martin
Yan, it's very serious business.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   FYI
</P>
<P>
   Find Martin Yan on the Internet at www.yancancook.com. (The site
receives 10,000 hits a week.) There, you can order Yan's books and
his line of knives. You can also visit ``wok talk'' and click into
recipes.
</P>
<P>
   Yan is hosting a tour to Beijing and Hong Kong. The trip is from
May 5-16 and includes a banquet inside the Imperial Palaces. Cost
per person is $4,488, and proceeds will benefit public TV station
KERA/Channel 13 of Dallas-Fort Worth. For more information, phone
(800) 292-1238.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Beverly Bundy is food editor for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram.
Send recipes and requests to Beverly Bundy, Fort Worth
Star-Telegram, Box 1870, Fort Worth, Texas 76101. Or E-mail to
bbundy(at)star-telegram.com. Include a daytime phone number.
Responses to requests will be made only through this column. Visit
the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
