<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-17 16:04 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8875 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MOUNT-EXHIBIT-TEX     02-17 0965
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOUNT-EXHIBIT-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PAINTINGS THAT TELL THE STORIES OF A CENTURY
</HEADLINE>
 
(EDS: Accompanied by MOUNT-BLACKS) (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JANET TYSON 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT WORTH, Texas _ The great allure of 19th-century American
art stems as much from history as it does from aesthetics _
especially when it comes to an artist like William Sidney Mount,
the subject of the Amon Carter Museum's newest show.
</P>
<P>
   The pre-eminent genre painter of his time, Mount was a skillful
technician who knew his art-historical sources. But Mount's forte
was his feel for the tellingly typical story, visually recounted.
So we look to Mount in search of America's past, seeking history in
its more intimate forms.
</P>
<P>
   And we need look no further than ``William Sidney Mount: Painter
of American Life,'' which presents a succinct selection of Mount's
paintings, preparatory drawings and printed reproductions. About 60
works are on view, including the artist's acknowledged masterpiece,
``Farmers Nooning'' (1836), and such important canvases as
``Bargaining for a Horse'' (1835), ``The Power of Music'' (1847),
``Dance of the Haymakers'' (1845) and ``Eel Spearing at Setauket''
(1845).
</P>
<P>
   The installation begins with early works that reflect Mount's
germination as a self-taught artist. If his rendering is somewhat
awkward, we nonetheless can see his knowledge of works by old
masters like Jacques-Louis David. In ``School Boys Quarreling''
(1830), for example, Mount's composition obviously borrows from
David's ``Oath of the Horatii'' (1784) _ an allusion that would
raise Mount in viewers' esteem, but also flatter viewers for
recognizing the art-historical source.
</P>
<P>
   David's painting is about morality, honor and self-sacrifice.
Mount's picture shows boys arguing about what likely is a trivial
matter. One has had his nose bloodied; his friends raise their
fists in his defense while the apparent aggressor glares at them
and points his finger accusingly _ and steps, literally, on the
toes of one of his opponents.
</P>
<P>
   The main figures are rendered convincingly, if not subtly,
although the worst caricaturing is reserved for a black youth, who
is looking on from the sidelines.
</P>
<P>
   But there is an underlying commentary, too, suggested by Mount's
inclusion of a book bearing the legend ``Ocular Analysis'' _ in
other words, visual perception as it applies to art. With this,
Mount addresses the ideological dispute between the upstart
National Academy of Design and the establishment American Academy
of Fine Arts.
</P>
<P>
   Many of Mount's other major canvases reflect a similar,
ideological perspective. This isn't really surprising from a
painter who lived in turbulent times _ when society was becoming
increasingly urbanized and industrialized, when political power was
transferring from an enlightened aristocracy to a more populist
base and when economic speculation would contribute to the Panic of
1837. And let's not forget the brewing tensions that led to the
Civil War in 1861.
</P>
<P>
   A crisper commentary _ simpler in composition and more obvious
in its symbolism _ comes in ``Politics of 1852 _ or, Who let down
the bar?'' (1853). Here, we see two men standing on either side of
a fence whose top two rails have been moved so that someone could
climb over. A poacher stands on the near side of the fence. On the
far side is the farmer who has caught wind of his activities. In an
attempt to deflect the farmer's anger, the poacher assumes a casual
pose and starts reading from the ``New York Herald.''
</P>
<P>
   Here, Mount is referring to the 1852 presidential election, in
which the Democratic and Whig candidates agreed on a number of
major issues, thus lowering the bar on, or blurring, distinctions
between one party and the other. Too, the ``Herald'' was a notably
nonpartisan publication that straddled the fence on a number of
issues.
</P>
<P>
   But Mount also was interested in the apolitical theme of music,
as seen in his portraits of musicians and in his pictures of people
enjoying music _ listening to it, dancing to it and playing it on
fiddle and banjo.
</P>
<P>
   Among Mount's best-known and most beloved musical images is
``Dance of the Haymakers,'' in which two men dance a robust jig on
the floor of a sturdy barn.
</P>
<P>
   The picture is replete with the sort of detail that must have
delighted viewers then and certainly delights us today.
</P>
<P>
   An assortment of men and children look on as the pair jounces
about to a tune played by a fiddle player, with the beat drummed by
a boy against the barn's open door. Onlookers include a couple of
farm children peering down from the hayloft and a more urbanely
dressed man seated on an upturned crate with a jug placed nearby.
</P>
<P>
   Outside, farm tools have been cast aside and the ground is
littered with chaff. A short-haired brown dog gazes attentively at
a cat that is hiding in the building's rock foundation. And,
perhaps as a purely painterly conceit, Mount also has included a
nicely painted, Dutch-inspired still life that rests on the
building's threshold.
</P>
<P>
   There may be other, perhaps sobering, themes underlying the
celebration this picture represents. Life may or may not have been
simpler and happier back then.
</P>
<P>
   No matter. Mount's ability to evoke a scene, to tell a story, is
sufficient reason to enjoy this and any number of other pictures on
view.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   ``William Sidney Mount: Painter of American Life''
</P>
<P>
   Through April 4: 10 a.m.-5 p.m. Tuesday-Saturday, noon-5 p.m.
Sunday at the Amon Carter Museum, 3501 Camp Bowie Blvd., Fort
Worth.
</P>
<P>
   Admission: Free
</P>
<P>
   Information: (817) 738-1933
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Janet Tyson is art critic for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram. You
can call her at (817) 390-7679. Visit the Star-Telegram's online
services on the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
