u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-IKEA-SPACE-ART-NYT &LR;      02-17 0831
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IKEA-SPACE-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A STORAGE-SPACE GUIDE TO BETTER RELATIONSHIPS 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.)  
 (bl)  
 By JULIE V. IOVINE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ She's always organizing, but her house is a mess.
</P>
<P>
   He leaves his running clothes all over the apartment. Her pumps
hog the closet floor.
</P>
<P>
   The children are having turf wars.
</P>
<P>
   Disputes over space _ especially the lack of it _ can turn a
happy marriage into the bitter, chandelier-swinging finale from the
divorce film, ``War of the Roses.''
</P>
<P>
   With that in mind, on the eve of Valentine's Day, Ikea in
Elizabeth, N.J., brought together two psychotherapists and an
interior designer to help customers sort out, or maybe even shelve,
their issues.
</P>
<P>
   ``Your thinking is too linear,'' Janice Simonsen, an Ikea
designer, advised a young woman who had split from her roommate.
Ms. Simonsen wasn't talking about the relationship but her approach
to closets. ``Most people can't see beyond that one rod in the back
of the closet,'' she added.
</P>
<P>
   A more liberating way is to think how every surface can lead a
double life. Shoe bags on the inside of the door; hooks on the
outside. Boxes on the floor; baskets on top of them. ``You have to
think `subdivide' and the space suddenly expands with
possibilities,'' Ms. Simonsen said.
</P>
<P>
   Next in search of insight was a man who needed a clever way to
store his bicycle. (Wall racks are for Seinfeld wannabes.) Ms.
Simsonsen suggested hanging it from inside the door of a deep
closet. ``It's space most people forget about,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Standing at the ready to counsel couples about how to cope with
relationship problems that may stem from cramped quarters were
Julie Iannone and Michele Mandel, psychotherapists from the Center
for Marital and Family Therapy in Manhattan. ``We'll help you find
space in your home and your relationships,'' Ms. Iannone called out
to a passer-by, who said he'd think about it but kept moving.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Mandel has had firsthand experience with confined spaces.
She lives in a two-bedroom Manhattan apartment with her husband and
15-month-old baby. Her daughter's bedroom doubles as an office for
her husband, a computer consultant.
</P>
<P>
   The two psychotherapists, in dark suits, were posted in front of
a model apartment chockablock with Ikea furnishings. They created
an eddy of calm as Saturday shoppers streamed by, driving heavily
loaded carts, as if they were cowboys rounding up unruly strays
from the herd.
</P>
<P>
   When Laurie Frey said that her youngest son, 1, was wrecking her
4-year-old son's Lego castles, leaving him angry and frustrated,
Ms. Simonsen suggested that she buy containers with little padlocks
``that'll make him feel more in control.''
</P>
<P>
   Phillip and Patricia Harris agreed that it has gotten too
claustrophobic in their three-bedroom apartment in Manhattan, and
not because of their five children. Harris complained that his
wife's dresser is stacked to the ceiling with her clothing, and the
drawers under the bed can't be opened because her proliferating
shoe collection blocks them. With romantic _ and commercial _
intent, Ms. Simonsen suggested an Ikea closet with 16-inch doors.
Each one would hold two shoe bags. (Total: 24 pairs of shoes.)
</P>
<P>
   ``Wouldn't you gain a lot more space if you just threw stuff
away?'' Harris asked. She disagreed. She was eyeing an extra-large
armoire.
</P>
<P>
   Problems with organization, not space, preoccupied David and
Michele Grimley and their two sons. ``Our real quest is to find
safe hooks, not the kind that, if you leaned back, they'd go
through your neck,'' said Michele Grimley as she admired
Shaker-style pegs installed around a child's bed. Lack of
organization, she continued, ``can affect the whole dynamic of a
relationship.'' Just having space isn't enough. ``When you can't
find something,'' she said, ``you get aggravated with each other.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Simonsen explained the basic principles of clever storage
(careful to suggest Ikea products).
</P>
<P>
   First rule: prioritize. A blanket bench at the foot of the bed
is best for storing blankets in frequent use, and as a place to put
on shoes. Woolly covers can be stored at a greater remove,
``reachable by a ladder once or twice a year,'' she added.
</P>
<P>
   Seth Weisleder, 26, on his way home to Fort Lee, N.J., stopped
by for tips on how to keep things neat. ``My Mom always told me,
`Never have a girl in the apartment when it's a mess; it leaves a
bad impression,''' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Look for storage space where you wouldn't normally think to find
it, Ms. Simonsen advised. Halls that are three and a half feet wide
offer plenty of room for an etagere. Weisleder chatted with the
psychotherapists. He said his girlfriend, who lived in
Philadelphia, wasn't able to come up for the weekend.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was disappointed,'' Ms. Iannone said later.
</P>
<P>
   ``Too much space,'' Ms. Mandel sighed.
</P>
</TEXT>
