<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-17 16:08 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8886 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-THOMPSON-COLUMN-$ADV2     02-17 0957
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-THOMPSON-COLUMN-$ADV21-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
POST-IMPEACHMENT THOUGHT: AMERICA FINDS LEADERSHIP WHEN NEEDED 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For release Sunday, Feb. 21)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ROBERT E. THOMPSON  
 c.1999 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ We Americans have been very fortunate. Whenever we
have needed strong, enlightened leadership to steer the republic
safely through perilous seas, we have found it.
</P>
<P>
   That was true when George Washington, John Adams, Thomas
Jefferson, James Madison, Ben Franklin and Alexander Hamilton
molded 13 small colonies on the Atlantic seaboard into a fledging
nation. We hope that will be true today in the wake of the divisive
impeachment trial of Bill Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   The leaders who have come to the fore in time of need have not
always been brilliant, but they have been courageous and dedicated.
They may not all have been presidential greats, but they have
served their country well.
</P>
<P>
   When Richard Nixon resigned a quarter century ago, the job of
healing the nation's post-Watergate wounds fell to Gerald Ford, a
decent man who performed the task with the skill of a political
professional who also happens to be a humanitarian.
</P>
<P>
   In the aftermath of the current scandal, the healer could be the
man who ignited the impeachment crisis and then fueled it with
deceptive declarations for a year. When Clinton rode out the storm
and retained the presidency, the duty of binding the lesions left
by bitter debate and angry denunciations fell to the president
himself.
</P>
<P>
   That is one of the major differences between the scandal that
ended Nixon's presidency and the one that eroded Clinton's.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton apologized for his actions and declared that we have
entered a time for reconciliation and renewal. But if he is to
leave a legacy other than that of his impeachment trial, he must do
as much as he can in less that two years to benefit the American
people, safeguard the republic and demonstrate that he can be
trusted.
</P>
<P>
   He must be diligent in seeking the bipartisan cooperation of
Congress on strengthening Social Security, Medicare, the
educational system and our national security and on such other
vital matters as economic prosperity and tax relief for the working
middle class.
</P>
<P>
   He would only compound his troubles and further weaken his
presidency if he were to seek revenge against those on Capitol Hill
who believed his indiscretions fit the high-crimes-and-misdemeanors
criteria established by the Constitution for removing a president
from office.
</P>
<P>
   Whether Clinton can achieve those objectives is uncertain. We
could experience nearly two years of stalemate until a new
president is sworn in _ or a period of unprecedented accomplishment
by a Democratic White House and a Republican Congress.
</P>
<P>
   Although two thirds of the people continue to approve Clinton's
presidential performance, a Gallup Poll last week showed that 59
percent believe he has lowered the stature of the presidency.
</P>
<P>
   The Republicans who dominate Capitol Hill have little to crow
about. Having watched the public reject their efforts to unseat
Clinton, they cannot afford to be seen as mere obstructionists who
simply oppose Clinton's initiatives.
</P>
<P>
   If Clinton and the current Congress cannot lead America out of
its morass, then in 2000 we will elect a new president and a new
Congress that may do so.
</P>
<P>
   At the birth of the republic 210 years ago, the American people
knew exactly the leader they wanted: Washington, a stalwart soldier
and statesman who had guided them to military victory against the
forces of George III and presided over the 1787 convention that
wrote the Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   In 1800 the people elected Jefferson, an illustrious visionary
and author of the Declaration of Independence who doubled the size
of the young nation with the Louisiana Purchase and dispatched
Meriwether Lewis and William Clark on a monumental expedition of
discovery up the Missouri River, across the Rocky Mountains and
down the Columbia River to the Pacific Ocean.
</P>
<P>
   With westward expansion, people on the frontier wanted a
president who would fight for their interests. They found him in a
colorful, fiery Tennessean named Andrew Jackson.
</P>
<P>
   From Jackson's presidency, which ended in 1837, to the beginning
of the Civil War, the republic did not have strong presidents. But
in 1860, the people elected Abraham Lincoln, a lanky lawyer from
Illinois, a courageous humanitarian who possessed a wealth of humor
and a determination to preserve the union.
</P>
<P>
   The period from the assassination of Lincoln in 1865 to the
beginning of the 20th century was another fallow time for
presidential leadership. But in 1901, after the assassination of
William McKinley, a 42-year-old force of nature named Theodore
Roosevelt burst upon the American scene. He introduced much-needed
reforms to benefit the common people rather than the rich and
powerful.
</P>
<P>
   Since Roosevelt, we have had in this century several recessions
and one Great Depression; wars in Europe, the Pacific, Korea,
Vietnam and the Persian Gulf; at least three major scandals that
reached into the White House, and various other crises that
demanded able leadership. For the most part, we have found it when
we needed it or we have replaced a failed leader with a good one.
</P>
<P>
   And we will do so again.
</P>
<P>
   On Aug. 9, 1974, when he picked up the presidential torch that
had fallen from Nixon's hands, Gerald Ford told the American people
that ``our long national nightmare is over. Our Constitution works.
Our great republic is a government of laws and not of men. Here the
people rule.''
</P>
<P>
   Those words are worth remembering at this time of transition
even for those who disagree with the Senate's exoneration of
Clinton.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
