<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-17 16:09 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8888 &Cx1f; tie-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CIR-TYPING-SOFTWARE-A     02-17 1285
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CIR-TYPING-SOFTWARE-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IT'S LIKE TYPING CLASS, BUT YOU SET THE RHYTHM 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.)  
 (af)  
 By J.D. BIERSDORFER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Typing class is one of those dreaded high-school rituals,
ranking right up there with (ugh) physical education class. If I
had only had a nice computer program back then to teach me, instead
of the bored teacher who was saddled with me, I might have actually
learned to type.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, I spent many fruitless hours banging away at an IBM
Selectric, hoping that some of the letters would be right.
</P>
<P>
   But that was 17 years ago. Today's typing student has a wide
variety of engaging software to choose from. With most programs,
you stick to the old tried-and-true method of typing instruction:
learn the home row keys (a, s, d, f, j, k, l, ;) and branch out
from there until your fingers are trained to find all the keys.
</P>
<P>
   The glory of technology allows the computer to respond directly
to the student's keystrokes and analyze them, in the ultimate
one-on-one tutorial. In many cases, users can even adjust the
program's skill level for a custom fit. Instead of pounding out
coma-inducing practice texts about cork trees in Algeria from
oversized typing manuals, students can spice up their lessons with
audio, video and electronic games.
</P>
<P>
   Now that computers are ubiquitous, it's not just secretaries and
writers who need to know how to use a keyboard. Typing as a
professional skill has been around for more than 100 years, and it
was even enthusiastically adopted by Mark Twain.
</P>
<P>
   Although some scholars dispute his recollections, Twain himself
recalled writing ``The Adventures of Tom Sawyer'' on his trusty
Remington typewriter and is credited with inventing the typed,
double-spaced manuscript format still in use in the editorial
world.
</P>
<P>
   Early examples of Twain's practice pages show them to be riddled
with typos. To be fair, however, there wasn't a lot of typing
instruction to be had at the time. Imagine what Twain could have
done with an iMac and a copy of Mavis Beacon.
</P>
<P>
   Here's one for the Great Paradoxes of History file: the first
successful typing machine in America _ a device intended to make
writing faster and more efficient _ used a keyboard layout that
made typists slow down.
</P>
<P>
   Although scholars debate the motivations behind this layout,
called the Qwerty keyboard for the letters above the left hand when
it is on the home keys, the popular legend remains: In 1868,
Christopher Latham Sholes, along with his friends Carlos Glidden
and S.W. Soule, patented an early version of what would become the
Type-Writer a few years later. But he couldn't stop the keys from
jamming if they were hit too rapidly in succession.
</P>
<P>
   Since it was not possible to fix this internal hardware glitch,
the story goes, Sholes replaced the sensible alphabetic arrangement
of the keys with the now-famous (and infamous) Qwerty keyboard. By
scattering commonly used letters around the keyboard, Sholes
effectively slowed down even the speediest typists of the late 19th
century. But by eliminating jammed keys, the new layout actually
speeded up the overall typing process.
</P>
<P>
   With the exception of the hunt-and-peck method (still used by
many today), there was no prescribed typing method for the early
machines. Typists were expected to look at the keys to see what
they were typing, and two fingers were thought to be perfectly
adequate (four fingers for overachievers) to work the Type-Writer.
</P>
<P>
   The first textbook to outline a typing method, ``Handbook of
Instruction for the Type-Writer'' by Edward F. Underhill, was
published in 1880. But few people bought the 16-page handbook,
preferring instead to take their typing advice straight from the
Bible: Seek and ye shall find.
</P>
<P>
   The Dvorak keyboard, patented in 1932 by August Dvorak and W.L.
Dealey, provided a more sensible arrangement of keys that let 70
percent of the typing take place in the home row. Perhaps Dvorak
just made too much sense for most people. The Qwerty keyboard, in
its most basic form, has survived to this day and is the standard
for the English-typing world. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Typing Instructor Deluxe, Version 9 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Individual Software; $29.95; Windows 3.1 and later.) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps to get the attention of wandering minds, Typing
Instructor takes the somewhat dry notion of typing lessons and
bends the practice into a globe-trotting theme. Upon starting the
software, the student enters the Main Terminal of a virtual
airport, and the travel motif continues throughout the program.
</P>
<P>
   You set your skill level in the Typing Passport, get your
Boarding Pass to start your lessons and gradually earn stamps for
it by passing typing tests that feature pictures of different
countries along with the test text.
</P>
<P>
   Students can choose from more than 20 musical styles _ like
Dixieland, Latin, Broadway, funk, dance and rock _ for the music
playing in the background as the typing lessons commence.
Fortunately, much of it sounds like that airy pseudojazz often
heard in supermarkets, so the impulse to quit the program and go
out to a club is quashed.
</P>
<P>
   The travel backdrop of this program has been well thought out
and will probably appeal to adult students. The theme is carried
out consistently. A digital Magazine Rack, much like those found in
airports, holds typing practice material from more than 300 books,
articles and short stories to keep the student engaged in the
routine of practicing.
</P>
<P>
   No typing program is complete these days without games to entice
students to hone their emerging skills through video combat. With
seven action games, Typing Instructor plays primarily to the male
gaming crowd.
</P>
<P>
   A mountain-biking contest called Xtreme Typing is designed to
improve typing speed, and Tomb Typer encourages accuracy, but _
sorry, boys _ there's no Lara Croft here. You might, however,
actually learn to type. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Disney's Adventures In Typing With Timon And Pumbaa &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Disney Interactive; $19.95; Windows 95 and later, and Power
Macintosh.) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Where are we going?'' the warthog asks his buddy, Timon the
meerkat, in the opening cartoon in Disney's Adventures in Typing
With Timon and Pumbaa.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are going on an adventure, Pumbaa,'' the meerkat replies.
``An adventure to broaden our horizons!''
</P>
<P>
   Broadening a young computer user's horizons by building keyboard
proficiency is the goal of this CD-ROM. The program uses three
popular characters from Disney's 1994 animated film ``The Lion
King'' _ Timon, Pumbaa and Rafiki the baboon _ to teach children
how to type.
</P>
<P>
   The program relies on a nice framing device to lure kids to the
keyboard. After Timon and Pumbaa tell Rafiki that they plan to go
on a jungle adventure, the wise old baboon realizes that the two
hapless friends will most likely get into trouble and will need a
little help to get back home again. With that, Rafiki presents the
user with a keyboard made from leaves and rocks, and the lessons
begin.
</P>
<P>
   The program is paced for young students. With on-screen
animations, the first lesson focuses on correct posture and hand
positions on the keyboard, as well as half of the home-row keys.
Lesson 2 picks up the rest of the home row.
</P>
<P>
   As the student works through the drills, the key combinations
gradually move from simple key repetitions (like ddd, fff, lll,
aaa, sss) to simple words (like sad, dad, falls) that help the user
see where all this is going. The rest of the keyboard is learned
quickly in subsequent lessons and then speed and precision are
emphasized.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
