NYT-02-17-99 1609EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990217.0233 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-17 16:10 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8891 &Cx1f; tie-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CIR-TYPING-SOFTWARE-A     02-17 1067
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CIR-TYPING-SOFTWARE-ART-2NDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 UNDATED: are emphasized.  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The program offers five games in which the student may aid Timon
and Pumbaa with typing. There's a Smack-a-Bug game in which little
insects with letters on their backs pop out of the ground to insult
the warthog, and the student can help the frustrated pig exact his
revenge by typing the proper letter. By completing the games and
the lessons, the student helps Timon and Pumbaa return home safely.
</P>
<P>
   There are 15 animated lessons from the old baboon in the
program. Lesson-by-lesson progress reports showing words-per-minute
typing speed as well as typing accuracy are available by clicking
on a program icons. The child can print out an award certificate at
the end of the course.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps the biggest selling point for this program is the fact
that it carries over much of the look of the ``Lion King'' movie,
not to mention the brand name. Adventures in Typing has much of the
wisecracking attitude of the film, and the animation is definitely
Disney. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Mavis Beacon Teaches Typing, Version 9 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Mindscape; $39.95; Windows 3.1 and later, and Macintosh.) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``You will master the keys by typing them repeatedly,'' the
teacher commands.
</P>
<P>
   She's not kidding. Mavis Beacon, the grande dame of
instructional typing software, rules her classroom with a firm yet
guiding hand. Keyboard drills are presented and repeated until the
student passes muster, but Mavis forgives early mistakes. ``This is
the hard part,'' she says. ``Keep going and soon it will get easier
_ I promise.''
</P>
<P>
   Mavis Beacon Teaches Typing is perhaps the most popular product
in the category, with more than six million copies sold since the
program's debut in 1987. Mavis Beacon Version 9 was released last
fall; it combines snazzy 3-D graphics and the calming voice of
Mavis with responsive, flexible programming that helps the user and
the software adapt to each other.
</P>
<P>
   Mavis Beacon can analyze a student's keystrokes and spot problem
areas, like transition rates between keys, shift-key errors and
doubled keys.
</P>
<P>
   The program is set in the Mavis Beacon Typing Institute, which
you see upon starting the software. Mavis greets you at the desk
and offers a variety of options.
</P>
<P>
   You can proceed directly to the lessons or visit some other
areas of Mavis' world. There's a Media Center, which has a Video
Viewer to demonstrate proper posture, typing techniques and office
ergonomics in video clips. A Practice Area lets the user select
different kinds of texts, including fiction and history, for a
keyboard workout.
</P>
<P>
   Mavis' Game Hallway offers eight games that are designed to
improve speed, proficiency and typing rhythm. The animated Shark
Attack, Penguin Crossing and Creature Lab games aim to strengthen
speed and accuracy by having the student rapidly type words as part
of the play. The Playing Ragtime game has students type letters to
the beat of a ticking metronome on an old piano.
</P>
<P>
   The student must repeat a drill to Mavis' satisfaction or there
is no moving on. Lessons can be modified to the user's tastes. For
example, users can import custom text that they would like to
practice on and can choose different types of music to type by.
</P>
<P>
   One warning: in the Country category, most of the tunes sound
like the schmaltzy 1970s-era Nashville Sound as played on a Kimball
Swinger Organ. The Classical category, however, provides quite nice
music to type by.
</P>
<P>
   Mavis Beacon isn't the flashiest typing program on the block
anymore. But even though Mavis is a creation of the Mindscape
company, her no-nonsense approach, familiar personality and
diligent, wide-ranging focus on all aspects of typing (plus an
extensive user's guide included with the CD-ROM) make her a most
comfortable teacher _ which is just what you want. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Typing Tutor '99 Platinum Edition &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Knowledge Adventure/Simon &AMP; Schuster; $49.99; Windows 3.1 and
later, and Power Macintosh.) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Stressing accuracy from every direction, the Platinum edition of
Typing Tutor '99 comes not only with the program CD-ROM but also
includes another disk, called 1001 Essential Letters, and a
paperback dictionary and thesaurus set. In addition to all this,
Typing Tutor provides something called the CETM Lesson Module.
</P>
<P>
   Although the title sounds like something from NASA's astronaut
school, you soon find out that CETM stands for Conceptual Effects
Typing Method. It is a series of exercises that dispenses with the
home-row methodology in favor of introducing the student to the
keyboard layout finger by finger.
</P>
<P>
   For example, the drill for the Left Little Finger has a series
of q-a-z combinations repeated over and over to help foster skill
memory. At first, CETM seems a little weird and annoying, but as
the 10 fingers learn their motor skills, it begins to make sense.
</P>
<P>
   The main Typing Tutor program, however, uses the traditional
method of learning the keyboard. The program will first ask you how
many words per minute you want to be able to type; after each
lesson, bar charts will show you how accurate you were in striking
each particular key and how fast you typed.
</P>
<P>
   Typing Tutor '99 includes only a few games, the most memorable
being Letter Invaders, which is based on Space Invaders, an arcade
staple.
</P>
<P>
   Like many other typing applications, the program contains a
video area. But instead of showing video clips of proper ergonomic
behavior, as the Mavis Beacon program does, Typing Tutor '99 lets
the student select a category like Newsreels or Sports.
</P>
<P>
   The Newsreels category contains digitized clips from historical
films, like ``Statehood for Alaska'' and ``F.D.R. Asks for War
Aid.'' The program displays a portion of practice text related to
the video clip, and once the student has completed the drill, the
video clip plays.
</P>
<P>
   Typing Tutor '99 is thorough and has quite a lot going for it.
The software will read aloud text passages so the user can practice
taking dictation, and it offers a Library List that provides
summaries and additional information on texts used as exercise
material.
</P>
<P>
   These features are found in the Bookshelf area, which mainly
serves to let students select famous literary works as practice
texts (as do most of the other programs tested). A notable
selection for typing software _ in a delightful sense of cosmic
justice _ is Mark Twain's ``Adventures of Tom Sawyer.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
