<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-17 16:10 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8893 &Cx1f; taf-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HOME-IMPROVEMENT-ART-     02-17 0862
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOME-IMPROVEMENT-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOME CLINIC: KEEPING WATCH ON CARBON MONOXIDE 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Diagram is being sent as photo and as graphic to NYT
photo-graphics clients. Non-subscribers can make individual
purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.)  
 (bl)  
 By EDWARD R. LIPINSKI   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   According to the American Medical Association, carbon monoxide
poisoning is one of the leading causes of accidental deaths in the
United States. Each year, there are more than 10,000 cases of
reported health injuries attributed to carbon monoxide exposure.
</P>
<P>
   During the winter months, the incidence of carbon monoxide
poisoning rises because people remain indoors with the windows
closed. Since carbon monoxide is produced by incomplete combustion
of carbon-based fuels (natural gas, heating oils, gasoline, wood,
kerosene), any malfunction in a heating or venting system can allow
this deadly gas to enter into the home environment.
</P>
<P>
   Many victims are not even aware when they are exposed to carbon
monoxide because it is a colorless, odorless gas, and the early
stages of carbon monoxide poisoning produce flu-like symptoms:
headaches, fatigue, nausea and dizziness.
</P>
<P>
   The first step in preventing carbon monoxide poisoning in the
home is to make sure that the heating system gets an annual tune-up
by a qualified heating specialist. The tune-up should include
burner cleaning and adjustment and a carbon monoxide test.
</P>
<P>
   Even the most efficient burners will produce some carbon
monoxide, but this usually presents no health hazard because the
combustion gases are expelled outside through the exhaust system.
Most home exhaust systems, however, rely on the natural buoyancy of
hot air to pull the exhaust gases outside; no fans are involved.
</P>
<P>
   The air that is expelled must be replaced by fresh air from the
outside. Sometimes, in newer homes, problems develop because the
structures are so tight that replacement air cannot enter. This
causes the combustion gases to build up in the system and
eventually drift into the living quarters.
</P>
<P>
   The problem is exacerbated if the house is fitted with exhaust
fans in the bathroom and over the stove. A clothes dryer will also
function like an exhaust fan when it is running. These fans force
air out of the house, and if fresh replacement air is not pulled in
from the outside, the fans will suck the combustion gases from the
heating vent system back into the house. This condition is known as
``backdrafting.''
</P>
<P>
   Carbon monoxide can also seep into the house through an attached
garage when an automobile is warming up on a cold morning. Safety
experts point out that in 1992 more than 45 percent of the
accidental carbon monoxide deaths were the result of auto exhausts
entering the home through the garage. Other sources of carbon
monoxide are a malfunctioning kitchen gas range, a smoldering fire
in the fireplace and a cracked flue in the chimney.
</P>
<P>
   Because carbon monoxide is colorless, odorless and tasteless, it
may go undetected even when there are high concentrations in the
air. You can protect your family by installing carbon monoxide
detectors in the house. These inexpensive devices (most sell for
less than $60) are designed to sound an alarm when the carbon
monoxide concentration becomes dangerously high (400 ppm for 15
minutes) or when low levels persist for more than 90 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Detectors are available as battery-operated models or plug-in
units. The plug-in units connect to a standard electrical outlet.
An obvious drawback is that they are useless in the event of a
power failure _ which is when people are most likely to turn to
backup sources like woodstoves and kerosene heaters, both potential
sources of carbon monoxide. Battery-operated units are not affected
by power failures, but you must replace the batteries periodically.
The best line of defense is install both types in your home.
</P>
<P>
   When purchasing a carbon monoxide detector, look for the
Underwriters Laboratory Logo (UL) to make sure the model meets the
official standard. Other important features include indicator
lights: one that shows the unit is receiving power, and another
light that glows when the alarm sounds. Battery- operated units
should have an indicator light to show when the battery is weak.
Another important feature is a test and reset button, so used to
make sure the unit is functioning properly.
</P>
<P>
   Install the detectors where they can be heard from the bedrooms
even with the doors closed. For more complete protection, install
detectors near potential sources of carbon monoxide _ the furnace,
the kitchen range, the fireplace and the garage. Do not, however,
install the detectors within 15 feet of fuel-burning appliances,
and do not install them in potentially humid areas like the
bathroom or laundry room.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike smoke detectors, carbon monoxide detectors should not be
installed on the ceiling. Instead they should be mounted on a wall
at eye level (some companies offer table-top detectors), so you
will notice and test them weekly. Be sure to carefully read the
manufacturer's instructions so you can clean and maintain the
detector properly. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
