<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-17 16:15 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8896 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TEX-LEGIS-PERMITS-COX     02-17 0704
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEX-LEGIS-PERMITS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Third time may not be a charm for bill to limit debate on
permits
 &HT;    
 &HT;    By Janet Jacobs
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONGVIEW, Texas _ For the third time in as many legislative
sessions in Texas, a bill being proposed to cut down on the amount
of public debate on permits is taking heat.
</P>
<P>
   House Bill 801 would take the public hearings out of the
environmental permitting process, and though it does provide for
input, it is not considered a positive change by environmentalists.
</P>
<P>
   Their concern is unnecessary, according to legislators
sponsoring the bill.
</P>
<P>
   ``By no means does it outlaw public participation,'' said Mike
Sizemore, office manager for state Sen. Ken Armbrister, D-Victoria.
Armbrister is expected to sponsor the bill if it makes it to the
Senate.
</P>
<P>
   The bill will change the way permits are opposed, but it won't
make protests impossible, according to state Rep. D.R. ``Tom''
Uher, D-Bay City.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a streamlined process to review permits and have public
input,'' Uher said. ``In my opinion, this opens up the door for
more people to be involved.''
</P>
<P>
   According to Uher, the proposed bill would allow people
statewide to comment in writing on any permit, but it will
eliminate the public hearing process now used.
</P>
<P>
   ``We provide for that if they send a comment; it's part of the
record,'' he said. ``We encourage the agency to review the comments
as they come in.''
</P>
<P>
   ``You won't have the adversarial system we have now, but we will
have a similar system because people will be able to take
depositions, and if someone is trying to be cute, they're going to
be caught at it,'' Uher said.
</P>
<P>
   Uher said the proposed system is the same one used by the
Environmental Protection Agency and many other states.
</P>
<P>
   It could dramatically cut down on the length of the permitting
process, according to officials with TNRCC.
</P>
<P>
   ``Contested case hearings, if eliminated, will shorten it by
several months,'' said Terry Hadley, spokesman for TNRCC.
</P>
<P>
   Currently, an average permit for wastewater or air emissions
takes several months, Hadley said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've seen everything from 30 days to extremes of several
years in terms of low-level radioactive waste,'' Hadley said. ``In
general terms, it is a several-months process.''
</P>
<P>
   If the process is cut down, it shouldn't be a free ride,
according to state Sen. Bill Ratliff, R-Mount Pleasant.
</P>
<P>
   Ratliff was a sponsor of a similar bill in the last session, but
he dropped his support of the bill when residents complained that
it would give local industries too much of an advantage in the
permitting process.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we probably do need to streamline the process,''
Ratliff said. ``I don't know if this is the way to do it.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I think if we do make it easier to get a permit, we ought to
make it a lot tougher when they are violated,'' Ratliff added.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just feel like, over the years, we've gotten to the point
that anybody who applies gets a permit. And the permit may require
a lot of things, but once the permit is issued, we have a lot of
people who just sort of routinely violate the permit.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is no teeth in the enforcement,'' Ratliff said.
</P>
<P>
   Adding teeth to the enforcement should include heavier fines or
even rescinding permits, Ratliff said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't have much problem streamlining the process, but if
we're going to do that, I think we need to make sure that if we do
that, we need to make sure those people who routinely violate the
process pay for it,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The state's environmental office does have some problems with
that, Hadley said, but he said the TNRCC does levy fines on
industries that violate permits and can take away permits issued.
</P>
<P>
   Under current law, a maximum of $10,000 per day per violation
can be fined. The TNRCC has levied fines that heavy in a few cases,
Hadley said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The biggest penalty was around $2 million,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Taking away permits is certainly a lengthy process, he added.
</P>
<P>
   ``What we're talking about here is a compliance issue,'' Hadley
said. ``The compliance issue should be a concern for everybody.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
