<HEADER>
A8942 &Cx1f; tie-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CIR-DIARIES-NYT &LR;      02-17 1020
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CIR-DIARIES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DIGITAL GUARDIANS OF SIBLING PEACE 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By MICHELLE SLATALLA   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   I cannot say whether Ella's suspicions were justified, but she
seemed quite convinced one day last week that her older sister had
read her diary. In retaliation, she drew a primitive skull and
crossbones on the book, then scrawled, ``Next time, Keep out or DIE
_ that means you ZOE.''
</P>
<P>
   Nor could I judge the accuracy of her older sister's hunch that
someone (Ella?) was sneaking red licorice from the trove hidden in
her dresser. Zoe had installed a security system by painstakingly
draping hairs over doorknobs, drawer openings and even the
licorice.
</P>
<P>
   This age-old childhood ritual _ sibling espionage _ seemed
harmless enough, if the sisters had in fact been carrying out
raids. But what if my daughters were becoming paranoid?
</P>
<P>
   I think I am amply qualified to recognize the signs. Over the
years I have been certain, at various times, that my sixth-grade
teacher was out to get me, that a dawdling counter clerk at
Starbuck's was out to get me and that the cats were out to get me.
I might have been wrong about my teacher.
</P>
<P>
   But the more practical problem in this instance was that Zoe, 9,
and Ella, 7, were using hopelessly old-fashioned ``Spy vs. Spy''
techniques to frustrate each other. How could they hope to generate
accurate field reports?
</P>
<P>
   To help, I suggested that my daughters embrace technology in the
form of a couple of new electronic toys called the Password Journal
and the Door Pass, which sell for $19.99 apiece. These anti-snooper
devices, which rely on voice-recognition technology and
irritatingly loud alarms, are among the first generation of
products from Girltech (www.girltech.com) and were created by the
mother-daughter design team of Janese and (12-year-old) Jackie
Swanson.
</P>
<P>
   I had some reservations, of course. Having experienced my
daughters' lukewarm reactions to most other microchip-enhanced
gadgetry _ even the Game Boy Color is moldering under a sofa _ I
was skeptical of Girltech's boast that the products could ``bring
girls closer to the world of technology.''
</P>
<P>
   But as soon as the test units arrived, I saw that my daughters
did, in fact, have an appetite for electronic devices. I learned
that while demonstrating the Password Journal, a bright purple
plastic box the size of a hardcover book. I explained that the
owner had to record a code word that would cause the box's top to
pop open. I showed them the little spiral-ringed notebook and
pencil stored inside. Also, I noted, there is a secret compartment
where you can hide your _ .
</P>
<P>
   Suddenly Ella snatched the journal, clutched it to her chest and
shrieked desperately: ``You can have anything else that you want,
Zoe, even my Barbies, but this is mine! Mine!''
</P>
<P>
   In the next few hours, I observed a curious pattern. First Ella
would record a password _ say, ``Ella rules _ you know it'' _ then
pop the lid, write a secret entry, snap the box shut and challenge
the rest of the family to break in. After all our attempts
(including my husband's incredibly Ella-like falsetto) failed, the
journal would announce ``access denied'' in a tinny voice and
tattle to Ella, ``Three intruders!'' Then she would cackle
maniacally and run off to change the password.
</P>
<P>
   By the next morning, the rest of us were getting a little sick
of the Password Journal. But Ella would not be parted from it and
begged to take it to school. At the breakfast table, she made a
show of changing her password to ``Zoe stinks,'' prompting Zoe to
yell, ``That's not true!'' while the machine was still recording.
Conscientiously, the journal subsequently refused to open unless
the sisters repeated their chorus.
</P>
<P>
   Fortunately, Zoe was equally intrigued by the Door Pass, a green
and purple plastic box that she attached to her bedroom door via
its Velcro mount. Armed with a motion sensor in addition to
fearsome voice-recognition capabilities, the Door Pass challenges
any trespasser. If the intruder fails to repeat the secret password
(``Our cats love Mom''), an alarm sounds.
</P>
<P>
   Returning home from school, Zoe was mystified to learn that
``one intruder'' had breached the premises _ until she realized
that her baby sister, Clementine, was in the hall clutching a
fistful of red licorice.
</P>
<P>
   ``Give it to me, Clemmie,'' she cajoled. ``No way! No way!''
Clementine yelled, running behind the bed and setting off the alarm
again.
</P>
<P>
   Impressed by the simple, efficient design of these gadgets, we
also tested Girltech's Beam-It ($9.99), a flashlight that would be
especially useful at slumber parties. It enables the user to
project a written message on a dark wall.
</P>
<P>
   Another Girltech product, a programmable photo frame ($14.99)
that will speak a sentence to describe the friend in the photo, did
not hold my daughters' interest for long. But Clementine, age 1,
conversed with it as she pushed it around in her doll stroller. The
frame announced, ``My friend is brave and bold and inventive and _
''
</P>
<P>
   ``No way! No way!'' Clementine responded.
</P>
<P>
   The only real criticism I had was with the toy company's name,
Girltech. If your purpose is to enfranchise girls and offer them
more choices, why pick a name that implicitly limits choice by
implying that all the other toys out there must be ``boy tech''?
</P>
<P>
   When I phoned Girltech's founder, Janese Swanson, she told me
that she had heard that complaint before. But she said her research
showed that too many girls still thought of all technology as
belonging to boys. So Girltech's name is a conscious effort to
counteract that perception.
</P>
<P>
   ``At this point,'' Ms. Swanson said, ``girls need to be able to
claim technology for themselves.''
</P>
<P>
   Then she told me about another toy in development, the Keepsafe
Box ($19.99). It will have a window in which you can display
valuables to tempt your enemies, er, siblings. It will drive them
crazy, of course, because the only person who can open the box will
be the owner, using a remote-controlled clicker. Call me paranoid,
but I think Zoe should keep her licorice in there.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
