<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-17 16:39 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8945 &Cx1f; tie-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CIR-DRIVING-GAME-NYT &LR;      02-17 1008
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CIR-DRIVING-GAME-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FEELING VIRTUAL WHEELS RUMBLE ON THE TRACK 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By J.C. HERZ   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The big news in the auto industry is computers _ how many chips
are on board in each new car and how software is improving car
performance and revolutionizing car design.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, companies like Microsoft and Electronic Arts are
trying to build steering wheels and brake pedals into their video
games. Now that computers are powerful enough to bring road rumble
and potholes and centrifugal force to bear on the virtual driving
experience, games enhanced with force feedback put you in the
driver's seat, albeit in a hyperbolic automotive theme world where
pebbles feel like giant boulders and idling engines buzz like chain
saws.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, steering wheels and driving games are nothing new.
Arguably, the first video-game steering wheel was the Atari 2600
paddle controller in 1978. Racing games for Atari and Colecovision
didn't have much in the way of special effects. But they did create
a competitive driving situation and, for a grade-school kid, that
was enough.
</P>
<P>
   A decade later, Sony and Nintendo introduced controllers that
vibrated, so if you crashed into a wall, you got buzzed. Around the
same time, makers of personal computer peripherals began making
bigger and more expensive versions of the same thing.
</P>
<P>
   Now tactile feedback is standard. You can feel the road surface.
You can feel torque and resistance around a corner. There is a
difference between rolling over the planks of a covered bridge and
cruising down an asphalt highway. If you speed up, the car handles
differently. It's not just about the quantity of feedback. The
information has quality as well.
</P>
<P>
   And where there are differences in quality, there are
differences of interpretation. Case in point: Monster Truck Madness
2, published by Microsoft, apparently to showcase the
force-feedback overkill capabilities of its Sidewinder racing
wheel.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, the version that comes bundled with the wheel is even
stronger and more rumbly than the version on store shelves.
</P>
<P>
   ``It almost shakes the wheel out of your hand,'' said Brett
Schnepf, the technical evangelist at Microsoft for Sidewinder game
devices. ``We joke about that when we go to developers _ the
Spielberg versus Newton implementation. Do you want to go Newton,
which is what the Flight Simulator guys do, versus the Spielberg,
which is more like Monster Truck Madness 2.''
</P>
<P>
   Need for Speed 3, published by Electronic Arts, doesn't quite
conform to Newtonian concepts of momentum and gravity, but it does
take a subtler approach. A valentine to car design, it offers the
player a chocolate box of high-performance name-brand automobiles
at their slickest and most shiny (a '98 Corvette C5, an Aston
Martin DB7, a Mercedes-Benz SL600, a Jaguar XK8, a couple of
Ferraris and a pair of Lamborghinis).
</P>
<P>
   Pebbles in the road are less important than the illusion that
you can tell the difference in handling between sports cars you're
never going to drive _ virtual connoisseurship, if you will.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, Need for Speed 3 is a cartoon as well. But who wants
to drive 55 miles per hour in cyberspace, anyway? In the absence of
highway fatalities, auto insurance premiums and gridlock, racing
games are a virtual autobahn where you can drive as fast as you
want with complete disregard for speed laws or physical safety.
</P>
<P>
   As long as you're flooring a Lamborghini Countach, your
immediate environment might as well feel like one big engine.
You're never going to drive that car in real life. Why not go for
the Spielberg version?
</P>
<P>
   There is the physical reality of driving: steering wheel,
pedals, rear-view mirror. And then there is the emotional
experience, the fantasy of driving, which begins the first time you
understand that the person in the front seat controls a car.
</P>
<P>
   Kids don't experience the physical reality of driving, but they
push toy cars around and say ``vrooom.'' They see pictures of cars
and learn about them. Later they fantasize about becoming race car
drivers. Playing computer games is part of that fantasy. Realism is
beside the point.
</P>
<P>
   But because steering a virtual car with a PC racing wheel
simulates the physical reality of a car (albeit with tremendous
distortion), it shapes your ideas about how driving should look and
feel, especially if you are too young to drive a car.
</P>
<P>
   By the time teen-agers get car keys, many of them have been
driving for 10 years. They've been driving Indy 500 race cars,
monster trucks, jet skis, spaceships and 40-foot robots. They have
ideas about what a vehicle is and what it can do for you.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, they quickly find out that driving a car is not
nearly so dramatic as piloting vehicles through a video game. But
that's easy to accept because reality defines the difference
between a virtual car and a two-ton hunk of steel.
</P>
<P>
   Other disparities are harder to accept because they have to do
with the way you process information while you're driving. A real
car gauges fuel, speed, mileage, revolutions per minute. To read
that information, you have to look down, and you cannot change the
way it's displayed.
</P>
<P>
   In Need for Speed 3, your windshield has a heads-up display that
can be completely customized (analog or digital speedometer with
readings in miles or kilometers, a tachometer that magnifies around
the red zone, etc.). It's more like a fighter plane than a car and
without a doubt, it works better.
</P>
<P>
   Someday, when thin-film windshield displays roll off the General
Motors assembly line, car magazines will make a big deal about it.
And young adults will shrug because they will have 10 years of
experience driving with heads-up displays.
</P>
<P>
   And if they are nice, they will help their parents when the
windshield starts flashing ``12:00.'' &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Monster Truck Madness 2; published by Microsoft; CD-ROM for
Windows 95 and 98; $49.95. Need for Speed 3; published by
Electronic Arts; CD-ROM for Windows 95 and 98; $49.95. Both games,
all ages.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
