<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PORKDISHES-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THIS LITTLE PIGGY OFFERS ONE CUT THAT'S A GREAT BUY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BEVERLY BUNDY 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   With one exception _ which savvy shoppers should note _
consumers aren't benefiting from the hard times hitting pig
farmers.
</P>
<P>
   Despite an oversupply of pigs, and farmers receiving $30 for a
hog that earned $60 a year ago, prices at the meat counter have
been steady.
</P>
<P>
   ``The demand for pork has risen 7 to 8 percent over the past two
to three years,'' says Robin Kline, director of consumer affairs
for the National Pork Producers Council. The increasing demand
allows supermarkets to keep prices at pre-surplus levels.
</P>
<P>
   ``Occasionally, you'll see some chains featuring pork chops,''
says Kline, ``but you're never going to see baby-back ribs on
special. Or tenderloins, because that's always been a highly
demanded cut.''
</P>
<P>
   However, one part of the hog has been on special regularly over
the winter months, and it's a prime part. Whole pork loins,
regularly priced at $3.99 a pound, are often featured at $1.99 a
pound.
</P>
<P>
   This 6- to 7-pound roll of boneless pork is a boon for the
bargain-shopping home cook. Sold vacuum-packed and unfrozen, it can
be taken home and divvied up into a decent-size roast, stir-fry
pieces, cubes for kebabs, butterfly pork chops, and medallions or
scallops. And because there is no bone involved, only the most
basic butchering skills are needed.
</P>
<P>
   Start with one of the three pork loin recipes here.
</P>
<P>
   And remember when you're preparing pork that trichinae, our
mothers' great fear, are killed at 137 degrees. Cooking pork to
170-185 degrees, the temperature recommended in old cookbooks,
produces dry, overcooked meat.
</P>
<P>
   ARISTA
</P>
<P>
   (TUSCAN HERB-INFUSED ROAST PORK LOIN)
</P>
<P>
   Serves 8
</P>
<P>
   2 1/2 tablespoons olive oil, divided use
</P>
<P>
   1 4-pound boneless pork loin, with a thin layer of fat left
intact
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup finely chopped fresh rosemary or 2 tablespoons dried
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons finely chopped fresh sage or 1 tablespoon dried
</P>
<P>
   2 teaspoons crushed fennel seed, see Note
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon kosher salt
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon freshly ground black pepper
</P>
<P>
   10 large garlic cloves, peeled and thinly sliced
</P>
<P>
   Pan sauce:
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup dry white wine
</P>
<P>
   1 cup chicken or beef stock
</P>
<P>
   Salt and freshly ground black pepper
</P>
<P>
   Note: To crush fennel seed, process in a small food processor or
place in a heavy, zipper-style plastic bag and pound with a mallet.
</P>
<P>
   Preheat oven to 450 degrees.
</P>
<P>
   Brush meat with 1 tablespoon olive oil. Combine herbs, fennel
seed, salt and pepper. Rub over meat. Drizzle meat with additional
1 tablespoon olive oil.
</P>
<P>
   Brush shallow roasting pan with 1/2 tablespoon olive oil and
scatter sliced garlic on bottom to provide a bed for the roast.
Place roast on garlic, fat side up. Place in middle of preheated
oven for 15 minutes. Turn oven to 300 degrees. Roast 1 1/4 hours
longer or until instant-read thermometer reads 150 degrees. Remove
from oven and cover loosely with aluminum foil.
</P>
<P>
   To prepare sauce, pour off fat and add wine to the roasting pan.
Bring to boil over high heat, scraping up any browned bits from the
bottom. Add stock and cook until the sauce is reduced by half. If
desired, strain the sauce. Taste and add salt and/or pepper as
needed. Slice pork and spoon sauce over the top.
</P>
<P>
   Nutritional analysis per serving: 355 calories, 22 grams fat, 1
gram carbohydrate, 46 grams protein, 102 milligrams cholesterol,
1,007 milligrams sodium, 56 percent of calories from fat.
</P>
<P>
   _ ``The Complete Meat Cookbook'' by Bruce Aidells and Denis
Kelly (Houghton Mifflin, 1998, $35)
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   STIR-FRIED PORK WITH SPINACH
</P>
<P>
   Serves 4
</P>
<P>
   1 pound pork loin, trimmed of external fat
</P>
<P>
   1 pound spinach, trimmed and well washed
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoon peanut or other vegetable oil
</P>
<P>
   1 1/2 tablespoons minced garlic
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon soy sauce
</P>
<P>
   Juice of 1/2 lime
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup minced scallion or 1/4 cup minced chives, for garnish
</P>
<P>
   Slice pork as thinly as possible (it's easier if you freeze it
for 15-20 minutes). Cut slices into bite-size pieces, about the
size of a quarter. Chop or tear spinach coarsely.
</P>
<P>
   When ready to cook, have all ingredients ready, including a
serving dish and cooked rice, if any. Preheat a wok or a large,
heavy skillet over high heat until it begins to smoke. Immediately
add half the peanut oil and all the pork. Cook, stirring
occasionally, until pork browns and loses all trace of pinkness,
about 3 minutes. Use a slotted spoon to remove pork to a bowl, and
lower heat to medium.
</P>
<P>
   Add remaining peanut oil to wok. Swirl it around and add garlic.
Stir once or twice. As soon as garlic begins to color _ about 15
seconds _ return heat to high and add spinach. Stir frequently,
just until spinach wilts, a minute or two longer.
</P>
<P>
   Add pork and stir for 1 minute. Add soy sauce and lime juice,
stir, turn off heat, garnish, and serve immediately.
</P>
<P>
   Nutritional analysis per serving: 266 calories, 16 grams fat, 5
grams carbohydrates, 27 grams protein, 67 milligrams cholesterol,
383 milligrams sodium, 53 percent of calories from fat.
</P>
<P>
   _ ``How to Cook Everything'' by Mark Bittman (Macmillan, $25)
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   PORK SALTIMBOCCA
</P>
<P>
   Serves 4
</P>
<P>
   6 1/2-inch-thick slices boneless pork loin (1 1/4-1 1/2 pounds
total), trimmed of all external fat
</P>
<P>
   6 thin slices prosciutto
</P>
<P>
   6 large sage or basil leaves or 1 teaspoon dried sage or basil
</P>
<P>
   Salt and freshly ground black pepper
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons olive oil, or more if necessary
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup dry white wine
</P>
<P>
   2 teaspoons minced garlic
</P>
<P>
   1/4 pound mushrooms, thinly sliced (optional)
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup veal or chicken stock
</P>
<P>
   Salt and freshly ground black pepper
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon chopped fresh parsley
</P>
<P>
   Using the flat side of a cleaver or meat mallet, gently pound
pork slices between two pieces of plastic wrap so that slices
measure 2 1/2 to 3 inches by 6 to 7 inches. They should be about
1/4-inch thick. Cover each slice with a slice of prosciutto and
place sage or basil leaf or a sprinkling of dried herbs on half of
each slice. Fold each slice in half over prosciutto and herbs; it
doesn't matter if some of the prosciutto sticks out around the
edges. Secure each packet with wooden toothpick. Season both sides
with salt and pepper.
</P>
<P>
   Heat oil in large, heavy skillet over high heat. Put in pork,
taking care not to crowd pan; fry in batches if necessary, adding
more oil as needed. Cook saltimbocca until lightly browned, 1 1/2
to 2 minutes on each side. Remove pork and set aside. Put in wine,
garlic and optional mushrooms and bring to a boil, scraping up any
browned bits from bottom of pan. Cook for 2-3 minutes, until wine
begins to reduce, then add stock and continue to boil until sauce
just turns syrupy. Taste for salt and pepper. Return saltimbocca to
pan and heat briefly in sauce to warm it through. (This time you
can crowd the pan if you need to.) Serve pork covered with sauce
and sprinkled with chopped parsley.
</P>
<P>
   Nutritional analysis per serving: 346 calories, 20 grams fat, 1
gram carbohydrates, 38 grams protein, 102 milligrams cholesterol,
398 milligrams sodium, 52 percent of calories from fat.
</P>
<P>
   _ ``The Complete Meat Cookbook''
</P>
<P>
   (Beverly Bundy is food editor for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram.
Send recipes and requests to Beverly Bundy, Fort Worth
Star-Telegram, Box 1870, Fort Worth, Texas 76101. Or E-mail to
bbundy(at)star-telegram.com. Include a daytime phone number.
Responses to requests will be made only through this column. Visit
the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
