<SLUG> BC-RECIPES-BUNDY-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ORANGE PUTS ZEST IN SALAD AND CHICKEN
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BEVERLY BUNDY 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Several readers sent in responses to our request for a recipe
for a salad that includes blue cheese and honey in the dressing.
None of the recipes includes blue cheese or honey, but this one
from Naomi Baker of Bedford, Texas, sounded the closest.
</P>
<P>
   MANDARIN SALAD
</P>
<P>
   Serves 4-6
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup sliced almonds
</P>
<P>
   3 tablespoons sugar
</P>
<P>
   1/2 head iceberg lettuce
</P>
<P>
   1/2 head romaine lettuce
</P>
<P>
   1 cup chopped celery
</P>
<P>
   2 whole green onions, chopped
</P>
<P>
   11-ounce can mandarin oranges, drained
</P>
<P>
   In small skillet over medium heat, toss almonds and sugar,
stirring constantly until almonds are coated and sugar dissolved.
Watch carefully, as they will burn easily. Cool and store in
airtight container.
</P>
<P>
   Combine lettuce, celery and onions. Just before serving, add
almonds and oranges. Toss with the dressing (see recipe below).
</P>
<P>
   Dressing:
</P>
<P>
   1/2 teaspoon salt
</P>
<P>
   Dash pepper
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup vegetable oil
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon chopped parsley
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons sugar
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons vinegar
</P>
<P>
   Dash of Tabasco sauce
</P>
<P>
   Combine all dressing ingredients and chill.
</P>
<P>
   Nutritional analysis per serving: 193 calories, 13 grams fat, 19
grams carbohydrates, 2 grams protein, 0 cholesterol, 222 milligrams
sodium, 60 percent of calories from fat.
</P>
<P>
   More on oranges: Margie Mitchell loves the orange chicken sold
at her local Kroger store. She has found several recipes for lemon
chicken, but none for orange. Here's one from ``365 More Ways to
Cook Chicken'' by Melanie Barnard (HarperCollins, $12.95).
</P>
<P>
   ORANGE CHICKEN
</P>
<P>
   Serves 4
</P>
<P>
   2 garlic cloves, minced
</P>
<P>
   3 tablespoons soy sauce
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon grated orange zest
</P>
<P>
   2 teaspoons dark Asian sesame oil
</P>
<P>
   1/4 teaspoon crushed hot red pepper
</P>
<P>
   3/4 pound skinless, boneless chicken breasts or thighs, cut into
thin strips
</P>
<P>
   2 teaspoons cornstarch
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup orange juice
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons peanut or other vegetable oil
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon minced fresh ginger
</P>
<P>
   6 ounces sugar snap peas, trimmed (about 2 cups)
</P>
<P>
   1 red bell pepper, cut into thin strips
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup sliced scallions
</P>
<P>
   In small bowl, combine garlic, soy sauce, orange zest, sesame
oil and hot pepper. Place chicken in shallow dish and coat with
half of garlic-soy mixture. Cover and refrigerate 30 minutes to 1
hour. Stir cornstarch and orange juice into remaining garlic
mixture. Reserve for sauce.
</P>
<P>
   In wok or large frying pan, heat oil over high heat. Add chicken
and stir-fry 2 minutes. Add ginger, peas and bell pepper. Stir-fry
until pepper is crisp-tender and chicken is white throughout, 2 to
3 minutes. Add scallions and reserved sauce and cook, stirring, 1
minute. Serve at once.
</P>
<P>
   Nutritional analysis per serving: 341 calories, 12 grams fat, 29
grams carbohydrates, 29 grams protein, 60 milligrams cholesterol,
581 milligrams sodium, 32 percent of calories from fat.
</P>
<P>
   Requests:
</P>
<P>
   Evelyn Lebahn of Cleburne, Texas, would like a recipe for a
cornflake cookies. It's not the usual one of egg whites,
marshmallow and cornflakes. The one she wants has other ingredients
in it, and she remembers it being about 4 inches long.
</P>
<P>
   (Beverly Bundy is food editor for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram.
Send recipes and requests to Beverly Bundy, Fort Worth
Star-Telegram, Box 1870, Fort Worth, Texas 76101. Or E-mail to
bbundy(at)star-telegram.com. Include a daytime phone number.
Responses to requests will be made only through this column. Visit
the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
