A8954 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-EMU-COMEBACK-TEX     02-17 1027
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EMU-COMEBACK-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FARMERS HOPE TO REVIVE DEMAND FOR EMUS BY PEDDLING BYPRODUCTS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By CAROLYN POIROT 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   When sizzling-hot grease popped out of the pan and singed the
wrist of a man frying funnel cakes at the Fort Worth Stock Show
this month, paramedics rushed the cook to a nearby booth where
North East Texas Emu was promoting new products.
</P>
<P>
   ``We got some emu oil on his burn right away, and it worked just
great,'' says Buddy Williams, an emu farmer and distributor for
``Soft-as-Silk'' emu products.
</P>
<P>
   Williams' wares have previously been called into emergency
service at a big event. Last summer, there was the Fire Ants
Festival in Marshall.
</P>
<P>
   ``Contestants try to see who can scoop the most fire ants into a
jar _ barehanded,'' Williams explains. ``There were two guys who
were stung from their fingertips clear up to their elbows. They
came running over to us, hollering, and we doped them down with emu
oil. Those fire ant stings didn't even fester.''
</P>
<P>
   On such testimonials are built the big bird's reputation for
healing.
</P>
<P>
   Although herds of the prolific birds have developed far more
quickly than the market for their meat _ leading to neglect and
abuse in a few well-publicized cases _ some emu farmers have begun
organizing co-ops to develop a market for oil, leather, feathers
and eggs, as well as the low-fat, iron-packed red meat.
</P>
<P>
   Only full use of the bird can return emu farming to the
profitable business it once promised, the Dallas-based American Emu
Association says.
</P>
<P>
   Emu oil, rendered from a layer of fat on the bird's back, was
first used as a traditional medicine throughout Australia by
aboriginal tribes.
</P>
<P>
   The oil is popular in the alternative-medicine community for the
relief of skin conditions including psoriasis and eczema, contact
dermatitis, stretch marks, scars, rashes, rosacea, burns, chapped
skin and diaper rash. It is also used on skin after radiation
treatment and cosmetic peels. Lotions, bath crystals, lip balm,
shampoos, soap and jerky are among the new products being
developed.
</P>
<P>
   Dave Leonard of Marlow, Okla., who has a herd of 350 slaughter
birds, 40 breeders and about 600 eggs incubating, says people often
ask him what they should use emu oil for.
</P>
<P>
   ``I say, it's easier to tell you what not to use it for. Don't
use it for poison oak or poison ivy. It's good for everything
else,'' Leonard says. ``It's a carrier compound, used as a pain
reliever primarily. You can combine it with anything, and it will
carry it into the body.''
</P>
<P>
   To treat arthritis, sports injuries and other muscle and joint
sprains and strains, pain relievers including capsaicin, tea tree
oil, aloe vera, menthol and eucalyptus, are mixed with emu oil,
which better penetrates the skin and carries heat deeper into the
body.
</P>
<P>
   Proponents say the emu oil has anti-inflammatory and
anti-bacterial properties. It penetrates and moisturizes,
revitalizes and restores skin with unsaturated and polyunsaturated
fatty acids.
</P>
<P>
   More specifically, laboratory testing has found that the oil
contains an unsaturated fatty acid known to ease joint pain.
</P>
<P>
   Doug Atkinson, sports medicine consultant and longtime trainer
for the Dallas Mavericks, says he has been using emu oil products
as part of his therapy programs for years.
</P>
<P>
   Atkinson was formerly associated with Maxim Care of Temple, a
company that makes creams that are specially formulated for sports
injuries and arthritis, as well as formulations for skin care,
burns, insect bites and cleansing.
</P>
<P>
   Maxim Care also produces gel caps of pure emu oil that can be
taken by mouth to help lower cholesterol and improve circulation,
provide arthritis relief and help regulate blood sugar levels.
</P>
<P>
   Those in the emu trade are counting on the developing market for
emu-based products to keep their business viable. The initial
interest in the birds came in the late 1980s, when health-conscious
Americans began looking for alternatives to beef, and farmers
realized they could raise emus in small pastures under less
hospitable conditions than it took to raise beef.
</P>
<P>
   But the whole bird wasn't being used. The first emu oil products
produced in the United States did not hit the market until 1992.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've been working in the emu business for about 12 years, but
for a long time the birds were valued at a lot more for breeding
stock than for their products,'' says Sue Ricks, a spokeswoman for
Maxim Care. ``It was a breeders' market. Everyone was in the
breeding business.''
</P>
<P>
   Which meant that suddenly there were too many emus.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are very good at raising a lot of birds,'' Williams agrees.
``But somebody had to develop the market.'' To that end, he and
five other East Texas emu farmers recently formed a co-op to look
into the possibilities.
</P>
<P>
   Helping to develop at least one segment of that emerging emu
byproducts market is Gary Gunn of Cresson, just southwest of Fort
Worth, who uses his emus' large, dark greenish-black eggs for
etching artwork. One egg takes him 10 to 12 hours to complete and
sells for about $150. Elvis, Marilyn Monroe and The Three Stooges
are among the famous likenesses etched into his beautiful eggs, but
he specializes in outdoor scenes and personalized custom designs.
With new emu products from oils to etched eggs being developed
every month and sale of the meat spreading worldwide, there should
never be an emu farmer who can't feed his livestock, says Donna
Womack of Fort Worth, who represents Texas on the national board of
the American Emu Association.
</P>
<P>
   A new brochure distributed by her organization claims that the
emu is totally usable livestock. ``Processed mainly for its meat,
hide and oil, it is also used for its feathers, eggs and
toenails.''
</P>
<P>
   Yes, toenails. Jewelry is fashioned from them.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   FYI BOX
</P>
<P>
   For more information on the American Emu Association or the
Texas Emu Association or where to find the products, call Donna
Womack at 236-3321 or the national office in Dallas at (214)
559-2321.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
