r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BLACKS-BREASTCANCER-T     02-17 0922
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BLACKS-BREASTCANCER-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A NEW APPROACH TO KEEPING MORE AFRICAN-AMERICAN WOMEN ALIVE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By GRACIE BONDS STAPLES 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   An easy smile flashes across Brenda Gordon's face like sunshine
bursting through dark clouds.
</P>
<P>
   The Arlington, Texas, woman is remembering how her breasts
swelled during the last months of her pregnancy and the feeling of
fulfillment she had birthing her daughter, Genesis Alana.
</P>
<P>
   At 34, Gordon says, she was the happiest she had been in her
life. For 10 years, nothing had been more important to her than
having a child.
</P>
<P>
   Then, after a routine doctor's exam a year after the birth of
her daughter, she discovered that 12 of the lymph nodes in her
right breast tested positive for cancer.
</P>
<P>
   For African-American women such as Gordon, such a diagnosis is
often viewed as a sure death sentence. Although black women have a
lower incidence of breast cancer, they continue to have the highest
breast cancer mortality rates of any ethnic group. According to the
American Cancer Society, the five-year survival rate for
African-American women is 70.6 percent, compared with 86.7 percent
for white women. And although breast cancer mortality rates
declined 6.1 percent for white women between 1990 and 1994, the
rate for African-American women dropped by about 1 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Social, economic and cultural factors cause the difference,
experts say.
</P>
<P>
   Black women's cancer is often diagnosed at more advanced stages,
so educating them about the importance of self-examining their
breasts is crucial, said Debby Vigeland, chairwoman of the Tarrant
County Komen Race for the Cure, a fund-raiser of the Susan G. Komen
Breast Cancer Foundation.
</P>
<P>
   In an effort to step up its attempt to reach this population and
reduce the number of deaths within it, the Susan G. Komen Breast
Cancer Foundation launched an African-American Women's Initiative
this month.
</P>
<P>
   Although the Dallas-based foundation has a long history of
funding national programs for the African-American community, this
is the first effort of its kind to bring together key experts in
the black community to come up with more effective ways of
educating women about breast cancer.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is very, very important to us,'' said Nancy Brinker,
Komen's founder. The mortality rate among black women ``screams one
thing: We have an obligation to help in this effort in any way we
can,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Under the initiative, the foundation will identify existing,
community-based, early-detection programs that work _ including
some funded by Komen. Additional funding will be used to replicate
several programs in other parts of the country. Those programs
include the Witness Project, a national cancer education project
that targets churches and has an active program in Mount Pleasant;
the East-West Breast Express, which educates women through public
transit sites in Atlanta and Oakland, Calif.; and the Navigator
Program at Harlem Hospital Center in New York, which helps women
get from screening to diagnosis to treatment.
</P>
<P>
   ``We believe the best way to reach women is in venues in which
they are comfortable,'' Brinker said.
</P>
<P>
   In keeping with that philosophy, the Tarrant County affiliate
three years ago began an outreach effort in African-American
churches to drum up support for its Race for the Cure.
</P>
<P>
   Penny Wallace, a radiation therapist and chairwoman of the local
church teams, said that although more progress is necessary, great
strides have been made.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're in one of three places,'' said Wallace, referring to
African-American women. ``In the mall shopping, the beauty shop or
the church. When I first started work on the race, there wasn't
much African-American participation. Now we have about 160 people
from 15 different churches. That was unheard of three years ago.''
</P>
<P>
   The Tarrant County affiliate raised $250,000 last year from its
race, Vigeland said. Of that, $10,000 was donated to the American
Cancer Society for use in its Church Connection Program. That money
was earmarked to fund early detection, education and patient
services, including screening and referral for underserved women in
the African-American community.
</P>
<P>
   The foundation's efforts have not been lost on Gordon, 46 and a
staunch supporter of the Race for the Cure, held across the country
to raise funds for breast cancer research, education and outreach.
</P>
<P>
   To help out, Gordon said, she shares her story as often as she
can, not only to encourage women who have breast cancer but also to
help raise awareness about the importance of self-exams.
</P>
<P>
   When Gordon first inquired about the lump in her breast, she
said, her doctor explained it away, saying it was just milk. A year
later, when she went in for a routine exam, ``I asked him, `What
about my breast?' '' she said recently. ``He said, `What about it?'
''
</P>
<P>
   A week later, Gordon said, she had a mammogram. A few days after
that, she had a biopsy and two days after that, a mastectomy.
</P>
<P>
   If Gordon's story seems outrageous, it is hardly that unusual,
Vigeland said.
</P>
<P>
   ``You really need to be an advocate for yourself,'' Vigeland
said. ``Don't take everything someone tells you as the gospel
truth. Know your body better than anyone.''
</P>
<P>
   For more information about breast cancer and the Komen
Foundation, call (800) IM-AWARE or check the organization's Web
site, www.breastcancerinfo.com.
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
