<HEADER>
A8960 &Cx1f; taf-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-QUILTS-DECODED-ART-NY     02-17 0921
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-QUILTS-DECODED-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
(ATTN: S.C.)  
 HOW SLAVES READ BETWEEN THE THREADS 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By PHIL PATTON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   One scholar compared it to the Rosetta stone,'' said Jacqueline
L. Tobin, the author, with Dr. Raymond G. Dobard, of ``Hidden in
Plain View,'' a new book that makes a startling claim about quilts:
some quilts were patterned as a code to direct escaping slaves.
</P>
<P>
   A quilt with a monkey-wrench pattern hung in a cabin window
signaled slaves to gather tools for the escape. Tumbling blocks
indicated imminent departure. The number and placement of knots
represented dates.
</P>
<P>
   The book, just published by Doubleday, has become a surprise hot
seller. The story of its origin is as intriguing as its theory.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Tobin, who is white, was first put on the trail in 1993 when
she met an African-American quilt maker, Ozella McDaniel Williams,
in the city marketplace in Charleston, S.C. Ms. Williams asked if
she knew that quilts had been used as a code on the underground
railroad. Returning home to Denver, Ms. Tobin, a professor of
women's studies at the University of Denver, enlisted Dobard, an
art history professor at Howard University and an African-American
quilter, to help research the subject.
</P>
<P>
   But in three years of telephone conversations with Ms. Williams,
Ms. Tobin was able to find out little more. Only when Ms. Tobin
returned to Charleston did Ms. Williams recite the code learned
from her mother: the Northern Star pattern suggested that escaping
slaves use the North Star for guidance; the Drunkard's Path pattern
advised taking an irregular course to avoid apprehension; Flying
Geese signaled the way north _ but only in the spring. These are
not exactly Rand McNally maps. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The idea of a code has a long life in oral tradition.
Gladys-Marie Fry, a University of Maryland historian who
specializes in black folklore, said in ``Stitched from the Soul:
Slave Quilts From the Ante-Bellum South'' (Dutton) that a black
quilt was thought to indicate a safe house, for instance. Dr.
Robert Farris Thompson, a professor of art history at Yale
University and an expert in African-American esthetics, agrees that
the idea of a code makes sense. ``There is a distinct African
current in quilts that can absorb any number of codes,'' he said. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   But is the Rosetta stone as solid as it looks? Quilt codes are
not mentioned in contemporaneous accounts of the underground
railroad, and the code doesn't reach the systematic nature of, say,
the symbols scrawled on fences by tramps a century ago to set apart
friendly farms from hostile ones.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. John Michael Vlach, chairman of African-American studies at
George Washington University, reviewed an early proposal for the
book for a rival publisher and was not convinced. ``It's a nice
idea,'' he said, ``and it would be marvelous if we could prove it.
But from the evidence I don't see the smoking gun _ or quilt.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Vlach argues that a quilt code goes against what we know of
slavery. While double meanings were an established part of slave
strategies of resistance, as in spirituals, a quilt code would have
been too risky. ``Penalties for taking slaves to freedom were so
severe that people would be much more circumspect,'' he said.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Was Ms. Williams, who died last May, really presenting the code
as a practical aid? As recited, it seems more inspirational than
navigational. Ms. Tobin recalled that Ms. Williams said over and
over of the code, ``It's all in your mind.'' To Ms. Tobin, this
meant the code was as much spiritual as practical. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Tobin recognizes that Ms. Williams' account is a slim reed
on which to base a theory, and the authors buttress their text with
not one but three forewords from scholars in the field. ``She
played an incredible game of what I call `putting on the massa,'''
Ms. Tobin said of Ms. Williams, ``where you appear to be ignorant
or uneducated.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Williams was, in fact, well educated, with a graduate degree
in chemistry. Ms. Tobin attributes her evasiveness to strong taboos
against sharing code information with whites. She hopes that
supporting evidence for the theory will emerge.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   But the appeal of the story suggests that the most important
codes may be more abstract. Quilts have become powerful metaphors
in late-20th-century America, in sentimental books like ``How to
Make an American Quilt'' or in the political speeches of Jesse
Jackson. Quilt has largely superseded melting pot as an upbeat
metaphor for the juxtapositions of cultures.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Designs for escape or designs for the dream of escape, the
quilts raise a problem. To undervalue the oral and visual record
runs the risk of compounding the slave owner's crime of depriving
slaves of a written language. The faint signals of memorized codes
were among the few that slaves had power to send across the
generations. But to romanticize efforts to escape from slavery
underplays the hopelessness that made the institution so evil.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Thompson suggests that quilts carry other codes. He praises
``their percussive flavors, vivid colors and offbeat visual
accents.'' African patterns survived in the quilts, working their
own random paths inside the box of the dominant culture, as the
quilt makers kept their identities alive inside the box of slavery.
They carry the emotional power of their makers' endurance.
</P>
<P>
   ``That code is forever,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The sad but likely truth is that for many, if not most, quilts
were not the escape map but the only escape.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
