r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SCHOOLS-RACE-HNS &LR;      02-17 0753
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCHOOLS-RACE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SAN FRANCISCO FACES OVERHAUL OF SCHOOL DESEGREGATION 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JULIAN GUTHRIE  
 c.1998 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ The tentative settlement of a lawsuit that
sought to overturn the San Francisco's school desegregation system
would force the city to redefine diversity in the classroom and
rethink the means to achieve it.
</P>
<P>
   The tentative settlement, reached Tuesday as a federal court
trial was about to begin, would topple the school district's
15-year-old admissions policy and phase out, by Dec. 31, 2002, the
annual $37 million in state aid that helps fund the desegregation
plan.
</P>
<P>
   Under the settlement, the district will have to craft a
colorblind admissions system by mid-March, which is when school
assignments are made for the fall.
</P>
<P>
   Ever since the desegregation policy was ordered in 1983, in
response to charges that the school district discriminated against
black children, the city's 62,000 students have been divided into
nine racial categories. No group could exceed more than 45 percent
of the students at any school, and at least four groups had to be
represented at every school.
</P>
<P>
   Superintendent Bill Rojas sees two key ways to ensure
integration without using race: redraw boundaries around schools to
enroll children from a variety of neighborhoods; or give enrollment
preferences to poor children.
</P>
<P>
   Students who live in public housing, for example, would have a
better chance at getting into a competitive school than a child
from a well-educated, middle-class family.
</P>
<P>
   ``This new approach of looking at students' economic status is
cutting edge, and people consider it fundamentally more fair than
counting race,'' said Richard Kahlenberg, the author of several
books on class-based affirmative action, including ``The Remedy:
Class, Race and Affirmative Action.''
</P>
<P>
   The tentative settlement mandating the dramatic enrollment
changes comes five years after three Chinese-American families sued
the district, the state and the National Association for the
Advancement of Colored People.
</P>
<P>
   The class-action suit alleged that the race-based desegregation
policy denied Chinese-American children the equal opportunity to
attend the schools of their choice.
</P>
<P>
   Under the tentative settlement, parents will no longer be
required to indicate a race when enrolling a child in school.
</P>
<P>
   The settlement stipulates that if the city's schools become
racially isolated, the NAACP will be able to go to court to ask for
a desegregation remedy, according to Daniel Girard, who represented
the Chinese-American plaintiffs.
</P>
<P>
   The settlement also gives the district ample time to come up
with a financial backup plan to replace lost state funds.
</P>
<P>
   Since the 1983 consent degree took effect, San Francisco schools
have received some $300 million to desegregate and create programs
aimed at boosting the academic performance of black and Hispanic
children.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no question that the end of the consent decree money
is a serious hit to the district,'' said state Assemblywoman Carol
Migden, a San Francisco Democrat. ``But we will work together as a
Legislature to find ways to make sure San Francisco continues to
receive the support it requires. It won't necessarily be a
straightforward formula like it is now, but there are ways to
subsidize the district without pushing hot-button issues of race.''
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. Supreme Court has ruled that government may use racial
quotas only in the rarest of circumstances, such as when state
authorities deliberately defy federal orders mandating
desegregation.
</P>
<P>
   Written statements made in recent months by U.S. District Judge
William Orrick, who signed the federal desegregation order in 1983
and was to preside over the trial, indicated that the district and
NAACP were heading for defeat.
</P>
<P>
   Settlement talks between the parties began last week and
continued through Monday, lawyers said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a very hard case to settle because everyone had a
deeply held principle,'' said David Levine, who also represented
the plaintiffs.
</P>
<P>
   School board member Steve Phillips, a defender of affirmative
action and an advocate for black children, said he was confident
the district would be clever enough to ensure diversity without
considering race.
</P>
<P>
   ``This settlement does not mean the end of programs that are
necessary to address persistent inequities,'' Phillips said. ``This
is the beginning of a new approach to desegregation.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
