<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RECORD-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A STORY OF LOVE, JOY AND LOSS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By PHIL RECORD 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   This is a Valentine's Day story of a romance that managed to
flower 37 years after being nipped in the bud.
</P>
<P>
   It is the story of Christy Kent and Bill Thurman.
</P>
<P>
   They first met while Bill was working as a teaching assistant
for Christy's father, Jack Kent, who taught physics and math at
Texas A&AMP;M University.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was love at first sight,'' Bill said.
</P>
<P>
   They dated for four years. But, as Christy later told me, any
plans for marriage were discouraged by her parents. The couple bid
each other a painful farewell in May 1960.
</P>
<P>
   Bill graduated from A&AMP;M with a degree in physics. He moved to
California and went to work for North American Aviation (now Boeing
Corp.).
</P>
<P>
   Christy married and had two sons. She and her husband eventually
moved to Dallas, where the marriage ended in divorce after nearly
20 years. She later remarried, but that union was short-lived.
</P>
<P>
   Christy was a survivor. At 15, she was stricken with polio,
which left her left leg paralyzed. Then she survived the heartbreak
of her broken marriages.
</P>
<P>
   Ten years ago, she was told she had terminal breast cancer. She
had a double mastectomy, but doctors held little hope that she
would live. She was told to ``go home and die.''
</P>
<P>
   Instead, she opted to have radiation and chemotherapy. The
treatment was devastating, but she survived.
</P>
<P>
   Through all these years, she never stopped loving Bill Thurman.
She often wondered what he was doing. She assumed that he had
married.
</P>
<P>
   In the meantime, she supported herself as a teacher in the
Dallas public school system. Several times, she tried to muster the
courage to find out Bill's address so she could write him a letter.
But being a child of an era in which women were not expected to be
so ``forward,'' she always backed away from the notion.
</P>
<P>
   Unknown to Christy, Bill had contacted her parents in 1963 in an
effort to get her address. He said they declined to provide it.
</P>
<P>
   Early last year, one of Christy's fellow teachers provided
sufficient encouragement for her to decide to write the man who was
still the love of her life.
</P>
<P>
   Knowing that A&AMP;M kept close tabs on former students, Christy
called the ex-students office and asked a clerk for the address of
William R. Thurman. The clerk not only provided an address in
California but also informed Christy that Bill had never married.
</P>
<P>
   So Christy, her heart pounding, wrote Bill. She simply said she
was hoping they could still be friends and asked that he give her
``one phone call'' so they could chat. There was no profession of
love.
</P>
<P>
   ``But her message came through clearly,'' he told me last week.
``... I had never stopped loving her. That's why I never married.''
</P>
<P>
   Bill received Christy's letter on Feb. 7, 1998. But there was a
problem: She had not included her phone number. A call to
information was futile. Christy had an unlisted number.
</P>
<P>
   So Bill wrote back immediately. She got the letter containing
his phone number when she returned home from school Feb. 11. She
called him immediately, and they talked for four hours.
</P>
<P>
   Bill was in Dallas two days later.
</P>
<P>
   They were married Nov. 14. Two days later, they flew to Italy
for a two-week honeymoon. That is where my wife and I met them.
</P>
<P>
   There were many stairs to be climbed, many hills to be navigated
as we toured Italy. Christy, with a cane in one hand and Bill
holding onto her other hand, managed to climb most of them. You
could tell it was painful at times. But Christy had learned long
ago to survive life's challenges.
</P>
<P>
   She and Bill told me their love story one morning while we ate
breakfast in a large dining room overlooking an orange grove in
Sorrento.
</P>
<P>
   ``You will never know how happy he has made me,'' the
58-year-old bride said of her 62-year-old mate.
</P>
<P>
   I later shared their story with several of our fellow tourists.
``You should write about that in one of your columns,'' one told
me. ``It is such a lovely love story.''
</P>
<P>
   So in the middle of last month, I called to ask their permission
to tell their story. Christy was a bit reluctant but finally gave
her permission.
</P>
<P>
   I explained that I had a couple of other projects in the works
and that I would call back in a couple of weeks to fill in some
details.
</P>
<P>
   I made that call the night of Feb. 5. Bill answered, and I told
him why I was calling and said that I wanted to speak to Christy
first.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have terrible news for you, Phil,'' Bill said, grief etched
in his voice. ``Christy died a week ago.''
</P>
<P>
   She was stricken with a neurological seizure at Skyline High
School, where she taught English. That triggered a cardiac arrest.
She died in a hospital two days later without regaining
consciousness.
</P>
<P>
   ``I still think it is a beautiful story that should be told,'' I
told Bill after recovering from my shock.
</P>
<P>
   ``I agree,'' he replied. ``And I think Christy would have wanted
it.''
</P>
<P>
   He said he thanked God for the months they had together.
</P>
<P>
   Bill is preparing to return to his home in California, where he
and Christy were going to live after her retirement next year.
</P>
<P>
   He will return home with a broken heart held together by the
memories of the happiest months of his life.
</P>
<P>
   (Retired ombudsman Phil Record is a consultant to the
``Star-Telegram.'' He can be reached at precord &LR; star-telegram.com.
Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com) &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
