<P>
   NATION
</P>
<P>
   JASPER _ Testimony continues Wednesday in the trial of Bill
King, accused of being the ringleader in the dragging death of a
black man last summer in East Texas. Prosecutors are expected to
discuss DNA evidence. Meanwhile, a black separatist group that
demonstrated with guns after the murder last summer was pressing to
get seats in the courtroom. Judge Bob Golden has agreed to let in
members of the New Black Panther Party as long as they are not
disruptive and do not wear insignia or uniforms. (Gamino, Austin
American-Statesman).
</P>
<P>
   OHIO-EXECUTION _ Unless 6th circuit court of appeals calls a
halt _ decision expected daily _ Ohio will join the college of
executioners Friday at 9 p.m. when it gives a lethal injection to
Wilford Berry _ abused as a child, suicidal as a child, diagnosed
schizophrenic and stone cold murderer. (Beyerlein, Dayton Daily
News). 25-30.
</P>
<P>
   STATE LEGISLATIVE NEWS
</P>
<P>
   GA-LEGIS-HEALTHCARE _ Gov. Roy Barnes proposes legislation to
reform managed care. With summary of the bill's key provisions and
reaction from key lawmakers and interest groups.
(Pruitt/AMiller/Harvey/Tharpe, Atlanta Journal-Constitution).
15-18.
</P>
<P>
   WITH
</P>
<P>
   GA-LEGIS-FOES _ Sidebar lays out main oppositon to Barnes
healthcare legislation _ doctors and hospital/insurance industries,
all among the state's best orgainized, best financed interest
groups. (Pruitt/AMiller, Atlanta Journal-Constitution). 18-20.
</P>
<P>
   GA-LEGIS-TEXAS _ Part of Gov. Roy Barnes' health-care reform
plan being announced Wednesday will deal with the right of insured
clients to sue their health care provider under a malpractice
statute if the provider refuses to pay for a procedure that later
turns out to have been necessary. The proposed legislation, to be
introduced as a separate bill, is draw on the Texas law enacted
last year but is said to be more contentious toward the providers.
A quick look at the Texas law: what it has done and where it has
enountered difficulties; have premiums risen as provider lobbyists
suggest?; have procedure costs risen? (Lore, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution). 12.
</P>
<P>
   TEX-LEGIS-PERMITS _ For the third time in as many legislative
sessions, a bill being proposed to cut down on the amount of public
debate on permits is taking heat. House Bill 801 would take the
public hearings out of the environmental permitting process, and
though it does provide for input, it is not considered a positive
change by environmentalists. (Jacobs, Longview News-Journal).
</P>
<P>
   TEX-LEGIS-UTMONEY _ UT-Austin needs at least $54 million in new
general revenue from the state to provide badly-needed compensation
for staff, faculty and graduate assistants. In all, they are asking
for more than $70 million. The Legislative Budget Board only has
$13 million appropriated for the flagship and lawmakers seem to
have little sympathy for UT after big salaries of coaches and
administrators and a fancy new club have been publicized. (Brooks,
Austin American-Statesman).
</P>
<P>
   TEX-LEGIS-UTGRAMM _ Sen. Phil Gramm speaks to UT students and
faculty Wednesday about the Student Tax Fairness Act, which passed
Congress last year. Student employees of universities no longer
will have to pay taxes on their earnings, which is especially
important to graduate students. (Roser, Austin American-Statesman).
</P>
