<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RENOVATE-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHAT AM I BID? FIVE CONTRACTORS ANSWER  
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds.: An optional sidebar is at end of 2ndtake.) 
(ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling 888-603-1036 or
888-346-9867.) 
(js) 
 By TRACIE ROZHON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ All right, so it's not a palace. Maybe you just
bought it. Maybe you just looked around and, for the first time,
spotted the cracked plaster, the 20 or 30 coats of paint, the
stains on the floors, the exposed electrical conduit and the
unmentionable kitchen.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe it's time for a renovation.
</P>
<P>
   You're in good company. In the last quarter of 1998, homeowners
spent $87.9 billion on renovations, 15 percent more than in the
same quarter two years earlier, according to the Joint Center for
Housing Studies at Harvard University. But with every dream of
renovation, whether it involves building a sun room or adding a
closet rod, comes the inevitable panic: assuming you've decided not
to do the job yourself, using your house as a lab experiment, how
do you find the right professional to help?
</P>
<P>
   If you don't have the budget or inclination for a big
architect-designed renovation, which could run to $75,000 for a
one-bedroom apartment, you'll probably hire a general contractor to
manage the job, including plumbing, wiring, tiling and carpentry.
How to weigh the widely varying, often impenetrable bids when they
arrive? What will the contractor expect from you? The questions are
as nerve-racking as finding the apartment in the first place.
</P>
<P>
   The House &AMP; Home section set out to see what an average
homeowner goes through during the initial bidding process, in hopes
of making it easier to fathom.
</P>
<P>
   A friend had just bought a down-at-the-heels one-bedroom
apartment in the East 80s and had no idea where to start, so I
borrowed it in a test to see what could be learned about hiring an
all-purpose general contractor at a reasonable price. I started as
so many homeowners do: asking for recommendations from friends,
along with building superintendents and the real estate agent who
brokered the purchase. Then I invited five contractors to see the
apartment, checked their references and, finally, analyzed their
bids. Over a decade, I have acted as my own general contractor on
11 house and apartment renovations. I thought I knew the territory.
(New lesson: Don't greet a contractor with, ``Now, I don't want to
spend a lot of money on this job.'' They don't like it.)
</P>
<P>
   For all the reported rush to renovate, we found that New York
City is still full of contractors eager to work _ all five said
they could begin almost immediately. One offered an especially low
rate because, he said, ``February is a dead month.''
</P>
<P>
   The contractors bid on what the owner actually asked for. No
walls in the 900-square-foot apartment had to be removed and no
rooms reconfigured _ that would require building permits _ and it
was easy to separate the overall job into small ones. The entire
apartment was to be plastered with a light coat of wallboard
compound mixed with plaster (a ``skim coat'') and painted. All
floors needed to be sanded and given two coats of polyurethane. The
chipped baseboard was to be replaced with gutsy seven-inch molding.
</P>
<P>
   The kitchen required complete remodeling. Old plastic-laminate
cabinets had to go, along with the orange and brown tile floor,
which looked like linoleum. We asked for custom-made raised-panel
cherry cabinets and new ceramic tiles. The plumbing had to be
changed, too, so the dishwasher could be nearer the table, and the
electrical conduit on one wall needed to be buried.
</P>
<P>
   To allow more room for a table in the kitchen, it seemed like a
good idea to move the doorway 18 inches to the right, also
improving the view from the front door: a visitor then would face
the Art Deco casement window, not a stove full of pots.
</P>
<P>
   The owner had one eccentric request: he didn't want to look at
the window air-conditioners nine months of the year, so we asked
the contractors to bid on a replacement window enclosure that could
be bolted in and then taken out in summer. They also bid on
building a new radiator front and adding a granite kitchen
windowsill. Finally, they were asked to remove the shelves in one
closet and replace them with a simple rod.
</P>
<P>
   The contractors did not have to supply materials: paint, new
appliances, a new granite counter or the new baseboard. Since they
were bidding on labor only, it would be easy to compare bids.
Although contractors would have preferred it, we didn't give them a
budget. We wanted to see what they would come up with.
</P>
<P>
   Johnny Nap, as he likes to be called professionally, was there
early, waiting by the curb in a fire-engine-red Jeep Cherokee. He
wore a satin baseball jacket the color of blueberry sorbet.
</P>
<P>
   ``Is that your real name?'' I asked.
</P>
<P>
   He laughed. ``No, it's Napolitano,'' he said with a certain
practiced air. ``You know, a fine Irish boy!''
</P>
<P>
   Nap, 50, hustled into the apartment and headed toward the ugly
air-conditioners. ``Is this building a landmark?'' he asked in
reference to changing the window. ``If it is, you can forget about
it.'' (It isn't, so no additional permit was needed.)
</P>
<P>
   Despite the bumpy walls and ceiling, Nap did not favor skim
coating. ``Forget about it,'' he said again. ``You'll save yourself
a bundle, and no one will know.'' But he agreed to estimate the job
both ways _ just repairing the cracks, then skim-coating and
painting the walls.
</P>
<P>
   Nap, who lives in the Bronx, advocated stock kitchen cabinets _
they're much cheaper _ but agreed to estimate the cost of
custom-made cherry cabinets, too.
</P>
<P>
   About 10 minutes after he arrived, he was gone. ``All right,
sweetheart,'' he said, ``I'll be back to you in a day or two.'' And
he was. His bid: $30,363.
</P>
<P>
   Next to arrive was Thomas Breslin, 48, a soft-spoken man with a
workshop in Brooklyn. He noticed a thin molding separating the
curve of a white ceiling and beige walls.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you want to pull that molding off, you'll need to decide
how you're going to handle the transition,'' he said, the only one
who pointed this out. ``Do you want to paint the room all one color
or try to paint a straight line in the middle of the curve running
around the top of the room?''
</P>
<P>
   Good question. The room, we decided, would be painted one light
color. He said that Benjamin Moore paint was reliable but that he
preferred Sherwin-Williams: ``Just as reliable, with more colors.''
</P>
<P>
   Breslin studied where the replacement window frame would go,
trying to figure out how he would attach Plexiglas or glass to the
existing frame. He decided to use glass encased in an aluminum
frame.
</P>
<P>
   In the kitchen, he discovered a place where the half-inch
plywood subfloor could be seen under the tile. Like three other
contractors, he hedged his bid in case the subfloor was rotten and
couldn't be saved when workers removed the tiles.
</P>
<P>
   Breslin was the only contractor who gave his source for kitchen
cabinets. ``Go to the Little Wolf Cabinet Shop on 82nd and First
Avenue,'' he said. ``He'll come here and measure and install them.
Just tell him Tommy sent you.'' (The cabinetmaker's bid for the
cabinets _ $3,400 _ is figured into Breslin's bid.)
</P>
<P>
   He stayed to chat. ``Some contractors don't want to give
anything away,'' he said.``I figure I'm not going to lose the job
because of it, and maybe I'll get the job because I did.'' In the
end, Breslin bid $20,325, making him a definite contender.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
