</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-17-99 1720EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990217.0270 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-17 17:20 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9029 &Cx1f; taf-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RENOVATE-ART-2NDTAKE-     02-17 1291
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RENOVATE-ART-2NDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 NEW YORK: definite contender.  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Michael Rooney, 34, a lanky man, was the most serious of the
group. He took extensive notes during his 20-minute visit. For the
walls and ceiling, he recommended fiberglass mesh on the old
plaster, then a skim coat. ``If you're going to go to the trouble
of skim coating,'' he said, ``you might as well do the job right.''
In my opinion, the walls weren't bad enough for so drastic a
solution. He agreed to bid the job as requested.
</P>
<P>
   Rooney, who is based in Queens, was the first to submit his bid:
$26,814, not including kitchen cabinets, which could easily add
more than $3,000. When he was informed that he was going to be part
of this article, he reacted angrily, saying he did not ``need any
publicity _ we've got plenty of work.''
</P>
<P>
   When David E. Lane, 33, is not working as a contractor, he's a
playwright.
</P>
<P>
   Lane, who lives in Manhattan, furnished the longest list of
references: six pages. He was also the only contractor to arrive
with a contract, an involved document that was only slightly
off-putting. ``I like taking care of all these details before the
job starts,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   In the kitchen, Lane considered laying new 12-inch ceramic floor
tile on top of the existing 8-inch tiles to save time. He said he
would replace the doorsill with a slightly higher one to make up
for the extra depth of the new tile _ an idea I found fraught with
peril, considering the unknown quality of the subfloor.
</P>
<P>
   In the end, his ``for February only'' price came in at $18,880.
</P>
<P>
   With his echo-chamber voice and black leather jacket, not to
mention his bearing, Mark William Stewart, 44, has to be an actor _
and he is.
</P>
<P>
   He is also a contractor with strong opinions. Stewart, who is
based in Manhattan, wrote in his bid: ``I've never heard of a
kitchen without a silverware drawer, and wouldn't want to leave my
silver sitting out in the grime, soot, etc.''
</P>
<P>
   Even after he learned that his bid _ $32,250 _ was higher than
those of other contractors, he generously offered less expensive
suggestions, faxing a fact sheet on a Marvel under-counter
refrigerator that he said could be bought for $649. (It was a good
tip: the refrigerator is half the street price of the Sub-Zero
245.)
</P>
<P>
   For an owner, and even for an experienced renovator, choosing
among the contractors would be a tough choice. It isn't just about
the lowest bid; it's the quality of the work.
</P>
<P>
   So I visited projects that each man had given as a reference and
found Nap himself working on a job on Central Park West, fitting
the kitchen cabinets himself. At the other contractors' job sites,
already finished, the owners were pleased with the work and went
out of their way to praise the contractors for their spirit and
willingness to return to make adjustments.
</P>
<P>
   It was time to analyze the bids, double-checking with the
contractors on points that were unclear. For instance, Stewart came
in significantly higher than the other contractors for the kitchen
cabinets. When questioned, he explained that he had added in the
cost of granite counter tops, to be supplied by the owner. Subtract
$1,200 from his bid. Stewart's figure for the kitchen floor
included a new plywood subfloor that might not be required. For the
electrical work, he added in items like track lighting, which he
said he was ``sure the owner would want later.''
</P>
<P>
   Reflecting on his bid, the highest of the group, Stewart said:
``Maybe I overanticipated. I knew what I would have done. If I had
just stuck to exactly what was stated, I would have come in lower.
I thought about it too much.''
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, Stewart's bid on the skim-coating and painting was
lower than those of the others because he knows an excellent
painter who was giving him a lower price ``as kind of a personal
favor.''
</P>
<P>
   Breslin, whose bid for sanding and refinishing the floors was
lowest, explained that he knew an experienced floor sander who
would work cheaply. His $1,200 bid for moving the kitchen door was
also lowest. ``I had just done the exact same job in a doctor's
office,'' he said, ``and I knew exactly how much it costs.''
</P>
<P>
   Since a contractor also depends on his subcontractors, Breslin
offered to allay any uncertainty about the quality of his
subcontractor's paint job by sending him to the apartment to do a
finished patch on the wall if he landed the job.
</P>
<P>
   Lane, whose bid for painting and plastering was low, said he
planned to do the painting himself, cutting the cost.
</P>
<P>
   In the end, I found the bids, which varied by nearly $14,000,
within the bounds of fairness. And they could be fine-tuned _
Stewart's bid presents a good example of how a contractor, having
overestimated several items, will renegotiate. To choose among
contractors who have references like those of these five and whose
completed jobs reflect similar competence, a homeowner might best
follow the advice of Breslin, the philosopher-contractor:
</P>
<P>
   ``Go with your gut,'' he said. ``If you don't get along with the
contractor at the beginning _ or if he's late or full of excuses _
it's only going to get worse.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL SIDEBAR FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Relating to Contractors: Prenuptial Agreements Can Help
</P>
<P>
   Fifteen years' experience working with general contractors has
yielded these insights about what to look for and to look out for
in the first interview.
</P>
<P>
   PROMPTNESS If he can't show up on time for the initial meeting,
what will he be like after he's pocketed your down payment?
</P>
<P>
   GREED Does he rush to talk about payment? A contractor is smart
to ask when he can begin work: for one thing, he's trying to judge
if you're a serious customer. But too much money talk at this stage
is troubling. He should wait until he gets the job to hammer out
payment schedules.
</P>
<P>
   CAGINESS When you ask about references _ which you should do at
this point _ does he say he will get back to you (after he enlists
his brother-in-law)? Try to find out about his most recent jobs and
ask to see them. A continuing job is best: drop in without an
appointment and hope to find the contractor there, supervising. And
ask for proof of liability insurance, which is required if you're
in a co-op. (Even if you aren't, it's important.)
</P>
<P>
   RAPPORT Don't underrate it. You're embarking on a long, long job
(even if it's only a month), and lawsuits can make it a lot longer.
Don't be afraid to ask any question. Do it now rather than later.
</P>
<P>
   Contractors size up customers, too. Here is what they look for
and look out for in a client, based on interviews with the
contractors who bid on this job:
</P>
<P>
   STINGINESS The contractor has to be sure of getting his money if
he completes the work satisfactorily. Contractors say that one
client trick is not to pay the last third. (Jobs are usually paid
in thirds.) They say the homeowner knows a contractor probably
won't go to court over the payment. ``If the first thing out of
your mouth is, `Now, I don't want to spend a lot of money on this
job,' I'm already walking out the door,'' Thomas Breslin said.
</P>
<P>
   WILLINGNESS TO STATE A BUDGET Three of the five contractors
asked for a budget and were disappointed _ some more than others _
not to get one. They feel that if the owner is honest about what he
can spend, they can respond accurately: if the budget is low, they
won't include gold faucets and fancy woodwork in their estimate.
</P>
<P>
   RAPPORT This goes both ways. ``I'm essentially going to be wed
to these people, and it's a shotgun wedding,'' Mark William Stewart
said. ``The level of trust is paramount.''
</P>
<P>
   EXPERIENCE Ideally, contractors like it if the client has been
through at least one other renovation. ``It's the virgins who are
the worst!'' Stewart said.
</P>
</TEXT>
