<SLUG> BC-CIR-GEEK-NOTES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEWS WATCH: PALM-SIZED COMPUTER _ WITH ENHANCEMENTS GALORE 
</HEADLINE>
  (lh) 
 By MATT RICHTEL   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The battle for the palm-sized computer market is about to become
a little more colorful. Compaq Computer Corp. is set to release its
new Aero 2100 unit next month, and one of the standout features of
the device is its 256-color high-resolution display. Although
3Com's Palm Pilot offers thousands of programs that run on the Palm
OS, Compaq is taking a different route with the Aero 2100. It uses
the Windows CE operating system, runs on a rechargeable lithium ion
battery and contains more on-board RAM (16 megabytes) than many
desktop PCs did just a few years ago. Pricing for the device has
not been announced.
</P>
<P>
   The Aero 2100 also has a slot for interchangeable cards that can
add such enhancements as a 56K modem, a pager card, 20 to 40
megabytes of additional RAM or a bar code scanner. With all of its
ambitious features, the Aero 2100 is not likely to enter the
marketplace quietly _ it also has voice recording and playback
ability.
</P>
<P>
   _ J.D. BIERSDORFER
</P>
<P>
   A Different Kind of Mouse
</P>
<P>
   A Silicon Valley company hopes to replace the mouse with the
parrot. The bird in question is not a piece of hardware but an
animated on-screen parrot that responds to voice commands.
</P>
<P>
   The parrot, named Prody, is programmed to perform certain tasks
like opening applications, notifying users when e-mail arrives and
permitting them to browse the Web via voice commands. It also can
remind users about forthcoming appointments, read news headlines
from the Internet in a synthesized voice and give real-time stock
quotes, so they can know when the portfolio has gone to the birds.
</P>
<P>
   The power behind Prody _ made by Mindmaker, a company based in
San Jose, Calif. _ is artificial intelligence and
speech-recognition technology that enables it to accept voice
commands and learn the user's preferences. In that regard, Prody is
not flying solo: a handful of companies are working with both
technologies to create on-screen digital assistants and, in some
cases, digital pets.
</P>
<P>
   In the case of Prody, its makers contend the $100 multicolored
African parrot is a breed apart because it integrates numerous of
the functions into a single software beast.
</P>
<P>
   But lovers of the mouse need not fear its extinction. Even when
parrot users are on the telephone, talking to friends or otherwise
don't want their virtual parrot to be listening, they'll have to
switch off the microphone used to direct Prody and turn to the
mouse.
</P>
<P>
   Chat Room to Telephone
</P>
<P>
   It's late at night in the online chat session. The virtual
discussion is getting hot and heavy, and it's time to take it to
the next step. No, not actual in-person interaction (that would
still would be too ``real''), but that old-fashioned form of
interplay known as a telephone conversation.
</P>
<P>
   Enter AT&AMP;T, which is marketing a new service to let chatters
turn their online discourse into telephone talk, but with a catch:
the telephone connection will be dialed by a computer so that the
participants won't know one another's phone numbers.
</P>
<P>
   The idea behind ``Chat 'N Talk'' is that chatters may want to
talk by phone, but also retain some of the anonymity provided by
the Internet. That way, they know they won't wind up being cold
called or harassed by the participant of some chat session gone
sour (or by some disappointed online romancer who finds out that
the object of his affections is not a 21-year-old Sports
Illustrated Super Model, but ``Hank,'' 49-year-old trucker from Des
Moines).
</P>
<P>
   The second catch is that the service is not cheap. It costs 15
cents a minute, which is charged to the credit card of the chatter
who initiates the ``Chat 'N Talk'' experience. Presently, the
service is available in chat rooms on two portals, Excite and
Lycos, is being integrated into I-village, a site geared toward
women, and AT&AMP;T said it also is negotiating for a similar
arrangement with Infoseek.
</P>
<P>
   A Cartoon Series _ for the Web
</P>
<P>
   Showtime Networks Inc.'s new animated series, called
``WhirlGirl,'' will debut later this month, but not on television.
The show, about a 21st century super heroine who takes on the evil
high-tech media empire, is will be seen exclusively on the Web.
</P>
<P>
   ``WhirlGirl'' is the first Web-only production for Showtime, but
company senior vice president Tom Hayden, said the series is
designed to drum up business for the television network. Hayden
said the 28 episodes, each three to four minutes long, are designed
to attract 15- to 34-year-olds to sign up for Showtime. He said
that depending on the reception given ``WhirlGirl,'' the company
may ultimately develop it into a program for Showtime, the
television network.
</P>
<P>
   Then there are the other business opportunities associated with
the project, said Hayden, noting, ``we'll exploit any merchandising
opportunities along the way.''
</P>
<P>
   Sounds like the kind of media empire WhirlGirl might want to
take a crack at.
</P>
<P>
   Looks Like a Movie ...
</P>
<P>
   In light of a fascinating development in optics, the time is
ripe for a movie sequel: ``Honey, I shrunk the big-screen theatre
complex down to the size of portable headset.''
</P>
<P>
   OK, so the title might be unwieldy, but the ``i-glasses''
technology is not.
</P>
<P>
   Said ``i-glasses'' are a portable DVD player that displays
movies on a headset and gives users the sensation they are sitting
in a theatre, watching a movie on a big screen.
</P>
<P>
   The headset, made by a Silicon Valley optics company called i-O
Display Systems, looks like a bulky visor attached to sunglasses.
Using optics technology and mirrors, the movie is projected into
the inside of the headset, so that users watch the movie as if
staring at images on the inside of their sunglasses.
</P>
<P>
   L.J. Simpson, marketing manager for i-O Systems in Menlo Park,
Calif. said the goggles give users the sensation that they are
inside a theatre, not sitting on an airplane, the couch, or in the
dentist's chair. And he's not kidding about the dentists. He said
many of the initial customers of the technology are dentists, who
show DVD movies to patients while they undergo gum surgery.
</P>
<P>
   Buyers of the i-glasses may want to try anesthetic when they
check out the product's cost. The whole package, including headset
and DVD player, is around $1,500.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
