<DOCTYPE> MISCELLANEOUS TEXT (slug-filter) </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-17 17:29 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9049 &Cx1f; tie-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CIR-Q&AMP;A-NYT &LR;      02-17 0283
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CIR-Q&AMP;A-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MULTIPLE MAILBOXES 
</HEADLINE>
  (lh) 
 By J.D. BIERSDORFER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q. I have two computers, each with a different e-mail account.
Is it possible to read the incoming mail from Computer A on
Computer B?
</P>
<P>
   A. If your Internet service provider for Computer A lets you use
a flexible e-mail program like Eudora Pro or Outlook Express, you
can set up a filter in the e-mail program to forward copies of all
the messages arriving at Computer A to the e-mail account on
Computer B.
</P>
<P>
   Filters, which most e-mail programs have (with the notable
exception of the America Online service), allow you to sort mail
into different mailboxes, forward messages and do a host of other
helpful organizational tasks, like program a particular sound to
play when mail arrives from a particular address, when you log on
to get your mail. Check the user's manual or the manufacturer's Web
site for information on how to set up filters for your particular
program.
</P>
<P>
   Some mail programs will also let you set up multiple e-mail
accounts from different ISPs on the same machine _ check your
program guide or call your provider.
</P>
<P>
   If you use America Online and want to get your mail on a
computer that doesn't have AOL software installed, you might try
the company's new Netmail feature. Although it doesn't work with
all browsers, Netmail allows you to read your incoming AOL mail
from your Web browser. You can read more about it at
www.aol.com/netmail.
</P>
<P>
   Circuits invites questions about computer-based technology, by
postal mail to Questions, Circuits, The New York Times, 229 West
43rd Street, New York, NY 10036-3959 or by e-mail to
QandA(AT)nytimes.com.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
