<HEADER>
A9051 &Cx1f; tad-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-PERLMAN21-COX     02-17 0653
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PERLMAN21-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Perlman roots into klezmer
 &HT;    EDs: Embargoed for Sunday Feb. 21.
 &HT;    By Judith Green
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The crossover bug continues to bite classical
musicians. In the case of violinist Itzhak Perlman, it's also given
him a chance to explore his roots.
</P>
<P>
   Perlman, 54, comes to Atlanta this week with ``In the Fiddler's
House,'' a program of klezmer music spun off from his 1995 PBS
special of the same name.
</P>
<P>
   Originally, PBS approached Perlman to host the special, which
was filmed in Poland, his parents' birthplace. ``I've heard
(klezmer music) all my life,'' the Israeli-born violinist said
recently in a telephone interview. ``But I'd never played it
before, and playing it never occurred to me.''
</P>
<P>
   However, ``the enthusiasm that this music gives the players is
quite infectious,'' and soon enough he found himself itching to
pick up his fiddle and join the klezmorim (klezmer musicians).
</P>
<P>
   Klezmer music, which has sometimes been called ``Jewish jazz,''
really isn't jazz, but it shares at least one characteristic with
jazz: the urge to improvise.
</P>
<P>
   Klezmer bands were composed of itinerant musicians who traveled
around the Jewish ghettos of Eastern Europe, playing at weddings
and festivals. They carried their instruments, which therefore had
to be portable: violins, clarinets, accordions.
</P>
<P>
   Their music was founded in Yiddish folk song and dance as well
as Jewish liturgical music, with healthy dollops of Romanian,
Ukrainian, Polish, Slavic, Greek, Turkish, Hungarian and Gypsy
music, used both for blend and contrast. Klezmer musicians treated
their source material as jazz treats classic blues or Tin Pan Alley
standards: After the basic sound of the group is established, the
instruments are free to wander at will along the song's harmonic
path.
</P>
<P>
   Klezmer music can be humorous or melancholy, but its sound is
unmistakable: nasal, like the cantors who led prayers in the
synagogue; heavy, like the feet in work boots and thick shoes that
danced at Jewish weddings; sweet-and-sour, like the inflections of
Yiddish itself, ending every sentence with ``nu?'' (``so?''). You
can almost hear it shrugging its shoulders.
</P>
<P>
   Perlman's classical background, which includes study at the
Juilliard School and the 1964 Leventritt Award that launched him on
an international career, hasn't kept him from other kinds of
crossover experiments, such as recording jazz classics with pianist
Oscar Peterson.
</P>
<P>
   His initial venture in klezmer goes back several years before
the PBS special, to the 1993 Oscar-winning film ``Schindler's
List.'' John Williams' score featured Perlman in a series of
klezmer-inspired melodic laments.
</P>
<P>
   The special introduced him to such groups as the Klezmer
Conservatory Band, Brave Old World, the Klezmatics and the Andy
Statman Klezmer Orchestra, all of which appear in the stage show.
Most of these ensembles, born in the 70s' klezmer revival,
represent various styles and traditions.
</P>
<P>
   Perlman, it has been said, plays klezmer like a classical
violinist, with clean scales and well-controlled ``blue notes.''
``Silk can't be wool,'' wrote New York Times reviewer Jon Pareles.
``Although he did carefully scratch a note every so often, the
rough-and-ready approach of klezmer's folk virtuosos isn't in his
vocabulary.''
</P>
<P>
   ``They have done all the scholarship,''
</P>
<P>
   Perlman says of his musical comrades. ``I'm taking it from them.
I get (them) to give me sheet music, and I get to know it by
heart.''
</P>
<P>
   ``In the Fiddler's House''
</P>
<P>
   Itzhak Perlman, violin, with the Klezmer Conservatory Band, Andy
Statman Klezmer Orchestra, Brave Old World and the Klezmatics. 8
p.m. Thursday, Fox Theatre, 660 Peachtree St. N.E. , Atlanta, Ga.
$45-$75. 404-817-8700.
</P>
<P>
   Judith Green writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
