A9052 &Cx1f; tad-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CLOONEY-GONE18-COX     02-17 0840
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLOONEY-GONE18-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Bye, George: `ER' can operate without Clooney
 &HT;    By Phil Kloer
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   He's self-righteous, narcissistic, somewhat self-destructive, a
pain in the bedpan to his friends, loved ones and co-workers.
</P>
<P>
   We're going to miss Dr. Doug Ross, even though ``ER'' is
unlikely to suffer much, if at all, from his departure.
</P>
<P>
   George Clooney takes his last walk through the swinging doors as
a regular cast member of ``ER'' tonight, although he'll pop back in
for guest appearances.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not just about you,'' Ross's live-in love, Carol
Hathaway, angrily told him on last week's episode, although lately,
it has been all about Ross, as the No. 1 series on television has
been laying the groundwork for his exit.
</P>
<P>
   To recap: The pediatrician helped a desperate mother deliver a
fatal dose of painkiller to her terminally ill son, which has
prompted his superiors to suspend him and the state attorney to
ponder murder charges against him. He's betrayed his co-workers by
going back on promises, violated the rules of a drug study and
caused the closure of Hathaway's clinic for indigent patients. At
the end of last Thursday's show, disobeying another order, he drove
off to help children trapped in an overturned school bus, only to
crash his car into a parked truck.
</P>
<P>
   It'll take a lot of cute chin-tilting and puppy-eyed looks to
get Ross out of this mess, and the biggest question tonight is
whether he will scrape out some measure of redemption or leave in
total disgrace.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever happens, the loss of Ross will be completely different
from the exit of another beloved prime-time hottie, Jimmy Smits as
Detective Bobby Simone on ``NYPD Blue,'' a mere three months ago.
That became a nationwide deathwatch; Clooney's departure has been
played out in a much lower key, due mainly to a decision by Clooney
and NBC not to over-hype it.
</P>
<P>
   Anthony Edwards, Clooney's co-star, says Ross' exit tonight is
``explosive and surprising in the way that 'ER' usually does
things, kind of against what would be predictable.''
</P>
<P>
   Clooney hasn't been giving interviews, although he did say while
in Atlanta last summer to promote the movie ``Out of Sight'' that
``I feel like I'm honoring a contract that was for five years. It's
better for a show like that to rejuvenate itself regularly, get
some fresh blood.''
</P>
<P>
   But Clooney won't be replaced, and the show will concentrate on
its cast of current characters, the largest on TV. That is the
show's strength; where ``NYPD'' rolled the dice (and won) by
replacing Smits with Rick Schroder, ``ER'' has so much going on
that not all its characters can get the screen time they deserve.
Take Jeannie Boulet (Gloria Reuben); the HIV-positive physician's
assistant has barely been seen this season. That will be changing,
as Boulet's health reportedly will get worse even as her stories
get better.
</P>
<P>
   Among the other arcs getting attention: Carter (Noah Wyle) has
started messing around with his med student Lucy (Kellie Martin), a
no-no; and Kerry Weaver (Laura Innes) is seething over the
loathsome, trollish Romano (Paul McCrane) being in charge of the
ER.
</P>
<P>
   So will Clooney be missed? A little. But Sherry Stringfield
walked out in the middle of a big romantic story, and the series
didn't miss a beat. (Next to leave: Emmy winner Julianna Marguiles,
who plays Hathaway, says she's gone at the end of next season.)
</P>
<P>
   Clooney could have left ``ER'' a couple of seasons ago. Although
he's not made it into the absolute top rank of feature film stars
(``four or five guys have to pass on a script, then I get to see
it,'' he likes to joke), he's certainly done better than most TV
actors who leave a show for greener pastures that eventually turn
out to be full of weeds and made-for-cable TV movies.
</P>
<P>
   Clooney has known his share of movie flops (``Batman and
Robin'') and modest but well-reviewed hits (``Out of Sight''), as
well as getting attention for his small role in Terrence Malick's
``The Thin Red Line,'' the type of part that gets Hollywood's
respect. He has production deals with both Warner Bros. and CBS and
will spend his time acting in movies and developing TV shows.
</P>
<P>
   In the works for Clooney:
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``Three Kings,'' a feature film about Gulf War vets
co-starring Ice Cube and Mark Wahlberg.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``Leatherheads,'' a movie about the early days of pro
football, directed by Steve Soderbergh (``Out of Sight'').
Currently on hold.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``Kilroy,'' a comedy for HBO that Clooney would produce but
not star in. It's a blend of fiction and reality (a la ``The Larry
Sanders Show'') in which a fictional actor would appear in other,
``real'' TV shows.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``Fail-Safe,'' a remake of the 1964 nuclear thriller for CBS.
Tentatively, it would be a live drama, in black-and-white, with
Clooney producing and taking a small role.
</P>
<P>
   ``ER''
</P>
<P>
   10 tonight on NBC
</P>
<P>
   Phil Kloer writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
