<HEADER>
A9066 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LEVIS-COMPETITION-HNS     02-17 0649
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LEVIS-COMPETITION-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LEVI STRAUSS FACES BATTLE TO RECOUP LOST TURF 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By VICTORIA COLLIVER  
 c.1998 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Dickies. JNCO. Fubu. Pelle Pelle. These are some
of the labels responsible for Levi Strauss &AMP; Co.'s 13 percent sales
slide in 1998, the jean maker's largest percentage decline in at
least 50 years.
</P>
<P>
   ``The young men's market is incredibly vibrant and Levi's is not
a part of it,'' said Robert Lohrer, editor of DNR, a New York-based
fashion trade magazine. ``Nobody in young men's is talking about
Levi Strauss.''
</P>
<P>
   But people are talking about whether San Francisco-based Levi
Strauss is on the right track to regain its footing in a market
that has become increasingly trendy and fickle. Since sales dropped
nearly 3 percent to $6.9 billion in 1997, the talk in the industry
has centered on how the company, founded by Bavarian native Levi
Strauss 146 years ago, stood by its classic styles when the world
was going baggy and flared.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday's announcement that sales had dipped further to $6
billion for the fiscal year ending Nov. 29 was disturbing but
hardly unexpected for both the company and analysts who follow the
brand.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the natural fallout of what has been happening. The
brand _ the 501 jean _ has been under attack,'' said Harry Bernard,
partner and chief marketing officer at Colton Bernard Inc., a San
Francisco marketing firm.
</P>
<P>
   The attack has come from both hip, upstart labels, small and
nimble enough to shift their focus with the latest designs, and
some of the country's largest retailers, such as Sears, Roebuck &AMP;
Co. and J.C. Penney Co., which have eaten into the mainstream
market with their private label jeans.
</P>
<P>
   While Levi Strauss still is the best-selling jeans brand, its
market share has fallen 38 percent between 1997 and 1998 among
females in the 13- to 24-year-old age group, according to a recent
survey by the Zandl Group, a New York-based trend-spotting firm.
Among males in that same age group, the decline was 30 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Levi Strauss admits it got too comfortable being the largest
apparel manufacturer in the world. For more than 100 years, the
company has been the world's dominant denim manufacturer.
</P>
<P>
   In the past year, the company has cut fat and revamped its image
in an effort to boost sales.
</P>
<P>
   The company cut 1,000 jobs in 1997 and last year slashed another
6,400 jobs, or about a third of its work force, by closing plants.
It announced a restructuring of the strategy to become more
consumer focused and marketing driven rather than relying on its
relationship with its retailers to sell jeans.
</P>
<P>
   And, just last month, Levi Strauss President Peter Jacobi
announced he would leave the company after nearly three decades.
While a new president has yet to be named, Jacobi has insisted that
his replacement come from outside the ranks of the company.
</P>
<P>
   ``They really do have on paper a new strategy,'' Bernard said.
``The key question remains, how will they implement it?''
</P>
<P>
   Levi Strauss spokesman Gavin Power said the selection of a new
president is still months away. And while the 1998 results are
disappointing, Power said, those numbers do not yet reflect some of
the changes that have taken place or are yet to be made.
</P>
<P>
   He said the company continues to work on a number of new styles,
such as a new Red Tab line featuring ``fashion-forward'' basics in
cargo, carpenter and other styles. Also, in an effort to reach out
to young people, Levi Strauss is sponsoring music tours and
introducing a line of clothing inspired by the ``Mod Squad'' movie
debuting in March.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're testing new ground,'' Power said. ``We want to come out
with new brands, sub brands and brand extensions that speak to the
diversity in the marketplace. The consumer base now is a lot more
complicated.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-17-99 1741EST &QL; 
