<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-17 17:50 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9082 &Cx1f; tie-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CIR-POMPEII-NYT &LR;      02-17 0870
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CIR-POMPEII-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VIRTUAL GUIDED TOUR OF POMPEII'S RUINS 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 By MICHAEL POLLAK   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   To study the richness of Pompeii and Herculaneum, the Roman
towns buried by the eruption of Mount Vesuvius in A.D. 79, nothing
beats a round-trip ticket to Naples.
</P>
<P>
   Then there's the Internet. True, no sun, pasta or Mediterranean.
On the other hand, no visas, tipping or civil servants who may be
neither. You still get a good look at two of antiquity's most
celebrated sites, which, Vesuvius being what it is, may not be
around forever.
</P>
<P>
   You also get great online Pompeian graffiti that is not in
typical textbooks, like ``Samius to Cornelius: go hang yourself''
and ``Virgula to her fellow Tertius: You're disgusting.''
</P>
<P>
   Samius and Virgula are only two of many writers whose excavated
graffiti come alive again on an entertaining Pompeii site from
Amherst (www.amherst.edu/classics/class36/basilica.html).
</P>
<P>
   ``Phileros is a eunuch,'' one scrawl reads (in Latin, with
translations). Other graffiti list gladiators' records in the
amphitheater. One begins: ``Calling all lovers! I want to break
Venus' ribs with clubs and cripple the loins of the goddess.''
</P>
<P>
   The Pompeii Forum Project (pompeii.virginia.edu) is a complex
venture sponsored by the University of Virginia, the National
Endowment for the Humanities and private donors. The nine-person
team, which includes two computer specialists, uses technology to
survey the central forum. The goal is to understand its evolution
from pre-Roman times. A major focus is the work on the forum after
a devastating earthquake in A.D. 62, until the eruption of 79
buried the city under volcanic ash, and how that work relates to
the older architecture of Pompeii.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. John J. Dobbins, a professor of classical art and archeology
at the University of Virginia who is the project leader, said the
issues faced then were still relevant today. He wrote by e-mail,
``You can almost hear the debates in the city council of Pompeii
about the proper way to repair downtown, the forum: Should we knock
down an entire section of the city center and build everything new,
or should we keep some of our old buildings because they are
important to us in a number of ways?''
</P>
<P>
   Diagrams of individual buildings include camera icons that not
only allow access to the images but also show the angles from which
they were taken.
</P>
<P>
   The site's Notes to Teachers and Students has a close-up of an
inscription, a dedication by the donor of a building, and its
translation. But that's just the start. What does the dedication
signify about the politics and social life of Pompeii? Who was the
donor? Why was it worded that way? What began as a simple picture
turns into a classical detective story. The teaching guide gives a
Pompeian wall painting a similar beneath-the-surface inquiry.
</P>
<P>
   The forum site also has a link to an Amherst College site that
prints two eyewitness letters to Tacitus, the historian, by Pliny
the Younger. He describes the eruption of Vesuvius and the death of
his uncle, Pliny the Elder, who, as commander of the Roman fleet,
was trying to rescue the trapped population.
</P>
<P>
   A geology site focusing on Vesuvius is
www.geo.mtu.edu/boris/VESUVIO.html. Besides linking to current
volcano sites, this one has a detailed account of the eruption of
A.D. 79, which killed thousands in a cloud of darkness similar to
the blast at Mount St. Helens in 1980.
</P>
<P>
   And don't miss The History of Plumbing: Pompeii and Herculaneum
(www.theplumber.com/pom.html).
</P>
<P>
   Although it has been overshadowed by the larger excavations at
Pompeii, the resort town of Herculaneum, buried by hot mud in the
eruption, may conceal a greater treasure. In the 18th century,
hundreds of papyrus scrolls, oxidized and congealed but many still
readable, were unearthed from a villa once owned by Julius Caesar's
father-in-law. Most contained the writings of Philodemus, an
Epicurean philosopher of the first century B.C. Some scholars
believe that the estate, now called the Villa dei Papiri, is likely
to have held a major library and that beneath 20 meters of
mud-turned-rock, there may still be readable scrolls of lost Greek
and Latin classics.
</P>
<P>
   The Philodemus Project, led from the University of California at
Los Angeles, is an international effort to piece together the
readable fragments properly, using modern techniques, and get
better translations
(www.humnet.ucla.edu/humnet/classics/Philodemus/philhome.htm). But
excavations have been halted because of a lack of money, as well as
flooding and rising methane gas, said Dr. David L. Blank, chairman
of the classics department at UCLA and the project leader, in an
e-mail message.
</P>
<P>
   ``Probably the biggest problem here is that of conservation,''
he wrote, referring to an ongoing debate about whether to forge
ahead with new excavations or to focus instead on preserving what
has already been found. ``Many scholars,'' he said, ``would even
prefer that the unexcavated areas here remain that way, rather than
expose their treasures to the inevitable depradations of time,
weather, uncontrollable plant growth, theft, vandalism'' and,
finally, ``tourism on an enormous scale.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-17-99 1750EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
