<SLUG> BC-STAPLES-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A LOOK BACK ON THE SCARS OF RACISM
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By GRACIE BONDS STAPLES 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   I sit staring at the card that I just drew from the bottom of a
drawer. It is a membership card I received 1976, when I was
inducted into Phi Theta Kappa, the national honor fraternity of
junior colleges.
</P>
<P>
   I read it, front to back, back to front, over and over, waiting
for some logical point to manifest itself, hoping for something
that will help me put it in its proper perspective.
</P>
<P>
   Nothing comes, and I am left only with the memory of a cool,
driving rain, of a slender, old white man and his stinging words,
``How did you get in this?''
</P>
<P>
   I sit now feeling as I did then, like an undeserving foreigner,
covered only by the distinction of the evening. And as I did then,
I remind myself that I got ``in'' the same way my white
counterparts had: I worked hard.
</P>
<P>
   I had been jolted back to that time just hours earlier, during a
dialogue with the Rev. Laurie Feille, pastor of Arlington Heights
Christian Church in Fort Worth. Both natives of Mississippi, we had
been asked by University Christian Church to come and talk about
our experiences coming of age there in the 1960s and how those
events affected our faith.
</P>
<P>
   But leaving the church that night, I was struck by the strong
emotion with which I had recounted such a distant memory. Somehow
it didn't feel like my past at all. Maybe it is my present. I was
no longer sure.
</P>
<P>
   In any case, I had been born black in McComb to parents with a
sixth-grade education, and Faille not more than 100 miles away to
white college graduates in Hattiesburg. From the time I was 12, I
spent most weekends and evenings working to help make ends meet.
She spent her time doing what children do.
</P>
<P>
   She was 32 when she learned that there had been bombings of
black residences in Hattiesburg. I grew up frightened and fully
aware of bombings occurring in McComb. The daughter of a college
professor, she enrolled at the University of Southern Mississippi
in 1976. I enrolled there in 1977, after graduating from junior
college. Even then, our worlds never meshed.
</P>
<P>
   A chance meeting last fall brought us together under the same
roof, and Sunday night we sat face to face, recounting our lives,
the roads we traveled, the signposts we either ignored or carefully
considered. We talked for nearly an hour like long-lost friends; as
the audience began asking questions, we talked some more.
</P>
<P>
   The event had been billed as a dialogue between me and Feille to
drive home the fact that racism happens. For me, it was more a
cleansing experience. I had never sat down and told a white person
how those experiences made me feel, and I was struck by the
audience's seeming willingness to listen and not judge or make
excuses; to try to find some way to close the gaping hole that
divides us.
</P>
<P>
   What I didn't expect were the apologies offered at the end of
our talk. Soliciting regret was never my goal. Fostering
understanding was.
</P>
<P>
   My life has been my life, a mixture of triumph and tragedy, joy
and despair. That was my promise, if you believe Scripture, from
the day I entered this world.
</P>
<P>
   In the scheme of things, my experiences as a black woman may
mean nothing or they may mean everything to those I spoke with
Sunday. But one thing is for sure, they are why I hold fast to my
faith, why I am convinced that without God's grace, much of what I
endured would have left me bitter or dead.
</P>
<P>
   I am neither.
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
