<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ANDERSON-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WE NEED CHEAPER WEAPONS IN AGING BATTLE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MONICA FRAZIER ANDERSON 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Everyone knows that it is expensive to raise children. Even kids
know that it's economically challenging to feed, clothe and care
for them, because we remind them about it all of the time.
</P>
<P>
   I don't know how many times I've said, ``Son, do you know how
much those shoes cost that you're dragging across the pavement like
Fred Flintstone? Fred did not have brakes on his cavemobile, but
you do have brakes on that bicycle.''
</P>
<P>
   Actually, I guess I haven't said that very many times, but I've
thought it a lot. Anyway, I know all about the high costs of the
spring and winter of our lives. It's the fall, the middle aging,
that's caught me by surprise.
</P>
<P>
   While some folks are adding shelves to their closets, we've had
to add more cabinets to our master bathroom to hold all the creams
and liniments that keep us in one piece from Monday to Friday.
</P>
<P>
   My husband has a green bottle of tablets for backaches and a
brown bottle of capsules for his headaches. The main ingredient in
each is acetaminophen, but I guess the rest of those minor
ingredients tell the pills which part of the body is hurting.
</P>
<P>
   He has five strengths of analgesic cream to rub on those sore
muscles after he plays his weekly game of basketball. One measly
game. I remember the days when he played ball all day long and then
took me dancing. Nothing ever hurt him back then. He'd sprain an
ankle playing football and it would heal before he made it to the
sideline.
</P>
<P>
   He also has a lot of mouthwash and hair-care products crammed
into that one drawer I've assigned to him. Well, it's a long
drawer. It's shallow, but it's long.
</P>
<P>
   The rest of the bathroom is filled with my stuff.
</P>
<P>
   Those cavewomen had it made. Run the fingers through the matted
hair once a week, and no makeup. I have to wash the hair, condition
it, dry it straight, then curl it again and finally arrange it so
the gray strands don't reflect a blinding light into the eyes of my
companions. My pores get opened and closed more than the front door
at Wal-Mart. And where does all this dry skin come from? And this
hair, too? I found a hair on my chin the other day that was 6
inches long. My husband wanted it, but I tossed itto in the trash.
Is this normal? No one ever talks about this stuff. All we see is
the end product.
</P>
<P>
   Now I know that underneath the perfect exteriors of the nightly
news anchors are gallons of moisturizer and yards of tape. Yes,
duct tape. Forget that expensive plastic surgery. You'll be amazed
at what a few strips of strategically placed duct tape can do to
combat the effects of age and gravity. It's a miracle, indeed.
</P>
<P>
   So I'm suggesting that we start a national discussion on aging,
not only graciously but also inexpensively. There has got to be a
better way to do this. Surely there's a way to simply widen my
shoes rather than buying a new pair. And hair loss for a lot of
guys is a big issue. We women have these chin hairs that we don't
want. Can't we recycle this stuff somehow?
</P>
<P>
   Think of all the money we could save with just a little
ingenuity. Hey, just think of all the tape we could buy!
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-17-99 1755EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
