<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-POPMUSIC-FERMAN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CAUGHT WITH A ROCK, BLUESMAN IS SENT TO A HARD PLACE
</HEADLINE>
 
(RESENDING to add byline) (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DAVE FERMAN 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   JACKSBORO, Texas _ U.P. Wilson strides into a small visiting
room of the John R. Lindsey State Jail and sticks out his hand.
</P>
<P>
   At 63, the popular Fort Worth bluesman is lean and strong;
moreover, he's clear-eyed, steady of voice and friendly.
Surprising, because Wilson has spent more than five months in this
facility 62 miles west of Fort Worth, thanks to his second cocaine
possession conviction in less than a year.
</P>
<P>
   His time in stir seems to have affected Wilson little, except
that he had to cancel many shows in Europe, where he has been a
regular on the blues-festival circuit for nearly a decade _ which
might be good and bad.
</P>
<P>
   Huary Perry Wilson, you see, knows all about the rumors
circulating for years in local blues circles: That he's a crack
addict, that he's broke, that he blows all the money he makes
playing lucrative shows in Europe. None of that, he says, is true.
Sure, he has smoked crack for the past three or four years. Yes,
he's been arrested twice, in September 1997 and May 1998, both
times at his home.
</P>
<P>
   But to Wilson, that does not add up to crack addiction. Two
busts within eight months would indicate a serious problem to some
people, but he doesn't see it that way.
</P>
<P>
   ``I might smoke crack two, three days in a row,'' he says. ``But
only if I was around somebody who had it. It never had ahold of
me.''
</P>
<P>
   More than that, he says, he is neither broke nor without a
career. Wilson says he is going right back to playing European
clubs and festivals this spring, to recording (he has released four
CDs on London's JSP Records) and to perhaps starting up his own
label. He has savings, his home _ he's hardly down and out, and he
wants everyone to know it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've made quite a few friends in here,'' he says. ``Maybe I
just needed a little time out. I'm fine in here _ I'm great. What I
miss most is my guitar; it's just everyday life in here.''
</P>
<P>
   In fact, Wilson admits that it's everyday life that has landed
him in such serious trouble. His increasing fame in Europe has
meant more downtime at home, more cash in his pocket _ and more
temptations.
</P>
<P>
   They say be careful what you wish for. U.P. Wilson got
everything he'd ever hoped for not too long ago, and it landed him
in a whole lot of trouble.
</P>
<P>
   A HOME-GROWN HERO
</P>
<P>
   Born in Shreveport, La., Wilson began playing in Fort Worth and
Dallas clubs in the mid-'50s, first with Robert Ealey and then,
beginning in the '60s, as a solo act.
</P>
<P>
   Even back then he had a great local reputation. Fort Worth was
full of young guys, white and black, who wanted to play like
Freddie King and B.B. King, and Wilson was their home-grown guitar
hero.
</P>
<P>
   ``We all used to go see him play; we'd all pick up ideas from
him,'' says well-known Fort Worth bluesman Sumter Bruton.
``Everybody in town did. There's a style of Fort Worth blues
playing _ a real hip, jazzy style _ and it comes from U.P., Cornell
Dupree and Raymond George.''
</P>
<P>
   Wilson was also known for driving audiences crazy with the
``table trick'': He would set the guitar on a table or a stool and
play a song with one hand while smoking a cigarette or drinking a
beer with the other. Guitarist/vocalist Dave Millsap remembers
playing the fabled Bluebird in the late '70s and seeing Wilson work
his magic on crowds.
</P>
<P>
   ``He'd make more money in 10 minutes than we did all night,''
Millsap says. ``People would go berserk when he came in. It was
like a preacher thing _ people would come up to him to give him
money.''
</P>
<P>
   But by 1987, Wilson had little besides a great local rep to show
for all those years of working the clubs. All that changed in 1988,
when Wilson was approached about cutting a record by Eddie Stout,
bassist and owner of the small PeeWee Records. That CD, ``On My
Way,'' led to a first trip to Europe. Soon he was going to Europe
several times a year for up to six weeks at a time, getting $450
for 45 minutes' work and coming home with thousands of dollars. He
quit his job as a janitor.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd make the same money playing in a week as I would working
for a month,'' he says with a laugh. ``They love the blues in
France. Your dressing room is crowded over there _ they're in line
to interview you.''
</P>
<P>
   And that was where the problems started. Wilson had money, a
certain amount of fame _ and, between tours, long periods of time
on his hands. When friends came over with crack, he says, he began
smoking more or less just for something to do.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was three, four years ago,'' he says. ``I'd smoke it on the
weekends. I smoked primo _ you crack the rocks up, sprinkle it on
weed or tobacco, and roll it up and smoke it like a cigarette.''
</P>
<P>
   Steve Meek, Wilson's drummer agrees, saying Wilson's problem is
less physical addiction than ``social addiction.''
</P>
<P>
   ``His friends keep him in it,'' says Meek, who has been booking
him and accompanying him to Europe since 1993. ``If I keep him
touring, he doesn't have a problem.''
</P>
<P>
   The first arrest came Sept. 24, 1997, when nine officers entered
his home and found ``a small off-white rocklike substance on the
table in the living room'' next to where Wilson was sitting. Wilson
had no prior convictions. He was charged with possession of a
controlled substance, less than 1 gram of cocaine. On April 22, he
was sentenced to 180 days in jail; he was given two years'
probation and fined $200. On May 8, he was arrested at home again.
This time, according to the police report, Wilson admitted he
smoked crack but said he did not deal it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had just come back from France and I was taking it easy,''
he says. ``They found a little ol' tiny piece, not even a good hit,
and took me down for that.''
</P>
<P>
   A PACK OF TROUBLES
</P>
<P>
   According to the police report, however, the home was awash in
drugs: Three small bags of crack were found, as well as five
separate pieces, a razor blade with white residue, and a pipe with
brown residue. Wilson was charged with possession of less than 1
gram of cocaine. His probation was revoked, and on Aug. 11 he was
sentenced to six months in a state jail.
</P>
<P>
   Wilson passed his time in Jacksboro quietly; he took classes
toward getting his GED, he says. He also played in the facility's
gospel band for a while, according to chaplain David McIntyre. ``He
can hammer on that guitar, but I'd tell him to tone it down some,''
McIntyre says. ``He has a lot of talent and a good heart.''
</P>
<P>
   The local bluesmen are rooting for him. Bruton, Millsap and
others have fond memories of him and sincerely hope he can keep
himself clean and active. ``I think this is a shame,'' Millsap
says. ``I hope he can walk the line. He might want to step back and
look at it and say, `This may be my last shot.' ''
</P>
<P>
   There's no question Wilson can continue to tour and record for
years to come if he stays out of trouble. But the drug issue is
still there; Wilson says he doesn't need crack, but not that he'll
never smoke it again.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not worried about it,'' he says. ``I wasn't addicted then,
so I can't get addicted now. I was never jonesin' for it in here.
Some people will do anything to get crack. I can't see that. I'm
not a fool behind it. I don't need it.''
</P>
<P>
   And really, he says, nobody should worry about him. He's fine,
he says, and champing at the bit to get back to playing his blues.
``I've done a lot of planning,'' he says, just before leaving to go
to lunch. ``I'm well-fixed for music and money. I'm in good shape.
I'm set. I'm ready. And they're ready for me.''
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL;
</P>
