<HEADER>
A9097 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BLACKHISTORY-ORAL-COX     02-17 0502
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BLACKHISTORY-ORAL-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    When there's a tale to tell
 &HT;    By John Keilman
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _ Collecting an oral history can be as easy as
sitting down with a tape recorder or notebook. But those who have
done it say it is far more effective if you follow a few tips:
</P>
<P>
   _ Be prepared. Annie Bonaparte, who has conducted oral history
sessions between teen-agers and seniors in West Dayton, says people
should think in advance about the things they're interested in
learning.
</P>
<P>
   ``Just sit down and think of the questions you want to ask a
person,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   You also should decide how you want to take down the history.
Many people use an audiotape recorder or a video camera, but if you
want a written account, Marlese Durr, a sociologist at Wright State
University, recommends a notebook and pen.
</P>
<P>
   ``I usually think the notes are good,'' she said. ``Otherwise,
you can spend a lot of time transcribing the interview or paying
for a transcriber.''
</P>
<P>
   Bonaparte says history collectors should make sure they find a
quiet place to conduct their conversations.
</P>
<P>
   _ Start at home. Many fascinating stories are probably within
your own household.
</P>
<P>
   ``First of all, talk to your relatives,'' said Sue Taylor, a
Howard University anthropologist who has collected oral histories
since the 1970s.
</P>
<P>
   ``Get them to help write down things that they remember. Ask
them in a way like this: `What was it like when . . . ?' Have them
tell you from that perspective.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Try a group setting. The Dayton Stories Project, which
collected tales from 1,200 local residents, used story circles in
which a number people told accounts of their lives.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a really good activity to do during a family reunion,''
said Marilyn Shannon, who ran the project. ``You have a lot of
different people there who can be there from all over.''
</P>
<P>
   But the success of this approach depends heavily on ground
rules.
</P>
<P>
   ``For anything like that you need a facilitator,'' Shannon said.
``One of the most important things any leader can do is make sure
people agree to a couple of rules.
</P>
<P>
   ``One of them is that people speak one at a time. No kibitzing,
no interrupting. That's very hard to do, but you can learn that.
And they have to agree to how much time they have. It's a really
democratic way to get everyone involved.''
</P>
<P>
   She also recommends asking people about specifics _ family
members, for instance, or various characters they once knew. And
don't worry if the conversation drifts a bit. It can remind people
of previously forgotten memories.
</P>
<P>
   _ Be bold. Don't worry about being turned down by a potential
subject. Bonaparte said people are usually more than willing to
answer questions about their lives.
</P>
<P>
   _ Finally, remember why you're doing this.
</P>
<P>
   ``Stories are different from a conversation,'' Shannon said.
``Stories have a meaning. You tell why things are important.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-17-99 1759EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990217.0298 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-17 17:59 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9098 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BLACKHISTORY-VOICES-P     02-17 0785
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BLACKHISTORY-VOICES-PIQUA-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Some black families never backed away from segregation, racism
in society
 &HT;    By Lisa Perry
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _ Acceptance into Piqua society came slow and hard
for black families at the height of the integration movement during
the early 1960s.
</P>
<P>
   But some, including the Elmer V. Harris family, didn't back down
to segregationist pressures and smoothed the road to integration
for future generations.
</P>
<P>
   The theater, health and civic clubs, educational and
occupational opportunities and social groups were among doors
closed to Elmer Harris, 76, the grandson of a freed Virginia slave;
his wife Willie Mae; son William and daughter Sue Randi.
</P>
<P>
   William Harris, 47, now president of Masonry Systems Inc. of
Piqua, remembers well that Wednesdays were the only nights open to
black kids at the YMCA pool or the roller skating rink.
</P>
<P>
   ``They would change the water Wednesday nights,'' he said.
Finally, through subtle pressure ``from within and without,''
Harris said he became the first black member of the YMCA when his
father signed him up for swim lessons and he was accepted.
</P>
<P>
   William, in the first grade at North Street Elementary School,
quickly made the swim team, and traveled to numerous swim meets.
</P>
<P>
   ``I never appreciated why my dad came to all those meets,''
William said. ``It was to cover my behind in case there was any
trouble.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite the elder Harris' presence, his was denied participation
at many swim meets.
</P>
<P>
   It wasn't Elmer Harris' first encounter with racism. His mother,
Clara B. Harris, a 1908 graduate of Wilberforce University, was
unable to find work in the Piqua City School system as a teacher.
Instead, she labored as a domestic.
</P>
<P>
   Piqua schools integrated in 1885, combining white students with
black students who formerly attended schools at the Cyrene Church
and Boone Street Colored School, closed in 1872 because of low
attendance, said Piqua historian James C. Oda.
</P>
<P>
   Elmer Harris graduated in 1941 and William Harris in 1969 from
the Piqua schools. Now, William's children, Lance and Laura,
attend.
</P>
<P>
   Though the elder Harris served honorably in the U.S. Navy and
lost a brother, also named William, a master sergeant chief line
mechanic with the Tuskegee Airmen, to an airplane accident in
Italy, blacks in Piqua found it necessary to create their own
Veterans of Foreign Wars post.
</P>
<P>
   The Stout-Harris post is named for William Harris and Alex
Stout, a black medic from Piqua killed in the D-Day invasion while
trying to rescue his commanding officer. On March 15, 1946, Elmer
Harris became quartermaster of the post.
</P>
<P>
   For those returning from the war, real estate was available only
in certain areas of town.
</P>
<P>
   ``They would not sell to you if you wanted property where they
didn't want you to live,'' the elder Harris said.
</P>
<P>
   And blacks weren't allowed to sit where local theater managers
didn't want them to sit.
</P>
<P>
   ``About 10 or 15 of us used to sit in the back rows'' reserved
for blacks at Schine's Piqua Theater, Harris said. When he and a
dozen or so of his fellow World War II veterans sat in the middle
rows and refused to move, management moved the whites away from the
middle.
</P>
<P>
   Theater management was directed not to sell tickets to Harris,
who was labeled a ``rabble-rouser.''
</P>
<P>
   But Harris said he was determined to make his life and vocation
in Piqua. Now president of his own masonry company, he said that
being invited to bid for a project was a challenge for black masons
until affirmative action opened the door.
</P>
<P>
   Once he and son William walked through that door and showed what
they were capable of doing, there was no turning back. They count
among their projects the Montgomery County Jail, the Dayton Arcade
and Wright State University's Ervin J. Nutter Center.
</P>
<P>
   ``By the mid-1980s, they accepted us for what we could do and
not because they had to have us,'' the elder Harris said.
</P>
<P>
   The younger Harris is quick to praise his father for sacrifices
he and others made during those volatile times.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am grateful for what (my dad) did. He is a quiet leader of
change, vocal and forceful,'' William said.
</P>
<P>
   Though William said he still feels subtle racism on occasion, it
was ``nothing to what my dad went through.''
</P>
<P>
   ``He made it possible for me and my friends to have what he
could not have,'' William said. And the lesson he learned from his
father he hopes to pass along to his own children.
</P>
<P>
   ``Give everybody the same benefit of the doubt,'' William said.
``I still don't get that today. Try to give everyone an even
break.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
