<HEADER>
A9132 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TEST-TUBE-MODEL-ART-5     02-17 1006
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEST-TUBE-MODEL-ART-570&AMP;ADD-NYTR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PIONEER TEST-TUBE BABY COMES OF AGE 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photo of Samantha Steele is being sent to NYT photo
clients. Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
(888) 603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.)  
(gm) 
 By TIM TESCONI   
 Santa Rosa (Calif.) Press Democrat   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SANTA ROSA, Calif. _ As the first American test tube baby,
17-year-old Samantha Steel is grateful her parents, Laurie and Jon
Steel, went to such extraordinary efforts to bring her into the
world.
</P>
<P>
   Conceived in a test tube in England, Samantha doesn't consider
herself a creature of science fiction but a miracle of technology
and her parents' enduring love.
</P>
<P>
   Today, Samantha, an American who was born in London, is among
the more than 500,000 children around the world who owe their lives
to in-vitro fertilization, which is the uniting of egg and sperm in
a glass container. The fertilized egg or embryo is then inserted
into the mother's womb where, if it implants, develops into a fetus
and nine months later, a baby.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel really lucky and so very grateful that I was born, that
I'm alive,'' said Samantha, who has lived in Kenwood, Calif., since
she was 5 years old.
</P>
<P>
   Born Oct. 21, 1982, Samantha is among the first crop of test
tube babies approaching adulthood. Louise Brown, the world's first
baby conceived through in-vitro fertilization, was born near
Manchester, England, in July 1978.
</P>
<P>
   Distinctions about the first test tube babies get tricky, said
Laurie Steel, a computer specialist who works out of her Kenwood
home. Samantha's father, Jon Steel, is a Sonoma County
veterinarian. The couple met while attending Stanford University,
married and studied in England where they were able to have the
child they always wanted.
</P>
<P>
   She said Samantha is the first American and the world's fourth
child conceived through in-vitro fertilization. Samantha was born
in England two months before Elizabeth Carr, 17, of Westminister,
Mass., who is recognized as the first test tube baby actually born
in the United States. Carr, born on Dec. 28, 1981, was conceived in
vitro at the Jones Institute for Reproductive Medicine in Norfolk,
Va.
</P>
<P>
   A willowy junior in high school, Samantha, cool and comfortable
about her beginnings in a glass dish, is embarking on a career as a
teen fashion model. On Valentine's Day she left for Tokyo and two
months in photography studios and on fashion runways. This summer
she will be modeling in Milan, Italy.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm in shock. I can't believe it's all happening. It's always
been my goal to travel the world and now it's happening,'' said
Samantha, an only child. She declines to say how much she's earning
but she says it's enough to finance her college education and buy a
car.
</P>
<P>
   It's Samantha's waif-like looks _ not her mysterious allure as a
test tube baby _ that is making her hot property in the fashion
world. She's 5 foot, 10 inches and a size 3.
</P>
<P>
   ``The fashion people don't even know I'm a test tube baby,''
said Samantha, who until recently worked part time at Squeezer's
Juice Bar in Santa Rosa.
</P>
<P>
   She attended Kenwood Elementary School and was a member of the
4-H and Girl Scouts. She plays the violin, kicks a soccer ball and
loves riding horses.
</P>
<P>
   For Samantha's parents, their beautiful child, produced through
what was once a revolutionary medical procedure, is a treasured
gift. And Samantha's birth is testament to Laurie and Jon Steel's
perseverance, borne of the belief that they were destined to be
parents.
</P>
<P>
   ``She is a miracle,'' said Laurie Steel, who could not conceive
a child. ``Obviously she was meant to be here.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   For 10 years, Laurie Steel sought help at fertility clinics but
couldn't get pregnant. She wouldn't give up, driven passionately by
her desire to have a child.
</P>
<P>
   Steel and her husband were U.S. students at Cambridge University
in England in 1978 when headlines screamed of the ``World's First
Tube Baby.'' Jon was enrolled in Cambridge University's veterinary
school and Laurie was studying violin. The couple had met at
Stanford University, married and then moved to England to finish
their education.
</P>
<P>
   Following the news of the scientific breakthrough, the Steels'
hopes for a child soared. But it would be more than two years
before they were accepted at an in-vitro fertilization clinic run
by the doctors who had perfected the procedure that produced Louise
Brown.
</P>
<P>
   Jon Steel graduated and worked as a veterinarian in England
while the couple waited for a chance at in vitro.
</P>
<P>
   There were thousands of women seeking the help of pioneering
fertility doctors Patrick Steptoe, a gynecologist, and Robert
Edwards who, coincidentally, had been Jon Steel's genetics
professor at Cambridge.
</P>
<P>
   Laurie Steel was the only woman in her group to become pregnant
during her session at the famed fertilization clinic _ called
Bourne Hall.
</P>
<P>
   Samantha, who has her father's eyes and her mother's mouth, was
born in London. The Steel family bounced between England and the
United States for several years before finally settling in Sonoma
County, where Jon opened his veterinary practice.
</P>
<P>
   Laurie Steel said because Samantha was the first American test
tube baby, reporters for the National Enquirer, the supermarket
tabloid, were hot on their trail. To thwart the tabloid, the Steels
gave the Ladies' Home Journal their exclusive story, which was
published in January 1982. A photograph of Laurie and 2-month old
Samantha share the magazine cover with actress Goldie Hawn.
</P>
<P>
   The story of how Samantha came to be has been openly discussed
among the Steels, who feel blessed and honored to be part of the
historic technology. Samantha said when she hears about her
parents' unrelenting efforts to have her she is genuinely touched
by the sacrifices that brought them together.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are a very loving family,'' Samantha said.
</P>
<P>
   (Tim Tesconi writes The Press Democrat in Santa Rosa, Calif.)
</P>
</TEXT>
