<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-CLOONEY-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WILL `ER' SURVIVE THE LOSS OF DR. ROSS? 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MATTHEW GILBERT  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The ads for Thursday night's's episode of ``ER'' show a picture
of George Clooney's Dr. Doug Ross beneath the question, ``Gone for
good?'' So maybe someone should notify NBC's clueless ad company
that Clooney's absolutely certain exit from ``ER'' has only been
the month's hottest TV story, most notably on last week's TV Guide
cover, which loudly declared ``Bye, George!'' Yes, George Clooney,
he of the heavy-duty eye contact and the bobbing and ever-stubbly
chin, is saying goodbye to the No. 1 drama to pursue his movie
career. And the real mystery is not whether Clooney will go, but
how the writers will usher him out (no advance tape was available
for critics) and how well the show will survive his absence. ``Gone
for ill?'' may be the better question.
</P>
<P>
   And it's easy to wonder if Clooney's departure will hurt the
five-year-old ``ER,'' which has been in a bit of a creative slump
this season. With his naturalistic acting style, Clooney has turned
his maverick pediatrician into one of the show's most appealing and
multidimensional characters, both in and out of the ER. Because Dr.
Ross is so reckless in his need to help children, and so ready to
ignore callous parents and insurance companies, he has instigated
some of the juciest ethical dilemmas on ``ER.'' Indeed, he'll leave
County General Memorial Hospital mired in an interesting and
complicated situation involving the euthanasia of a dying
8-year-old boy whom we saw moaning from unstoppable pain. And
because Doug has been so reckless in his need to flee from
emotional commitment, and so ready to shed his scrubs for a
one-night-stand, he has stimulated some of the show's dishiest
melodrama, including an affair with his father's ex. He's been both
an anti-romantic and a romantic hero in the course of his tenure on
the show.
</P>
<P>
   Actually, of all the vivid characters in the ``ER'' ensemble,
including Gloria Reuben's Jeannie Boulet and Julianna Margulies's
Carol Hathaway, Clooney's Ross has had the fullest arc of
development. He is a different man from the womanizing hothead of
the first season _ and not just because he's been through a
veritable Us magazine of much-commented-upon hair styles. We saw
him bottom out after the overdose of a one-night-stand whose name
he didn't know; we saw him cope with the death of his father, who
was driving drunk and killed a father of six; and we saw him get
back together with Carol and patiently wait for her to feel safe
with him again. Part of the reason his renewed relationship with
Carol has been so satisfying to watch is that we've seen the two
weather so much together, with the sort of realism and thoroughness
not often found on TV dramas.
</P>
<P>
   But ``ER'' is in danger of losing some of its valuable realism
and thoroughness this season. The most glaring example was a garish
four-episode plotline involving guest star Mare Winningham as a
woman who passed herself off as a celebrated doctor and became
obsessed with Mark Greene. It belonged in a horror setting, it came
to an abrupt conclusion, and it dangerously resembled a better _
and similarly stunted _ story from last year, in which Greene was
involved with the fragile Cynthia Hooper. This season has also seen
the ill-advised downplaying of Jeannie, the silly coincidence that
has John Carter living in Kerry Weaver's basement, and a
consistently predictable relationship between Carter and student
Lucy Knight. Also, the fraught affair between Peter Benton and
Elizabeth Corday never really came to a head before it ended; it
petered out. There's only so much irresolution that we can chalk up
to the slick verite style of ``ER,'' before it starts to undermine
the show's life.
</P>
<P>
   The recent problems that have befallen Doug Ross, interesting as
they are, also have an inorganic feel to them. For one thing, Ross
hasn't been much of a loose cannon lately, as a result of his
emotional growth in the last two seasons. For him to steal trial
medication, ignore the punishment that forbade him to prescribe
narcotics, take a drug machine from Carol's clinic, and then show
the sick boy's mother how to give a lethal dose of dilaudid on the
machine _ it all seems very Season Three. Also, since Ross has
survived so very many of these mishaps, why is this one suddenly
exploding in his face? So far, Ross's final exit feels a little out
of character and sudden, even though Clooney announced his
intention to leave ``ER'' last March. And, unless there's a
surprise twist in Thursday night's's episode, last week's car-crash
cliffhanger seems rather gratuitous and manipulative.
</P>
<P>
   OK, no show is perfect. Even when it gets sloppy, ``ER'' is
superior drama, with an ensemble of strong actors and filming
techniques that are consistently amazing. Once Clooney is gone,
there are a number of well-drawn characters who could stand some
new emphasis. That's partly why NBC is downplaying Clooney's
departure: It doesn't want the show to look like damaged goods when
it still has so much promise. Let's hope that, just as the
declining ``NYPD Blue'' has made something positive from Jimmy
Smits's absence, ``ER'' turns Thursday night's's sad farewell into
a happy opportunity.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
