<SLUG> BC-OBITUARY-MCMAHON-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THOMAS A. MCMAHON, 55; INVENTED `TUNED' RUNNING TRACK 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (a and s coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By TOM LONG  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   A memorial service will be held Friday for Thomas A. McMahon, a
biology professor at Harvard University who invented the ``tuned''
running track, explained how the South American ``Jesus Christ
Lizard'' appears to walk on water, and shared his enthusiasm for
science in several well-received novels.
</P>
<P>
   Mr. McMahon died Sunday in his home in Wellesley, Mass., where
he was recovering from surgery. He was 55.
</P>
<P>
   An authority on the physics of animal locomotion, Mr. McMahon
and his colleague Peter R. Greene designed the ``tuned'' running
track at Harvard's Gordon Indoor Track and Tennis facility that has
improved running times by about 3 percent while cutting injuries in
half.
</P>
<P>
   The unusually soft and springy ``tuned tracks'' were also
installed at Yale University, the Meadowlands Arena in New Jersey,
and Madison Square Garden in New York City. When the Madison Square
Garden track was first used, 12 events were held and 11 resulted in
record times.
</P>
<P>
   Three years ago, Mr. McMahon and graduate student James Glasheen
gained wide notice for experiments demonstrating how the basilisk
lizard, a Central and South American creature sometimes known as
the ``Jesus Christ Lizard,'' scampers across rivers fast enough to
``walk on water.''
</P>
<P>
   His 1987 novel ``Loving Little Egypt,'' about a nearly blind
genius who tapped long-distance phone lines to create an
underground network through which the blind could communicate, was
hailed by Globe reviewer Robert Taylor as a ``technological fable
crackling with the elation, nostalgia and suspense of scientific
discovery.''
</P>
<P>
   The book won the American Academy of Arts and Letters' Rosenthal
Award. Mr. McMahon was also the author of the ``Principles of
American Nuclear Chemistry: A Novel'' and ``McKay's Bees.''
</P>
<P>
   In a profile published in The Boston Globe on April 19, 1987, he
explained why he used scientists as his protagonists in his novels.
``I think that there are stories in the lives of scientists just as
there are everywhere. Relationships among people are the substance
of fiction and really nothing else. Most of the time you get
stories about police, undergraduates and English professors.
Science has stories at least as good as those.''
</P>
<P>
   ``People turn on lights, use telephones and other inventions
every day,'' he said in a story published in the Harvard Gazette on
Oct. 11, 1993. ``But they know little about the inventors or the
circumstances that gave birth to these conveniences. I enjoy
weaving such elements into fictional stories that inform people and
divert them from their everyday cares.''
</P>
<P>
   He was born in Dayton, Ohio, and raised in Lexington. He
graduated from Cornell University and earned a master's degree and
doctorate at Massachusetts Institute of Technology.
</P>
<P>
   He leaves his wife, Carol (Ehlers); a son, James R. of Atlanta;
a daughter, Elizabeth Kirsten McMahon; two sisters, Jean Humez of
Somerville and Nancy McMahon Swanborn of Duxbury; and a
granddaughter.
</P>
<P>
   The memorial service will be held at 2 p.m. at Story Chapel at
Mt. Auburn Cemetery in Cambridge, Mass.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-17-99 1824EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990217.0315 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-17 18:24 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9144 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MEADOW-DANCE-REVIEW-A     02-17 0874
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEADOW-DANCE-REVIEW-ART-400&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FROM GRAHAM, VIA JUNG, A JOURNEY THROUGH AN EROTIC LANDSCAPE 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036.) 
(lh) 
 By ANNA KISSELGOFF   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ More than most of Martha Graham's works, ``Dark
Meadow'' is one of those dances meant to be sensed rather than
understood.
</P>
<P>
   To borrow a line from former Sen. Dale Bumpers, ``It's about
sex.''
</P>
<P>
   But sex is always part of the grander scheme of things in
Graham. The nameless heroine in search of a sexual awakening amid
Isamu Noguchi's overtly phallic sculptures at the Joyce Theater
this week will also be in quest of rebirth and life's mysteries.
</P>
<P>
   Created in 1946 to a commissioned score by Carlos Chavez and
revived on Tuesday night by the Martha Graham Dance Company, ``Dark
Meadow'' is a great but difficult work. It contains some of
Graham's most beautiful ensemble choreography, for a chorus of
archaic lovers who amplify the heroine's own search.
</P>
<P>
   Terese Capucilli as the archetypal female offered a wonderful
lyrical performance in a delicate role that makes her look
deceptively passive. ``Dark Meadow'' itself is a delicate work. It
would be easy to reduce the action to boy meets girl with a
matchmaker involved. But Graham, a student of Jung rather than
Freud, gives us something else: her own version of Jung's
collective unconscious.
</P>
<P>
   The encounter between the woman and the embodiment of a male
principle, hurried along by an earth mother priestess, is
meaningful to us precisely because Graham is dealing in archetypes.
One might even say that the sexual symbolism, in decor and images,
might look too obvious. But if the worship of the lingam, the
phallic symbol derived from the adoration of the Hindu god Siva, is
clear, the specific details on view would require a scholarly
treatise.
</P>
<P>
   These specifics are as usual open to interpretation. The title
comes from Empedocles: the dark meadow of Ate is where the soul
fell from the region of light.
</P>
<P>
   Graham said that she was not depicting a ritual, but the success
of ``Dark Meadow'' lies in its ritualistic cast. As Noguchi's three
green branches sprout out of a tall knifelike form in the rear, the
action resolves into a ceremony of rebirth.
</P>
<P>
   You don't have to reread your Greeks and your Jung to see that
something happens onstage each time that Katherine Crockett, in a
tight brown sheath with a crown of leaves, passes by. As She of the
Ground, she is deliberately limited in her movement by her costume.
Statuesque, treelike, angular and serene even in the strange
squatting walk she is given at one point, Ms. Crockett is striking
as the earth mother catalyst.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Ms. Capucilli is One Who Seeks, and she is initially surrounded
by five women in sarongs and bare midriffs. Their stamping evokes
the aim of all fertility rituals: to make the crops grow.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Capucilli's natural dynamic is toward the angular. But
Graham's choreography here is not percussive, and there is an
impressive flow to Ms. Capucilli's movement. Martin Lofsnes, as He
Who Summons, is the initiator. Graham's interest in ancestral
memory is suggested in her primeval imagery. Lofsnes' costume, with
its pleated tails, implies that he is still a human in evolution,
and the black cloth Ms. Capucilli manipulates may look awkward but
it also suggests a cave of memory.
</P>
<P>
   Lofsnes, in his best performance to date, has a breathtaking
dynamic power in a role that has more flexed feet and archaic
profiles than complexity. Together, he and Ms. Capucilli brought
their final duet to a full boil of intensity.
</P>
<P>
   Although this is not strictly one of her ``Greek'' pieces,
Graham makes use of a chorus that amplifies the action. The imagery
is tender for the lovers and full of sculptural embraces. Yet it is
also resonant of the abduction scenes of antiquity. You will get
the point when Ms. Crockett, in a green cape, embraces a yellow
phallic form and flowers bloom. But you will also have the same
sense of fulfillment when the couples embrace.
</P>
<P>
   Admirably precise in their alignment, these dancers included
Elizabeth Auclair, Theresa Da Silva, Jennifer DePalo, Sandra
Kaufmann, Virginie Mecene, Alessandra Prosperi, Ariel Bonilla,
Tadej Brdnik, Daniel Cardoso, Gary Galbraith and Christophe
Jeannot.
</P>
<P>
   Sexual initiation was treated with more extreme metaphors on the
same program in ``Errand into the Maze.'' Miki Orihara made a fine
role debut as the Theseus-Ariadne figure. She looked dazed rather
than tormented, offering a less powerful image than others but also
less convulsive and all the more persuasive. Galbraith's bull
figure, stronger than ever, had a new dramatic edge.
</P>
<P>
   Beginning its final week of the season at the Joyce, the Graham
company was in top form. Joyce Herring brought to the figure of the
Virgin in ``Primitive Mysteries'' power and concentration that made
a difference. She has a human warmth and earthy grandeur.
</P>
<P>
   The program was completed by ``Acts of Light,'' in which Peter
Roel and Ms. Auclair did not shy away from the eroticism of the
first section.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-17-99 1824EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990217.0316 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-17 18:26 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9146 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-OBITUARY-MCMAHON-BOS &LR;      02-17 0547
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OBITUARY-MCMAHON-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THOMAS A. MCMAHON, 55; INVENTED `TUNED' RUNNING TRACK 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (a and s coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By TOM LONG  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
