<SLUG> BC-KURD-TURKEY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TURKEY EXULTS IN KURD'S CAPTURE AND VOWS A FAIR TRIAL 
</HEADLINE>
  (With KURD-EUROPE) 
(bl) 
 By STEPHEN KINZER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   ISTANBUL, Turkey _ Jubilation enveloped Turkey on Wednesday
after the capture of the country's most-wanted fugitive, Kurdish
rebel leader Abdullah Ocalan, but debate over his trial has already
begun to turn bitter.
</P>
<P>
   A team of Ocalan's lawyers was denied entry into the country
Wednesday, and the government said it would not permit foreign
observers at his trial.
</P>
<P>
   Foreign leaders and human rights groups issued a stream of
statements urging Turkey to give Ocalan a chance to defend himself
fully. Several Turkish commentators said the trial could prove a
crucial test of Turkey's much-criticized judicial system.
</P>
<P>
   Ocalan was captured late Monday night in Kenya, where he had
been living clandestinely under the protection of Greek diplomats.
Turkish commandos brought him to Turkey before dawn Tuesday, and he
has been taken to an island prison from which all other inmates are
being evacuated.
</P>
<P>
   The government's determination to continue pursuing Kurdish
guerrillas was made clear Wednesday as an estimated 3,000 Turkish
troops crossed into northern Iraq to attack what officers say are
guerrilla sanctuaries. Turkish troops have carried out such
operations regularly in recent years.
</P>
<P>
   In a televised interview, Prime Minister Bulent Ecevit brushed
aside concerns about Ocalan's trial, which is expected to focus on
a few specific massacres that are said to have been perpetrated by
his Kurdistan Workers Party, or PKK.
</P>
<P>
   ``It will be very free, a very just trial, because justice is
very free in Turkey, autonomous,'' Ecevit said. ``It need not last
too long because all the illegal actions, the crimes of the PKK's
leadership, are well known.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked about his government's refusal to allow Ocalan's lawyers
to enter the country, he replied: ``They want, more or less, to
inspect the Turkish justice system, but they have no right to have
any doubts about it. Also, the Turkish justice system has certain
rules about who can defend.''
</P>
<P>
   A Foreign Ministry spokesman, Sermet Atacanli, later said Turkey
would not allow foreign governments or organizations to send
observers to Ocalan's trial.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is not possible for us to accept actions from outside
Turkey which might be an intervention in the Turkish judicial
process,'' Atacanli said. ``Thus we could not accept such things as
observers.''
</P>
<P>
   Atacanli said the trial would be open to the public, but that
``if people who give themselves legal titles such as observers or
lawyers come to Turkey to behave like an inspector, they will not
be allowed to do that.''
</P>
<P>
   The chief of Ocalan's legal team, Britte Boehler, a German
national who is based in the Netherlands, said after her failed
attempt to enter Turkey that she feared that Ocalan was being
tortured.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are telling Turkey we are on this case and we intend to
stay on it,'' Ms. Boehler told reporters at the Amsterdam airport.
She said the fact that she was not permitted to visit her client
was ``a clear symbol of how the trial would be.''
</P>
<P>
   Turkish newspapers Wednesday published new details about the
commando operation that resulted in Ocalan's capture. Many were
contradictory, however.
</P>
<P>
   Some reported that Greek Embassy officials in Kenya knew they
were sending Ocalan into a trap when they let him be taken to the
Nairobi airport. Others claimed that Kenyans had participated. Many
said the CIA had provided the first tip that Ocalan was in Kenya,
and several said Israeli secret services had provided advice or
other help.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the interest of not disturbing those parties who took part
in this operation,'' Prime Minister Ecevit told one interviewer,
``I will use a local expression and say, `Let us eat the grape and
not ask where it came from.'''
</P>
<P>
   Turkish television stations Wednesday broadcast a video showing
some aspects of the operation. In it, Ocalan is seen being led onto
a small plane, handcuffed and blindfolded. After being handcuffed
to a seat, his blindfold was removed, revealing his sweat-drenched
face.
</P>
<P>
   In what seemed to be a bizarre comment from a figure who has
portrayed himself as a fearless revolutionary, Ocalan is heard to
tell his captors: ``If the truth needs to be told, I love Turkey
and the Turkish nation, and I want to serve it. If I have the
chance, I would be pleased to serve. Let there be no torture or
anything. I would be happy to serve.''
</P>
<P>
   Later, Ocalan was shown being led to a bed, unsteady and
apparently drowsy, as commandos gave each other high-five slaps and
flashed the victory sign.
</P>
<P>
   Statements urging Turkey to guarantee Ocalan good treatment and
a fair trial came from many world capitals Wednesday. The British
government said it would urge that the trial be conducted ``in
strict accordance with the rule of law and due process.''
</P>
<P>
   In Geneva, the chief United Nations investigator for torture,
Sir Nigel Rodley, said: ``Without in any way implying any
conclusion as to the facts of the case, I appeal to the Turkish
authorities for clarification of the circumstances with a view to
insuring that Ocalan's right to physical and mental integrity is
respected.''
</P>
<P>
   Influential Turks made similar appeals. ``This is obviously a
great success in operational terms, but it could also be turned
against Turkey,'' Haluk Sahin, one of the country's most respected
commentators, wrote in a newspaper column. ``Turkey must now prove
to the world that it can give Ocalan a fair trial in keeping with
universal standards of justice and human rights.''
</P>
<P>
   Conflicting impulses seem to be raging in many Turkish hearts
this week. The emotional desire to inflict swift and preferably
excruciating punishment on Ocalan is at war with the realization
that the world will be carefully watching what Turkey does.
</P>
<P>
   Nowhere was the jumble of emotions more visible than among the
mourners at Edirnekapi Sehitligi, an Istanbul cemetery where
soldiers killed in the Kurdish war are buried.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wish they would give him to us so we could torture and kill
him,'' one mourner at the cemetery, Fatma Elkan, said as she wept
at the grave of her son, who was killed in 1993 at the age of 21.
``But I know this is not possible. We have to count on the state to
give him the punishment he deserves.''
</P>
<P>
   Another mourner, Kazim Kalyon, who also lost a son in the war,
said Ocalan ``certainly deserves to be executed, but to protect our
image in the world, we need to give him a fair trial.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I predict that he will be sentenced to death but that the
sentence will be commuted to life imprisonment,'' Kalyon said.
``That might be even worse than dying.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
