<HEADER>
A9167 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CHINA-LOTTERY-ART-NYT     02-17 0931
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHINA-LOTTERY-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHINA'S GOVERNMENT AND PEOPLE DISCOVER THE LURE OF LOTTERIES 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(bl) 
 By ERIK ECKHOLM   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   BEIJING _ As cameras crowded in, the old man wore a grin as wide
as his ears. His thin body was nearly overwhelmed by the giant red
bow someone had draped across his chest.
</P>
<P>
   Hu Muqin, 63, was the third winner the other morning of a
gleaming new $15,000 Citroen _ the top prize in the public
lotteries that Beijing and many other Chinese cities are holding
all this week to raise money for victims of last year's floods.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm so happy,'' said Hu, a retired forestry official. He said
he would give the car to his 30-year-old daughter, who was learning
to drive.
</P>
<P>
   In the two weeks surrounding the lunar New Year, or Spring
Festival as the Chinese call their biggest holiday, ancient temples
resound to drums and lion dances, and trains and buses overflow
with people visiting their relatives.
</P>
<P>
   But nothing has drawn out the people of Beijing like the
lotteries that began last weekend at several parks and vacant lots
around the city, part of a national craze. Hundreds of thousands of
Beijingers have elbowed their way to the long rows of ticket
windows, heeding the giant red signs that say ``Make Your Dreams
Come True'' by buying wads of tickets at 24 cents each.
</P>
<P>
   Buyers get immediate results by scratching their tickets to see
what if anything they have won, and the lotteries are structured,
in the best Las Vegas psychology, to produce an impression of
constant winners.
</P>
<P>
   In the festive throngs around every lottery site a striking
number of people carry boxes of cheap glassware or stainless steel
bowls, items awarded by the hundreds of thousands here this week.
Others, luckier, struggle with microwave ovens, or have hired a
cart to haul their complete home-entertainment systems.
</P>
<P>
   Scratch the surface, and ticket buyers admit to a common
yearning for today's No. 1 prestige possession.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody who comes here has just one goal, to win a car,''
said Ling Xiaoping, a migrant from southern China who mans a street
stall in Beijing.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nothing else is important,'' said Ling, who bought 100
tickets, came up dry and was debating whether to fork out more
cash. ``I can't actually drive a car,'' he said, ``but I'd use it
somehow.''
</P>
<P>
   Two hundred Citroens, which are on display next to the ticket
windows, will be given out in Beijing in the course of the week.
</P>
<P>
   China has been notably unsuccessful at collecting personal
income taxes from its citizens. But, like Western governments, it
has discovered a politically painless way to supplement its
revenues even as it supposedly maintains a general ban on gambling.
</P>
<P>
   What the government calls ``welfare lotteries'' began in 1987,
and in the last few years they have really taken off. Reflecting
the aspirations of a fast-developing consumer culture, the grand
prizes, too, have evolved _ from color televisions to cars.
</P>
<P>
   For the government, the proceeds are significant. According to
the official press, the lotteries scheduled between October 1998
and June 1999 will sell tickets equivalent to $1.20 for every
Chinese. That is close to $1.5 billion _ with half the money
supposed to go for prizes, 20 percent for administration and 30
percent for relief programs of some sort.
</P>
<P>
   By regulation, most of the lotteries keep going until they sell
all of a predetermined number of tickets, usually the scratch-it
kind. But in some places, computer drawings, too, have been
introduced. In Shanghai, huge cash prizes are doled out weekly on a
popular television show.
</P>
<P>
   The rush in Beijing this week appears downright tame compared
with reported scenes in some southern cities, where frenzied hordes
have been reported to snap up millions of dollars worth of tickets
within a day or two.
</P>
<P>
   Some faint voices of concern have appeared in the press. There
was the report of an old woman in Sichuan province who had a fatal
stroke when she heard she had won a big prize. In Jiangsu province,
an elated car-winner had a drunken party, then crashed and died in
his new car that very night.
</P>
<P>
   In another part of Jiangsu, a man who could not afford it
borrowed $120 to play and won nothing. His wife was so distraught,
the papers said, that she killed herself with pesticides.
</P>
<P>
   Last fall in Sichuan, when a lottery was halted, supposedly by
accident, before all the prizes were awarded, buyers went amok,
looting the warehouse and setting banners on fire.
</P>
<P>
   An article this month in People's Daily, the mouthpiece of the
Chinese Communist Party, extolled the welfare lotteries, which by
regulation must be used to help ``the old, the handicapped,
orphaned and hard-up.''
</P>
<P>
   Some people have worried, the article said, that the lotteries
encourage dangerous speculation by people of little means. ``But
the leader of the Welfare Lottery Committee believes this is
unwarranted,'' the article duly reported. ``The reasons are that
China's welfare lotteries are conducted by the government, and the
cost of tickets is kept low.''
</P>
<P>
   In Beijing this week, anyway, there were no visible signs of
sore losers or lottery addicts gambling the clothes off their
backs.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the New Year, so why not try your luck?'' said Zhang
Dafa, 30, as he scratched the last of his 100 tickets without even
winning a set of drinking glasses. ``And anyway, the money goes for
a good cause.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-17-99 1844EST &QL; 
