<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-17 18:44 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9168 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KURD-U.S.-NYT &LR;      02-17 0361
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KURD-U.S.-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
U.S. WARNS AMERICANS ABROAD ABOUT VIOLENCE LINKED TO KURD CAPTURE 
</HEADLINE>
  (See also KURD-EUROPE, KURD-TURKEY) 
(bl) 
 By PHILIP SHENON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The State Department issued a worldwide travel
warning Wednesday and urged Americans to take special security
precautions abroad as a result of this week's violent protests in
Europe over the arrest of the top Kurdish rebel leader.
</P>
<P>
   ``Greek diplomatic missions and personnel have been subjected to
violence and it is possible that this danger may extend to American
interests as well,'' the advisory said. ``Americans traveling or
residing abroad are urged to review their personal security.''
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday, when a wave of violent Kurdish protests swept across
Europe, the department announced that it had stepped up security at
U.S. embassies.
</P>
<P>
   Department officials said they feared that news reports
suggesting U.S. involvement in Turkey's apprehension of Kurdish
rebel leader Abdullah Ocalan would lead to attacks on U.S.
diplomats.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton administration spokesmen have denied that the United
States had any direct involvement in the capture of Ocalan, whose
rebel group has been labeled a terrorist organization by the United
States.
</P>
<P>
   But they have refused to comment on the possibility that the
United States had indirect involvement in the arrest, or on news
reports in Europe suggesting that Israeli intelligence officers
were involved in the arrest. Israel has categorically denied the
reports.
</P>
<P>
   Greek embassies were the initial targets of the protests since
Ocalan had apparently been in hiding at the Greek Embassy in
Nairobi, Kenya, in the hours before his capture in Kenya late
Monday and transfer to Turkey.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have heightened our security posture and alerted Americans
in Turkey and elsewhere of the need for caution,'' said James
Foley, a State Department spokesman.
</P>
<P>
   The State Department travel advisory, which was placed on its
Web site at www.state.gov, also urged Americans traveling or
residing abroad to contact the nearest U.S. embassy or consulate
for the latest information on security threats.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
