<HEADLINE>
WEATHER 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds: The following text accompanies the weather map for Thursday,
Feb. 18, 1999, sent to computer graphics clients of The New York
Times News Service. For information call: 888-603-1036.) 
(rk) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL FORECAST &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Rain will brush the coast from the Carolinas to New England
Thursday as a series of weak low pressure areas move along a front
near the Atlantic Seaboard. A few rumbles of thunder will accompany
the rain in the eastern Carolinas early Thursday. Farther west,
mostly cloudy skies will linger near the Appalachians. Clouds will
yield to some sun as drier air arrives from the eastern Ohio Valley
to the interior Middle Atlantic States.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday will begin with patchy fog in parts of the Tennessee
Valley and southern Appalachians. Otherwise, ample sunshine will
prevail over most of the Southeast as slightly cooler air spreads
over the region. Meanwhile, scattered strong thunderstorms will
erupt in the warm, humid air over southeastern Florida.
</P>
<P>
   A broken area of snow and rain will rapidly develop from the
southern Missouri Valley to the central Mississippi Valley as a
potent jet-stream disturbance moves southeast across these regions.
Vigorous upward motion will cool the air enough to promote
intermittent snow from eastern Nebraska to southern Iowa and
northern Missouri. Showers will develop farther to the south over
Missouri and Arkansas. Later Thursday night, the showers will
expand into the interior Southeast as low pressure gradually
strengthens over the Tennessee Valley.
</P>
<P>
   The latest in a series of fast-moving fronts will cause rain and
mountain snow from northern California to western Washington. The
heaviest rain is expected during the morning and midday when
onshore winds are strongest in northern California and southern
Oregon. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Focus: Iris Blooms
</P>
<P>
   Tropical Storm Iris sprung to life over the Philippine Sea late
Tuesday. Unlike the limited hurricane seasons of the tropical
Atlantic and eastern Pacific basins, the western Pacific never
sleeps. Indeed, tropical storms and typhoons (the name given to
hurricanes west of the International Date Line) have been observed
in the western Pacific during each month of the year. Ceaseless
trade winds blowing over tropical Pacific seas push equatorial
waters westward, forming a thick layer of warm water a few hundred
meters deep that sometimes set the stage for a few tropical storms
in winter. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
