<HEADLINE>
BUSH `WARMING TO THE TASK' OF RUNNING FOR PRESIDENT 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  (Attn: S.C., N.J.) 
(Eds.: Optional trim included) 
 
By R.G. RATCLIFFE 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Gov. George W. Bush responded Wednesday to weeks
of being urged to run for the GOP presidential nomination by
elected officials and political activists from other states,
saying, ``I'm warming to the task.''
</P>
<P>
   While hardly a declaration, Bush's statement marked the first
time that he has said he is inclined toward running.
</P>
<P>
   Up until now, Bush has repeatedly said he is seriously
``interested'' but voiced reservations about taking his wife,
Laura, and twin daughters into the limelight of presidential
politics.
</P>
<P>
   Bush made his comments after meeting privately at the Governor's
Mansion with South Carolina Lt. Gov. Robert L. Peel and three
legislators from New Jersey. The New Jersey lawmakers said they
urged Bush to run for president.
</P>
<P>
   Peel did not speak to the news media, but another South Carolina
politician, House Speaker David H. Wilkins, publicly released a
letter signed by himself and 59 other Republican House members
urging Bush to run for president.
</P>
<P>
   ``George W. Bush best represents the ideals and goals of South
Carolina families,'' Wilkins said in a statement. ``He understands
government should work for the people and not lord over them.''
</P>
<P>
   Wilkins said he would volunteer for Bush's leadership team if he
decides to run. South Carolina has one of the nation's earliest
primaries, currently set for March 4, 2000, and Republicans there
are considering moving the primary into February.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday's meeting marked the second time political leaders
from New Jersey have met with Bush. Senate Majority Whip Diane
Allen and state Sen. John Bennett said they were undecided before
meeting with Bush but now believe he should run.
</P>
<P>
   ``I came down here wanting to listen to what George W. Bush had
to say, to look him in the eye and size him up. I've decided to be
a supporter,'' Allen said.
</P>
<P>
   Alex DeCroce, deputy speaker of the New Jersey assembly, said he
urged Bush to run because he has a proven record of electability.
He said potential Republican presidential candidate Steve Forbes, a
New Jersey resident, has never been elected to an office.
</P>
<P>
   ``Steve Forbes, we don't know if he's electable. We know this
governor's electable,'' DeCroce said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Bush last week received a delegation from Iowa urging him to
run, and he previously received a letter from California Republican
lawmakers promoting his candidacy. About 50 current and former
members of Congress urged him to run last week and he has had a
trail of foreign dignitaries visiting Austin to meet him.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(END OPTIONAL TRIM) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Bush has said he will form an exploratory committee by next
month if he is inclined toward running.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
