A9179 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-VENGEROV-MUSIC-REVIEW     02-17 0444
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VENGEROV-MUSIC-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A YOUNG VIOLINIST'S VIRTUOSITY AND VIGOR 
</HEADLINE>
  (lh) 
 By ALLAN KOZINN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Musical prodigies grow up with lots of eyes on them,
and under pressures that can be as easily crushing as fortifying.
Maxim Vengerov, the violinist, seems to have come through those
demands intact. When he first performed in New York, he was barely
18 and won a large following with his finely polished technique and
interpretive assertiveness.
</P>
<P>
   Now Vengerov is 24, and at his recital at Carnegie Hall on
Tuesday evening it seemed that the characteristics that first drew
attention to his playing remain firmly intact and have in some ways
become magnified. It also seemed, though, that he had not come
fully to terms with at least one corner of the repertory that
eluded him a few years ago.
</P>
<P>
   That corner is where the Brahms sonatas are shelved. Vengerov,
with Alexander Markovich at the piano, opened his concert with the
second of them, the A Major (Op. 100). His reading had its
attractions, not the least being a lovely bloom in his phrasing and
a glowing Elman-like vibrato in the andante tranquillo. Yet the
performance never cohered as more than a sequence of discrete,
passing moments, some beautiful, others nondescript. This made for
a peculiar sense of distance: Vengerov looked passionate about the
work, but that passion registered on the eye more than the ear, and
the ear more than the heart.
</P>
<P>
   Prokofiev, on the other hand, has long been one of Vengerov's
strengths, and in the Sonata No. 1 in F minor (Op. 80) Vengerov and
Markovich played with a relentless, captivating intensity. Vengerov
was fully conversant with the extremes that this work touches _ the
icy beauty of the quicksilver, pianissimo passages that appear in
the first and last movements, the steely power of the Allegro
brusco, and the lushness of the andante _ and he moved easily and
persuasively between them, with Markovich deftly mirroring these
shifts of mood and coloration.
</P>
<P>
   The shorter works on the second half of the program afforded
Vengerov an opportunity to show off the breadth of his palette and
his sheer virtuosity, and if the material was lightweight after the
exertions of the Brahms and Prokofiev, it brought a measure of
pure, vigorous entertainment to the evening. Sarasate's ``Caprice
Basque,'' a work with bags of technical trickery, left Vengerov
unfazed, as did a broken string in Waxman's wild pastiche of
``Carmen'' themes. He also offered an alluringly throaty rending of
Ravel's ``Tzigane'' and a few moments of unalloyed sentimentality
in Rachmaninoff's ``Vocalise.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
