<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    MICROSOFT CLAIMS NETSCAPE FABRICATED CHARGES
 &HT;    Moving in (w) Washington and (f) financial categories.
 &HT;    By ANDREW J. GLASS
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Contrary to the government's claims, Microsoft
Corp. never sought to illegally divide the Internet market with
Netscape, a top Microsoft official asserted in written testimony
made public Wednesday in the landmark antitrust trial.
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft's Daniel Rosen, who helped organize the disputed June
21, 1995 meeting with Netscape Communications Corp., termed the
charges ``fiction, absurd and untrue,'' and said they were ``either
fabrications or the products of a fundamental misunderstanding.''
</P>
<P>
   Rosen's 90 pages of written testimony amount to the most direct
denial to date of the explosive allegations against the world's
largest software firm by James Barksdale, Netscape's chief
executive officer. Barksdale told the court that Microsoft had
proposed at the
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-17-99 1855EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990217.0340 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-17 18:55 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9182 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SOCIAL-SECURITY18-COX     02-17 0576
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOCIAL-SECURITY18-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    CLINTON, REPUBLICANS SKIRMISH OVER SOCIAL SECURITY, TAXES
 &HT;    By LARRY LIPMAN
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ With the impeachment battle behind them, President
Clinton and congressional Republicans skirmished Wednesday over
plans to save Social Security and cut taxes.
</P>
<P>
   In a speech from the White House East Room linked by satellite
to 41 college campuses, Clinton said the choice facing the country
was whether to use projected budget surpluses ``on a terrifically
appealing tax cut'' or to strengthen Social Security and Medicare
by reducing the debt.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans argued that Clinton's proposal would increase the
debt
</P>
<P>
   Clinton said a proposed 10 percent across-the-board income tax
cut proposed by Rep. John Kasich, R-Ohio, chairman of the House
Budget Committee, would ``spend too much of the surplus now and
invest too ... little of it for tomorrow. I believe it would target
the lion's share of the benefits away from the middle class ...
(and) reward consumption over savings.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton has proposed using 62 percent of the anticipated surplus
over 15 years to reduce the debt and earmark the savings for Social
Security. He has proposed using another 15 percent of the surplus
to shore up the Medicare program and using some of the surplus to
provide 401(k)-style individual savings accounts to workers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Their idea sounds simpler, sounds good, even sounds fair _ 10
percent for
</P>
<P>
   everybody,'' Clinton said. ``Our idea will give you a stronger
economy, will save Social Security and Medicare, will stabilize
families, will strengthen the ability of the United States to lead
the world, and will make you feel a whole lot better 15 years from
now.''
</P>
<P>
   Republicans called Clinton's characterization of their position
unfair and his description of his plan inaccurate.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not fair for the president to say it's a choice between
this and a tax cut when the Republicans have said that we would
hold 62 percent of the surplus until Social Security is fixed,''
said Rep. E. Clay Shaw Jr., R-Fla., chairman of the House Social
Security subcommittee.
</P>
<P>
   Shaw noted that Republicans have not fully endorsed the 10
percent tax cut plan.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's John Kasich's position. The Ways and Means Committee
has not signed off on that, and I don't think that would be our
approach,'' Shaw said. ``We hope that there is enough surplus after
we save Social Security so we can give some tax relief, but we
haven't figured out how much that will be, or where it will be, and
we also want to pay down the accumulated national debt.''
</P>
<P>
   Ways and Means Chairman Bill Archer, R-Texas, sent Clinton a
letter noting a Congressional Budget Office prediction that the
administration proposal would require raising the $5.95 trillion
debt ceiling by 2001. Without the proposal, the ceiling would not
be raised until 2009.
</P>
<P>
   The White House has argued that Clinton's proposal would reduce
the ``publicly held'' debt _ the amount the government owes the
public _ but Republicans say it would raise the total national
debt, including what the government owes its trust funds.
</P>
<P>
   ``If your budget proposal were to increase total government debt
by adding large quantities of federal debt to the Social Security
trust funds, our children will be forced to repay this money,''
Archer said.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
