<SLUG> BC-ASH-WEDNESDAY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ASH WEDNESDAY SERVICES GROWING IN POPULARITY
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Mass., Calif., Ill., Mo., Colo.)  (nk) 
 By GUSTAV NIEBUHR   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
  
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ At a midday service at Christ Church United Methodist
in Manhattan, the Rev. Stephen P. Bauman and his associate, the
Rev. Javier A. Viera, invited several dozen people to come toward
the altar. Each clergyman dipped a finger into a small bowl of
ashes and then smudged a cross onto the foreheads of those who came
up the aisle.
</P>
<P>
   Afterward, Dan Domingo, 39, a veterinarian, said, ``It's
preparing ourselves, reflecting on what we've done, and our
relationship with the Lord and with others.''
</P>
<P>
   Ash Wednesday services across the nation announced the start of
Lent, the 40-day period of prayer and penitence that precedes the
celebration of Jesus' resurrection on Easter.
</P>
<P>
   Receiving ashes ``is a sign of our mortality,'' as well as
humility, said Sister Ann Rehrauer, associate director of the U.S.
Catholic Conference's liturgy office. ``One of the phrases with the
imposition of ashes is, `Remember you are dust and to dust you will
return.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Among Roman Catholics, Ash Wednesday Masses typically draw not
only the dedicated, but those who rarely cross a church threshold.
</P>
<P>
   Ash Wednesday is also traditionally marked by Episcopalians and
Lutherans. But it is increasingly important among some other
Protestant churches, where interest in traditional forms of liturgy
has been growing.
</P>
<P>
   Such practices give people a formal means to express belief ``in
a time when so much seems confusing and unstructured,'' said Wes
Granberg-Michaelson, general-secretary of the 185,000-member
Reformed Church in America.
</P>
<P>
   The Rev. Hoyt Hickman, retired director of worship resource
development for the 8.5 million-member United Methodist Church,
said the practice has become common among United Methodists.
</P>
<P>
   ``Very, very few Methodists that I knew of were doing it in the
'50s and '60s,'' he added, ``but it began to grow in the '60s and
'70s.''
</P>
<P>
   It has also grown among Presbyterians. ``Certainly, this has
been a phenomenon of the last 20 years,'' said the Rev. Brad Kent,
an official in the spiritual formation office of the 2.7
million-member Presbyterian Church (U.S.A.).
</P>
<P>
   When he served as a minister in Kansas City, Mo., a decade ago,
Kent said his church began holding Ash Wednesday services with
three other congregations _ one Methodist, one Disciples of Christ
and one United Church of Christ.
</P>
<P>
   Churchgoers interviewed around the country Wednesday spoke of
finding various meanings in the beginning of Lent.
</P>
<P>
   At St. James Episcopal Church in Los Angeles, Cesar Vega, 28, an
air-conditioning technician, said he was returning to church for
the first time in 15 years. ``It's been a long time, I've forgotten
most everything, but it feels good,'' he said. ``Your spirit gets a
little clean.''
</P>
<P>
   In Chicago, Maria Evola, 37, a Catholic, said Ash Wednesday ``is
about a renewing of faith and a reminding of what is the practicing
of faith on a day-to-day basis.''
</P>
<P>
   Outside the Episcopal Cathedral Church of St. Paul in Boston,
Gail Brazil, 51, a senior operations clerk at a bank, said Lent is
one of the most important times of the year, as it prompts her to
examine her spiritual life.
</P>
<P>
   ``Instead of giving up something I'll take something on, whether
it's taking 15 minutes a day and saying I am go to meditate,'' she
said.
</P>
<P>
   At St. Paul's Lutheran Church in Denver, the Rev. Steve Swanson
said he has noticed an increase in recent years in the number of
people with ashes on their foreheads. ``People want to participate
in their religion, not just observe it,'' he said. ``Lent is a
journey, and I think people _ young people especially _ don't want
to just observe others practicing.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
