<HEADLINE>
BURNS TO REJOIN REVOLUTION 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By FRANK DELL'APA  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Defender Mike Burns will rejoin the Revolution after
signing a multiyear contract with Major League Soccer, the team
announced Wednesday. Burns, who tried out for three teams in
Europe, will join training camp in Italy Monday.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some compromises were made on both parts, and I have no
problem with the contract,'' Burns said. ``I always said I wanted
to start and end my pro career here. I tried a couple of things,
but my heart was always here. It was just part of the process. I'm
in a good frame of mind to go into the season, and I don't have bad
feelings toward the league or the Revolution.''
</P>
<P>
   Burns, of Marlborough, Mass., has captained the Revolution in 79
games over three seasons.
</P>
<P>
   The Revolution have 24 players on the roster and must cut to 22
by March 1. They opened their exhibition season Wednesday with a
1-1 tie against Prato.
</P>
<P>
   Giovanni Savarese scored in his first game for the Revolution,
on a rebound after Imad Baba set up Joe-Max Moore for a close-range
shot in the 15th minute.
</P>
<P>
   Walter Zenga played 30 minutes in goal, and the Revolution
surrendered the tying score 30 seconds after he was replaced by
Jeff Causey. Cosimo Mobile scored on a corner kick for Prato, which
is in seventh place in Italy's Serie C2A with a 9-6-8 record.
</P>
<P>
   The Revolution will meet Carrarese of Serie C1 in Carrara
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Lynne Meterparel, former director of crowd building for the
Revolution, was named general manager of the San Jose Clash. At 30,
she is the youngest GM in the MLS. Revolution owners Robert and
Jonathan Kraft purchased the Clash last month.
</P>
</TEXT>
