<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-CAMBY-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CAMBY NAMED IN BREACH-OF-CONTRACT SUIT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOE BURRIS  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Former University of Massachusetts basketball star Marcus Camby
probably regrets the day he became acquainted with would-be sports
agents seeking to represent him at the NBA level. Three years after
forgoing his final year of college eligibility to go pro and
admitting to taking money and gifts from would-be agents, Camby is
still being asked to answer for his transgressions.
</P>
<P>
   John Lounsbury, who claims he and Camby made an oral agreement
of reprsentation after he spent $40,000 in gifts luring the former
national player of the year, filed a breach-of-contract lawsuit
last month against Camby (now with the New York Knicks) and his
agents, ProServ Inc.
</P>
<P>
   Lounsbury says Camby demanded money and gifts, including rental
cars and jewelry, between October 1994 and April 1996 in exchange
for a promise that Camby would hire Lounsbury as his agent once
Camby turned pro.
</P>
<P>
   In June 1996, UMass alerted the NCAA that Camby, who was chosen
by Toronto with the No. 2 pick in the '96 NBA draft, may have
committed violations by accepting cash and jewelry from agents,
including Lounsbury.
</P>
<P>
   Camby, who was traded by Toronto to the Knicks before this
season, said he accepted thousands of dollars from Lounsbury in
1995 and two necklaces and a diamond pendant from Wesley Spears, a
Hartford lawyer.
</P>
<P>
   UMass was stripped of its 1996 NCAA regional championship and
was forced to return the money it earned by making it to the Final
Four of the NCAA tournament.
</P>
<P>
   In December 1997, Lounsbury agreed not to act as a sports agent
for five years. That agreement with the Connecticut Department of
Consumer Protection stemmed from his purchase of airline tickets
for two University of Connecticut players, Ricky Moore and Kirk
King.
</P>
<P>
   Lounsbury's lawyer, John Williams, said Wednesday Lounsbury
sought his services last year. Williams said he decided to take on
the civil suit against Camby after reading a November New York
Times article that he said praised Camby while vilifying Lounsbury.
</P>
<P>
   ``It said that John was a pimp. It was like it had been written
by (Camby's) publicist,'' said Williams. ``I have always
represented little guys being screwed over by big guys, and I
firmly believe that this happens to be just that. John Lounsbury
was a starry-eyed wannabe crushed by some big guys, so I took on
the case to hope to even things up a bit.''
</P>
<P>
   The new development came as a shock to Camby's agent, James
Bryant, who said ProServ reached a settlement with Lounsbury three
years ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``I guess in America you can always find an attorney that will
take any case,'' said Byrant. ``It's incredible because it was
three years ago and this is the first person in NCAA history to
ever get his money back in a settlement. We paid him his money back
for any influence he tried to have over Marcus Camby.
</P>
<P>
   ``Usually, when someone breaks the NCAA rules, they go away
quietly, and if they get paid they go away even quieter. Camby
settled this three years ago, and if (Lounsbury's) attorney doesn't
know that, he will be sued for malpractice and sanctioned by a
judge.''
</P>
<P>
   When asked if he knew of the settlement, Williams said, ``I'm
not aware of any court documents, but I am aware of news accounts
and a letter that says ProServ paid a portion of what John
Lounsbury had laid out, and it was only a portion.
</P>
<P>
   ``They claimed it was to save him from loan sharks. They are
entitled to get credit for that, but I don't believe it was a
settlement. If they have a different view, it will be litigated and
whoever wins wins.''
</P>
<P>
   Alex Johnson, vice president of ProServ Basketball, said he has
received documents naming the agency in a suit by Lounsbury twice
in the past two years.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every now and then we get papers with John looking for more
money,'' Johnson said, ``and that's not going to happen. But I
think this time he's found a law firm willing to go all the way.
Anyone who has done their research knows the suit has no grounds,
but they think it does so we'll see them in court.''
</P>
<P>
   Williams said the case will be heard in Waterbury, Conn. ``Such
cases in Waterbury take four years from the return date (of the
suit) to the trial date,'' he added. ``My client is not happy about
(the four-year wait) but he doesn't have any choice.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
