<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STATES-SENS-PA </SLUG>

 &HT;        THE VERDICT IS IN: SPECTER AND SANTORUM BOMBARDED WITH
RESPONSE TO IMPEACHMENT VOTES   By Lisa Fine  
 &HT;    c. 1999 States News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON, Feb. 17 -- When Sen. Arlen Specter invoked Scottish
law and voted ``not proven, therefore not guilty'' in President
Clinton's impeachment trial last week, there was a pause of hushed
murmuring on the Senate floor.
</P>
<P>
   But the response since then from residents of Pennsylvania and
around the nation has been deafening.
</P>
<P>
   From calls for Specter's resignation to cries of ``Why don't you
move to Scotland,'' E-mail letter writers from both parties
expressed surprise and confusion about the Pennsylvania
Republican's unique verdict.
</P>
<P>
   Mark Andersen, of Rapid City, South Dakota sent a one word
letter to the senator: ``Why???''
</P>
<P>
   Specter spokesman John Ullyot said he had no comment about the
remarks made in the letters, but said Specter planned to respond to
``as many of them as he can.''
</P>
<P>
   Specter's office refused to release the number of calls and
letters received after the Senate voted Friday to acquit Clinton on
obstruction of justice and perjury charges. Ullyot declined to
characterize the response from constituents to Specter's ``not
proven'' verdict.
</P>
<P>
   ``We do not have a day to day breakdown of the responses
received,'' said Ullyot. ``We have heard from thousands of people
since the trial began. Sen. Specter believes it is time for the
Senate to move on to more pressing issues.''
</P>
<P>
   But more than one thousand authors of e-mail letters who sent
their correspondence to Specter through a nonpartisan political
website, www.senatevote.com, agreed also to post them publicly.
</P>
<P>
   Many letter writers lambasted Specter's use of Scottish
precedent, which he said allows jurors three choices for a verdict:
guilty, not guilty or not proven.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hey Specter!!! HELLOOOOOO. We don't live in Scotland, or
hadn't you heard? And you were a prosecutor??? If it weren't so
sad, it would be funny. I'm disgusted,'' wrote D. Kopsa, of New
Jersey.
</P>
<P>
   Art Stetson, of Chicago, wrote, ``I think you look good in
Kilts. You have nothing to hide under them.''
</P>
<P>
   Calling it a ``sham trial,'' Specter said last week the House
impeachment managers' ability to prove the charges was hindered
because the Senate wouldn't allow live witness testimony. He also
said he thought there was a lack of relevant evidence.
</P>
<P>
   When he announced his intentions, Specter said he knew there was
a risk of angering both sides of the political spectrum.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've done that before,'' he said and laughed. Other letter
writers praised Specter for not attacking Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   ``Thank you for wrapping up this silly thing called an
impeachment, it was really a witch hunt,'' wrote Tom Brian, of
Osceola, Pennsylvania.
</P>
<P>
   Several letter writers said they thought Specter's position was
cowardly.
</P>
<P>
   ``What a spineless wonder you are,'' wrote Sonja R. Hassinger,
of Milton Pennsylvania. ``You are a coward without a conscience.
There was plenty of proof and evidence. I am sorry I ever pulled
the lever below your name and believe me I will never vote for you
again.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Sen. Rick Santorum's office received several hundred
phone calls, letters and faxes, mostly lauding his expected votes
of ``guilty'' on the perjury and obstruction of justice charges,
according to his spokesman.
</P>
<P>
   ``The calls were 98 percent favorable,'' said Robert Traynham, a
Santorum spokesman. ``They were very proud of their senator.''
</P>
<P>
   But the more than 1,000 letters posted on the website to
Santorum, R-Pa., reflected a slightly more mixed reaction.
</P>
<P>
   ``Thank you for your brave and honest votes on the impeachment
measures,'' wrote Patricia Kottke, of Fogelsville, Pennsylvania.
</P>
<P>
   Others weren't so happy.
</P>
<P>
   ``Senator, you sold out to the right wing zealots you think will
help elect you in 2000,'' wrote Scott T. Redman, of Springdale,
Pennsylvania. ``You won't have my vote.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
