A9207 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-PAKISTAN-EXECUTE-BOS &LR;      02-17 0770
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PAKISTAN-EXECUTE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PAKISTANI MILITARY COURTS RULED UNCONSTITUTIONAL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By INDIRA A.R. LAKSHMANAN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ISLAMABAD, Pakistan _ Pakistan's Supreme Court ruled Wednesday
that special military courts and their recent executions of two men
were unconstitutional, scoring a victory for an independent
judiciary.
</P>
<P>
   The military courts were established last December in the port
town of Karachi to combat violence and were run by military
officers, not judges. The courts were under the command of the
federal government, and decisions could not be appealed to civilian
courts.
</P>
<P>
   Two men have been hanged by the courts, and a 13-year-old boy
was ordered to die for murder, but he was later acquitted.
</P>
<P>
   Civil rights advocates hailed the unanimous court ruling, saying
it upholds the independence of Pakistan's judiciary, and blocks the
government's attempt to create a ``parallel justice system'' run by
the army that was not answerable to the Supreme Court. The decision
also spares 14 people facing death sentences ordered by the
now-illegal courts.
</P>
<P>
   Opposition leaders also praised the decision, saying it knocks
down a government effort to centralize power and limit rights.
Besides establishing military courts, Prime Minister Nawaz Sharif's
government is lobbying for ``sharia,'' or Islamic law. It was
recently accused of attacking press freedom by withholding
newsprint and serving crippling tax notices on a newspaper chain
that did not obey demands to fire critical journalists.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a humiliating defeat for the government,'' said Aitzaz
Ahsan, the lead attorney who argued against military courts, and
Senate president of the opposition Pakistan People's Party. ``The
government wanted to employ courts subordinate to itself to
victimize its political opponents.''
</P>
<P>
   Some independent lawyers disagreed, however, saying that even
though military courts were the wrong answer, the government's
intention was to suppress spiraling lawlessness, not peaceful
political dissent.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is totally wrong to say it was directed against political
opponents,'' said Muhammad Bilal, chairman of the international
relations committee of the Pakistan Bar Council. ``Constitutionally
it's hard to support'' military courts, ``but with crime so bad, it
may have seemed necessary.''
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday's ruling nullifies the military courts and transfers
their cases to special antiterrorism courts the government created
in 1997, but which remain under the Supreme Court. The Supreme
Court instructed antiterrorism courts to decide cases and appeals
within seven days, and called on the military to assist by
protecting witnesses or conducting investigations if needed.
</P>
<P>
   The government had argued that military courts were needed,
because other courts were not acting quickly enough. The government
also said crime dropped in Karachi after the courts were
established. They were under orders to decide cases within three
days. That was later extended to eight days.
</P>
<P>
   Political and sectarian murders in Karachi are estimated to have
hit 1,000 annually over the last three years. Battles are being
waged in Karachi between rival factions of the Muttaheda Qami
Movement, a small ethnic political party. Tensions also run high
between Urdu-speaking Muttaheda Qami Movement loyalists who came to
Karachi after partition from India and indigenous Sindhi-speakers.
</P>
<P>
   The ruling should end ``efforts to solve political problems
through instant justice, short-circuiting due process,'' said I.A.
Rehman, director of the Human Rights Commission of Pakistan.
</P>
<P>
   By dispensing summary justice, the government was ignoring the
need to reform the police, the investigative process and judiciary
itself, he added.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever their faults, military courts were preferable to
government-sponsored killings, some lawyers noted. ``Under Benazir
Bhutto, the government dealt with crime by killing suspects during
so-called investigations,'' said Raja Imran Aziz, a High Court
advocate in Rawalpindi, echoing a complaint by human rights
activists about the former prime minister.
</P>
<P>
   Attorney General Mohammad Chaudhry Farooq said in an interview
that he did not consider the ruling a loss, because the Supreme
Court had shored up the resources and responsibilities of the
antiterrorism courts.
</P>
<P>
   ``As I see it, the Supreme Court has undertaken the
responsibility to insure terrorism is eliminated in this country,
and people involved in terrorism are suitably dealt with,'' Farooq
said. ``I don't see any element of defeat.''
</P>
</TEXT>
