</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AMR-PILOTS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AMERICAN, PILOTS DISPUTE COSTS OF SICKOUT 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By MATTHEW L. WALD   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   American Airlines presented its bill for damages to a U.S.
District Court judge in Dallas Wednesday, contending that its
revenues fell $58.7 million short of projections while the
airline's pilots continued their sickout in defiance of the judge's
order.
</P>
<P>
   The Allied Pilots Association, which has already put $10 million
on deposit with the court, questioned the accounting and asked for
three months to analyze it. The judge, Joe Kendall, gave the union
until April 12.
</P>
<P>
   The union also agreed to an extension of the judge's temporary
restraining order against the sickout until May 10, with a hearing
scheduled for May 8 on whether that should be turned into a
permanent injunction.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the two parties continued negotiations on the
underlying issue: how pilots should be paid while American _ a
subsidiary of AMR Corp. _ integrates into its system Reno Air,
which it bought in December. Both sides said they were making some
progress on peripheral issues, but none at all on the union's main
demand that pay scales should be adjusted retroactive to Dec. 23.
</P>
<P>
   Kendall, who also demanded a $10,000 check from the union's
president, scolded him in court. ``I meant what I said, when I said
you would pay for what you broke,'' the judge said.
</P>
<P>
   The union has about $38 million in assets, counting the $10
million already on deposit.
</P>
<P>
   Richard LaVoy, the union president, said, ``We're going to
examine their methodology. It wasn't intuitive the way they did
it.''
</P>
<P>
   LaVoy said he suspected that the airline canceled the least
profitable flights. American said it canceled about 6,600 flights
during the 10-day dispute. More than half those flights were
canceled during the three and a half days after the judge ordered
the pilots who called in sick to go back to work, but before most
of them did so.
</P>
<P>
   The airline said it had not included extra overtime costs and
that its estimate was ``conservative.''
</P>
<P>
   Under the Railway Labor Act, which governs American's
relationship with the union, the dispute could end up in mediation
or arbitration. LaVoy said the union's intention was to reach a
negotiated settlement, but he complained that as far as its demand
that American should have immediately integrated the pilot lists,
at least for pay purposes, ``they don't even want to discuss it.''
</P>
<P>
   Christopher Chiames, a spokesman for American, replied that such
an instant integration had ``never been done before.'' If the union
could dictate such terms, he said, ``that would essentially
eliminate our ability to pursue another transaction in the future,
should there be consolidation in the industry.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-17-99 1913EST &QL; 
