A9212 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TEXAS-LOBBYIST-HNS &LR;      02-17 0466
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEXAS-LOBBYIST-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TEXAS LAWMAKERS SEEK LOBBYIST FOR MILITARY AFFAIRS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By LAURA TOLLEY  
 c.1999 San Antonio Express-News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ In an effort to keep military installations in
Texas, two lawmakers on Wednesday proposed hiring a lobbyist in
Washington to keep track of defense-related issues for the state.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Carlos Truan, D-Corpus Christi, and Rep. Judy Hawley,
D-Portland, proposed legislation that would hire the lobbyist and
expand the responsibilities of the state's Office of Defense
Affairs to make it the focal point for coordinating all matters
that affect the defense community in Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Lawmakers are seeking $20 million over the next two years to pay
for the legislation, including the lobbying effort.
</P>
<P>
   Hawley said Texas needs a lobbyist in Washington to make sure
the state gets the most updated information about issues involving
the military and defense industry. The idea is to help Texas
communities avoid additional base closings.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our objective is to make sure all the communities that have
military interests in Texas are as competitive as they can possible
be when we're looking at (future) BRAC closures and that we are as
militarily aware as possible we can be,'' she said, referring to
the Base Closure and Realignment Commission, commonly known as
BRAC.
</P>
<P>
   Hawley said the military industry is worth some $37 billion to
the state's economy.
</P>
<P>
   ``You would do anything to attract an industry that size to your
state,'' Hawley said. ``It's a very, very huge part of our economic
development in the state of Texas.''
</P>
<P>
   State Reps. Ruth Jones McClendon and Juan Solis, both Democrats
of San Antonio, expressed support for the legislation at a news
conference Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``I remember all too well being in city council on June 12,
1995, when we heard about the first round of closures (involving)
Kelly Air Force Base,'' Solis said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We moved and acted immediately. But if we had had this
organization in place it would have been a lot different, I think.
We would have been better prepared, and I believe we would have
transitioned faster,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's important that we start to think together as a
state,'' Solis said. ``In the past we made decisions in San Antonio
for ourselves, but we should no longer think like that but rather
as a whole state. I think the message has to be sent to Washington
that we're not ready to sacrifice our industry or our military
readiness for a few savings.''
</P>
<P>
   Solis said the money would fund efforts to keep existing
military installations, pay for the lobbyist and help fund some
transitional programs for communities affected by base closings.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is more like preventive medicine,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
