<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IMMIGRATION-0218-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    INS TO HIRE 1,600 NEW AGENTS, INSPECTORS
 &HT;    By SUE SCHULTZ
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Days after a congressman called for her dismissal,
Immigration and Naturalization Services Commissioner Doris Meissner
announced Wednesday 1,600 new border patrol agents and immigration
inspectors will be hired throughout the nation.
</P>
<P>
   INS plans to increase the number of border agents and inspectors
to handle a rise in the number of immigrants. The new positions are
part of the $3.9 billion INS budget that went into effect Oct. 1.
</P>
<P>
   ``With these deployments, the INS will continue to make great
strides in enforcing U.S. borders,'' Meissner said, later adding
that she does not plan to resign. ``The Clinton Administration is
committed to continued strengthening of our enforcement
operations.''
</P>
<P>
   Just Thursday, Rep. Lamar Smith, a Republican from Texas, and
chairman of the House Immigration subcommittee, sent a letter to
U.S. Attorney General Janet Reno criticizing the INS's performance
and asking that Meissner be replaced if changes aren't made
quickly.
</P>
<P>
   In the Feb. 11 letter, Smith chided INS officials after reading
a newspaper article that said INS planned to release undocumented
immigrants with criminal records.
</P>
<P>
   ``In our view, a top priority of the INS should be the strict
enforcement of the laws pertaining to criminal aliens,'' Smith said
in the letter. ``If the INS fails in this critical mission, it is
endangering the safety of countless citizens throughout the United
States.''
</P>
<P>
   Meissner on Wednesday said the INS had not released any
undocumented immigrants with criminal records and is still
considering what to do with the criminal immigrants in their
custody.
</P>
<P>
   Under the proposal Meissner discussed Wednesday, the INS will
add:
</P>
<P>
   1,000 new border patrol agents, mostly to the southwest border.
Texas will receive 485 agents, Arizona 395, California 83, and New
Mexico 15. Another 22 agents will be sent to three locations along
the U.S.-Canadian border.
</P>
<P>
   100 new immigration inspectors to airports within the U.S. and
overseas affected by high immigrant traffic. The INS hopes the new
additions will cut passenger processing time to under 45 minutes.
Atlanta and Miami are among the airports targeted to receive new
inspectors.
</P>
<P>
   300 immigration workers to INS Service centers to reduce the
backlog of citizenship applications in Chicago, Los Angeles, Miami,
New York City, San Francisco, Boston, Dallas and Houston. The
current process to become a U.S. citizen takes 15 months, but the
increased positions should help reduce the time to six months,
Meissner said.
</P>
<P>
   ``These 300 new positions dedicated to the citizenship caseload
will help deliver better customer service to our nation's legal
immigrants,'' Meissner said.
</P>
<P>
   90 detention and deportation employees to manage 400 new beds at
Port Isabel, Texas, and 11 new workers to support an increase of
126 juvenile beds.
</P>
<P>
   In the fall, Congress approved $171 million for the INS
naturalization program. The INS also plans to use an additional $5
million to transfer paper records to electronic databases.
</P>
<P>
   While Smith did not rescind his request for Meissner's
dismissal, he welcomed the new jobs Wednesday, saying the proposal
fulfilled a congressional priority: ``I am hopeful that now the
agency will focus on fixing its mismanagement of handling criminal
aliens to make the best use of its budget.''
</P>
<P>
   endit
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
