<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-17 19:27 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9224 &Cx1f; kan-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NUKES-TESTING-2NDTAKE     02-17 0733
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NUKES-TESTING-2NDTAKE-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
   
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ form and fit?''
</P>
<P>
   At Lawrence Livermore's National Ignition Facility, money is
being spent to use 192 lasers to explore the feasibility of pure
fusion.
</P>
<P>
   Some call the program ``gold-plated.''
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of people know that the Stockpile Stewardship may well
be over-funded, but they're biting their tongues because they like
the (testing) moratorium,'' said Michael Krepon, president of the
arms-researching Henry L. Stimson Center in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   ``This test ban treaty is so important that a lot of people, me
included, are willing to get out the wallets,'' Krepon said. Hawks
insist that Stockpile Stewardship is simply the labs' reward for
forsaking testing.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's an out-and-out bribe,'' said Frank Gaffney, the director
of the Center for Security Policy. ``The only hope that the
administration has is if the labs continue to stay bought. If
anybody speaks up, this treaty is toast.''
</P>
<P>
   Doves, on the other hand, oppose the plan because it keeps the
nuclear weapons assembly line in place and gives designers new
tools _ the supercomputers and laser device _ that will tempt them
to make the next generation of thermonuclear monsters.
</P>
<P>
   ``You don't need weapons designers,'' said Hisham Zerriffi, a
project scientist at the Institute for Energy and Environmental
Research. ``All you need is engineers who can replace the old
parts.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're setting up some sort of virtual arms race....Some
country is going to go back to the old way of building more weapons
out of fear of falling too far behind.''
</P>
<P>
   The conservative and liberal critics converge on their criticism
of the science on which the program relies.
</P>
<P>
   For decades, America maintained a mastery over its nuclear
weapons with continued refinements that were always double-checked
with test explosions, turning desert sand to glass, obliterating
Pacific atolls and finally moving underground in Nevada.
</P>
<P>
   An intercontinental ballistic missile, for instance, might be
plucked randomly from its silo. The missile might be fired at a
benign ocean target after the warhead was taken out. The warhead
would be dissected to figure out how its steels, aluminums and
ceramics had aged, then reassembled and detonated at the Nevada
Test Site.
</P>
<P>
   All those warhead checks continue under the Stockpile
Stewardship Program, except for the underground explosions.
</P>
<P>
   Critics note that while the weapons are not new, some of their
parts are. The parts are made differently today because, for
instance, the methods used at the defunct Rocky Flats nuclear
trigger factory were environmental disasters. That and age cause
subtle variations.
</P>
<P>
   ``The science is pretty good for the next week, the next year or
the next month,'' said Baker Spring, a national security analyst
for the Heritage Foundation. ``The issue is whether it's going to
be good 10 years from now.''
</P>
<P>
   Some doves advocate scrapping weapons when signs of decay
appear.
</P>
<P>
   ``The danger is that you will make changes that create an
inoperable weapon or a more volatile weapon,'' said Ray Kidder, a
retired physicist who designed nuclear weapons at Lawrence
Livermore.
</P>
<P>
   Such criticism underestimates the value of the tools at the
disposal of the weapons labs, defenders of the program say.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can test them just fine in the computer,'' said Michael
Hynes, a physicist with nuclear testing experience who studies
research and development management for the Rand Corp. think tank.
</P>
<P>
   ``From all I've talked (about) with my designer friends, there's
about 99 percent confidence that the computers will be able to do
the job.''
</P>
<P>
   But even Reis at the Energy Department conceded that no one can
be absolutely certain it will work.
</P>
<P>
   He noted, however, that even live tests in the past didn't
simulate all the factors that a warhead would face in combat.
Instead of launching an armed missile from its silo into suborbital
flight to see whether it would destroy a target thousands of miles
away, for instance, the elements of the weapons were tested
separately.
</P>
<P>
   That did not prompt a wave of concern that America's nukes might
be unreliable, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't know the limits of virtual world testing...'' Reis
conceded. But he added: ``We think the fixes will be something we
can understand.''
</P>
</TEXT>
