<HEADLINE>
NEW NOTES, DOMINO DELAYED AGAIN, LOTUS SAYS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By HIAWATHA BRAY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Release of the new version of Lotus Development Corp.'s flagship
Notes and Domino software has been delayed again because of bugs in
the product.
</P>
<P>
   The delay contradicts a pledge at last month's Lotusphere trade
show, where Lotus CEO Jeff Papows promised to have the software
ready this month. Instead, the product, called Version R5, won't
ship until the end of March.
</P>
<P>
   ``It has resulted from the realization that there were more bugs
to fix,'' said Lotus spokesman Paul Labelle. Trial versions of
Version R5 have been distributed to thousands of corporate computer
administrators, said Labelle, and they found some unexpected
problems which must be repaired before shipping. Labelle said that
Notes and Domino should achieve ``virtual zero bug status'' next
week, meaning it should be free of all serious bugs. It will then
take several more weeks to produce copies for shipment to
customers.
</P>
<P>
   Version R5 of Notes and Domino are seen as vital for the future
of Lotus, a Cambridge, Mass. subsidiary of IBM Corp. Notes and
Domino are the leading brands of ``groupware,'' software that runs
on powerful server computers to help large groups of workers
collaborate on projects. Rival software company Microsoft Corp. has
launched an aggressive campaign to win this market with its own
groupware product, called Exchange.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's something to be said for delaying the release just to
ensure a better-performing product,'' said Mike Comiskey,
collaborative computing analyst at International Data Corp. in
Framingham, Mass.. ``I don't think that's going to be that
significant.''
</P>
<P>
   But some customers aren't pleased. Rushi Shah, system
administrator for a nonprofit agency in McLean, Va., thinks Lotus
knew all along that the product would be late, and should have told
customers sooner. ``All this could have been avoided if they'd just
said it's going to be out at the end of March,'' said Shah. ``I've
got a server that's on order and it's going to be sitting there for
a month doing nothing.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-17-99 1927EST &QL; 
