<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-17 19:28 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9227 &Cx1f; kan-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NUKES-TESTING-2TAKES-     02-17 0999
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NUKES-TESTING-2TAKES-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UNCERTAINTY SURROUNDS `VIRTUAL' TESTS OF AGING NUKES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SCOTT CANON  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ A third of a billion dollars pours into
Kansas City's AlliedSignal plant yearly to ponder explosive
riddles:
</P>
<P>
   What does time do to the fuse of a B61-7 warhead? How does the
passing of years in a North Dakota missile silo affect the radar of
a nuclear weapon made in the Johnson administration?
</P>
<P>
   If they were uncorked on a future enemy, would they be duds? Or
worse, could they blow on their own?
</P>
<P>
   Experience suggests no problems. Decades of exploding America's
nukes in tests hints only at reliability, however horrific.
</P>
<P>
   But those real-world tests have stopped. And one of the new
questions is whether the chaos of a nuclear explosion can be
captured in even the world's most dazzling computers.
</P>
<P>
   The so-called Stockpile Stewardship Program is a $4.5 billion
annual gamble that it can. The program _ an amalgam of scientists,
engineers, supercomputers and lasers scattered across the country _
hopes to find out what old age does to The Bomb.
</P>
<P>
   Few would quibble with the need to constantly check that the
nuclear stockpile is in working order, to replace parts made
brittle by heat, moisture and the passing of time.
</P>
<P>
   But hawks and doves alike are edgy about what they see as the
country's new half-in, half-out approach to the nuclear weapons
business. They argue that in its desire to win Senate ratification
of a key arms treaty, the Clinton administration settled on a plan
that invites dangerously bad science.
</P>
<P>
   ``Virtual'' detonations in a supercomputer cannot replace the
real thing, they argue.
</P>
<P>
   ``The danger here is that they will make a mistake somewhere
along the line and the computer won't catch it,'' said Jonathan
Katz, a physicist who consults for the Defense Department on
nuclear weapons.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nature is more clever than scientists,'' Katz said. ``Without
experiments, you always get it wrong.''
</P>
<P>
   The administration defends Stockpile Stewardship as the least
risky way for America to deal with its nuclear weapons now that the
arms race has been won.
</P>
<P>
   First, its defenders say the program clears the way for _ is, in
fact, vital to _ the nation's ratification of the Comprehensive
Test Ban Treaty.
</P>
<P>
   Next, the administration says that critics underestimate the
power of teaming past underground testing data with savvy
scientists and computing power undreamed of just a few years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, officials stress that if those scientists begin to feel
uneasy about vouching for the weapons, the president would withdraw
from the test ban treaty and that the secretaries of energy and
defense could effectively yank the plug on the computer modeling
system if they lost confidence in it.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, the Nevada Test Site, the proving ground for America's
warheads, is kept in working order so underground testing could
resume on short notice.
</P>
<P>
   ``You've made, in a sense, the health of the stockpile a supreme
national interest,'' said Victor Reis, the Energy Department's
assistant secretary for defense programs. ``We believe it's working
now and that it will continue to work.''
The last underground nuclear test _ code-named ``Divider'' and
described by the Department of Defense only as ``less than 20
kilotons'' _ took place Sept. 23, 1992.
</P>
<P>
   The next year, the new energy secretary, Hazel O'Leary, held a
two-day meeting in Washington to discuss the Comprehensive Test Ban
Treaty. She called together much of America's nuclear brain trust _
from the Pentagon, from the Energy Department, from the Los Alamos,
Lawrence Livermore and Sandia national laboratories.
</P>
<P>
   The directors of the weapons labs had the most at stake, but
perhaps the strongest trump card.
</P>
<P>
   The labs risked losing what had been their mission for the
previous half-century _ the design and manufacture of nuclear
warheads.
</P>
<P>
   If the lab directors publicly opposed the test ban, the Joint
Chiefs of Staff would follow. The joint chiefs' opposition, in
turn, would doom the treaty in the U.S. Senate, where ratification
is still pending.
</P>
<P>
   Frank von Hippel, who was then assistant director for national
security in the White House Office of Science and Technology, said
the labs were offered Stockpile Stewardship. The plan promised a
continued payroll, and the kind of high-tech goodies needed to
tempt bright young minds to work on nuclear weapons.
</P>
<P>
   ``The deal between the Clinton administration and the weapons
labs was that the weapons labs would only support a test ban if
they were given as much money for not testing the weapons as they
got for testing them,'' said von Hippel, who teaches physics at
Princeton.
</P>
<P>
   Supporters of the new approach don't recall such an explicit
bargain.
</P>
<P>
   ``(O'Leary) asked the laboratory people there, specifically,
could they maintain the stockpile basically without testing,''
recalled Reis, who is in charge of the Energy Department's nuclear
warhead monitoring.
</P>
<P>
   ``Their reaction was...`we would certainly give it a try,' but
that it might very well cost more money.''
</P>
<P>
   Stockpile Stewardship outfits the labs with the world's fastest
computers. A computer capable of modeling a nuclear detonation is
due to crank up by 2004, when about half the country's physicists
with nuclear testing experience will have retired.
</P>
<P>
   Already in Kansas City, a smaller but still brawny supercomputer
is solving manufacturing problems that had frustrated engineers for
years.
</P>
<P>
   The AlliedSignal work force in Kansas City is down by about a
fourth, to about 3,000, since 1997, but the supercomputer delivered
in November gives the engineers here an unrivaled tool for solving
manufacturing problems.
</P>
<P>
   ``We might use the computer to study what happens if you move a
part,'' said Gayle Brace, a manager at the plant. ``Does it improve
the weapon system's reliability? What does it do to form and fit?''
MORE
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-17-99 1928EST &QL; 
