<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-17 19:29 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9228 &Cx1f; kan-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CITY-COMEBACK-KAN &LR;      02-17 0689
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CITY-COMEBACK-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KANSAS CITY, LIKE RUST BELT CITIES, ENJOYING A COMEBACK 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JEFFREY SPIVAK  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ For a long time, no city wanted to be
associated with the ``Rust Belt,'' identified for decades with some
of the nation's worst economic and demographic trends.
</P>
<P>
   But Kansas City finds the Rust Belt pretty good company
following a report from the U.S. Census Bureau that says Rust Belt
cities are ``comeback cities.''
</P>
<P>
   Unemployment is down. Welfare is down. Crime is down.
Construction is up. And population is up or stable.
</P>
<P>
   ``It sounds like Kansas City to me,'' said Frank Lenk, director
of research services for the Mid-America Regional Council, which
tracks the Kansas City area's performance.
</P>
<P>
   While the census report didn't include Kansas City because of a
statistical quirk, one of the bureau's chief analysts said this
region fit into the Rust Belt peripherally and fit with its
recovery generally.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're similar in what they're going through in the '90s,''
said Glenn King, chief of the census statistical branch that put
out Tuesday's study.
</P>
<P>
   The statistics from the census' recent State and Metropolitan
Area Data Book show Kansas City has:
</P>
<P>
   A population growth rate that is one-third higher than the
1980s, including a projected increase in the city of Kansas City
for the first time since the 1950s.
</P>
<P>
   A pace of housing construction that by 1997 already surpassed
the 1980s in terms of total building permit units.
</P>
<P>
   A 43-percent plunge in welfare recipients on the Missouri side
since 1993 and a 41-percent plunge on the Kansas side since 1996.
</P>
<P>
   A decline by nearly one-quarter in the unemployment rate between
1990 and 1996, and last year the state of Missouri reported the
lowest jobless rate for this area since records were first kept in
1974.
</P>
<P>
   A one-third drop in total violent crime within Kansas City
itself, whose crime rate dwarfs that of the suburbs, since
killings, rapes, assaults and the like peaked in 1992.
</P>
<P>
   Kansas City resident Yvette Johnson has lived the turnaround.
</P>
<P>
   Soon after the start of this decade, Johnson returned to her
hometown, pregnant with her fourth child. She quit the working
world and went on welfare. She relied on government assistance for
roughly seven years.
</P>
<P>
   When her youngest child reached school age, she decided to sign
up for job training classes and landed a spot at Sprint Corp.'s
long-distance call center in the 18th and Vine historic district.
</P>
<P>
   ``It feels good not to sit home all day doing nothing,'' Johnson
said Tuesday. ``My children are happy and I'm happy and we can pay
our bills now.''
</P>
<P>
   The Rust Belt has no formal boundary. It's typically thought to
stretch from Pennsylvania into Missouri. Cities known for steel and
auto plants such as Pittsburgh, Cleveland, Detroit, Chicago and St.
Louis all lost manufacturing jobs during the 1970s, the 1980s and
the first three years of this decade.
</P>
<P>
   So did Kansas City. At the end of the 1980s, with the closing of
General Motors' Leeds assembly plant, Kansas City relinquished its
long-held national perch at No. 3 in automobile assembly.
</P>
<P>
   In the new Rust Belt report, the Census Bureau looked at those
regions that had reversed both population declines and economic
downturns. Kansas City missed making the list because its
metro-area population never stopped growing, unlike its city
population.
</P>
<P>
   The report highlighted Detroit, Cleveland and Louisville among
major metro areas. Detroit has experienced nearly a 5 percent
population increase this decade after falling 2 percent in the
'80s.
</P>
<P>
   The Rust Belt comeback, the census report observed, has resulted
from today's economic boom and the economic shift from
goods-related jobs to services. The boom has helped the entire
nation. The Rust Belt, for instance, still trails southern Sun Belt
regions in most performance indicators.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're tracking with the national economy now,'' the Census
Bureau's King said of the Rust Belt, ``when they had lagged behind
the national economy in the '80s.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
