<SLUG> BC-SAFRICA-BIKO-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BIKO FAMILY STILL DOESN'T KNOW DETAILS OF FATAL INJURIES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KURT SHILLINGER  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   JOHANNESBURG _ After two inquests and more than 20 years of
waiting, the family of Stephen Bantu Biko still does not know the
truth of how the antiapartheid activist received the injuries that
killed him.
</P>
<P>
   But for his widow and two sons, the decision late Tuesday night
to deny amnesty to the former Security Branch policemen who
interrogated him in the days before his death in detention came as
a welcome step forward in their search for justice. For the first
time the police version of what happened _ an explanation accepted
by a magistrate in 1977 even though it failed to square with
forensic evidence _ has been officially rejected as false by South
Africa's Truth and Reconciliation Commission .
</P>
<P>
   ``There is emotional satisfaction for the Biko family and the
world at large in having it known that the police lied then and
they lied now,'' said George Bizos, the Bikos' lawyer during during
both the Commission's hearings and 1977 probes.
</P>
<P>
   The question is what happens now. The decision not to grant
amnesty to Biko's police interrogators provides the first
high-profile test for South Africa's experiment in reconciliation.
Because the case is so prominent, analysts say, how the legal
community follows up on it will affect the public's willingness to
lay the past to rest.
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutors are now reviewing the case, but seem skeptical about
the possibility of a conviction.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are going to have to make a study of the whole issue. It's
quite a complex one, working out whether we have a case to
prosecute or not,'' said Les Roberts, top prosecutor for the
Eastern Cape Province, where the case would be tried. ``Our options
are murder or nothing.''
</P>
<P>
   For most of the last three years, the truth commission enticed
the perpetrators of apartheid violence to come clean about their
actions in exchange for immunity from prosecution. That trade-off,
it was hoped, would yield the most complete record possible of how
the white minority protected its power. The amnesty provision was
internationally unprecedented, and implied specific social costs.
It meant that many victims would see their aggressors go free for
the sake of national unity. It also meant that perpetrators who
failed to participate fully in the national catharsis could be
punished.
</P>
<P>
   More than 7,000 people applied for amnesty. The criteria for
approval was straightfoward. Applicants had to make full
disclosures. They also had to prove that their actions were
politically motivated and that circumstances justified the manner
in which they were carried out.
</P>
<P>
   The commission concluded its work except for the amnesty cases
last year. As it issues judgments on individual applications, it is
uncertain that those who have been denied amnesty will be brought
to court. By law, evidence brought before the commission cannot be
used in subsequent criminal prosecutions. Other factors, including
age, health, and the amount of time that has lapsed since the act
was committed could influence a decision not to take a case
forward. And given the potential post-commission caseload, the
national prosecutor's office has for the most part drawn a line at
murder: lesser crimes won't be considered.
</P>
<P>
   Biko's case runs into most of these obstacles. Arrested a
healthy man in August 1977, the charismatic leader of the Black
Consciousness Movement died of severe head injuries three weeks
later, chained and naked on the floor of a prison cell. At the
inquest that year, the interrogating officers claimed Biko lost his
balance during a scuffle and hit his head against the wall.
</P>
<P>
   They did not change their testimony significantly during the
hearings in 1997 and 1998. The panel denied amnesty for four of the
applicants Tuesday on the basis that they did not make full
disclosures about what happened. Their version of events did not
explain the forensic evidence. The fifth officer was denied amnesty
in December for the same reason.
</P>
<P>
   The family wants to prosecute the four surviving officers (a
fifth died late last year). That may not be possible since a
20-year statute of limitations has lapsed, thereby limiting the
kind of charges they can pursue.
</P>
<P>
   Bizos doubts a murder charge could be won. He hopes, however,
that prosecutors will follow the only other option _ what South
African law calls ``constructive intent to murder,'' a lesser
charge that carries up to 15 years in prison.
</P>
<P>
   The family's lawyer says there is more than sufficient evidence
to convict on that count.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
