<HEADLINE>
SIEMENS UNIT EXPECTED TO BUY SWITCHING DEVELOPER ARGON 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RONALD ROSENBERG  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Siemens AG, the German electronics and telecommunications giant,
is expected to acquire Argon Networks Inc. of Littleton, Mass., a
two-year-old developer of data switches, for $240 million,
according to several sources familiar with the Siemens' plans.
</P>
<P>
   A formal announcement is expected the week of March 8.
</P>
<P>
   Siemens is purchasing privately held Argon in order to enter the
next generation of voice and data networking. The German company,
which is a major supplier of voice equipment, wants to become a
major player in providing equipment and services for data and
Internet communications.
</P>
<P>
   With a goal of competing against North American heavyweights
such as Lucent Technologies Inc., Cisco Systems Inc. and Northern
Telecomm, Siemens is also looking beyond privately-held Argon to
acquire three or four other small telecommunications companies.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Grady, Argon president, declined to confirm or deny the
Siemens acquisition, which has been rumored for more than six
months. However, some of Argon's 70 employees were informed of the
deal on Monday, the Globe has learned.
</P>
<P>
   Grady founded Argon in February 1997 along with Steven Willis,
Argon's chief technology officer. Willis previously was a cofounder
of Wellfleet Communications, which became part of Bay Networks of
California. Their goal was to develop a high-speed data switch,
called a terabit router, that could simultaneously move Internet
traffic and corporate data, along with new video and voice
services, very quickly and efficiently.
</P>
<P>
   To fund Argon's product development, the company has received
$34 million in venture capital funds led by Matrix Partners, North
Bridge Venture Partners, Greylock Management and Sigma Partners.
</P>
<P>
   Under the pending Siemens deal, Argon's private investors will
receive $200 million. Most of the $200 million who go to venture
capitalists who will earn nearly six times their investment in two
years. The rest of the $200 million will go to the founders and
employees. An additional $40 million will be paid in stages to
Argon employees.
</P>
<P>
   ``The price tag is good for Argon's equity holders, but still
reasonable given that Siemens is buying a company at its early
stage,'' said Paul Johnson, a senior telecommunications analyst at
BankBoston/Robertson Stephens ``But Siemens is competing against
very established players like Lucent, which made a string of much
bigger telecom equipment acquisitions recently, and Cisco, the
leader in the data switching and networking space. So I am in the
camp that thinks Siemens might be too late.''
</P>
<P>
   A spokesman for Siemens Information and Technology Inc., based
in Boca Raton, Fla., which markets telephone switching and wireless
equipment in the United States and Canada, declined to confirm or
deny the Argon deal. However, he cited a recent speech by Siemens
top executives that the company, which had revenues of $66 billion
last year, is looking to move into the converging voice and data
networking markets through acquistions and joint partnerships.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
