<SLUG> BC-SCANA-NCUTILITY18-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    SCANA makes key N.C. acquisition
 &HT;    By Matthew C. Quinn
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ SCANA Corp. said Wednesday its $900 million
acquisition of a natural gas utility in North Carolina will nearly
double its customer base, and as a result will boost its Georgia
natural gas marketing business.
</P>
<P>
   The South Carolina-based electric and gas utility announced it
will buy Public Service Co. of North Carolina, which supplies
natural gas to the fast-growing Research Triangle area, for $900
million in stock, cash and assumed debt.
</P>
<P>
   The acquisition would make SCANA the second-largest natural gas
utility in the Southeast, after Atlanta Gas Light Co., with 760,000
customers in three contiguous states.
</P>
<P>
   Roger Schrum, a spokesman for the company, said the acquisition
will bring ``critical mass'' to SCANA's Georgia gas marketing
business. SCANA is widely acknowledged as the market leader after
three months of deregulation. ``The ability to provide gas more
efficiently for a larger customer base allows us to be more
competitive,'' Schrum said.
</P>
<P>
   SCANA's energy marketing subsidiary claims a 45 percent share of
the Georgia market, with about 175,000 customers. Georgia start-up
costs accounted for most of the company's $11 million in
fourth-quarter 1998 losses.
</P>
<P>
   SCANA's largest subsidiary, South Carolina Electric &AMP; Gas Co.,
has 257,000 customers for gas and 517,000 for electricity in South
Carolina. Public Service Co. would add 340,000 gas customers.
</P>
<P>
   SCANA has opposed opening its South Carolina utility market to
outside competitors, but has aggressively pursued Georgia's
competitive market. The North Carolina acquisition would position
the company to compete in the sale of electricity with
Raleigh-based Carolina Power &AMP; Light if and when North Carolina's
utility markets are deregulated.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
