<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MA-BUDGET-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CELLUCCI WOULD SPEND SURPLUS ON ROADS, BRIDGES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By THOMAS C. PALMER JR.  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ The Cellucci administration Wednesday proposed spending
almost the entire 1999 state budget surplus, which could be $300
million or more, on roads and bridges.
</P>
<P>
   And not on the Big Dig.
</P>
<P>
   To be sure, the $10.8 billion Central Artery/Ted Williams Tunnel
project will continue to get the billions of dollars it needs. But
that huge job, combined with a 40 percent cut in federal highway
funds to Massachusetts over the next several years, has put non-Big
Dig transportation projects and repairs in jeopardy.
</P>
<P>
   So transportation and state finance officials Wednesday rolled
out a plan to spend a minimum of $80 million, and maybe upward of
$300 million, to get more than 100 backlogged construction projects
rolling.
</P>
<P>
   ``Out on the street _ this construction season,'' said
transportation secretary Kevin J. Sullivan. ``By June or July.''
</P>
<P>
   It's possible that a huge surplus won't materialize, rendering
the construction plan moot. Also, the highway plan will have to be
approved by the Legislature.
</P>
<P>
   At the moment, though, administration officials are still
predicting a big budget surplus when the books are closed four
months from now, and they contend it makes sense to use the money
the neglected projects.
</P>
<P>
   Administration and Finance secretary Fred Laskey said devoting
almost the entire surplus to transportation needs would not affect
Governor Paul Cellucci's pledge to cut taxes. About $1 billion in
tax cuts has been built into budgets in each of the two years, 1999
and 2000, Laskey said, even before the surplus is taken into
account.
</P>
<P>
   Asked Wednesday whether there will be anything left of the 1999
surplus for tax cuts, Cellucci said, ``We don't know yet, because
we don't know what that surplus will be. But we do need to address
this shortfall in federal revenue'' for highways.
</P>
<P>
   Unofficial predictions say the surplus could go as high as $700
million, which would greatly increase the chances Legislators would
earmark $300 million for roads because it would leave some money
for other purposes.
</P>
<P>
   At the end of 1998, the state had a surplus of about $800
million, state finance officials said, though several hundred
million of that has now been spent.
</P>
<P>
   Cellucci said his ``number one priority'' was still cutting the
income tax back to five percent, which is provided for in the 2000
budget. After that reduction goes into effect, any annual budget
surplus could be reduced or eliminated, so officials are not
counting on surpluses to fund transportaion needs after 1999.
</P>
<P>
   One finance official said the state would spend ``the
overwhelming majority'' of any 1999 surplus on transportation, up
to $300 million or more, reactivating more than 100 projects from
Acton to Yarmouth that have been on hold because of cash drawers
emptied by the Big Dig megaproject.
</P>
<P>
   Laskey and Sullivan said the plan would allow the state to spend
a total of $600 million or so a year on non-Big Dig projects
through 2003.
</P>
<P>
   That is about the same amount that has been spent over the last
several years, though the officials acknowledged that the share
that goes to cities and towns _ as opposed to highway work on
interstates for example _ would be reduced.
</P>
<P>
   The Cellucci administration appears to have accepted the advice
of some legislators, including the cochairmen of the transportation
committee, who both in recent weeks have urged that a goodly
portion of the surplus be devoted to crumbling bridges and potholed
roads throughout the state.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's clear the state needs to step up to the plate to fund the
gap,'' said secretary Sullivan.
</P>
<P>
   Representative Joseph C. Sullivan (D-Braintree), cochair of the
Legislature's transportation committee, offered praise and caution.
``The governor is listening to the Legislature and recognizing
there's a need to jumpstart a number of projects,'' Sullivan said,
adding that highway spending is a good idea because it generates
economic activity.
</P>
<P>
   However, Sullivan said that cities and towns may not be getting
enough money under the ratio proposed Wednesday by the Cellucci
administration.
</P>
<P>
   Cellucci's proposed annual spending through 2003 would allocate
about $500 million to state projects and $100 million to cities and
towns. Rep. Sullivan noted that in the last two years communities
had received about $150 million, and legislators may want to
maintain that level.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think a reduction in the amount is something we'd be
looking to do,'' he said. Sullivan added that the Cellucci proposal
is not unlike one that the Legislature proposed in the fall _ and
the governor vetoed.
</P>
<P>
   ``He called it $200 million in `unnecessary expenditures,' ''
Sullivan said. ``Today it's `the way to go.'
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not going to kick a gift horse in the mouth, but I'm going
to be like Ronald Reagan. I'm going to trust but verify.''
</P>
<P>
   David C. Soule, executive director of the Metropolitan Area
Planning Council, echoed Sullivan's concerns about a shrinking
program for cities and towns. But he said getting the 100-plus
construction projects that are on hold moving would be very
welcome.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our local officials have been very frustrated,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Transportation secretary Sullivan said the state has made huge
progress since 1990 in improving roads and bridges. The amount of
pavement that is not in good condition has been reduced from 64 to
22 percent of the state's 2,900 miles of roads, he said.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, the number of structurally deficient bridges has
been dropped from 864 in 1991 to 598, a 31 percent decline.
</P>
<P>
   ``The public has seen a quantifiable benefit,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the administration Wednesday filed a $6 billion state
transportation bond bill, which if passed will provide funds for
Big Dig and other work. It would also restructure the finances of
the debt-ridden MBTA.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Tina Cassidy of the Globe Staff contributed to this article.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
