<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BIZMAGS18-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Internet trading raises question about future of stockbrokers
 &HT;    By Tom Walker
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ With billions of dollars flowing into stock index
funds, thousands of computer owners engaging in day trading and an
Internet full of research, who needs a stockbroker any more?
</P>
<P>
   Business Week (Feb. 22) makes a case that technology is causing
seismic waves that will eventually change the way Wall Street does
business.
</P>
<P>
   ``Thanks to two phenomena born of cheap computing _ indexing and
the Internet _ investors are standing Wall Street on its head by
cutting out the middleman and taking control of their portfolios,''
the magazine says.
</P>
<P>
   And it doesn't stop with trading. It reaches into money
management, or the advice part of the business.
</P>
<P>
   Separately, Business Week notes the Internet also is having a
major impact on the economy, boosting growth but also creating
fresh risks, some of which are still unclear.
</P>
<P>
   LOOKING FOR AN ADVANTAGE
</P>
<P>
   With a bull this old and stock prices this high, cautious
investors are always looking for some new ways to get into the game
and win. The business press is there to help:
</P>
<P>
   _ Money (March) suggests investors go ``against the grain'' in
their stock picking. Sometimes called contrarian investing, the
idea is to look for investments among out-of-favor stocks on the
theory that great investors win by going where others don't.
</P>
<P>
   Oil, steel and aluminum, real estate investment trusts and
utilities are among the industry groups in which these future
winners may be found.
</P>
<P>
   Money cites several stocks that fit this criterion: Halliburton
(ticker symbol HAL), Steel Dynamics (STLD), Alcoa (AA), Teco Energy
(TE) and Peoples Energy (PGL).
</P>
<P>
   _ Smart Money (March), meanwhile, looks at Wall Street's hottest
stocks and suggests that ``it's not too late'' to buy them, despite
their high prices.
</P>
<P>
   You just have to wait until they come down in price for one
reason or another, which they always do sooner or later.
</P>
<P>
   Smart Money identifies some of these stocks and calculates a
share price at which they would be good buys.
</P>
<P>
   America Online (AOL) may be out of reach at the current $153,
but would be a buy at $86, the magazine says.
</P>
<P>
   Some others are: Cisco System (CSCO), now $97.12 1/2, and a buy
at $80; Dell Computer (DELL), $81.63 3/4 and $50; General Electric
(GE), $99.31 1/4 and $85, and IBM (IBM), $170.50 and $120.
</P>
<P>
   _ Kiplinger's Personal Finance Magazine (March) says the biggest
mistake investors make in choosing a mutual fund is not to match
the fund with some specific goal, or objective _ saving for
retirement, college for the kids, a new house.
</P>
<P>
   The magazine says there are rules of thumb anybody can follow to
get it right, and makes recommendations as to which funds meet
those goals. The magazine also looks at the top 500 funds.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
