<SLUG> BC-BLACK-BUYPOWER18-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Black buying power takes healthy jump to $392 billion
 &HT;    By Shelia M. Poole
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Barry Corker is typical of many middle-class blacks.
</P>
<P>
   His income is rising and so is his spending, said Corker, a
financial consultant with Merrill Lynch Inc. in Buckhead.
</P>
<P>
   Overall, black buying power _ money from salaries and wages _
rose to $392 billion in 1997 from $367 billion a year earlier,
according to the fifth annual report on the buying power of blacks,
released Wednesday by Chicago-based Target Market News. In Atlanta,
black buying power reached $4 billion in 1997, up from $3.6
billion.
</P>
<P>
   ``Because of the nation's strong economy, African-American
consumers are continuing to purchase at a brisk rate,'' said Ken
Smikle, president of Target Market News. The emphasis, however, is
shifting away from big-ticket products for the home and toward
personal items, according to the survey.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm spending more mainly because of my business and because
the kids are into so many outside activities like baseball,'' said
Corker, a father of five.
</P>
<P>
   Blacks spent the most _ $104.8 billion _ on housing and related
charges, the survey said. But the biggest increases were for
personal care services and online access to the Internet. Internet
spending, for example, was up sixfold to $60 million in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   Such purchases indicate that African-Americans still feel
``confident about the economy and their personal financial
status,'' said Smikle. Among the biggest economic winners were
black women, he said, whose presence in the work force grew by 2
percent, vs. less than 1 percent for black men.
</P>
<P>
   Target Market News based its findings on analysis of data from
the U.S. departments of Commerce and Labor.
</P>
<P>
   Companies use figures on black buying power to gauge market
potential, said Tomikea Flowers, an assistant media planner for the
Atlanta office of Burrell Communications Group, whose clients
include Procter &AMP; Gamble and McDonalds.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of companies are learning how to direct advertising
toward African-Americans,'' she said. ``The purchasing power of
African-Americans is essential.''
</P>
<P>
   A similar study on black buying power is done by the University
of Georgia's Selig Center for Economic Growth. In the most recent
UGA study, blacks are expected to spend $30.37 billion in Georgia
this year and $532.67 billion nationally.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
