</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HARBINGER18-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Software maker Harbinger pins hopes on business-to-business
e-commerce
 &HT;    By Michael E. Kanell
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Four months after laying off 10 percent of its work
force, Harbinger Corp. executives on Wednesday announced a sweeping
new Internet strategy and predicted solid revenue growth.
</P>
<P>
   The Atlanta-based software company in March will formally launch
an Internet portal, a site that will provide information about
electronic commerce, offer service help to Harbinger customers and,
most importantly, let companies do business with each other.
</P>
<P>
   ``I believe these are probably the most important announcements
that our company has ever made,'' said C. Tycho Howle, Harbinger
chairman and chief executive officer.
</P>
<P>
   Well-known consumer portals like Yahoo!, Lycos and Excite offer
a range of information, as well as ways for users to shop and chat.
With companies increasingly using Internet technology to transmit
information, Harbinger is betting it can build a brand name by
tailoring a portal to electronic commerce for businesses.
</P>
<P>
   Harbinger has always specialized in electronic commerce. The
Internet site is designed to handle orders between two companies,
creating records of the transaction at each, Howle said.
</P>
<P>
   To stay ahead of the technology needed, Harbinger Labs has been
established as a unit within the company. It has about 20 people
but will grow to 30 this year, taking about 25 percent of the
company's research and development budget, Howle said. ``Everybody
wants to connect up with their trading partners. It turns out this
is not so easy to do.''
</P>
<P>
   Harbinger is toying with several ways to make money from the
site. Unlike consumer portals such as Yahoo!, mass advertising
seems an unlikely source of revenue for Harbinger. Instead,
Harbinger may charge for each transaction or possibly offer
``subscriptions'' to companies that use the service regularly.
</P>
<P>
   But, like Yahoo!, much of the site will be free.
</P>
<P>
   Companies in electronic commerce will grow an average of 30
percent a year for the next three years, Howle said. ``We expect to
grow faster than our industry, not only in the year 2000 and beyond
but in 1999.''
</P>
<P>
   In a dramatic effort at a turnaround, Harbinger in October
eliminated 110 jobs.
</P>
<P>
   The company finished the year with $135 million in revenues, but
the October changes included elimination of products that account
for about $18 million in annual revenue. Chief Financial Officer
Joel Katz predicted Wednesday that Harbinger will end this year
with more than $130 million in revenue and grow to $185 million in
revenue in 2000.
</P>
<P>
   Harbinger grew at a healthy clip from 1989 to 1997, running into
trouble after making a series of acquisitions. Company focus has
returned, Howle said. ``I believe those challenges are now behind
us. We are now one Harbinger _ we weren't one Harbinger in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
