<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-17 19:51 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9264 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-OCALAN-DEATHS-BOS &LR;      02-17 1368
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OCALAN-DEATHS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SHOOTINGS HEIGHTEN TENSIONS OVER KURDISH LEADER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By COLUM LYNCH AND JONATHAN GORVETT S  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNITED NATIONS _ Israeli security guards Wednesday shot and
killed three Kurdish demonstrators who stormed the Israel embassy
in Berlin. In all, 14 were injuring in the melee, which heightened
tensions in Europe following the capture of rebel leader Abdullah
Ocalan.
</P>
<P>
   Israel's Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu, claiming his forces
acted in self-defense, voiced regret at the loss of life and
ordered the closure of all Israel's European embassies as a
security precaution. Fearing more reprisals by Kurdish protesters,
Kenya closed all of its embassies around the world.
</P>
<P>
   The Kurds' decision to target the Israeli embassy reflected the
growing skepticism by Ocalan's supporters over Israeli and American
denials that they played a role in his capture Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   In the first image of the Kurdish separatist since his arrest,
Turkish television released footage of hooded agents
``high-fiving'' each another before removing a blindfold from
Ocalan, who was securely fastened to an airplane seat.
</P>
<P>
   ``Welcome, to your country,'' the special forces commander
asked, ``How are you feeling?''
</P>
<P>
   ``Thank you,'' Ocalan replied. ``I really love Turkey and the
Turkish people.'
</P>
<P>
   Turkish authorities, meanwhile, revealed that five or six
Turkish agents from the Turkish secret service captured Ocalan
after a secret 12-day operation. Turkish media reported that a
commando team in Nairobi drugged Ocalan and loaded him onto a
private plane owned by a Turkish businessman and politician, Cavit
Caglar.
</P>
<P>
   The reports noted that the Turkish government had learned five
days ago of Ocalan's presence in Nairobi. The team then flew to
Kenya in Caglar's unmarked aircraft and, according to the reports,
moved in on Ocalan after learning that the Greeks had turned him
over to the Kenyans for a plane bound for the Netherlands.
</P>
<P>
   Lawyers for Ocalan, however, flatly deny that account and
claimed Tuesday that he had been forcibly removed from the Greek
ambassador's compound in Nairobi.
</P>
<P>
   Turkish intelligence said Ocalan was traveling on a Cypriot
passport with the name of a prominent Greek-Cypriot jounralist. He
has since been jailed in the island of Imrali in the Maramara Sea
near Turkey's western province of Bursa.
</P>
<P>
   Kenyan Foreign Minister Bonya Godana continued to insist that
his government played no role in the capture of Ocalan. ``We would
like to assure everybody, Kurds included, that we had no role in
this affair.''
</P>
<P>
   The State Department, fearing Kurdish protesters will turn
against Americans, went on high alert Wednesday, warning Americans
around the world that the threat of violence spreading across
Europe ``may extend to American interests.''
</P>
<P>
   Ocalan's supporters have charged American and Israeli
intelligence agencies with aiding Turkey in its capture of Ocalan.
The United States, while denying it played a ``direct role'' in his
arrest, has declined to comment on reports that it provided
intelligence on his whereabouts to Turkey.
</P>
<P>
   However, American officials acknowledge that the Clinton
administration decided to help Turkey bring Ocalan to trial after
he was jailed in Rome last November.
</P>
<P>
   At the time, the State Department considered expanding the scope
of a war crimes tribunal in the Hague to include Ocalan as well as
trying him in the United States for crimes against American
citizens.
</P>
<P>
   While Ocalan was in custody in Rome, the United States also
sought to persuade Italy to turn him over to Germany, where he was
under indictment for terrorist activities. ``There was a dual
desire to bring him to justice without facing capital punishment,''
explained a White House official.
</P>
<P>
   Germany, which does not have a death penalty, chose not to
accept Ocalan.
</P>
<P>
   ``The US has added fuel to the fire by providing intelligence to
Turkey,'' said Kani Xulam, a Washington-based Turkish Kurd who
maintains contacts with Ocalan's Kurdistan Workers' Party (PKK).
``I hope the Kurds will not jump to conclusion and declare the US
enemy number one. Our fight is not with the Americans.''
</P>
<P>
   US officials have also declined to comment on reports that the
the Clinton administration provided Turkey with intelligence on
Ocalan's whereabouts in Greece. ``I have no information on that and
we never discuss intelligence matters,'' said a US official.
</P>
<P>
   ``The most interesting question belongs to the Greeks,'' he
added. ``What on earth were they doing?''
</P>
<P>
   While the arrest has strengthened the government of Turkish
Prime Minister Bulent Ecevit on the eve of Turkey's April
elections, it has undermined the Greek government, which is under
attack from the country's nationalists for letting Ocalan fall into
Turkish hands. Greek Foreign Minister Theodoros Pangalos, the
target of resignation calls, assured parliament that it was Kenya,
not Greece, that betrayed Ocalan.
</P>
<P>
   The Ocalan affair has also exacerbated already poor relations
between the two NATO members. While publicly stating that it did
not know where Ocalan was, Greece was sheltering him in its
ambassador's residence in the Kenyan capital of Nairobi for 12
days.
</P>
<P>
   As Kurdish protesters ended many of their demonstrations
throughout Europe and released the Greek ambassador to Austria,
whom they had held hostage in Vienna, new protests sprung up from
Switzerland to Turkey, sparking warnings of tough response from
besieged European governments.
</P>
<P>
   In Diyarbakir, the capital of the southeastern region of Turkey,
a Kurdish protester, angered by the arrest, set himself on fire. In
Geneva, some 20 Kurdish protesters occupied, and later evacuated,
the headquarters of the United Nations' refugee agency. In Zurich,
about 60 demonstrators held a policeman at the Greek consulate.
</P>
<P>
   But the worst violence occurred in Germany, where Kurdish
demonstrators were violently repulsed as they sought to seize the
Israeli embassy.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our people have standing orders to prevent the taking of
hostages and to defend the taking of hostages and to defend
themselves with force,'' Netanyahu said, noting that the
demonstrators had seized an Israeli woman. ``We are involved in a
battle against terrorism and it is our duty to defend our nationals
and our facilities.''
</P>
<P>
   German Chancellor Gerhard Schroeder warned that foreign
protesters would be deported. ``Anyone who breaks the law is not
our friend,'' he said. `` We will tell them politely, but clearly,
to leave.''
</P>
<P>
   Turkey reacted angrily to European demands that it honor human
rights standards in its upcoming trial of Ocalan on terrorist
charges, and it refused an appeal by the UN Special Rapporteur on
Torture to allow international monitors to observe the trial.
</P>
<P>
   ``No European country has the right to lecture us on this
subject,'' Turkey's Prime Minister told ``CNN Wednesday.'' ``Those
who suspend justice for fear of violence in the streets have no
right to warn or criticize us.''
</P>
<P>
   Many observers believe that Germany declined to call for
Ocalan's transfer for prosecution from Italy last fall out of fear
of violence from the thousands of Kurds living within its borders.
</P>
<P>
   Capitalizing on its capture of the rebel leader, Turkey
Wednesday ordered 15,000 troops, backed by air support, to pursue
Ocalan forces based in northern Iraq. The PKK fighters for years
have used northern Iraq as a base for mounting cross-border raids
into souteastern Turkey.
</P>
<P>
   Since Ocalan was first detained in Italy last November, Turkish
security forces have maintained a crackdown on Kurdish political
activities in Turkey. Following his arrest Monday, police in Turkey
have arrested demonstrators, members of human rights groups and
pro-Kurdish political parties.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hundreds were detained last night,'' said Nazmi Gur, a
spokesman for the Ankara based Human Rights Association, Wednesday.
``Six lawyers were among them, so now, we really don't know what
will happen next.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Colum Lynch reported from the United Nations and Jonathan Gorvett
from Istanbul. Wire service mateiral was used to prepare this
report.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
