<SLUG> BC-ARGENTINA-BONDS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INVESTORS WARM TO ARGENTINA'S BONDS  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By JONATHAN FUERBRINGER    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ In a sign that investors still are willing to lend to
the right emerging-market country, Argentina easily sold $1 billion
in new 20-year bonds Wednesday to eager American and European
investors.
</P>
<P>
   The deal, however, also showed that the investors still were
demanding high interest rates and some extra sweeteners.
</P>
<P>
   The bond sale, with J.P. Morgan as the lead underwriter, was one
of the biggest emerging-market deals since Brazil devalued its
currency last month. Mexico did a $1 billion deal two weeks ago.
</P>
<P>
   Argentina's success _ there were $2 billion of bids _ indicates
that the financial market fallout from the Brazilian devaluation
has not been intense. In fact, some analysts are arguing that
because of Argentina's tight link to the U.S. dollar and other
economic policies, it might be able to ``delink'' from Brazil
despite the two countries' strong economic ties.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the deal was expensive, although Argentina can get a
better deal than other emerging-market countries. The 20-year bonds
were priced to yield 12.177 percent, 6.78 percentage points above
the yield on a comparable Treasury bond. The J.P. Morgan index of
all major emerging-market debt was at a spread above Treasuries of
11.66 percentage points Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   The bond includes warrants that give the owner the right to buy
more of the same 20-year bonds in a year at a set price. The future
price is $103.10, compared with the $99.6135 the bonds were sold at
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   The last Argentinian bond deal, which was done in November, also
included warrants to buy additional bonds in the future at a fixed
price. These warrants were for an existing 30-year bond. At the
time of the deal, the fixed price to buy the bond in a year was
$93.30, while the bond was trading at $85.50. But while the price
of the bond rose after the deal, it fell later. It was trading at
about $84 Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Argentina is doing the borrowing now to assure that it has the
cash on hand to meet the principal payments on existing debt that
come due this year. This effort to refinance the existing debt
early is, in fact, one of the reasons that investors are interested
in Argentina.
</P>
<P>
   The more refinancing Argentina does, the less concerned
investors have to be about the possibility of default, which is
still a worry for investors in other emerging-market countries. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-17-99 1957EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990217.0386 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-17 19:58 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9272 &Cx1f; tta-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-REPUBS-FUTURE-2TAKES(     02-17 1217
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-REPUBS-FUTURE-2TAKES(1,200)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GOP SPLIT OVER WHETHER TO LET SCANDAL DIE
</HEADLINE>
   (nk) 
 By RICHARD L. BERKE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ As many Republicans struggle to move beyond
impeachment, they find their party fractured by a hard reality:
Many other Republicans, particularly conservatives, do not want to
move beyond impeachment.
</P>
<P>
   Those frustrated by months of polling that showed impeachment
caused the public to see the Republicans as partisan and
mean-spirited hoped that President Clinton's acquittal would give
them an opportunity to change the subject. But a vocal minority are
pressing forward, in as public a manner as possible, with the
argument that Clinton should be held accountable for his conduct.
</P>
<P>
   These Republicans do not think they are committing political
suicide. Sooner or later, they contend, voters will punish
Democrats for the Lewinsky scandal. They say that the president's
poll ratings have been artificially high and could fall once people
put the impeachment saga in perspective, or if another scandal
shakes the White House.
</P>
<P>
   For example, Senate Majority Leader Trent Lott has predicted
that public sentiment could change dramatically as voters _ hungry
for politicians of moral character _ reward Republicans in the 2000
elections for taking on Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   Craig Shirley, a veteran conservative public relations
operative, summed up the argument: ``It would be horrible to run
away from the Clinton scandals because you are giving up something
that is important to the base of the Republican Party _ and you're
suggesting that we were somehow wrong in going after Clinton.''
</P>
<P>
   Paul Weyrich, head of the Free Congress Foundation, a
conservative group, said, ``Everyone says, `Oh, this is poison and
people shouldn't talk about it.' I think they have to. It's one of
the most important events of the second half of the 20th century.
The fact that Clinton remains in office, if that's not challenged,
it is sweeping something under the rug which is going to come back
to bite us.''
</P>
<P>
   The Republicans' apparent impeachment albatross has delighted
White House advisers, who vow to cast the GOP as controlled by
extremists who are bent on prolonging the impeachment ordeal.
``There's an opportunity for a national message against the
Republican Party,'' said Mark Penn, the president's pollster.
``That it is too extreme and its leadership is too far to the
right. And that national message could have a lot of impact come
2000.''
</P>
<P>
   Penn scoffed at the notion advanced by Lott and others that
Clinton's approval ratings might sag. ``If you were a Martian and
you came down and just read the polls, you would not know that the
Monica Lewinsky scandal existed,'' he said, ``because he was in
good shape before, during and after because the public
fundamentally separated this issue from his performance as
president.''
</P>
<P>
   There are also many Republicans who fear that the ghost of
impeachment could haunt and define the party. Many party leaders,
including several governors, seem terrified that the Democrats
could seize on their party's handling of impeachment to win back
Congress in 2000, and have warned their colleagues to drop the
issue. They argued that the No. 1 priority of Republicans should be
to move on the offensive with an ambitious issue agenda. Yet
Republicans are not united over just what that agenda should be.
</P>
<P>
   ``What we should be talking about is for us to move on,'' Gov.
George Pataki of New York said in an interview Wednesday, ``and in
moving on to focus on the core beliefs of our party.''
</P>
<P>
   Dave Carney, a longtime Republican strategist in New Hampshire,
was almost testy in his advising party members to let go of
impeachment. ``The Republicans who are fixated on this, these
people need to get a life,'' he said. ``I don't know what drug
treatment they need. I don't know what psychotherapy they need. But
the country's moved beyond this. What about free trade? Crime in
the streets? Kosovo? There are other issues out there.''
</P>
<P>
   Carney predicted that impeachment will be so far from voters'
minds next year that neither party would benefit _ or suffer _ from
the issue. `` `Vote for me in 2000 because I voted to keep Bill
Clinton in office.' That's not going to work on a bumper sticker or
in a commercial. Or, `Vote for me in 2000 because I tried to get
rid of the bum.' That's ridiculous.''
</P>
<P>
   Gov. Edward T. Schafer of North Dakota, a Republican, put it
this way: ``I don't think you use it as a weapon. You don't say,
`Oh, there's a Democratic candidate and they're a member of the
party that lied and cheated and then acquitted the perpetrator.'
There's going to be an underlying issue of what the president did
wrong. But we should point to the positive aspects of our
candidates.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet a looming trouble spot as Republicans try to hold on to
their control of Congress and regain the White House in 2000 is not
that voters will lash out at the party's candidates _ but that the
issue will make it much easier for Democrats to raise money and
recruit prospects.
</P>
<P>
   Gov. Paul Cellucci of Massachusetts, a Republican, said his
party has to be especially aggressive in countering the Democrats'
recruitment drives. ``For the Republican Party at the state level
to succeed, I think we need a national message.'' In 1998, he
added, the party was ``consumed with this impeachment thing; they
weren't even out there advocating tax cuts.''
</P>
<P>
   Compounding the potential perils for Republicans is that even
with the party's biggest lightning rod _ Newt Gingrich _ gone as
speaker, there are still Republicans in Congress at center stage
who were among the most vociferous proponents of impeachment, such
as Reps. Tom DeLay of Texas, the majority whip, and Henry Hyde of
Illinois, chairman of the Judiciary Committee.
</P>
<P>
   DeLay's constituents, in fact, are encouraging his continued
attacks on Clinton. Next month, he will be honored with the 1999
Political Courage Award at the Harris County Republican Party's
Lincoln Day Dinner.
</P>
<P>
   The drive to keep impeachment alive is also being fueled the
most by politicians with the most conservative constituents.
</P>
<P>
   At a town meeting the other day in Douglas County, a Republican
enclave about 25 miles south of Denver, only a handful of people
mentioned impeachment to Sen. Wayne Allard, R-Colo. Those who did
praised Allard's votes to oust the president. After the meeting,
Allard stopped short of saying Republicans could turn impeachment
to their advantage. But he did say that by focusing on cutting
taxes and fighting crime, the party could prevent a backlash
against Republicans.
</P>
<P>
   Ed Brookover, who stepped down after the November elections as
political director of the National Republican Congressional
Committee, said his party faced a classic dilemma of whether to
appeal to the outspoken conservatives whose support can be crucial
in primaries _ or whether to appeal to the broader, general
electorate.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's always the constant argument inside the party, whether
you play to the base or play to the middle,'' Brookover said. ``A
winning campaign figures out how to do both. But I don't know if
we've yet landed on a winning way.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Around the country, Democrats have begun plotting how to
capitalize on the Republicans' quandary. In Oregon, Sen. Gordon
Smith, a Republican, is not even facing re-election until 2002, but
Democrats already vow to target him for voting to convict Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   ``Here's a guy who has always portrayed himself as a moderate,''
said Jim Edmundson, a lawyer who is chairman of the Oregon
Democratic Party. ``But he is not. This vote really reveals the
depth of his religious conservatism. This will leave a residual
feeling among moderate voters that he is out of touch with them.''
</P>
<P>
   Smith, the only statewide elected Republican in Oregon,
acknowledged the high stakes of his vote in a state that tends
toward moderation. ``I'll account for it the rest of my public
life,'' he told reporters.
</P>
<P>
   Perry Atkinson, chairman of the Oregon Republican Party, said
Smith cemented his support with conservatives by voting guilty on
both counts. Had Smith voted not guilty on one of the counts _ as
he had talked about doing _ Atkinson said ``it would have sent
mixed messages.''
</P>
<P>
   Richard N. Bond, a former chairman of the Republican National
Committee, offered this advice to his party: ``The Republican Party
had a president who the entire country believed was a lying
adulterer. And they couldn't convince their own Republicans to do
something about it. What does that say about the efficacy of the
issue?''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
