<DOCNO> NYT19990217.0393 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-17 20:06 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9284 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ABCNETWORK-MOVE-NYT &LR;  &UR;      02-17 0453
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ABCNETWORK-MOVE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TO LOS ANGELES  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   ABC MOVING TOP MANAGEMENT FROM NEW YORK By BILL CARTER    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ABC will move more than 200 of its employees, including most of
its top management, from New York to Los Angeles within the next 18
months, ABC executives said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   The moves are intended to consolidate the management of the
network at the headquarters of Walt Disney Co., ABC's parent. Among
the divisions based in New York that will be relocated are daytime,
research, promotion and advertising, and corporate and public
relations.
</P>
<P>
   The decision involves 240 positions at ABC, about 5 percent of
its work force, but only 211 employees will be affected because the
other 29 positions are now vacant.
</P>
<P>
   The move to the West Coast, first reported Wednesday in the
entertainment trade publication The Hollywood Reporter, reaches
even the network's top executive, Patricia Fili-Krushel, the
president of the network. Robert A. Iger, the president of ABC Inc,
will be based in both New York and Los Angeles, ABC executives
said, though it has not yet been determined where he will live.
</P>
<P>
   Among other ABC executives who received official notice last
week that their positions would be moving were Alex Wallau, the
president of administration; Angela Shapiro, the president of
daytime programming; Alan Wurtzel, the executive vice president of
research; Alan Cohen, the senior vice president of marketing, and
Patricia Matson, the senior vice president of communications.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Matson said: ``We've known about this for some time. It's
not as if it was a surprise.''
</P>
<P>
   But several ABC executives who insisted on anonymity said they
were surprised by the move.
</P>
<P>
   Iger presented a broad outline of ABC's plans in a memorandum to
the company staff, issued last June. At that time he wrote that he
and the chairman of the Disney company, Michael Eisner, had devised
a plan to integrate more of the company's activities in Los
Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   He announced then that the company would begin construction of a
new building on the Disney studio lot in Burbank, Calif., which
would be used to house ABC. Iger did not specify which employees
would be moved, but estimated they would number between 300 and
400.
</P>
<P>
   In a memo issued on Feb. 12, Iger said that to achieve the
company's ``day-to-day objectives'' it was critical that ``we be
adjacent to Disney senior management.''
</P>
<P>
   ABC will not make the move until September 2000, deciding to
give its employees long advance notice so they could plan their
personal lives around the decision. But employees must inform ABC
of their intention either to make the move or to leave the company
by Aug. 31 of this year.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
