A9288 &Cx1f; taf-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CLINTON-SOCSEC-NYT &LR;      02-17 0838
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-SOCSEC-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GOP PLAN FOR SHORING UP SOCIAL SECURITY IS DISCLOSED
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Ill., Fla.)  (nk) 
 By RICHARD W. STEVENSON  
c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The Republican chairman of the House subcommittee
that oversees Social Security provided the first details Wednesday
of his approach to shoring up the retirement system, saying that he
planned to introduce legislation that would create private
investment accounts but insulate retirees from the risks of the
stock market.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. E. Clay Shaw Jr. of Florida, chairman of the Ways and Means
Committee's Social Security Subcommittee, said the plan would use a
large portion of the federal budget surplus to finance the
investment accounts.
</P>
<P>
   Although members of both parties have made specific proposals on
Social Security, the Republican leadership has so far been
reluctant to endorse a particular approach, calling on President
Clinton instead to present a detailed package as the basis for
negotiations.
</P>
<P>
   Shaw said his plan, which will be the starting point for the
bill most likely to reach the House floor later this year, would
still have to be reviewed by his party's leaders. But he said his
approach had the general support of most House Republicans, and his
willingness to outline legislation could mark the beginning of a
more intense debate over how the nation should deal with pressures
facing the social welfare system as the population ages.
</P>
<P>
   Republican leaders have agreed with Clinton that 62 percent of
the projected federal budget surpluses, or $2.7 trillion over the
next 15 years, should be set aside to help put Social Security on
firmer financial footing as the baby boom generation approaches
retirement. While there is no assurance that the surpluses will
actually materialize, both parties are counting on them to minimize
or eliminate the need for benefit cuts or tax increases.
</P>
<P>
   But the two parties are far apart over how to use the money for
Social Security. Clinton, backed by nearly all Democrats in the
House and most in the Senate, wants to use the money to pay down
the national debt and earmark the savings for Social Security.
</P>
<P>
   Members of both parties are skeptical that they can reach
agreement on an issue that is so politically sensitive and brings
out the deep ideological differences between them, especially in
the aftermath of the impeachment trial and with the 2000 elections
looming.
</P>
<P>
   Shaw's approach, while still in tentative form and lacking many
of the details that could determine its fate, would use the surplus
to help individuals buy stocks and bonds for private accounts that
would be part of the Social Security system.
</P>
<P>
   Shaw said he believed most people would do better under his plan
than under the current system. But he said his plan would set a
guaranteed benefit level that all retirees could count on even if
their investments performed poorly. Shaw did not provide details on
how the guarantee would be financed, and it was not clear whether
the plan would allow a benefit equal to what current retirees
receive, or if the level would have to be reduced.
</P>
<P>
   He said the plan would also make private investment voluntary,
at least at first, permitting people intimidated by the stock
market to opt for the guaranteed benefit.
</P>
<P>
   Shaw described his approach even as Clinton was holding an event
at the White House to develop support for his approach.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to using the bulk of the surplus for debt reduction,
the president's plan calls for the federal government to invest a
portion of Social Security's reserves in the stock market in an
effort to generate higher returns. These reserves are currently
invested in a low-yielding but safe form of Treasury bond.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's plan rejects the creation of individual investment
accounts within the Social Security system, but calls for the use
of tax breaks to help finance new savings accounts for low- and
middle-income people as a supplement to Social Security.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Republican leadership has said that generally it supports
setting aside 62 percent of the surplus until we save Social
Security,'' Clinton said Wednesday. ``That's good and I appreciate
that.''
</P>
<P>
   But, Clinton added, ``That's where the agreement ends.''
</P>
<P>
   Gene Sperling, Clinton's economic adviser, said the
administration had ``real skepticism'' about individual investment
accounts, but said Shaw's proposal could be constructive.
</P>
<P>
   ``To the degree that he's putting his own specific ideas into
the debate rather than simply launching critiques, that's a
positive step,'' Sperling said.
</P>
<P>
   Both the White House and the Republican leadership have pledged
to work together to see if a bipartisan deal on Social Security is
possible this year. House Speaker Dennis Hastert of Illinois will
meet with Clinton next week to discuss the issue. But so far there
have been no efforts by either side to negotiate.
</P>
<P>
   Without any changes, the system will run short of money to pay
all promised benefits starting in 2032.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
