<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FALL-FASHIONS18-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Lauren conjures up a rainbow
 &HT;    By A. Scott Walton
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YOK _ Buyers and editors toasted designer Ralph Lauren with
a standing ovation Wednesday after his fall/winter collection
preview. The reed-thin Lauren had managed to design a dazzling
array of fine woolen pieces without once resorting to camel, the
most often-seen shade this Fashion Week. ``I didn't see a thing I
could wear,'' joked actor Samuel L. Jackson, who sat front row for
the all-womenswear show. ``But I'm sure there are some things there
my 16-year-old daughter (Zoe) would like.''
</P>
<P>
   Make that a double. Jackson's wife, actress LaTanya Jackson, a
Spelman College trustee, saw plenty to covet.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm so glad he's trying to bring color back,'' she said. ``We
African-Americans, especially, look good in bright colors.''
</P>
<P>
   The fact that Lauren's collection was rooted in the sportswear
aesthetic surprised no one. His attempt to inject his designs with
futuristic touches _ no-fuss fasteners, A-line shapes and minimal
ornamentation _ was equally predictable. And anyone who has paid
attention to New York designers' fabrics of choice for the next
cold season could have told you Lauren would bulk up on two-ply
cashmeres and featherweight felts.
</P>
<P>
   He did all the right things where prevailing trends are
concerned. Better still, he strayed far from the pack that's relied
on camel _ and other shades of brown.
</P>
<P>
   Audience members got a refreshing whiff of pale blue, pink,
purple, red, yellow and green along with the neutrals (black, gray
and cream.)
</P>
<P>
   The basic components of Lauren's collection were lean, clean
pants; awesome sweaters; knee-length skirts; and outerwear (from
vests to capes) to suit any lifestyle.
</P>
<P>
   To keep a woman from looking like the clothes are wearing her,
Lauren made sure every jacket, shell, turtleneck and tunic had a
neckline that formed a flattering frame around the face. And to
illustrate the beauty of simplicity, his eveningwear consisted of
such all-American looks as felt shirts and turtlenecks over
same-shade satin skirts.
</P>
<P>
   ``I love that look of comfortable luxury,'' actress Lynn
Whitfield said. ``It's new and never pretentious.''
</P>
<P>
   Fashion Week gives buyers and the media a look at top designers'
clothing for fall/winter 1999-2000.
</P>
<P>
   A. Scott Walton writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
