<HEADER>
A9290 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FASHION-SCENE18-COX     02-17 0646
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FASHION-SCENE18-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Mark Eisen's collection of don'ts
 &HT;    By A. Scott Walton
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The prevailing attitude among editors at Mark Eisen's
fall/winter preview show on Tuesday night was there were too many
styles that looked too coarse, too primitive, too misshapen, too
odd.
</P>
<P>
   It's not likely stylish women will look to Eisen in particular
when it's time to spruce up their winter wardrobes.
</P>
<P>
   In general terms, however, Eisen's show highlighted nearly all
of the fall/winter trends that have emerged during the runway
previews as well as expose some of the potential hazards along the
way.
</P>
<P>
   Eisen said he wanted to prove that, ``The urban nomad of today
and timeless nomad of lore have more in common than meets the
eye.''
</P>
<P>
   In his own meanderings through the prevailing trends, he made a
few wrong turns. But stylish women won't, as long as they watch
their steps more carefully.
</P>
<P>
   Step 1: Choose the right leather pieces. Leather, especially in
shades of brown, looks like it will be a wardrobe essential. Any
sleek, supple, sexy and shiny skirt, shirt, jacket or pants will
do. Eisen's saddle leather skirts were sleek, shiny and sexy _ in
an off-beat sort of way _ but far from supple. And they looked
ungainly in their short, slit interpretation.
</P>
<P>
   Step 2: Mothball any pair of pants that could be described as,
``Capri-length,'' as soon as summer ends. Every designer's showing
trim-fitting pants that flare out from the knee. Eisen did so, too,
but his stopped at the length of gauchos.
</P>
<P>
   Step 3: When you select a coat with hidden, magnetic closures,
make sure those closure are actually hidden. Eisen telegraphed his
awareness of the magnetic closure trend by sewing a chunky,
functionless button to the outside of his coats.
</P>
<P>
   Step 4: Think modern, millenial even, but don't dress as if
you're an extra in the next set of ``Star Wars'' movies. Some of
Eisen's heavy wool dresses looked crude and boxy as if they'd been
sewn by Chewbaca and fitted on Obi Won Knobe.
</P>
<P>
   Step 5: Knitwear is surfacing as a force in coats, suits and
separates. And the shoulder-capping shrug, returns for another
cold-weather season as the hot item to have. But some designers'
sweater-over-sweater alternatives to donning traditional outerwear
are dead-ends, Eisen's included.
</P>
<P>
   Step 6: When you select a pair of knee-high boots make sure
they've got a modicum of sex appeal. Leather and suede boots with
moderate to high heels are getting as much exposure as flats did in
the spring/summer '99 collections. Eisen showed knee-high boots
with thick flat soles that caused his models to plod instead of
prance.
</P>
<P>
   Step 7: Get used to uttering the words ``corduroy'' and ``chic''
in the same sentence. Some designers have found a way of making
corduroy look less bulky and matted. But Eisen tried too hard to
make the most of corduroy _ using it for floor-length gowns _ and
wound up proving that moderation has its merits.
</P>
<P>
   Nicole Miller: Some editors here say things are ``quiet'' in
terms of fall/winter trends worth trumpeting. Be that as it may,
Nicole Miller certainly made some noise with her collection of
inspired suits, separates and gowns. Zip closures of her Lycra
cardigans. Scratch went the eye-catching Velcro closures on her
streamlined leather coats. Clink went the hook-and-eye closures on
the back of her felt dresses. Miller indulged in the color black
more than most designers have so far, but there was also an
abundance of color in the collection (teal, lilac, plum, raspberry,
and pink). She also introduced some eye-catching new fabrics, like
the ''crushed'' taffeta and ''reflective'' wool blends she used for
eveningwear.
</P>
<P>
   A. Scott Walton writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
