<SLUG> BC-MARKET-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TECHNOLOGY COMPANIES SPARK STOCK MARKET DROP 
</HEADLINE>
  (rk) 
 By KENNETH N. GILPIN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK_ Stock prices fell sharply Wednesday, pulled down by
software and computer companies, which fell in the wake of
weaker-than-expected sales from Dell Computer and Hewlett-Packard.
</P>
<P>
   By most standards, Dell's fourth-quarter numbers, released after
the market's close on Tuesday, were exemplary: a 49 percent jump in
net income but sales growth of ``only'' 38 percent.
</P>
<P>
   The revenue number was a disappointment because Dell had
reported average quarterly sales growth of 56 percent over the
previous eight quarters.
</P>
<P>
   Some analysts had predicted Dell's sales would fall short of its
performance over the last two years, and the stock fell sharply on
Friday and again on Tuesday. It tumbled another 7 3/16 Wednesday ,
to 81 9/16.
</P>
<P>
   Since the close on Feb. 11, Dell, the best-performing stock in
the Standard &AMP; Poor's 500-stock index over the last three years,
has declined 20 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Evidence that a market leader had stumbled spread through the
technology sector and spilled into the overall market, clipping
prices of everything from blue chips to small company stocks.
</P>
<P>
   On the New York Stock Exchange, declining issues outnumbered
those that advanced by nearly 2 to 1. Volume on the Big Board was
moderate, at 735 million shares. On the Nasdaq, just more than 900
million shares changed hands.
</P>
<P>
   The Dow Jones industrial average fell 101.56 points, or 1.1
percent, to 9,195.47. The S&AMP;P 500 fell 17.84 points, or 1.4
percent, to 1,224.03. The Russell 2000 index of smaller companies
was battered, dropping 6.87 points, or 1.7 percent, to 389.53. For
the year, the index is down 7.7 percent.
</P>
<P>
   But the biggest declines of the session were recorded by stocks
that make up the Nasdaq composite index.
</P>
<P>
   Nasdaq fell 64.96 points, or 2.8 percent, to 2,248.91. Since
Feb. 11, the Nasdaq has declined 6.5 percent, its biggest
three-session loss since October 1998.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are a lot of reasons for the market to get hit, and
virtually no reasons for it to go up,'' said one stock trader. ``At
best, I think we will tread water between 9,100 and 9,400 on the
Dow. But I would not be at all surprised to see it take a little
hit and go through 9,100.''
</P>
<P>
   John Manley, an equity strategist at Salomon Smith Barney, said
``strong pressures'' are working on stock prices, some positively,
others much less so.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Fed is trying to keep the financial system from imploding,
but economic growth in significant portions of the world, including
Europe and Latin America, is slowing,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``More than ever,'' he added, ``the United States is affected by
what is happening overseas. The market action over the past five
days has been markedly affected by what is happening in Japan.''
</P>
<P>
   In this country, the recent rise in Japanese interest rates has
not only pushed up bond yields but also shown that stocks are
vulnerable to an increase in interest rates. Bond prices rose
slightly and yields fell for a second day Wednesday, and the
improvement helped many interest-sensitive bank and financial
company shares.
</P>
<P>
   But that development did nothing to stem the decline in
high-flying technology shares.
</P>
<P>
   Hewlett-Packard was the worst performing component of the Dow,
shedding 2], to 68[. Like Dell, Hewlett, the world's second-biggest
computer maker, reported a slowdown in its fiscal first-quarter
sales growth and said sales were likely to be lackluster for the
rest of the year. Traders chose to concentrate on the slower sales
and ignored earnings that beat analysts' consensus estimates by 9
cents a share.
</P>
<P>
   Other computer manufacturers also got punished.
</P>
<P>
   IBM lost 2\, to 170{. And Compaq Computer fell 1 13/16, to 41.
</P>
<P>
   Among other leading technology companies, Microsoft slumped 6\,
to 150. Cisco Systems lost 3 5/16, to 95[. And Sun Microsystems
fell 6], to 94 1/16.
</P>
<P>
   Bond Prices Rise  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Bond prices rose Wednesday for a second day as declining
commodity prices and a Federal Reserve report showing no pick-up in
industrial production bolstered expectations for subdued inflation.
</P>
<P>
   The drop in commodities, including gold, ``points to low
inflation,'' said Barry Evans, who helps oversee $10 billion of
bonds at John Hancock Funds in Boston, including some treasuries
purchased Wednesday. ``That's better for bonds.''
</P>
<P>
   The price of the 30-year Treasury bond rose 15/32, to 99 4/32.
The bond's yield, which moves in the opposite direction from the
price, fell to 5.31 percent from 5.34 percent on Tuesday.  &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
