<HEADER>
A9294 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BOSTON-HOUSING-NYT &LR;      02-17 0466
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOSTON-HOUSING-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
U.S. ACCUSES BOSTON HOUSING AGENCY OF WIDE RACIAL BIAS 
</HEADLINE>
  (nk) 
 By CAREY GOLDBERG   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Federal housing officials announced Wednesday that they
were filing their first charges ever of ``systemic
discrimination,'' accusing the Boston Housing Authority of failing
to stop the harassment of nine minority families in two
predominantly white housing projects.
</P>
<P>
   The charges stemmed from 1996 complaints by the nine families,
almost all headed by single mothers, that their young children were
beaten by gangs of white teen-agers, that their homes and cars were
vandalized and that they were otherwise terrorized, but the housing
authority failed to protect or promptly transfer them.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not just talking about individual acts of racial
violence, but acts of racial violence and harassment that almost
amounted to government-sanctioned lynchings,'' said Ozell Hudson,
executive director of the Boston Lawyers' Committee for Civil
Rights, which represents the families.
</P>
<P>
   Responding to the federal charges Wednesday, the administrator
of the housing authority, Sandra B. Henriquez, said the agency's
policies had changed considerably since the families were harassed
from 1992 to 1996. It has brought in a civil rights protection plan
that includes a hot line for such complaints, has trained employees
in racial sensitivity and has moved more actively to evict
aggressors, she said in a statement.
</P>
<P>
   The charges, filed by the Department of Housing and Urban
Development, are to be heard before a department judge unless those
involved in the case ask to go to federal court instead. The
families have already brought a separate suit in federal court,
Hudson said, and are seeking at least $1 million along with the
dismissals of accused officials and other changes. HUD is seeking
unspecified damages for the victims and may also ask that the
housing authority be fined for its violations; it is also
considering whether to withdraw some funding from Boston.
</P>
<P>
   The case highlights the difficulties of integrating housing
projects in Boston, which had a number of racial disputes over
busing in the 1970s.
</P>
<P>
   The housing projects at issue, in South Boston and Charlestown,
were almost entirely white before a court ordered them to become
more integrated in the late 1980s. Black and Hispanic families thus
moved into a potentially hostile environment and, the families
charge, the housing authority was reluctant to transfer them when
they complained about living in fear.
</P>
<P>
   The families complained that, among other things, a gunshot was
fired into one of their homes and a woman in her third trimester of
pregnancy found that vandals had tied up the doorknob of her
apartment to prevent her from getting out.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
