<SLUG> BC-DNC-CONVENTION-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MAYOR SAYS BOSTON HAS LOST OUT ON DEMOCRATIC CONVENTION 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ANTHONY FLINT AND JUDY RAKOWSKY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Mayor Thomas M. Menino conceded Wednesday that Boston's
spirited longshot bid to host the 2000 Democratic National
Convention is dead and that the big party will instead be held in
Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   Officials from the Democratic National Committee, however,
denied that any formal decision had been made, but Menino said Joe
Andrew, the head of DNC's site selection committee, told him
Wednesday afternoon by telephone that a contract had been offered
to Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's politics. That's the bottom line. We have a city that
wants it badly, that has come together like never before. But
California has 54 electoral votes,'' Menino said.
</P>
<P>
   Menino led Boston's first bid for a political convention and
made it to the final round of cities in the running, with Los
Angeles and Denver. The city proposed holding the convention in the
Fleet Center and assured party officials there were adequate hotel
rooms and other facilities; Menino said Boston was a laboratory for
Democratic policies and would have national appeal as the
``birthplace of democracy.''
</P>
<P>
   But the media exposure from the four-day convention was deemed
to have more of an impact in California, a major battleground in
any modern presidential race, rather than in Massachusetts, which
traditionally votes Democratic anyway, Menino said. Massachusetts
has 12 electoral votes and the six-state New England region totals
35, compared to California's 54.
</P>
<P>
   Menino said Andrew told him Los Angeles was not a done deal, and
pleaded with him not to give up. ``He said there was some
possibility that LA wouldn't agree to stipulations in the contract,
but that's very slim. If they offer a contract, they offer a
contract, and they want it in LA.''
</P>
<P>
   A top City Hall official said Menino was so angered by a Clinton
administration report on racial problems in the city's public
housing developments he decided to preempt plans for a formal
announcement by national Democratic Party officials that the
convention would be held in Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   The report, made public Wednesday in Washington by US Housing
and Urban Development secretary Andrew Cuomo, angered Menino ``more
than anything else in his career'' and was viewed by the mayor as a
``cheap shot,'' this official said.
</P>
<P>
   There is said to be an informal agreement among the mayors of
the cities in the running for the convention to let national
Democrats make the formal announcement of the site. Menino said
Wednesday that ``nobody ever told me about that.''
</P>
<P>
   He said he had not spoken to President Clinton or Vice President
Al Gore, the front-runner for the Democratic nomination for
president in 2000, who is in South Africa but is expected in New
Hampshire in the next 24 hours.
</P>
<P>
   City Hall officials and national Democrats in Massachusetts and
Washington expressed surprise that Menino publicly threw in the
towel and officially denied that Los Angeles was chosen.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Democratic National Committee has not made a final
decision on the city to host the 2000 Democratic National
Convention. Although we have intensified discussion with LA
recently, nothing has been finalized,'' said Melissa Bonney
Ratcliff, press secretary for the Democratic National Committee.
</P>
<P>
   As late as Wednesday afternoon, Howard R. Leibowitz, head of
intergovernmental affairs at City Hall and the point man on
Boston's convention bid, said ``nothing was official.''
</P>
<P>
   Steven Grossman, outgoing chairman of the DNC, said, likewise,
that Menino's concession was premature. ``Boston's convention bid
is by no means dead,'' he said. Grossman added that Menino's
comments will not condemn Boston's bid.
</P>
<P>
   ``I won't dispute the characterization of Los Angeles as the
front-runner. In many ways it has been the front-runner from the
beginning,'' Grossman said. ``I understand his disappointment in
what he perceives to be a decision already made. But these
discussions have by no means reached a conclusive stage.''
</P>
<P>
   By the end of the day, however, top party officials were
conceding that Menino's comments were accurate: that the Democrats
wanted to hold the convention in Los Angeles. Some officials
familiar with the negotiations even used the terms of a post-mortem
on Boston's bid, indicating the competition was indeed over. ``Few
cities did as well as Boston in the initial site visit. The mayor
was so gracious in welcoming everybody,'' said one.
</P>
<P>
   Menino acknowledged that Boston may have always been a longshot
for the convention, though he said the city proved it could host
the four-day affair from a logistical standpoint.
</P>
<P>
   The bid for the gathering _ which would have brought 35,000
delegates, party officials, and media representatives to Boston,
pumped millions into the regional economy and gained the city
international publicity _ was initially viewed as a lark by some at
City Hall.
</P>
<P>
   But through the fall, many city officials became convinced that
Boston could actually land the convention, and Menino led a
personal campaign with Clinton, Gore, and others to keep the city
in the realm of serious consideration. Advisers said the mayor
regarded winning the DNC convention as the ultimate coup and a
major part of his legacy.
</P>
<P>
   The DNC's decision to go to Los Angeles comes on the heels of
MacWorld organizers this week announcing that they would not hold
their major convention in Boston. But city boosters say they are
now looking forward to other major events, such as the All-Star
game at Fenway Park this summer.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Ann Kornblut of the Globe Washington bureau contributed to this
report.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
