<HEADLINE>
GERMAN UNION PRESSES STRIKE THREAT 
</HEADLINE>
  (lh) 
 By EDMUND L. ANDREWS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   FRANKFURT, Germany _ The last several years have been grim ones
for Germany's once-powerful labor unions.
</P>
<P>
   Hammered by the loss of nearly a million industrial jobs since
1990, union leaders have settled for negligible wage increases for
the last three years. They have made big concessions on extra pay
for overtime and on weekend work. And they have watched helplessly
as many companies in eastern Germany refused to negotiate with them
at all.
</P>
<P>
   Yet as Germany's biggest union edged closer to an all-out strike
against manufacturers, the balance of power may be shifting.
Proclaiming ``an end to modesty'' in its demands, the giant IG
Metall metal workers' union has pressed its most aggressive wage
demands in years and promised to prepare for a strike if it did not
reach an agreement with industry by midnight Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   The deadline passed without an agreement, but negotiators
continued to talk early Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   The union, which represents 3.5 million workers, is holding out
for raises of more than 4 percent, plus a significant one-time
payment to each worker. The employers, which include
DaimlerChrysler and big manufacturers of machine tools and factory
equipment, have dismissed the demands and are offering a 2.3
percent raise and a maximum one-time payment of five-tenths of a
percent of a worker's salary.
</P>
<P>
   The confrontation is unusually bitter and comes at a difficult
time. German workers are among the highest paid in the world, but
unemployment in this country remains above 10 percent and the
economy has markedly slowed in recent months.
</P>
<P>
   That poses a hard challenge for Germany's new Social Democratic
chancellor, Gerhard Schroeder, who made unemployment the central
issue of his election campaign last fall. A major strike would
almost certainly ruin Schroeder's plans to create jobs through his
``Alliance for Jobs'' _ a series of round-table talks between
industry, unions and the government. Yet Schroeder cannot afford to
alienate unions, which have enormous power in his Social Democratic
Party. Indeed, the new labor minister, Walter Riester, is the
former vice chairman of IG Metall.
</P>
<P>
   German factory workers earn an average of $30.20 an hour,
according to the Organization for Economic Cooperation and
Development in Paris. That makes them the highest paid in the world
and well ahead of their American counterparts, with an average of
$23.60 an hour.
</P>
<P>
   But the average take-home pay of German workers has been
stagnant for the last three years, after accounting for inflation
and new tax increases. At the same time, productivity for each
worker has soared because of wage restraint and streamlining in
factories. The government estimates that productivity in
manufacturing industries has climbed 7 percent annually over the
last few years.
</P>
<P>
   Union leaders argue that their members are overdue for a
significant raise. ``The industry is earning record profits and
their stocks have increased enormously,'' said Juergen Peters, vice
president of IG Metall. ``The workers have to take part in that, as
well.''
</P>
<P>
   But financial turmoil in Asia, Russia and Latin America has
slowed the economy. Most experts think that growth will not exceed
2 percent this year, down from 2.8 percent in 1998, and that
unemployment will remain around 10 percent.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Strikes are rare in Germany, where companies and unions strive
for consensus whenever possible. As a result, union leaders have
been increasing pressure. In December, they announced their basic
demands. Then they staged a series of ``warning strikes'' of
several hours each at factories across the country.
</P>
<P>
   The union originally set a deadline for talks on Feb. 11. When
both sides refused to budge, the government offered to mediate.
Union leaders agreed to resume talks on Tuesday in Stuttgart,
setting the new deadline of midnight Wednesday. Barring success,
the union said its members would vote next week to strike on March
1.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am very, very skeptical'' about reaching an agreement, said
Berthold Huber, the lead negotiator for IG Metall, as he took a
break from the talks on Wednesday evening. Huber and other union
leaders insisted that they wanted to avoid a strike and had
signaled their willingness to accept a wage increase of more than 4
percent instead of 6.5 percent.
</P>
<P>
   The last strike by IG Metall was in 1995, when workers in
Bavaria remained off the job for two weeks. Before that, the last
truly big strike lasted seven weeks in 1984 in the states of
Baden-Wuerttemburg and Hesse, which led to a reduction in the
standard workweek to 35 hours from 37.
</P>
<P>
   Germany's finance minister, Oskar Lafontaine, has argued that
workers are overdue for a raise because wages have lagged well
behind increases in productivity. ``The workers have to receive a
fair share of what they have produced,'' he said on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   But most economists argue that a surge in labor costs would
aggravate unemployment. ``The moderate wage policies in recent
years have brought about an improvement, and they should be
continued,'' said Harmen Lehment, a labor analyst at the Institute
for World Economics at the University of Kiel. ``What we don't want
to see is a repeat of 1995, when we had strikes in Bavaria and big
wage increases followed by rising unemployment. The moderate wage
policies in recent years should be continued.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
