<SLUG> BC-DNC-POLITICS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN THE END, IT WAS POLITICS THAT DECIDED CONVENTION SITE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ANNE E. KORNBLUT  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ One has a historic backdrop. The other has an
endless parking lot.
</P>
<P>
   But political decisions are rarely based on beauty. And
throughout the process of choosing a site for the 2000 Democratic
National Convention, politics have outweighed practicality, and
economics have overruled emotions, analysts and sources close to
the decision said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``California is essential to the Democrats' electoral process,''
Democratic consultant Bill Carrick, whose clients includes Boston
Mayor Thomas Menino, said.
</P>
<P>
   Art Torres, a retired state senator who has led the charge to
bring the convention to Los Angeles, said that ``clearly, the 54
electoral votes'' in California makes a difference, overshadowing
Massachusetts' meager 12.
</P>
<P>
   Although, he joked, he and Senator Edward M. Kennedy ``have been
arguing about what's better in the summer, the Cape or Malibu. I
said, we've got sailboats out here, too, Ted.''
</P>
<P>
   According to Democrats close to the negotiations, Boston has all
the baseline logistical requirements for hosting the convention: a
sizable convention hall, just enough hotel space for the 20,000 or
so overnight guests, and a political climate overwhelmingly
friendly to Democrats.
</P>
<P>
   Even the Big Dig, with its unsightly construction sites and
mounds of dirt, is not an automatic strike against Boston. One
Democrat familiar with the negotiations said convention planners at
the Democratic National Committee ``asked a lot of questions about
the Big Dig.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The city of Boston was very good at being very up front about
it, giving information about where they were at with the Big Dig
and where they thought they would be in 2000,'' the source said.
</P>
<P>
   Financially, the three front-runners _ Boston, Los Angeles and
Denver _ have pledged roughly equal amounts, in the ballpark of $35
million, so the bottom line would not be a deciding factor in which
city would land the lucrative deal.
</P>
<P>
   But the source of the money would likely play a role: While
Boston and Denver relied heavily on state and city funding in their
proposals, the Los Angeles package mirrored its 1984 Olympics bid,
relying mostly on private donors and not buradening taxpayers,
several Democratic sources said.
</P>
<P>
   Even more important, however, is politics.
</P>
<P>
   According to John Brockelman, director of the Massachusetts
Republican Party, the difficulties Boston's Democrats have had in
attempting to lure the convention is proof of their powerlessness
nationwide.
</P>
<P>
   ``Boston has put together a great package,'' Brockelman said.
But, he added, ``We know our delegation has zero clout in Congress.
Now it is starting to look like they have zero clout in their own
party.''
</P>
<P>
   However, a source close to the negotiations defended the effort
by Boston officials, saying ``they had a very solid proposal,'' and
their proposal is still ``right up there, and it's very
competitive.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite concerns about bringing the Democrats to California _
home of Monica S. Lewinsky and one of Vice President Al Gore's more
high-profile fund-raising debacles _ political experts said the
benefits of such a decision would far outweigh any risks,
particularly because California is a greater question mark in
Gore's presidential race than Boston or Massachusetts.
Representative Barney Frank, a Massachusetts Democrat, said the
apparent choice of Los Angeles was ``a decision obviously made by
Gore.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I suppose if we lost it to Salt Lake City we could get
suspicious,'' Frank said, referring to the recent Olympics scandal
in Utah. ``But losing it to Los Angeles? It was a political
calculation made by Al Gore.''
</P>
<P>
   The Democratic National Committee refused Wednesday to confirm
reports that Los Angeles had already won the contract. Melissa
Bonney Ratcliffe, a spokeswoman for the DNC, issued a statement:
``Although we have intensified discussions with Los Angeles
recently, nothing has been finalized.''
</P>
<P>
   Officials at the DNC are expected to make a formal announcement
in early March, some 17 months before the August 2000 convention
takes place.
</P>
<P>
   Despite Wednesday's concessional remarks made by Menino, even
Torres, the California State Democratic Party chairman, refused to
celebrate Los Angeles's apparent victory, saying he had not been
informed by Democratic officials.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I knew,'' he said, ``I'd be jumping up and down.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-17-99 2017EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
