<DOCNO> NYT19990217.0405 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-17 20:17 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9302 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GERONIMO-PRATT-NYT &LR;      02-17 0682
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GERONIMO-PRATT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
30-YEAR MURDER CHARGE AGAINST FORMER BLACK PANTHER IS DROPPED
</HEADLINE>
   (sw) 
 By DON TERRY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ For 30 years, Elmer ``Geronimo'' Pratt and the
State of California have been at war with each other.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday, the state raised the white flag.
</P>
<P>
   In a terse, four-paragraph statement, the Los Angeles County
district attorney, Gil Garcetti, said his office will no longer try
to send Pratt, a former leader of the Black Panther Party, back to
prison for the 1968 robbery and murder of a woman on a Santa Monica
tennis court.
</P>
<P>
   Pratt spent 27 years in jail and prison for the slaying, but
steadfastly maintained his innocence, filing numerous appeals. In
1997 an Orange County Superior Court judge, Everett W. Dickey,
threw out the conviction, ruling that prosecutors had withheld
crucial evidence about a witness that may have cleared the
decorated Vietnam War veteran at his trial in 1972.
</P>
<P>
   Pratt, 51, a defiant symbol of the black empowerment movement of
the 1960s, was released to a hero's welcome. But Garcetti appealed
the ruling.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, a state appellate court unanimously upheld Dickey's
decision, and on Wednesday Garcetti said the criminal case against
Pratt was over.
</P>
<P>
   ``We accept the decision of the court of appeals,'' Garcetti
said in a statement. ``The murder at issue in this case occurred
over 30 years ago. Most of the witnesses to the case are deceased.
It would be virtually impossible to retry this case. In our
professional judgment, there would be no reasonable likelihood of
conviction.''
</P>
<P>
   Laurie Levenson, a former federal prosecutor and associate dean
of the Loyola Law School in Los Angeles, said Garcetti's decision
was ``probably the only decision he could make.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's frustrating because the DA's still believe Pratt was
responsible for the murder,'' Ms. Levenson said. ``They don't have
their eyewitnesses anymore, their government informant is worth
zero and all the police officers who worked with the informant are
tainted.''
</P>
<P>
   At their home in Louisiana, Ashaki Pratt, who married Pratt
during his first decade of imprisonment, said she was overjoyed.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's finally over,'' she said. ``I'm just so happy. At last.
At last. It's finally over.''
</P>
<P>
   Stuart Hanlon, one of Pratt's lawyers, said he felt a mixture of
joy, anger and frustration.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is very fulfilling to reach this point after all these
years,'' Hanlon said. ``But my overwhelming feeling is anger.
Garcetti fought us every step of the way.''
</P>
<P>
   Now that the criminal case is over, Hanlon said Pratt's lawyers,
including Johnnie L. Cochran Jr., will be able to devote much more
time and energy to Pratt's civil lawsuit against the state.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now,'' Hanlon said, ``we're going to see what a jury thinks of
what happened.''
</P>
<P>
   The case stretches back to a December night in 1968. A young
couple, Kenneth and Caroline Olsen, were playing tennis under the
lights when two men approached them and demanded money. The men got
$18 and then started shooting. Mrs. Olsen was killed and her
husband was wounded.
</P>
<P>
   Pratt, a rising star in the Black Panther Party, was arrested
two years later and convicted in 1972, largely on the testimony of
a former Black Panther and one-time Los Angeles County sheriff's
deputy, Julius Butler.
</P>
<P>
   Pratt said he was innocent and had been at a party meeting in
Oakland at the time of the killing. But the case began to slowly
unravel several years later when it was revealed that Butler had
been a police informant, a fact that had been kept from Pratt's
lawyers. It was also disclosed that Butler had been given money by
the authorities to buy a gun and other favors around the time he
was testifying against Pratt.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most human beings cannot do what Geronimo Pratt did,'' said
Gigi Gordon, a prominent Los Angeles lawyer and legal commentator.
``They don't have the strength, the endurance, and they don't
believe enough in the system to believe they can be saved. You have
to believe in the system to fight the system. Or you give up.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-17-99 2017EST &QL; 
