<HEADER>
A9305 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-EDITORIAL-DEATH-BOS &LR;      02-17 0365
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDITORIAL-DEATH-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A FATAL MISTAKE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``Revenge is a kind of wild justice, which the more man's nature
runs to, the more ought law to weed it out.''
</P>
<P>
   Francis Bacon, 1625 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The last time the Commonwealth of Massachusetts took its
ultimate revenge was shortly after midnight on the 9th of May,
1947, when two petty hoodlums named Edward ``Dutchy'' Gersten and
Philip Bellino received the usual 2,200 volts of electricity in the
old Charlestown State Prison, long since torn down. The two had
killed a man during a stickup gone wrong at a floating crap game.
Nobody in Massachusetts has since been executed.
</P>
<P>
   Governor &UR;  &LR; Paul Cellucci, fulfilling a campaign promise, would
revive that practice, which the state put behind it more than 50
years ago. ``I am more determined than ever to wage this fight for
justice,'' Cellucci said, describing murderers as ``monsters who do
not deserve hope.''
</P>
<P>
   Many murderers are indeed monsters who do not deserve hope, the
murder of 10-year-old Jeffrey Curley being a case in point.
However, there is life without parole to deny murderers hope.
</P>
<P>
   Cellucci says the death penalty would act as a deterrent. Yet
the statistical evidence does not support him. States that execute
their criminals do not generally produce fewer murderers than
states that do not, such as Massachusetts.
</P>
<P>
   The governor proposes an elaborate set of safeguards to prevent
innocent persons from going to their deaths. Yet here again, the
evidence shows case after case of death row inmates who are found
not to have done it after all. In Illinois there have been 10 such
cases in 20 years.
</P>
<P>
   So, when all is said and done it is a matter of revenge.
Undeniably, retribution is a legitimate part of punishment, and we
can understand the governor's desire for it. But instead of turning
``the heat up,'' as Cellucci asked voters to do, it is time to turn
the heat down on this emotional issue. The needs of retribution can
be met without the too-wild justice of death. Massachusetts is one
of only 12 states to eschew the death penalty, and it should remain
proud of it.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
