<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDITORIAL-KURD-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DUE PROCESS FOR A TERRORIST 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Turkey's capture of the Kurdish terrorist Abdullah Ocalan has
all the elements of a garish potboiler about terrorism,
international intrigue, and the duplicity of nation-states, those
entities that Lord Acton called ``cold monsters.''
</P>
<P>
   Although it is not clear exactly how Ocalan ended up in the
clutches of a Turkish special operations unit in Nairobi, Kenya, it
is clear that the Greek Embassy sheltered him. There is no good
reason for the Greek government to meddle in the bitter conflict
between Turkish authorities and the Kurdish separatists lest it be
to follow blindly the old Balkan principle that the enemy of my
enemy is my friend. There are more than enough causes of hostility
between Athens and Ankara without adding to the docket a Greek
intervention in a civil war that has snuffed out 30,000 lives. It
would be fitting if the Greek officials who approved the sheltering
of Ocalan were forced to resign.
</P>
<P>
   As for those Kurds who assaulted Greek and Kenyan embassies
around the world, taking women and children hostage, they have done
considerable harm to their cause. Rather than eliciting sympathy
for the 10 million Turkish Kurds, the protesters drew comparisons
with IRA bombers and the Palestinian terrorists of the 1970s.
</P>
<P>
   Now that Ocalan has fallen into Turkish hands, the government of
Turkey's Social Democratic prime minister, Bulent Ecevit, would be
wise to demonstrate that it is capable of honoring Ocalan's human
rights by giving him a trial that the world can watch and adjudge
to be fair. Lawyers of his choice should be able to defend their
client without arbitrary restrictions. Although the Turks are not
always wise in these matters, Ocalan must not be tortured by his
jailers. In any case, Turkey's brutal repression of its Kurdish
minority cannot excuse the tactics of Ocalan and his terrorists.
</P>
<P>
   Ultimately both Turks and Kurds will have to seek and find a
negotiated political solution to their conflict.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
