<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-17 20:21 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9308 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KURD-ISRAEL-NYT &LR;      02-17 0513
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KURD-ISRAEL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ISRAEL ON HEIGHTENED ALERT FOR ATTACKS BY KURDS 
</HEADLINE>
  (See related stories: KURD-EUROPE, KURD-TURKEY, KURD-U.S.) 
(rk) 
 By JOEL GREENBERG   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   JERUSALEM _ Israel is bracing for reprisals after Wednesday's
killings of three Kurdish protesters at its consulate in Berlin.
</P>
<P>
   It was already a target of Kurdish rage because of its strong
military and intelligence links with Turkey. Followers of the
arrested Kurdish leader Abdullah Ocalan have accused Mossad,
Israel's overseas intelligence service, of helping to track him
down. They contend that Turkey and Israel are joining in a ``dirty
war'' against his Kurdistan Workers Party.
</P>
<P>
   But analysts in Jerusalem said they have concluded that Israel
would not have helped to carry out the capture, while conceding
that Israeli has offered antiterrorist assistance to Turkey.
</P>
<P>
   In recent years Israel and Turkey have forged a high-profile
strategic alliance that has served as a counterweight to mutual
perceived threats from Syria and Iran. Israeli pilots have trained
in Turkish air space, the two countries have carried out a joint
naval rescue exercise, and Israel has upgraded Turkish fighter
planes.
</P>
<P>
   There have been mutual visits by defense and military chiefs
from both countries, meetings between intelligence officials and a
military cooperation agreement signed in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   Along with intelligence-sharing, Israel has advised Turkey on
antiterrorism methods, which the Turks have used in their long war
with Ocalan's separatist Kurdish movement. The methods have
reportedly included fencing-off and mining border areas, curfews
and interrogation techniques, cross-border incursions against
guerrilla bases in Iraq and establishment of a Turkish controlled
``security zone'' there.
</P>
<P>
   Yet Israeli governments have avoided taking a direct and active
role in Turkey's war with the Kurds. ``Israel doesn't want to open
a new front with terrorism, because we have enough problems
already,'' said Yossi Melman, an Israeli journalist who has written
a book on Israel's intelligence agencies.
</P>
<P>
   For the same reason, Melman added, it is unlikely that Israel
would have participated in the capture of Ocalan, despite Turkish
requests for help in tracking him down.
</P>
<P>
   Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu drew a distinction between
antiterrorism assistance to Turkey and the capture of Ocalan.
</P>
<P>
   ``Israel's activity does not include any role in the struggle
against Ocalan, and we did not cooperate with any element in
apprehending Ocalan,'' Netanyahu told a news conference. ``We
always fight terrorism, and we will always fight terrorism, but we
certainly had no part in the capture of Ocalan.''
</P>
<P>
   Regardless of whether or not Israel was involved in seizing
Ocalan, it has been drawn into the maelstrom set off by his arrest.
Israeli embassies, consulates and airlines have been put on
heightened security alert amid growing concerns that this country,
long a target of Arab terrorist attacks, could now become a target
of Kurdish terrorism.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
