<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDITORIAL-PILOTS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FLYING THROUGH TURBULENCE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The annals of labor have many loftier causes than those at issue
between American Airlines and its fractious pilot corps. Most labor
disagreements involve primarily the parties themselves, with
limited collateral damage to customers and the general public. But
American and its pilots have demonstrated a willingness to visit
inconvenience, congestion, and delay on hundreds of thousands of
passengers throughout the industry. It is less than a tribute in a
field where common sense should prevail. No kamikaze spirit here,
thank you.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the pilots' concerns are legitimate. There are issues
that rumble through an industry in flux and driven by intense
competition, with periodic price wars, constant pressure to cut
costs, and frequent attempts to start new regional lines. Pilots,
cabin personnel, and other employees have turned to strikes in
clashes over hours and conditions of work.
</P>
<P>
   The American Airlines dispute is only peripherally related to
these issues. The airline is acquiring a regional carrier, Reno
Air, with a rival union, lower pay scales, and different work
rules. American's pilots object to the way the integration will
occur. They argue that their contract requires that all of
American's pilots belong to their union and receive their pay and
benefits.
</P>
<P>
   But the dispute at this point does not involve their own
security or compensation. It is, as one pilot said, a matter of a
slippery slope in which future rights might be eroded. The
breakdown of talks on the issue argues that there were hardened
positions on both sides that led to the sickout, crippling
operations until a federal judge intervened and fined the pilots
$10 million.
</P>
<P>
   Among organized employees, pilots are well paid and generally
enjoy public confidence and admiration. The spectacle of
knock-down, drag-out battles between privileged parties enhances no
one's reputation and runs the risk of alienating a flying public
that already sees itself more in the role of cattle than paying
customer. Some accommodation, please, on both sides.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
