<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FRUGAL-FILENES-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SUIT FOCUSES ON WEEKEND RETAIL PRACTICES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CHRIS REIDY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Does a ``weekend warrior'' retailer _ a chain that
opens its stores only on weekends _ use inventory practices and
pricing policies that are so peculiar and rare that they constitute
trade secrets that merit special protection?
</P>
<P>
   That's an issue that may have to be decided by Suffolk Superior
Court judge Barbara J. Rouse.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday an attorney for the Westwood company that operates
Frugal Fannie's Fashion Warehouse told Rouse's court that its trade
secrets may have been compromised when Filene's Basement Corp.
hired Frugal Fannie's former president last year to help launch
Aisle 3, a chain of stores that, like Frugal Fannie's, will open
only on weekends and holidays.
</P>
<P>
   Frugal Fannie's is seeking a preliminary injunction that would
prevent its former president, James A. McGowan, from working for
Aisle 3's weekend-only operations; McGowan could still work for the
Basement's seven-day-a-week operations.
</P>
<P>
   But what Frugal Fannie's regards as trade secrets are common
industry practices, and it is harldy the only weekend warrior in
retail, claims Wellesley-based Filene's Basement.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is not a case about trade secrets; this is a case about
competition,'' said Basement attorney Robert Popeo of the Boston
law firm of Mintz Levin Cohn Ferris Glovsky and Popeo.
</P>
<P>
   Rouse heard arguments from both sides Wednesday but did not
issue a ruling.
</P>
<P>
   One odd twist in the case: Court documents hint that the
Basement was in negotiations to acquire Frugal Fannie's in the
fall. Negotiations broke off before a deal could be reached.
</P>
<P>
   At the heart of the case may be what constitutes a weekend
warrior's retail trade secrets.
</P>
<P>
   With estimated annual revenues of about $60 million, Frugal
Fannie's operates about seven stores.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, to augment annual revenues of about $560 million,
Filene's Basement plans to open the Aisle 3 weekend chain that will
be separate from its traditional off-price stores. The new chain
will open its first stores in Maryland, New York, and New Jersey.
</P>
<P>
   According to Frugal Fannie's, operating a weekend store is
radically different from running a seven-day-a-week retailer.
</P>
<P>
   The inventory practices, pricing policies, and advertising
strategies that a weekend store uses are so singular that they
constitute trade secrets, said Frugal Fannie attorney Kenneth R.
Berman of the Boston law firm of Sherin and Lodgen.
</P>
<P>
   And when Filene's Basement hired McGowan, a top Frugal Fannie's
executive from 1996 to 1998, to help launch its Aisle 3 format, the
Basement may have improperly benefitted from Frugal Fannie's trade
secrets, Berman claimed.
</P>
<P>
   In dispute is how McGowan left Frugal Fannie's. One scenario had
him resigning after Frugal Fannie's rejected his plan to rapidly
expand the chain. Another had him taking this blueprint for weekend
growth to Filene's Basement.
</P>
<P>
   According to Frugal Fannie's, McGowan signed on as a
$30,000-per-month consultant to Filene's Basement in June while he
was still an executive at Frugal Fannie's, a characterization
disputed by McGowan's attorney, Mary E. O'Neal of the Boston law
firm of Masterman Culbert &AMP; Tully.
</P>
<P>
   Arguing on behalf of Filene's Basement, Popeo said that Aisle
3's stores will be much larger than Frugal Fannies stores and have
a very different merchandise mix.
</P>
<P>
   Frugal Fannie's sells mostly private-label clothing to women,
Popeo claimed, but Aisle 3 will sell brand-name men's and women's
clothing as well as home furnishings and gourmet food.
</P>
<P>
   Plans call for nine Aisle 3 stores to open this year; none of
these stores will be ``within 50 miles'' of an existing Frugal
Fannie's store, Popeo asserted, though Berman wondered whether
future Aisle 3 stores would encroach on Frugal Fannie turf.
</P>
<P>
   Popeo also noted that Filene's Basement has paid various
consultants about $10 million in its efforts to launch Aisle 3.
</P>
<P>
   If McGowan had shared any trade secrets with his new employer
and if these secrets had any value to a retailer whose annual sales
are nearly 10 times greater than Frugal Fannie's, the Basement
wouldn't have needed the services of so many consultants, Popeo
suggested.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-17-99 2023EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990217.0412 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-17 20:23 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9313 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BUDGET-ECONSCENE-NYT &LR;      02-17 1013
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUDGET-ECONSCENE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEWS ANALYSIS: NOT ALL DEBT IS BAD, ADMINISTRATION TELLS GOP
CRITICS 
</HEADLINE>
  (nk) 
 By MICHAEL M. WEINSTEIN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Congressional Republicans are finding all kinds of suspicious
elements in President Clinton's budget plan.
</P>
<P>
   First, they accused the administration of double counting the
surplus in the Social Security program _ the amount by which
payroll taxes in a given year exceed payments to retirees _ by
adding it twice to the Social Security trust fund. Though the
charge is technically accurate, it lacks, according to many
economists, the nefarious purpose or impact implied by its critics.
</P>
<P>
   Now, Rep. Wally Herger, R-Calif., a member of the House budget
committee, pointing to page 389 of the president's budget, accuses
the president of proposing to increase the federal debt by more
than $1 trillion by 2004. So a budget that the administration
boasts would use trillions of dollars over the next 15 years to buy
back government bonds held by the public in reality, according to
this argument, digs a deeper financial hole.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Bill Archer, R-Texas, chairman of the House Ways and Means
Committee, says the plan will put a ``large burden on our children
and grandchildren who will have to repay this debt.'' Sen. William
V. Roth Jr., R-Del., chairman of the Senate Finance Committee, has
made similar criticisms.
</P>
<P>
   Once again, according to administration officials and many
outside analysts, the Republican accusations are factually correct
but substantively confused.
</P>
<P>
   Herger asks, ``If, as the administration claims, the budget is
balanced and saves Social Security, why is federal debt still
rising?''
</P>
<P>
   The administration's answer also lies on page 389 of the budget,
two lines below the figures Herger focuses on. The table shows that
under the Clinton plan, federal debt held by the public _ let's
call it external debt _ falls from about $3.7 trillion today to
about $3.3 trillion in 2004. But, as the Republican critics note,
total federal debt rises from about $5.6 trillion to about $6.8
trillion during the same period. Total debt equals debt held by the
public (external debt) plus debt held by various government
agencies or trust funds (let's call that internal debt).
</P>
<P>
   The answer to Herger's question is that the two debt figures
move in opposite directions because the president proposes to use
surplus revenue from the Social Security payroll tax to buy back
government bonds held by the public. External debt would fall. The
president would then, in effect, deposit the purchased bonds into
the Social Security and Medicare trust funds. Internal debt would
rise, because the bonds represent loans from the trust funds to the
Treasury. Some day the funds will return those bonds for cash.
</P>
<P>
   So which side has the better economic case: the Democrats, who
point to falling external debt as a virtue, or the Republicans, who
point to rising internal debt as a vice?
</P>
<P>
   External debt _ borrowing money from the public _ has real
economic consequences. It siphons dollars away from savers and,
therefore, private capital markets. Private investment drops,
leaving the economy with less plant, equipment and technological
change. Depending on how the government uses the borrowed money,
economic growth could suffer.
</P>
<P>
   Internal debt siphons no money out of the economy. It draws down
no private saving or investment. For one agency to lend money to
another agency is akin to taking $20 out of one's right pocket,
depositing it into the left pocket and reimbursing the right pocket
with a $20 IOU. The internal loan does not change the person's
financial status one iota. One can still spend $20, nothing more
and nothing less.
</P>
<P>
   By running down external debt and running up internal debt, the
president leaves more money in private capital markets. Indeed, his
plan nearly wipes out external debt, drawing it down from almost 45
percent of gross domestic product today to about 7 percent in 15
years.
</P>
<P>
   Internal debt soars under the plan: The right pocket of
government owes the left pocket a whole lot more money.
</P>
<P>
   Yet Archer takes a look at these trends and cries foul on behalf
of his grandchildren. The administration's defense comes in two
parts.
</P>
<P>
   First, its budget would not raise Social Security spending by a
nickel now or in the future. Retirement benefits are determined by
statute, not by the size of the trust fund. If Clinton never added
a bond to the trust fund, government would still owe retirees money
_ money that, if otherwise unavailable, would have to be raised by
borrowing or taxing. The bonds add no burden on future taxpayers.
</P>
<P>
   Second, the administration's budget projections show large
overall surpluses even during the years when the Social Security
trust fund will be returning bonds to the Treasury for cash. The
surpluses, if they materialize, guarantee that the Treasury would
have enough cash to redeem the Social Security bonds and still pay
for other federal programs. Archer's grandchildren will not have to
pay extra taxes. Nor will government have to invade private capital
markets.
</P>
<P>
   There are legitimate reasons to question the president's plan.
Should Congress pledge money to Social Security based on guesses
that federal surpluses will materialize in the future? Should
Congress, by piling up bonds in the Social Security and Medicare
trust funds, give those programs first call on general tax
revenues? After all, the political consensus behind Social Security
rests in part on the fact that the program has depended from its
inception on its own source of money, the payroll tax.
</P>
<P>
   But recent Republican criticisms take on different colors.
``Debt is debt, and no matter how classified, our children and
grandchildren must repay,'' Herger says.
</P>
<P>
   This, says the administration, reflects a fundamental confusion.
All debt is far from the same. External debt can be cancerous.
Internal debt is benign. There is as much need to drive down
internal debt as there is for my right pocket to repay my left
pocket.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-17-99 2023EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
