<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-17 20:27 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9318 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HUD-BOSTON-BOS &LR;      02-17 0972
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HUD-BOSTON-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HUD CHARGES BOSTON WITH HOUSING DISCRIMINATION 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JUDY RAKOWSKY AND LOUISE D. PALMER  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Federal housing officials charged Boston Wednesday
with ``systematic discrimination'' against nine minority families
when they lived in South Boston and Charlestown housing
developments, calling it the most serious discrimination case ever
brought against a local housing agency.
</P>
<P>
   ``Housing discrimination is an ugly part of our nation's past
that has no place in America today,'' said Housing Secretary Andrew
Cuomo
</P>
<P>
   Claims of racially motivated vandalism, assaults, and harassment
were downplayed or ignored by Boston housing officials from 1990
through 1996, the US Department of Housing and Urban Development
found in a three-year investigation.
</P>
<P>
   Requests for protection and emergency transfers ran into brick
walls of bureaucracy, with Boston Housing Authority police and
staff members refusing to uphold civil rights complaints or
demanding extensive data to back up the simplest assault claim,
according to HUD.
</P>
<P>
   At times, even though Boston police substantiated claims of
harassment or hate crimes, the information never made it into BHA
files or was not pursued by the housing agency, HUD found.
</P>
<P>
   Conversely, BHA never invoked lease restrictions that permitted
officials to evict tenants for harassing minority neighbors by
setting fires, tying doors closed, smashing windows, and slashing
tires, HUD found.
</P>
<P>
   Cuomo also announced a 30-day investigation into the BHA's
actions since 1996. A HUD special counsel will determine whether
Boston followed through on a 1996 agreement with the federal
government to enforce a policy of ``zero tolerance'' of racial and
ethnic discrimination.
</P>
<P>
   Based on the findings of that review, HUD could tighten
supervision on BHA or further restrict how it spends the $141
million a year it receives in federal money, Cuomo said.
</P>
<P>
   In Boston, lawyers for the nine families welcomed HUD's
findings, although they said the three-year wait was hard on their
clients.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our clients have waited a long time for their complaints to be
vindicated,'' said Nadine Cohen, an attorney volunteering for the
Lawyers' Committee for Civil Rights, an arm of the Boston Bar
Association. ``There was a culture at BHA that didn't want to see
the harassment going on,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Armed with the HUD findings, the nine families can choose to
seek damages from one of three forums: an administrative law judge,
suits filed through the Department of Justice in US District Court,
or pursuing the civil suit already pending against BHA and city
officials in federal Court.
</P>
<P>
   The families would have to ask for damages based on the
emotional distress and lost materials they suffered. But the BHA's
exposure varies widely depending on which avenue the families
follow: An administrative law judge could order BHA to pay up to
$10,000 for each of the nine victims plus another $10,000 for the
systemic discrimination that HUD found. If the federal government
sued, BHA could face fines of up to $50,000 per offense. But if the
families pursue the suit they filed in February 1996, BHA could
face unlimited damages, according to HUD officials.
</P>
<P>
   Mayor Thomas Menino was visibly upset Wednesday over the damning
report, about which he said he expected a warning from HUD and
Cuomo specifically, rather than being ``blindsided'' by press
reports. Menino defended BHA Administrator Sandra Henriquez and
recent efforts by the agency to evict wrongdoers and stamp out
intolerance. Menino and Henriquez, who was hired in 1996, stressed
that none of the incidents cited by HUD occurred on her watch.
</P>
<P>
   But City Council President James Kelly, of South Boston,
questioned HUD's findings and said he has reviewed complaints of
minority residents of South Boston housing complexes in the past
and found them to be overstated.
</P>
<P>
   ``I suspect there's a lot of fabrication and a lot of
exaggeration in the least,'' Kelly said. ``It's all about making a
financial settlement for people who are willing to take the time
and claim that they've been victimized by white people in general
and the system.''
</P>
<P>
   In contrast, Ozell Hudson, executive director of the Lawyers
Committee for Civil Rights, representing the tenants for free, said
that while his clients will accept at least $1 million in
compensation for the incidents, the case is not motivated simply by
money awards.
</P>
<P>
   ``This case is about remedying the longstanding practice of
discrimination,'' Hudson said. ``BHA acquiesed and condoned this
systematic, egregious discrimination and became co-conspirators in
it.''
</P>
<P>
   HUD's findings of a failure system-wide at the BHA to shield
tenants or to even devise a clear procedure for seeking remedies
for discrimination differs from its past cases. HUD has always been
able to reach settlements between city housing agencies and the
complaining tenants, said one HUD official in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   But Boston did not move to integrate the Old Colony housing
development in South Boston and the Bunker Hill development in
Charlestown until the federal government forced the move in 1988.
</P>
<P>
   Even then, with a consent decree in place, HUD said, the agency
did not protect tenants from racial and ethnic discrimination.
</P>
<P>
   ``BHA is one of the bureaucracies where who you know gets you
your job and allows you to keep your job,'' said Hudson, adding
that BHA employees should be disciplined or fired in the wake of
the HUD report.
</P>
<P>
   ``Heads might have to roll,'' Hudson said.
</P>
<P>
   The BHA, said HUD, has argued that it had policies in place to
protect its tenants between 1992 and 1996, and that significant
improvements had been made since 1996. But HUD rejected these
arguments.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
