<SLUG> BC-LEWINSKY-INTERVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WALTERS SEEKS NOD FROM STARR TO INTERVIEW LEWINSKY 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By LAWRIE MIFFLIN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Barbara Walters of ABC News continues to be
frustrated by the Office of the Independent Counsel in her effort
to interview Monica Lewinsky, but the newswoman hopes to gain the
necessary clearance by the end of this week, said ABC News
officials, who spoke on condition of anonymity.
</P>
<P>
   The officials said there was cautious hope that Walters would
get the interview in time for it to be broadcast on ``20/20'' on
March 3, the final night of the February ``sweeps'' rating period,
whose Nielsen rating figures are used to set advertising rates for
the next quarterly period.
</P>
<P>
   Although the impeachment proceedings have ended, Ms. Lewinsky
has not yet been given dispensation from Kenneth Starr, the
independent counsel, to proceed with her agreed-upon exclusive
interview with Walters.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Lewinsky's lawyers declined to comment.
</P>
<P>
   Charles Bakaly III, the spokesman for Starr, did not respond to
telephone messages seeking comment. In the past, he has declined to
discuss the conditions under which Ms. Lewinsky might be permitted
to speak to news organizations.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Lewinsky's immunity agreement specifies that ``pending a
final resolution of this matter,'' she may not talk to
representatives of news organizations ``without first obtaining the
OIC's approval.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Ms. Lewinsky's book, co-authored with Andrew Morton,
is nearly finished. But the publisher, St. Martin's Press, is still
deciding how to proceed. Within St. Martin's, a division of
Macmillan Publishers Ltd., there has been debate about whether the
silencing order could be skirted by insisting that Morton, as an
author, is not a member of a news organization.
</P>
<P>
   A publishing executive who insisted on anonymity said Ms.
Lewinsky would not proceed with the interview with Walters unless
the book was completed because of concerns that the book's sales
would be hurt if it was published too far after the interview. St.
Martin's is hoping the book will be completed by the end of this
month.
</P>
</TEXT>
