<SLUG> BC-NY-IMMIGRANT-FUNERAL-ART-625&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SHOOTING VICTIM IS BURIED IN HIS HOME VILLAGE 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036.) 
(lh) 
 By SUSAN SACHS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOLLANDE BOURU, Guinea _ Amadou Diallo, wrapped in a white cloth
and covered with hand-hewn logs and fragrant leaves, was buried
Wednesday under a fig tree in the village that his
great-grandfather founded more than 100 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   The funeral, deep in the parched countryside of Guinea, ended a
remarkable journey that began with the death of Diallo death two
weeks ago, when he was shot by four New York City police officers
who were searching for someone else.
</P>
<P>
   About 1,500 relatives and friends, including two government
ministers and every local official, crowded into the village of
round thatched huts and simple concrete-block houses. Most walked
to Hollande Bouru across miles of rock-studded fields and past
fences of dried twigs lashed together. Many had been waiting since
Sunday in the village, which has no electricity or running water,
to recite prayers over Diallo's body and to accompany it with
melodic chanting to the cemetery.
</P>
<P>
   The number of mourners was a sign of the size and prestige of
his vast extended family in Guinea, a country of 7 million where
Diallo's ethnic group, the Fulani, makes up 40 percent of the
population. It was also further evidence of how Diallo, an unarmed
black immigrant shot at 41 times by white officers at his home in
the Bronx, has become a symbol for many Guineans of everything that
can go wrong for a young black man who tries to follow a dream of a
better life far from home.
</P>
<P>
   ``I remember my father saying before he died, `God bless
America,''' said Amadou Balde, who is married to one of Diallo's
aunts and drives a taxi in the capital, Conakry, 300 miles south of
Hollande Bouru. ``But when I got big, I realized that in America
somebody can just take a gun and prey on you.''
</P>
<P>
   The plain pine coffin containing Diallo's body arrived in the
village before dawn, having made a journey from a Harlem funeral
home to the Islamic Cultural Center of New York for a tumultuous
prayer service, and to Newark (N.J.) International Airport at the
head of a motorcade organized by the National Action Network, a
black political organization.
</P>
<P>
   The arrival of the coffin in Conakry on Monday night was greeted
by the country's government ministers, who led a procession that
sped the body from the airport to a morgue. But when the
much-traveled coffin arrived by Guinean military truck in Hollande
Bouru, it was met with a ritual of simple dignity.
</P>
<P>
   Villagers placed it on a carpet in a small concrete-block
building, called the Grandfathers' House, where all the significant
events, from marriage to communal meetings to funeral services,
take place. Women and men filed in to weep or pray silently.
</P>
<P>
   Diallo's 71-year-old maternal grandfather, Ahmadou Bailo Diallo,
edged in and nodded to the men around him to open the coffin.
</P>
<P>
   When the zinc-lined top was lifted off, he gently turned back
the shroud covering his grandson's face for the mourners to see.
The grandfather's expression did not change.
</P>
<P>
   Amadou Diallo, who spent most of his life outside Guinea,
visited Hollande Bouru, a village of 10,000 people, on school
holidays, but never lived there. Still, his father, Saikou Amad
Diallo, is one of its wealthiest and most prominent men. A trader
since his teens, when he bought a truck and drove it loaded with
cotton, coffee and other products from Guinea to neighboring
countries, Saikou Diallo set up import-export companies in Liberia,
Singapore, Thailand and Togo.
</P>
<P>
   Upon hearing of the death of Amadou, the third of his four sons,
he flew to New York from Ho Chi Minh City, Vietnam, which is now
his home. His trip with his son's body is his first visit here in
14 years.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Saikou Diallo received condolences and greetings from the porch
of a concrete house, one of the largest in the village, that he
built in 1973. Hollande Bouru, he said, was founded by his
grandfather, who brought his relatives there from a nearby city to
raise cattle. The villagers still have cattle and grow corn and
root vegetables. Orange trees rise from the packed dirt between the
huts.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not a poor village,'' said the elder Diallo. Then he
corrected himself. ``It's poor, of course,'' he added. ``But
everyone survives on their own labor.''
</P>
<P>
   The only funeral ever held in the village that rivaled Diallo's
in size was that of his paternal grandfather, Ibrahim, who taught
boys from all the surrounding villages the Islamic holy book, the
Koran.
</P>
<P>
   Amadou Diallo was buried next to his revered grandfather. Saikou
Diallo said he planned to build a Koranic school near the cemetery
to honor both of them.
</P>
<P>
   Around 2:30 p.m. Wednesday, shortly after Diallo's parents
arrived at the village from Conakry after a nine-hour trip on roads
that ranged from rutted asphalt to red dirt, the coffin was carried
to a spot near the cemetery and placed in front of a twisted bare
tree called the teke, facing east toward Mecca.
</P>
<P>
   There, speakers raised the subject of how Diallo died.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have come to say to the men of the village where Amadou's
father and grandfather come from, that we in America pledge to
fight for justice for Amadou,'' the Rev. Al Sharpton, who has made
the Diallo killing a political cause for his National Action
Network and helped finance the parents' trips to New York and to
Guinea, said in remarks translated into the Fulani language. ``We
will not rest until those who are guilty face justice.''
</P>
<P>
   A group of men rose to carry the coffin to the cemetery, where
it was opened and the shrouded body gently lowered into the grave.
Atop the body, the men placed lengths of different kinds of wood,
cut from trees near the village, followed by boughs from the fig
tree above and, finally, dirt. In keeping with Islamic custom, the
coffin was discarded.
</P>
<P>
   Calmly, the crowd turned from the grave and wandered back
through the village for conversation and food and to comfort the
family.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
