<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-17 20:31 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9322 &Cx1f; tth-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BOOKS-TULIPS-SPI &LR;      02-17 1104
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOKS-TULIPS-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AN EPIC DRAMA OF THE `FLOWER THAT HAS MADE MEN MAD' 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JOHN MARSHALL  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Tulips still entice with their vibrant colors, their sensuous
shape, their delicate grace, their promise of summer to follow.
</P>
<P>
   Tulips, though, have now become so commonplace that they are
sold in grocery stores, which is why it is difficult to imagine
that this one flower could create fortunes, prompt bankruptcies,
undermine heads of state, spur intrigues, engender passions, foster
art in various mediums and enflame unquenchable obsessions.
</P>
<P>
   Yet this is indeed the amazing history of the tulip, as British
gardening writer Anna Pavord makes clear in her fascinating and
sumptuous new account, ``The Tulip: The Story of a Flower That Has
Made Men Mad'' (Bloomsbury, 439 pages, $35).
</P>
<P>
   This is not a gardening book, with planting tips and how-to
hints. This is instead an epic drama, a true tale that spans
continents and centuries, shows humankind at its worst and its
best, with heroes and villains galore., And it's already a No. 1
best seller in Britain.
</P>
<P>
   No one is more astonished by its success than the author
herself, one of Britain's leading gardening journalists, who
thought for a long time that all the research on tulips that she
had collected over the years was probably just a reflection of her
own obsession.
</P>
<P>
   Pavord, 58, has been so consumed by tulips that she had no
hesitancy about driving through dangerous, isolated sections of the
Turkish countryside, near the border with Iran, in hopes of
actually glimpsing tulips growing in the wild. And She was not even
deterred even when frequent army roadroundblocks resulted in
machine guns being stuck poked inside the car.
</P>
<P>
   Pavord and her companions, including her husband of 33 years,
were deathly afraid, but the mission was definitely worth the
perils. She was searching, after all, for tulips.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I had died then,'' Pavord said in an interview, ``I would
have died happy.''
</P>
<P>
   Pavord is a Wales-born force of nature, a farmer's daughter of
guileless charms and irresistible enthusiasms. She laughs hardest
when she laughs at her own predilections and predicaments.
</P>
<P>
   Pavord is abuzz when describing her brief visit this week to the
still-dormant tulip fields of the Skagit Valley north of Seattle
and meeting growers there: ``They wanted my autograph _ crumbs! For
me, meeting them was like meeting a Rothschild!''
</P>
<P>
   She is quieter, but still unabashed, when describing her battle
against cancer last year that resulted in major surgery, but did
not convince her to undergo radiation or chemotheraphy: ``My future
is in the lap of the gods, but my will is as strong as any machine
_ and I did not want to muck up my body.''
</P>
<P>
   But nothing seems to inspire Pavord's zeal quite like the tulip.
She can readily recall the first tulip she ever planted four
decades ago. Its charactertistics are as fresh to her as today's
bouquet. It was love at first bloom. It was also a case, she later
understood, of how opposites do attract.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm, by nature, solitary and introverted, a woman of such
height that I was ungainly until I learned to carry myself,''
Pavord related. ``I just wish I was like a tulip _ with its
flamboyance, its sexiness _ but I don't share any of the tulip's
traits.''
</P>
<P>
   Those traits enslaved the fancies of men and women from the time
the tulip was discovered in the wilds of central Asia and the
Caucasus.
</P>
<P>
   The enflamed passion for the flower swept across the Ottoman
Empire and then successive countries in Europe, starting in the
1500s, and finally engulfed America as well.
</P>
<P>
   Tulips were worn in turbans in Turkey (the source of a
misunderstanding that led to the tulip's name: When a Flemish
ambassador asked an interpreter the name of an unfamiliar flower
tucked in a turban, he mistakenly picked up and later used the word
for turban instead of the word for tulip).
</P>
<P>
   Tulips were worn in the decolletage of dresses in France just
like diamond jewelry.
</P>
<P>
   Tulips became a symbol of love. ``When a young man presents a
tulip to his mistress,'' reported a 17th-century traveler in Iran,
``he gives her to understand by the general colour of the flower,
that he is on fire with her beauty, and by the black base, that his
heart has burned to coal.''
</P>
<P>
   There were even periods of unbridled tulipomania, first in
France and later in Holland, times in which the tulip was in such
demand and subject to such speculation that it was the Amazon.com
stock of its day. The price of a single bulb of a prized tulip
variety escalated so steeply at Holland auctions, between 1634 and
1637, that it rivaled the cost of the best townhome in Amsterdam.
</P>
<P>
   The mania was fueled by the great mystery of how the most prized
tulips would ``break'' into different colors and patterns. This
phenomenon was not explained until the 1920s when the electron
microscope revealed that such breaks were caused by a most mundane
source _ a plant virus transported by an aphid.
</P>
<P>
   Pavord revels in such ironies in tulip history, but none more
than the fact that the most beautiful tulips ever bred came from
the work of dedicated amateurs in England. These were tradesmen and
artisans in the early 1800s with tough daily lives who were
slavishly devoted to perfecting the beauty of a flower, despite the
seven years it takes for a tulip seed to become a tulip bulb.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was the most touching thing I discovered in my
research,'' Pavord stresses. ``Here were shoemakers and people who
had started working in factories at age 8, people with horrible
lives, and they gave us some of the most beautiful tulips ever.
They had a commitment to the ideal of beauty, despite their grim
circumstances.''
</P>
<P>
   Tulips have gone on to become a worldwide industry, dominated by
the Netherlands. That small country devotes almost half of its land
to growing tulip bulbs and annually exports 2 billion bulbs.
</P>
<P>
   Varieties of tulips once carried names that spoke poetry about
the flower's allure _ Sparkling Fire, Spring Song, Black Swan,
Eros. Now tulips have become such a part of popular culture that
varieties sport names that include President Kennedy, Scarlett
O'Hara, Bing Crosby and Mickey Mouse.
</P>
<P>
   Tulipomania may have faded, but the magic of the tulip still
remains.
</P>
<P>
   As Pavord writes, ``On a grey, sunless day, when a northeasterly
wind is whipping the skin off the backs of your knuckles, nothing
cheers the heart more than a bunch of tulips, weaving and bending
in their vase like a flock of inquisitive birds.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
