<HEADER>
A9325 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HEINZ-CUTBACKS-NYT &LR;      02-17 0859
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HEINZ-CUTBACKS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HEINZ PLANS DRAMATIC CHANGES AND LAYOFFS  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Pa., Fla., Italy )  By DAVID BARBOZA    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Hoping to revitalize its sagging food business, H.J. Heinz Co.
said Wednesday that over the next four or five years it would
revamp its global operations, lay off up to 10 percent of its work
force and sell its Weight Watchers International division.
</P>
<P>
   The company, which had sales of more than $9 billion last year,
said the moves would amount to the ``greatest transformation in the
history of Heinz,'' eventually generating savings of more than $200
million a year and earnings-per-share growth of 10 percent to 12
percent, not including the sale of Weight Watchers.
</P>
<P>
   As part of the plan, the maker of Heinz ketchup, Star-Kist tuna
and other well-known processed foods said it would raise spending
on marketing to stimulate the sales of food products that have been
losing market share in recent years.
</P>
<P>
   Wall Street analysts, who were not surprised by the
announcement, cheered the news, saying it showed that after two
years of flat sales growth, Heinz was disciplining its management
team and sharpening its strategy.
</P>
<P>
   ``This allows Heinz to focus on grocery,'' said John McMillin, a
food industry analyst at Prudential Securities. ``They're a food
company, they're not in the preaching business. I think they're on
a better path than they were before.''
</P>
<P>
   Shares of Heinz, which had climbed about 8 percent in the week
leading up to the announcement, rose 25 cents Wednesday, to
$55.875.
</P>
<P>
   Because of the make-over, Heinz will take a charge of more than
$1 billion over the next four years. But the company expects to
reap tremendous cost savings and invest an additional $100 million
in marketing and pricing initiatives to lift sales.
</P>
<P>
   While the Weight Watchers classroom operation, which counsels
customers on weight loss, increasingly had become profitable the
last year, officials at Heinz said that it was not a vital fit in
the food business. The company did not say how much the unit would
bring, but nearly 30 million people have attended sessions the last
year and operating profits have been projected at $85 million.
Heinz will, however, retain its Weight Watchers food line.
</P>
<P>
   The company declined to comment on whether it would also divest
itself of the Cardio-Fitness Corp., a smaller health and fitness
division based in New York.
</P>
<P>
   But Heinz officials did say a drastic make-over was under way in
everything from marketing and packaging to the introduction of new
products. Heinz officials hope these moves will help revitalize a
company that has been best-known for ketchup; Charlie the Tuna, the
cartoon pitchman for Star-Kist; Ore-Ida frozen potatoes, and Morris
the Cat's favorite food, 9 Lives.
</P>
<P>
   The announcement, which came during the Consumer Analysts Group
of New York meeting in Naples, Fla., the company said it would
close up to 20 factories around the world, downsize at least 10
more and reduce its 43,000-strong work force by about 4,000. Other
factories would be expanded and dedicated to particular products.
</P>
<P>
   The company, based in Pittsburgh, did not say how many jobs
would be cut in the United States. But about a third of the plant
closings are expected to take place in Europe.
</P>
<P>
   Heinz also will reorganize its global operations by doing away
with affiliate units, such as Heinz Italy, in favor of organizing
the company along six primary categories and six regions. That
shift, the company said, will streamline operations, improve how
factories are used and save hundreds of millions of dollars that
could later be used to increase sales of its core food products.
</P>
<P>
   ``The $64,000 question is. `Will this restructuring help
transform top-line growth?' '' said McMillin. ``It definitely
supplies the ammunition, but will they be able to move the needle
on ketchup or frozen potatoes? It's not easy to change consumer
behavior.''
</P>
<P>
   The man trying to transform Heinz is William R. Johnson, who
took over as the chief executive at Heinz in 1998 after the company
was criticized for lavish spending, high executive salaries and a
lagging stock price under his predecessor, Anthony J.F. O'Reilly.
</P>
<P>
   Since 1996, the company has lost market share in some of its key
products. Now, Johnson and Heinz say they will bolster marketing
and advertising costs, introduce new pricing initiatives _
including a 99-cent commemorative bottle of Heinz ketchup _ and
introduce new packaging as a way to win back market share.
</P>
<P>
   Several Wall Street analysts say Heinz has not been aggressively
marketing and advertising its products and that it raised its
prices on several items, allowing smaller private-label companies
to gain market share. Now it is trying to reverse that course, and
the company says recent marketing pushes have led to stronger sales
of ketchup.
</P>
<P>
   ``In Ore-Ida, they've been losing market share to private labels
because of the gap in price,'' said Nomi Ghez, an analyst at
Goldman, Sachs. ``But everything we heard today is good news. The
company is definitely doing what's right for the long term.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
