<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEXICO-MOVIES-LATINTRADE-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOGGING THE LIMELIGHT _ AND AN ACT OF CONGRESS: A TALK WITH MARIA
ROJO
</HEADLINE>
  (This ``separate buy'' article is from Latin Trade magazine.) 
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times sales representatives OLIVIA
VASQUEZ in Los Angeles at 310-798-0970 or fax at 310-798-7338; or
KARL HORWITZ in Paris at 47-42-17-11, or fax at 47-42-80-44 or
47-42-18-81; or CONNIE WHITE in Kansas City at 1-800-444-0267 or
816-822-8448, or fax at 816-822-1444.) 
 (They also have information on how to subscribe to Latin Trade's
service for newspapers _ the magazine's exclusives and other
articles are transmitted every week.) 
 By BRENDAN M. CASE and DOUGLASS STINSON 
 c.1999 Latin Trade 
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) 
 &HT;    
 &HT;    MEXICO CITY _ In the golden age of Mexican cinema, the ballads
of mariachis and the antics of Cantinflas ruled theater screens
from the Rio Grande to Tierra del Fuego.
 &HT;    But the success of the 1940s and 1950s led to excess. The
government controlled ticket prices, distribution, and even theater
ownership. The labor union was so tough that it allowed only one
employee per cinema to serve popcorn and one to serve soft drinks.
Those patrons who wanted both had to stand in line twice. Once
inside, the entertainment value fell further: The popcorn was
usually stale, the screens rundown and the seats so decrepit that
some patrons reported sustaining flea bites.
 &HT;    Over the years, theater attendance plummeted from a high of 400
million tickets sold in 1980 to 60 million in 1995. ``It was
tragic,'' says Roberto Jenkins, the general director of Cinemark in
Mexico. ``People stopped going to the movies and rented movies to
watch at home instead.''
 &HT;    Now, Mexican movie theatres are entering a new golden era.
Cinemark is one of several companies building multiplexes with
sparkling sound systems and fresh popcorn that have moviegoers
giving up the VCR in favor of a flick. This year, operators will
sell more than 100 million tickets, according to the National
Cinema Chamber.
 &HT;    The deluxe cinema chains, on par with the comforts of any movie
house in the world, have coaxed Mexicans back to the movies. But
they offer little else other than Hollywood blockbusters at a time
when the Mexican film industry is slogging through a slump.
 &HT;    During the industry's heyday, nearly 100 films came out each
year. But over each of the last two years, Mexican cinematographers
have turned out less than a dozen films. Funding is the perennial
problem. ``There's no way to produce movies in Mexico,'' says
independent film maker V ictor Ugalde. ``The only funding comes
from the [government's Cinema Fund and it rejects many interesting
projects.''
 &HT;    Plagued by poor distribution and lackluster promotion, the few
locally produced films face predictably little public interest. The
often money-losing ventures command even less attention from
private financiers.
 &HT;    Critics contend what the industry needs is more control. In
response to the nationalistic cry, Maria Rojo, a former actress
turned politician, pushed through Congress a law that requires
theaters to reserve 10 percent of screen time for domestic films.
``We're talking about part of our cultural heritage,'' says
congresswoman Rojo.
 &HT;    Owners of movie theaters, however, say the new law goes against
the emerging free-market culture that has allowed them to flourish.
They fear that the legislation will simply lock them into showing
money-losing flicks.
 &HT;    Both government and unions were removed from the movie business
in recent years as a part of the country's economic reforms. In
their place, several entrepreneurs have invested nearly US$400
million to open an estimated 1,000 state-of-the-art theaters across
the country. To ensure a speedy return on their investment, the new
movie-theater moguls are showing the films that they believe people
want to see: the best action films, romances and comedies coming
out of the Mecca of filmed entertainment, Hollywood. ``Hey, I want
Mexican movies to work as much as the next guy, but when they suck
I have to pull them because no one will pay to see them,'' says one
theater executive. ``I need to maximize profits.''
 &HT;    Such market rationale prevails at the three companies that have
pioneered the new generation of theaters: Grupo Cinemex,
Organizacion Ramirez and Cinemark. And their logic seems to be
paying off.
 &HT;    Despite eroding purchasing power, moviegoers now spend as much
as US$3 per megaplex ticket. ``People go to the movies to have a
good time,'' says Matthew Heyman, one of Cinemex's three directors,
who together dreamed up the company while studying at Harvard
Business School. ``If you build the sound systems and the screens,
and you make the theaters a fun place to be, people will spend the
money.''
 &HT;    More theaters are on the way. Cinemex recently opened a $15
million complex of 19 theaters in northwestern Mexico City, as well
as several complexes in the provinces. Organizacion Ramirez, which
runs the Cinepolis line of theaters among others, plans to open a
20-theater complex in a huge new mall in Guadalajara in the first
half of 1999.
 &HT;    And despite Congress's nationalist sensibilities, audiences do
not seem to mind foreign films playing on their screens, just as
long as the view is good and the popcorn fresh. ``This is like
going to the movies in the glory days of Mexican cinema, when the
screens were big and everybody went to the movies,'' says Daniel
Rodriguez, a city employee in Mexico City who brought his two young
sons to see Disney's ``A Bug's Life'' at a local Cinemex. ``I'd
like to see more good Mexican movies, but I also like the ones from
Hollywood.''
 &HT;    
 &HT;    AN ACT OF CONGRESS: A TALK WITH MARIA ROJO
 &HT;    In her latest film, Maria Rojo plays a woman overflowing with
love, so much so that she assembles five husbands on whom to lavish
her passions. When her multiple marriages come to light, the main
character is thrust into the media spotlight and she becomes a
champion for women oppressed by overwhelming, macho men.
 &HT;    These days, Rojo's own storyline reads much like that of her
character in the film, ``De noche vienes, Esmeralda'' (``Esmeralda
Comes by Night.'') The actress turned member of Congress is
attempting to save what she loves best. Her passion has pushed her
onto center stage to champion Mexican film against the overwhelming
power of the big-budget Hollywood movie machine.
 &HT;    Rojo sponsored a new law that requires movie theaters to show
Mexican films during a tenth of the theaters' total running time.
Chair of the congressional committee on culture, she spent nearly
two years pushing the bill to change Mexico's cinema law. Her
original proposal was even stronger, asking for nearly a third of
screen time and a tax on movie tickets to fund local filmmaking
efforts.
 &HT;    The 50-year-old film star entered the limelight long ago,
playing her first screen role at age 17. She steadily gained fame
in Mexico from work in the movies and TV soap operas, and starred
in the 1995 El Callejon de los Milagros (known in English as
``Midaq Alley'') which won 49 international awards. Rojo is
considered a major Latin American film star, though she's hardly a
household name in Hollywood. In 1997, she staged a second career,
winning election to Mexico's lower house of Congress.
 &HT;    In her current battle, Rojo has picked up fellow Mexican ally,
blockbuster actress Salma Hayek, who also played supporting role to
Rojo in El Callejon. ``It's important that we promote and support
Mexican talent _ because we have a financial crisis, but we do not
have a talent crisis,'' Hayek said in a recent interview. ``Most of
us [Mexicans in Hollywood have dreams of going back and doing some
quality stuff down there.''
 &HT;    That's exactly why Rojo has been so committed to her cause.
``The cinema in Mexico is a poor industry,'' Rojo has said, ``but
it's there and we want to keep it in existence.''
 &HT;     
 -0- 
 c.1999 Latin Trade 
<TEXT>
 &UR; (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) &QL;
</TEXT>
