<SLUG> BC-LEGO-AD-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ADVERTISING:   TV SPOTS FOR LEGOLAND BORROW FROM SPIELBERG 
</HEADLINE>
  (rk) 
 By ANDREA ADELSON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ As the opening approaches for Legoland, the Lego
Group's $130 million theme park in California, the company will
begin a regional television campaign on Sunday that departs from
traditional amusement park advertising.
</P>
<P>
   Instead of camera cuts from the latest white-knuckle thrill ride
or sentimental spots using life-sized characters, the Lego ads use
contemporary children and special effects to summon up a modern-day
fairy tale filled with mysterious expectation.
</P>
<P>
   Parents who see the spot may notice that it seems to borrow its
emotional texture _ a sense of innocent wonderment _ from the
Steven Spielberg film ``E.T.: The Extra-Terrestrial.''
</P>
<P>
   It isn't the mood alone that seems cribbed from E.T., the
heavy-headed alien whose index finger glowed. In the initial teaser
spots, each child is a recipient of a comet-delivered,
glow-in-the-dark Lego brick. In the ads' second half, the children
are drawn to a moonlit field, a secret society where each reveals a
glowing treasure to the other. The spot ends with a chant,
``Legoland is coming,'' that is reminiscent of the Walt Disney
movie ``The Lion King.''
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't go wrong by doing Spielberg,'' said Bruce R.
Dundore, a partner and chief creative officer for Asher &AMP; Partners
in Los Angeles, the agency that created the $15 million campaign.
``It wasn't intentional,'' added Barry H. Schoenfeld, an Asher
partner and director of business development.
</P>
<P>
   The agency, which also produced the campaign for the New York,
New York casino in Las Vegas, Nev., had a tall order to fill:
standing out in what is considered one of the nation's most
fiercely competitive theme-park markets.
</P>
<P>
   Legoland will open next month on a 128-acre seaside bluff in
Carlsbad, north of San Diego, the third park opened by the Danish
toy company and its first in the United States. Yet an hour or two
away are many better-known rivals, including Universal Studios and
the granddaddy of the industry, Disneyland.
</P>
<P>
   Legoland's promise is to be true to its legacy, a build-your-own
toy that encourages creative thinking among children 12 and
younger. On visits to Legoland parks in Denmark and Britain,
Schoenfeld observed parents and children engaged in a way that
differed markedly from the typical theme-park experience. The
campaign set out to distill that distinction.
</P>
<P>
   At most theme parks, ``the creativity of the builders is set out
for you,'' Schoenfeld said. ``At Legoland, it's almost as if they
took it so far, but the rest is up to you.''
</P>
<P>
   For example, he said, a driving school attraction has no
guardrails, allowing riders to drive when and where they choose. At
another attraction, the ``power tower,'' youngsters propel
themselves up and free fall to the bottom.
</P>
<P>
   ``It isn't about thrills and chills,'' Schoenfeld said. ``What
you get out of the park is what you put into it.''
</P>
<P>
   A second spot, scheduled for broadcast on children's shows
beginning in mid-March through Labor Day, builds on the initial
ads' fairy-tale theme, but with a jack-in-the-beanstalk twist.
</P>
<P>
   The children from the original spot are seen planting their
luminous bricks and are surprised at the result; the ground sprouts
a towering giraffe and slightly threatening dinosaur, built of
cunningly assembled Lego bricks.
</P>
<P>
   The images are among the Lego-brick replicas that populate the
park, including Mount Rushmore, the Statue of Liberty and the White
House. Of the eight model builders, all but one is a veteran of the
Danish park.
</P>
<P>
   ``They captured the essence of it,'' said Marianne M. Flowers,
Legoland's marketing director, referring to the agency. Asher was
selected from among 58 that competed for the account. One element
that set Asher apart, she said, was a resonant jingle, ``Now's a
country just for kids,'' that is incorporated in the second spot.
</P>
<P>
   Legoland seeks to draw 1.8 million visitors in its first year.
The park is promoting weekday use by encouraging student field
trips, offering teachers resource guides in math, physics and
science that are adapted to the state's curriculum.
</P>
<P>
   For example, children will be able to test their skills at
building model cars and racing them on a timed indoor track, and
then make their own comparisons riding the park roller coaster,
said Jonna Rae Bartges, a park spokeswoman.
</P>
<P>
   Education is not really the point, even if Legoland ads lack
commercial directness. The park itself is an oversize commercial.
It conveniently includes a shop that is stocked with a broader
inventory of Lego products than any toy store.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
