<SLUG> BC-TV-ER-415&AMP;ADD-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`ER'S' GEORGE CLOONEY HANGS UP HIS SCRUBS 
</HEADLINE>
   (Eds.: Check local listings for time and channel.)  
 By JOHN CARMAN  
 c.1999, San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   George Clooney leaves ``ER'' Thursday night on the path to
Hollywood immortality, or possibly en route to accidental
obscurity.
</P>
<P>
   It could go either way. Many of the big screen's biggest names _
Clint Eastwood, Tom Hanks, John Travolta, Robin Williams and Eddie
Murphy jump to mind _ made the transition from TV stardom.
</P>
<P>
   But for every Tom Hanks, there's a David Caruso, and for every
Clint Eastwood, a Pernell Roberts _ actors who bailed too soon from
hit shows.
</P>
<P>
   As he departs television's only remaining 30-share series,
Clooney has one thing going for him that Caruso and several other
past evacuees, including McLean Stevenson of ``MASH,'' didn't have.
</P>
<P>
   That's the gratitude and good wishes of the colleagues he leaves
behind. He gave ``ER'' the contractually prescribed five seasons.
He didn't cheat the network, the producers or his friends on the
show.
</P>
<P>
   ``ER'' executive producer John Wells has said that Clooney
``lost literally millions of dollars by staying on the show.''
</P>
<P>
   The reason is that although Clooney has been able to double his
workload and moonlight on the big screen, he presumably could have
been free for more feature film work without his ``ER'' commitment.
</P>
<P>
   ``George has done the thing that few people do,'' Wells said of
Clooney's fidelity to the TV series. ``That ethic is something that
has been less and less present over the last few years.''
</P>
<P>
   Clooney is leaving ``ER'' in just about the way you'd expect his
character, Dr. Douglas Ross, to act. He's taking a risk, but at the
same time flashing his deep-seated loyalty to his colleagues.
</P>
<P>
   NBC didn't send Thursday night's episode for preview, but the
consensus seems to be that Ross will be ash-canned by County
Hospital for breaking rules in administering painkillers to a dying
boy. At least that exit relieves Clooney of one anxiety.
</P>
<P>
   ``He kept coming to me and saying, `I just don't want testicular
cancer,''' Wells said. Wish granted, apparently.
</P>
<P>
   Keeping Ross alive also raises the prospect of future
appearances on the show. On ``MASH,'' by contrast, Stevenson was
terminated with extreme prejudice; Henry Blake was killed in a
helicopter crash.
</P>
<P>
   The biggest obstacle Thursday night is another TV network. ABC
is carrying the final hour of the miniseries ``Storm of the
Century'' against ``ER.'' It's a contest NBC and ``ER'' are
expected to win.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
    &UR; (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL ADD FOLLOWS) &LR;  &QC; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   It's tough to gauge Clooney's Hollywood future from his past.
</P>
<P>
   Clooney has star attributes _ the manly jaw, the bedroom eyes,
the killer grin and adequate acting talent. His blend of
sex-infused humor and macho presence is rooted in the Clark Gable
school of film stardom.
</P>
<P>
   But then, there are the movies to date: ``One Fine Day,'' ``From
Dusk Till Dawn,'' ``The Peacemaker,'' ``Batman and Robin.'' Not a
blockbuster in the bunch. In each of these cases, though, the blame
could be assessed to the material and not to Clooney's prospective
star power.
</P>
<P>
   Last year's ``Out of Sight'' is harder to explain. Based on an
Elmore Leonard best-seller, the movie appeared to be a home run.
Clooney was perfect for the role of a charming bank robber. He had
a roiling chemistry with co-star Jennifer Lopez. The supporting
cast was perfect. The movie was a sharply directed mixture of
bankable elements _ sex and violence _ and the critics rightly
adored it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Out of Sight'' should have gone through the roof but never
really got out of the parlor. It grossed $74.4 million last year,
with the domestic box office accounting for only $37.6 million of
that total. Not a commercial dud, but no fireball either.
</P>
<P>
   So you have to wonder. How is Clooney going to improve on an
inherently appealing and critically praised movie that managed to
finish only 52nd on the year's box-office roster?
</P>
<P>
   Clooney might reply with a string of TV titles _ ``E/R'' the CBS
sitcom (1984), ``Sunset Beat'' (1990), ``Baby Talk'' (1991) and
``Bodies of Evidence'' (1992).
</P>
<P>
   Together with scarcely notable roles on ``Facts of Life,''
``Roseanne'' and ``Sisters,'' these shows constituted Clooney's
less-than-stellar television credits before ``ER'' premiered in
1994.
</P>
<P>
   It's true in TV, and it's true in the movies. One monster hit
and all the earlier disappointments are nothing more than trivia
questions.
</P>
<P>
   In Clooney's case, a whole lot of people are cheering for a good
guy to knock one out of the park.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service clients) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
