<HEADER>
A9348 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SWISS-TREASON-CHARGE-     02-17 1043
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SWISS-TREASON-CHARGE-475&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SWISS TRUTH-TELLER OR LYING TRAITOR? 
</HEADLINE>
  (lh) 
 By ELIZABETH OLSON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   GENEVA _ In this button-down nation, mentioning the name of
Holocaust-era chronicler Jean Ziegler evokes passion. To many, he
sheds indispensable light on Switzerland's wartime past. To others,
his efforts are such outrageous calumnies that they amount to
treason.
</P>
<P>
   Ziegler's 1997 book, ``The Swiss, the Gold and the Dead,''
accused his wartime countrymen of helping to finance the Third
Reich and prolonging World War II by purchasing Nazi gold,
withholding funds in Jewish bank accounts and turning away tens of
thousands of Jewish refugees.
</P>
<P>
   Criticized as inaccurate and exaggerated, the book has roused a
group of fellow citizens to file charges of treason against the
University of Geneva professor.
</P>
<P>
   Largely from the northern city of Basel, the group, consisting
of 20 men old enough to remember the war, is trying to strip
Ziegler of the legal immunity he enjoys because he also is a member
of Parliament. If successful, the effort would open the way for a
trial and the possibility of a five-year prison term and stiff
financial penalties.
</P>
<P>
   His detractors maintain that Ziegler, who teaches sociology, not
only wrote a book based on shoddy research and invented anecdotes,
but has promoted his views worldwide. Particularly galling to them
was his testimony at a U.S. Senate banking committee hearing last
July about Hitler-era gold purchases.
</P>
<P>
   ``His book is full of lies and insults,'' insisted Matthias
Eckenstein, a Basel architect who organized the group.
</P>
<P>
   Eckenstein, who knows Ziegler from their days as students in the
1950s, singled out a highly contested scene in the book that
strikes at Switzerland's neutrality. Ziegler described, as a boy,
seeing German war materiel in a local rail yard.
</P>
<P>
   ``Late one afternoon in December 1943,'' Ziegler wrote, a
violent snowstorm hit with such force that ``dozens of freight cars
bearing the black eagle and the initials DRB, for Deutsche
Reichsbahn, toppled over.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Strewn across the tracks like corpses on a battlefield'' were
machine guns, ammunition boxes, artillery shells, antiaircraft guns
and tank turrets, Ziegler wrote. This was his ``first encounter
with the Swiss neutrality lie.''
</P>
<P>
   Eckenstein dismisses the anecdote. ``Nobody has ever heard
anything about this accident, or the train,'' he said in an
interview.
</P>
<P>
   Jean-Francois Bergier, a Zurich historian who heads the
government commission reviewing Swiss wartime actions, agreed. ``As
far as I know, this is unknown in the documents of the time. There
is no trace of the accident,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But Ziegler brushes aside the criticism. ``They accuse me of
lying and say it's an incredible story because it attacks the idea
that Switzerland is the haven of God's chosen ... that it was
protected during the war because of its neutrality,'' he said in an
interview. ``But I stand by it. It happened.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The book, sold widely in the United States, appeared just as
lawsuits in American courts cast doubt on Switzerland's neutrality
during the war.
</P>
<P>
   Nonbelievers, like Ziegler, see Switzerland as infinitely more
practical. ``The Reichsmark was not convertible. Twice a week
lorries came through Basel and brought gold to Bern, and it was
laundered through the national bank,'' Ziegler said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hitler depended on the world market for strategic war
equipment. The Swiss paid for those war goods. The Swiss were
fences and money launderers,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   To Eckenstein and others, those statements confirm that Ziegler
is a traitor ``who has damaged the image of Switzerland abroad.''
They also charge Ziegler with ``reinforcing the position'' of
``blackmailers'' _ apparently referring to class-action lawsuits by
American Jewish groups that sought the return of Holocaust-era
monies from Swiss banks. Those suits were settled with a $1.25
billion settlement that was signed last month.
</P>
<P>
   Ziegler testified last summer that ``Switzerland received much
more German assets, especially stolen gold, than it admitted,'' and
urged the Swiss national bank and private banks to restore the
sums.
</P>
<P>
   Sebastian Schmid, a retired chemical industry executive who also
signed the complaint against Ziegler, argued that Ziegler was
muddled over the gold issue, and that landlocked Switzerland had to
deal with the Nazis ``to get food and fuel to survive.''
</P>
<P>
   Under Swiss law, citizens may ask the federal prosecutor for a
criminal indictment for acts against the country. Whether Ziegler
can be tried for treason will be tested when either a federal
parliamentary committee or the federal Cabinet hears the
historian's defense.
</P>
<P>
   Ziegler, long an iconoclast in his country, has felt the law's
sting before this. His previous books about Swiss banks, accusing
them of ignoring money laundering and accepting monies from
dictators, have drawn legal action. One book left Ziegler with more
than 50 percent of his salary garnisheed. He wrote that book while
in Parliament, but the government decided it wasn't protected by
legislative immunity.
</P>
<P>
   Ziegler could well lose his immunity without the government
doing anything. Under Socialist Party rules, Ziegler cannot stand
re-election because he has held his seat for 12 consecutive years.
So he is considering running for a different seat to retain his
immunity. Swiss parliamentarians do not have to live in the
districts they represent, if their political party agrees.
Ziegler's Socialist allies have indicated he would likely receive a
waiver.
</P>
<P>
   Eckenstein says his group would settle for a conviction that
would forgo fines against Ziegler.
</P>
<P>
   ``He could go to jail for one to two weeks. And if he continues,
he could go to jail for longer,'' he said. ``We want him to stop
saying things like this.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We want people to know that you should be slightly proud to be
Swiss,'' Eckenstein insisted.
</P>
<P>
   Ziegler accuses his detractors of needing a scapegoat. ``They
would like to silence me once and for all,'' he said. ``If they can
prove in Switzerland that it's all my fault, then no one can say,
`You lied for 50 years.'''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
