<SLUG> BC-MA-WAGE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MINIMUM WAGE INCREASE PUSHED IN BAY STATE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MEG VAILLANCOURT  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ With support strong on Beacon Hill to help
Massachusetts' lowest-paid workers, Senate President Thomas
Birmingham and Governor Paul Cellucci are pushing competing plans
to boost the minimum wage.
</P>
<P>
   Birmingham is calling for the more aggressive hike to the
state's minimum wage, which is currently $5.25 a hour. His plan
would increase the rate by $1.50 over the next three years. The
Chelsea Democrat also would tie future increases to the state's
minimum wage to the consumer price index, a main gauge of
inflation.
</P>
<P>
   ``I believe that if you work for a living in Massachusetts, you
should be able to make a living here, which is just not the case
with the present minimum wage,'' Birmingham said in an interview
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not just an economic issue, it's a paramount issue of
social justice that in this era of great prosperity we should
recognize that the riches aren't being evenly shared.''
</P>
<P>
   Cellucci's plan, which he plans to file Thursday, calls for a
90-cent hike over two years. It does not include any automatic
hikes after the second increase goes into effect.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd like to get to the point where the federal minimum wage
and the state's minimum wage are the same,'' Cellucci, a
Republican, said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Federal law currently sets the minimum wage at $5.15 an hour,
though President Clinton and US Senator Edward Kennedy are pressing
to boost it by $1 over the next two years.
</P>
<P>
   The push to raise Massachusetts' minimum wage is putting the
spotlight on House Speaker Thomas Finneran, who single-handedly
killed a proposed hike last year. Finneran not only blocked a House
vote on Birmingham's bill, but by refusing to assign the bill to a
committee, he prohibited his members from even debating it.
</P>
<P>
   But House members, including some of Finneran's own leadership
team, said Wednesday that was strong support for minimum wage hike
in the House. The question is whether Finneran will allow it to
come to the floor for a vote.
</P>
<P>
   ``If this comes up for a House vote it will pass, and Finneran
knows that,'' said one House member. ``And with Birmingham moving
to get the bill over here so early in the legislative session, it
will impossible for him to argue there isn't enough time to
consider it, like he did last year.''
</P>
<P>
   Finneran could not be reached for comment.
</P>
<P>
   Last year the Senate passed Birmingham's bill, which would raise
the minimum wage by 50 cents an hour each year for three years, by
a vote of 35-4 as an amendment to the budget. But after Finneran
refused to assign the bill to a committee, it couldn't move forward
in the legislative process. When the session ended in July, the
wage hike proposal died.
</P>
<P>
   This year Birmingham has taken the unusual step of bypassing the
House in the early legislative stages and assigning his wage bill
to the Senate's Ways and Means Committee. Usually, such a bill
would go to a committee controlled jointly by the House and Senate.
</P>
<P>
   The Ways and Means Committee will hold a hearing on the matter
Thursday. Birmingham expects the Senate to adopt the measure within
the next two weeks.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Senate has spoken on this issue and will again soon,''
Birmingham said. ``If the Speaker's position is that of the members
of the House, then so be it.''
</P>
<P>
   But some House members worry that Birmingham's aggressive
tactics will anger Finneran and provoke him to block the measure
from coming up for consideration in the House.
</P>
<P>
   While labor unions support a minimum wage hike, business groups
oppose it, arguing that Massachusetts is already a high-cost state.
Raising the minimum wage, opponents say, will make Massachusetts
less competitive with other states.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Tina Cassidy of the Globe staff contributed to this report.)
</P>
</TEXT>
