<HEADER>
A9361 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BRITISH/AMERICAN-THEA     02-17 0902
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BRITISH/AMERICAN-THEATER-3TAKES-$ADV21-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LONDON-NEW YORK: A ONE-WAY STREET?  
(FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, FEB. 21)
</HEADLINE>
  (af) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The British tide that periodically washes over the American
theater is surging again. Already ensconced on New York stages are
David Hare's ``Blue Room,'' David Leveaux's production of
``Electra'' and Harold Pinter's ``Ashes to Ashes.'' And what about
Diana Rigg's recent visit in ``Phedre'' and ``Britannicus'' at the
Brooklyn Academy of Music, where ``Blue Heart,'' the double bill by
Caryl Churchill, winds up its run today? Then there was Matthew
Bourne's ``Swan Lake,'' the ballet that played Broadway as
comfortably as a musical. Speaking of Broadway, half a dozen more
theaters are about to open their doors to productions that have
already won attention in London: Kevin Spacey in ``The Iceman
Cometh'' and Dame Judi Dench in ``Amy's View'' among them.
</P>
<P>
   What does it all mean? And what about traffic the other way?
This special section on theater tries to answer those questions,
starting off with a conversation among the three theater critics of
The New York Times: Ben Brantley, Vincent Canby and Peter Marks.
Their talk _ over tea and biscuits, appropriately _ was recorded by
the theater editor of Arts and Leisure, Andrea Stevens, who began
by asking if the crowd of arriving British productions would risk
canceling one another out. Here are excerpts from the discussion.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   VINCENT CANBY. I don't think people think of them as English
shows or not English shows, if they're good shows.
</P>
<P>
   BEN BRANTLEY. And they are such different species. ``Not About
Nightingales'' is coming by way of Trevor Nunn and Vanessa
Redgrave. Nonetheless, when I saw it in Houston, I would not have
said, ``Wow, what a great British production.'' It's a resurrection
of a purely Tennessee Williams play and purely American.
</P>
<P>
   PETER MARKS. But who would have thought a year ago that you
would have so many plays to choose from?
</P>
<P>
   CANBY. Don't you think it's a product of having had ``The Beauty
Queen of Leenane,'' which started it, and then we suddenly got a
whole rash?
</P>
<P>
   BRANTLEY. Janet McTeer's revival of ``A Doll's House,'' I think,
was key in opening the door. What is interesting is what we seem to
be getting from it. Yes, it has the English pedigree, so everyone
salivates. But it's not ``Masterpiece Theater.'' There's a vitality
in these productions that we don't get very often from American
straight plays. At least those that are seen on Broadway. If you're
comparing ``Getting and Spending'' with ``Closer,'' I mean__
</P>
<P>
   CANBY. ``Shopping and ... '' or ``The Weir''?
</P>
<P>
   BRANTLEY. I went to see Mark Ravenhill's other play,
``Handbag,'' in London, and it made me think maybe I should
reconsider ``Shopping and ... ''; that it suffered from being done
here with an American cast. I don't think I'd ever like it. But I
can see now what the buzz was about it, because there's an energy,
there's a sense of connection of the theater in England with its
audiences that we've lost. There are exceptions. Last night I went
to see the Richard Foreman play ``Paradise Hotel.'' That was an
exciting audience. But for the most part on Broadway they go
anesthetized, they leave anesthetized and they don't want anything
that's going to interrupt their anesthesia. There's no buzz. At
intermission, you don't hear people talking excitedly, as they did
at ``A Doll's House.''
</P>
<P>
   CANBY. Have you gone back to see ``Art'' with the new cast?
</P>
<P>
   BRANTLEY. No.
</P>
<P>
   CANBY. I did.
</P>
<P>
   MARKS. You liked it a lot.
</P>
<P>
   CANBY. I'm astonished by its longevity and the way it holds an
audience. And the fact that almost anybody can play it. You could
put baboons in it and it would still be funny.
</P>
<P>
   BRANTLEY. Are you saying the three of us?
</P>
<P>
   CANBY. Oh, boy. Don't let that idea get out.
</P>
<P>
   MARKS. They'll sell six tickets.
</P>
<P>
   CANBY. No, they'll sell out the house and give them tomatoes and
fruit to throw.
</P>
<P>
   ANDREA STEVENS. Do you think there's a difference between the
audiences here and in London?
</P>
<P>
   CANBY. Absolutely.
</P>
<P>
   BRANTLEY. In London there's still a habit of going to the
theater.
</P>
<P>
   STEVENS. But that habit is supposedly dwindling.
</P>
<P>
   BRANTLEY. I know. And Ian McKellen has gone up to the north
country, to Leeds, because he's dissatisfied with what he sees of
London audiences. But comparatively, there's still an ``Oh, let's
go to the theater.'' Here, there are such expectations that there
is this self-consciousness on either side of the proscenium: the
audience saying, ``Oh, my God, can I get the sitter, blah, blah,
blah,'' and those in the production thinking, ``Well, we've got to
give them what they want.''
</P>
<P>
   MARKS. We have a skewed sense of English theater here because
the best things usually come in. Still, when I go to a play from
London, very often I think, ``Which country is the older country?''
Because I always feel like theirs is so much fresher.
</P>
<P>
   BRANTLEY. It's true.
</P>
<P>
   MARKS. What's coming over here feels reinvented. It's coming out
of the mind anew. And what originates here is so much more
conservative. Look at the plays that won Tony Awards in the last
few years. We're so reflective and nostalgic _ ``Last Night at
Ballyhoo.'' The one original new American play that comes to
Broadway this season is ``Side Man,'' which is a memory play with
echoes of Williams.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   BRANTLEY. Don't you think it has to do with the general climate
of caution, though? If it's proven in England, it arrives with the
English imprimatur. There's a sense that people will be willing to
gamble on it. But I know exactly what you're saying. Which
(italics)is(end italics) the younger country, in fact? That has to
do not only with the habit of going to the theater but of making
theater. It's just something you do. It seems like an organic
thing. Where you don't have 20 levels of marketing between the
production and the idea. America is pathetic right now, as far as
that stuff goes.
</P>
<P>
   CANBY. Do we have as much marketing going on with straight
plays? It seems to me what's happened recently has been that as a
result of the success of English straight plays here, we are
getting many more attempts to do straight American plays. They're
coming up out of Off Broadway.
</P>
<P>
   BRANTLEY. Or the regional theater.
</P>
<P>
   CANBY. Or staying Off Broadway.
</P>
<P>
   BRANTLEY. As annoying as a lot of English theater is, you still
want to go every night.
</P>
<P>
   MARKS. They write in response to something visceral. Politics
and ideas are still big themes in British plays. And you've still
got David Hare and Tom Stoppard _ two immense bookends of the
theater _ writing these plays on topics that fill a big space, even
if they're small plays. Here _ talk about compartmentalizing _
playwrights have got the message that they're writing in a smaller
artistic pursuit. They're told it's a small medium, it's not
movies, so they write small plays. Even the most major playwrights
_ with the exception of Tony Kushner, who wrote the one play of the
decade.
</P>
<P>
   BRANTLEY. Which came to us by way of England.
</P>
<P>
   MARKS. But it's so interesting that these plays are all about
families, or about ethnic identity and gender identity. They're
picking up on that somewhat in London; it's starting to be more
obsessive there. But these are relatively tiny concerns. And you
sometimes feel in a big space: ``Why am I seeing this play here? I
need to be with these people in a small room.'' Maybe that's why
``Wit'' works where it is. Maybe it was the right decision not to
move that play, even though it's a lovely play, to a big, big
space.
</P>
<P>
   CANBY. There's a big difference between Stoppard and Hare.
Stoppard's plays are alive and working on all sorts of levels.
Hare's plays, for me, too often seem to be operating from an idea
down.
</P>
<P>
   BRANTLEY. Stoppard is much more of a linguist than Hare. He
starts with the love of language.
</P>
<P>
   MARKS. Yet Hare has tremendous currency here. Three of his plays
are being done this season.
</P>
<P>
   BRANTLEY. We have to think of ``The Blue Room'' as an exception.
And also as an example of what's shameful in the British
theatergoing character.
</P>
<P>
   CANBY. I enjoyed it more than I've enjoyed almost any Hare play,
I'm afraid.
</P>
<P>
   BRANTLEY. I didn't like it at all.
</P>
<P>
   CANBY. Well, it's painless.
</P>
<P>
   BRANTLEY. Yes, that's true. But I'd rather be__
</P>
<P>
   CANBY. In pain?
</P>
<P>
   BRANTLEY. Yes, I would. If it stimulates some kind of response.
Even if it makes me angry. With ``The Blue Room,'' I wanted to yawn
all the way through.
</P>
<P>
   CANBY. Well, I haven't been made angry. I have yawned at a lot
of Hare's work.
</P>
<P>
   BRANTLEY. Even if it is starting with an idea, I think he has so
much personally invested in those ideas and putting them across. At
his best, it's not a one-sided polemic. He does present the debate
at least, and he doesn't come to easy conclusions. But it's true:
Who else can make Oscar Wilde boring? But he keeps producing. He
keeps the dialogue alive.
</P>
<P>
   CANBY. That's true of all writers. They have to keep writing to
write well.
</P>
<P>
   BRANTLEY. And he's responsive, as Peter was saying, to what's
going on in the world around him. There is a sense of a dialogue
with the audience that you don't get with American theater now.
</P>
<P>
   CANBY. It's the same with our movies. Hollywood films, most of
them, could have been made on the moon. Much of our entertainment _
television sitcoms and whatnot _ has nothing to do with the lives
of the people who see them. Whereas in London and Paris, you do get
pop entertainment that is very much concerned with that world.
</P>
<P>
   BRANTLEY. When was the last time an American play got into the
conversation?
</P>
<P>
   BRANTLEY and MARKS. ``Angels in America.''
</P>
<P>
   MARKS. The difference is in this country when kids are in fourth
grade they do ``Peter Pan'' or ``Once Upon a Mattress.'' That's
what our theater education involves, the show business aspect. In
England, they feel it's theirs. Shakespeare is in their blood.
There's no fear, there's no insecurity. Part of our embrace of the
English is that in some ways we haven't gotten over England.
</P>
<P>
   BRANTLEY. It's still a colonialist attitude to some degree.
</P>
<P>
   CANBY. It's not just that. They bring the best over, too. We
aren't willing to see something about which we know nothing.
</P>
<P>
   BRANTLEY. Let's not forget that London also gave us ``The Herbal
Bed.''
</P>
<P>
   CANBY. That was certainly a cause for celebration.
</P>
<P>
   BRANTLEY. Fusty, self-conscious, quote, cultured English theater
at its worst, end quote. And I think it is a testimony to the
discriminating taste, for once, of American audiences that it
didn't take off.
</P>
<P>
   MARKS. But the question of why we fall in love over and over
with what they bring in _ that hasn't changed in 30 years.
</P>
<P>
   BRANTLEY. In the beginning of the 20th century you had Sarah
Bernhardt and Eleanora Duse coming over. And no one cared that they
couldn't speak the language. They just wanted to see them. There's
nothing comparable right now.
</P>
<P>
   CANBY. They also have a whole raft of actors who do nothing but
work in the theater. And that gives them an ability to do things
that we could never match. I think of Peter Hall's ``Ideal
Husband'' _ it still remains in my memory. And they can do French
farce, which I've seen done in London, which always fails here. We
don't know how to do it.
</P>
<P>
   BRANTLEY. On the other hand, you look at something like Lincoln
Center Theater, which, at its best, does provide the equivalent of
what ``An Ideal Husband'' was, which I think of as the
well-upholstered play. I was thinking of ``A Delicate Balance,''
for example.
</P>
<P>
   MARKS. Which we sent over there and they did.
</P>
<P>
   BRANTLEY. That's right, but in another production.
</P>
<P>
   STEVENS. What do you think about that _ the exchanges negotiated
by the actors' unions here and in England? Apparently, British
Equity has suggested to American Equity that the two sides try a
year with no restrictions and see what happens. Do you think
American actors would suffer because it would be all in one
direction?
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   BRANTLEY. I like the idea.
</P>
<P>
   CANBY. You might get a lot of English so-called stars coming
over. I think it would be a terrific idea.
</P>
<P>
   MARKS. It's crazy to have these restrictions. I don't understand
why for this profession the Hague Convention has to be invoked. If
you go down the line, how many people are we talking about? Maybe
50 jobs.
</P>
<P>
   STEVENS. What about the theory that when we send our plays over
that show us off to bad advantage, the English love them?
</P>
<P>
   MARKS. What's more common is portrayals by British playwrights
of Americans.
</P>
<P>
   BRANTLEY. Like ``Taking Sides.''
</P>
<P>
   MARKS. Exactly. They're stereotypes, but it's mostly lesser
playwrights.
</P>
<P>
   CANBY. Arthur Miller is celebrated there.
</P>
<P>
   MARKS. It's ``Death of a Salesman,'' for crying out loud. He's
so cynical about American culture and American politics. The
English love that.
</P>
<P>
   CANBY. Though ``Death of a Salesman'' was not a smash when it
first opened in London.
</P>
<P>
   BRANTLEY. It's also his earnestness. The other thing is, the
English have an archival interest in the theater that doesn't
necessarily have to produce just dust and footnotes: the fact that
Vanessa Redgrave's own personal passion and interest in Tennessee
Williams would lead her to bring out ``Not About Nightingales''
from some academic vault. And then to give it the kind of
passionate production that it has. Again, I think a London audience
is, shamefully, going to be more interested in Tennessee Williams.
Even if this isn't a perfect play, they will say, ``Let's go and
see what he was thinking at that time.'' Whereas here, it's going
to be: ``Is it perfect? Is it thumbs up or thumbs down? Is it a
blockbuster evening?'' We demand too much and too little at once.
</P>
<P>
   CANBY. Because London has a theater culture that doesn't exist
in New York. So there isn't that great pool.
</P>
<P>
   MARKS. London was never a moviegoing city. Television was on
three channels, not 72 channels. Just the mix of the media was
different. They always felt theater was theirs. And in a funny way
we never have.
</P>
<P>
   BRANTLEY. I'll be very interested to see what the response is
here to ``Not About Nightingales.'' People think if they're going
to go out, they want to have a good time. The number of people,
smart people, too, real theatergoers, who have said, ``Oh, `Wit.'
Well I don't know, a play about death. I don't really think I'm up
to that tonight.'' I've used the metaphor before, but people want
the theater to be a geisha. It's like: ``If I'm spending this much
money, you make me feel good. You give me a massage like I've never
had before.''
</P>
<P>
   MARKS. What do you think we do as well, if not better than the
English in theater?
</P>
<P>
   BRANTLEY. It is a cyclical thing. Mid-century, I don't think
there was anything in contemporary English theater that matched
what was coming out here. I don't think anything John Osborne wrote
is half as good as anything Tennessee Williams wrote. It does go
through cycles, and you have to figure that the balance is in their
favor right now for a lot of reasons.
</P>
<P>
   What is interesting about Kushner and the reason we keep going
back to him _ although I was not a fan of his second adaptation of
``The Dybbuk''; I liked the first better _ is this: When I went to
``Love's Fire,'' the evening of plays inspired by Shakespeare's
sonnets, suddenly, when his one-act comes on, after listening to
everyone else and their rote formulas, there is a passion about
language that is so rare in American theater now that he does have.
</P>
<P>
   CANBY. Also, as you said earlier, he is aware of the world
around him. I think ``Slavs!'' is a marvelous play. It's better
than any other American play that year.
</P>
<P>
   BRANTLEY. But it's not just topical. With him there is an
awareness and a commitment. And it all seems to be part of the same
package: the passion transfuses his approach to the world. But also
the possibility of language to shape, to change, to mutate, is what
I think is so great about him. It's what the theater can do that
film can't.
</P>
<P>
   MARKS. We spend a lot of time trying to emulate the movies on
stage.
</P>
<P>
   BRANTLEY. Which I think is always disastrous.
</P>
<P>
   CANBY. Movies have made the staging of plays much more fluid.
Their influence has been all to the good, I think. I'm talking
about plays that move simply and easily from one scene to another.
And we all accept it. You don't ned three-sided sets and all that
baloney. Some plays do need them. But many are freed by
acknowledging that the audience has an imagination and it will go
anywhere if the play is good.
</P>
<P>
   BRANTLEY. Movies are much more literal-minded.
</P>
<P>
   CANBY. Let me ask you: What do you think is the difference
between London critics and New York critics?
</P>
<P>
   MARKS. Oh, boy. I'm not touching that. What do you think?
</P>
<P>
   CANBY. I'm baffled, because some of them are among the brightest
people I know. And the difference in taste is just extraordinary at
times.
</P>
<P>
   BRANTLEY. Remember, they're writing that night for the most
part. And we have the luxury of a day or even several to reflect
and distill. I think it's healthy that there are so many of them
coming from so many different directions, because it's not this
monolithic voice saying go or not.
</P>
<P>
   CANBY. Also, I think they are all encouraged to be
personalities.
</P>
<P>
   BRANTLEY. That's true. But the reviews of ``The Blue Room''
mystify me. I do think that was a provincial reaction.
</P>
<P>
   STEVENS. Would you say that American audiences are waiting to be
told what to go to, whereas in England, critics are writing for
someone who may throw down the review and say, ``I don't care, I'm
going''?
</P>
<P>
   BRANTLEY. It goes back to the idea of an open dialogue.
</P>
<P>
   MARKS. The perfect example is that when a bunch of critics
directed plays in London, they were savaged by the directors, who
wrote reviews that were published.
</P>
<P>
   CANBY. If you try to write for an audience, you're going to be
in hot water. You just try to be as articulate as you can. One
problem with all reviewing is that 99 percent of what you see is
neither very good nor very bad. And as writers, there is a problem
with trying to make that interesting to read.
</P>
<P>
   MARKS. If you just say, ``No, no, no,'' people may not admit it
_ they always say they want you to go thumbs up or down _ but if
you do that they turn off. They think you're a crank or you're a
cheerleader. So, it's a trap.
</P>
<P>
   CANBY. I think all readers who read any paper conscientiously or
regularly, find out where they stand in relation to a particular
critic. They come to recognize a critic's tics and how to interpret
them. They know whether if somebody likes something, then maybe I
will like it, but not necessarily.
</P>
<P>
   MARKS. There is that response, that immediacy that people feel
sometimes.
</P>
<P>
   CANBY. Then you come upon something that you like so much that
you can't bear the idea that it won't be seen and you can't wait to
write the first word. You're excited and on fire for something.
It's great fun to write those reviews.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
