<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-17 20:50 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9368 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CLINTON-NHAMPSHIRE-BO     02-17 0833
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-NHAMPSHIRE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LINTON TO RETURN TO GRANITE STATE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (w and a coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ANN SCALES  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Exactly seven years after New Hampshire voters
resurrected his faltering political career in the wake of the
Gennifer Flowers and Vietnam War draft controversies, President
Clinton, on the mend from a tortuous 13-month sex scandal, makes a
somewhat nostalgic visit there Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   The Granite State is where Clinton dubbed himself the ``Comeback
Kid'' after a strong second-place primary finish in the 1992
presidential campaign despite allegations of marital infidelity and
questions about how he avoided the draft, and where he is coming
back to make his first political appearance since his Senate
impeachment trial ended in acquittal.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton is scheduled to deliver a speech on health care in
Dover, and attend a private lunch with friends and supporters in
Merrimack and a state Democratic Party dinner in Manchester during
the one-day trip that organizers said was confirmed a few days
after the Dec. 19 House vote to impeach him.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's something special about New Hampshire for the
president,'' said White House press secretary Joseph Lockhart,
specifically mentioning the '92 primary. He dismissed the idea of
any symbolism in the president's visit, calling the timing
``coincidental,'' and delivering a crisp ``no'' when asked whether
Clinton was going there to gloat about his Senate acquittal.
</P>
<P>
   In 1992, to cheering supporters on primary night in Merrimack,
Clinton said, ``New Hampshire tonight has made Bill Clinton the
comeback kid.'' He added: ``At least I proved one thing, I can take
a punch.''
</P>
<P>
   That ability to take a punch, and New Hampshire's willingness to
help him get back on his feet, may be part of the mutual appeal.
</P>
<P>
   ``Voters here are proud of the fact that he can take a punch,
dust himself off and keep on going, no matter what his adversaries
say about him,'' said Joseph Keefe, former New Hampshire Democratic
Party chairman.
</P>
<P>
   ``New Hampshire voters were the first Americans to make the
distinction between the president's private life and his public
duties. That distinction has since been embraced by a great
majority of Americans,'' said Keefe, who also is a member of the
Democratic National Committee.
</P>
<P>
   During the visit, Clinton plans to promote his budget proposal
for targeted tax relief, including a $1,000 tax credit for
long-term care. He will address the 40th anniversary dinner of the
New Hampshire State Democratic Party's ``100 Club.''
</P>
<P>
   Jeff Woodburn, current chairman of the state Democratic Party,
said Clinton was booked in August for the dinner, but those plans
had to be canceled because of independent counsel Kenneth W.
Starr's investigation of the president's affair with Monica S.
Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
   Woodburn said Clinton was invited because of his ability to draw
a crowd, which is difficult in New Hamsphire ``when you have the
presidential candidates around as frequently as they are.''
Woodburn said he expects up to 1,000 people to attend the
fund-raising dinner and reception, which he hopes will raise more
than $100,000 for Democratic candidates. Ticket prices range
between $100 and $750.
</P>
<P>
   The timing of the dinner _ the seventh anniversary of Clinton's
strong showing in the state primary _ was no mistake.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's made a lot of friends in the state, and I think New
Hampshire feels a lot of ownership in this presidency,'' Woodburn
said. ``We saw beyond Gennifer Flowers, the draft issue, and we saw
the quality of the human being standing before us and embraced that
person.''
</P>
<P>
   Back then, when those scandals surfaced, Clinton went to the
Dover Elks Lodge and asked the state's voters to give him a second
chance.
</P>
<P>
   ``They say I'm on the ropes now, not because of anything I did
in my public life, not because of anything I've done to you,'' he
said. ``I'm on the ropes because people questioned my life, after
years of public service.''
</P>
<P>
   And in what would become some of the most memorable lines of his
campaign, he said, ``I won't forget who gave me a second chance.
I'll be there with you until the last dog dies.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton is not expected to make a repeat trip to the Elks Lodge,
but Clark Hubbard, a political scientist at the University of New
Hampshire, said the president's visit will be ``very symbolic both
for Clinton personally and in terms of his renewed efforts to
rehabilitate his image.''
</P>
<P>
   ``He recovered from the Gennifer Flowers fiasco here in New
Hampshire. That was sort of his first big test, not of his
presidency, but his pre-presidency, and now he's facing the next
big test of his presidency,'' Hubbard said. ``And I think he's
going to get it off the ground here. New Hampshire voters seem to
have a sympathetic ear for him.''
</P>
<P>
   He added: ``He's rehabilitated his image here once before, so it
seems like a logical place to do it once again.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
