<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-17 20:50 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9369 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-KRIKORIAN-COLUMN-     02-17 0885
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-KRIKORIAN-COLUMN-LBPT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WILL RODMAN HOP ON JERRY'S BUSS?
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DOUG KRIKORIAN  
 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   INGLEWOOD, Calif. _ There was Jerry Buss in his pregame element
at his dining table at the Forum Club, surrounded by his fawning
subjects that included, of course, his Designated Date For The
Evening who happened to be a very tall blonde in very tight pants
and looked as though she had celebrated very few birthdays.
</P>
<P>
   ``Why haven't you been able to sign Dennis Rodman?'' I asked the
Lakers owner, so cool, so poised, so in control of his domain.
</P>
<P>
   ``Money,'' Buss said. ``Dennis has to get used to the idea that
we can pay him only a few hundred thousand dollars. You must
understand Dennis made $10 million last year playing for the
Chicago Bulls.
</P>
<P>
   ``No way we can pay that because of salary cap restrictions.
Dennis right now is in a state of denial, like a guy who's just
been told he has cancer. He wants us to pay more, but we can't do
it. I talked to Dennis on the phone today. He wants to play for us.
I want him to play for us. But we can only give him so much.''
</P>
<P>
   Why does Buss want Rodman?
</P>
<P>
   ``Because he's a good player who can help us,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But at what price?
</P>
<P>
   Is Dennis Rodman worth all the commotion he's already created on
the Lakers?
</P>
<P>
   The Lakers coach, Del Harris, whose job status becomes a source
of passionate debate each time his team fails to beat a quality
opponent, is so uptight about the Rodman situation that, according
to Shaquille O'Neal, he's threatened to fine his players if they
consent to talk about it any longer with the media.
</P>
<P>
   ``I come from a military family, and you do what the general
tells you to do,'' O'Neal said Tuesday night after the Lakers
breezed past the Charlotte Hornets. ``The coach told us not to talk
about Rodman, so I'm not talking about him.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Doesn't that violate your First Amendment rights of free
speech?'' I asked.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yeah, I guess it does, but that's the way it is,'' O'Neal
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``How much did Harris say the fine would be if you talked about
Rodman?'' I wanted to know.
</P>
<P>
   ``Five thousand dollars,'' O'Neal said.
</P>
<P>
   ``You're kidding?''
</P>
<P>
   ``No, I'm serious. Honestly. Five thousand dollars. It's just
not worth blowing that money over Dennis Rodman.''
</P>
<P>
   Shaquille O'Neal wasn't laughing.
</P>
<P>
   Neither is Jerry West these days.
</P>
<P>
   It seems, once again, my two favorite Jerrys, Buss and West, are
having their differences.
</P>
<P>
   While Buss thinks Rodman would give the Lakers the rebounding
toughness and intense competitiveness they lack, West sees a young
team he's built being blown asunder by the outlandish antics that
are a daily part of Rodman's persona.
</P>
<P>
   A year ago, West attempted to trade Eddie Jones, the Lakers'
notoriously erratic guard known for his strange playoff
disappearances, for the perennial All-Star guard, Mitch Richmond,
then with the Sacramento Kings.
</P>
<P>
   But Buss, with prodding from his accountants, nixed the
transaction, thereby depriving the Lakers of one of the NBA's most
accomplished shooters that would have given them the link they so
desperately miss late in tight games.
</P>
<P>
   Buss and West also had a well-publicized monetary disagreement,
which nearly led to West's departure from an organization he's been
with since 1960.
</P>
<P>
   The two men effected an agreement that was reached over the
summer when Buss gave West a four-year contract extension, worth an
estimated $16 million.
</P>
<P>
   It seemed cordial bliss was restored, but the two strong willed
fellows are at loggerheads again because of Rodman.
</P>
<P>
   Whereas Buss sees rebounds grabbed and tickets peddled because
of Rodman's presence, West envisions a media horror show that would
unravel his young team.
</P>
<P>
   Whereas Buss sees another world championship banner for the
Lakers because of Rodman's presence, West envisions an insurrection
among his troops when it becomes apparent that Rodman will be given
preferential treatment by the the team's coaching staff.
</P>
<P>
   Whereas Buss sees the Lakers instantly turning into the NBA's
reigning glamour team featured most often on ESPN's Sports Center
because of Rodman's presence, West envisions a Rodman-distracted
team performing below expectations and becoming nothing more than a
cult favorite among diamond cutters, cross-dressers, hairstylists,
tattoo artists, bartenders, blackjack dealers, and massage parlor
bouncers.
</P>
<P>
   Poor Jerry West.
</P>
<P>
   He was quite conspicuous by his absence at Tuesday's Laker game,
and I strongly think there is a direct corollary between his
absence and Buss' wooing of Rodman.
</P>
<P>
   Karen West, Jerry's wife, said her husband wasn't feeling well,
and I'm sure he wasn't.
</P>
<P>
   If the Lakers do wind up with Rodman, Jerry West will feel even
sicker and might miss a lot more Laker games this season.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have mixed feelings about us getting Dennis Rodman,''
veteran guard Derek Harper said. ``I think he's a player who can
help the team. He's smart, knows how to win, and is a great
rebounder. But he also can bring distractions, and that can cause
problems for a young team that is fragile.''
</P>
<P>
   Oh, is this Dennis Rodman stuff fun!
</P>
<P>
   Except to Jerry West.
</P>
<P>
   And Del Harris.
</P>
<P>
   And perhaps now even to the tongue-tied Shaquille O'Neal.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
