<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-TALKS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEWS ANALYIS: RAMBOUILLET IS NO DAYTON
</HEADLINE>
   (With BC-KOSOVO-NYT) 
(sw) 
 By JANE PERLEZ   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PARIS _ When the idea of a peace conference for the tormented
province of Kosovo was first broached, there were instant
flashbacks to the Dayton talks that ended the war in Bosnia.
</P>
<P>
   Warring factions from the Balkans quarantined in close quarters,
negotiators shuttling between the sides, suspense about the
outcome, high stakes for big countries _ all this conjured up a
reprise of what happened at an out-of-the-way military base in Ohio
more than three years ago.
</P>
<P>
   But 10 days into the negotiations in the gilded castle at
Rambouillet, 30 miles south of Paris, the differences are more
striking than the similarities.
</P>
<P>
   The Dayton talks were an American show from start to finish. Not
only did Richard Holbrooke, then an assistant secretary of state,
dominate the negotiations with his forceful personality, but he was
backed by more than 20,000 American troops that President Clinton
said would be deployed to enforce the peace the moment a deal was
signed.
</P>
<P>
   At Rambouillet, the Americans are smaller players. The chief of
a trio of negotiators is an American, Ambassador Christopher Hill,
but he lacks the relentless rhythms of Holbrooke. More
significantly, he lacks the commitment of a large number of
American troops to back him up.
</P>
<P>
   This time, a senior American military officer noted, the Clinton
administration is getting involved with the ``greatest
reluctance.''
</P>
<P>
   The process at Rambouillet is a European show, shepherded by the
French and to a lesser extent the British, and represents an effort
by the Europeans to prove that they can shoulder responsibilities
in their own backyard. Kosovo is a forlorn piece of land in
southern Europe, but its fighting threatens to spill into a wider
war and send waves of refugees onto the rest of the continent.
</P>
<P>
   Another big difference is that at Rambouillet there is very
little discussion, negotiating or even arguing with the warring
sides.
</P>
<P>
   At Dayton, the leaders of Croatia, Serbia and Bosnia were all
present, and feared by the negotiators for what tantrums they might
throw, what demands they might make.
</P>
<P>
   In the French countryside, the 16-member ethnic Albanian
delegation and the 13 Serbs are actually bit characters.
</P>
<P>
   The ethnic Albanians have been diligent in studying the few
documents that have been passed around, making written comments and
waiting for answers, according to diplomats. The Serbs, by
contrast, have no authority from their master in Belgrade, the
Yugoslav president, Slobodan Milosevic, and, according to
participants in the conference, have been spending the evenings
playing the piano and singing.
</P>
<P>
   The real negotiating, and bickering, according to diplomats, is
among the six host countries, known as the Contact Group. This
group _ the United States, France, Britain, Germany, Italy and
Russia _ was established to resolve the problems of the former
Yugoslavia and is now trying to demonstrate that on the Kosovo
question, its past reputation for glacial diplomacy is unfounded.
</P>
<P>
   But the squabbling among the sponsors has ranged from whether
NATO should be allowed to have officers present at the conference
to whether a monitoring mission established in Kosovo four months
ago by the Organization for Security and Cooperation in Europe
should be allowed to continue with an American leading the project.
</P>
<P>
   The French, who are the official hosts of the conference, argued
against allowing NATO officers at the conference, European and
American diplomats said. With the exception of a cameo appearance
before the ethnic Albanians by two American colonels, the absence
of high-ranking military officers at Rambouillet has been another
contrast to the Dayton talks.
</P>
<P>
   Russia, according to diplomats, was against a NATO presence at
the conference, and, unlike at Dayton, Russia is a pivotal player
at Rambouillet. On Sunday at a Contact Group meeting, Russia said
that, under certain conditions, it would join a NATO-led force in
Kosovo, thus isolating its traditional ally, Milosevic, at a
critical moment.
</P>
<P>
   The more intense quarreling among the sponsors of the talks has
been over which country should do what in Kosovo in the event of a
peace agreement.
</P>
<P>
   France, Germany and to a lesser extent Britain, according to
diplomats, are arguing that since the Europeans are planning to put
more troops into peacekeeping and more money into the civil
reconstruction of Kosovo than the United States, then European
nations should have the largest say _ and presumably the largest
glory _ in what will become the quasi protectorate of Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   Thus, on phone lines and in meeting rooms at Rambouillet and
elsewhere, the European sponsors have argued that the Organization
for Security and Cooperation in Europe, which now has 1,300
monitors in Kosovo, should be supplanted by a newly created
organization, similar to the Office of the Higher Representative in
Bosnia. Most importantly, the Europeans argue, a European should
head the new organization. The OSCE mission in Kosovo is led by
William G. Walker, a former American ambassador to El Salvador.
</P>
<P>
   In an unusual alliance within the OSCE, a 54-nation
trans-Atlantic organization, the United States and Russia are
trying to fight off the European demands, diplomats said.
</P>
<P>
   All this diplomatic squabbling has made one point clear: Even
though the settlement of a Balkans war is the centerpiece,
Rambouillet is no Dayton. The most striking reason is that even
though Washington may feel uncomfortable being the junior partner,
the United States has decided to let the Europeans carry their
share of the burden.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
