<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-SENATE-LAUTENBERG-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: LAUTENBERG BOWS OUT 
</HEADLINE>
  (See also NJ-LAUTENBERG-RETIREE) 
(DW) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial for Thursday, Feb. 18:
</P>
<P>
   New Jersey voters may have felt a bit jealous this week
listening to speculation about whether Hillary Rodham Clinton and
Rudolph Giuliani would give New York the Senate race of the
millennium. But now it appears that New Jersey will have its own
exciting Senate contest in 2000. Sen. Frank Lautenberg has
announced that he will be quitting at the end of the present term,
and each party has several qualified candidates who might want to
succeed him. Mrs. Clinton's name has not surfaced so far, but Gov.
Christine Todd Whitman becomes an instant prospect. Former Gov.
James Florio also has been mentioned, as has Rep. Robert Menendez
of Hudson County.
</P>
<P>
   Lautenberg's retirement came as a bit of a surprise. Although he
will be 76 in the year 2000, he had given every indication he
intended to run for a fourth term. Many senators have served the
nation brilliantly at Lautenberg's age. But the real trick for any
senator is maintaining the same level of enthusiasm after a number
of six-year terms in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   Like Daniel Patrick Moynihan of New York, Lautenberg has opted
to leave with grace while he is still wanted. He will be remembered
as a strong voice in the Senate for stiffer gun-control laws, a
supporter of environmental legislation and a fighter for the
interests of the Northeast.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Whitman, in comments Wednesday, seemed to be opening the
door to a possible run for Lautenberg's seat. Her hopes of moving
up to the national level have been blocked so far by the Republican
Party's right wing. But New Jersey voters almost elected Mrs.
Whitman to the Senate when she was a relative unknown, chosen to
run as a sacrificial lamb against the popular Sen. Bill Bradley.
She could be a formidable candidate.
</P>
<P>
   But New Jersey has an ample supply of other attractive moderate
Republicans who could also make good nominees. On the Democratic
side, the early money is on Menendez, a Cuban-American who recently
was elected to a top job in the Democratic House leadership.
</P>
<P>
   New Jersey had some experience with the downside of competitive
politics in the rancorous Senate contest that was won by Robert
Torricelli in 1996. Still, in an era when so many elections seem to
be over before they begin, the prospect of a hard-fought battle
featuring good candidates is welcome, even if none of them are
married to the president of the United States.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
