<HEADER>
A9381 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HKN-KINGS-LBPT     02-17 0807
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-KINGS-LBPT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KINGS WON''T SELL THE FARM FOR FLEURY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ROGER PHILLIPS  
 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Expressing serious concerns with National Hockey
League economics, Kings president Tim Leiweke said this week that
the team will not drain its pool of young talent to acquire a
marquee player, specifically Theo Fleury.
</P>
<P>
   ``It doesn't mean we're out of the star market,'' said Leiweke,
who didn't rule out trying to acquire the Calgary Flames'
30-year-old right wing if an acceptable deal can be struck. ``We're
into the long-term survival of the sport. Everybody better stay
focused on that. If people in the league don't stay focused, the
league as we know it will disappear.''
</P>
<P>
   More on this last part later. First though, comes the issue of
the perceived need for a star player, a need seemingly heightened
by the dire state of the Kings' playoff hopes as they enter
tonight's key game at the Forum against the Edmonton Oilers.
</P>
<P>
   Leiweke would not reveal the names of specific Kings prospects
the Flames are asking for in exchange for Fleury, who is believed
likely to switch uniforms by the March 23 trading deadline as
Calgary seeks compensation for a player who will be the top
unrestricted free agent this summer.
</P>
<P>
   According to an NHL source, the Flames have asked for junior
defenseman Mathieu Biron and junior right wing Scott Barney, along
with one or more draft choices. Biron was the Kings' first-round
draft choice last year and plays for Shawinigan in the Quebec
league, and Barney was a second-round choice in 1997 who is having
a big year with Peterborough in the Ontario Hockey League.
</P>
<P>
   Leiweke acknowledged that the Flames want prospects, but said
the Kings are concerned with the long-range effects of dealing
talented young players for established stars approaching the latter
stages of their careers. He said it has not been shown that a team
can buy a Stanley Cup, and that when a team chooses to spend money
on established stars rather than developing prospects, it leads to
ticket-price increases.
</P>
<P>
   ``At the end of the day,'' Leiweke said, ``you have to show,
philosophically, the ability to pick and choose well, develop
players and, in particular, you can't give up your young kids.
</P>
<P>
   ``The reality is, we've had active conversations with (Calgary).
... What I'm saying is, if the price of a Fleury is ultimately that
you've got to give up two, three, four kids and increase ticket
prices 20 to 25 percent, I don't know if this gives you a team that
can be competitive and I'm not sure there will be anybody in the
stands if you keep increasing ticket prices like that.''
</P>
<P>
   When it was mentioned to Leiweke that some Kings fans, yearning
for a marquee player, would be unhappy reading comments indicating
the organization might be backing off its star search, he said,
``This is good news for the fans. We will not price fans out of the
building to go try to buy a Stanley Cup. ... There's a feeling in
the organization that we are nervous about the league, the
economics, the salaries. The majority of teams lose money, and
we're losing a lot. We can't keep jumping into the free-agent
market, passing those costs on to the fans. Then, at some point,
you have an average price of $50 or $60.''
</P>
<P>
   The Kings' average ticket price this season is more than $37,
and the Kings are believed to be on course to lose as much as $20
million this season. A majority of the NHL's 27 teams are believed
to be operating at deficits. The Kings will have a sizable increase
in income when they move into the Staples Center next season, but
NHL television income is minute compared with that of the NBA, NFL
and Major League Baseball.
</P>
<P>
   The Kings' average announced attendance at the 16,005-seat Forum
is a little more than 12,000. When the Flames visited the Forum
last month, an announced crowd of 10,334 turned out to watch
Fleury, leaving one wondering exactly how much marquee power the
gritty 5-foot-6 winger actually would have in Los Angeles. Fleury
may command an annual salary of $8 million when he tests the market
this summer.
</P>
<P>
   ``My opinion is fans want to see a bunch of guys go out and give
it 100 percent every night,'' Leiweke said. ``This isn't an
admission that we're going backward. We've picked up some good
talent this year. But each club in the league has to take a look at
where the league is headed. Right now, this business doesn't make
sense.''
</P>
<P>
   As for whether the Kings' apparent hesitancy to acquire a
marquee player indicated that the team's owners lack commitment to
winning or to remaining involved in the NHL, Leiweke said, ``I
think we're committed. This is a good ownership group. Philip
(Anschutz) is as good an owner as I've seen in 20 years in sports.
He's very committed.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
