<HEADER>
A9382 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NJ-LAUTENBERG-RETIRE-     02-17 1131
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NJ-LAUTENBERG-RETIRE-560&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
2000
</HEADLINE>
 
SENATOR LAUTENBERG CHANGES HIS MIND, WILL NOT RUN FOR 4th TERM IN (fe) 
 By ABBY GOODNOUGH 
  
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service 
  
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEWARK, N.J. _ U.S. Sen. Frank Lautenberg, the New Jersey
Democrat who declared last fall that he would seek a fourth term in
2000, announced on Wednesday that he would not run for re-election
after all.
</P>
<P>
   In a news conference here, Lautenberg, 75, said he was stepping
down only because he did not want to spend the next two years
raising money for a campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Lautenberg's surprise announcement prompted immediate
speculation in both parties about who might run for the seat, which
he has held since 1982. Gov. Christie Whitman, a Republican who
lost a close Senate race to Bill Bradley in 1990, has been
frequently mentioned in recent weeks as a potential Senate
candidate.
</P>
<P>
   Other Republicans who are said to be interested in the seat
include Rep. Marge Roukema; James Treffinger, the Essex County
executive; and Richard Zimmer, the former congressman who lost a
Senate campaign to Robert Torricelli in 1996. Among Democrats, Rep.
Robert Menendez and former Gov. James Florio are strong
possibilities, party leaders said.
</P>
<P>
   For her part, the governor sounded more interested in the
possibility of another run for the Senate than she had in the past.
``I rule nothing out,'' Whitman said at a news conference in
Hamilton Township, where she was helping to dedicate a new train
station. ``It is going to be a personal determination and what I
think will be best for the state.''
</P>
<P>
   Whitman's current term, her second, expires in 2001 and she is
barred by state law from seeking another consecutive term.
</P>
<P>
   Lautenberg said in November that he would seek re-election
because he believed that the Democrats would regain control of the
Senate. If that happened, Lautenberg said, he would have a good
chance of becoming chairman of the powerful Budget Committee, where
he is now the ranking minority member. Lautenberg also said last
fall that he was interested in becoming chairman of the Environment
and Public Works Committee, which has jurisdiction over
transportation programs, an area of interest to him.
</P>
<P>
   In explaining his change of heart on Wednesday, he said he had
decided that fund raising would consume to much of his time. ``I
did not want to sit there all those hours of each day asking for
money when in fact there is good solid work to be done,'' he said.
``It would distract me from the job I was sent to Washington to
do.''
</P>
<P>
   Although Lautenberg is a multimillionaire who has spent heavily
in past campaigns, he said he did not relish a race that he
estimated would cost at least $12 million.
</P>
<P>
   Other Democrats have privately expressed doubts that Lautenberg
would run again, noting that he had raised barely any money for a
fast-approaching campaign. Lautenberg raised only about $70,000 in
1998 and had just over $500,000 in his campaign war chest,
according to federal records released this month. He said on
Wednesday that he had not worked hard at raising money out of
deference to other New Jersey Democrats whose campaigns were more
imminent.
</P>
<P>
   Democratic leaders also say that after 16 years in Washington,
Lautenberg was out of touch with the state party and would have had
a hard time building organizational support. His prickly
personality and a public battle last year with Torricelli, New
Jersey's junior senator, might also have impeded his fund-raising
efforts, they said.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Lautenberg, who is considered an intelligent and hard-working
legislator, is best known for his work on tobacco control, drunken
driving, the environment and the budget. He pushed through a bill
that banned smoking on domestic airline flights and another that
prohibited ocean dumping of sewage and plastics. He has pressed for
the cleanup of Superfund sites, secured millions of dollars in
federal transportation funds for New Jersey and fought for tougher
laws against drunken driving.
</P>
<P>
   But to Lautenberg's constant frustration, he has been
overshadowed by more prominent _ and more telegenic _ senators from
New Jersey: first Bradley, who worked beside Lautenberg for 14
years, and now Torricelli, who has quickly become a vocal
Democratic senators.
</P>
<P>
   For the first half of 1998, Lautenberg and Torricelli barely
exchanged a word and publicly complained about each other. They
finally declared a detente last May, at Lautenberg's urging. But
while Lautenberg devoted much of his news conference on Wednesday
to praising fellow Democrats, he did not mention Torricelli. Asked
to characterize their relationship, Lautenberg flatly said, ``It's
OK.''
</P>
<P>
   But Lautenberg only briefly mentioned his failure to capture the
spotlight, saying: ``I would like to get more attention for the
things I've done, sure. But people know.''
</P>
<P>
   Torricelli, who was in California on Wednesday raising money for
Senate Democrats, said in a telephone interview that Lautenberg had
been especially effective in pushing through legislation and
securing funds that had a direct impact on New Jersey residents.
``I don't think there is a county in New Jersey without a road, a
railroad, a bridge or a mass-transit project where Frank Lautenberg
did not deliver the federal funds,'' Torricelli said. ``He should
be very proud of his public career.''
</P>
<P>
   Bradley was also complimentary, saying in a statement that
Lautenberg ``was an effective advocate for those things that
directly touched people's lives.''
</P>
<P>
   Lautenberg was raised in the industrial city of Paterson, where
his father, a Polish immigrant, worked in the silk mills. He
enlisted in the Army after high school and served in the Signal
Corps in Europe during World War II. After the war, he used the GI
Bill to attend Columbia University, graduating in 1949 with a
degree in economics.
</P>
<P>
   In the early 1950s, Lautenberg helped found a storefront company
in Paterson that provided payroll services to businesses. The
company, Automatic Data Processing, evolved into one of the largest
computing services companies in the world. It built a fortune for
Lautenberg, who used some of his assets and his fierce competitive
streak to fight his way into elected office in 1982, when he
defeated Rep. Millicent Fenwick.
</P>
<P>
   During that House race, Lautenberg questioned the 72-year-old
congresswoman's ``fitness'' and ``her ability to do the job.'' But
in recent years, Lautenberg has dismissed questions about his own
age, bragging that he could ski faster than his four children.
</P>
<P>
   He stressed on Wednesday that age had nothing to do with his
decision to step down.
</P>
<P>
   ``They know I don't tire easily,'' he said. ``If I were any
younger, I'd be dangerous.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
