<SLUG> BC-MANN-OFFER-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PACIFIC THEATERS OFFERS TO BUY MANN CHAIN
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
BY DAVE MCNARY  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &LR; LOS ANGELES -- Pacific Theaters disclosed Wednesday it has
offered to buy the Mann Theatres chain, three weeks after Mann went
on the sales block.
</P>
<P>
   The deal would double the number of screens operated by Los
Angeles-based Pacific, which has been one of the most aggressive
builders of state-of-the-art ``megaplexes'' in Southern California.
Pacific would obtain the legendary Chinese Theater in Hollywood and
the landmark Village Theater in Westwood but would also inherit the
problem of invigorating many outdated properties in the 60-theater
Mann chain in California and Colorado.
</P>
<P>
   Pacific, owned by the Forman family, had no comment beyond
confirming the offer. Industry trackers said the declining value of
older theaters will force Wall Street investment firm Warburg
Pincus, Mann's principal owner, to take a major loss on the $165
million buyout it led in late 1997.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a buyers' market right now,'' said Kevin Skislock, a
consultant with Laguna Research Partners. ``Warburg should take
whatever's offered because they'll get less tomorrow. Every new
megaplex that goes up knocks down the value of older theaters.''
</P>
<P>
   Encino-based Mann and Warburg, which hired investment banker
Bear Stearns to unload Mann, had no comment on the offer. Robert
Laemmle, owner of the Los Angeles-based art-house chain of the same
name, said the deal would represent a strategic departure for
Pacific, which has opened a dozen megaplexes in recent years and
has plans for 11 more in Southern California and Hawaii over the
next two years.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's possible that Pacific is doing this as a defensive
strategy to keep someone else out of the market,'' Laemmle added.
</P>
<P>
   Skislock asserted Pacific will be best served by tearing down
many Mann facilities and building megaplexes. ``The best name on an
older theater cannot go toe to toe with a top-line new theater,''
he added. ``Keeping older theaters is a market-share siren song
because consumers can so easily tell the difference.''
</P>
<P>
   Megaplexes, which cost about $1 million per screen to build,
accounted for more than half of the 3,086 new screens built last
year in the United States. Chains such as AMC, Regal, General
Cinema and Carmike led the impressive expansion pace, driven by the
improved financial performance that the new theaters deliver.
</P>
<P>
   ``To say there's no turning back from megaplexing is an
understatement,'' Skislock said. ``This battle is only going to get
more intense.''
</P>
<P>
   Pacific opened one of the region's largest theaters, the
6,000-seat Winnetka 20, a year ago and launched the Northridge
Fashion Center All Stadium 10 in December. It recently closed its
five-plex at the Sherman Oaks Galleria, to be replaced by an
18-screen megaplex next year.
</P>
<P>
   Mann has launched new theaters in Glendale, Thousand Oaks and
Westlake Village in recent years but its first megaplex, the Plant
16 at the former General Motors factory in Van Nuys, has only nine
auditoriums operating more than a month after the first screen
opened.
</P>
<P>
   Stocks of publicly held chains have been hammered in recent
months and several other midsize chains have joined Mann on the
sales block. Profits have been squeezed due to poor performance
from older theaters, the expense of megaplexes and tough
comparisons from the year-ago period when ``Titanic'' dominated.
</P>
<P>
   For example, General Cinema parent GC Cos. reported Wednesday a
55 percent decline in profits to $1.4 million, or 18 cents a share,
for its first quarter ended Jan. 31. The conglomerate blamed a huge
decline in domestic theatrical operating profits, which slid to
$400,000 from $7.9 million, and its stock fell 62.50 cents to
$34.375, down 36 percent from its 52-week high.
</P>
<P>
   X X X &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
