<HEADER>
A9389 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-OHIO-EXECUTION18-COX     02-17 0786
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OHIO-EXECUTION18-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Court refuses to stop Berry execution
 &HT;    By Tom Beyerlein
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _ A federal appeals court Wednesday refused to halt
the execution of Wilford Berry Jr., who is scheduled on Friday to
become the first convict to be put to death in Ohio since 1963.
</P>
<P>
   The 6th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals in Cincinnati ruled it
does not have jurisdiction to decide whether head injuries Berry
reportedly sustained in a September 1997 prison riot impaired his
competence to waive his right to legal appeals of his death
sentence in the 1989 murder of a Cleveland baker.
</P>
<P>
   ``At this point, the issues raised by the new evidence are
appropriate only in the Ohio state courts,'' a three-judge panel
ruled. But the court noted that ``the issue of competency was
decided a substantial time before Berry received his injuries in
the riot at the prison.''
</P>
<P>
   Public defenders Wednesday night asked the full, 15-judge
appeals court to reconsider the three-judge panel's decision, state
Public Defender David Bodiker said. He hoped for a decision on that
request today. A majority of the 15 appellate judges must agree
before the court can rehear the issue.
</P>
<P>
   Gov. Bob Taft, who has the power to commute Berry's sentence to
life imprisonment, was briefed on the federal court ruling by his
chief legal counsel, Bill Klatt. Taft made no decision on
commutation Wednesday, but ``the governor is coming to closure on
this,'' said spokesman Scott Milburn.
</P>
<P>
   Berry, however, told Klatt in a 15-minute meeting Wednesday
evening that he is mentally competent and asked that Taft not
commute his sentence.
</P>
<P>
   Berry, 36, has been dubbed ``The Volunteer'' because he has
waived appeals and says he'd rather die than spend the rest of his
life in prison for the robbery-murder of Charles Mitroff Jr.
Although Berry has a long history of mental illness, he has
repeatedly been found legally competent.
</P>
<P>
   ``We believe the federal appeals court made the correct
decision,'' said deputy Ohio attorney general Mark R. Weaver. ``The
law is very clear on this point: Competent people are allowed to
waive their appeals. Wilford Berry has done that and his execution
should go forward on Friday.''
</P>
<P>
   Berry, who has been held at the Correctional Medical Center
prison hospital outside Columbus since his beating on death row at
Mansfield Correctional Institution, is scheduled to die by lethal
injection at 9 p.m. Friday at the Southern Ohio Correctional
Facility at Lucasville.
</P>
<P>
   The Ohio public defender's office filed the federal appeal on
behalf of Berry's mother and sister. If all else fails, public
defender's officials have said they plan to file a last-ditch
request for a stay of execution in Cuyahoga County Common Pleas
Court, where Berry was sentenced to die. The basis of the request,
they said, would be a 1986 U.S. Supreme Court ruling that it is
unconstitutional to execute a person who doesn't understand the
death penalty or why he's being put to death.
</P>
<P>
   But Weaver said ``there's just no evidence that Wilford Berry
doesn't understand these two points.''
</P>
<P>
   He said public defenders would have to show probable cause why a
hearing on such a motion should be held in order to postpone
Friday's execution. ``Under the state statute, a judge could
dismiss their petition just by looking at it.''
</P>
<P>
   Public defenders can also appeal to the U.S. Supreme Court,
Weaver said, but ``precedent is pretty strong on our side.''
</P>
<P>
   State Sen. Rhine McLin, D-Dayton, one of 11 lawmakers who
visited Taft on Tuesday to urge commutation, on Wednesday called
the chances of gubernatorial intervention ``nil.''
</P>
<P>
   McLin, who opposes capital punishment, said Berry's execution is
especially objectionable because of his history of mental problems.
``Do you want your first execution since 1963 to be clouded with
mental health issues?'' she asked.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Berry on Wednesday refused to meet with state Sen.
Robert Hagan of Youngstown, who had asked to visit him, said Linda
Jenks of the prison hospital staff. Hagan, one of the lawmakers who
had met with Taft, could not be reached for comment.
</P>
<P>
   But Berry spent most of the day Tuesday visiting with his mother
and sister. Jenks called the visit uneventful, calm and positive.
Berry was handcuffed and a supervisor was present, but the family
members met in the same room with Berry, she said. Except for a
break for lunch, the visit ran from 9 a.m. to 4:20 p.m. They are
not expected to visit again.
</P>
<P>
   Anti-death penalty activists from the Dayton area plan to travel
to Lucasville on Friday to protest the execution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
