<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-17 21:05 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9390 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKC-MCAFEE-MILESTONE1     02-17 1058
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-MCAFEE-MILESTONE18-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Morehouse's McAfee 499 wins strong
 &HT;    WITH PHOTOS
 &HT;    By Jack Wilkinson
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The ritual resumes at 7:30 tonight, just before the
opening tipoff, as Arthur McAfee takes his accustomed seat at the
head of the Morehouse bench. Seeing that, Craig Boyd, the Maroon
Tigers' head trainer, will reach over McAfee's shoulder and hand
the old coach a roll of white athletic tape, which doubles as
talisman and stress reducer. Then the man Morehouse men have called
Coach Mac for 34 winters will attempt what he's accomplished 499
times before: to win a college basketball game.
</P>
<P>
   Jerry Tarkanian has his teething towel, Bob Knight his terrible
temper, Arthur McAfee his tape. When Morehouse hosts LeMoyne-Owen
tonight and McAfee seeks his 500th victory, he'll do so with a
twirl of the tape. Constantly twirling the tape on his left thumb
with the fingers of his right hand, a sight as enduring as the man
himself.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've just always had it,'' said McAfee, 70, who began coaching
high school basketball nearly a half-century ago. ``I guess I
started it when I first started coaching.''
</P>
<P>
   That was long ago in Florida, at Jones High in Orlando.
</P>
<P>
   McAfee is still rolling his tape more than four decades later,
34 years since arriving at Morehouse in 1965.
</P>
<P>
   There were several lean years, hardly surprising at a school
with such stiff entrance requirements, heavy academic regimen and
limited athletic scholarships. But 95 percent of his athletes have
graduated despite the requirements that McAfee hopes never change.
</P>
<P>
   And there were the glory years, 1989-92, when Morehouse went
90-30 and reached the 1990 NCAA Division II Final Four. There have
been many seasons like this one; the 'House is 12-11, 7-8 in SIAC
play.
</P>
<P>
   Yet tonight, McAfee, whose 38-year career record of 499-494
includes a 441-425 mark at Morehouse, will try to become the 23rd
Division II coach in college basketball history to win No. 500.
``It means I've been around a long time,'' McAfee said, laughing.
``I've been lucky enough to be around a long time.''
</P>
<P>
   His son knows better. ``It means quite a bit to him,'' said
Arthur McAfee III, his father's point guard from 1980-83, now a
lawyer and a legal counsel for the NFL Players Association. ``It
puts him in a category with a lot of his friends.'' Friends and
former adversaries like ``Big House'' Gaines, who won 828 games at
Winston-Salem, and John McClendon, the legendary ex-Tennessee State
coach.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's pretty excited about it,'' said Arthur III. ``He's always
tried to downplay these milestones. And I'm really excited for him,
too.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been fun,'' McAfee said about his life in basketball.
``I've gotten gray and got my brains beaten out. But it's been fun.
I guess that's why I'm still in it. I've been lucky, no health
problems. I've told my wife (Sylvia), `If I ever get up and say I
don't want to go to work, you tell me and I'll get out.' And I
would.''
</P>
<P>
   Born and raised in Wichita, Kan., McAfee graduated from what is
now Emporia State, played AAU basketball, served in the Air Force
and nearly became a dentist before choosing coaching. From Jones
High, McAfee went home to Emporia as an assistant. He got his first
collegiate head-coaching job at Lane College, then he went to
Mississippi Vocational (now Mississippi Valley), Lincoln, Mo., and
Bishop College in Dallas. His 1963 Mississippi Vocational team
qualified for the NAIA national tournament but was barred from
playing because Mississippi state law banned interracial play by
state-supported schools.
</P>
<P>
   When McAfee succeeded Frank Forbes as head coach at Morehouse
for the 1965-66 season, the job was a bit different. McAfee also
scouted for the football team, helped coach baseball, even drove
the tennis team to road trips when Forbes had a conflict. ``They
knew more about tennis than I did,'' McAfee said.
</P>
<P>
   The closest McAfee came to leaving Morehouse was in 1971. There
were other overtures _ North Carolina-Charlotte, Southern Illinois,
Emporia State, other SIAC schools _ but in '71 McAfee agreed to
become the head coach at San Jose State.
</P>
<P>
   ``You're playing in the upper division (there),'' McAfee said,
referring to Division I. ``The scholarships. Full staff. You can
recruit anywhere.'' Not even an opener against John Wooden's UCLA
defending champions daunted McAfee. But his wife loved Atlanta; so
did their daughters, Gwendolyn and Sylvia. So they stayed at
Morehouse, once McAfee also was named athletics director.
</P>
<P>
   He still employs the Morehouse man-to-man defense. The Maroon
Tigers run what McAfee calls ``A pressure break, not a fast break.
We can break only as fast as you can control the ball.''
</P>
<P>
   He had a terrific run of talent 1989-92, most notably Harold
Ellis, a three-time Division II All-American and the school's
career scoring leader who went on to play for the Los Angeles
Clippers. ``Hopefully, that'll happen again. I probably won't be
here. But hopefully, it'll happen for the next group of coaches.''
</P>
<P>
   That would be Grady Brewer, the top assistant, and Roderick
Stubbs, both of whom played for McAfee. McAfee will keep coaching
``as long as I'm feeling good,'' he said. ``But I will not allow
myself to get into a spin I can't get out of and mess up Morehouse
basketball.''
</P>
<P>
   Three more years is the maximum, he said. ``I have two people
working for me who deserve a chance.''
</P>
<P>
   Now the third vice president of the National Association of
Basketball Coaches, McAfee will become the NABC president for the
2001-02 season, the first Division II coach in years to hold that
position.
</P>
<P>
   Until retirement, however, McAfee will play man-to-man D, break
when possible and preach his gospel to recruits and players: ``No.
1, I want you to go to school. No. 2, I want you to graduate. In
between, there's me and basketball. I'm going to give you
everything I have. I'm not going to cuss you out. I was never
cussed out. I'm not going to embarrass you; don't you embarass
me.''
</P>
<P>
   So for now, especially for No. 500 tonight, play ball. The right
way. ``I guess I'm an old dinosaur, old-fashioned,'' McAfee said.
``The end result is who puts the ball in the basket more, isn't it?
And we've tried to do that.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
