<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SUICIDE-REPORT-ART-2TAKES(1,070)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OREGON REPORTS 15 LEGAL SUICIDES IN LAW'S FIRST YEAR
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Graphic with statistics from Oregon's assisted suicide
report is being sent to NYT photo clients. Nonsubscribers can make
individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(nk) 
 By SAM HOWE VERHOVEK   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ Oregon officials reported Wednesday that in the first
year of the only legally sanctioned assisted-suicide program in the
world, 15 terminally ill people in the state ended their lives with
lethal medication.
</P>
<P>
   The average age of the eight men and seven women who took their
lives was 69, the state said; 13 had cancer and the other two had
heart or lung disease. Fourteen had lived in the state for at least
six months and one came to the state to be with a family member.
Eight other people also received prescriptions for drugs to end
their lives in 1998, but six died from their illnesses before
taking the drugs and two were still alive as of Jan. 1, 1999.
</P>
<P>
   The state Health Division's official report on the state's Death
with Dignity Act was quickly hailed by advocates of doctor-aided
dying as evidence that the law had not led to abuses, botched
suicides or a widespread rush among the sick or suffering to move
to Oregon for the right to be put to death, as many critics of the
law had contended.
</P>
<P>
   ``This law has been seldom and carefully used with no failures,
no complications, no misdeeds, no mistakes,'' said George Eighmey,
executive director of Compassion in Dying of Oregon, a nonprofit
group that worked to get the law passed.
</P>
<P>
   The report said that for some physicians the suicide process had
``exacted a large emotional toll,'' but some of the doctors also
spoke up Wednesday in praise of the law.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a very positive thing to have people gather around and
say their final goodbyes and reminisce,'' said Dr. Peter Rasmussen,
a cancer specialist in Salem, Ore., who said he has been present
for at least two such occasions, in which terminally ill patients
died after taking chocolate pudding laced with barbiturates. ``One
of the potential advantages is, you can plan it _ people who have
relatives far away can gather everybody together. I've seen it
happen and it was a very positive, joyful experience.''
</P>
<P>
   But far from easing the debate over assisted suicide,
Wednesday's release of the state report seemed only to inflame it.
Archbishop John Vlazny of Portland, the state's leading Catholic
spokesman, said in a statement that the findings were a cause for
``sadness and shame'' across the state. ``In allowing assisted
suicide to continue, the state of Oregon dismisses the value of
human life,'' the archbishop said.
</P>
<P>
   Suicide was briefly legalized in the Northern Territory of
Australia, from July 1996 to March 1997, but today Oregon is the
only place in the world where doctor-assisted suicide is legally
sanctioned.
</P>
<P>
   In the Netherlands, though, it has been practiced for many
years; while it is technically illegal there, it is rarely
prosecuted. And a report in the Journal of Medical Ethics,
coincidentally to be released Thursday, found evidence of a
``slippery slope'' in the Netherlands, with many cases of both
voluntary and involuntary euthanasia by doctors going ``unreported
and unchecked.''
</P>
<P>
   In Oregon, an adult of sound mind who has, in the opinion of two
doctors, less than six months to live may request authorization for
lethal drugs. Doctors may prescribe but not administer the lethal
dose. Those wishing to die fill out and sign a single-page form,
titled ``Request for medication to end my life in a humane and
dignified manner.'' There were 29,000 deaths in Oregon last year,
according to the report, and for the 15 who used the law, the cause
of death was simply listed as ``Drug overdose, legally
prescribed.''
</P>
<P>
   The state report, a version of which was also released in the
New England Journal of Medicine, was in part a compendium of
statistics that provided a broad snapshot of the practice of
assisted suicide. The average time to unconsciousness was 5
minutes, with the overall range from 3 to 20 minutes; and the
average time to death was 26 minutes, with the range from 15
minutes to 11 1/2 hours.
</P>
<P>
   But the report also suggested there were common elements in the
profiles of those who chose assisted suicide, and one principal
finding was that the primary factor cited by those who opted for
the process was ``the importance of autonomy and personal
control.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Physician-assisted suicide was not disproportionately chosen
by terminally ill patients who were poor, uneducated, uninsured,
fearful of the financial consequences of their illnesses, or who
lacked end of life care,'' the report summary said.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Katrina Hedberg, a medical epidemiologist at the Health
Division and an author of the report, said the state was attempting
to be ``totally neutral'' in its presentation of the report. ``We
were given a mandate to collect this information,'' she said in an
interview.
</P>
<P>
   But, inevitably, release of the findings spurred the question
Wednesday of how or even whether they would change the debate over
assisted suicide in other states and elsewhere in the world.
</P>
<P>
   Advocates of the process clearly hoped that their cause would be
aided by the relatively limited numbers of deaths in Oregon and the
reasons cited by those who chose it, such as ``dignity'' and ``some
feeling of control over my body,'' as opposed to the chaos and
forced euthanasia predicted by some critics.
</P>
<P>
   And in the state capitol in Salem, under the auspices of
Compassion in Dying, a Portland area woman who has a terminal brain
tumor spoke out Wednesday in support of the law.
</P>
<P>
   ``You don't know how fantastic a feeling of relief it is to know
that I have this available to me,'' said Barbara Oskamp, who is in
her late 60s and who said she may opt for lethal medication if she
feels she has become an undue burden to her family.
</P>
<P>
   The Oregon law was first approved, 51 percent to 49 percent, in
a 1994 vote by state residents, but was promptly put on hold amid
great legal wrangling. Then, in 1997, the state's voters backed the
law again, this time by a decisive margin of 60 percent to 40
percent.
</P>
<P>
   Even then, though, the law was held up: Federal drug-enforcement
officials threatened to impose severe sanctions on any doctor who
aided in suicides. Attorney General Janet Reno effectively removed
that obstacle last year, however, by declaring that doctors would
not be prosecuted if they were obeying state laws.
</P>
<P>
   The Oregon report covered all of 1998, the first full year of
the assisted-suicide law. Although it took effect in late October
1997, no deaths were reported in that year.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   According to the researchers, no person who chose assisted
suicide expressed a concern about their financial situation to
their doctor, nor was the pain of a prolonged illness cited as a
major fear. Rather, they said, ``Many physicians reported that
their patients had been decisive and independent throughout their
lives or that the decision to request a lethal prescription was
consistent with a longstanding belief about the importance of
controlling the manner in which they died.''
</P>
<P>
   But the Oregon law has yet to create any kind of discernible
groundswell elsewhere. Measures legalizing doctor-assisted suicide
have been blocked or rejected in at least 20 state legislatures.
Ballot initiatives in California and Washington state both failed
in the early 1990s and just this past fall, Michigan voters solidly
turned back an assisted-suicide measure.
</P>
<P>
   That measure may have foundered in part because the nation's
best-known advocate of physician-aided death, Dr. Jack Kevorkian,
who lives in Michigan, opposed the initiative, claiming it imposed
too many restrictions and too much bureaucracy on the process.
</P>
<P>
   One other possible movement toward assisted suicide is occurring
now in Alaska, where two terminally ill patients have mounted a
legal challenge to the state ban on the practice. Advocates are
hoping to expand that challenge into a sort of class-action
lawsuit, in which they would argue that the state constitution's
privacy guarantees include the right to die.
</P>
</TEXT>
