u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN-CHIPPER-DIVORCE18     02-17 0967
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-CHIPPER-DIVORCE18-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Joneses file for divorce after `going public' fails
 &HT;    By Carroll Rogers
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   LAKE BUENA VISTA, Fla. _ Atlanta Braves third baseman Chipper
Jones already has admitted to fathering an illegitimate child _
putting a major strain on his standing as one of the most popular
Braves players.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday, Jones said the strain was too much for his
marriage. Jones and his wife, Karin, were separated weeks after his
public confession in October and have filed for divorce, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've never been so glad for a baseball season to start,''
Jones said at the Braves spring-training facility. ``It's been a
long, hard, lonely offseason.''
</P>
<P>
   Both Karin and Chipper said Wednesday that they did not realize
what was ahead for them when in October he admitted having affairs,
fathering the child out of wedlock and vowing to change his
lifestyle. They separated several weeks later.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I had this thing to do over again, I'd do it a lot
differently,'' Chipper Jones said. ``Going public was a decision
Karin and I made together. It was as much my decision as it was
hers. Obviously, if I had known what was going to happen a month
later, I'd have kept it all private.''
</P>
<P>
   Karin Jones said Wednesday that she thought at the time that
talking about their troubles publicly was the right thing to do.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought that would bring some honor to a dishonorable
situation,'' she said. ``I didn't know then things would turn out
the way they did. Things didn't turn out the way I had hoped they
would.''
</P>
<P>
   Since November, Karin has been living in the couple's home in
Alpharetta. Chipper has moved into an apartment in Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm deeply saddened and hurt,'' Karin Jones said. ``I'm just
starting to deal with the disappointment.''
</P>
<P>
   That disappointment extended to both families. Chipper's parents
said Wednesday they have known about their son's infidelity for a
year and a half. But they continue to try to understand it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've tried to reconcile it in my mind,'' Larry Jones Sr. said
Wednesday from his home in Pearson, Fla. ``My wife (Lynne) was
saying if I ever did that to her she'd never be able to forget it.
And I said the same thing to her. ...
</P>
<P>
   ``(As a family) we went through the yelling and the screaming
and the `You weren't brought up this way,' and the `How can you do
this to our family?' You reach a point where no matter what he
does, he's still my son, and I love him to death. I don't condone
what he did. He's made some changes in his lifestyle. That's
important in this stage of the game. He doesn't make excuses for
what he did. I appreciate that. He knows what he did was wrong, and
he owns up to that fact. He's doing right by his son; I appreciate
that.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's how it is in real life. You face the music, take your
beating and move on ... Sometimes (professional athletes) think
they're bulletproof. They aren't.''
</P>
<P>
   The senior Jones said that seeing Karin and Chipper separate
``breaks his heart,'' but he added that it might be the best for
both, if they couldn't put their problems behind them.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the biggest thing for Chipper and Karin both was
making the step to cut the ties or mend them, but being in limbo
was difficult,'' Larry Jones said. ``Four or five months ago, I
remember asking him if everything's going to be all right, and he
said, `I hope so.' Now when I ask him, he says, `I'm doing good.'''
</P>
<P>
   With the start of the baseball season less than six weeks away,
Chipper Jones said he knows he will undergo public scrutiny. But he
said he is confident that his off-field problems won't affect his
play.
</P>
<P>
   ``If it didn't affect me over the last two years, it's not going
to affect me now,'' Jones said. ``That's another reason I'm
excited. Hopefully, I can get this stuff behind me and go through
the season without any distractions.''
</P>
<P>
   One way Jones has kept his mind off his personal problems during
the offseason is by working out. He has added more than 20 pounds
of muscle. The 6-foot-4 Jones, who weighed 198 at the end of last
season, weighs 220. He expects the added strength to help his power
and stamina late in the season.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've thrown myself into my workouts to try to take my mind off
things,'' Jones said. ``It's still there, still part of my every
day life, but not having it thrown in my face is sort of a
relief.''
</P>
<P>
   The baseball might be easier than facing his fans.
</P>
<P>
   ``What's done is done,'' Jones said. ``I've heard a lot of
support from people in the few public appearances I've had since
then. People have come up and expressed how sorry they are and hope
things work out for the both of us.''
</P>
<P>
   In October, Chipper and Karin Jones talked publicly about trying
to deal with the several affairs he had after the 1996 World
Series, which the Braves lost to the Yankees in six games.
</P>
<P>
   Jones, who apologized to fans, said that in one of the affairs
he fathered a child with a woman who had worked as a waitress at a
Hooters restaurant in West Palm Beach, Fla. The child, a son, was
born in March 1998, and Jones said he acknowledged paternity and
was providing support.
</P>
<P>
   After the admission and apology in the fall, Jones, who had more
commercial endorsements than any other Braves, lost some of that
income. Fan reaction was mixed, although most seemed willing to
forgive and forget.
</P>
<P>
   Larry Jones said his son is prepared to deal with any kind of
fan reaction.
</P>
<P>
   ``He says `I'm going to have to accept it however it comes,'''
Larry Jones said. ``I said, `You have a tremendous opportunity here
to talk to people about some of the pitfalls that go with fame and
fortune and celebrity and how to deal with it.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
