<SLUG> BC-EDIT-OBSERVER-FOG-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL OBSERVER: EARLY MORNING FOG 
 (DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By VERLYN KLINKENBORG   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Fog is fin-de-siecle weather, or so it seemed on an
early morning walk across town Wednesday. Perhaps it was the sight
of a working gaslight on 35th Street the night before or the fact
that the Met Life Building had been blotted out by the fog and a
shroud of steam was rising from Grand Central at 7 a.m. Something
had put the end of Whistler's century in my mind, and the thought
was slow to dissipate.
</P>
<P>
   Jo Davidson's sculpture of Gertrude Stein _ that most un-fin of
authors _ stared out over Bryant Park, past the white tents of this
year's Fashion Week, past the pale London plane trees rising like
models' wrists into the fog. For a moment, even Ms. Stein seemed as
much an esthete, as much a part of a century's last days, as Aubrey
Beardsley himself.
</P>
<P>
   A city is a set for its players, the crowds that throng it every
weekday. When the set is empty, as it tends to be at 7 in the
morning, it is still hard to put the players out of mind. Walking
up a quiet Park Avenue, past a custodian raising the American flag
outside a fog-stunted skyscraper, I found myself imagining the
rails and roadways that fan out from New York like crooked rays
from the sun, each of them at that moment full of inbound commuters
about to repossess the city.
</P>
<P>
   T.S. Eliot's evocation of urban life _ the undone dead peopling
London's wasteland in ``the brown fog of a winter noon'' _ has hung
over this century since 1922. But this fog wasn't brown, and it
wasn't death that had released the people rattling in even now,
only sleep.
</P>
<P>
   I thought there was a 24-hour newsstand on 42nd Street near
Times Square, but when I got there its metal shutter was still
half-drawn. The woman behind the counter remembered that in her
grandfather's day the stand had been open year round, day and
night, but that, she said, was when New York had 11 newspapers. I
lingered for a few minutes, watching the floor being mopped and
papers from all across the country being stacked on the counter.
</P>
<P>
   By the time I stepped beneath the shutter again, the fragile
morning quiet had faded. Five minutes, and one city had become
another.
</P>
<P>
   The sounds of construction rang off buildings, no longer muffled
by the fog. Near the Port Authority Bus Terminal, people spilled
across intersections, unconstrained by lights or crosswalks. The
end of one century had lifted, and a morning at the end of another
century had begun in earnest.  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
