<SLUG> BC-BBN-BRAVES-NOTES18-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Wohlers upbeat on return
 &HT;    By Carroll Rogers
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   LAKE BUENA VISTA, Fla. _ As promised, Braves closer Mark Wohlers
spoke about pitching when he arrived in Florida on Wednesday for
the start of spring training. But the comments came in a mix of
seriousness and sarcasm from a pitcher who is trying to find the
strike zone and salvage his career.
</P>
<P>
   When asked what he planned to do differently this spring
training, Wohlers said laughing: ``Maybe this year, I'll try to
throw a strike.'' Then he added: ``What I want to do is just get in
the program and go along with everybody else. No special treatment,
no early workouts. People know what I've gone through in the past.
I've been working hard; there's been some upside; there's been some
positive things that have happened (at Camp Leo workouts) in
Atlanta.''
</P>
<P>
   Then he had some more humor for the group of reporters around
his locker.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's not to say that (when) you guys are sitting in the
press box I might not launch a ball up there,'' Wohlers said. ``It
might be intentional, it might not, but at least I have an out.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite the pressure, Wohlers said he's approaching this spring
training with the same goals he normally does.
</P>
<P>
   ``Just because I went through a lot of stuff last year, I'm not
going to change my goals,'' said Wohlers, who spent most of the
season in Class AAA Richmond. ``I'd like to peak at the end of
camp, be healthy, have a strong camp, go north with the club and
contribute to try and win a world championship for Atlanta.''
</P>
<P>
   Through it all, Wohlers is trying to concentrate on the
positive, and he found some of that on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm here, that's positive,'' Wohlers said. ``I went through
some (bad things) last year, and I'm still here.''
</P>
<P>
   LOCKHART'S ROAD TO RECOVERY
</P>
<P>
   Keith Lockhart is in camp early _ position players aren't
required to report until Monday _ continuing to work his way back
from reconstructive shoulder surgery on his non-throwing arm.
</P>
<P>
   As he approaches the four-month mark since his surgery, Lockhart
said he is ahead of schedule. He was released by doctors Tuesday to
start hitting off a tee and soft toss and expects to see some
machine-pitch work as early as next week.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every other day, I've been swinging off the tee, and it hasn't
been sore,'' Lockhart said. ``It feels great. ... I don't know if
I'll be playing in the first game (of spring training), but as far
as being ready for the season, yeah.''
</P>
<P>
   THIS AND THAT
</P>
<P>
   The Braves agreed to terms with second baseman Tony Graffanino,
right-hander Luis Rivera and catcher Fernando Lunar, bringing the
total number of players signed to 31 out of 40 players on the
Braves' major-league roster.
</P>
<P>
   Graffanino's chances of making the squad are slim considering
last season's struggle, the addition of Bret Boone and the
anticipated recovery of Lockhart. Graffanino hit .211 with five
home runs and 22 RBIs in 105 games.
</P>
<P>
   Rivera, 20, was 5-5 with a 3.98 ERA in 20 games for Class A
Macon last year to go along with 118 strikeouts in 92 2/3 innings.
Lunar, 21, hit .220 with three home runs and 28 RBIs in 91 games
for the Class A Danville team. ... Pitcher Odaliz Perez of the
Dominican Republic was not at Camp Leo in Atlanta because of visa
problems but is scheduled to arrive on time and be ready when
workouts for pitchers and catchers begin today. ... Catcher Adrian
Manzano, a non-roster invitee, is the only player who has reported
visa delays. He will not arrive from Mexico until Wednesday, the
second day of full-squad workouts.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
