<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-AIRCRAFT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MORE U.S. PLANES FOR NATO STRIKES 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds: See also KOSOVO, KOSOVO-TALKS, EDIT-KOSOVO) 
(mk) 
 By STEVEN LEE MYERS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ANDREWS AIR FORCE BASE, Md. _ The Pentagon announced Wednesday
night that it was sending 51 additional aircraft, including 12
F-117 stealth fighter jets, to bases in Europe, as part of an
effort to pressure President Slobodan Milosevic to accept a peace
agreement that would include a NATO-led ground force in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   The deployment brings to 260 the total U.S. aircraft overseas
available for use in NATO strikes on Serbian military targets
should Milosevic not accede to demands for a settlement with the
ethnic Albanians who are the majority in Kosovo province.
</P>
<P>
   NATO has authorized the strikes in Kosovo and in other parts of
Serbia in the event that Milosevic does not agree to a settlement
that includes a NATO peacekeeping force of 28,000 soldiers.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton announced on Saturday that he would commit
nearly 4,000 American troops to the ground force should the two
sides reach a deal. The deadline for an agreement is Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   In all, 430 NATO aircraft that would take part in any NATO
strike have been placed on 48-hour attack alert. In an interview
Wednesday, Samuel Berger, the national security adviser, reiterated
a warning that the United States and its NATO allies were prepared
to strike if the Serbs did not accept the agreement being
negotiated over the last 10 days in Rambouillet, France.
</P>
<P>
   ``If he doesn't comply and if he doesn't sign a political
settlement, then he will be facing a military confrontation with
NATO,'' Berger said.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to the F-117s, 10EA-6B radar jamming jets and 29
aerial refuelers, the United States has also pledged to use B-52
bombers in a military strike.
</P>
<P>
   ``No decision has been made with respect to the use of force,''
the Pentagon's statement said. ``This deployment is a precautionary
measure to assure that NATO has the capability to conduct
operations should that prove necessary.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
