<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AOL-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 AOL to Offer Cheap Long-Distance Calls  &HT;       
 By Jon Swartz and Jamie Beckett 
 &HT;     c. 1999 San Francisco Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL; 
The giant of the Internet may be getting bigger. In a pair of moves
to extend its services, America Online will soon offer
long-distance phone calls over the Internet and also may get into
the Web auction business.
</P>
<P>
   The world's largest online service said yesterday it will
incorporate sound into its popular ICQ instant-messaging system
next week. This will allow it to offer telephonelike service over
the Internet for a fraction of regular long-distance rates. At the
same time, AOL reportedly is in discussions with eBay about buying
a minority stake in the popular San Jose online auction company.
</P>
<P>
   Both moves could significantly increase the company's revenue
streams and customer base. It now reaches 16 million computer
users. AOL is in the midst of a fierce battle with other Internet
and media companies to gain the widest membership possible.
</P>
<P>
   AOL officials are particularly interested in jointly developing
online content and services with eBay, according to a report in
yesterday's Wall Street Journal.
</P>
<P>
   AOL refused to comment on the report. ``We've been rumored to be
buying companies I've never even heard of,'' AOL CEO Steve Case
said in an interview yesterday, following a speech at San
Francisco's Commonwealth Club. ``This climate (of acquisitions in
the Internet market) is crazy.''
</P>
<P>
   Last September, eBay agreed to pay AOL at least $12 million over
three years to advertise on AOL. Case has repeatedly called eBay
one of the Web businesses he most admires.
</P>
<P>
   Officials at eBay called the rumored alliance ``pure
speculation.''
</P>
<P>
   Although AOL is the better-known company and commands more than
half of the domestic Web audience, there's plenty to attract the
Virginia giant to eBay, industry observers said.
</P>
<P>
   The Web's most popular online auction site has 2.1 million users
buying everything from autographed baseballs to Beanie Babies. It's
one of the ``stickiest'' sites on the Internet, capturing an
average user's attention for 27 minutes per visit _ an important
selling point to advertisers.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; One thing eBay isn't, however, is cheap. Its stock price has
soared nearly tenfold since it went public in September. Yesterday,
after initially jumping on news of the possible AOL alliance, eBay
fell $4.50 to close at $233 per share. That gives eBay a market
capitalization of nearly $9.4 billion.
</P>
<P>
   Investors evidently think an AOL investment in eBay would be too
costly. Its shares slid $6.50, to $153.
</P>
<P>
   But analysts said eBay could provide a tremendous new source of
revenue for AOL. EBay ``is basically turning Beanie Babies into
bucks. People are buying and selling, and they (AOL) are going to
get a piece of that action,'' said Jae Kim, an analyst with Paul
Kagan &AMP; Associates in Carmel.
</P>
<P>
   While AOL officials were mum on eBay rumors, they acknowledged
that they have melded voice technology into their ICQ
instant-messaging service, creating a cyber equivalent to the phone
system.
</P>
<P>
   Internet telephony _ voice conversations relayed between two PCs
over the Internet _ is still in its infancy. It can suffer from
quality and reliability problems, and can be cumbersome to set up.
</P>
<P>
   Kim, the Paul Kagan analyst, said the addition of voice to ICQ
could be a boon for Internet telephony, which currently has an
estimated 10 million active users.
</P>
<P>
   ``This will make the whole notion of Internet telephony more
legitimate,'' he said. ``For the most part, nothing on the Internet
becomes consumer-friendly until AOL does it.''
</P>
<P>
   ICQ (Internetese for ``I Seek You'') boasts 28 million
registered users and is adding an average of 90,000 customers a
day. The wildly popular real-time chat technology allows users to
exchange private pop-up messages that are instantly relayed over
the Net.
</P>
<P>
   AOL acquired Mirabilis, the Israeli company that created ICQ,
for $287 million last June.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
