<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TOBACCO-LAWYER-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FBI MAKES INQUIRIES ABOUT LAWYERS' CONTRACTS IN TOBACCO LAWSUIT 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By CLAY ROBISON 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ The FBI is asking questions about former
Attorney General Dan Morales' contacts with two Houston attorneys
in connection with the state's successful lawsuit against tobacco
companies.
</P>
<P>
   One is Joe Jamail, a famous litigator who claimed Morales
improperly solicited millions of dollars from him and other lawyers
in seeking help in the lawsuit. The other is Marc Murr, a friend of
Morales' and little-known plaintiffs' attorney whose critics claim
he did little to earn the huge fees he is seeking in the tobacco
case.
</P>
<P>
   Murr has claimed he was actively involved in an advisory role to
Morales even before the state's lawsuit was filed and that he
contributed up to 2,000 hours to the anti-tobacco effort.
</P>
<P>
   But phone records and sign-in sheets indicate Murr infrequently
visited the attorney general's office during the lawsuit and was
only occasionally called &UR;  &LR; by Morales.
</P>
<P>
   Attorney General John Cornyn also began investigating Murr after
succeeding Morales in January.
</P>
<P>
   Cornyn spokeswoman Heather Brown confirmed Wednesday that
Cornyn's office has been contacted by the FBI about Murr.
</P>
<P>
   She declined to comment further on federal inquiries, but one
informed source said that the FBI also was looking into the
allegations Jamail initially raised last year.
</P>
<P>
   An FBI spokesman in San Antonio refused to comment. Morales and
Murr didn't return phone calls, but Morales has consistently denied
Jamail's claims.
</P>
<P>
   In a document filed in federal court by several state
legislators last spring, Jamail said Morales solicited $1 million
from each of several lawyers he considered hiring for the tobacco
lawsuit.
</P>
<P>
   The money was ``purportedly for the purpose of defending General
Morales against possible attacks from the tobacco companies,'' the
document said. It didn't specify what types of attacks.
</P>
<P>
   Jamail, best-known for winning a $10.5 billion verdict for
Pennzoil in 1987, wasn't hired for the lawsuit, which was filed in
March 1996. The tobacco case was settled for $17.3 billion last
year.
</P>
<P>
   The legislators who made Jamail's allegations public were
fighting legal fees sought by five outside lawyers hired by
Morales. A national arbitration panel eventually awarded those
lawyers $3.3 billion, which cigarette makers have agreed to pay
over as many as 25 years.
</P>
<P>
   Jamail, who also was unavailable for comment Wednesday, has
refused to elaborate on his allegations in interviews. But he has
said he would be willing to provide more details under oath in a
courtroom or other legal proceeding.
</P>
<P>
   When Jamail's charges first surfaced, a spokesman for Morales
said the only money that the attorney general asked the private
lawyers to provide was for lawsuit expenses. Each of the five
lawyers agreed to risk $2 million of his own money in return for a
share of a 15 percent contingency agreement.
</P>
<P>
   A spokesman for the lawyers _ Walter Umphrey and Wayne Reaud of
Beaumont, John O'Quinn and John Eddie Williams of Houston and
Harold Nix of Daingerfield _ also denied Jamail's allegations.
</P>
<P>
   Murr's involvement in the tobacco case was not widely known
until after the settlement was announced in January 1998, and he
began fighting for a fee.
</P>
<P>
   He was not part of the Umphrey team, and the other private
lawyers have refused to share their fees with him.
</P>
<P>
   Murr met Morales in the early 1980s when both men were young
attorneys at Houston's Bracewell &AMP; Patterson law firm. Murr
eventually left the firm to launch his solo practice, and he was
one of the attorneys who negotiated a settlement in the 1989
Phillips Petroleum explosion in Pasadena, Texas. He also
represented Morales in a 1990 libel lawsuit.
</P>
<P>
   Murr attended some of the negotiating sessions that produced the
tobacco settlement. However, according to other lawyers, he didn't
make any courtroom appearances during months of pretrial
preparations in 1996 and 1997. His name didn't appear on any of the
hundreds of court documents filed during that time.
</P>
<P>
   Morales has called Murr's assistance ``critical'' to Texas'
success in the case and said he did his work behind the scenes as a
key adviser.
</P>
<P>
   In a memo prepared for the national arbitration panel on legal
fees, Murr's lawyer, Roy Minton of Austin, said Murr was Morales'
``co-pilot'' in the lawsuit.
</P>
<P>
   But the three national arbitrators, handpicked by the Umphrey
team and the tobacco industry, rejected Murr's claim for a 3
percent contingency fee _ or more than half a billion dollars _ and
awarded him $1 million.
</P>
<P>
   A separate state arbitration panel of three retired judges
picked by Morales and Murr has awarded Murr $260 million. That
figure would amount to a fee of $130,000 an hour, if Murr worked
the 2,000 hours that he claimed.
</P>
<P>
   But cigarette makers are obligated to pay only the $1 million
set by the national panel.
</P>
<P>
   Murr could ask a federal judge to order the state to pay the
difference _ an action that would be fought by Cornyn, Gov. George
W. Bush and several state legislators.
</P>
<P>
   According to sign-in logs at the attorney general's building,
Murr visited Morales' office only nine times from late March 1996,
the month the tobacco lawsuit was filed, through the end of 1997,
when settlement negotiations had begun.
</P>
<P>
   In January 1998, the month the settlement was announced, he
signed into the building on seven days.
</P>
<P>
   Then, according to the logs, Murr visited the attorney general's
office on 16 days from February through November 1998, while the
lawyers' legal fees and a share of settlement proceeds for county
hospital districts were being debated. Sometimes, Murr was
accompanied by Minton, who represented his interests in the fight
for fees.
</P>
<P>
   Minton has said Murr played a key role in resolving the hospital
district dispute, which was settled in July, but other lawyers
dispute that.
</P>
<P>
   Telephone records obtained from the Cornyn administration show
that a single one-minute call was placed to Murr from the attorney
general's administrative offices in January 1996, as, presumably,
the finishing touches were being put on the tobacco lawsuit two
months before filing.
</P>
<P>
   No calls were recorded in February 1996, and four calls totaling
fewer than five minutes were placed to Murr in March 1996, the
month the lawsuit was filed.
</P>
<P>
   The office records cover only outgoing long-distance calls
within Texas; they don't reflect how many times Murr may have
called Morales or someone else at the attorney general's office.
</P>
<P>
   Murr has a phone at an office in Austin, which he periodically
visits. That phone, if it were used, also isn't covered in the
phone records.
</P>
<P>
   Only 14 long distance calls were placed to Murr from the
attorney general's office during the remainder of 1996, the records
indicate.
</P>
<P>
   Calls to Murr from January through November of 1997 averaged
about three a month, most of short duration. During that time,
lawyers for the state and the tobacco industry were facing off in
numerous pretrial hearings in Beaumont and Texarkana and flooding
the federal court with documents.
</P>
<P>
   In February 1997, Morales or an aide placed three calls to Murr
totaling about three minutes. That same month, the attorney
general's office placed 15 calls, totaling 101 minutes, to Houston
attorney Grant Kaiser, a liaison for the Umphrey team of outside
lawyers.
</P>
<P>
   The next month, Murr got one, two-minute call from the attorney
general. Kaiser got 19 calls, totaling 108 minutes. Murr got one
call, of less than a minute's duration, in April 1997, while Kaiser
got 16, totaling 83 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Murr started getting more calls from Morales' office in December
1997, when settlement negotiations were under way.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Nine calls that month totaled 53 minutes. The records on nine
other calls were unreadable.
</P>
<P>
   Morales or someone in his office called Murr 36 times, totaling
107 minutes, in January 1998, the month the settlement was
announced.
</P>
<P>
   Murr got 13 calls, totaling 199 minutes, from the attorney
general's office in October 1998, the month the state arbitrators
picked by Murr and Morales awarded the Houston lawyer $260 million.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
