<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PENTIUM-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 Intel Puts Pentium III On Display  &HT;       
 By Dan Fost 
 &HT;     c. 1999 San Francisco Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL; 
Intel Corp. yesterday offered a dose of high-tech hype as an
antidote to privacy advocates' threatened boycott of its new
Pentium III chip.
</P>
<P>
   The Pentium III, which will start appearing in new PCs at the
end of this month, was the star of a ``preview day'' at the San
Jose Convention Center yesterday.
</P>
<P>
   More than 250 companies ranging from geeky software and hardware
developers to real-world retailers such as the Sharper Image showed
off different ways they plan to use the new chip's 3-D
capabilities.
</P>
<P>
   These companies also shrugged off the privacy furor that has
dogged Intel since its disclosure last month that the chips would
carry an identifying number. The purpose of the number is to
increase security so that a Web site knows what computer it's
dealing with, but privacy advocates fear companies could use it to
track Web users' activities online.
</P>
<P>
   Intel will spend more than $300 million to promote the chip,
from television ads to flying banners over Sydney, Australia.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  The Pentium III represents a great leap forward in using 3-D
technology. Intel demonstrated some examples, including a search on
the Excite Internet directory that served up results looking like
satellites orbiting small planets.
</P>
<P>
   Intel's largest competitor, Advanced Micro Devices of Sunnyvale,
has already been shipping chips with its 3DNow technology, which
offers similar 3-D performance. But while AMD said its chips would
run the same programs as the new Intel chips, Intel said many
software developers will create programs specifically for the
Pentium III.
</P>
<P>
   The Pentium III will be fast, too. Intel surprised analysts by
saying a 550-MHz chip will ship by July _ a faster chip coming out
sooner than expected. The chip will be 50 percent faster than the
speediest 400-MHz Pentium II chip now on the market.
</P>
<P>
   Analyst Nathan Brookwood, who runs the consulting firm Insight
64 in Saratoga, pronounced the new features ``marvelous,'' but said
AMD may be able to undercut Intel's prices with similar chips.
</P>
<P>
   Intel wouldn't reveal prices, except to say that desktop PCs
with Pentium IIIs would sell for below $2,000 _ a price targeted at
high-end users. AMD made tremendous inroads against Intel in the
past year in equipping PCs that sell for less than $1,000.
</P>
<P>
   But despite all the Intel hoopla, analyst Jonathan Joseph of
NationsBanc Montgomery Securities sees the Pentium III as just an
incremental improvement. ``It's not a huge event,'' he said. ``For
the average guy, it means a slight leg up.''
</P>
<P>
   In fact, the identification number is one the chip's main
advances. Although no one picketed yesterday's event, there were a
few flyers outside, mocking Intel's branding for the Pentium III.
Instead of Intel's Pentium III logo _ a door marked ``This Way In''
_ the flyers showed a door marked ``No Way Out.''
</P>
<P>
   Intel executives defended the serial number as boosting security
for electronic commerce and said users can turn off the number to
protect their privacy.
</P>
<P>
   Privacy advocates see that option as hollow, since Web sites and
software programs could require users to release the number in
exchange for access.
</P>
<P>
   But Intel said the serial number will ultimately prove popular.
People ``will have to decide what's more important,'' said Intel
Vice President Mike Aymar. ``It's similar to ordering something
over the phone with a credit card,'' he said, noting those
transactions are not necessarily secure, but that people have grown
comfortable with them.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
