   KOSOVO (Kostrce, Serbia) _ If the Kosovo Liberation Army's
negotiators are talking in France about peace, its officers in the
forbidding, frozen hills of southern Kosovo are still preparing for
war. ``No peace is possible without a military _ to live without a
military is not a serious idea,'' said Maj. Sadik Halitjaha. ``No
one here trusts the Serbs, with their brutal expansionism and their
megalomania. No one can trust them after they burned our villages,
poisoned our wells, killed women and children and cut out the eyes
of the dead.'' By Steven Erlanger. (The story has moved in ``i''
news file.) 1,600 words.
</P>
<P>
   With KOSOVO-TALKS, inside.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-SLOW-LIGHT (Undated) _ When light travels through empty
space, it zips along at a speed of 186,171 miles a second _ the
highest speed anything can attain, even in principle. A moonbeam
takes only a little over one second to reach Earth. But a Danish
physicist and her team of collaborators have found a way to slow
light down to about 38 mph, a speed exceeded by a strong bicyclist.
By Malcolm W. Browne. (The story has moved in ``a'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   BOTTOM
</P>
<P>
   GLOBAL-ECON-IV (Undated) _ The economic series, part 4 of 4: The
autopsy of a world crisis, and what it tells some experts about
avoiding future ills. By Nicholas D. Kristof. (The report has moved
in ``i'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   With photo and graphics; 6,000 words.
</P>
<P>
   INSIDE STORIES PROMOTED ON PAGE 1:
</P>
<P>
   LABOR-POLITICS (Miami Beach) _ Hoping to build on its political
successes, the AFL-CIO votes to spend $46 million on political
activities in the next two years and to develop a continuous
grassroots lobbying and campaign effort involving thousands of
union members. By Steven Greenhouse. (The story has moved in ``a''
news file.)
</P>
<P>
   NY-IMMIGRANT-FUNERAL (Hollande Bouru, Guinea) _ Funeral services
for Amadou Diallo in his ancestral village. Diallo died in New York
when he was shot by police. By Susan Sachs. (The story has moved in
``i'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   GERONIMO-PRATT (Los Angeles) _ The three-decade legal battle of
Elmer ``Geronimo'' Pratt ends with the district attorney's decision
to drop further prosecution of the former Black Panther who spent
27 years in prison for a murder he said he didn't commit. By Don
Terry. (The story has moved in ``a'' news file.)
</P>
