<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OBIT-DICKLER-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GERALD DICKLER, LAWYER WHO AIDED ARTISTS, DIES AT 86  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: N.Y., Fla., N.C., Mass. )  By WOLFGANG SAXON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Gerald Dickler, a New York lawyer who represented
artists, writers and broadcasters, including some of those
blacklisted in the McCarthy era, died last Saturday at Mount Sinai
Medical Center. He was 86 and lived in Manhattan.
</P>
<P>
   The cause was pneumonia, his family said.
</P>
<P>
   At his death, Dickler was chairman of the Pollock-Krasner
Foundation, which he helped to establish in 1985 under the will of
Lee Krasner, the Abstract Expressionist painter and widow of
Jackson Pollock. Dickler was the lawyer for Lee Krasner's estate.
The foundation gives individual grants to ``talented visual artists
in need of funds'' in the United States and abroad. Its most recent
report said it had assets of almost $50 million.
</P>
<P>
   Besides his volunteer work, Dickler was a successful lawyer with
lucrative links to the broadcast industry. He was a founder and
corporate secretary of Capital Cities Broadcasting in the
mid-1950s. In 1959, he joined what is now the firm of Hall,
Dickler, Kent, Friedman &AMP; Wood, from which he retired as a senior,
founding partner in 1989.
</P>
<P>
   He was born in Manhattan to immigrants from Russia and Romania
and graduated from George Washington High School in 1928. After
completing Columbia College in 1931, he got his law degree from
Columbia Law School at 20 in 1933 and went to work for the law firm
of Sam Rosenman, a member of Franklin D. Roosevelt's New Deal brain
trust, his policy-making advisers. Two years later, he went into
practice on his own.
</P>
<P>
   One day he received a call from Rolf Kaltenborn, son of the news
broadcaster and commentator H.V. Kaltenborn, requesting his legal
help _ without pay _ to organize the first radio workers' union, a
forerunner of Aftra, the American Federation of Television and
Radio Artists.
</P>
<P>
   Dickler's work for the union shaped his career. H.V. Kaltenborn,
impressed by the work of the 23-year-old lawyer, recommended him to
others in the business, and Dickler went to work with the writer
and broadcaster Lowell Thomas and Mike Todd, the movie director, in
promoting Cinerama, the wide-screen movie format.
</P>
<P>
   After Cinerama was sold in the mid-1950s, Dickler and others
joined to buy a small radio station in Albany and a television
outlet in Durham, N.C. They formed the cornerstones of Capital
Cities Communications, which grew into a major media force with
stakes in radio, television and publishing.
</P>
<P>
   In 1986, the company took over ABC and became Capital Cities/ABC
Inc., of which Dickler was a board member emeritus; it, in turn,
was swallowed up in 1996 by the Walt Disney Company.
</P>
<P>
   Dickler was the author of ``Man on Trial: History-Making Trials
from Socrates to Oppenheimer'' (Doubleday, 1962). It summed up 13
trials and excerpted court records from cases that he selected for
having reflected their times and leaving an impact on Western
history.
</P>
<P>
   Dickler represented John Henry Faulk, whose career in radio and
television was cut short when CBS fired him 1955. The dismissal
followed allegations of Communist sympathies on Faulk's part.
Dickler, his former business manager, worked for him without pay in
the ensuing litigation.
</P>
<P>
   He also had his brush with the bitter and labyrinthine feud over
the valuable estate of Mark Rothko that went on for years among the
painter's heirs, executors and other parties. Rothko committed
suicide, and Dickler represented the guardian and aunt of Rothko's
young son, Christopher, in the court battles.
</P>
<P>
   Dickler is survived by his wife of 65 years, Ruth Crohn Dickler;
three daughters, Abby Pratt of West Stockbridge, Mass., Jane Lebow
of Manhattan and Susan Dickler of Lexington, Mass.; a brother,
Irving, of Sunrise, Fla., and four grandchildren.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-17-99 2123EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
