<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-DODGERS-NOTES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MLICKI DEALS WITH TRADE TALK
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BRIAN DOHN  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   VERO BEACH, Fla. _ The numbers weren't gaudy, but in 20 starts
with the Dodgers last season Dave Mlicki did more than go 7-3. The
consensus among baseball people was he showed he belonged in the
rotation rather than the bullpen.
</P>
<P>
   Yet, here he is again, fighting for a starting role as spring
training commences. This time, though, the battle figures to
involve his future with the Dodgers. Mlicki, 30, concedes starters
Chan Ho Park, Kevin Brown and Darren Dreifort aren't going
anywhere. With Carlos Perez looming as the lone left-handed
starter, it leaves Mlicki and Ismael Valdes, 25, for the fifth
starting spot. By process of elimination, Mlicki is the leading
contender to be traded.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's nothing you can do about it,'' Mlicki said Wednesday,
a day before pitchers and catchers voluntarily report to
Dodgertown. ``I've been dealing with this for a while now. It used
to bother me, but now I kind of look at it as a positive. When
there's that many teams out there who want me, you have to look at
it that way.''
</P>
<P>
   What could ultimately determine Mlicki's address when spring
training breaks won't necessarily be who's interested, but what
they're willing to part with in a trade.
</P>
<P>
   Dodgers general manager Kevin Malone said he won't make a deal
for the sake of making a deal. He also said he's wary of dealing a
starter before spring training even begins.
</P>
<P>
   Given his druthers, there's no question where Mlicki wants to
play.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd love to stay here,'' Mlicki said. ``I think when you look
at this team, a lot of good things are going to happen, and I
definitely want to be a part of it. L.A. is a great place, and you
can't get much better than the Dodgers.''
</P>
<P>
   Mlicki's role became more defined, and his value may have
increased, after he came to the team in the Hideo Nomo deal last
season. He went 7-3 with a 4.05 ERA in 20 starts as a starter with
the Dodgers.
</P>
<P>
   Before that there were questions of whether Mlicki, who is 31-35
lifetime, would be better used out of the bullpen. In 1996, he went
6-7 with a 3.30 ERA as a middle reliever and spot starter with the
New York Mets.
</P>
<P>
   ``(Starting) is what I prefer to do, it's what I've always
done,'' said Mlicki, who is 24-30 as a starter. ``The one year I
relieved with the Mets, I felt like I did a good job, and I think
they liked the job I did, but I'm just not that type of guy.''
</P>
<P>
   Come see Dodgers . . . and beaches: With the Dodgers examining a
move to a new spring training site in Arizona, Indian River County
(Fla.) wants to show tourists there is more to Vero Beach, and the
surrounding area, than six weeks of baseball in February and March.
</P>
<P>
   The county will advertise on cable stations within Florida,
enticing tourists to attend spring training games and then check
out the area. The 30-second television ads, to be paid for with
tourist development tax money, will feature the area's beaches,
shops and hotels.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-17-99 2130EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990217.0475 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-17 21:31 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9421 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-OCTOBER-SKY-REVIEW-LA     02-17 0550
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OCTOBER-SKY-REVIEW-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OUR RATING: 3 STARS 
 

</HEADLINE>
 
(For use by NYTimes News Service clients) By BOB STRAUSS  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ ``October Sky'' tells the more or less true story
of Homer Hickam, a West Virginia coal miner's son whose youthful
fascination with rocket science eventually led to a career with
NASA.
</P>
<P>
   Some Hollywood rocket scientists _ director Joe Johnston
(``Jumanji''), producer Charles Gordon (``Waterworld,'' ``Field of
Dreams'') and screenwriter Lewis Colick (``Ghosts of Mississippi'')
_ have apparently worked over Hickam's memoir ``Rocket Boys'' to a
commercial fare-thee-well. The thing plays like a ``Rocky'' movie
for physics nerds, with a male weepie subplot of father-son
friction thrown in for good measure.
</P>
<P>
   Cliched as the film may be, though, there are far worse things
than promoting learning in a beat-the-odds, rah-rah manner _ and it
must be noted that ``October Sky'' handles the material in a much
more subdued, naturalistic way than the slicker, superficial ``Dead
Poets Society'' did. We're also fortunate that the skeptical,
hard-bitten dad is played by Chris Cooper, whose convincing,
sympathetic presence has grounded hokum of all stripes (``Lone
Star,'' ``The Horse Whisperer,'' ``A Time to Kill'') in honest
behavior.
</P>
<P>
   Young Homer, played earnestly by Jake Gyllenhaal, is, like many
Americans, alarmed and inspired when the Soviet Union launches the
first Sputnik satellite in 1957. Too puny to earn the football
scholarship his older brother (Scott Miles) is headed for, Jake is
expected to go straight to the mines once he graduates high school.
</P>
<P>
   But now his head's in the heavens, not down in the hole. Risking
social ostracism by befriending the school geek Quentin (Chris Owen
of ``She's All That'' and TV's ``7th Heaven''), Homer and his pals
Roy Lee (William Lee Scott) and O'Dell (Chad Lindberg), set to
studying jet propulsion and experimenting with increasingly
powerful _ and unpredictable _ homemade rocket launches.
</P>
<P>
   Such activity is encouraged by Miss Riley (Laura Dern), one of
those super-supportive movie teachers who can't be long for this
world. It's pretty much dismissed as pie-in-the-sky nonsense by
everybody else, most particularly Homer's mine foreman father John
(Cooper). Tensions mount when a predictable cave-in, then a strike,
threatens John's livelihood. But gosh darn it, that national
science fair is coming up, and somebody's got to win it and get
their hand shook by Werner Von Braun.
</P>
<P>
   For the most part, the filmmakers treat the town's doubters with
respect; in the late '50s, outer space was indeed a fantasy realm,
and why should a culture built on the ultimate down-to-earth
business think otherwise? If Homer or one of his buddies gets
uppity about their self-advancement agenda, a working man soon
comes along to remind them that hard labor is noble, too.
</P>
<P>
   This, like a dozen other crowd-massaging touches (Homer's
spunky, encouraging mom, the girl who likes him for his brain more
than his rising local celebrity, etc.), comes off as manufactured
as the movie's overall, triumphal inevitability. But ``October
Sky's'' love of brainwork is genuine enough, and that's really all
the movie needs to rise above its mundane fundamentals.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-17-99 2131EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990217.0476 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-17 21:32 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9424 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-WISE-COLUMN-NYT &LR;      02-17 0773
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-WISE-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: NOW YOUNG PLAYERS CAN ESCAPE COMPARISONS TO JORDAN 
</HEADLINE>
  (rk) 
 By   MIKE WISE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Jason Williams, the rookie point guard from the
University of Florida currently distributing flair in Sacramento,
is lucky. He does not have to be like Mike. Instead of needing the
Dean Smith stamp of approval and a clean collegiate image, he can
merely prove himself as a player and not worry about his sketchy
past.
</P>
<P>
   Instead of trying to measure up to Michael Jordan, whose
presence in the NBA grew larger than legend, he can find a kindred
spirit in someone like, well, Jayson Williams _ the Nets center who
went from being a young knucklehead to a hard-working veteran.
</P>
<P>
   The best thing about Jordan's retirement is not that another
team will take home a title. Crucial to the game's success, the
next generation of players now has a chance to be viewed more
realistically.
</P>
<P>
   Role models more human than holy will help them much more than a
basketball deity.
</P>
<P>
   ``You always want to set high standards, but you don't want them
to be unreachable,'' said Scottie Pippen, Jordan's sidekick on the
Bulls. ``There are boundaries you need to put up to let yourself
know that. With Michael gone, maybe that will be easier. Being
alongside Michael and playing with him, I didn't see him as a
mega-superstar. I was on the inside and looked at the young players
as they just had to wait their turn. But I could see, the
opportunity for anyone to overshadow Michael and the Bulls just
wasn't there.''
</P>
<P>
   Pippen spoke a few hours before his new team, Houston, met
Minnesota and Kevin Garnett. It was also the day before he and the
Rockets would match up against another gifted young player, Keith
Van Horn of the Nets.
</P>
<P>
   Garnett's three-year career is often used as a blueprint for
everything that is wrong with the NBA: teen-age star skips college,
signs ridiculously rich contract based on potential rather than
experience and has to carry, unfairly, a franchise at the ripe old
age of 22.
</P>
<P>
   But Garnett and, to a lesser extent, Kobe Bryant have become
exceptions to the rule. Bryant also skipped college, but these two
play and work hard and win, oblivious to the pressure of propelling
a league trying to recapture its mass appeal.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's one very simple reason no one can be Jordan,'' said
Jerry Reynolds, Sacramento's director of player personnel.
``They're not nearly as good as he was. If someone is trying to be
Michael, they're going to be nothing but a big disappointment.
Whoever is trying to promote their players like Michael is also
going to fail miserably.''
</P>
<P>
   Reynolds and the Kings' staff interviewed Williams before they
drafted him seventh last June. His dismissal from his college team
20 games into his senior season for violating team and athletic
department policy and his history of transferring in and out of
schools _ he signed with Providence, spurned the Friars and went to
Marshall, then transferred to Florida _ frightened many teams away.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was pretty honest,'' Reynolds said of the meeting. ``He
said he did something _ marijuana was involved _ but he added that
most of the problems stemmed from the fact he didn't like college.
I just told him: `We'll never make you go to class. Just take Jump
Shots 101, and you'll be fine.'
</P>
<P>
   ``Some kids mess up when they're 20 and keep doing it. Others
straighten out and mature. For a lot of these guys, though, the
margin of error is much slimmer than it is with society.''
</P>
<P>
   As the incomparable big brother who got straight A's, Jordan
fostered that belief. He was good. Any cocksure youngster who spoke
back to him was bad. While he, Pippen and the Bulls rose in
stature, it was almost as if a part of the NBA family was off
trying to get attention in dubious ways.
</P>
<P>
   The players who come into the league today do not have to work
that hard for attention. They may not be players whom you remember
from March Madness; they may even be players who opted out of
college. The first time you may get to know them is as young
millionaires with either peach fuzz or troubled pasts or both.
</P>
<P>
   It is a tough sell, but at least they can play their game and
plan their futures without such an unfair and unrealistic
comparison.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of us have to step up and fill those big shoes that have
been missing,'' Detroit's Grant Hill said.
</P>
<P>
   At least they don't have to be judged alongside Jordan anymore.
As even a squeaky-clean all-star from Duke knows: it is one thing
to take your team to the playoffs, it is completely another to try
to make yourself into a myth. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-17-99 2132EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990217.0477 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-17 21:34 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9427 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-OCTOBER-SKY-REVIEW-LA     02-17 0557
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OCTOBER-SKY-REVIEW-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TALE OF COAL MINER'S SON RISES ABOVE, TOO
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
OUR RATING: 3 STARS 
 
 
By BOB STRAUSS  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ ``October Sky'' tells the more or less true story
of Homer Hickam, a West Virginia coal miner's son whose youthful
fascination with rocket science eventually led to a career with
