</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990217.0478 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-17 21:35 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9428 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GA-LEGIS-FOES18-COX     02-17 0539
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GA-LEGIS-FOES18-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Small businesses worry about costs
 &HT;    By Andy Miller and Kathey Pruitt
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Tib's Electrical Service Co. pays all costs of health
insurance for covering its 45 employees. The suburban Atlanta firm
offers a rich benefits plan because ``it's hard to keep quality
electricians,'' said general manager Todd Tibbetts.
</P>
<P>
   But the company's health costs, at about $200,000 annually, go
up by 10 percent a year for its PPO managed care plan, Tibbetts
said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   That's why Tibbetts is concerned that managed care legislation
pushed by Gov. Roy Barnes will mean even higher premium increases _
by much more than the 1.6 percent maximum the governor asserts.
</P>
<P>
   ``One percent is very unrealistic,'' Tibbetts said.
</P>
<P>
   Getting support of such small firms as Tib's, and their larger
corporate counterparts, will be crucial for the managed care
industry to defeat pieces of Barnes' health care plan.
</P>
<P>
   Business and insurance officials scrambled Wednesday to get
details of the Barnes package. And they expressed frustration that
the actual bills would not be introduced until Monday. That
effectively gives the governor nine working days to force them
through one chamber of the Legislature.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is extremely important,'' said Bert Fridlin of the
National Federation of Independent Business. ``You can't take on
something this sweeping and do it overnight.''
</P>
<P>
   The Legislature should allow enough time to study the issues,
said Earl Rogers of the Georgia Chamber of Commerce.
</P>
<P>
   Political analysts say lack of time may be the most effective
argument opponents can raise to a package of reforms by a popular
governor directed at an unpopular industry. Attempting to delay the
bills for more in-depth analysis, which would defer them to next
year, might be more successful than trying to kill them outright,
political scientists said.
</P>
<P>
   The business-insurance collaboration, successful in the past at
opposing smaller insurance bills, will likely focus its efforts on
two Barnes proposals: liability for managed care companies on
coverage decisions, and wider patient choice of doctor and
hospital.
</P>
<P>
   Their argument will hinge on one central factor: cost.
</P>
<P>
   If legislation raises premiums for employers, the cost will be
borne by workers as well, Fridlin said. Another danger is that more
companies will drop insurance _ leading to more uninsured
Georgians, said Betsey Weltner, spokeswoman for the Georgia
Association of HMOs.
</P>
<P>
   Under Barnes' choice-of-doctor issue, patients would be able to
select a health plan allowing them to visit non-network providers.
The consumers would generally pay a premium differential of no more
than 7.5 percent.
</P>
<P>
   That doesn't cover the true market cost of choice, Fridlin
added. Under Barnes' proposal, ``employers will have to eat a lot
of the costs and shift costs to the employees,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Barnes' plan for opening up networks to other doctors would
reduce the quality of care, argued physicians for Kaiser
Permanente, a leading HMO. ``We couldn't monitor quality,'' said
Dr. Bruce Perry of the Permanente group.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
