<DOCNO> NYT19990217.0479 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-17 21:35 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9429 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GA-LEGIS-HEALTHCARE18     02-17 1111
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GA-LEGIS-HEALTHCARE18-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Georgia Gov. Barnes' plans to expand doctor choice, right to sue
HMOs likely to draw stiff opposition
 &HT;    By Kathey Pruitt and Andy Miller
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Gov. Roy Barnes prescribed a package of far-reaching
health care reform Wednesday, touching off what may be his most
ambitious and contentious effort of the legislative session.
</P>
<P>
   In the forefront are his plans to open HMO networks to more
doctor choice and more lawsuits if patients are denied treatment.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're in for a fight with the insurance industry money on one
side and what the people of Georgia want on the other,'' Barnes
said. ``But I'm used to fights with a lot of money on the other
side.''
</P>
<P>
   The last major piece of Barnes' first-year legislative agenda _
three bills to be introduced Monday _ will initiate the reforms
that were the most visible and most promised of Barnes' campaign
for governor. The proposed changes will let managed care patients
go to any doctor and pay minimal additional costs as long as the
doctor agrees to terms of the HMO plan.
</P>
<P>
   And managed care networks will be opened to lawsuits over denial
of treatment as the last step of an external appeals process.
Barnes also intends to create an insurance consumer advocate to
fight for lower rates and represent consumers in insurance
disputes.
</P>
<P>
   Representatives of insurance companies, small-business and
big-business lobbying groups and HMOs who had been anticipating
this action for months responded immediately. Their warning:
Barnes' plan could mean skyrocketing insurance rates for patients
and employers.
</P>
<P>
   Betsey Weltner, speaking for the Georgia Association of HMOs,
called the effort ``the largest proposed changes to health care
laws in 20 years.'' She cautioned the combined steps advocated by
the governor could jack up rates by double-digit percentage
increases.
</P>
<P>
   Barnes rejected those claims, citing a Congressional Budget
Office study indicating such reforms would inject, at most, a 1.6
percent rate increase.
</P>
<P>
   Barnes' press for change in the face of insurers' resistance
sets the stage for what may be the fiercest battle of a legislative
session in which opposition to his other legislative initiatives
has evaporated almost before it had a chance to form. On Wednesday,
the governor found potential allies among Republicans who had
earlier decried his proposals.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a pretty good middle ground he's found,'' said House
Minority Leader Bob Irvin (R-Atlanta). Irvin was reassured by
provisions to protect employers from liability and by the two-step
appeals process that makes lawsuits a final resort. ``He's moved a
long way in the direction we've been pushing,'' Irvin said.
</P>
<P>
   Other lawmakers who for years have fought unsuccessfully for
major insurance and health care reform applauded the initiatives as
long overdue.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the past it's been blocked by the power of the industry,''
said Rep. Nan Orrock (D-Atlanta). ``But I'd say they've met their
match with Roy Barnes.''
</P>
<P>
   Unlike his proposal to create a transportation superagency to
deal with metro Atlanta's traffic gridlock and pollution, the new
governor has now tackled an issue that touches every corner of the
state.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of people don't have to get out and fight traffic every
day, where they do have to worry about health care,'' said Charles
Bullock, a University of Georgia political scientist.
</P>
<P>
   Under Barnes' proposal, HMOs must offer clients an opportunity
to enroll in a ``consumer choice option'' that permits them to go
to any doctor they choose. But the patient must pick up the
additional costs, capped at 7.5 percent of the premium.
</P>
<P>
   The governor also proposes an appeals process to deal with
denial of treatment. Patients first would bring a grievance to a
panel of outside doctors to review the case. That's a process
several of Georgia's eight managed care providers voluntarily
agreed to this year.
</P>
<P>
   But HMOs balk at the next step: allowing patients to sue managed
care providers for injury resulting from denied or delayed
treatment. Currently, Georgia law restricts such lawsuits to breach
of contract or physician malpractice.
</P>
<P>
   Barnes modeled his enhanced liability proposal after a Texas
law. But he said he won't follow Texas' example and open HMOs to
punitive damages that insurers warn would drive settlements into
the hundreds of millions of dollars.
</P>
<P>
   Two lawsuits have been filed since the Texas law was enacted in
September 1997, according to a spokesman for the Texas insurance
commissioner's office. But the law has resulted in more than 400
independent reviews, according to Texas health care attorney George
Parker Young. And about half of those reviews resulted in HMOs
reversing their decision.
</P>
<P>
   ``I haven't seen any downside to it,'' said Charles Inlander,
president of the People's Medical Society, a nonprofit grass-roots
medical advocacy group for patients. ``This is sound consumer
protection.''
</P>
<P>
   Barnes also disputes claims that his reforms will hit small
businesses who buy outside insurance harder than it will big
companies, whose self-insured plans typically are not regulated by
the state. The liability reform will apply to all companies, Barnes
said, including those that self-insure, if they employ an outside
plan administrator.
</P>
<P>
   Barnes' plan for an insurance advocacy office isn't expected to
run into as much opposition.
</P>
<P>
   ``A competent, independent advocate could play an important role
on rate increases and services,'' said consumer health advocate
Linda Lowe. ``That person could identify problems and patterns of
anti-consumer actions, and propose remedies.''
</P>
<P>
   Legislation to create a health department consolidating several
state agencies _ another Barnes proposal _ also will be introduced
next week.
</P>
<P>
   With the 40-day General Assembly session almost two-thirds done,
the governor's health care overhaul will have nine working days to
move through one legislative chamber or be put on hold for the
year. Though he says he's not concerned about the time constraints,
Barnes is splitting up the package. He's starting one bill in the
House and two in the Senate in what some political observers say is
a compartmentalization strategy to ensure that some portion of it
stays afloat.
</P>
<P>
   ``We think time is on our side,'' Barnes said. ``No longer are
we going to cower to those in the halls that say that the world is
going to come to an end ... just because we want to reform what is
a harsh system.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Staff writer Diane Lore contributed to this report.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
