A9430 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GA-LEGIS-TEXAS18-COX     02-17 0458
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GA-LEGIS-TEXAS18-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Texas health care law produces few suits
 &HT;    By Diane Lore
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ A Texas law that allows some patients to sue their
HMOs has not opened a floodgate of lawsuits and has provided fairly
solid protection for patients, advocates and Texas officials say.
</P>
<P>
   Two lawsuits have been filed since the law was enacted in
September 1997, according to Lee Jones, spokesman for the Texas
insurance commissioner's office. But the law has resulted in more
than 400 independent reviews, according to Texas health care
attorney George Parker Young. And about half of those reviews
resulted in HMOs reversing their decision.
</P>
<P>
   ``I haven't seen any downside to it,'' said Charles Inlander,
president of the People's Medical Society, a nonprofit grass-roots
medical advocacy group for patients. ``This is sound consumer
protection.''
</P>
<P>
   Gov. Roy Barnes wants to enact a similar law for Georgia
consumers. In Texas:
</P>
<P>
   _ HMOs have liability for the care they oversee.
</P>
<P>
   _ Patients have the right to an independent review of rejected
claims for proposed treatments.
</P>
<P>
   _ HMOs cannot retaliate against doctors for mentioning treatment
options not covered by a patient's plan.
</P>
<P>
   _ Doctors cannot be forced to sign contracts that hold them
solely liable for care.
</P>
<P>
   The law does not protect in many ways employees who get their
health coverage through self-insured plans. Those plans, usually
offered by large employers, are protected by federal statute from
state oversight.
</P>
<P>
   However, that might change. After Aetna U.S. Healthcare
challenged the law in court last fall, a federal judge ruled that
such plans may be held liable for care.
</P>
<P>
   Both Texas and the insurer are appealing the split ruling.
</P>
<P>
   The Barnes proposal has caused shudders throughout the insurance
industry, which fears it will promote frivolous and expensive
lawsuits that could drive up premiums.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our main concern is whenever we open the door for liability,
costs go up,'' said Betsy Weltner, spokeswoman for the Georgia
Association of HMOs. In Georgia, an average of three patients per
plan per year are dissatisfied with insurers' review policies, she
said. ``We don't have a huge problem.''
</P>
<P>
   Kaiser Permanente of Georgia, for example, already can be sued
because of its unique structure where the doctors are an integral
part of the corporation.
</P>
<P>
   But that doesn't mean the HMO would support such a proposal,
said Laura Marshall, a Kaiser Permanente spokeswoman.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would just encourage people to take action too quickly,''
said Marshall. ``And that would lead to costs that are too high,
even if you won.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
