<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-YANKS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
YANKEE CONFIDENCE COMES NATURALLY
</HEADLINE>
   (See also BBA-YANKS-STRAWBERRY)  
 (nk) 
 By BUSTER OLNEY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   TAMPA, Fla. _ Joe Torre believes he managed the best team in
baseball history last season. The Yankees, Torre is sure, scaled
baseball's mountaintop, breathed the most pristine air of
accomplishment and planted their legacy.
</P>
<P>
   So, as the Yankees prepared Wednesday to open spring training,
with pitchers and catchers set to work out Thursday, Torre made no
flippant claims about winning 125 games and matching or surpassing
the feats of the 1998 Yankees. Torre does not believe that will
happen.
</P>
<P>
   What he did say is that the Yankees need to participate in the
World Series. It's in their nature. Dogs need to chase cats, lions
need to stalk zebras and the Yankees need championships.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need to get to the World Series,'' said Torre, leaning back
in his office chair, his black hair shining after a post-workout
shower. ``Because of who we are and what we spend on players. It's
a pressure, but it's a confident type of pressure.''
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees have great reason to be sure of themselves. George
Steinbrenner, the principal owner, will spend about $83 million to
$84 million to keep almost the entire team intact; part-time
outfielder Tim Raines is the only departed player. Bernie Williams
returns, with a new $87.5 million contract, and David Cone is back,
with a one-year, $8 million deal. The players whose intensity set
the tone for this team last year _ among them Derek Jeter, Paul
O'Neill and Scott Brosius _ are back.
</P>
<P>
   And the rest of the American League East is in transition. The
Boston Red Sox, a wild-card team last year, lost slugger Mo Vaughn
to the Anaheim Angels. The Baltimore Orioles must incorporate
Albert Belle, Will Clark and Delino DeShields. The Toronto Blue
Jays might trade ace pitcher Roger Clemens. So the Yankees are
heavily favored to win the division and return to the World Series.
They need the World Series.
</P>
<P>
   In spite of their spring training pre-eminence, the Yankees do
have a list of issues that will be addressed before they open the
season at Oakland on April 5.
</P>
<P>
   Once again, Torre must decide how he will dole out playing time
in left field to a long list of candidates. Ricky Ledee played
terrifically in the World Series, Shane Spencer was arguably the
American League's best player for a three-week period, and Darryl
Strawberry, who bashed 24 home runs last season, is attempting to
come back from colon cancer. ``And don't forget Chad Curtis,'' said
Torre, mentioning the veteran outfielder who is in the first year
of a three-year contract.
</P>
<P>
   Curtis carries additional value because he is the only other
outfielder who has played center field on a regular basis, and will
fill in if Williams get hurt. As spring training begins and
Strawberry's status is uncertain, it figures that a platoon of the
left-handed-hitting Ledee and the right-handed-hitting Curtis may
emerge. If Spencer doesn't have a great spring, the Yankees could
deal him to Oakland for the right-handed pitcher Blake Stein.
</P>
<P>
   The rotation is all but set with Cone, David Wells, Orlando
Hernandez, Andy Pettitte and Hideki Irabu, with Ramiro Mendoza in
reserve.
</P>
<P>
   If the Yankees are to approach 114 regular-season victories
again, it will be because the rotation is as good as it was last
year. But, Torre noted, Cone and Wells are each a year older, and
Irabu was inconsistent last season. ``Irabu needs to step it up, no
question,'' said Torre, remembering that when Irabu pitched well
early last year, ``maybe he thought it was easy.''
</P>
<P>
   Jorge Posada started at catcher in 85 of the Yankees' 162 games
last season, nine more than Joe Girardi. The Yankees decided to
keep Girardi, at the behest of Torre and at an expense of $3.4
million, but Torre indicated that he intends to use Posada more and
more, to the point where he will be prepared to catch every single
day in years to come.
</P>
<P>
   To that end, Torre intends to mix up his catching rotation.
Posada always caught Hernandez, Irabu and Wells last season, while
Girardi was behind the plate for Pettitte and Cone.
</P>
<P>
   ``What I'm going to do in the spring is make sure Jorge catches
guys he didn't catch last year,'' Torre said.
</P>
<P>
   Jeff Nelson and Darren Holmes both had back trouble last year,
and both say they are feeling fine now. But they will be watched
carefully _ Nelson in particular, because of his importance to the
club's middle relief.
</P>
<P>
   Torre will meet with the full squad next week, and he is
uncertain exactly what he will say. He knows he's not going to ask
his players to reach for 125 victories. ``They have to be careful
of what's haunted us all winter,'' Torre said. ``What are you going
to do next year?''
</P>
<P>
   Torre will ask the Yankees to prepare well and play hard, as
they did last year.
</P>
<P>
   And he might ask them to once again quench their need for the
World Series.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
