<P>
   (NYT24) HOLLANDE BOURU, Guinea -- Feb. 17, 1999 --
NY-IMMIGRANT-FUNERAL, 2-17 -- Amadou Diallo is buried Wednesday
under a fig tree in the village that his great-grandfather founded
more than 100 years ago; Saikou Diallo stands to the right of Al
Sharpton as his son is placed in the ground. The funeral ended a
remarkable journey that began with the death of Diallo death two
weeks ago, when he was accidentally shot by four New York City
police officers. (Ozier Muhammad/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT23) BOSTON -- Feb. 17, 1999 -- ASH-WEDNESDAY, 2-17 -- The
Right Rev. Barbara Harris places ashes on the forehead of a
parishioner at the Cathedral Church of Saint Paul in Boston on
Wednesday. Such practices (which are growing in popularity) give
people a formal means to express belief ``in a time when so much
seems confusing and unstructured,'' says Wes Granberg-Michaelson,
general-secretary of the 185,000-member Reformed Church in America.
(Evan Richman/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT22) MOJOKERTO, Indonesia -- Feb. 17, 1999 --
GLOBAL-ECON-IV-2, 2-17 -- Hard times in Indonesia have turned
people against one another. Mr. Salamet, a rickshaw driver
(carrying bat), goes with a group of neighbors to hunt ``ninja'' -
outsiders viewed as sorcerers - who have been blamed for a series
of anti-Muslim killings. (Stuart Isett/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT21) CANTRALL, Ill. -- Feb. 17, 1999 -- GLOBAL-ECON-IV-1,
2-17 -- The crunch in Thailand has squeezed this Midwesterner, who
now has too many hogs and not enough welcoming Asian chopsticks.
``I don't know what we're going to do in the next three months,''
says Charles E. Burrus, 65, oblivious to the stench of the 7,000
animals around him. ``We're losing $10,000 to $15,000 a semi
load.'' (Ozier Muhammad/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT20) WASHINGTON -- Feb. 17, 1999 -- CLINTON-SOCSEC, 2-17 --
Social Security was the issue being discussed Wednesday at the
White House. President Clinton and his wife, Hillary Rodham
Clinton, react to a question about her running for the senate from
New York. (Stephen Crowley/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT19) ISTANBUL, Turkey -- Feb. 17, 1999 -- KURD-TURKEY, 2-17
-- Jubilation enveloped Turkey on Wednesday after the capture of
the country's most-wanted fugitive, Kurdish rebel leader Abdullah
Ocalan, but debate over his trial has already begun to turn bitter.
Nowhere is the emotional chaos more visible than among the mourners
at Edirnekapi Sehitligi, an Istanbul cemetery where soldiers killed
in the Kurdish war are buried. (Staton R. Winter/New York Times
Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT18) BEIJING -- Feb. 17, 1999 -- CHINA-LOTTERY, 2-17 -- Hu
Muqin, 63, won a car, the top prize, in one of Beijing's lotteries.
Nothing has drawn out the people of this city like the lotteries
that began last weekend and which are part of a national craze.
Hundreds of thousands of Beijingers have endured the long rows of
ticket windows, heeding the giant red signs that say ``Make Your
Dreams Come True'' by buying wads of tickets at 24 cents each.
(Erik Eckholm/New York Times Photo) *LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT17) LOS ANGELES -- Feb. 17, 1999 -- HOLOCAUST-HISTORIANS,
2-17 -- Saul Friedlander, a history professor at the University of
Tel Aviv, says he was approached recently by officials of
Bertelsmann, the German publishing company, after an article in a
Swiss magazine accused the company of publishing pro-Nazi and
anti-Semitic books in the Nazi years. Freidlander's recruitment
illustrates the current demand for World War II research. (Marissa
Roth/New York Times Photo) *LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT16) NEW YORK -- Feb. 17, 1999 -- MEADOW-DANCE-REVIEW, 2-17
-- Terese Capucilli, seated, as One Who Seeks, with other members
of the Martha Graham Dance Company in ``Dark Meadow.'' More than
most of Martha Graham's works, ``Meadow'' is one of those dances
meant to be sensed rather than understood. (Andrea Mohin/New York
Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT15) ELIZABETH, N.J. -- Feb. 17, 1999 -- IKEA-SPACE, 2-17 --
Seth Weisleder seeks Janice Simonsen's advice about shelves. ``You
have to think 'subdivide' and the space suddenly expands with
possibilities,'' says Ms. Simonsen, an Ikea designer. (Norman Y.
Lono/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT14) NEW YORK -- Feb. 17, 1999 -- RENOVATE, 2-17 -- This
apartment's owner will supply the paint, tile, baseboards - all but
the cherry cabinets. Five contractors with varying bids competed to
put it all together. (Suzanne DeChillo/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT13) CAMBRIDGE, Mass. -- Feb. 17, 1999 -- KITCHEN-TECH, 2-17
-- Counter Intelligence is not developing anything that is more
than 15 years away, in terms of technology. Most of it, including
the talking oven mitt, is inexpensive enough to mass-produce now,
says Ted Selker, a visiting professor and IBM fellow who developed
the mitt. (Evan Richman/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT12) NEWARK, N.J. -- Feb. 17, 1999 -- NY-LAUTENBERG-RETIRE,
02-17 -- Sen. Frank Lautenberg telling a crowd in the building that
houses his Newark office that he will not seek a fourth term in
2000. ``I weighed the option of spending two years primarily
fund-raising for my election against spending full time on the
job,'' says Lautenberg, 75. ``I've come down on the side of
continuing my work for the people of New Jersey.'' (Chang W.
Lee/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT11) HANOVER, N.H. -- Feb. 17, 1999 -- RETIREMENT-CAMPUS-BOS,
2-17 --- Kendal resident Betty ``BeeGee'' Tuttle, 81, at Dartmouth
Green. She often goes to the school for classes and cultural
events, as well as volunteer work. Ms. Tuttle is among the growing
number of older people who, instead of moving to a Sun Belt
``leisure village'' built around a golf course, have opted for
retirement communities built close to major colleges and
universities such as Dartmouth. (Tom Herde/Boston Globe Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT10) CHARLESTOWN, Mass. -- Feb. 17, 1999 --
VENTURE-INTERNET-BOS, 2-17 --- Yoland Chery, founder and chief
executive technology officer at Virtual Ink Inc., draws on a
``white board'' - an electronic device that uses the Internet to
transmit images from office or school to distant points as they are
being drawn. Of the 99 New England companies receiving venture
financing during the last quarter, at least 41 were Internet
related, according to the Money Tree Survey. (Pam Berry/Boston
Globe Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT9) BOSTON -- Feb. 17, 1999 -- URBAN-LABOR-BOS, 2-17 --
Robert Regan, left, president of the New England College of
Finance, and George Russell, senior vice president and director of
community affairs at State Street Corp. As jobless rates hover at
4.3 percent nationally, more companies are recruiting from
communities once ignored, offering jobs and training to candidates
with limited education. ``We have an enlightened self-interest,''
acknowledges Russell. (Janet Knott/Boston Globe Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT8) SANTA ROSA, Calif. -- Feb. 17, 1999 --
SUB-TEST-TUBE-MODEL, 2-17 -- The first American test tube baby,
Samantha Steel, poses with her mother, Lori. Samantha, now 17, an
American who was born in London, is the world's fourth child
conceived through in-vitro fertilization. At 5 foot, 10 inches and
a size 3, she is an aspiring fashion model currently working in
Tokyo. This summer she will be modeling in Milan, Italy. (John
Burgess/Santa Rosa Press-Democrat Photo) *LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT7) UNDATED -- Feb. 17, 1999 -- SUB-HOME-IMPROVEMENT-B&AMP;W,
2-17 -- The first step in preventing carbon monoxide poisoning in
the home is to make sure that the heating system gets an annual
tune-up by a qualified heating specialist. The tune-up should
include burner cleaning and adjustment and a carbon monoxide test.
(Edward R. Lipinski/New York Times Photo) *LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT6) PHNOM PENH, Cambodia -- Feb. 17, 1990 --
CAMBODIA-GENOCIDE-COX, 02-17 -- At the Tuol Sleng Museum of
Genocide is a display of Khmer Rouge victims' skulls from the
1975-79 ``killing fields'' period. It illustrates why Cambodians
have such strong feelings on whether surviving Khmer Rouge leaders
should be put on trial. The museum is the former Security Prison
21, where more than 17,000 people were held before being executed.
(Joseph P. Albright/Cox News Service Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT5) WACO, Texas -- Feb. 17, 199 -- CIR-GARDENING-ONLINE, 2-17
-- Brenda Killough, a master gardener in Waco, is among the plant
enthusiasts who pursue their interests on the Internet. She says
she will make enough money selling seeds online this year to help
finance a trip to the Chelsea Flower Show in England. ``I've had
packets of milkweed seed sell for $35,'' says Ms. Killough, who
marvels at what people will buy and the amounts they are willing to
spend. (Rod Aydelotte/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT4) PORTLAND, Oregon -- Feb. 17, 199 -- CIR-DISSERTATIONS,
2-17 -- Sonciray Bonnell holding a picture that illustrates her
dissertation on an Indian school. Academic dissertations are
creeping into wider circulation thanks to the vast distribution
routes of the cyberworld. ``It's been a fantastic networking
tool,'' says Ms. Bonnell, an academic adviser at Portland State
University in Oregon. (John Gress/New York Times Photo) *LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT3) UNDATED -- Feb. 17, 199 -- CIR-HEADSETS, 2-17 -- These
days, anyone who needs to type on a computer, open mail or apply
fingernail polish while talking on the phone may want to buy a
headset. The GN Netcom Profile Surefit 405-FLEX headset, left, goes
for $112, and is the only three-in-one headset (traditional headset
plus ear loops and ear hooks) on the market; the Radio Shack Super
Lightweight Telephone Headset ET-153 is a small phone attached to a
headset, so no separate amplifier is needed. (Tony Cenicola/New
York Times Photos)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT2) NEW YORK -- Feb. 17, 1999 -- CIR-MARS-RESTAURANT, 2-17 --
A Martian greeting diners at the Mars 2112 restaurant in Manhattan.
Mars 2112 (the year of this imagined convergence of the culinary
and the celestial), a new $15 million theme restaurant in
Manhattan, tries to create the experience of a meal on the planet
Mars. (Angel Franco/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT1) SANTA MONICA, Calif. -- Feb. 17, 1999 --
CIR-ONLINE-STAMPS, 2-17 -- John M. Payne, 43, chief executive of
Stamps.com, holds a letter with postage printed from his site.
``We've learned there is a lot of pent-up demand by small business
that is tired of being under the iron grip of a monopoly,'' he
explains. (Kim Kulish/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   The New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
