<P>
   (NYT27) NEW YORK -- Feb. 17, 1999 -- NY-WOMENS-FASHION, 2-17 --
From left, Nicole Miller's crushed taffeta tank and shimmer skirt;
Rebecca Danenberg's long jacket over dress with ammunition-style
belt; Michael Kors' fur vest, cashmere sweater and slim pants.
(Corina Lecca/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT26) CAMBRIDGE, Mass. -- Feb. 17, 1999 -- SOROS-RUMORS, 2-17
-- Paul Krugman, the noted economist and columnist, had to retract
a suggestion that George Soros had engaged in insider trading. ``I
allowed myself to serve as a conduit to the media for this story,
and I shouldn't have done that,'' Krugman says. ``I'm a believer
that these things happen, but I don't know what actually happened
and I shouldn't have conveyed that impression.'' (Michael Quan/New
York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT25) BOSTON -- Feb. 17, 1999 -- BOSTON-NEW-MONEY, 2-17 --
Once a ``poor boy from Queens,'' the novelist Robin Cook bought his
Louisburg Square town house in Boston after writing the best-seller
``Coma.'' Thirty years ago, the 27 town houses that line the square
sold for about $100,000, but recent sales in the carefully
preserved area have exceeded $4 million. (Evan Richman/New York
Times Photo)
</P>
