<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-17 21:46 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9443 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CANBY-THEATER-ART-2TA     02-17 1134
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CANBY-THEATER-ART-2TAKES-$ADV21-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOR THIS `SALESMAN' A SOFT SELL IS THE WAY 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, FEB. 21) 
(af) 
 By VINCENT CANBY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The soul of Arthur Miller's ``Death of a Salesman''
looms behind the small, unthreatening revival of the play, now at
the Eugene O'Neill Theater, like the promise of a fierce,
revivifying midsummer storm. You await its imminent arrival, the
signs being right.
</P>
<P>
   As you watch the play being performed, you could swear there are
shifty winds around you, intermittently turning the leaves of the
oak trees pale-side-up. In the distance, you can almost see dark
roiling cumulus clouds and flashes of lightning, but the play's
sharp claps of thunder and their ominous reverberations remain
muted.
</P>
<P>
   Even the short, intense downpours _ sudden theatrical explosions
that briefly engage the emotions _ are the kind that Midwestern
farmers dismiss as ``spoilers.'' The water evaporates before
soaking into the earth. Finally, the play's angry, disembodied soul
moves along the far horizon and vanishes entirely.
</P>
<P>
   Thus is lost the full primal power of ``Death of a Salesman,''
the poetic, rock-hard evocation of the last desperate days in the
life of Willy Loman. Though you may never have seen this modern
classic, you probably know Willy Loman, one of the most haunting
characters in modern American literature, the Brooklyn drummer
whose name has become a generic term for any old-time, worn-out
salesman.
</P>
<P>
   The revival, which originated last year at the Goodman Theater
in Chicago, was staged by Robert Falls, the Goodman's artistic
director, and stars Brian Dennehy as Willy Loman. The production
doesn't do damage to this seminal work, but the play isn't fully
there.
</P>
<P>
   What is most extraordinary about the Miller text is that it is
as pertinent today as it was when it first arrived in New York
exactly a half-century ago on Feb. 10. That was less than four
years after the end of World War II. America was euphoric with its
victory, with its new status as a superpower and with the idea that
material success is, if not a sign of God's favor, then a very good
substitute.
</P>
<P>
   Willy may not be a victim of the system as much as he is a
victim of his own acceptance of the distorted values the system
promotes, the least pernicious of which are his faith in brand
names and dependency on installment buying.
</P>
<P>
   Told that there is still one more payment due on the
refrigerator, which is now not working right, Willy roars in fury:
``Once in my life I'd like to own something outright before it's
broken! I'm always in a race with the junkyard!'' Yet he sees no
connection between his race with the junkyard and the world in
which he lives, and which now sees him as redundant.
</P>
<P>
   Just around Willy's corner there is always an idea that will pay
off big. He remembers his fabled brother Ben in Africa. Ben walked
into the jungle at the age of 17 and came out four years later with
his pockets full of diamonds.
</P>
<P>
   Success, Willy says, that's the goal, but you need contacts.
``It's who you know and the smile on your face!'' To be successful,
you have to be more than just liked: you have to be well liked. You
accommodate your clients. You aim to please and, if you have to lie
a little or shape your personality to make the sale, that's all
part of the game. He is not only out of touch with himself, but he
has also _ with love and care _ raised a couple of misfits.
</P>
<P>
   We never learn what Willy has been selling all these years but,
whatever it is, it's beside the point. Willy trafficks in
transactions and possibilities, in ephemera.
</P>
<P>
   ``Death of a Salesman'' is a stern play but also a profoundly
humane and moving one. Though a fraud, Willy is an essentially
decent man trying blindly to cope with his own failure and with the
grown sons he no longer understands.
</P>
<P>
   Happy, the younger, is a good-natured slob, the kind of
compulsive who in the 1940s was called a skirt-chaser; the beloved
Biff, the high school football hero who once had the promise of a
University of Virginia athletic scholarship, is a drifter and
part-time kleptomaniac. Even Linda, Willy's patient, worried wife,
can infuriate him. Her devotion only feeds his sense of guilt and
despair.
</P>
<P>
   ``Death of a Salesman'' is not easily staged, though not
necessarily because Willy's breakdown takes the form of a seamless
cinematic hallucination. As his memories overtake him, past and
present overlap within single scenes. The actor playing Willy must
somehow have a fixed focus on what are really two different
characters inhabiting a single mind at the same time.
</P>
<P>
   There is the burned-out ruin of the hardy American optimist and,
staggering around within, a man in shock, trying to salvage some
dignity and hope from the wreckage.
</P>
<P>
   Dennehy, whom I remember most happily as the fast-talking Walter
Burns in a revival of ``The Front Page'' many years ago, is a
physically impressive figure on the stage. He is big. Though he has
weight as a man, he is weightless as Willy, in part because he
appears to be in such robust health and is extremely well-tailored
for someone who has to borrow $50 a month for the household bills
and a little more to pay his insurance premiums.
</P>
<P>
   Dennehy can play the superficial Willy, the hail-fellow-well-met
drummer, but the anguished soul within never emerges with
conviction. There is no repose in the performance. His Willy ceases
to exist when the actor isn't doing something, which results in a
reliance on gestures that have the effect of seeming busy, actorly.
</P>
<P>
   Kevin Anderson effectively plays the soft, troubled inside of
Biff, the man who harbors a terrible, life-changing grudge against
the father he once worshiped. It's a performance of dour, collected
intelligence, though there is little to suggest that he was ever an
athlete of even high school celebrity. Ted Koch does well as the
cheerfully amoral, self-satisfied Happy.
</P>
<P>
   The production's most skillful, controlled and fully realized
performance is that of Elizabeth Franz, a timeless Linda, a woman
held together by her mission to save Willy from himself. She is
quite wonderful, though not because she seems to sound a lot like
Mildred Dunnock, who originated the role opposite the great Lee J.
Cobb.
</P>
<P>
   Very good, too, are several members of the supporting cast:
Howard Witt as Willy's steadfast, if sarcastic, best friend; Steve
Pickering as the bored young executive who casually fires Willy,
and Richard Thompson as the ``anemic'' next door, the bookish,
nerdy kid who grows up to argue cases before the United States
Supreme Court.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
</TEXT>
