<DOCNO> NYT19990217.0493 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-17 21:47 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9446 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CANBY-THEATER-ART-2ND     02-17 0959
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CANBY-THEATER-ART-2NDTAKE-$ADV21-NYT </SLUG>
  
 UNDATED: Supreme Court.  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Everyone who stages ``Death of a Salesman'' must be haunted by
the dreamlike setting that was designed by Jo Mielziner for Elia
Kazan's memorable initial production: a skeletal representation of
the Lomans' two-story Brooklyn house, as spare of line as an Al
Hirschfeld drawing, hemmed in by apartment buildings.
</P>
<P>
   With magical lighting (also designed by Mielziner), attention
was effortlessly shifted among the playing areas to facilitate and
enhance Willy's split-second swerves from present to past and back
again.
</P>
<P>
   The setting for Falls' production, designed by Mark Wendland,
might possibly be described as post-modern in that it makes no
attempt to seduce the imagination. It is a large dark space spread
out over much of the stage. Its most prominent feature: a large,
old-fashioned revolving platform that holds a small, three-sided,
doll-house-like representation of the Loman kitchen, as well as
some of the other minimally defined playing areas. The setting is
functional and bleak, though not in a way that has much to do with
what happens inside it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Death of a Salesman'' will survive.
</P>
<P>
   Gone now _ and, I hope, forever _ are the debates that raged
after the play had its New York premiere, about whether or not
Willy Loman is a truly tragic figure. The subject was raised
largely in reaction to those ecstatic initial reviews that
identified Willy as a character to rank with Oedipus and Lear.
</P>
<P>
   Gone also are the suspicions that Miller's purpose in writing
``Death of a Salesman'' was to undermine the United States
Constitution, the American way of life, fatherhood, motherhood,
hardworking salesmen and the fine, upstanding firms that employ
them, if only on a commission basis.
</P>
<P>
   Today we recognize Willy as a quintessential American character,
a well-meaning but fatally self-deceiving fellow who bought, lock,
stock and barrel, the cliches and pieties that continue to give
order to so much of American life. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   --- &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The nimble Roger Rees is the deliberately fibrillative heart of
Martin Crimp's very free, otherwise exhausting update of Moliere's
1666 Paris hit, ``The Misanthrope.'' The play, directed by Barry
Edelstein, is now playing Off Broadway at the Classic Stage
Company.
</P>
<P>
   The production's other principal attraction: Uma Thurman, the
tall, pencil-thin, often steamy Hollywood actress (``Pulp
Fiction''), making her thoroughly gallant, if modest, professional
New York stage debut, playing Celimene opposite Rees' Alceste. To
call the performance modest is no put-down.
</P>
<P>
   I suspect that not many other actresses, no matter what their
stage experience, would have the courage to try to speak Crimp's
overstuffed English dialogue. That is, rhyming couplets in which
there always seems to be an excess of words. They may be needed to
meet the demands of the meter, but they have the effect of blunting
not only the wit but also all meaning.
</P>
<P>
   The only other ``Misanthrope'' I have seen was the Royal
National Theater's 1973 production, which later visited New York. I
remember that production, in an English verse translation by Tony
Harrison, as a joy. But perhaps I'm remembering the young Diana
Rigg's delicious Celimene.
</P>
<P>
   Crimp's version places Moliere's vicious sendup of 17th-century
court manners in contemporary London, where Moliere's aristocratic
hypocrites have been transformed into a bunch of back-stabbing
movie folk.
</P>
<P>
   The beautiful Celimene (now renamed Jennifer) is an American
star famous for her sexpot roles. The jaundiced Alceste, who
insists on speaking the truth and loves Jennifer, is a celebrated
writer. With several additional exceptions, the other roles are
less easily recognizable equivalents to those in the original.
</P>
<P>
   Rees commands the stage, but for good reason: no one else can
master the lumpy name-dropping verse with anything like ease. The
physical production looks very rich by Off Broadway standards, but
Ms. Thurman, in person, live on stage, playing opposite an actor of
Rees' stature, is a certifiable event. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   --- &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A far less shaky certifiable event is ``James Naughton: Street
of Dreams,'' the easygoing, smooth-as-butter one-man cabaret turn
by Naughton, who most recently starred in the revival of
``Chicago'' and, before that, in ``City of Angels.'' Mike Nichols
is presenting the show for a limited run at the Promenade Theater.
</P>
<P>
   Even if you delighted in Naughton's performance as the nervy
Windy City mouthpiece in ``Chicago,'' you have had only a glimpse
of the engaging personality who holds the stage at the Promenade
for 90 minutes, without a break, backed by a first-rate five-man
combo led by the pianist John Oddo.
</P>
<P>
   The format is familiar: songs, backstage stories, some personal
reminiscences and more songs. Included are standards from the
repertories of the Mills Brothers (``Glow Worm''), Bing Crosby
(``Pennies From Heaven'') and Elvis Presley (``Are You Lonesome
Tonight?''), more arcane material by Randy Newman and Billy
Strayhorn, among others, a still-funny Cole Porter parody (``You're
the Pits''), as well as the odd, not easily identified (by me)
novelty number.
</P>
<P>
   Naughton's baritone is as sure as it is flexible. If at times he
appears to be acting as if he were more relaxed than he actually
is, that is also all right: he is a good actor. Just as he doesn't
push, he clearly isn't bored by having done all this for too many
years.
</P>
<P>
   The manner is that of a (comparatively) ordinary guy who has
always wanted to get up and do his own cabaret show, who finally
gets the nerve to try it, and who finds, by golly, that he can.
</P>
<P>
   No one could be more surprised and delighted than he is. The
pleasure is mutual. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
