<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990217.0496 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-17 21:50 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9449 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TV-LANSKY-2TAKES-$ADV     02-17 0792
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-LANSKY-2TAKES-$ADV21-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE HERO AS GANGSTER AND WANDERING JEW  
(FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, FEB. 21)
</HEADLINE>
  (af) 
 By JAMES STERNGOLD   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ David Mamet has always chosen his heroes with
care, and so it is noteworthy that this playwright and
screenwriter, whose dramas tend to read like projections of his own
smoldering inner battles, has made his latest, distinctly American
hero an alienated street fighter trying to flee the country.
</P>
<P>
   He is an immigrant, a criminal angry at being treated like a
criminal, and, perhaps most important for Mamet, he is a Jew.
</P>
<P>
   For his first television movie, Mamet has chosen as his subject
the gangster Meyer Lansky and attracted a strong cast that includes
Richard Dreyfuss (as a largely quiet and introspective Lansky),
Eric Roberts, Anthony LaPaglia, Illeana Douglas and Max Perlich.
Most of the typical elements are there _ rubouts, skimming and
double-crosses _ as the movie, directed by John McNaughton, follows
Lansky from his native Poland to the streets of New York in the
early part of the century and finally to Miami Beach in the 1970s.
</P>
<P>
   But ``Lansky,'' which will have its premiere on HBO Saturday
night at 8, is a deeply unusual picture. It defies many of the
conventions of its two genres, gangster films and
made-for-television movies. And it is a much more visible search
for identity than Mamet, the author of plays like ``American
Buffalo'' and ``Glengarry Glen Ross,'' is used to portraying, even
if that search is concealed within a supposed historical profile.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a loving movie about a kind of people,'' Mamet said in
a telephone interview from his home near Boston, adding that in
recent years he had become closer to his Jewishness and what, for
him, is its accompanying sense of being a perpetual outsider.
</P>
<P>
   ``His whole life,'' he said of Lansky, ``he's trying to build a
life in a world he sees as very, very threatening.''
</P>
<P>
   In Mamet's view, Lansky felt wronged, by his government, by
Congress and by society, largely because he was a Jew in an
anti-Semitic country. Although ``Lansky'' shows its title character
involved in murder and as a leader of the Mafia, the portrait is
affectionate.
</P>
<P>
   Lansky's choice of a career, as an operator of illegal casinos,
is shown as about the only rational choice under the rough
conditions in which he grew up.
</P>
<P>
   ``We just felt anti-Semitism is touched on far too little in
American movies,'' said Fred Zollo, executive producer of
``Lansky'' and the producer of numerous Mamet plays and films.
</P>
<P>
   Lansky was troubled by the violence he had experienced, the
movie suggests, but was unapologetic about it, and bitterly
resented the fact that he was singled out for condemnation by
Congress and the police (though he was never convicted of a major
crime) when others who he felt had done worse _ he had Joseph P.
Kennedy and the Bronfman family in mind _ achieved legitimacy.
</P>
<P>
   This is, in fact, how Lansky felt, says Brett Ratner, the young
director of ``Rush Hour,'' who grew up in Miami Beach and knew
Lansky well as a boy. Lansky, he added, often complained about his
vilification, which he never seemed to understand or accept.
</P>
<P>
   ``What he would say is: `What's wrong with me? Why are they
treating me this way?' '' said Ratner, who is currently working on
a book about the gangster, based on his diaries. ``He'd say, `I'm
as much of an American as they are.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Ratner added: ``He was a very Jewish guy. He loved Yiddish. I
remember I learned one Yiddish song, and he'd always ask me to sing
it.''
</P>
<P>
   For Mamet, all of this _ but particularly Lansky's unwillingness
to accept his government's judgment, his railing against the
identity assigned to him _ made him a fitting emblem of Jewish
identity in America.
</P>
<P>
   This is not the first time, of course, that Mamet has taken
organized crime and gangsters as his subject. He wrote the
screenplays for ``Hoffa'' and ``The Untouchables.'' But to
Dreyfuss, who acknowledged that all actors loved to play gangsters,
this movie felt different in other ways. ``It's not about a
gangster,'' he said. ``I don't know exactly how to explain it. It
smells of family to me.''
</P>
<P>
   There may be good reason for that. Mamet made it clear that in
addition to the powerful identification he felt with Lansky's
Jewishness, there was another subtle but personal connection. He
said he had actually seen Lansky on several occasions when, as a
young man, he had been taken on business trips to Miami by his
demanding father, a labor lawyer whose image has dominated many of
his earlier works.
</P>
<P>
   The two frequently ate at a popular Jewish deli, Wolfie's, which
was a favorite of Lansky's in his later years.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   ``He's dead now and rest in peace, but my father would point out
Meyer Lansky,'' said Mamet. ``I was intrigued.''
</P>
<P>
   Mamet hinted that because of that connection, ``Lansky'' touched
on his feelings for his own father. In fact, several people
involved in the movie made similar observations, particularly
because of the way Lansky is shown dealing with his own sons,
embracing them and trying to prepare them for life but not being
willing to fully disclose to them who he is.
</P>
<P>
   In one speech, Lansky lies to his son and insists he is a mere
businessman but also emphasizes that his son must learn to ignore
the taunts of his rivals, take strength from their enmity and focus
on what he feels he needs to do to survive.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't emphasize too much how familiar this character was to
me,'' said Dreyfuss. ``The speech he gives to his son, I could have
heard that from my father or from my grandfather.''
</P>
<P>
   To make his points about family and about Jewishness, Mamet
concedes, he may not have shown absolute fidelity to the historical
personae. ``In the end, I made it up,'' he said. ``I don't know if
it's the way he thought. It's not the Discovery Channel. It's a
drama.''
</P>
<P>
   Lansky's life story is not, on the face of it, great movie
material, although his beginnings were dramatic. He immigrated from
Poland, where he witnessed pogroms and the murder of his
grandfather at the hands of a mob.
</P>
<P>
   His family made it to New York, where he learned to stand up for
himself in the tough training ground of the streets. He committed
his first murder, of a gambling rival, when he was little more than
a boy. His protector was another Jew, Ben Siegel, later called
Bugsy, who was a lifelong friend, until Lansky acquiesced in his
killing at the hands of the mob for failing to make a success of
his Mafia-financed Las Vegas casino.
</P>
<P>
   But Lansky's forte was the business of organized crime rather
than the warfare of a street soldier, and so the movie is largely
the tale of someone who saw himself as a businessman, even if the
business, gambling, was an illegal one.
</P>
<P>
   It was not that point of view, it seems, that almost blocked
``Lansky'' from being made, though. The script, with its unhurried
pace, fractured dialogue and unconventional narrative style,
jumping back and forth in time, was almost dropped by HBO.
</P>
<P>
   Mamet, originally hired in May 1995 to write the script,
delivered it in January 1996. HBO suggested some changes to create
a clearer narrative and had it rewritten, but lost interest in the
project. The script sat on a shelf.
</P>
<P>
   Two years later the new chairman, Jeff Bewkes, and the new
president of HBO Productions, John Matoian, took another look and
finally gave it the green light last June.
</P>
<P>
   Further changes were proposed, but Mamet essentially ignored
them. Bewkes explained: ``The truth is, he said, `I hear you, but
I'm going to do it this way.' We decided that was O.K.''
</P>
<P>
   And so many distinctive Mamet touches are in the script,
particularly dialogue with battered syntax and messages that are at
best elusive. At one point, Lansky sums up the immigrant experience
this way: ``Time passes. The dust settles. Then it's over and done
with.''
</P>
<P>
   In another scene, Lansky defends himself for running illegal
gambling operations by insisting that the government eventually
will get into the gambling, prostitution and drug businesses. ``Do
you believe that?'' Lansky asks. ``Sore throat, chicken soup.''
</P>
<P>
   Then, near the end, when he is talking to a journalist in
Wolfie's about his life, he concludes: ``Who you are is who you
are, and that's everyone. You want some more coffee?''
</P>
<P>
   Ultimately, the answers Mamet supplies are implicit, felt rather
than enunciated. After Lansky has a heart attack and is lying in a
hospital bed, he motions for the nurse to come close. ``I'll tell
you a secret,'' he says. ``I'll tell you a secret.'' Then he drifts
off, the answer withheld.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-17-99 2150EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
