<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990217.0498 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-17 21:56 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9454 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-YANKS-ENGLISH-THEATER     02-17 0878
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-YANKS-ENGLISH-THEATER-3TAKES-$ADV21-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WORDS TO PROMPT DISDAIN IN LONDON: NEW YORK HIT  
(FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, FEB. 21)
</HEADLINE>
  (af) 
Matt Wolf is the London theater critic for Variety and a regular
writer on the arts from Europe. 
 By MATT WOLF   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The special relationship is beginning to look awfully one-sided.
For years, the assumption has been that New York and London enjoyed
a uniquely symbiotic rapport, so that a major success in one city
could be counted on to open _ and be appreciated _ in the other.
</P>
<P>
   Ask an English theatergoer of a certain age, and one hears of
the defining impact made in London by the original Broadway
productions (occasionally with their New York leads) of
``Company,'' ``West Side Story'' or even ``Oklahoma!'' Both ``Annie
Get Your Gun'' and ``The Sound of Music'' had longer initial runs
on the West End than they did on Broadway.
</P>
<P>
   And while British drama of, say, the 1950s could seem stuffy and
class-bound, the American work of the same period was seismically
invigorating.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was in love with the American theater before I fell in love
with theater as a whole,'' Richard Eyre, the former artistic
director of the Royal National Theater, has said. ``The British
stuff seemed incredibly etiolated, extremely bloodless,'' he
recalled of the playwriting he knew growing up. Whereas with
O'Neill and Tennessee Williams, suddenly, he said, ``drama had
fangs.''
</P>
<P>
   How ironic, then, that the English nowadays regard so much
American drama as toothless and readily bare their own fangs to
dismember many a New York hit. To be sure, Williams, O'Neill and
Arthur Miller are still revered, with Miller joining Sam Shepard,
David Mamet and, occasionally, Stephen Sondheim among a handful of
American writers to enjoy Honorary Englishman status.
</P>
<P>
   But members of the subsequent generations must go it alone, as
must any Shepard-Mamet contemporary _ Terrence McNally, for example
_ who has had the misfortune of arriving in London with a play that
has already had commercial success in New York. More than one West
End producer has remarked that the phrase ``Broadway hit'' seems to
be anathema to London critics.
</P>
<P>
   They apparently prefer to nurture homegrown stars like David
Hare or Tom Stoppard _ or even discover American playwrights like
Tony Kushner or Phyllis Nagy for themselves _ rather than follow a
parade that originated elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
   Yet the American appetite for English work appears only to
intensify over time, as this New York theater season bears out. So
it can be dismaying when the traffic is reversed to find that the
enthusiasm is not.
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes it's enough merely to cite a show's origins, with a
single place name, to speak pejorative volumes. ``You can take a
show out of New York but you cannot take New York out of the
show,'' John Peter in The Sunday Times of London wrote of the West
End opening last May of the American musical ``Rent,'' before
deriding the late Jonathan Larson's ``well-meaning but oppressive
political correctness that sometimes makes you recoil in despair.''
</P>
<P>
   (Peter's review was gentle; three of his colleagues went so far
as to imply, however facetiously, that Larson's death before the
New York production had even opened was a canny career move.)
</P>
<P>
   Conversely, the musical ``Chicago,'' currently on Broadway and
in the West End, received glowing notices in London, but that is a
show that portrays Americans as hard-edged and cynical _ everything
the singularly open-hearted ``Rent,'' for all its real flaws, does
not.
</P>
<P>
   In a review of ``The Vagina Monologues,'' the solo piece by Eve
Ensler that the American writer and actress is performing at the
King's Head Theater through March 7, Nick Curtis wrote in The
Evening Standard: ``The tone is an uneasy mixture of the wry and
the wrenching, of sit-down comedy and theater as therapy.'' Then
the dig: ``Oh, and it comes from New York, in case you hadn't
guessed.''
</P>
<P>
   Even a writer of Edward Albee's eminence isn't necessarily
spared. In London last September, for the world premiere of his
very fine ``Play About the Baby,'' he must have looked on with some
surprise as the British reviews appeared almost uniformly hostile,
while those from American critics were almost uniformly positive.
Given the opprobrium heaped upon him over time back home, Albee
could be forgiven for perhaps anticipating the opposite response.
</P>
<P>
   The more prizes a show has won in the United States _ three
seasons ago, for example, ``Rent'' won both the Pulitzer Prize for
drama and the Tony Award for best musical _ the more that seems to
irk the British.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't like huge hoopla and success,'' said Jonathan Kent,
co-artistic director of the Almeida Theater in North London, a
company that has tended to present American plays (``The Play About
the Baby'' and Ellen McLaughlin's ``Tongue of a Bird,'' among them)
before they reach New York. ``When a show comes trailing every
award known to man, we get nervous.''
</P>
<P>
   In New York, by contrast, Kent said, ``All success becomes their
success; it becomes universal _ that's what is enlivening about
working there.'' But, he cautioned, referring to the city's
hit-flop mentality, ``that's also what's dangerous.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Accordingly, the London response to New York hits, whether large
scale or small, can be grudging at best, fierce at worst.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the second time I have seen McNally's play,'' Alastair
Macaulay wrote in The Financial Times about the 1997 West End
opening of ``Master Class,'' starring Patti LuPone as Maria Callas,
``and it is the second time its distortion of Callas has made me
shake with rage.''
</P>
<P>
   Nicholas de Jongh, in The Evening Standard, dismissed the same
play, which in New York had won a Tony, as ``breathtakingly vacuous
melodrama.'' In the end, ``Master Class'' lasted barely two months
in a city that had always celebrated Callas at least as
ecsatically as New York.
</P>
<P>
   Or maybe that was the problem. McNally, hardly a local favorite
to begin with, could never hope to recreate a Callas to rival
British memories of the real thing. One has to wonder, though, how
the same text would have been received had it starred a local icon
like Diana Rigg or Maggie Smith and been billed as the work of,
say, Pam Gems, who wrote ``Stanley,'' ``Piaf'' and ``Marlene.''
</P>
<P>
   Paula Vogel's Pulitzer Prize-winning ``How I Learned to Drive''
fared little better in its London debut last summer at the Donmar
Warehouse, despite the fact that Ms. Vogel has cited Caryl
Churchill and Harold Pinter among her stylistic influences. Calling
the writing ``unintentionally creepy,'' Charles Spencer in The
Daily Telegraph faulted ``that peculiarly American
soft-centeredness, that craven desire not to cause offense.
</P>
<P>
   ``If it is possible to imagine a `feel-good' show about child
abuse, then this is it.''
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps it is simply that ``How I Learned to Drive'' had the
misfortune to open not long before the Almeida Theater revival of
Racine's ``Phedre,'' directed by Kent and starring Ms. Rigg. (That
same production traveled last month to the Brooklyn Academy of
Music.)
</P>
<P>
   In England, it seems, incest is stageworthy if it is
neoclassical and rhetorically high-flown; transpose the same
subject to the American South, as enacted by characters with names
like Li'l Bit, and the London critics turn away. By Racinian
standards, Ms. Vogel is unseemly.
</P>
<P>
   As for ``Jackie'' and ``Sylvia,'' far better not to go there.
Whereas Gip Hoppe's semi-satire about the phenomenon of Jacqueline
Onassis limped along in New York for much of last season, its
London incarnation last fall barely lasted a month, in a city where
shows can stagger on for years.
</P>
<P>
   Steven Brinberg, a New York female impersonator, made a far
greater impact as Barbra Streisand in the sellout London run at the
(admittedly tiny) Jermyn Street Theater of his ``Simply Barbra: The
Wedding Tour'' than a hapless Lysette Anthony ever did as Jackie O.
</P>
<P>
   A.R. Gurney's off-broadway hit ``Sylvia,'' meanwhile, might have
been thought to benefit three years ago from the London casting of
Zoe Wanamaker, Broadway's current Electra, as the eponymous dog,
not to mention opening in a nation besotted with pets. But Britons
apparently prefer their pooches to be authentic, not
anthropomorphized into cutesy stage heroines, and the comedy closed
after two weeks.
</P>
<P>
   In a postmortem, its London director, Michael Blakemore (``City
of Angels,'' ``Copenhagen''), maintained that Britain is so
consistently fed a journalistic and television news diet of
American sensationalism and violence that it has no frame of
reference for unsensational plays about _ gasp _ well-heeled
people.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, American white-trash plays, however silly or over the
top, routinely get English raves. The Chicago writer Rebecca
Gilman's recent Royal Court hit, ``The Glory of Living,'' is only
the latest in a line-up that has included Tracy Letts' ``Killer
Joe,'' currently playing in New York, and David Beaird's ``900
Oneonta''; each caters to the image of a grotesque, loutish America
that the English already possess.
</P>
<P>
   None of those three plays arrived in London with any New York
cachet; nor did David Greer's wildly overrated ``Burning Blue,''
about gay Americans in the military, a London critical hit in 1994.
In retrospect, anonymity at home may represent an American writer's
best chances for success here unless he or she can go one better,
as Arthur Miller has for much of his career, and play the
misunderstood martyr card.
</P>
<P>
   Who would have thought, for instance, that Neil Simon's Broadway
flop, ``Proposals,'' would find serious champions in the English
press in its European premiere last season in the Yorkshire city of
Leeds? The play, wrote Michael Coveney in The Daily Mail at the
time, ``was far too good for Broadway,'' and will be opening in
London in the fall.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, one recalls Sondheim, during the 1990 National
Theater engagement of ``Sunday in the Park With George,'' being
told at a public discussion that it was a shame he had not been
born English so that he could pursue his career in the protected
environment of London's state-supported theater. Sondheim's deadpan
reply: ``I've enjoyed working on Broadway.''
</P>
<P>
   Commenting on why American plays often do not do well in
Britain, the young English director of ``Art,'' Matthew Warchus ,
said, ``I don't think it has totally to do with nationality.''
Warchus, who estimates that a good third of his career has been
devoted to American shows, said: ``It's to do with the level of
enthusiasm generated in the theater. And I don't think London has
nearly as vibrant and enthusiastic a theater culture as New York.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   ``In New York, there probably would be an instinct to embrace
many different nationalities of imported work as well as homegrown
work. In London, it's hard to work up any real buzz about anything
from our own country, let alone from anyone else's.''
</P>
<P>
   Last year, Mike Bradwell, artistic director of the small Bush
Theater in West London, imported the production of David Rabe's
``Question of Mercy'' from the Long Wharf Theater in New Haven. The
drama, about a doctor's involvement in an assisted suicide for a
man dying of AIDS, received largely negative reviews.
</P>
<P>
   Spencer, in The Daily Telegraph, said, ``All the arguments about
mercy killing are duly and tediously rehearsed, in that
sanctimonious, self-congratulatory manner that characterizes
American `issue' plays.'' Bradwell said audiences amounted to less
than 20 percent of capacity. ``There's very little good will toward
American writing,'' he added. ``The response to David's play was
definitely xenophobic.''
</P>
<P>
   It isn't easy for American writers in London, said the
playwright David Hare, who by April will have had three productions
on Broadway this season, and whose directing credits include ``The
Designated Mourner'' by the American dramatist and actor Wallace
Shawn, a longtime friend. (A revival of Shawn's 1985 play ``Aunt
Dan and Lemon'' will open at the Almeida Theater in the spring.)
</P>
<P>
   ``There are three or four name American writers,'' Hare said,
``who are on the modern syllabus whose plays will always pack
theaters and will be given a hearing. We are extremely intolerant
for the row immediately below.''
</P>
<P>
   That may explain why Paul Rudnick and Wendy Wasserstein have
rarely been seen beyond the Greenwich Theater in southeast London,
which has now closed. And why Donald Margulies, Jon Robin Baitz and
John Patrick Shanley, three often produced American dramatists, are
among those who barely raise a flicker of recognition in England.
</P>
<P>
   ``I certainly tell them it's unlikely they'll ever get a
production in the West End,'' said one New York agent who handles
several leading American playwrights. ``It's always a great
surprise if anyone in London shows any interest at all.''
</P>
<P>
   And yet, the two-way traffic continues. Richard Greenberg's
``Three Days of Rain,'' seen at the Manhattan Theater Club in 1997,
is now in rehearsals for a London debut on March 2 as part of a
monthlong American Imports season at the nonprofit Donmar
Warehouse. Colin Firth and Elizabeth McGovern head a starry cast.
</P>
<P>
   Lucy Davies, literary manager of the Donmar and producer of the
American season, called plays like Greenberg's ``such an enormously
unmined area.''
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a real one-way traffic of our finest British plays,
particularly to New York,'' she said. ``And I've noticed a lot of
anger among young American writers and theaters that emphasize new
writing there. The chances are that a young British playwright is
going to get a play on there before a homegrown talent. We're
sending all our plays over, but we don't seem to be importing
anything back.''
</P>
<P>
   In the commercial sector, it is business as usual in a city that
has 40 West End theaters to fill. ``When Pigs Fly,'' the gay
musical revue, and ``Defending the Caveman,'' Rob Becker's musings
on the battle of the sexes, both began commercial runs in London
this past week. In each case they were Anglicized to varying
degrees so as to play down any New York pedigree (both shows had
long runs in New York) _ as if, by contrast, any producer taking a
London hit to New York would deny its prior success.
</P>
<P>
   Moises Kaufman's ``Gross Indecency,'' a critical and popular hit
in New York, will make its London debut next month in what might
seem a classic case of coals-to-Newcastle: an American play about
Oscar Wilde on the West End.
</P>
<P>
   Further ahead, surely no show will make a London noise this year
comparable to that of ``The Lion King,'' which will have its local
premiere at the Lyceum Theater on Oct. 19. And there have been as
many as a dozen requests to bring to London the Off Broadway play
``Wit,'' about an English professor and Donne scholar who is dying
of ovarian cancer.
</P>
<P>
   The New York producers of the play may well present it
themselves next season in London, retaining, one hopes, its current
lead, Kathleen Chalfant.
</P>
<P>
   ``It feels like this play is not so American,'' said one of the
co-producers, Bernard Telsey, peering into his crystal ball. If
Margaret Edson's play does reach London, it will be in the same
city that two decades ago embraced _ and eventually exported _ a
far cruder deathbed drama, ``Whose Life Is It, Anyway?'' by Brian
Clark.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe because it's about life and death,'' Telsey said of
``Wit,'' ``things like nationality really don't matter.''
</P>
<P>
   But in England maybe they do.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
