<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-17 21:57 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9457 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-DELL-MARKETPLACE-NYT &LR;      02-17 1011
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DELL-MARKETPLACE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MARKET PLACE: SOME DETECTED WARNING SIGNS ON DELL'S SALES 
</HEADLINE>
  (bl) 
 By EDWARD WYATT   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Daniel Niles wants to make one thing perfectly clear: his nephew
does not work at Dell Computer.
</P>
<P>
   Niles, who follows Dell and other computer companies for
BancBoston Robertson Stephens, made a prescient call last week on
Dell's shares. That prompted a round of rumors Wednesday on Wall
Street that Niles had a nephew or other informant inside Dell, the
company that surprised most stock analysts a day earlier by
reporting revenue short of their estimates.
</P>
<P>
   Niles, though, told his firm's clients Friday that Dell's sales
had slowed and that the company was unlikely to meet estimates for
growth in sales. Since last Thursday, when Dell shares closed at
$101.875, they have lost nearly 20 percent of their value.
Wednesday, the stock fell $7.1875 to close at $81.5625, as 112
million shares traded, the third-largest volume for a Nasdaq stock
ever.
</P>
<P>
   Until this week, Dell had beaten analysts' predictions of
revenue and profit growth every quarter for at least two years.
Niles' suggestion that the company would fail to do so now, when
the economy is strong and everyone seems to want to connect to the
Internet, was scoffed at by several institutional investors.
</P>
<P>
   Mutual fund managers and other financial professionals who have
reaped big profits from Dell stock did not want to hear that the
party might be over.
</P>
<P>
   But Niles says that plenty of warning signs were there to be
found for anyone who did a little digging. ``Everybody thought they
would do the usual job of beating the Street's profit estimates by
a penny and that revenues would come in a little better than the
$5.4- to $5.6-billion estimates,'' he said in an interview
Wednesday. ``I think people got lazy. They said, `We know Dell, and
they are telling us that everything is fine.'''
</P>
<P>
   But in ``doing the usual checks'' with firms that track personal
computer sales, Niles said he determined that Dell's fourth-quarter
sales would grow only to $5.2 billion, well below those estimates.
When a company does not meet sales estimates, it frequently falls
short of profit projections, as well. But Niles predicted that
would not be the case with Dell. Better expense control and good
profit margins would put the company's earnings right on target, he
told investors last week.
</P>
<P>
   When Dell reported Tuesday that it earned 31 cents a share on
$5.173 billion in sales, it was as if the company was reading
directly off Niles' research report.
</P>
<P>
   He said his ``usual checks'' were with several market-data firms
that publish estimates on quarterly shipments of personal
computers. Because Dell's fiscal fourth quarter ended in January, a
month later than most other companies in the industry, Niles said
he took the other companies' already reported results and saw that
the portion of the market that was left for Dell was less that what
Wall Street was predicting.
</P>
<P>
   And he insists that no one at Dell tipped him off. Since his
report came out on Friday, ``I still haven't gotten a call from
Michael Dell or Tom Meredith,'' Dell's chief financial officer, he
said. Nor, he said, has he been contacted by the Securities and
Exchange Commission or other market regulators charged with making
sure that corporate earnings information is disseminated fairly.
</P>
<P>
   The SEC, as is its common practice, would neither confirm or
deny that it had looked into the situation.
</P>
<P>
   Niles was not the only Wall Street analyst to foreshadow some
disappointment in Dell's results. Richard Gardner of Salomon Smith
Barney also made cautionary comments Friday, saying that Compaq
Computer was cutting into Dell's business.
</P>
<P>
   But it was Niles who nailed many of the details _ including that
Dell's stock would probably fall to about $80 in the near term.
</P>
<P>
   Even after its big decline Wednesday, Dell remains the
best-performing issue in the Standard &AMP; Poor's 500-stock index
since the beginning of the 1990s, with a gain of 71,000 percent _
twice that of the next-best performer, EMC Corp.
</P>
<P>
   The key question for analysts and investors is whether its
profit will continue to grow at a rate that will justify what
remains a high stock price. Dell stock is trading at 55 times what
analysts expect the company to earn this year, more than double the
overall market's valuation. It reached its closing high Feb. 2, at
$108.625.
</P>
<P>
   Niles said that ``Dell may head lower than I originally
thought.'' Part of the problem, he said, is that Dell has warned
that it will put new emphasis on the market for computers costing
less than $1,000, a low-margin business that analysts fear will
hurt the company's rich profit margins.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, Compaq and others are cutting into Dell's most
profitable lines, including big computer systems that companies use
to power their Internet sites.
</P>
<P>
   That gives Niles and others continued cause to worry. Among them
is William H. Miller III, who oversees the Legg Mason Value Trust
and whose holdings of Dell since 1996 have helped his fund beat the
S&AMP;P 500 several years running.
</P>
<P>
   ``Dell's P/E is on a slow glide path down,'' Miller said
Wednesday. He said the company still had a competitive advantage
that could last as long as 10 years, during which its returns on
capital and earnings growth could be above average. The trouble,
Miller added, is that investors had been expecting that advantage
to last 15 years.
</P>
<P>
   ``With Dell's stock here in the low '80s, it looks fairly valued
in the near term,'' he said. And if the stock falls to the
mid-'50s, that would present an opportunity for conservative
investors to start buying again.
</P>
<P>
   Niles is unsure about the short-term outlook. ``From wherever
the stock bottoms out, it will do better than 95 percent of the
stocks on Nasdaq over the next two to three years,'' he said. ``But
that bottom could be at $80, $70, $60 or $50. Any one of those
numbers makes sense depending what price-earnings multiple you are
willing to put on the stock.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
