</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BIZGLANCE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSINESS AT A GLANCE 
</HEADLINE>
  (bl) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   STOCKS ARE DRAGGED DOWN BY HIGH-TECHNOLOGY SHARES
</P>
<P>
   Stock prices Wednesday fell sharply, pulled down by software and
computer companies, which fell in the wake of weaker-than-expected
sales from Dell Computer and Hewlett-Packard.
</P>
<P>
   The biggest declines of the session were recorded by stocks in
the Nasdaq composite index, which fell 64.96 points, or 2.8
percent, to 2,248.91. The Dow Jones industrial average fell 101.56
points, or 1.1 percent, to 9,195.47, and the Standard &AMP; Poor's
500-stock index fell 17.84 points, or 1.4 percent, to 1,224.03.
</P>
<P>
   Argentina easily sold $1 billion in new 20-year bonds to eager
investors.
</P>
<P>
   LABOR BALANCE SHIFTING IN GERMANY
</P>
<P>
   Although labor leaders in Germany have accepted negligible wage
increases for workers over the last three years and made big
concessions on extra pay for overtime and on weekend work, the
balance of power may be shifting as the nation's biggest union
edges closer to an all-out strike against manufacturers.
</P>
<P>
   EXECUTIVE SHAKE-UP SEEN AT NEC
</P>
<P>
   NEC of Japan, one of the world's largest makers of computer
chips, may be poised for a further board room shake-up less than
four months after the company forced its prominent chairman out in
the wake of a military-procurement scandal.
</P>
<P>
   AMERICAN AIRLINES BILLS UNION
</P>
<P>
   American Airlines presented its bill for damages to a U.S.
District Court judge in Dallas, contending that its revenues fell
$58.7 million short of projections while the airline's pilots
continued their sickout in defiance of the judge's order. The
pilots' union, which has already put $10 million on deposit with
the court, questioned the accounting and asked for three months to
analyze it. The judge gave the union until April 12.
</P>
<P>
   CONSTRUCTION OF NEW HOMES RISES
</P>
<P>
   New-home construction starts rose in January at the fastest pace
in 12 years, bolstered by strong gains in the South and West, and
factory production increased for the fourth month, federal reports
showed.
</P>
<P>
   COMEDY CENTRAL CHOOSES NEW CHIEF
</P>
<P>
   Ending a closely watched talent search, the Comedy Central cable
channel has decided to name Larry Divney, an advertising executive
at the channel, as president and chief executive, people close to
the company said.
</P>
<P>
   ABC will move more than 200 of its employees, including most of
its top management, from New York to Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   ODD ALLIANCE AT MICROSOFT TRIAL
</P>
<P>
   A senior executive of Microsoft, Brad Chase, reported in federal
court that America Online had, at least for now, renewed its
contract to equip its users with Microsoft's browser _ even though
it is buying Netscape Communications, Microsoft's main competitor
in the browser field. Chase added that he thought that America
Online had chosen to stick with Microsoft for the time being in
part because the company wanted to influence the outcome of the
antitrust case.
</P>
<P>
   A Microsoft executive denied that the company had both
threatened its main rival in the Internet software business and
made it an illegal offer to divide the market.
</P>
<P>
   BP AMOCO TO SPEED COST-CUTTING
</P>
<P>
   BP Amoco said that it would accelerate its cost-cutting plan and
dismiss more workers after a prolonged slump in oil prices led to a
37 percent drop in fourth-quarter profit.
</P>
<P>
   SOFTBANK REDUCES STAKE IN YAHOO
</P>
<P>
   Softbank, Japan's top software distributor and a shareholder in
Internet ventures, said it had reduced its stake in Yahoo to 28
percent from 30 percent to finance new investments.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
