<SLUG> BC-FBN-PATRIOTS-600&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDWARDS' INJURY KEEPS AFC EAST IN THE SPOTLIGHT
</HEADLINE>
   (rk) 
 By   GERALD ESKENAZI   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ It is the off-season for professional football, but
the AFC East, the division that sent four teams to the playoffs
last season, continues to make news.
</P>
<P>
   The latest development comes out of New England, where the
Patriots seem doomed to continue to feel the aftereffects of Bill
Parcells' defection to the Jets two years ago. But in this
instance, Parcells did not even do anything.
</P>
<P>
   But he did a year ago, when Parcells lured away Curtis Martin,
the Patriots' outstanding running back, with a big free-agent
offer. The Patriots responded by drafting Robert Edwards as their
No. 1 pick in the 1998 draft, hoping the rookie out of Georgia
could replace Martin.
</P>
<P>
   And to a considerable extent, he did, gaining 1,115 yards on 291
carries and scoring nine touchdowns. But now he is lost for 1999,
and perhaps for good because of a freakish knee injury incurred
during a rookie flag-football game on the beach at Waikiki during
Pro Bowl week.
</P>
<P>
   After four hours of surgery on Tuesday, when surgeons discovered
he had injuries to all four ligaments in his left knee as well as
nerve damage, the Patriots' orthopedist, Bertram Zarins, said he
was ``pessimistic'' that Edwards would play again.
</P>
<P>
   Edwards' lawyer and agent, Allan J. Wade, did not quite agree
with that assessment, saying Wednesday that after speaking with
Zarins he had the impression that the serious nerve damage in the
lower leg _ which now prevents feeling _ can heal over time.
</P>
<P>
   ``The nerve was not severed,'' Wade said, ``and that's a good
sign.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, the Patriots will have to do without Edwards. And right
now, their No. 2 runner is Sedric Shaw, who carried all of 48 times
last season.
</P>
<P>
   An official with knowledge of the league's workings suggested
that the Patriots may demand an extra draft choice from the NFL to
compensate for losing Edwards. The beach game was sponsored by the
league's properties division.
</P>
<P>
   Whether the Patriots get that extra pick or not, the Patriots,
who were eliminated in the first round of the playoffs, will
obviously have to go shopping for another running back. And
interestingly, they happen to have an extra first-round pick in
this year's draft, the last draft choice remaining from the
compensation package the Jets had to give the Patriots when
Parcells switched sides.
</P>
<P>
   So New England will have its own first-round pick (No. 20) as
well as the Jets' No. 28. With those picks they will not get anyone
like running back Ricky Williams, the Heisman Trophy winner from
Texas. But they could get lucky and find someone as good as
Edwards.
</P>
<P>
   The contractual ramifications of Edwards' injury remain unclear.
Commissioner Paul Tagliabue on Wednesday ordered the league to
begin a review of the complicated affair, including a look at the
event that caused the injury.
</P>
<P>
   Players in the actual Pro Bowl game are protected in case of
injury; they receive the next season's salary if they cannot play
as a result of being hurt in the game. But the flag-football game
for rookies, Wade said, ``is a hybrid.''
</P>
<P>
   Wade contended that the Patriots are responsible for paying
Edwards because he was fulfilling the terms of his contract by
``promoting football.''
</P>
<P>
   Edwards originally signed a five-year, $5.75 million contract
with the Patriots that included a $2 million bonus. He received $1
million of that bonus up front and will receive the other half
regardless of whether he plays again, said Robert Kraft, the
Patriots' owner.
</P>
<P>
   But it is not clear whether the Patriots would be willing to pay
anything beyond that to Edwards, whose contract, like almost all
other players, is not guaranteed.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Wade said that contrary to published reports, he was not aware
of any private insurance policy that Edwards has that would pay his
salary while he was out with the injury.
</P>
<P>
   In any event, the injury to Edwards is one more unusual
development in a division that last season saw Vinny Testaverde and
Doug Flutie surprisingly emerge as top quarterbacks with the Jets
and the Buffalo Bills, and saw Miami's Jimmy Johnson add to all the
intense feelings within the division by stomping on a Flutie Flakes
cereal box after the Dolphins just held off the Bills in a
first-round playoff game.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson and Flutie will go at it twice next season. And so will
Parcells and the Patriots, who will not have Edwards in the
backfield.  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
