<SLUG> BC-OFFICE-REVIEW-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JUDGE'S LIVE-ACTION `OFFICE SPACE' LOOKS A BIT VACANT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
OUR RATING: 2 STARS 
 
 
By GLENN WHIPP  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Cross the sardonic workplace of ``Dilbert'' with
the good-ol'-boy sensibility of ``King of the Hill,'' and you've
got ``Office Space,'' animator Mike Judge's debut as a live-action
feature writer and director. It sounds promising enough, but
unfortunately this sporadically funny film has about as much plot
as a three-panel ``Dilbert'' cartoon strip and runs long even at
its scant 89 minutes. It does contain a ``cornhole'' reference
though, which should at least satisfy Judge's ``Beavis and
Butt-head'' fans.
</P>
<P>
   ``Office Space'' begins promisingly enough with several inspired
sketches that wickedly spoof cubicle culture. We follow Peter
Gibbons (Ron Livingston) slowly inching along the freeway, not even
able to keep pace with an old man using a walker. Nothing improves
once he arrives. His smarmy boss (a pitch-perfect creature from
hell as played by Gary Cole) is obsessed with memos and meetings
but not with inspiring the troops. And Peter needs inspiration in
the worst way.
</P>
<P>
   Recoiling from his grim, gray workplace, Peter visits a
hypnotherapist who induces a state of blissed-out nirvana and then
keels over before he can snap Peter out of it.
</P>
<P>
   So while co-workers Michael Bolton (David Herman, playing a
character who is not the singer, but Judge gets plenty of mileage
out of the name) and Samir (Ajay Naidu) obsess at their computer
workstations, Peter sleeps late, arrives for work when he feels
like it and ends up getting promoted for his defiance by a couple
of know-nothing consultants. (``He's got `upper management' written
all over him,'' one of them notes.)
</P>
<P>
   Judge, known best for creating ``Beavis and Butt-head,'' has a
sharp eye for the minor annoyances of the everyday work world. But
he doesn't really have enough material for a movie here. At the
halfway point, ``Office Space'' turns into a clunky caper movie and
wobbles to a predictable finale involving a disgruntled office
worker (Stephen Root) that you can see coming from the moment the
character is introduced.
</P>
<P>
   Livingston is likable enough as Peter, but it's the supporting
actors _ Cole and Root _ who register most strongly. Diedrich Bader
also has some funny moments as Peter's redneck neighbor, the kind
of guy who, when asked what he would do with $1 million, answers:
``Two chicks at the same time.''
</P>
<P>
   Speaking of chicks, Jennifer Aniston shows up in a few scenes as
a waitress working at a TGI Friday-style restaurant (she's required
to wear at least 15 pieces of ``flair,'' which includes mostly
oversize buttons). It's a thinly drawn role, good mostly for its
visual gags. As such, it's indicative of ``Office Space'' as a
whole _ lots of flair, little substance.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
