</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KURD-EUROPE-ART-1STLD-WRITETHRU-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
3 KILLED IN BERLIN WHEN ISRAELIS FIRE ON KURDS STORMING THEIR
CONSULATE 
</HEADLINE>
 
(Subs 1st graf to insert that capture was on Monday. Subs 8th graf
to insert a first sentence giving an overview of the protests and
embassy takeovers. Inserts a new 9th graf with quotation from the
Turkish prime minister about outside help in the capture. Subs 10th
graf to remove the slang about high fives. Subs 21st graf to make
first sentence read more gracefully.) (See also KURD-TURKEY, KURD-U.S.) 
(ART ADV: Graphic map is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(fe) 
 By ROGER COHEN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BERLIN _ Israeli guards opened fire on Wednesday on dozens of
Kurds trying to occupy the Israeli Consulate here, killing three
people and wounding 16 in the worst violence since Europewide
protests erupted over the capture of a rebel Kurdish leader on
Monday.
</P>
<P>
   The police said the shooting began after about 55 Kurds tried to
enter the consulate in a tranquil Berlin suburb. The Kurds
apparently chose their target in response to rumors that the
Israeli secret service, Mossad, had played a role in Turkey's
capture of Abdullah Ocalan, the leader of the Kurdish Workers
Party.
</P>
<P>
   The Israeli prime minister, Benjamin Netanyahu, said in Tel Aviv
on Wednesday that the guards had fired in self-defense after Kurds
brandishing hammers and clubs entered the Berlin consulate. He
denied any Israeli role in Ocalan's capture.
</P>
<P>
   ``We did not cooperate with any element in Ocalan's capture,''
Netanyahu said. ``We have to make this clear and emphasize this
because this is the reality and this is the truth.'' Israel, which
has a security cooperation agreement with Turkey, was the object of
``false accusations,'' he added.
</P>
<P>
   An hour after the shootings, blood from the wounded lay
spattered on freshly fallen snow in a wide area around the Israeli
consulate. Police officers had encircled two groups of shivering
Kurds, numbering about 30 in all, and refused to let reporters
speak to them on the grounds that they were ``under arrest.'' The
entire area was cordoned off, and helicopters circled over the
four-story consulate building near the Grunewald, a forest in the
western part of Berlin.
</P>
<P>
   The consul, Miriam Shomrat, was not in the building, but another
Israeli woman was briefly held by the Kurds.
</P>
<P>
   Ocalan, whose followers have waged a long separatist war in
southeastern Turkey in which more than 30,000 people have died, was
seized in Nairobi, Kenya, on Monday in circumstances that remain
murky. Turkish security agents then flew him to Turkey where he
faces a possible death sentence on charges including treason and
murder.
</P>
<P>
   On the second day of protests, embassies and consulates in
London, Zurich and Bern remained occupied by Kurds, and new
demonstrations sprang up in places that included a U.N. office in
Geneva and offices in Canada and Australia. Protests initially
focused on Kenyan and Greek missions in Europe because Ocalan was
arrested after leaving the Greek embassy in Nairobi, which
apparently led many to believe he had been betrayed by the Greeks.
</P>
<P>
   Prime Minister Bulent Ecevit of Turkey did not dispel or confirm
any rumors. ``In the interest of not disturbing those parties who
took part in this operation,'' he told one interviewer, ``I will
use a local expression and say, `Let us eat the grape and not ask
where it came from.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Turkish television showed film on Wednesday of Ocalan being led
onto a small plane, handcuffed and blindfolded. After being
handcuffed to a seat, his blindfold was removed, revealing his
sweat-drenched face. Later an unsteady and apparently drowsy Ocalan
was shown being led to a bed as commandos jubilantly congratulated
each other.
</P>
<P>
   The swift violence of the Israeli response stood in sharp
contrast to the restraint of other embassies. ``Our people have
standing orders to prevent, with force if necessary, including by
opening fire, any attempt to take hostages and to defend
themselves,'' Netanyahu said.
</P>
<P>
   Avigdor Kahlani, the Israeli minister of public security, said
there were three Israeli guards at the consulate and accused German
authorities of exposing them through incompetence.
</P>
<P>
   ``Those who were supposed to do the work from Germany didn't do
their job,'' he said. ``The guards fired first in the air and then
fired to hit in order to save themselves and defend the
consulate.''
</P>
<P>
   A German police spokesman, Norbert Gunckel, said there were two
German police officers outside the consulate at the time the
protest began. He did not explain why protection was so light or
comment on the response of the two officers. ``There was a clash,
and several shots were fired,'' Gunckel said, but he declined to
elaborate.
</P>
<P>
   All Israeli embassies in Europe were ordered closed for the day,
and the United States urged Americans abroad to be cautious.
</P>
<P>
   Witnesses said the Kurdish protesters had no guns. Lukas
Billinski, who was walking his dog in the area, said he heard nine
shots inside the consulate building, followed by five more a little
later.
</P>
<P>
   There is intense debate in Germany over the large number of
foreigners here, and the violence on Thursday seemed certain to
feed a growing uneasiness. Gerhard Schroeder, the chancellor, said
after the shooting that Kurds who did not respect the law would be
deported.
</P>
<P>
   ``If those living here do not respect the law, they will have to
leave the country,'' Schroeder, a Social Democrat, said in a
statement reminiscent of the position of the Christian Democratic
government he replaced three months ago.
</P>
<P>
   Several German cities _ including Bonn, Leipzig, Stuttgart,
Frankfurt and Cologne _ were hit by Kurdish protests on Tuesday.
These incidents abated on Wednesday, but about 15 Kurds broke into
the offices of the Social Democratic Party in Hamburg, taking a
staff member hostage. A mosque and a Turkish restaurant in Hamburg
were also attacked.
</P>
<P>
   ``No constitutional state can just wait and watch a civil war
being implanted into its midst by a foreign minority,'' declared an
editorial in the conservative newspaper Die Welt. ``This experience
comes in time to give us a lesson in the political naivete of an
undifferentiated citizenship law.''
</P>
<P>
   About 500,000 Kurds and more than 2 million Turks live in
Germany, by far the largest such populations in Europe. Schroeder
has proposed new legislation that would make it easier for them and
other foreigners to become German citizens.
</P>
<P>
   Elsewhere in Europe, most of the protests against more than 20
Greek and Kenyan missions ended. But in London, Kurds inside the
Greek embassy said they were on hunger strike and would set
themselves on fire if the police stormed the building.
</P>
<P>
   In Switzerland, about 60 protesters continued to hold a
policeman at the Greek Consulate in Zurich, and the Greek Embassy
in Bern remained occupied by Kurds. In Sydney and Melbourne,
Australia, demonstrators and police officers clashed and 65 Kurds
were arrested.
</P>
<P>
   About 20 Kurds today forced their way into the Geneva
headquarters of the United Nations High Commissioner for Refugees
and left about three hours later after a spokesman for the agency
read a statement saying that the United Nations should send a
mission to examine the plight of the Kurds.
</P>
<P>
   In Ottawa about 200 Kurdish protesters rushed a police barricade
in front of the Turkish Embassy, hurling rocks, snowballs, ice and
homemade gasoline bombs and burning Greek and United States flags.
The police retaliated with pepper spray.
</P>
<P>
   There are more than 20 million Kurds worldwide, and many of
those living in Turkey and neighboring countries have suffered
persecution.
</P>
<P>
   Ocalan has used violent guerrilla methods over the last 14 years
to pursue a goal of Kurdish self-rule and civil rights in Turkey.
He has been met with a violent Turkish response, including
documented torture of Kurdish guerrilla suspects and secret trials
by state security courts.
</P>
<P>
   Bulent Ecevit, the Turkish prime minister, said on Wednesday
that Ocalan, who was being held in a prison on Imraili island in
the Sea of Marmara, would be given a fair trial.
</P>
<P>
   But human rights groups, including Amnesty International,
expressed concerns over Ocalan's fate, and Ocalan's lawyers were
not allowed to enter Turkey on Wednesday after traveling from the
Netherlands.
</P>
<P>
   Since Ocalan was first arrested in Italy last year, European
governments have been at a loss as to what to do, torn between
their rejection of the Kurdish movement's methods and their
abhorrence of the Turkish government's frequent flouting of human
rights in fighting the Kurds.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   The result has been confusion and buck passing. ``The reality is
that the Kurds are a nation, the Kurdish Workers Party is a party,
and the European Union is neither one nor the other,'' wrote Boris
Bianchieri, a former Italian diplomat, in the Turin daily La
Stampa. ``Maybe the Kurdish problem is insoluble. But Europe has
neither the courage to face up to it nor to deny its existence.''
</P>
<P>
   Kurds are not recognized as a minority in Turkey, a status that
would give them the right to teach in their own language. Turkish
sensitivity to the issue is extreme. One factor in the discussion
of possible independence for the ethnic Albanians of Kosovo has
been the fear of opening a Pandora's box in which Kurdish demands
for a state would figure prominently, American officials said.
</P>
<P>
   In the last few months, the United States had expressed quiet
support for Ocalan's arrest and his handover to Turkey, a pivotal
NATO ally and an important base for American air patrols over Iraq.
</P>
<P>
   The Turkish daily Yeni Yuzyil said on Thursday that Washington
had helped the Turkish government seize Ocalan in return for its
rejection of Iraqi demands to end American use of Turkish bases for
air missions over Iraq. But the Clinton administration has denied
any direct involvement in his arrest in Kenya.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
