<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-17 22:05 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9465 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBA-YANKS-STRAWBERRY-     02-17 1078
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-YANKS-STRAWBERRY-625&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STRAWBERY SAYS HE'S LUCKY, NOT CURED 
</HEADLINE>
   (See BBA-YANKS) 
 (lh) 
 By JACK CURRY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   TAMPA, Fla. _ The early, balmy days of spring training are
supposed to be about hopes and dreams, especially for a team that
won 125 games and a World Series championship last year. The
same-look Yankees have obvious reasons to believe they can win the
Series once again. More than any team, New York's prospects are
more realistic than they are hopeful.
</P>
<P>
   But Darryl Strawberry descended upon this relaxed atmosphere
Wednesday and stoically reminded everyone that not even baseball
can hide the gloomy aspects of life. Strawberry was here six days
earlier than he had to be to meet with doctors and schedule his
weekly chemotherapy sessions while he is trying to resume his
baseball career. He is still fighting colon cancer.
</P>
<P>
   So as a robust Strawberry stood inside the clubhouse at the
minor-league complex, with minor-leaguers peeking at this real,
live Yankee, he initially spoke hopefully and then spoke honestly
about an uncertain future. Strawberry has been around cancer
patients for four months, and he has seen what the disease does. He
called himself lucky, but not cured.
</P>
<P>
   For 15 minutes that seemed like 15 hours, Strawberry spoke about
how cancer can demoralize people and make them feel lifeless. He
talked about winning the open left-field job with the Yankees, but
he also turned somber while discussing the possibility that he
could someday die from cancer. It was not the sort of emotional
outpouring normally associated with this serene baseball setting.
</P>
<P>
   ``No matter what is said and no matter what the percentages are,
I look it as a day-to-day thing that I'm surviving,'' Strawberry
said. ``As a survivor, so far to this point, I can carry the
message to others who are suffering from the disease and give them
hope. You can't give up. Giving up is the easy way out. I've seen
many patients who suffered with what I've suffered with and have no
hope. If I walked around with no hope, it wouldn't encourage
anybody.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet, minutes later, Strawberry veered from encouraging to
eye-opening. While finishing a rambling answer about what doctors
have said about his progress, Strawberry speculated about what
might happen if the cancer went into remission and returned.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the cancer came back, I'd be able to handle it much better
than I probably ever would because I've been through it before,''
Strawberry said. ``It won't be a surprise. It will be like, `Well,
if it's terminal and I'm going to die from it, I'm going to fight
it until the end.' That's the only way I'm going to look at it.''
</P>
<P>
   Strawberry, whose weight is up to 222 from a low of 185 and who
flashed biceps that looked like bowling pins, said doctors told him
he has made great strides and should be optimistic.
</P>
<P>
   Strawberry, who is expected to continue treatments until the end
of April, did not discuss the fact that the cancer had spread to 1
of 36 lymph nodes removed from his abdomen during surgery last Oct.
3.
</P>
<P>
   Cancer experts not associated with Strawberry's case said the
finding reduced the prospects of a five-year cure from the roughly
90 percent that could have been anticipated if the cancer had not
spread. These experts said the odds of long-term survival seemed to
be in Strawberry's favor, but they gave disparate figures, ranging
from 35 percent to 75 percent, for the prospect of the 36-year-old
being cured in five years. The figures were based on studies of
patients with colon cancer.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some of us make it, some don't,'' Strawberry said. ``But the
majority of us don't make it. That's why it's so important that we
find a cure, because if we don't, more people are going to die than
survive.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   With a condition that will cause him to have two types of
chemotherapy pumped intravenously into him for 45 minutes every
Friday for the next 10 weeks, can Strawberry play baseball?
Strawberry said he has had no side effects from chemotherapy. With
Chad Curtis, Ricky Ledee and Shane Spencer pushing for time in left
field, can Strawberry, even if he is healthy, make the opening day
roster?
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm saying yes,'' said Joe Torre, who also called Strawberry
the biggest question mark on the team. ``He's very enthusiastic
about it. He feels good.''
</P>
<P>
   Ever an optimist, Strawberry said: ``I don't have any concerns
about my health and ability to play. It might be a concern to
others. I don't think any of them can judge me until they see me
perform and see where I'm at mentally.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, even as Strawberry spoke about mental toughness on the
eve of what would be his 16th season in a turbulent career, he
stressed that conquering cancer is tougher than conquering
substance abuse, which he has done.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been through a lot, but I've never felt so bad as when I
was cut open right down the middle of my gut,'' Strawberry said.
``Having to have surgery where they go in, you have a tumor pulled
out of you and they just have to move everything inside of you.
It's a week and a half before things start to work inside you.
That's bad.''
</P>
<P>
   Whenever Strawberry discussed his cancer, baseball seemed like a
far-away notion. Still, Strawberry was feisty enough to declare
that he does not care if the Yankees bring in 10 left fielders to
compete against him and, although his preference is to remain with
them, he considers the spring a showcase if New York no longer
wants him.
</P>
<P>
   ``After what I've been through, I can't do nothing but have
fun,'' Strawberry said. ``I was in the hospital in New York. I
could barely walk. I couldn't eat. I went home and started chemo
and had another surgery in January. So this is gravy, just being
able to play baseball.''
</P>
<P>
   Between visiting with some of his teammates, setting his
chemotherapy schedule and insisting that he will be able to play in
two months, Strawberry, a born-again Christian, mostly talked like
a man who expects to defeat cancer. But he also talked like a man
who realizes the serious battle is not over.
</P>
<P>
   ``One day, we're all going to die,'' Strawberry said. ``We just
don't know what it's going to be from. I hate to say this, but
cancer is not a way for anybody to die. But it is a common thing
that people die from every day. Just hope you don't have to suffer
long if you're going to die from it because it's deadly.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
