<SLUG> BC-OBIT-KESSEN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WILLIAM KESSEN, 74, A PROFESSOR   AND EXPERT ON CHILD PSYCHOLOGY 
 (DW)
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Conn., Mo., Mass., Md., Fla.)  By ERICA GOODE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Dr. William Kessen, a developmental psychologist whose research,
theoretical contributions and teaching at Yale University helped
shape the thinking of a generation of child psychologists, died on
Saturday at a hospital in New Haven. He was 74 and lived in
Branford, Conn.
</P>
<P>
   The cause was a stroke, his family said.
</P>
<P>
   In the 1960s and '70s, Kessen conducted classic studies on
visual perception, activity level and other aspects of the first
years of life, and made fundamental contributions to the
understanding of how infants perceive and make sense of the world.
Later in his career he did research in many other areas of child
development, including problem solving, and studied the later
19th-century emergence of professional psychology.
</P>
<P>
   He was also influential as a theorist. In ``The Language of
Psychology'' (John Wiley &AMP; Sons, 1959), a book he edited with the
psychologist Dr. George Mandler, Kessen addressed fundamental
problems in psychology that are still central 40 years later, his
colleagues said.
</P>
<P>
   He wrote or edited several other books on child psychology and
at his death was completing ``The Baby Book: 75 Years of Infant
Care.''
</P>
<P>
   William Kessen was born in Key West, Fla.; received his
bachelor's degree from the University of Florida in 1948, his
master's from Brown University in 1950 and his doctorate from Yale
in 1952. In the same year, he began a postdoctoral fellowship at
the Child Study Center at Yale.
</P>
<P>
   From 1977 to 1980, Kessen was chairman of the psychology
department at Yale, and was named as the Eugene Higgins Professor
of Psychology in 1976. He was also a professor of pediatrics,
retiring in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   In the early 1970s, Kessen led one of the first American
delegations to China after the United States re-established
diplomatic relations with Beijing.
</P>
<P>
   He was a fellow of the American Association for the Advancement
of Science and a trustee of Barnard College and was to receive the
Distinguished Contributions to Education in Child Development Award
from the Society for Research and Child Development in April.
</P>
<P>
   Many leading developmental psychologists are former students of
Kessen. ``The question you ask about someone like him is, `Were
your students so inspired that they went on and became eminent
themselves?''' said Dr. Jerome Kagan, a professor of psychology at
Harvard University who attended graduate school with Kessen. ``Bill
had a high batting average.''
</P>
<P>
   He is survived by his wife, Marion Lord Kessen; three daughters,
Judith Crawford of Millersville, Md., Deborah Trofatter of
Branford, and Anne Lowell of St. Louis; three sons, Peter C., of
Branford, and Andrew L. and John M., both of Boston, and six
grandchildren.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
