<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-17 22:12 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9477 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NJ-POLITICS-570&AMP;ADD-N     02-17 0732
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NJ-POLITICS-570&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NO SHORTAGE OF POTENTIAL SUCCESSORS
</HEADLINE>
  (See also NJ-LAUTENBERG-RETIRE, EDIT-SENATE-LAUTENBERG) 
 (nk) 
 By   JENNIFER PRESTON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   TRENTON, N.J. _ The decision by Sen. Frank Lautenberg to retire
next year gives New Jersey's younger elected officials an
opportunity to move in from the sidelines and some of the state's
veterans a chance for a new political life.
</P>
<P>
   With Lautenberg's unexpected announcement Wednesday, politicians
from former Gov. Jim Florio to Gov. Christie Whitman to Susan Bass
Levin, mayor of Cherry Hill, said that they were considering making
a bid. And as the day progressed, the list grew, swelling to at
least eight Democrats and seven Republicans by early evening.
</P>
<P>
   ``This creates a whole new political dynamic,'' said Thomas P.
Giblin, chairman of New Jersey's Democratic State Committee. ``On
our side, there are a lot of names out there. There is no shortage
of candidates.''
</P>
<P>
   For the Democrats, analysts say that Rep. Bob Menendez, a
four-term congressman, is a party favorite and has built a
considerable war chest in the last two years, raising $1.5 million
in anticipation of Lautenberg's retirement. But Menendez, in the
interest of party unity, pulled back last fall when Lautenberg
announced that he planned to run for a fourth term.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have said all along that I would support the senator if he
ran, and that I would consider running if he did not,'' Menendez
said. ``I will probably make a decision about running by early next
week.''
</P>
<P>
   On the Republican side, Whitman, who is limited to two terms as
governor, said Wednesday that she was ``seriously considering all
of my options.'' When asked in the past, Whitman always quickly
pointed out that she was happy in her role as governor, and that
she did not have a campaign apparatus or fund-raising operation in
place.
</P>
<P>
   But Wednesday, when pressed by reporters as she attended the
opening of a new train station in Hamilton Township, her words
seemed to be more carefully chosen, as if she was more open to the
prospect of a Senate campaign. Her aides said privately that she
was giving it some serious thought.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is going to be a personal determination and what I think
will be best for the state,'' said Whitman, who made a strong
challenge to former Sen. Bill Bradley in 1990. ``I have always been
interested. I ran back in 1990.''
</P>
<P>
   If Whitman runs, Lautenberg's announcement could alter the
playing field not only for next year's Senate race but also for the
gubernatorial contest in 2001. That is because the Senate
president, Donald T. DiFrancesco, a Republican who is planning to
run for governor in 2001, will step into Whitman's job to finish
her term if she wins the Senate seat.
</P>
<P>
   Chuck Haytaian, chairman of New Jersey's Republican State
Committee, said that if Whitman decided to pursue a Senate
campaign, other Republican contenders would likely step aside.
Among those Republicans who expressed interest Wednesday were state
Sen. William L. Gormley; Essex County Executive James Treffinger;
Reps. Marge S. Roukema and Frank LoBiondo; former Rep. Richard A.
Zimmer, who ran unsuccessfully for the Senate in 1996; and Murray
Sabrin, a college professor who ran for governor as a member of the
Libertarian Party in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to Florio, Menendez and Ms. Levin, the list of
Democrats who said Wednesday that they were considering a bid
included Reps. Frank Pallone Jr. and Steven R. Rothman; B. Thomas
Byrne Jr., a former state party chairman; and Assemblymen Robert G.
Smith and Neil M. Cohen.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Florio, a former congressman who served one term as governor
before being ousted by Whitman in 1993, said he was giving a run
serious thought in part because he worked on many of the same
transportation and environmental issues as Lautenberg when he was
in Congress, and would like to continue that work.
</P>
<P>
   But party leaders said privately that the prospect of a rematch
between Whitman and Florio was unlikely because they would like to
use this open seat to promote new faces.
</P>
<P>
   Lautenberg declined to say whom he preferred to succeed him, but
said: ``I would like to see someone who is going to carry on the
agenda that we, the Democrats, are presently working with. Anyone
who will take that agenda and work hard.''
</P>
</TEXT>
