<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JASPER-TRIAL-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EX-GIRLFRIEND PLACES SUSPECT IN PICKUP USED IN JASPER DRAGGING
DEATH 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  (Eds.: See JASPER-TATTOOS) 
(Eds.: Optional ending included) 
 
By PATTY REINERT 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   JASPER, Texas _ The ex-girlfriend of white supremacist and
capital murder defendant John W. ``Bill'' King testified Wednesday
that she saw King get into a pickup with two friends and drive
toward Martin Luther King Boulevard the night a black man was
picked up there and later dragged to his death.
</P>
<P>
   King, 24, and those two friends _ Shawn Allen Berry, 24, and
Lawrence Russell Brewer Jr., 31 _ are now accused of kidnapping
James Byrd Jr., chaining him to the pickup, dragging him three
miles and depositing his dismembered corpse outside a rural black
cemetery. If convicted in the June 7, 1998, killing, all three
white men could face the death penalty.
</P>
<P>
   Keisha Adkins, 21, also told jurors that while visiting her
ex-con ex-boyfriend at his apartment, she saw a Zippo cigarette
lighter engraved with King's prison nickname, ``Possum,'' on a
counter. Prosecutors believe it was the same lighter found at the
crime scene. King claimed he had lost the lighter the week before
the killing.
</P>
<P>
   But while some of her testimony appeared to link King to the
crime, Adkins waffled on her previous statement to investigators
that she also had seen King wearing a pair of sandals when he said
good-bye to her that night.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was wearing them earlier that night,'' she said, visibly
nervous on the witness stand. ``But I just don't know if I saw him
wearing them when he got into the pickup.''
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutors believe the sandals are stained with Byrd's blood,
and say they will present DNA evidence to prove it Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Adkins was among five witnesses who took the stand Wednesday,
the second day of testimony in King's trial. Much of the day was
devoted to investigators testifying as to how they collected the
physical evidence, both at the crime scene and at King's apartment.
</P>
<P>
   Late in the day, Jasper police Detective Rich Ford explained the
meaning of King's numerous tattoos, as well as the tattoos of his
co-defendants, as prosecutors flashed slides of the skin art on a
screen above the jury box.
</P>
<P>
   The tattoos, which the jury of 11 whites and one black saw for
the first time Wednesday, include a Satanic image of the Virgin
Mary holding a horned baby Jesus, Nazi and racist prison gang
insignia, Ku Klux Klan symbols and the figure of a lynched black
man.
</P>
<P>
   Defense attorneys C. Haden ``Sonny'' Cribbs Jr. and Brack Jones
Jr., methodically objected as evidence was presented, and on
cross-examination attempted to challenge the investigators'
evidence-gathering techniques, suggesting the evidence could easily
have been contaminated.
</P>
<P>
   They challenged the tattoos on constitutional grounds, saying
their client's beliefs are protected under the First Amendment's
guarantee of free speech and free association.
</P>
<P>
   Asked later about the cigarette lighter Adkins saw at King's
apartment, Jones said, ``She said she saw A cigarette lighter with
the word Possum on it,'' indicating there could have been more than
one lighter.
</P>
<P>
   King himself discussed the lighter in a statement to the media
last November.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's verifiable that the lighter found with ``Possum''
inscribed on it, is indeed my property,'' he wrote in a statement
his father released to The Dallas Morning News. ``The
aforementioned cigarette lighter had been misplaced a week or so
prior to these fraudulent charges that have been brought against
Russell Brewer and me.''
</P>
<P>
   The Byrd family, who filled the first two rows of the courtroom,
said the testimony was a little easier to take Wednesday. The day
before, several members were overcome with emotion and left the
courtroom in tears as investigators described the horrific
condition of Byrd's corpse and showed the jury his underwear and
other clothing.
</P>
<P>
   King's father, Ronald, who had cried and moaned quietly through
much of Tuesday's testimony, did not return to the courtroom
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Houston black activist Quanell X and one of his followers
observed the trial for a little over an hour Wednesday afternoon,
complying with state District Judge Joe Bob Golden's request that
they refrain from wearing the group's military-style uniform of
black fatigues and that they not disrupt the proceedings. An FBI
agent sat next to them in the courtroom.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the judge's court order barring demonstrations on the
courthouse square, Golden relented and allowed a few uniformed
members of the group to stand on the lawn briefly so they could be
seen by the media.
</P>
<P>
   On the day of Byrd's funeral, militant black and white groups,
some of them armed, marched through the streets of the East Texas
city of 7,600 residents.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are not here to send a message of hate to anyone,'' Quanell
X, head of the National Black Muslims in Houston, said as he
entered the courthouse. ``But we are here to let our brothers and
sisters know that we care. We support them, we love them, and if
they need us, we'll be here again.''
</P>
<P>
   As he left the courthouse he said the death was not a murder,
but more precisely, a lynching.
</P>
<P>
   The activist also urged the death penalty for King, as did
several local African-Americans who arrived outside the courthouse
just in time to see officers escort King from the building into a
waiting car. Several complained that King was allowed to wear
street clothes to the trial and was transported between the
courthouse and jail in a private car.
</P>
<P>
   ``It makes me mad as hell,'' said Ethel Parks of Jasper. ``When
they arrest us for shoplifting, they handcuff us and put us in the
back of a patrol car and dress us in orange pants. Then they bring
this dog up here in a luxury car? After what he did?''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Karolyn Lewis, who lives near Huff Creek Road, where Byrd was
dragged, showed up at the courthouse with her five children, saying
she wanted to ``show them that life is not always fair.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to show them what justice is supposed to be about in
Jasper, Texas,'' she said. ``I hope and I pray that he gets the
death penalty.''
</P>
<P>
   But she added that she has little faith in the nearly all-white
jury. ``I think they put all the whites on there so they can award
him life in prison,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
