<HEADLINE>
JUDGE GIVES HOPE TO MAN HELD FOR DEPORTATION 
</HEADLINE>
  (lh) 
 By RONALD SMOTHERS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEWARK, N.J. _ An immigration court judge closed testimony
Wednesday in what he called the ``unusual and difficult''
deportation case of a Palestinian man who has been linked by secret
evidence to terrorist organizations and the World Trade Center
bombing, and said he would now consider a request that the man be
released on bail.
</P>
<P>
   The judge, Daniel Meisner, gave new hope to the man, Hany
Kiareldeen, 31, who has been detained for nearly a year. Meisner
had denied three earlier bail motions.
</P>
<P>
   An expert on terrorism challenged the secret evidence of the FBI
in testimony on Tuesday, saying the accusations contradicted the
federal government's own case against the bombers.
</P>
<P>
   Kiareldeen's lawyers, Houeida Saad and Regis Fernandez, said
Wednesday that Meisner's invitation to seek bail was an encouraging
sign that their evidence was beginning to undermine the Immigration
and Naturalization Service's case.
</P>
<P>
   The expert witness, Laurie Mylroie, is the co-author of the 1991
best seller ``Saddam Hussein and the Crisis in the Gulf'' and was
an analyst and consultant on the bombing case for ABC and Newsweek.
</P>
<P>
   In declassified summaries of still-secret evidence against
Kiareldeen, informers say he was a member of an unnamed terrorist
organization, Ms. Mylroie said. This contradicts the government's
theory in the World Trade Center case _ that the 1993 bombing was
the work of ``independent radical terrorists'' unconnected with
organized groups, she testified.
</P>
<P>
   The summaries, prepared for Kiareldeen's lawyers by the FBI,
also say he met with Nidal A. Ayyad, one of the convicted
co-conspirators in the bombing, a week before the bombing.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Mylroie said she had analyzed transcripts from the bombing
trials and examined the telephone logs of the co-conspirators, and
Kiareldeen's telephone number and name did not appear in any of
those logs.
</P>
<P>
   Throughout the hearings, Kiareldeen and his lawyers have
maintained that his former wife, Amal Mohamed, was the source of
the terrorism accusations.
</P>
<P>
   Efforts to get Ms. Mohamed on the stand to testify last fall
ended abruptly when she acknowledged talking to FBI agents but
refused to give details of those talks, saying she feared for her
life. Since then, the INS and the U.S. attorney for New Jersey have
blocked efforts to compel her testimony.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Mylroie said Kiareldeen did not fit the profile of the
near-ascetic terrorist obsessed with Mideastern politics. This
contention was echoed by friends of Kiareldeen's, who testified on
Tuesday that he was like many young American men.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was not political or religious, and he went to go-go bars
and liked to drink and dance,'' said Mansour Saqfelhait, one of the
friends.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-17-99 2216EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990217.0519 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-17 22:17 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9482 &Cx1f; taf-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NY-FASHION-ART-900(2T     02-17 0954
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-FASHION-ART-900(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VISIONS BRAZEN AND CONVENTIONAL 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photos are being sent to NYT photo clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036.) 
(lh) 
 By CONSTANCE C.R. WHITE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The startling ``jeans alibi'' scandal unfolding in
Italy and Helmut Lang's bold fall collection, were just the jolts
needed to remind one during show week that fashion will not allow
itself to be dismissed as merely two sleeves and a collar.
</P>
<P>
   First, the scandal. An Italian court in its wisdom has ruled
that a woman cannot be raped if she is wearing jeans, because they
cannot be removed without her help. (Obviously, these judges have
never slipped into a pair of ultra-baggy rapper or raver jeans.)
However ridiculous the ruling, it reminds one of fashion's
possibilities for broad political statement and cultural
significance _ as does Lang.
</P>
<P>
   There are three things one should know about Lang. He's
Austrian. He combs his long hair back like a European rock star.
And he possesses a dry wit. (His fashion show invitation suggested
black tie _ a bit of humor, it turned out, not a requirement for
attendance.)
</P>
<P>
   His clothes reflect all three influences. Imagine a spacecraft
returning to Earth, releasing a pod that delicately opens. Out
steps a traveler, moving in cadence to music from the ``Star Wars''
trilogy and ``Pomp and Circumstance'' March No. 2, dressed for a
new century of both innocence and urban aggression.
</P>
<P>
   For Lang, this is his millennial collection: flight suits in
gossamer white organza, stark evening gowns and black leather
motocross trousers with multiple zippers running vertically down
the leg _ like astronauts' or pilots' flight suits.
</P>
<P>
   Please, don't think John Glenn. Lang's clothes, notoriously
unforgiving, are for men who are young and slim, and for ``boys
with breasts,'' as Tom Wolfe calls fit, angular women in his latest
novel, ``A Man in Full.''
</P>
<P>
   Lang captured precisely the foreboding and wide-eyed optimism
that a culture feels greeting a new century. Insightfully, he drew
parallels between astronauts exploring new frontiers and graduating
students, palms sweaty but hearts racing to music that mixes
pageantry and nostalgia.
</P>
<P>
   What was brazen about Lang's vision is that these are designs he
has given us before, just further evolved. He was positing his past
work as modern enough for the future. No argument here; everything
he showed looked ready for 2000.
</P>
<P>
   Here were the jackets slung from the back with straps like a
knapsack. Here, too, were his cashmere sweaters slit at the elbow
but skinnier and more refined, and here were coats with inner
straps dangling, or inexplicably strapped to one leg.
</P>
<P>
   But we've never seen a neck pillow on a runway before as part of
an outfit. That's new.
</P>
<P>
   Ralph Lauren is another man who has seen the future. And it is
in double-faced wool. The very premise of his show, a millennial
collection in double-faced wool, unduly taxes the brain, so
conventional is this fabric.
</P>
<P>
   There are three things one should know about Ralph Lauren. He is
Ralph Lauren. He is Ralph Lauren. And he is Ralph Lauren _ a man
very serious about his image.
</P>
<P>
   It must be hard to focus on design at Polo Ralph Lauren right
now, what with the layoffs of 250 employees, store closings and the
T.H. problem. When asked last week about the bite that Tommy
Hilfiger has taken out of his business by appropriating his
country-club esthetic, Lauren appeared unfazed. But perhaps the
sign of Lauren's concern was on the runway Wednesday, where he
presented an about-face from last season's relaxed bravura.
</P>
<P>
   Felt, which Lauren called ``the essence of the collection'' in
his program notes, turned up in chilly ivory jackets and skirts,
and then in black jackets and circle skirts. It all looked stiff,
the models stalking along in a bloodless trance. Felt gives clothes
a precise, sculptured look, and the medium got the better of the
designer.
</P>
<P>
   Wonderful cashmere turtlenecks cropped just below the bosom were
drowned out by double-faced wool jackets in screaming yellow, or by
pants and coats in harsh red or deep coral, typical of the 1980s.
</P>
<P>
   These days, when Hillary Rodham Clinton's popularity is at an
all-time high as she stands by her man, the '80s are over, the
moment seems to demand clothes that are softer, prettier and more
introspective.
</P>
<P>
   The '80s, of course, were the age of irony, a mood recalled in
shows by Rebecca Danenberg and Maja. Ms. Danenberg's woman wore
sexy sweaters slit down the side, sweaters with curved hems and
long jackets over slim dresses. But she accessorized with belts
that resembled ammunition belts pulled tight around the waist, or
slung low on the hips. These are clothes for a woman who insists on
having her femininity tempered with a butch edge.
</P>
<P>
   The Maja line was the Danenberg collection's alter ego. It was a
romp among girlfriends in a tableau created by Ellen von Unwerth, a
photographer known for raw, sexual imagery. Don't ask Ms. von
Unwerth to decorate if your tastes do not run toward wall-to-wall
red, plastic foliage and leopard-print sofas. Dancing and
frolicking in staged debauchery, models wore little fox-trim
sweaters and tight shiny skirts, and shimmery bra tops and panties.
</P>
<P>
   Maja will no doubt find its way into the wardrobes of
Hollywood's young and restless, and numerous club kids. Bawdiness
can be fun. But so can propriety, and Michael Kors' winning
collection was the picture of it. The men's line, in its third
season, was little more than luxury Gap, but the women's was more
nuanced.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Inspired by horse country, they had an old-money hautiness to
them. The secret to Kors' success in evoking a style of living
irrelevant to most is that nothing is literal. What was called a
``barn jacket'' was not the commodious, rough-hewn garment one
expected, but a sleek, short leather piece with whipstitching.
Lean, sexy trousers in cashmere and wool coolly flared over
knife-sharp stilettos or pony-skin boots.
</P>
<P>
   Riding skirts in taffeta were unappealing and awkward. Taffeta
sometimes has a mind of its own. But a bone dress with a zip-front
and the shorter godet at the back suggesting a riding habit was an
arresting gown. Kors may or may not live the country manor life,
but he's surrounded by customers who do.
</P>
<P>
   Nicole Miller, on the other hand, created a line in her image _
a very good one _ as sexy, offhand and urban as she is. Almost a
decade ago, Donna Karan and Jean Paul Gaultier began using
neoprene. Now, Ms. Miller, with a more populist sensibility, has
interpreted it for a broad audience. Her black neoprene jackets
with Velcro closures are attractive and understandable to all.
Imbuing the old with the new, she also showed pale pink blouses
that closed with hook and eyes, and simple skirts made interesting
with fabrics like crinkled taffeta resembling crushed aluminum
foil.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Miller gave thought to how her designs may flatter a woman's
body and reflect her beauty. But neither idea seems to have crossed
Mark Eisen's mind. If Eisen continues to show painfully contorted
avant-garde clothes, as he did on Tuesday, he may not be on the
fashion world's list of must-see shows much longer.
</P>
<P>
   Neither clever nor accomplished, the collection consisted of
long, dense jackets in manly shapes, dresses with a sad flap of
fabric wilting down the front, and a gray felted dress with a big
belt. Eisen appeared to be unacquainted with Static Guard, or with
the fabrics or drapes that ensure a skirt falls gracefully. His
skirts in cashmere or taffeta bunched horribly around and between
models' legs.
</P>
<P>
   Richard Tyler's presentations have been in a lull, too, but for
different reasons, since Tyler most certainly knows his way around
a drape and a cut. This season, similar to last, he showed only 20
looks, and they were not jewels in a crown. There were nice, short
dresses including one for daytime _ a lush white wrap _ and another
one, party-girl cute with ruby-colored sequins and a veiled
midriff.
</P>
<P>
   Hugo Boss floundered, introducing its women's collection with
its men's wear for the first time. For women, there were
knee-length skirts with accordian-pleated borders at the hem, and
droopy tunics over similarly lackluster trousers. For men, a few
corduroy jackets and ombre jeans. No word on whether the jeans were
rape proof.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
