</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VENEZUELA-ECONOMY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VENEZUELAN LEADER SEEKS EMERGENCY CONTROL OVER ECONOMY 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By DIANA JEAN SCHEMO   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   RIO DE JANEIRO, Brazil _ Venezuela's new president said
Wednesday that he would seek special authority from Congress to
impose tax and spending changes by emergency decree.
</P>
<P>
   In a televised speech, President Hugo Chavez said the 15-page
package of ``enabling laws'' was necessary ``to take on and
overcome the extremely difficult situation that Venezuela is
confronting.'' His agenda calls for a reduction in government
spending, changes in the sales tax and a delay in some foreign debt
payments.
</P>
<P>
   Chavez took office two weeks ago, inheriting an economy in
shambles from President Rafael Caldera. The government's budget
deficit is equivalent to 9 percent of the entire economy, and more
than 30 percent of the national budget goes for foreign debt
payments this year. And with the price of oil, the country's
biggest export, at a 25-year low, Venezuela has little cause for
optimism.
</P>
<P>
   Chavez's announcement amounted to his first policy statement on
the economy, and it suggested that the new president would not
allow spending cuts to bog down in congressional wrangling.
</P>
<P>
   The announcement comes against the backdrop of a brewing clash,
pitting the president against Congress and the judiciary. Chavez,
who made an unsuccessful attempt to seize power in a coup d'etat in
1992, has placed a proposal to rewrite the constitution at the top
of his agenda. He has scheduled a referendum for May 2, proposing
that Venezuelans convene a constitutional assembly and grant him
broad powers to select its members.
</P>
<P>
   With the Supreme Court weighing the legality of the referendum,
the president appeared to make an attempt at intimidation, saying
he would call on Venezuelans to protest in the streets if the court
acted to block the referendum.
</P>
<P>
   Political and economic analysts in Venezuela said Wednesday that
the president's economic project suggested that he wants to avoid
having the country's financial problems become a bargaining chip
with congressional opponents. Some of the measures, like
streamlining government, would appeal to orthodox economists, while
others, like seeking the grace period on foreign debt, are likely
to win support among the poor.
</P>
<P>
   But the president appeared determined to tackle the country's
dire economic troubles head on, rather than to win popularity.
``This is the first time that he's actually addressing Congress on
fundamental matters of national importance, and he's doing so fully
within the established rules of the democratic process,'' Eric
Eckvall, a Caracas-based political consultant, said in a telephone
interview. ``It shows that these are issues of such major
importance that he doesn't feel that he's in a position to play
politics with them.''
</P>
<P>
   The enabling legislation includes measures to reduce a wholesale
tax by one percentage point, to 15.5 percent, but to broaden it as
a value-added tax; and a proposal for a one-year tax of five-tenths
of a percentage point on financial transactions. Under his proposed
law, the government would begin collecting income tax on a monthly
basis, rather than once a year.
</P>
<P>
   Chavez said his package includes ``payment deferrals'' on
foreign debt to reduce the fiscal deficit. He said he would seek to
negotiate a ``grace period'' on foreign debt that had not already
been restructured.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, he said the package would also include measures to
protect foreign and domestic investments, and to boost Venezuela's
credibility in financial markets.
</P>
<P>
   Such executive decrees are not uncommon in South America.
Brazilian President Fernando Henrique Cardoso has used such decrees
_ which, in Brazil, require renewed congressional authorization
every 30 days _ hundreds of times over the last four years.
</P>
<P>
   Chavez canceled a planned trip to Washington next week, during
which he was to have met with officials at the International
Monetary Fund, but he denied that the change in plans had anything
to do with his economic proposals for debt restructuring. He said,
rather, that he canceled when he discovered that President Clinton
would not be in Washington then.
</P>
<P>
   ``My trip to the United States was pretty much dependent on
having the opportunity to meet with Clinton, and when I found out
he wasn't going to be there I decided to attend to our own domestic
issues,'' the Venezuelan president said.
</P>
<P>
   It was not clear how opposition parties, which enjoy a
two-thirds majority in congress, would treat the president's
request. Some of their members told reporters in Caracas that they
would only know after studying the measures individually.
</P>
<P>
   ``Chavez's economic package is only going to bring more misery
to Venezuela,'' Alberto Franceschi, an opposition deputy of the
Proyecto Venezuela party, was quoted as saying during a debate in
Congress.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
