<SLUG> BC-NY-LEVIN-DEATH-300&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MOTHER OF SLAIN TEACHER FAULTS JURY FOR ACQUITTING ACCUSED MAN
</HEADLINE>
   (rk) 
 By   DAVID ROHDE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ A week after a Brooklyn man was acquitted of all
charges in the slaying of her son, Carol Levin said Wednesday that
the jury was wrong to free the man, Montoun T. Hart, and that she
has concluded that Hart participated in the torture and killing of
her son, Jonathan M. Levin.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking in her first interview since Hart's acquittal last
Thursday, Ms. Levin told a small group of reporters Wednesday that
Hart's testimony that he played no role in the killing initially
``turned my life upside down,'' but now, she said, she believes a
confession he had made earlier.
</P>
<P>
   She criticized the jurors' decision to disregard the confession
after Hart testified that the police coerced him into making false
statements while he was drunk and high on marijuana. Jurors said he
appeared ``wasted'' in police photographs.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think that's naive to think that you could look good after
six hours of questioning,'' Ms. Levin said. ``It wasn't quite right
to disregard those statements entirely.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Levin said that she agreed with prosecutors that the murder
was carried out by Hart and Corey Arthur, a former student of
Levin's at Taft High School in the Bronx, who prosecutors said shot
his former teacher in the head after torturing him to learn the
access code for his bank card.
</P>
<P>
   Arthur, who has refused to say who was with him in the teacher's
apartment, was convicted of second-degree murder in November and is
serving 25 years to life.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Levin said she wondered whether the recent police shooting
of an African immigrant, Amadou Diallo, in the Bronx might have
affected the jury's view of the police in her son's case. But
jurors, who spoke on condition of anonymity last week, said that
the shooting of Diallo played no role in their verdict.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Jurors said that race was never an issue during deliberations.
The Manhattan panel consisted of seven whites, four blacks and one
Asian. Levin is white, Hart is black. One detective who Hart said
coerced him was Hispanic, the other is white.
</P>
<P>
   Defense lawyers accused the police of a ``rush to judgment'' in
the slaying of Levin, the son of the Time Warner chairman, Gerald
M. Levin. David Stern, Hart's lawyer, criticized detectives for
failing to videotape the confession. And Anthony Ricco, one of
Arthur's lawyers, repeated his argument Wednesday that Arthur was
in the teacher's apartment the day of the murder, but ``two to
three'' others who were present are still at large.
</P>
<P>
   But Ms. Levin dismissed the defense arguments. She said she
believed only Hart and Arthur were involved, adding that law
enforcement officials told her they did not videotape Hart's
confession because his lawyer called and ordered the questioning
halted.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't know with 100 percent certainty,'' she said. ``But in
order to calm myself down, I have to believe it was them.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
