</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-IMMIGRANT-FBI-375&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FBI EXAMINES SITE IN BRONX WHERE POLICE FATALLY SHOT UNARMED MAN 
</HEADLINE>
  (lh) 
 By PAUL ZIELBAUER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ In a sign that the federal government has deepened
its involvement in the investigation of the fatal police shooting
of an unarmed West African immigrant, Federal Bureau of
Investigation agents spent hours Wednesday taking measurements of
the bullet-riddled building entrance where Amadou Diallo was
killed.
</P>
<P>
   The agents, escorted by New York City police officers, spent
about four hours examining the many bullet holes and photographing
the ground-floor hallway behind the vestibule where four undercover
officers confronted and shot Diallo two weeks ago. Their efforts
Wednesday coincided with yet another protest and a commemoration of
Diallo in Brooklyn, and the continued investigation by a Bronx
grand jury.
</P>
<P>
   The FBI agents, using yellow measuring tape and more advanced
instruments, took precise measurements of virtually every object in
the immediate area of the vestibule, down to the building's red
bricks.
</P>
<P>
   Police Commissioner Howard Safir said that the work would help
federal officials reconstruct the shooting. ``The FBI is doing a
re-enactment of the shooting,'' he said. Last week, Mary Jo White,
the U.S. attorney in Manhattan, said her office had begun a
forensic analysis of the scene.
</P>
<P>
   Special Agent Joseph A. Valiquette, a spokesman for the FBI,
confirmed that agents had visited Diallo's apartment building, on
Wheeler Avenue in the Soundview section of the Bronx, but he
declined to explain the nature of their work.
</P>
<P>
   Kyle B. Watters, a lawyer representing Diallo's family, said he
was encouraged by the FBI's involvement in the investigation. But
he criticized the amount of information he said was leaking from
the Police Department as the Bronx grand jury gathers testimony
from people who were near the scene of Diallo's shooting on Feb. 4.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Police Department is leaking so much about the
investigation that the integrity of the investigation is being
affected,'' Watters said. ``Clearly, they have a motivation to help
their fellow officers.''
</P>
<P>
   The grand jury continued to hear testimony Wednesday, including
accounts from one of Diallo's roommates and from the paramedics who
arrived after the shooting, a source involved in the legal
proceedings said.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The investigative work by the police and FBI was just one
indication that Diallo's death _ in a torrent of 41 bullets _ is
likely to remain under intense scrutiny.
</P>
<P>
   In Brooklyn, more protesters met to denounce a number of police
shootings. And in a 90-minute prayer service for Diallo, 22, who
had worked as a street vendor, an interfaith group of religious
leaders labeled Mayor Rudolph Giuliani's ``zero-tolerance'' brand
of police enforcement as a catalyst to police brutality.
</P>
<P>
   ``The mayor has called for a zero tolerance,'' Benjamin E.
Muhammad, a representative of Louis Farrakhan, minister of the
Nation of Islam, said to about 125 people inside the House of the
Lord Church. ``Well, we must have a zero tolerance for racist,
killer police officers that come into our community and victimize
our people.''
</P>
<P>
   Most of the six speakers urged people not to allow their sense
of urgency surrounding his death to fade.
</P>
<P>
   ``My brothers and sisters, we have to stand up for our rights
and we must fight until justice is served,'' said Mamadou Conde,
Diallo's cousin, to a standing ovation.
</P>
<P>
   Diallo's killing also echoed Wednesday outside the offices of
the Brooklyn district attorney, Charles Hynes, where 100 protesters
gathered to denounce the slow pace of an inquiry into another fatal
shooting involving Officer Kenneth Boss, one of the four officers
who shot at Diallo. In that case, in October 1997, Boss and other
officers shot Patrick Bailey, 20, who was carrying an unloaded,
inoperable shotgun.
</P>
<P>
   As religious and community leaders vowed to keep pressure on
city officials, calls for justice for Diallo spread to Washington.
In a letter Wednesday, Hugh B. Price, the president of the National
Urban League, implored President Clinton to ``address the festering
issue of police abuse of minorities,'' and to attend the funeral of
the next victim of a questionable police slaying.
</P>
</TEXT>
