<SLUG> BC-JASPER-TATTOOS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JASPER JURY SHOWN RACIST, SATANIC TATTOOS 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  (Eds.: See JASPER-TRIAL) 
 
By RICHARD STEWART 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   JASPER, Texas _ John William ``Bill'' King is a walking gallery
of skin art _ prison-made tattoos ranging from reminders of time in
a particular prison to a demonic Woody Woodpecker peeking from
under a Klan hood and pointing to a black figure hanging from a
tree.
</P>
<P>
   Jasper Police Detective Rich Ford took the jury for a
photographic tour Wednesday of the tattoos of King and the other
two white men charged with dragging a black man, James Byrd Jr., to
death.
</P>
<P>
   There was little reaction in the courtroom other than an
occasional gasp as the racist and satanic tattoos were displayed.
</P>
<P>
   As defense attorneys lodged continuing protests, Ford used a
laser pointer to guide the jury through giant projected blow-ups of
the three men's tattoos _ mainly King's.
</P>
<P>
   King is festooned with figures, including an upside-down
pentagram on the back of his head. His arms are a melange of
figures, unintelligible except in close-ups.
</P>
<P>
   There are demonic figures, reproductions of Church of Satan
founder Anton LaVey preaching and goat heads. A Madonna holds what
looks like a baby Jesus with horns. Valentine hearts are turned
upside down _ a symbol of hate, Ford testified.
</P>
<P>
   There are several allusions to ``peckerwoods,'' a name Ford said
stands for white men in prison. One tattoo says ``100 percent loco
wood,'' and another reads ``PWCCA,'' standing for Peckerwood
Confederate Coalition of America, Ford said.
</P>
<P>
   On one arm is the wild-eyed, demonic-looking, hooded woodpecker
pointing to one of the smallest drawings in the nightmare mixture
of ink. It is a tiny figure of a black man hanging from a tree.
</P>
<P>
   One tattoo may predict King's future if the jury convicts him of
capital murder _ it is of playing cards showing aces and eights,
the traditional dead man's poker hand.
</P>
<P>
   Another tells of his past _ it is a dragon emblazoned with
``Beto I'' _ the Texas prison unit where he got most of the tattoos
while incarcerated there from 1995 to 1997.
</P>
<P>
   Pentagrams _ a five-pointed star inside a circle _ itself a sign
of evil, and its upside-down and even worse version, the bathomet,
is found on the back of his scalp.
</P>
<P>
   Jasper County District Attorney Guy James Gray introduced a
life-sized photograph of King holding his left arm up, displaying a
bathomet in his left armpit.
</P>
<P>
   Gray said the tattoos show that the men _ especially King and
former prison buddy Lawrence Russell Brewer Jr., were racists and
were in a frame of mind to kill a black man.
</P>
<P>
   Both King and Brewer have large crests symbolizing the
Confederate Knights of America _ a Klan-related prison group they
both belonged to. On Tuesday, prosecutors introduced King's
writings found in his apartment that showed he was forming a
Klan-type group called Texas Rebel Soldiers, an offshoot of the
Confederate Knights of America.
</P>
<P>
   Their tattooed shields include Confederate-style stars and bars,
blazing crosses, Nazi-style ``SS'' lightning bolts and the slogan,
``Aryan Pride.''
</P>
<P>
   Brewer has almost as many tattoos, including one that looks like
a pirate, a patch over one eye, his lips sewn shut and a rope
around his neck.
</P>
<P>
   A sort of white supremacy time line winds around one arm, with
Norsemen giving way to pirates, then cowboys and modern-day bikers,
Ford explained.
</P>
<P>
   One tattoo reads ``CKA,'' meaning Confederate Knights of America
and ``Death before dishonor.''
</P>
<P>
   Compared to the other two, Shawn Allen Berry's tattoos are mild.
</P>
<P>
   He has a death's head in a three-horned helmet, emblazoned with
the slogan, ``Brotherhood.'' He also has a grim reaper, but no
tattoos that indicated Klan-like sympathies.
</P>
<P>
   Among items introduced Wednesday was a King mimic of the 23rd
Psalm that he called ``The Psalm of Tattoos.'' It began:
</P>
<P>
   King Tattoo is my shepard, (sic) I shall always want
</P>
<P>
   He maketh me be stung by the needle
</P>
<P>
   He coloreth me with the evil waters
</P>
<P>
   He remaketh my soul
</P>
<P>
   King's attorneys said the tattoos were protected by their
client's first-amendment right to free expression.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think just the tattoos themselves make him a racist,''
said King's attorney, C. Haden ``Sonny'' Cribbs Jr.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
