<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RESCUED-SAILOR-420&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A NEW STORM THREATENS RESCUED SAILOR AND HER SAVIOR
</HEADLINE>
   (rk) 
 By   BARBARA LLOYD   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   After a harrowing rescue at sea, Isabelle Autissier is savoring
her good fortune safe inside a friend's race boat on the way to
Punta del Este, Uruguay.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel very relieved,'' Autissier, a French solo sailor, said
Wednesday night in a satellite phone interview a day after being
fetched from her overturned yacht in the South Pacific by the
Italian Giovanni Soldini. ``I was very concerned about everybody
else in the race because they would try to find me. But I knew
someone would be coming.''
</P>
<P>
   The feeling of relief could be short-lived for Autissier,
Soldini and the rest of the fleet racing in the Around Alone
round-the-world race. Another storm is expected to strike Friday in
an area of the South Pacific Ocean where the 10 competitors are
making their way toward South America.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was worried about the new storm,'' Autissier said. ``I
thought that maybe a piece of my boat's mast, which was still
attached to the hull by a halyard, might break off and put a hole
in my boat.''
</P>
<P>
   The predicted storm carries with it 60-knot winds and 30-foot
seas. While perhaps not as frightening as waiting for help from the
innards of a capsized yacht, it is still potentially as serious.
</P>
<P>
   The gale is expected to cut through the Around Alone fleet,
which is spread out over 2,000 miles, like a thresher through
wheat. The worst of it is likely to hit Autissier and Soldini,
aboard Soldini's 60-foot sailboat, Fila, as they head toward Cape
Horn at the tip of South America, a distance as of late Wednesday
of about 1,600 miles.
</P>
<P>
   Soldini, who saved his friend and fellow-competitor after an
all-night search doesn't fear another storm.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are looking at it,'' the 32-year-old Soldini said Wednesday
night in the ship-to-shore phone interview. ``Maybe we will get
some of the wind. But probably the worst part will be around boats
in the back of the fleet.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, it may be hard to get excited about wind when you're
trying to harness the breeze to win a race.
</P>
<P>
   Ken Campbell, a weather forecaster for the Around Alone, put it
in perspective Wednesday:
</P>
<P>
   ``They're not viewing this as life-threatening,'' Campbell said.
``They're viewing it as advantageous. Storms like this are not
terribly unusual where they are. It's a stormy part of the world.
But that's part of the ball game _ 30 to 40 knots makes their boats
move fast. You've got to realize these people are in powerful
machines.''
</P>
<P>
   And then he added, ``But sometimes, machines break.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Autissier, however, is still raw from her experience. It was
only three days ago that her life was nearly snuffed out as PRB,
the 60-foot race boat, lost control. She was second in a fleet at
the time, on course 1,900 miles from Cape Horn.
</P>
<P>
   Autissier has surmised that the yacht's self-steering gear may
have gone haywire. By changing course unexpectedly, the autopilot
made Autissier's big, flat-bottomed sailboat rear up like a wounded
bull. The 17,000-pound vessel fell over on its side as if a
toreador had stuck a sword in its back.
</P>
<P>
   Struggling to control the million-dollar yacht, Autissier had no
choice but to dive for cover below deck, and shut the hatch behind
her. She could hear the yacht's towering mast break up as it hung
suspended in the void of water beneath her.
</P>
<P>
   She waited inside the dark, wet hull for nearly 22 hours, not
knowing if it might sink before rescue came. ``My worries were
about the little leaks in the deck, and maybe my boat very slowly
filling with water,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I knew someone would come, but I did not know when,'' she
said. ``I thought that if the storm came first, I might have to
wait for a few days. I could do nothing but get my safety gear
ready in the back of the boat, and some food and water.''
</P>
<P>
   Autissier said that she will have to wait to talk with her
yacht's designers, Groupe Finot of France, to determine exactly
what went wrong. But she does know that she was fortunate to have
lived through the experience.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I had been in the back of the boat, I would have fallen
overboard,'' she said. ``The boat would have fallen on top of me.
But it was over on its side so quickly, I could not even go in the
cockpit. I'm really very surprised by what happened.''
</P>
<P>
   She was reminded at the time of her friend, Gerry Roufs, a
Canadian solo sailor who was lost at sea during a race for solo
sailors two years ago. He disappeared in that very same expanse of
open ocean.
</P>
<P>
   When Soldini pulled along side her stricken yacht at dawn
Tuesday, Autissier had fallen asleep inside the cavernous hull. He
screamed for her, ``Isabelle, Isabelle!'' But it wasn't until he
threw a hammer on its hard surface that she awoke. She grabbed her
life raft, inflated it and slipped out of the catacomb of PRB. It
was then that Soldini nuzzled up alongside PRB, and helped his
bedraggled friend scramble to safety.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the trauma of what happened, Autissier said she doesn't
plan to give up solo sailing. Still, she may retire from racing.
``I will not say I am going to stop because I was afraid to die,''
she said matter-of-factly. ``If I stop, it will be because I have
been doing this for 10 years, and now maybe it is time to do
something else.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
