<HEADLINE>
WORLD NEWS IN BRIEF 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   EUROPE
</P>
<P>
   Russia: Ukraine Treaty Ratified
</P>
<P>
   MOSCOW: The upper house of Parliament voted to ratify a treaty
that effectively abandons the Kremlin's claims on Crimea on
condition that Ukraine's legislature guarantee that the Russian
fleet can maintain its existing fleet there. Prime Minister Yevgeny
Primakov had sought the treaty in part to brake Ukraine's plans to
join NATO.
</P>
<P>
   Northern Ireland: Antagonists Meet
</P>
<P>
   BELFAST _ Officials of the Ulster Unionists and Sinn Fein met
privately in Belfast for the first time and discussed problems in
the peace effort. Leaders of the Unionists, the largest Protestant
party, and Sinn Fein, the political wing of the IRA, said the
meeting was useful, but that they had failed to make progress on
the bitter dispute over IRA disarmament.
</P>
<P>
   European Union: End to Duty-Free Sales
</P>
<P>
   The European Commission repeated its determination to outlaw
tax-free sales of liquor, tobacco and other goods by July.
Duty-free shop operators said they would continue to campaign
against the decision, which they argue will cost jobs. The
commission said the move would generate $2.2 billion in taxes.
</P>
<P>
   THE AMERICAS
</P>
<P>
   Mexico: Halting Forest Fires
</P>
<P>
   Chiapas state has proposed a law to fine and jail farmers who
start forest fires by setting fields on fire to prepare for the
next planting. Last spring fires in Chiapas swept across 500,000
acres, consuming precious rain forests.
</P>
<P>
   Colombia: Investigators Freed
</P>
<P>
   Right-wing paramilitary forces have released nine government
investigators who were abducted and held for a day while they were
searching for a mass grave in Antioquia province, BBC News
reported. The investigators had been searching for a pit that was
said to contain victims of political violence.
</P>
<P>
   MIDDLE EAST
</P>
<P>
   Israel: U.S. Warning on Computer Piracy
</P>
<P>
   Israel has failed to crack down on counterfeit music CDs and
computer software and could face trade sanctions later this year,
Ambassador Edward Walker said. After Israel was placed on an annual
watch list of intellectual-property violators in April, the
government promised to pass a new copyright law and pursue vendors
of pirated CDs.
</P>
<P>
   AFRICA
</P>
<P>
   South Africa: Torturer Gets Amnesty
</P>
<P>
   A Cape Town police officer who specialized in torturing
anti-apartheid activists by wrapping wet bags over their heads and
repeatedly bringing them to the point of suffocation has been
granted amnesty by the Truth and Reconciliation Commission. The
officer, Jeffrey Benzien, had told the panel that the method was so
effective that his victims usually ``talked'' within half an hour.
</P>
<P>
   South Africa: Conservative Budget
</P>
<P>
   PRETORIA _ The government presented a plan to increase taxes on
cigarettes and liquor but offer tax cuts for corporations and
consumers. With the nation's second post-apartheid elections
expected in May, the government appeared to have resisted the
temptation to buy votes for the ruling African National Congress.
</P>
</TEXT>
