A9494 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-AMERICAN-PILOTS-TEX     02-17 0929
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AMERICAN-PILOTS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AIRLINE SAYS SICKOUT COST $58.7 MILLION
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DAN REED 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DALLAS _ American Airlines said Wednesday that its pilots union,
in prolonging a sickout last week after a federal judge ordered
members back to work, cost the carrier at least $58.7 million.
</P>
<P>
   But the Allied Pilots Association asked for time to review those
claims, and U.S. District Judge Joe Kendall recessed the hearing
until April 12.
</P>
<P>
   Kendall found the pilots in contempt of court Saturday for
ignoring his back-to-work order and hammered them for bargaining
tactics that he compared to a mob shakedown. On Tuesday, the court
collected a $10 million down payment from the union toward the
fines and damages Kendall intends to assess.
</P>
<P>
   Both sides said the negotiations over the underlying issue _ the
integration of Reno Air pilots into the American system _ were
stalled Wednesday. And the sticking point is the same as it was on
Feb. 5, when the union launched its sickout.
</P>
<P>
   The union, which represents 9,300 pilots, has demanded that
Reno's 300 pilots be paid on American's higher pay scale
retroactive to Dec. 23, the day American gained financial control
of Reno. The union is also demanding that American first officers
who will be promoted to captain because of the Reno deal be paid
captain's wages retractive to Dec. 23.
</P>
<P>
   This week, management offered to raise Reno pilots' pay as much
as 56 percent immediately.
</P>
<P>
   But citing industry precedents, American doesn't want to pay
Reno pilots on the still-higher scale until they are assigned to
their new jobs at American. Nor does the company want to give a
raise to its own pilots who will be promoted as a result of the
acquisition until they are assigned to their new positions.
</P>
<P>
   Union President Rich LaVoy said the talks ``are going
backwards.'' He called the demand that all pilots affected by the
Reno merger receive their pay raises retroactive to Dec. 23 a
``core principle.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We simply cannot set a precedent of American Airlines, even
for a day, controlling a low-paid carrier, after we've really
fought and bargained so hard to bring back what we had lost in the
early '80s,'' LaVoy said.
</P>
<P>
   American spokesman Chris Chiames said management is just as
adamant about not granting raises retroactively, even though the
airline's financial loss from the sickout is more than retroactive
pay would have cost.
</P>
<P>
   That is because the airline does not want to set a precedent
that would make future mergers too expensive, he said.
</P>
<P>
   In the courtroom Wednesday, Doug Herring, American's vice
president and controller, said the company lost at least $150
million during the sickout.
</P>
<P>
   Kendall issued his back-to-work order Feb. 10, five days after
the sickout began, but the number of pilots on the sick list grew
through Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   Herring said American lost at least $58.7 million from Feb. 10
through Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   After Kendall's ruling Saturday morning, the union stepped up
its efforts to persuade pilots to return to work. As a result,
American's operations began returning to normal on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday was the first day since Feb. 5 that American reported
no flight cancellations because of crew shortages.
</P>
<P>
   Union lawyers are expected to argue that the period when the
union was in contempt was much shorter, perhaps as little as 21
hours, until LaVoy taped a new phone message for the pilots hot
line.
</P>
<P>
   To bolster its contention that union leaders encouraged pilots
to ignore the back-to-work order, American introduced into evidence
a series of e-mail messages from union board members in New York
and San Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   The messages, all logged between Feb. 6 and 4:22 p.m. on Feb.
10, warned pilots that a federal judge would probably issue a
temporary restraining order against the union. They advised members
that such an order would be binding only on the union's leadership
and not on rank-and-file members.
</P>
<P>
   A similar statement by LaVoy on the union's telephone hot line
after Kendall had issued his back-to-work order was one reasons the
judge cited for his contempt ruling.
</P>
<P>
   The e-mail messages also advised pilots that no judge could make
them fly if they declared themselves unfit under federal aviation
regulations. And they warned pilots that the judge might force
union leaders to ``sanitize'' their official communications with
members.
</P>
<P>
   One such e-mail message, composed by Randy Trommer, a union
board member representing pilots in San Francisco, said:
``Depending on what legal orders are received, our direct
communication ability may be impaired. Talk to each other! ... We
will do our best to communicate with you. Realize, however, that
our abilities will be hampered.''
</P>
<P>
   American apparently was given copies of those e-mail messages by
a pilot with access to the union's private Web site. The copies of
the e-mail entered into the record were edited to conceal the
identity of the recipient.
</P>
<P>
   Dee Kelly, American's lawyer, also gave Kendall a copy of an
e-mail message that he said was ``unfit to read'' in public and
which contained a specific threat against the judge. Kelly, who
declined to make copies of the message public, said he had turned
it over to the U.S. Marshals Service for investigation. Kendall
took no public action, and the marshals office declined to comment.
</P>
<P>
   LaVoy said he regretted that the message was transmitted via the
union's Web site.
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
