<HEADLINE>
GUARD PAYS PRICE FOR GONZAGA SUCCESS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JON WILNER  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   MORAGA _ Gonzaga junior guard Matt Santangelo stared into the
cold rain outside the St. Mary's gym after a recent victory and
described his bittersweet season. He is 6-foot-1 and 175 pounds,
with dark, straight hair, hard features and the sullen look of
someone who has taken one for the team.
</P>
<P>
   ``Personally, it's been very frustrating,'' he said. ``I know
people are looking at me and wondering, `What's going on with
Santangelo?' ''
</P>
<P>
   The player and the team have emerged as two of the best stories
of the college season, but for reasons as disparate as victory and
defeat.
</P>
<P>
   Santangelo is the Bulldogs' best player. In fact, he and Boise
State's Roberto Bergersen are the best unknown players in the West.
Although he has been compared to former Gonzaga guard John Stockton
_ a smart, shooting point guard with deceptive quickness and superb
instincts _ a more apt comparison is ex-Santa Clara and current
Dallas Mavericks guard Steve Nash.
</P>
<P>
   The Bulldogs, who play at Pepperdine on Friday night, are the
West Coast Conference's best team. Thanks to a 21-5 record and
tough nonconference schedule _ losses to Kansas, Purdue and Texas
Christian; a victory over Washington _ they may earn an NCAA
at-large bid if they don't win the WCC tournament next week.
</P>
<P>
   That's where the paths cross: Gonzaga has played well because
Santangelo has not.
</P>
<P>
   To make room for 5-8 senior guard Quentin Hall, Bulldogs coach
Dan Monson asked Santangelo before the season to move from point
guard, his natural position, to shooting guard. Reluctantly,
Santangelo agreed.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's sacrificed a lot,'' Monson said. ``At the beginning of
the season, he was not his usual self and his confidence wasn't
like it was last year, because he didn't have the ball in his
hands. But it has helped him become a more complete player.''
</P>
<P>
   Santangelo doesn't argue that point. On the wing, he has learned
to move without the ball, use screens and defend bigger players
while improving his rebounding. He remains Gonzaga's leader, both
on the court and in the locker room, and when needed he can take
over a game.
</P>
<P>
   But his production has plummeted. Last year, Santangelo shot
43.5 percent from the field, 43.3 percent from 3-point range and
averaged 16.2 points. This year, he's shooting 36 percent from the
field, 34 percent from 3-point range and averaging 11.7 points.
</P>
<P>
   ``In my former life, I was a shooter,'' he said quietly.
</P>
<P>
   Although Gonzaga's success has made the switch tolerable,
Santangelo can't help but wonder about his future _ about the
impact of the position change on his NBA potential.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know that's selfish, but it's also natural to think about
it,'' he said, staring into the rain. ``I do want to play at the
next level, and this year has really been a sacrifice. Hopefully,
I'll be back at point guard next year.''
</P>
<P>
   Burgeoning bubble: As Selection Sunday approaches, a few things
to watch:
</P>
<P>
   How will middle-tier teams in the major conferences fare in the
final weeks? Nebraska, Oklahoma State, Mississippi State, Arkansas,
Georgia, Florida State, California, Minnesota and Northwestern are
in tenuous positions. Not even Kansas is assured an at-large bid.
</P>
<P>
   How will the top mid-major teams perform in their conference
tournaments? Miami-Ohio (Mid-American), Southwest Missouri State
(Missouri Valley) and Gonzaga have strong power ratings and may get
at-large invitations if they don't win their league tournaments. If
so, they'd suck bids away from the Pacific-10, ACC, Big Ten and
SEC.
</P>
<P>
   What of the Big Ten? Eight bids seem unlikely, but it may get
seven. Michigan State, Ohio State, Wisconsin, Iowa and Indiana are
in. Minnesota, Purdue and Northwestern are questionable.
</P>
<P>
   The Stanford situation. The Cardinal has lost its grip on a No.
1 seed and may not win the Pac-10. That would clear a path for
Arizona to stay in the West, where the regionals are scheduled for
America West Arena in Phoenix, its home-away-from-home.
</P>
<P>
   The New Mexico situation. Despite 20 wins and a No. 24 ranking,
the Lobos DO NOT deserve an at-large bid. They are 2-5 on the road,
they played a pathetic nonconference schedule, they lost at home to
Utah by 18 points, and they are No. 103 in the latest Ratings
Percentage Index rankings.
</P>
<P>
   Around the Pac-10: From the ``Bad behavior is not relegated to
UCLA'' file: Five Arizona freshmen were late to a film session and
forced to run extra laps around McKale Center after a recent game.
. . .
</P>
<P>
   Oregon won its first home conference game on Feb. 11. . . .
</P>
<P>
   Arizona State has two non-Division I victories, Chaminade and
Alaska-Anchorage. That could crush the Sun Devils on Selection
Sunday, even with a strong finish. . . .
</P>
<P>
   Comment: USC coach Henry Bobby says, ``There were a lot of
expectations on us to be a great team.''
</P>
<P>
   Response: From whom? . . .
</P>
<P>
   Stanford coach Mike Montgomery confirmed Tuesday that reserve
guard Ryan Mendez will not return this season from a stress
reaction in his knee. He has not practiced in months. . . .
</P>
<P>
   And finally, Pac-10 teams in the latest RPI rankings: 3.
Stanford, 16. Arizona, 18. Washington, 19. UCLA. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
