<SLUG> BC-PHARMANEX-VICTORY-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PHARMANEX VICTORIOUS IN FIGHT OVER SUPPLEMENT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
BY BEN SULLIVAN  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SIMI VALLEY, Calif. -- In a major win for the nutritional
supplements industry, a federal judge has ruled in favor of
supplements maker Pharmanex Inc. in its two-year legal battle with
the U.S. Food and Drug Administration.
</P>
<P>
   The Pharmanex case centered on whether a cholesterol-lowering
substance that the Simi Valley company markets under the name
Cholestin is a drug or a dietary supplement. Because it contains
the same active ingredient as a prescription medicine sold by drug
giant Merck &AMP; Co., the FDA argued it is a drug, subject to strict
government approval and regulation guidelines.
</P>
<P>
   But Pharmanex attorneys argued that because the substance is
naturally occurring -- Cholestin is harvested from a red yeast
found on certain kinds of rice -- it is merely a supplement, a
product category virtually unregulated by the FDA under the 1994
Dietary Supplement Health and Education Act.
</P>
<P>
   In his ruling late Tuesday, U.S. District Court Judge Dale
Kimball agreed with Pharmanex, permanently lifting a ban ordered by
the FDA last May on Pharmanex imports of Cholestin ingredients from
its Chinese supplier. Kimball said Cholestin clearly meets the
dietary-supplement definition as a product other than tobacco
intended to supplement the diet.
</P>
<P>
   The judge's ruling allows Pharmanex to continue importing the
red yeast rice to its Farmington, Utah, factory where it produces
90,000 capsules of Cholestin a day. Pharmanex was purchased last
October by Nu Skin Enterprises, based in Provo, Utah, one of the
nation's largest direct marketers of health and beauty aids.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts said the case will have broad implications for the $5
billion-per-year nutritional supplements industry, which
increasingly markets products to consumers for conditions, ranging
from high cholesterol to impotence, previously considered the sole
domain of prescription medicines.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is highly significant because it reconfirms that
naturally occurring substances sold off the shelf are not drugs,''
said analyst Patricia Negron at Adams, Harkness &AMP; Hill Inc.
``Companies like Merck and other large pharmaceutical entities with
longstanding relationships with the FDA are threatened by these
kinds of products and have used their muscle to prevent them being
sold. This is a very important milestone for the (supplements)
industry.''
</P>
<P>
   Negron predicted the ruling will further motivate drug companies
to establish their own supplement lines to augment their
prescription drug business.
</P>
<P>
   Pharmanex President Bill McGlashin said the company was pleased
with the judge's ruling, adding that intense study by Pharmanex or
another dietary supplements maker, to identify the key ingredient
of a naturally occurring product, does not ``transform (the
product) into a drug.''
</P>
<P>
   X X X &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
