u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MICROSOFT-COMPAQ-HNS &LR;      02-17 0782
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MICROSOFT-COMPAQ-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GOVERNMENT ATTORNEY CHALLENGES COMPAQ EXECUTIVE AT MICROSOFT TRIAL 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  (Filed in ``w'' and ``f'' categories) 
 
By DAVID IVANOVICH 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ A government attorney in the Microsoft Corp.
antitrust trial assailed a Compaq Computer Corp. witness' assertion
the software giant did not improperly attempt to coerce his company
into scrapping plans to install a Web browser made by Microsoft
rival Netscape Communications Corp.
</P>
<P>
   Compaq Senior Vice President John Rose testified Wednesday he
and several other company executives reached a ``verbal'' agreement
with Microsoft during a conference call Aug. 8, 1995, promising the
Houston-based computer maker would not modify the kits used to load
Microsoft's popular Windows operating system into Compaq's Presario
line of personal computers.
</P>
<P>
   That oral agreement, Rose said, meant Compaq could not remove
the icons for Microsoft's Web browser _ Internet Explorer _ or for
Microsoft's online service _ Microsoft Network _ from the Windows
95 default desktop.
</P>
<P>
   But little more than two weeks later, on Aug. 23, 1995, Compaq
officials signed a written agreement with the Dulles, Va.-based
online service provider America Online that would have done just
that.
</P>
<P>
   The AOL deal would have removed the Internet Explorer icon and
replaced it with AOL's featured Web browser, Netscape's Navigator.
</P>
<P>
   Compaq officials had failed to get the word out about the
Microsoft agreement, Rose argued.
</P>
<P>
   ``Unfortunately, we had a communications breakdown,'' Rose said,
adding ``the person that signed the agreement did not get the
message.''
</P>
<P>
   That person was Compaq Vice President Celeste Dunn. And in a
deposition taken last October, Rose identified Dunn as one of the
Compaq executives who had participated in the Microsoft conference
call.
</P>
<P>
   But Microsoft officials produced a document that suggested Rose
had confused Dunn with another woman executive at the company.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. Justice Department and attorneys general from 19 states
have accused Microsoft of using its virtual monopoly power over
computer operating systems to thwart Netscape's efforts to market
its Web browser.
</P>
<P>
   Rose's testimony was designed to counter the testimony of
Netscape President James Barksdale, the government's lead-off
witness in the four-month-old trial, who had accused Microsoft of
threatening Compaq for featuring the Navigator icon on the Windows
desktop.
</P>
<P>
   In February 1996, Compaq announced plans to team up with
Netscape on a project involving computer servers. The computer
maker also began using Netscape for some internal communications.
</P>
<P>
   In May, a company executive sent an e-mail warning: ``Microsoft
was upset with our announcement and our internal use of Netscape.''
</P>
<P>
   On May 31, Microsoft sent a letter threatening to terminate
Compaq's license to use Windows, noting that Compaq had removed the
Microsoft Network icon from the desktop.
</P>
<P>
   Rose testified that it was not until Compaq received that letter
that he learned about the terms of the AOL agreement. Compaq
officials then went back to AOL and renegotiated their deal.
</P>
<P>
   Compaq then agreed to reinstate the icons for Internet Explorer
and Microsoft Network but told Microsoft it was adding icons for
AOL and Navigator.
</P>
<P>
   Smiling and confident through much of his testimony, Rose told
the court he is sometimes referred to as the ``father of the
Presario.''
</P>
<P>
   But Rose was taken aback when the government's lead attorney,
David Boies, produced an internal Compaq document from Nov. 10,
1998, in which an unspecified Compaq employee described Microsoft's
business terms for manufacturers as ``what one would expect from a
monopoly.''
</P>
<P>
   Rose said he was not familiar with the document and did not
agree with the ``monopoly'' description.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think it's ever had executive-level visibility,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Also Wednesday, Dan Rosen, Microsoft's general manager for new
technology, disputed a critical government claim that Microsoft
officials offered to carve up the browser market with Netscape
during a June 21, 1995, meeting with Netscape's Barksdale.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was no proposed `market division''' Rosen said.
Barksdale has said he was ``stunned'' by the proposal, but Rosen
said he did not sense from any of the participants in the meeting
that they had regarded the proposals being discussed as ``illegal
or improper.''
</P>
<P>
   Rosen also attacked Netscape co-founder Marc Andreessen's notes
of the session, noting: ``Throughout most of the meeting, Mr.
Andreessen did not appear to be paying attention ... .''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
