<SLUG> BC-TEX-LEGIS-UTGRAMM18-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Texas graduate students to receive tax break
 &HT;    By Mary Ann Roser
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Texas universities and graduate students who
help teach and do research will get a tax break totaling millions
of dollars, but when they'll see the money is in dispute, officials
said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   The tax cut is the result of a federal law, passed in October,
that put Texas on par with 47 other states that exempt the earnings
of working graduate students and their schools from Social Security
taxes. For every dollar a Texas student earns, 7.65 cents is
withheld, and the university pays the same amount in payroll taxes.
</P>
<P>
   Reaching parity with other states has been an issue for
University of Texas graduate students and administrators because
the tax, coupled with inadequate pay for working graduate students,
has caused UT to lose top-notch students to better-paying schools,
said Teresa Sullivan, dean of graduate studies at UT. The average
graduate student who teaches at UT earns about $10,500 for a
nine-month school year.
</P>
<P>
   For Kim Nixon, a UT doctoral student in psychology and a
teaching assistant, the tax exemption will mean an extra $70 a
month.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's food,'' she said. ``That's a significant amount.''
</P>
<P>
   For the UT System, the tax break means $4.3 million a year in
income to 15,868 students and another $4.3 million in payroll tax
savings to the system's universities, said UT System Chancellor
William Cunningham.
</P>
<P>
   Across Texas, the savings work out to $13 million for all
graduate students and $13 million for all of the public
universities, Cunningham said.
</P>
<P>
   Cunningham, who sought the tax-exemption law, and U.S. Sen. Phil
Gramm, the Texas Republican who got it passed, briefed UT students
and faculty about the law on Wednesday. Cunningham and Gramm said
they would like to see the students' paychecks reflect the increase
by May.
</P>
<P>
   But Dan Stewart, state Social Security administrator for the
Employees Retirement System of Texas, said he was told Texas should
not expect the increases until after June 30, 2000.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Social Security Administration indicates that the
legislation doesn't allow an earlier time frame,'' Stewart said.
``Of course, I'm hearing Senator Gramm wants to move more quickly
than that, and, obviously, we think it's a good thing.''
</P>
<P>
   Whether that can happen remains to be seen, Stewart said.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
