<SLUG> BC-BORDER-INS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TEXAS DUE 500 MORE INS AGENTS ALONG BORDER 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  (Attn: Ariz.) 
 
By JENNIFER DAY 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Texas will get 500 more Border Patrol agents, half
the number of new agents hired this fiscal year by the INS, to
bolster a 19-month-old operation along the Rio Grande.
</P>
<P>
   Immigration and Naturalization Service Commissioner Doris
Meissner said Wednesday she plans to hire 1,000 new agents as part
of the agency's $3.9 billion in spending for 1999.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the new agents deployed in Texas will work on Operation
Rio Grande, Meissner said, an intensive Border Patrol operation
that began in July 1997. The new agents represent a 15 percent
increase over the 3,433 patrol agents now on the Texas-Mexico
border. Arizona will get 395 new agents.
</P>
<P>
   The INS and the Department of Justice began five years ago to
target specific corridors of illegal immigration along the United
States' southwestern border, flooding those areas with manpower and
resources.
</P>
<P>
   Of the 500 new Texas hires, 250 agents will be sent to the
McAllen sector, an area through which illegal immigrants attempt to
reach Houston, said Mark Reed, director of the INS' Central Region.
Del Rio will get 80 more agents and Laredo will get 120. The El
Paso and Marfa sectors will get 25 each.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, the INS plans to spend $20.9 million to construct
new Border Patrol facilities in Hebbronville, Falfurrias, Sierra
Blanca, Brownsville and the Del Rio Presidio station. Road and
lighting improvements will be made in the Del Rio, Laredo and Marfa
sectors at a cost of $939,000.
</P>
<P>
   INS also will spend $1 million to add 90 jobs in its detention
and deportation operations and to place 400 new beds in facilities
in Port Isabel. Each of the INS's 11 regions will get a new
juvenile coordinator to oversee development of 126 additional
juvenile beds.
</P>
<P>
   The INS has been under fire over detentions since reports
earlier this month the agency was considering the release of
illegal immigrants being held for criminal offenses.
</P>
<P>
   Several members of Congress wrote letters of protest after INS
memos were made public that detailed a plan to release aliens being
held on charges ranging from assault and burglary to manslaughter
and sexual molestation.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd like to state emphatically that INS is not releasing any
detainees, nor do we plan to,'' Meissner said. She is exploring
other options that will relieve INS detention centers of crowding,
she said.
</P>
<P>
   But U.S. Rep. Lamar Smith, R-San Antonio, who heads the House
immigration subcommittee, still is not satisfied, said his
spokesman, Allen Kay.
</P>
<P>
   ``She did not rule out the possibility of INS releasing
criminals into your neighborhood in the future, and that is a point
the congressman remains concerned about,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Although Meissner declined to comment specifically on options
INS was considering to relieve crowding, she said there has been an
ongoing discussion about what kinds of offenders are being
detained.
</P>
<P>
   Detainees range from those who are breaking civil immigration
laws to convicted felons, she said.
</P>
<P>
   Releasing even nonviolent offenders may cause problems, Kay
said. Justice Department statistics show that 90 percent of
non-criminal illegal aliens who are detained are never deported.
</P>
<P>
   ``If, to any extent, INS is going to release non-criminal
aliens, they're saying they're giving up on trying to deport
them,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Reed said detention facilities in El Paso and Port Isabel still
can handle the load, but they need to be upgraded.
</P>
<P>
   INS also contracts with several county jails and facilities in
Houston, he said, mostly because the city is convenient to a number
of consulates, attorneys for immigrants and major airports that
provide direct flights out of the United States.
</P>
<P>
   Problems with crowding have been magnified since INS decided not
to immediately deport illegal aliens from Central America because
of devastation caused by Hurricane Mitch in Nicaragua, Honduras,
Guatemala and El Salvador, Meissner said.
</P>
<P>
   To deal with that problem, INS has requested an $80 million
supplemental budget.
</P>
<P>
   Beyond funding for enforcement, Houston will receive 10 of 200
temporary adjudicators hired to reduce the backlog of
naturalization applications in eight cities.
</P>
<P>
   Among other items included in the INS budget are 100 new
immigration inspectors in 13 major airports in the United States,
Aruba and Ireland; 100 immigration information officers in INS
service centers throughout the country; 36 management positions to
oversee construction projects; and 10 positions for the Office of
Internal Audit.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
