<HEADLINE>
IS SHE OR ISN'T SHE? 
BLOCKING `OKLAHOMA!' 
IT'S NOT ALWAYS WHO YOU KNOW
</HEADLINE>
   (mk) 
 By JAMES BARRON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ So many is-she-or-isn't-she questions, so few facts.
</P>
<P>
   Hillary Rodham Clinton may or may not be running for the U.S.
Senate. She may or may not be buying a certain apartment on the
Upper West Side.
</P>
<P>
   She has not weighed in. But it seems as if everyone else has.
Her chances against Republicans like Mayor Rudolph Giuliani and her
chances with Manhattan's notoriously fickle co-op boards have been
dissected with unusual care this week.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Monica stuff is over, and people are looking for something
to gossip about,'' said one Democrat who spoke on the condition of
anonymity. ``The lack of information makes it even more
titillating.''
</P>
<P>
   The speculation continued Wednesday with more talk about Mrs.
Clinton's supposed interest in a cooperative apartment at 290 West
End Ave. that has been on the market for $1.295 million. Never mind
that the doormen and the managing agent say that Mrs. Clinton has
not even stopped by for a look-see.
</P>
<P>
   ``The funniest thing about the real estate community is,
everybody's talking about what they've read in the papers,'' said
one real estate agent who has been showing the apartment. ``There's
absolutely no true corroboration available.''
</P>
<P>
   Which is about what Harold Ickes, a former White House official
who has discussed the Senate race with Mrs. Clinton, said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know nothing about an apartment, nothing whatsoever,'' he
said. ``This stuff is wildfire.''
</P>
<P>
   Maybe Mrs. Clinton has compartmentalized her life, separating
her apartment-hunting from her campaign decision-making to the
point of keeping an insider like Ickes out of the real estate loop.
Or maybe she has realized what those who already live in New York
know only too well: It is an expensive place, and the Clintons have
never been wealthy.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can form a committee to pay legal bills, you can form a
committee to set up a library,'' Ickes said. ``You cannot form a
committee to raise money for everyday living in New York or else
we'd all have committees.''
</P>
<P>
   Would renting be more affordable, as some Democrats noted?
William Rudin, the president of a large family-run real estate firm
whose roster of tenants has included VIPs like former Mayor David
Dinkins, answered the question with a question: ``Hillary who?''
</P>
<P>
   Wild West End
</P>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Trevor Nunn's ``Oklahoma!'' is not OK with Actors'
Equity, at least not the way he wanted to do it.
</P>
<P>
   Nunn wanted to import the entire British company of
``Oklahoma!'' _ perhaps the quintessential American musical, with
spirited cowboys and farm girls singing about the land they love _
to Broadway. He said his schedule was too tight to rehearse a new
cast here.
</P>
<P>
   But the union's governing council turned down the request
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are disappointed,'' said Bert Fink, a spokesman for the
Rodgers and Hammerstein estate. ``It means `Oklahoma!' is, at the
very least, indefinitely postponed.''
</P>
<P>
   Unconnected
</P>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ In 1991, when Kevin Baker was working as the chief
historical researcher for what became Harold Evans' 720-page book
``The American Century,'' he finished a novel he had been writing
in his spare time.
</P>
<P>
   He submitted it to Random House, which rejected it, even though
Evans was the president and publisher of Random House's trade group
at the time.
</P>
<P>
   ``He didn't read it himself,'' Baker said. ``It was about
baseball and Ty Cobb, which isn't his area of expertise, and it was
turned down there. I thought, what kind of career do I have here?
I'm on good terms with the president of the company and it doesn't
sell.''
</P>
<P>
   Crown published that book, and Baker began another,
``Dreamland.''
</P>
<P>
   But once again, Evans was no help. ``He had just left Random
House by the time I got this in shape to send out,'' Baker said.
</P>
<P>
   So HarperCollins is publishing ``Dreamland.'' For the record,
Knopf, a Random House imprint, published ``The American Century.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
