A9515 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NY-COL-RACISM-NYT &LR;      02-17 0780
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-COL-RACISM-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ONCE, RACISM MEANT LEAVING HARLEM ALONE  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By JOHN TIERNEY    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ In the fall of 1963, a rookie patrolman named David
Durk reported for duty to the 28th precinct in Harlem. Durk, who
would later achieve fame for fighting police corruption, recalled
listening with other new officers as the sergeant read a primer
about Harlem.
</P>
<P>
   The sergeant quoted Adam Clayton Powell Jr. on Harlem's arrest
rate, which was eight times the city average _ and, to Powell,
proof of police racism. The sergeant kept reading the primer,
according to an account of the scene in Durk's biography,
``Crusader,'' by James Lardner:
</P>
<P>
   `` `This is a vibrant, vital community,' the sergeant read,
without much conviction. He put down the clipboard and looked his
men in the eye: ``All right. I'll skip the rest of this
[expletive). I want you to go out there. Don't lose sight of your
partner, don't go down any block alone, don't go into any
buildings, and no arrests unless you're personally assaulted.'''
</P>
<P>
   Durk and his partner, a fellow white officer, were assigned a
beat on Lenox Avenue, where men were gambling on the sidewalk. The
patrolmen, according to the biography, politely let the game go on.
They and many other officers spent the evening at a theater
watching a Tarzan movie.
</P>
<P>
   Well, some might say today, at least those officers weren't out
killing unarmed black men. But other people were. The next year the
number of homicides in New York rose above 600 for the first time.
By 1968, as the toll neared 1,000 (it eventually exceeded 2,000 in
1990), the front page of The New York Times carried a headline:
``NAACP Deplores Harlem Terror.''
</P>
<P>
   The article described a report from the New York branch of the
National Association for the Advancement of Colored People, which
expressed shock at the number of criminals ``who are permitted to
roam the streets and hallways without hindrance.'' It demanded
tougher jail sentences, armed guards in housing projects and more
police officers in Harlem.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is not police brutality that makes people afraid to walk
the streets at night,'' one of the report's authors, Vincent Baker,
said at the time, explaining that the chief problem for blacks was
``criminal brutality.''
</P>
<P>
   His words may sound odd today, as ministers and politicians from
the Bronx to West Africa are protesting overly aggressive policing,
but the worst form of police racism used to consist of doing
nothing about crimes involving only blacks.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everywhere in Southern Negro communities, I have met the
complaint from law-abiding Negroes that they are left practically
without police protection,'' Gunnar Myrdal wrote in his classic
1944 treatise on race, ``An American Dilemma.''
</P>
<P>
   Whatever mistakes were made by the white members of the street
crimes unit who fired at Amadou Diallo on Feb. 4, they were not
guilty of ignoring black-on-black crime. They were searching for a
black serial rapist who had been attacking women in black and
Hispanic neighborhoods.
</P>
<P>
   ``Once upon a time, a special police squad like that would have
been hunting for jewel thieves on the Upper East Side instead of a
rapist in a poor neighborhood,'' said Thomas A. Reppetto, president
of the Citizens Crime Commission of New York City. ``Certain
ghettos were written off by police as areas where nothing could be
done about crime.''
</P>
<P>
   Obviously, there are many alternatives to doing nothing. The
police could still combat crime in the Bronx without stopping as
many young black and Hispanic men as they have been doing. It can
be argued that many of these encounters are ill advised because
they're too risky and arouse too much resentment in the innocent
people who are stopped.
</P>
<P>
   But the protesters already demanding jail terms for the officers
who shot Diallo might consider who will be hurt if the police turn
more passive. Blacks suffer disproportionately from violence, and
it's not usually from whites in the police force or anywhere else.
Most black victims, like most white victims, are attacked by
members of their own race. (In the case of interracial crimes of
violence, a great majority of victims nationwide are white.)
</P>
<P>
   So if the police are searching less aggressively for that serial
rapist, who is believed to have struck again on Sunday, the chief
victims will probably be black and Hispanic women.
</P>
<P>
   If there were a rise in the number of homicides _ which are down
to the level of the early 1960s _ the victims would be mainly black
and Hispanic men. The police would do just fine if they stopped
bothering strangers at night. They'd be much safer watching a
Tarzan movie.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-17-99 2248EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
