<SLUG> BC-GERMANY-LABOR-1STLD-WRITETHRU-450&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STRIKE BY BIGGEST GERMAN UNION IS AVERTED 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (SUBS to update; total rewrite.)  (lh) 
 By EDMUND L. ANDREWS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   FRANKFURT, Germany _ Germany's largest union reached an
agreement with employers early Thursday, averting what would have
been the nation's first strike in four years.
</P>
<P>
   The union, IG Metall, which represents 3.5 million
metal-industry workers and others, agreed with big employers on pay
raises totaling 3.2 percent, to be paid over 14 months beginning
March 1. They also agreed to a 1 percent bonus not linked to
company profit. The union strongly opposed profit-linked bonuses.
</P>
<P>
   IG Metall had been holding out for raises of more than 4
percent, plus a significant one-time payment to each worker. The
employers, which include DaimlerChrysler and big producers of
machine tools and other factory equipment, had offered a 2.3
percent raise and a maximum one-time payment of five-tenths of a
percent of a worker's salary.
</P>
<P>
   The agreement came more than two hours after a midnight strike
authorization deadline for workers in the state of
Baden-Wuerttemberg, home to most of the country's auto industry. A
strike in the state could have slowed production at
DaimlerChrysler, Porsche AG, Volkswagen AG's Audi unit and Robert
Bosch GmbH.
</P>
<P>
   The union originally set a deadline for talks on Feb. 11. When
both sides refused to budge, the government offered to mediate.
Union leaders agreed to resume talks on Tuesday in Stuttgart,
setting the new deadline of midnight Wednesday. Barring success,
the union said, its members would vote to strike on March 1.
</P>
<P>
   The confrontation was bitter and came at a difficult time.
German workers are among the highest paid in the world, but
unemployment in this country remains above 10 percent, and the
economy has slowed in recent months.
</P>
<P>
   IG Metall has been hammered by the loss of nearly a million
industrial jobs since 1990, and union leaders have settled for
negligible wage increases for the last three years. They have made
big concessions on extra pay for overtime and on weekend work. And
they have watched as many companies in eastern Germany refused to
negotiate with them at all. But this time the union, proclaiming
``an end to modesty,'' pressed its most aggressive wage demands in
years.
</P>
<P>
   The dispute posed a hard challenge for Germany's new Social
Democratic chancellor, Gerhard Schroeder, who made unemployment the
central issue of his election campaign last fall. A major strike
would almost certainly have ruined Schroeder's plans to create jobs
through his ``Alliance for Jobs'' _ a series of round-table talks
between industry, unions and the government. Yet Schroeder could
not afford to alienate unions, which have enormous power in his
Social Democratic Party. Indeed, the new labor minister, Walter
Riester, is the former vice chairman of IG Metall.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   German factory workers earn an average of $30.20 an hour,
according to the Organization for Economic Cooperation and
Development in Paris. That makes them the highest paid in the world
and well ahead of their American counterparts, with an average of
$23.60 an hour.
</P>
<P>
   But the average take-home pay of German workers has been
stagnant for the last three years, after accounting for inflation
and new tax increases. At the same time, productivity for each
worker has soared because of wage restraint and streamlining in
factories. The government estimates that productivity in
manufacturing industries has climbed 7 percent annually over the
last few years.
</P>
<P>
   Union leaders argued that their members were overdue for a
significant raise. ``The industry is earning record profits and
their stocks have increased enormously,'' said Juergen Peters, vice
president of IG Metall. ``The workers have to take part in that, as
well.''
</P>
<P>
   But financial turmoil in Asia, Russia and Latin America has
slowed the economy. Most experts think that growth will not exceed
2 percent this year, down from 2.8 percent in 1998, and that
unemployment will remain around 10 percent.
</P>
<P>
   The last strike by IG Metall was in 1995, when workers in
Bavaria remained off the job for two weeks. Before that, the last
truly big strike lasted seven weeks in 1984 in the states of
Baden-Wuerttemberg and Hesse, which led to a reduction in the
workweek to 35 hours from 37.
</P>
<P>
   Germany's finance minister, Oskar Lafontaine, had argued that
workers were overdue for a raise because wages have lagged well
behind increases in productivity. ``The workers have to receive a
fair share of what they have produced,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But most economists argue that a surge in labor costs would
aggravate unemployment. ``The moderate wage policies in recent
years have brought about an improvement, and they should be
continued,'' said Harmen Lehment of the Institute for World
Economics at the University of Kiel. ``What we don't want to see is
a repeat of 1995, when we had strikes in Bavaria and big wage
increases followed by rising unemployment. The moderate wage
policies in recent years should be continued.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-17-99 2249EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990217.0537 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-17 22:50 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9517 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BOX-TRINIDAD-525&AMP;ADD-     02-17 0728
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOX-TRINIDAD-525&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TRINIDAD: TALE OF THE TAPE OR BATTLE OF THE BULGE? 
</HEADLINE>
  (lh) 
 By TIMOTHY W. SMITH   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   There was speculation during last week's World Boxing Council
welterweight showdown between Oscar De La Hoya and Ike Quartey that
Felix Trinidad, the International Boxing Federation welterweight
champion, weighed as much as 156 pounds with less than two weeks to
go before he climbed into the ring against Pernell Whitaker.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday afternoon, before a news conference to publicize the
fight, Trinidad's father, manager and trainer, Felix Sr., frowned
at the assertion that his son is having trouble making the weight
for Saturday's bout at Madison Square Garden.
</P>
<P>
   ``The official weigh-in is going to be Friday,'' he said. ``If
he goes on the scale, he will weigh in at 147 pounds.''
</P>
<P>
   Trinidad, 26, is coming off a 10-month layoff. When he started
training camp for the Whitaker fight two months ago, he weighed 162
pounds. He is definitely outgrowing the division, but he is trying
to hang in there for the big-money fights.
</P>
<P>
   The last time that Trinidad (33-0) fought in Madison Square
Garden, he weighed 154 pounds, but that was the prescribed weight
for his bout against Troy Waters on Aug. 23, 1997. Trinidad was
supposed to fight Terry Norris for his IBF superwelterweight title.
But Norris backed out of the bout, hoping to get a more lucrative
shot at De La Hoya. Trinidad scored a first-round technical
knockout over Waters. Norris later lost his title to Keith Mullings
and saw his payday against De La Hoya go up in flames.
</P>
<P>
   Now, Trinidad is positioning himself for a lucrative bout
against De La Hoya.
</P>
<P>
   Don King, Trinidad's promoter, attended Wednesday's news
conference after giving a deposition in Mike Tyson's lawsuit
against him.
</P>
<P>
   King issued a challenge to De La Hoya for the winner of the
Whitaker-Trinidad bout. ``We're talking about Oscar De La Hoya's
talent, we're talking about his guts, we're talking about his
machismo,'' King said. ``The man cannot live with himself if he
doesn't meet this challenge.''
</P>
<P>
   A fight with De La Hoya would hold no intrigue for Whitaker,
because he has already faced De La Hoya. Whitaker lost his WBC
title to De La Hoya in a controversial 12-round decision in 1997.
Whitaker still believes he won the fight, and it's difficult to
find anyone who disagrees with him.
</P>
<P>
   But for Trinidad, it would be a golden opportunity to
demonstrate his skills as a boxer and a puncher. His 88 percent
knockout rate (29 knockouts in 33 fights) is one of the highest in
boxing. Trinidad has been insisting upon parity in pay if he meets
De La Hoya, but it's a tough sell, because he can't drive the
promotion. De La Hoya is vastly more popular.
</P>
<P>
   It is difficult to understand why Trinidad is not a more popular
fighter in the United States. He has held his title longer than any
of the current welterweight champions, winning it in 1993 by
knocking out Maurice Blocker in the second round. And his skills
are matchless. But he speaks little English and lives with his
family and spends much of his time at his home in Cupey Alto,
Puerto Rico, where he raises horses. And he hasn't been marketed
the way De La Hoya has.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Trinidad has not been the focus of King's attention. But that
could change now that a potentially lucrative match against De La
Hoya lies ahead.
</P>
<P>
   Last year Trinidad grew frustrated with King, because he didn't
believe King was interested in getting him big fights. So, he filed
a lawsuit against King to get out of his contract and signed a new
deal with Main Events. He was supposed to fight Quartey last
November. But U.S. District Judge Lawrence McKenna ruled against
Trinidad, and the fighter ended up signing a new deal with King.
It's a $49.9 million contract that has a three-fight, four-year
term, but realistically will last as long as Trinidad can fight.
The Whitaker fight is the first under the new deal.
</P>
<P>
   Whitaker is a crafty fighter, who makes his opponents look bad.
Plus, he's a left-hander. Trinidad said he has fought left-handers
before and will be looking to end it quickly.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every fighter wants to end a fight in the quickest way,''
Trinidad said. ``If I hit him with the first punch then I'll try to
end the fight.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
