<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CT-AMATO-SCHOOLS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HARTFORD'S NEW SCHOOL CHIEF PLEDGES TO PUT A LAPTOP IN EVERY
BACKPACK 
</HEADLINE>
  (rk) 
 By MIKE ALLEN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   HARTFORD, Conn. _ The Hartford school system, so troubled that
it has spent the last two years under state control, hired one of
New York City's most innovative educators Wednesday as its eighth
superintendent in 10 years.
</P>
<P>
   The new school chief, Anthony S. Amato, has spent the last 12
years as superintendent of District 6 in upper Manhattan, where he
won a reputation for persuading parents and corporations to help
rescue a poor and crowded district. When he takes office on April
1, he will head a system that has consistently ranked last in
Connecticut.
</P>
<P>
   Like a motivational speaker with Santa's pack on his back, Amato
immediately took the stage Wednesday in the gymnasium at Hartford
High School, which was stripped of its accreditation two years ago,
and pledged to help put a laptop in every backpack, a free Internet
connection in every pupil's home, and a school in each quadrant of
the city that will offer dental, legal and medical services.
</P>
<P>
   ``I guarantee you as I stand here: Hartford will not be last at
this time next year,'' Amato said to a burst of applause. ``And we
will never be last again.'' Promising a busy summer of planning,
purchasing and training, he added: ``You're not going to have to
wait too long. I'm not about waiting.''
</P>
<P>
   In another setting, the many promises and the can-do brashness
might have seemed overbearing, but the words were welcome in a city
where the schools have produced little but embarrassment. ``We
can't aim for No. 1,'' said Ana V. Ortiz, the principal of Betances
Elementary School. ``But we need to aim to get closer.''
</P>
<P>
   Amato, 51, who moves from a district with 28,000 pupils to a
citywide system with 4,000 fewer, is known for his emphasis on
basics, updated with a heavy dollop of technology. When Bill Gates,
the chairman of Microsoft, was looking for a school to visit as he
sought to polish his image last year, he chose a sixth-grade class
at Mott Hall School, in Amato's district.
</P>
<P>
   When Amato arrived in District 6 in 1987, it ranked last in
reading out of New York's 32 local school districts and 23rd in
mathematics. Last year, it had risen to 19th in reading and 13th in
math. Among schools with similar poverty levels, the district
ranked among the top three in recent years.
</P>
<P>
   He imposed a uniform curriculum on all schools in the district,
and established leadership teams of parents and teachers well in
advance of a citywide deadline to do so. And he helped set up six
schools that stay open from 7 a.m. to 10 p.m., providing medical
and educational services not just to students but to their
families.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday, Amato said he planned to bring to Hartford his plan
that provided laptop computers to 3,000 pupils, paid for partly by
their parents and partly by the school district and Microsoft. He
also promised free Internet access to every school family in
Hartford, to allow e-mail between parents and teachers, and the
fetching of research materials online.
</P>
<P>
   Among the ideas Amato said he planned to import from New York
were a six-week summer training program for parents and instruction
in child care that begins ``even before conception.'' In addition,
he said he wanted to help parents with their own educations, from
literacy through master's degree programs.
</P>
</TEXT>
