<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GERMAN-EXECUTION-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GERMANY, CLINTON JOIN DRIVE TO STOP EXECUTION OF 2 BROTHERS IN
ARIZONA 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By MARK SHAFFER  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX _ From President Clinton to Gov. Jane Hull, the German
government is putting on a full court press to try to save the
lives of two brothers scheduled to be executed for a grisly 1982
murder.
</P>
<P>
   German citizens Karl and Walter LaGrand, who were born in
Germany and raised in southern Arizona, are scheduled to go to the
gas chamber at the Arizona State Prison in Florence, Karl next
Wednesday and Walter on March 3, for the 1982 murder of Marana bank
manager Kenneth Hartsock.
</P>
<P>
   That the brothers chose gas for death, given the country's Nazi
Holocaust past, isn't the only thing unusual. Four of the five
German nationals on death rows in U.S. prisons are in Florence.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've gone back decades and decades looking for other German
nationals executed in the U.S. and haven't found any,'' said Jean
Pierre Rollin, Germany's deputy counsel general in Los Angeles.
``Now, we possibly have two in Arizona in the next two weeks.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's very strange. It certainly has raised a lot of attention
in Germany and throughout Europe.''
</P>
<P>
   The other two Germans, brothers Rudi and Michael Apelt, are on
death row at Florence for the 1988 killing of Michael Apelt's
U.S.-born wife in hopes of cashing in on a $400,000 insurance
policy. The only other German death-row inmate is in Florida.
</P>
<P>
   German officials are hoping for the same results as Mexican
diplomats, who were instrumental in getting the death sentence of
double murderer Ramon Martinez-Villareal stayed by the U.S. Supreme
Court in 1997. Efforts by the Honduran government to save the life
of citizen Jose Roberto Villafuerte last April were unsuccessful.
</P>
<P>
   Hull met for 30 minutes with Germany's top two diplomats in the
U.S. on Tuesday about the cases. Top German government officials in
Bonn also have contacted President Clinton, Attorney General Janet
Reno and Secretary of State Madeleine Albright, pleading for
clemency. German representatives of Amnesty International are
planning to file an appeal in the World Court.
</P>
<P>
   A large contingent of German officials and media are expected to
attend Karl LaGrand's hearing before the State Board of Executive
Clemency next Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   From Munich to Hamburg, the media have been saturated in recent
weeks with death-row feature stories about the LaGrand brothers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Gov. Hull listened to all of their concerns,'' said Francie
Noyes, the governor's spokeswoman. ``But one thing in her mind
always is the victim and family members of the victim.''
</P>
<P>
   According to court records, 35-year-old Karl LaGrand was the
third of three illegitimate children from different GI fathers born
to their German mother, Emma, in the small Bavarian city of
Augsburg.
</P>
<P>
   Their mother then married a U.S. Army soldier, who adopted the
children, and the family moved to this country in 1967.
</P>
<P>
   Karl was a troubled child who first got in trouble with the law
at age 9 when he stole $9.69 from a store in Sierra Vista and a
pair of shoes from another store two months later. Emma LaGrand
said that Karl and Walter also set fire to a golf course, which did
$20,000 damage, while the family lived at a military post in Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Karl bounced between home, programs for troubled youths and
juvenile centers until he and Walter were convicted of the armed
robbery of three Tucson supermarkets in a six-day period in 1981.
They both were imprisoned at that point.
</P>
<P>
   ``Karl never wanted to learn. He always got F's in school,''
Emma LaGrand told Pima County probation workers. ``They (Karl and
Walter) liked to run around like dogs. They should be treated like
dogs.''
</P>
<P>
   After their release, the brothers wanted a quick fix for their
money woes.
</P>
<P>
   So, they drove north on Interstate 10 to the Valley National
Bank in Marana at dawn on the morning of Jan. 7, 1982, waiting for
bank personnel to come to work. They brought a briefcase with a
steak knife, bandanas, electrical tape, police radio scanner and
toy gun inside.
</P>
<P>
   Hartsock, the bank manager, showed up a few minutes later and
brought the U.S. and Arizona flags outside to be raised for the
day. Karl pulled the toy gun and ordered him inside the building.
</P>
<P>
   A 20-year-old female teller pulled up a few minutes later. The
two told the LaGrand brothers that they only knew half of the
combination to the safe and that they would have to wait for a
third bank employee to report to work before it could be opened.
Hartsock and the woman were then bound and gagged.
</P>
<P>
   The LaGrands became increasingly anxious as the other employee
failed to show up. Hartsock, believing that Karl LaGrand was about
to attack the woman, kicked him in the shins. A savage response
ensued.
</P>
<P>
   Hartsock's throat was slashed and he suffered 23 other knife
wounds, at least six of which could have been fatal, investigators
said. The woman also was stabbed seven times in the head, side and
shoulder but survived.
</P>
<P>
   Carla Ryan, Karl LaGrand's Tucson attorney, said she thinks she
has ``a good shot'' at getting his death sentence commuted.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was nothing planned. It was just part of a terrible
accident,'' Ryan said. ``When the victim kicked Karl in the leg, he
grabbed a letter opener and just freaked out. They had been about
to give up and leave at that point.''
</P>
<P>
   Ryan also said she hopes the clemency board will consider the
prolonged suffering that inmate Donald Eugene Harding suffered when
he was executed by the use of gas in 1992. Lethal injection has
been used in other executions since that time.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, German press accounts have focused on the veritable
German colony of death-row inmates that has come about at the
Florence prison, noting that the Apelt brothers are only a couple
of cells removed from the LaGrands.
</P>
<P>
   ``Here, everybody goes nuts time and again,'' Karl LaGrand told
one German reporter. &QL; 
Mark Shaffer can be reached at 444-8057 or at
mark.shaffer(at)pni.com via e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-17-99 2252EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
