<SLUG> BC-HKN-ISLES-PENGUINS-430&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ISLANDERS STOP PENGUINS' 10-VICTORY STREAK
</HEADLINE>
   (nk) 
 By TARIK EL-BASHIR  
c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNIONDALE, N.Y. _ Jaromir Jagr and the Pittsburgh Penguins came
to Long Island having won 10 consecutive games, a span that
stretched over 20 days. And it is probably safe to say that no
Penguin fan figured the winning streak, second-longest in the
league this season, would come to an end against the downtrodden
Islanders.
</P>
<P>
   But that is what happened Wednesday night as an inspired
Islanders team outplayed the Penguins on both ends, contained Jagr,
the league's leading scorer, and skated away with an improbable 3-1
victory before 10,148 fans at Nassau Coliseum.
</P>
<P>
   The Islanders controlled the game from the opening minutes
through the final buzzer, playing a physical, defensively
responsible game anchored by Kenny Jonsson and Rich Pilon. Tommy
Salo, the Islander goalie, was solid with 20 saves and just missed
earning his sixth shutout of the season. But perhaps, most
important for Islander fans, the offense managed to score timely
goals.
</P>
<P>
   Robert Reichel scored the Islanders' first goal in the second
period off a rebound, and then Mark Lawrence and Trevor Linden
scored in the third period to secure the victory by the
second-worst team in the Eastern Conference over the third-best
team.
</P>
<P>
   Kip Miller scored the Penguin goal with only 2 minutes 6 seconds
left in the game. Jagr got an assist on the goal.
</P>
<P>
   Lawrence's goal came on a redirection of a centering pass off
Jiri Slegr's leg and past Peter Skudra, the Penguin goaltender.
Linden put the game out of the Penguins' reach midway in the third
period, also off a rebound.
</P>
<P>
   The Islanders matched the Penguins' effort and intensity early
in the game and were rewarded. After a scoreless opening period,
the Islanders cranked it up a notch and scored the only goal in the
second period.
</P>
<P>
   Reichel chipped in a rebound at 12:24 to give the Islanders a
1-0 lead. Zigmund Palffy took the first shot, and Reichel was in
front of Skudra to backhand the puck underneath the crossbar.
</P>
<P>
   The Islanders kept Jagr and the rest of the Penguins'
league-leading offense under wraps through two periods. Jagr, who
leads the National Hockey League in scoring, has 27 goals and 59
assists in 53 games and is favored to win his third league scoring
title in five seasons. During the Penguins' streak, Jagr had 26
points, with 6 games of 3 points or more.
</P>
<P>
   Jagr gave the Penguins a scare in the second period when he got
up grimacing after he was slashed on the hand by Pilon. Jagr
immediately shook off his glove and skated to the bench. He
returned to the game a few minutes later.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Jagr said recently he and other elite players who rely on speed
and finesse were benefiting from the league's crackdown this season
on holding, clutching and grabbing. For years, those tactics have
allowed marginally talented players to pull down the quality of
play.
</P>
<P>
   Jagr's leadership has also been more of a factor this season.
Having succeeded Ron Francis as the Penguins' captain, he is more
vocal in the locker room and on the bench. And many of his
teammates say that his leadership has rallied the team.
</P>
<P>
   He may have the most points, but Jagr is not the only player
behind the Penguins' success. Since moving to Jagr's line, Miller
has 11 goals and 18 points in the last 12 games. Martin Straka,
another former Islander, has 24 goals and 33 assists and made the
All-Star team this season. And Aleksei Kovalev, who was traded from
the Rangers for Petr Nedved two and a half months ago, has 18 goals
since joining the Penguins.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
