<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AMWEST-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLOCK BEGINS TICKING TO AVERT STRIKE AGAINST AMERICA WEST 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By DAWN GILBERTSON AND PETER CORBETT  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX _ With America West jets taking off every few minutes in
the background, the airline's flight attendants on Wednesday
started a countdown to a strike that would ground flights at a few
minutes' notice.
</P>
<P>
   The clock on the federally mandated 30-day cooling-off period
between management and the Association of Flight Attendants union
has started ticking and officially ends at 10 p.m. Arizona time on
March 19, a Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Unless a contract agreement is reached by then _ something both
sides say they will strive for in stepped-up talks over pay issues
_ the union will start its long-threatened CHAOS campaign.
</P>
<P>
   An alternative to a total walkout, CHAOS stands for Create Havoc
Around our System and involves intermittent walkouts.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can design it any way we want to,'' Bill McGlashen,
president of the AFA Council 66 at America West, said in announcing
the strike countdown at Sky Harbor International Airport.
</P>
<P>
   ``It can be one-hour strikes here and there. It could be strikes
on flights headed to the East Coast, or flights heading to the West
Coast. A two-day shutdown. A four-day shutdown.''
</P>
<P>
   America West won't know what's on tap until it gets a call from
a union official saying that flight attendants won't be staffing
certain flights, McGlashen said. That could occur as little as 15
minutes before takeoff, he said. Flight attendants will not walk
off any flights after they have boarded, however, because that
would be illegal.
</P>
<P>
   America West, Sky Harbor's busiest carrier, with 214 daily
departures, could opt to shut down entirely to avoid a string of
last-minute surprises for customers.
</P>
<P>
   CHAOS ``may require AWA to shut down its operations and furlough
many of its employees in order to protect our customers from
service disruptions,'' Richard Goodmanson, president and chief
operating officer, said in a memo to employees last Friday.
</P>
<P>
   The notice about possible layoffs, which the airline said could
occur as early as March 15, is required by the Worker Adjustment
and Retraining Notification Act.
</P>
<P>
   A strike, which would hit in the peak of the Valley's tourist
season, would come after four years of often tense negotiations
between the two sides. A tentative contract was overwhelmingly
rejected by the flight attendants in December 1997.
</P>
<P>
   Other offers have been bandied about, but union leaders say
America West's offer is $16.5 million less than what they are
seeking for the 2,400 America West flight attendants. Over a
five-year contract, that amounts to $3.3 million a year in salary
that divides the two sides.
</P>
<P>
   The union wants to increase top salaries from about $22,000
annually to $32,000.
</P>
<P>
   America West says on average its flight attendants are paid
$22,856 annually for about 29 hours per week of work, which does
not include their time for layovers or overnight stays.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not here because we want to get rich and we have dollar
signs in our eyes,'' McGlashen said. ``We're here because we want a
fair, reasonable agreement. That's what the union has on the table.
What the company has on the table . . . doesn't recognize the
sacrifices that employees have made'' since the carrier's
bankruptcy reorganization in 1994.
</P>
<P>
   Travelers will hear plenty from the flight attendants in the
next few weeks.
</P>
<P>
   Beginning Friday at the Camelback Esplanade in Phoenix, the
union will hand out pamphlets warning of the strike and the union's
position. The campaign will continue with meetings with companies
that book a lot of travel on America West, as well as students
planning spring break trips.
</P>
<P>
   The union is calling it an educational campaign, but the intent
is clear: Get the public to put more pressure on America West
management to settle.
</P>
<P>
   No negotiations are now scheduled, McGlashen said, but the plan
is to have non-stop talks to reach an agreement.
</P>
<P>
   America West concurred.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our Number One goal is to reach a fair and responsible
agreement with the flight attendants and avoid any disruption of
service to our customers,'' Greg Garger, vice president of labor
relations, said in a statement. ``We are hopeful we will achieve
that over the next 30 days.
</P>
<P>
   A settlement would be welcome news to the Valley's tourist
industry and the throngs of travelers who live here and help make
America West the top airline at Sky Harbor International Airport,
with about 42 percent of the market.
</P>
<P>
   The strike would start the weekend that the NCAA West Regional
mens basketball tournament is to be played at America West Arena.
Games are scheduled March 18 and March 20. Also that weekend is the
LPGA Standard Register Ping golf tournament.
</P>
<P>
   There would be 10 days of spring training baseball games left, a
couple of big conventions, and countless vacations scheduled at the
Valley's resorts and hotels.
</P>
<P>
   For local travelers, it could disrupt spring break plans,
business trips and, possibly, Easter vacations. &QL; 
Dawn Gilbertson may be reached at 444-8617 or at
dawn.gilbertson(at)pni.com via e-mail. &QL; 
Peter Corbett can be reached at 444-4815 or at
peter.corbett(at)pni.com via e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
