<HEADER>
A9686 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NJ-TROOPERS-INQUIRY-5     02-17 0866
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NJ-TROOPERS-INQUIRY-520&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
U.S. LOOKS AT RACIAL PROFILING IN N.J. 
</HEADLINE>
  (nk) 
 By DAVID KOCIENIEWSKI   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   TRENTON, N.J. _ Federal civil rights officials disclosed
Wednesday that they have been investigating the New Jersey State
Police for more than two years to determine whether troopers
illegally target black motorists on state highways.
</P>
<P>
   Responding to requests from defense lawyers, black leaders and
even some troopers, Justice Department officials acknowledged that
they have been conducting a ``pattern and practice'' investigation
focusing on so-called racial profiling _ the tactic of stopping
motorists not because they are breaking the law, but solely because
of the color of their skin.
</P>
<P>
   The inquiry was apparently spawned by a 1996 court case in which
a state judge ruled that troopers in southern New Jersey had indeed
targeted motorists using race-based profiles.
</P>
<P>
   Calls for a federal investigation grew last year after state
troopers patrolling the New Jersey Turnpike shot at a van carrying
three black men and one Hispanic man, wounding three of them, but
federal officials never publicly acknowledged that such an inquiry
was already under way.
</P>
<P>
   Investigators from the Justice Department's civil rights
division have reviewed troopers' arrest reports, court testimony
about tactics used on the force, statistical breakdowns of police
activity and a variety of training and procedural manuals,
according to a law enforcement official who spoke on the condition
of anonymity.
</P>
<P>
   Under the federal pattern and practice law, if Justice
Department attorneys find convincing evidence that troopers engaged
in discriminatory behavior, the government can file a suit against
the State Police and ask a judge to order reforms. But Christine
DiBartolo, a spokeswoman for the civil rights division, said it was
still unclear when the Justice Department would decide whether to
pursue a suit.
</P>
<P>
   ``All I can say is we've been looking at this department for
some time now,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Gov. Christie Whitman has denounced racial profiling as illegal,
and vowed that she would not tolerate such tactics. Faced with
rising complaints, this month she ordered state Attorney General
Peter Verniero to review the force's practices, but as recently as
Tuesday she spoke of a federal investigation as only a possibility,
rather than as a process already well under way.
</P>
<P>
   Verniero expressed surprise Wednesday that federal officials had
described their actions as an investigation, because he had
considered his dealings with the Justice Department to be part of a
routine, cooperative assessment, he said. ``If this is an
investigation, I'd like to know when we'll find out the results,''
he said. ``But whether or not the Justice Department ratchets this
up to an investigation, I have an obligation to carry out my own
review.''
</P>
<P>
   He said he expected to finish his assessment within four months.
</P>
<P>
   But many defense lawyers and civil rights advocates objected to
the choice of Verniero to assess the state police agency because
his office is defending the state police in an appeal of the 1996
court decision, which found that some troopers routinely practiced
racial profiling.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The political and legal controversy over racial profiling was
rekindled after the shootings in April. Troopers fired 11 shots at
the four unarmed men inside the van.
</P>
<P>
   In recent months, three current and former troopers have filed
lawsuits alleging that they were forced to target black motorists
in an effort to raise their arrest and gun seizure statistics and
the agency's as well. Early this month, The Star-Ledger of Newark
reported that during the first two months of 1997, blacks made up
75 percent of the people arrested by troopers on the N.J. Turnpike.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, a group of influential black ministers and the
National Association for the Advancement of Colored People asked
U.S. Attorney General Janet Reno to intervene, saying they did not
trust the state to investigate its own police force. The ministers
also called for the dismissal of Col. Carl A. Williams, the state
police superintendent, saying he could not correct the problem
because he has refused to acknowledge mounting evidence that racial
profiling has been encouraged or tolerated by troopers for years.
</P>
<P>
   Williams, who has steadfastly denied that troopers engage in
profiling, said he had no intention of resigning. He said he was
already directing a variety of policy changes to improve relations
with members of N.J.'s minority groups and to recruit more blacks
and Hispanic people to the force.
</P>
<P>
   But Jeffrey Wintner, the public defender who won the 1996 ruling
that first established the existence of racial profiling, said he
was surprised that federal authorities had not already taken
action. Wintner was contacted by investigators from the Justice
Department's civil rights division in late 1996 and has provided
them with information on several subsequent occasions.
</P>
<P>
   ``This has all been sitting there for years, out in the open, in
public,'' he said. ``Something has to be done.''
</P>
</TEXT>
