<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SKI-SKIING-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUY OR RENT? SKIERS MUST DECIDE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ART BENTLEY  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   BIG BEAR LAKE, Calif. _ To buy or not to buy? It would perplex
even Hamlet if he were weighing the options of buying or renting a
pair of skis.
</P>
<P>
   Given the changes in the past three years in shape, length and
design of boards, especially those in the high-performance
categories favored by advanced skiers that can exceed $700 a pair,
it's a fair question. And it becomes even more relevant to a skier
who logs no more than a few days on the mountain a year but
appreciates and wants to use the latest top-of-the-line equipment.
</P>
<P>
   There are sound economic reasons for renting premium ``demo''
skis for a few outings a year. At Bear Mountain, for example, such
a pair will cost $28 per day. Nearby ski shops charge up to $30.
</P>
<P>
   Similar rates prevail at other resorts and customers without
skies of their own willingly pay them. Simple arithmetic reveals
that five days on skis at $28 a day will cost $140; 10 days, $280.
</P>
<P>
   And skiers can experiment with a different set every day,
experiencing the effects of variable sidecuts, lengths, widths and
flex patterns. These characteristics determine how a ski performs _
whether it makes long-radius turns, for example, or short, tight
arcs. How readily it carves when tipped on edge. Whether it's
responsive, snappy and precise underfoot, or quick from edge to
edge, or floats in powder or blasts through crud. Or whether it's
stable or erratic at speed.
</P>
<P>
   If a skier spends $140 per year on demo skis, it would take five
years to eat up the cash needed to purchase that $700 pair he was
eyeing. At the rate technology and design have been changing
recently, that new pair could have long since become obsolete.
</P>
<P>
   Jim Bollingmo, owner of Alpine Sports Center in Big Bear Lake,
sees ``a bit of a trend'' toward renting instead of buying high-end
skis. However, he does not consider it a threat to the financial
health of his store, which, like most similar enterprises, is
primarily in business to sell equipment.
</P>
<P>
   ``Somebody who skis five times a year can ski on the latest and
greatest and never have to own,'' Bollingmo said. ``It's a concern
but it's not something that's been a huge alarm to me yet.''
</P>
<P>
   Demo skis, as the term suggests, are intended to demonstrate a
ski's attributes and help renters decide what boards to buy.
Typically, shops will deduct some of the rental charges from the
purchase price. Sports Limited in Woodland Hills, for instance,
which charges $30 for the day to rent demos and $10 per day
thereafter, will knock $40 off the price tag.
</P>
<P>
   But some shop personnel maintain there also is a significant
disadvantage to relying exclusive on a variety of rentals. They
contend that skiers who choose this course never find a ski upon
which they're comfortable because it takes time to become fully
accustomed to a ski's traits _ a comfort level that usually comes
with the purchase of a pair.
</P>
<P>
   Also, there's a convenience factor. Many people ski at very busy
times _ weekends and holidays _ when there is a greater risk the
ski they prefer is unavailable. Or they have to wait for it to be
returned. If the waiting is done at the hill, that cuts into ski
time, which does not come cheap.
</P>
<P>
   Lenny Rosenberg at Sports Limited has a word of caution for
those who expect skis to change significantly in design.
</P>
<P>
   ``What people don't realize is that skis are not going to change
that much more in shape because it costs the industry so much to
keep putting new designs out there,'' Rosenberg said.
</P>
<P>
   Yet few would argue the value of trying before buying _ and ski
resorts try to make it easy. At Snow Summit, skiers can step into
as many Rossignol models as they wish during a two-hour period for
$5. Bear Mountain offers the same terms on Dynastar skis during a
four-hour period for $15.
</P>
<P>
   Russ Blevins, proprietor of Skyline Ski and Sports in Big Bear
Lake, offers a sound suggestion for those planning to compare the
performance of different skis: Use only one pair of boots.
</P>
<P>
   ``All you want is one variable, and that should be the skis,''
he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
