<HEADER>
A9688 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TEX-LEGIS-UTMONEY18-C     02-17 0938
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEX-LEGIS-UTMONEY18-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Lawmakers: Big budget increase for UT unlikely
 &HT;    By A. Phillips Brooks
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Some key Texas lawmakers, citing lavish athletic
spending and other budget priorities, say the University of Texas
System stands little chance of getting the $85 million in
additional state aid it is seeking for staff pay raises and
recruitment programs.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think it will happen,'' said Rep. Rob Junell (D-San
Angelo), chairman of the budget-writing House Appropriations
Committee.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think they generate much outside support for their
cause,'' Junell said Wednesday. ``What (the public) sees is the
football stadium, the football coach and some of the excesses that
occur on the college campuses.''
</P>
<P>
   Junell's sentiment was echoed this week by several lawmakers
reviewing UT's budget request, which is six times more than the $14
million increase that budget writers recommended in state aid for
the 2000-01 budget years.
</P>
<P>
   Last session, lawmakers allocated $600 million in new state aid
to Texas public colleges and universities.
</P>
<P>
   This time, however, UT's all-out pitch for more money by its top
brass _ including UT System Chancellor William Cunningham and
UT-Austin President Larry Faulkner _ is being heavily scrutinized
by lawmakers, who are questioning whether the university should
divert some of its athletic gate receipts to academic programs
instead of relying so heavily on state aid.
</P>
<P>
   ``You depend on the state dollars for recruiting students when
you have access to millions,'' said Sen. Carlos Truan (D-Corpus
Christi). ``Why can't you use the dollars from the ticket sales of
the football games? Is there a constitutional clause that prevents
that?''
</P>
<P>
   Limiting UT's budget increase to $14 million would hit the
university hard, said Faulkner. He told lawmakers UT needs at least
$66 million over the two-year budget cycle to provide pay raises
for graduate assistants, staff and faculty. He also wants to
finance recruitment programs and other ``essential needs,''
including hiring new faculty to help reduce student-to-faculty
ratios to about 23 students to one instructor.
</P>
<P>
   Along with the Legislative Budget Board's proposed $14 million
in additional state aid, UT-Austin would gain another $12 million
from tuition increases, for a total of $26 million from state and
tuition sources. But Faulkner said if the current budget proposal
were adopted, UT would be $40 million in the hole.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the shortfall, Faulkner said UT would finance $56
million in pay raises, including a 10 percent hike for graduate
assistants, 6 percent for staff and 4 percent for faculty. The
shortfall would be covered by ``freezing or severely limiting
hiring,'' a move that would drive up class sizes.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have to fund them,'' he said of the pay raises.
</P>
<P>
   Salaries of about 12,000 nonteaching staff at UT _ everyone from
janitors to student advisers and research technicians _ have been
an issue for years. The UT University Staff Association plans to
protest pay scales at the Capitol today.
</P>
<P>
   Reports last year said nine of 10 UT staff members were paid
below the Austin market average. Some full-time workers make as
little as $14,000 a year.
</P>
<P>
   Under the recommended budget, UT is not the only university that
would feel the pinch. The Legislative Budget Board is recommending
that the public university system receive $4.1 billion for the
upcoming two-year budget cycle. That is about $1.2 billion less
than university leaders want.
</P>
<P>
   Cunningham and five other university chancellors cited data that
showed Texas will enroll about 9,000 new students annually in
colleges and universities. The $1.2 billion, which includes about
$200 million for scholarships and grants, is needed to help bring
Texas up to the national average in enrolling students in and
graduating them from college.
</P>
<P>
   ``All we are asking is to reach the national average,''
Cunningham said.
</P>
<P>
   The chances of getting $1.2 billion? ``None,'' replied Junell.
</P>
<P>
   Pleas for money are being drowned out by more pressing budget
priorities, including tax cuts and new money for public education
proposed by Gov. George W. Bush. Bush has pledged to cut property
taxes by $2 billion, other taxes by about $500,000, and to increase
funding for public schools by $1 billion.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Bill Ratliff, chairman of the Senate Finance Committee,
said it will be difficult to provide significant increases to
higher education in light of those priorities.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think higher education is on the bubble, meaning that
they're funding competes directly with tax cuts,'' said Ratliff.
</P>
<P>
   Cunningham said UT-Austin would fall farther behind other
flagships, such as the University of California at Berkeley, in
attracting quality faculty and reducing class sizes if UT-Austin
does not receive significantly more than budget writers recommend.
</P>
<P>
   Truan and some other lawmakers questioned UT's commitment to
recruiting African-American and Hispanic students who are not
involved in collegiate athletics, and the school's need for the
money in light of spending on coaches salaries and athletic
facilities. Junell said enrollment has remained flat at UT for
several years.
</P>
<P>
   Figures provided by Junell show UT's enrollment declined, from
50,245 students in 1990 to 48,917 this fall. Meanwhile, full-time
employees rose from 12,310 to 13,092 during that same period. At
the same time, state aid rose from about $250 million in 1990 to
about about $317 million in 1999.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
