<SLUG> BC-HKN-DEVILS-LIGHTNING-325&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EVERYBODY GETS INTO THE ACT FOR THE DEVILS
</HEADLINE>
   (nk) 
 By STEVE POPPER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   EAST RUTHERFORD, N.J. _ As the minutes ticked down Wednesday
night, the Devils continued to score goals as if they were in a
practice drill, the game with the Tampa Bay Lightning reduced to a
series of celebrations.
</P>
<P>
   The Devils could forget the woes that have been plaguing them on
home ice as they rolled to a 7-1 triumph at Continental Arena. That
a lot of teams get healthy on the Lightning, the worst team in the
National Hockey League, could neither diminish the moment nor sour
the mood. For one night, the Devils could forget the way their
longest homestand of the season began and just enjoy the ending.
</P>
<P>
   Goals by Brendan Morrison and Jay Pandolfo in the final four
minutes capped a game in which seven Devils scored in their most
lopsided victory of the season. The outburst gave New Jersey 16
goals in its last three games, two victories and a tie. But even
the Devils know that those numbers may not be enough to send the
team into the post-season intact.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the ease of Wednesday night's victory, the Devils
struggled to a 2-3-1 record on the homestand. But they improved
their record at home against Tampa Bay to 14-1-1.
</P>
<P>
   The Devils scored three times in the first period against former
Devil goaltender Corey Schwab. Schwab, who was 0-3-0 with the
Devils, fell to 0-6-0 against them.
</P>
<P>
   Sergei Brylin started the scoring for the Devils just 1 minute
16 seconds into the game, slipping a shot from the right circle
past Schwab. Denis Pederson and Jason Arnott scored within 51
seconds of each other later in the period.
</P>
<P>
   When the Lightning pulled Schwab and replaced him with Bill
Ranford to start the second period, Tampa Bay quickly got a lift,
scoring on a steal and breakaway by Benoit Hogue at 1:05.
</P>
<P>
   But Petr Sykora answered with a goal at 4:26 on a blast from
just inside the blue line, and Scott Niedermayer scored on a pretty
feed from Brylin at 9:21 to give the Devils a 5-1 lead.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   There has been conjecture that the Devils will try to make a
deal before the March 23 trading deadline to bolster their offense
for the stretch run. They have made that kind of move in previous
seasons, acquiring Neal Broten, Doug Gilmour and Dave Andreychuk,
all within a month of the deadline.
</P>
<P>
   What the Devils could be searching for _ a veteran offensive
talent _ may be right under their noses and ready to join them in
the form of Andreychuk, a 35-year-old left wing.
</P>
<P>
   After a two-day hospital stay to be treated for an infection
that resulted from surgery on his fractured right ankle, Andreychuk
returned to the ice Wednesday for the morning workout. Andreychuk
hopes to make a surprisingly quick return to the lineup. He
fractured the ankle on Jan. 5 and underwent surgery three days
later to have seven pins inserted.
</P>
<P>
   Andreychuk missed his 20th game Wednesday night, but he is
hoping that the ankle does not swell so he can practice on Thursday
and return to the lineup either Friday in Detroit or Saturday at
home against the Islanders. The original prognosis called for him
to miss as many as 10 weeks.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel a lot better than I did before I went in the
hospital,'' Andreychuk said. ``But I did lose some days skating, so
I'm going to need a couple more days of skating. As far as I know,
I'm going to Detroit.''
</P>
<P>
   While Andreychuk will give the ankle its next test in Thursday's
practice, he could have taken the ice Wednesday night and got a
workout no rougher than what assistant coach Vyacheslav Fetisov put
him through in the morning as he skated with a few teammates and
Coach Robbie Ftorek's 14-year-old son, Casey.
</P>
</TEXT>
