<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-NISSAN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TIMING, MONEY ATTRACT STARS TO NISSAN
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DAVE SHELBURNE  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ The Nissan Open begins today at Riviera Country
Club with a $2.8 million purse and the best field in the 73-year
history of the tournament.
</P>
<P>
   Seven players ranked in the current world top-10, headed by the
dynamic 1-2 duo of Tiger Woods and David Duval, are on hand.
Twenty-eight others who will join those seven in next week's 64-man
World Match Play Championship at La Costa also are entered.
</P>
<P>
   Many in those two groups have contributed to this year's Nissan
being able to field 22 major winners _ including reigning titlists
Lee Janzen (U.S. Open) and Vijay Singh (PGA Championship).
</P>
<P>
   The best measure of the '99 Nissan depth might be that it could
absorb the late loss of two recent British Open champions _ Tom
Lehman and John Daly withdrew on Monday _ and still have so much
star power remaining.
</P>
<P>
   That depth is partly the result of timing and money _ with a
combined $7.8 million available this week and next, $1.5 million
just to the winners. But one of golf's most-respected players
thinks the quality of this field also has much to do with history.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a very good field and, to me, it's a compliment to the
golf course,'' Ryder Cup captain Ben Crenshaw said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a different place, a unique place. It's meant a lot to
our tour, a lot to our golf history. There's been a great legacy
left behind here by Ben Hogan, Byron Nelson, Lloyd Mangrum. . . .
Everybody that has been a great player on tour has played here and
in Los Angeles. A lot of people would love to win here.''
</P>
<P>
   This week's favorites have to include Woods, 23, and Duval, 27,
whose brilliant play is bringing back memories of the Jack
Nicklaus-Arnold Palmer rivalry of the 1960s and '70s.
</P>
<P>
   Although neither has played as many as five full seasons (Duval
joined the tour in '95, Woods late in '96), the two already have
combined for 17 wins, nine by Duval.
</P>
<P>
   Woods broke out of an 11-month victory drought last week at the
Buick Invitational in San Diego, but he had been playing well much
of that time.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just hadn't won,'' said the world's top-ranked player, who
started his career with six wins in less than his first full year,
including a record 12-stroke victory at the 1997 Masters.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was very pleased with the progress I'd made. I just needed
to be patient. That's just part of the game. It's just a matter of
time.''
</P>
<P>
   Other prominent names this week include defending champion Billy
Mayfair, who edged Woods in a playoff in last year's Nissan at
Valencia Country Club, and recent champions Corey Pavin, Craig
Stadler and Fred Couples.
</P>
<P>
   What that latter trio has in common besides Nissan trophies is a
long time on tour _ something that comes into play often in the
winner's circle at Riviera.
</P>
<P>
   Pavin, 39, one of only four players _ with MacDonald Smith, Ben
Hogan and Palmer _ to win consecutive Nissans (1994-95), benefited
from course knowledge gained playing Riviera in his UCLA days.
</P>
<P>
   Course familiarity also paid off for 1996 Nissan champ Stadler,
45. The well-aging Walrus from USC who was third at Pebble Beach
two weeks ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've played (Riviera) a zillion times,'' Stadler said at last
week's Buick Invitational, where he included a round of 65 in a
26th-place finish. ``I know it pretty well and always seem to play
well there.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The old guys, you see them doing well,'' said Bob Burns, the
30-year-old former Cal State Northridge star back on tour after
winning last year's Nike Tour Championship and money title.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a traditional old course and there are guys that have
been coming out here for 20 years. Freddie likes this course.''
</P>
<P>
   Does he ever.
</P>
<P>
   Couples, hardly old but no longer one of the young whiz kids
despite his youthful appearance (the 1992 Masters champ will turn
40 in October), doubts he'll ever pass up a chance to play at
Riviera if he's healthy.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's one of the best courses we play on tour,'' said the man
who won the Nissan at Riviera in 1990 and '92 and finished second
twice there in the last five years.
</P>
<P>
   Couples likes the way the course suits his left-to-right game,
he loves the small greens and he really appreciates the way the
fans support him _ boisterous roars of ``Boom-Boom'' echoing
through the eucalyptus trees are an annual rite of winter at the
wind-buffeted Pacific Palisades course.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't veer too far away from events where I play well,''
Couples said, ``and I don't know how you can get a better course
for a PGA Tour event.''
</P>
<P>
   Crenshaw, who has been coming to Riviera almost annually every
year since 1974, agrees with that.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been a great part of our tour,'' he said. ``This course
is a challenge.''
</P>
<P>
   And this week, it seems, Riviera has a field equipped for the
challenge.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
