<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-CROUSE-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HARD TO JUSTIFY STIPEND FOR PGA PLAYERS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KAREN CROUSE  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PACIFIC PALISADES _ Starting today, Ben E. Fits is guaranteed
two trips around one of Southern California's loveliest layouts. A
clubhouse buffet, a courtesy car and four clubhouse badges come
with this E-ticket (can you say elitist?) ride through Riviera
Country Club, the course that George C. Thomas designed and Ben
Hogan deified.
</P>
<P>
   Housing doesn't have to be a hassle. There are plenty of people
in Brentwood and Beverly Hills willing to swing open their doors to
Ben E. Fits for nothing more than a couple of tournament badges
and/or the pleasure of his company. Well, that and a few chipping
tips.
</P>
<P>
   If he gets hungry for a sumptuous feast, Ben E. Fits can cover a
week's worth of dinner tabs at the Hotel Bel-Air simply by agreeing
to swing some manufacturer's club or tee up its ball.
</P>
<P>
   About the only thing Ben E. Fits can't summon with the snap of
his fingers is a paycheck. He has to earn that by shooting a
36-hole score that's lower than roughly half the 144-man Nissan
Open field. As far as performance curves go, that sure beats Mr.
Johnson's 12th-grade calculus class.
</P>
<P>
   To be sure, Ben E. Fits has it a whole lot better than a lot of
working stiffs. That would include his caddy, who works dawn to
dusk all week as a greens guru/golden retriever/scapegoat and is
guaranteed only about $800 for his toil and trouble; more if his
man makes the weekend cut.
</P>
<P>
   It doesn't take a victory to raise Ben E. Fits' standard of
living. Goodness gracious, no. In 1998, Bruce Lietzke played in 10
tournaments and earned $377,188. Next to his schedule, commercial
airline pilots, with their 15-hour work weeks and six-figure
salaries, do have room to gripe.
</P>
<P>
   Then there's Doug Martin, who mustered one top-10 finish (a tie
for seventh) in 33 events last year and earned $301,718. Think
that's incredible? Consider this: There were 101 golfers who made
more than Martin and seven of them surpassed the $1 million mark
without the benefits of a win.
</P>
<P>
   Heaven knows there's a lot more gold where that pot came from.
Tournament prize money on the PGA Tour has risen from $96 million
in 1998 to $134 million this year. There are people (accountants
and personal managers, mostly) bracing right now for the
possibility that David Duval or Tiger Woods will surpass the $4
million mark, which is a few thousand dollars more than Arnold
Palmer has earned in official prize money in 45 years as a
professional.
</P>
<P>
   It's a Fantasy Island for those equipped to swim with the
sharks. For those who aren't, there's Ben E. Fits' bail-out plan,
as championed by at least four dozen PGA Tour professionals.
</P>
<P>
   Ben E. Fits and Co. think the PGA Tour ought to throw a lifeline
to those golfers who miss the cut every week to help them tread
water until their ship comes in. A $2,000 stipend has been
suggested for those who are victimized by their own missed putts,
scattershot drives and/or leaden iron shots.
</P>
<P>
   If Ben E. Fits had any say in it, Chip Beck would have earned
$68,866 in 1998. As it was, Beck, a former U.S. Ryder Cup team
member, took home $10,866 after making two cuts in 29 tournaments.
That was better than the $10,653 he earned in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   Woods said Wednesday that Beck deserves to be compensated for
his time and trouble.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was good enough to earn his card,'' he pointed out. ``He
just happened to go through a dry spell.''
</P>
<P>
   Before the drought, Beck's career had been marked by El Nino
conditions. In his first 18 years on the Tour, Beck earned more
than $5.9 million. If two arid seasons have parched Beck's savings,
he doesn't need financial compensation, he needs new financial
advisers.
</P>
<P>
   What Ben E. Fits and his cohorts are conveniently forgetting is
that a large part of the appeal of the PGA Tour to its sponsors is
its overt capitalism.
</P>
<P>
   Because they can't get the guaranteed contracts that turn a lot
of hungry baseball, football and basketball players into complacent
multimillionaires, golfers are looked upon kindly by Corporate
America. They're viewed as characters straight out of a Horatio
Alger story, starting every year with nothing and gaining success
through their own goodness and courage.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tattered Tom (Byrum)'', anyone?
</P>
<P>
   Or how about ``Ragged Dick (Mast)''?
</P>
<P>
   Ben Crenshaw, the captain of this year's U.S. Ryder Cup team,
has been on the PGA Tour since 1973, long enough to remember
``rabbit'' qualifying on Mondays and $185,000 tournament purses.
</P>
<P>
   For any of their colleagues to call for the deconstruction of a
framework that so many PGA Tour veterans worked tooth and nail to
hammer out, ``is a lot for players who have played so long to
swallow,'' Crenshaw said.
</P>
<P>
   If that's the case, those same players must have choked on
Stiles Mitchell's words. Mitchell, a Nike Tour player whose length
off the tee is John Daly-esque, recently ripped the disparity
between the purses in the Nike and PGA Tours.
</P>
<P>
   If Mitchell thinks a $75,000 gain at the year's end is unworthy
of his talents, perhaps he should pursue a club pro's position
(there are over 300 courses in California alone). Then let us see
if he's so quick to pop off. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-17-99 2325EST &QL; 
