<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-REEVES-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SOUTH TEXAS WOULD BE FINE HOME FOR SPRING TRAINING
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JIM REEVES 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The sultry breezes of South Florida beckon. It's a siren song
I've happily answered every spring for almost a quarter of a
century.
</P>
<P>
   But I'd trade that Jimmy Buffet melody in an Okeechobee minute
for a new spring-training frontier in South Texas, and it's time
for Rangers president Tom Schieffer to quit tantalizing us with the
prospect and make it happen.
</P>
<P>
   Schieffer is guilty of two very large mistakes, and we're not
going to let him forget them.
</P>
<P>
   First, he showed what a can-do guy he is by overseeing the
architectural development and construction of The Ballpark in
Arlington, arguably the finest facility of its kind in the world.
</P>
<P>
   Second, he happened to mention maybe three years ago that he
could someday envision South Texas as a new spring-training mecca
for major-league teams who are discovering that Florida and Arizona
are not the ideal situations they once were, now that baseball has
located teams in Miami and Tampa-St. Pete and another in Phoenix.
</P>
<P>
   I say he's a visionary. I say it's time to turn his fantasy
island into reality. And I'm more than willing to play the little
guy that runs around screaming, ``De plane, Boss! De plane!'' to
Schieffer's Mr. Roarke.
</P>
<P>
   Just do it, Tom. And quit wasting time.
</P>
<P>
   If owner Tom Hicks was smart _ and if he was any smarter he'd be
running this country (another idea that might need developing) _
he'd snap his fingers, tell Schieffer to pack his golf clubs and
head due south, and don't come back until he has a concrete plan in
place for developing a new spring-training venue right here in his
home state.
</P>
<P>
   I guarantee you, Schieffer can and would get it done.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need to focus on it, and I'm not sure we don't need to get
something started,'' Schieffer said with the Rangers'
spring-training camp in Port Charlotte opening today. ``I would
like to do it. It makes a lot of sense.''
</P>
<P>
   It makes all the sense in the world.
</P>
<P>
   With the Devil Rays and Marlins in Florida and the Diamondbacks
in Phoenix, the magic of spring training has lost some of its
allure to fans in Florida and Arizona. Many are retirees on fixed
incomes. If they're going to see baseball, they reason, why not
save their money for games that really mean something?
</P>
<P>
   Suddenly, baseball is in danger of overexposure in those two
states. That's why South Texas makes so much sense, especially for
the Rangers and Astros, who can further develop fans and an
intrastate rivalry by sharing spring-training headquarters.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think, to make it work, it would take at least six teams
committing to the plan,'' Schieffer said.
</P>
<P>
   So start lining them up. South Texas is ready.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hidaglo and Cameron County have gone together to form a sports
authority under the auspices of the Brimer Bill,'' said Cullen
Looney, an Edinburg attorney who once served in the legislature
with Schieffer. ``We have the structure to work with, and that
board has been appointed.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're in the midst of having a feasibility study done. That's
kind of the next step we're going through, and I think it's going
to come back with a recommendation to move forward and pointing out
ways to get it done. We have a meeting scheduled next week.''
</P>
<P>
   Schieffer envisions three spring-training ballparks, complete
with practice facilities for major- and minor-league teams, being
built in the Brownsville-Harlingen-Weslaco-McAllen-Edinburg-Mission
geographical area. The furthest distance, from Brownsville to
Mission, is about 70 miles.
</P>
<P>
   ``You're talking about, by the year 2000, having 1 million
people in a four-county area,'' Looney said, ``and that doesn't
count Mexico. There are probably 2 \Rmillion\S to 3 million people
right across the border, and Monterrey's only about 150 miles
south.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think this would be a great industry for the Valley.''
</P>
<P>
   One major roadblock, a familiar one, stands in the way: Who's
going to pay for it?
</P>
<P>
   ``It would take some kind of public-private partnership,''
Schieffer said.
</P>
<P>
   We know that euphemism by now. That means the taxpayer pays.
</P>
<P>
   ``Support from the community is very strong for it,'' Looney
said. ``Now, I don't know how much public support there'll be if
you ask people to tax themselves.
</P>
<P>
   ``One of the problems under the Brimer Bill is that we don't
have any room to generate any sales tax money. About the only thing
we've got that could generate any money would be hotel-motel tax,
or automobile rental tax, which would generate some money but won't
generate enough in the big scheme of things.''
</P>
<P>
   The funding of three separate spring-training facilities is no
small challenge, but if anyone can make it work ... well, it's
you-know-who.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's going to take some creativity, something like
\RSchieffer\S was able to put together there in Arlington,'' Looney
said, ``and I think people are open to discuss that.''
</P>
<P>
   As much as I've enjoyed heading to Florida all these years, a
condo on the beach at South Padre sounds even more appealing.
</P>
<P>
   It's time for Schieffer to don Mr. Roarke's white tropical suit
and make all our fantasies come true.
</P>
<P>
   De plane, Boss. De company plane.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-17-99 2330EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
