<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-RANGERS-CANADIENS-330&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RANGERS ARE AILING, AND THE RESULTS SHOW IT 
</HEADLINE>
  (nk) 
 By JOE LAPOINTE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Neil Smith, president and general manager of the
Rangers, attends most home games, but he did not witness Wednesday
night's debacle at Madison Square Garden. Smith was out of town on
a scouting mission, hoping to build a better future for his team.
Had he stayed around, he might have been tempted to boo, hoot or
leave early the way many customers did.
</P>
<P>
   At present, things are bad for the Blue Shirts and getting
worse. In losing 6-3 to the Montreal Canadiens, the Rangers
squandered another chance to move up in the Eastern Conference
playoff race. They lost their fourth game in their last five and
their 10th game in their last 14. At home, they are 1-7 in their
last eight.
</P>
<P>
   Want more? Their first-string goalie, Mike Richter, failed to
survive the first period for his second consecutive start. Their
second-best goal scorer, John MacLean, went home early with a nerve
injury in his neck.
</P>
<P>
   Want excuses? Sure, there are many. Besides MacLean, the Rangers
played without two other key players, also injured, both
defensemen. They were playing their fourth game in six nights,
never a good thing for a team that depends far too much on veterans
in their 30s.
</P>
<P>
   Want to stress the positive? Mike Knuble of the Rangers broke
out of a 14-game slump without a goal by scoring twice. And Petr
Nedved, slumping with one goal in his previous 13 games, scored a
power-play goal that briefly cut the Montreal lead to two goals
late in the third period.
</P>
<P>
   Need a little cockeyed optimism? Depending on the Florida-Dallas
result _ the game Smith was scouting _ the Rangers are only 5, 6 or
7 points behind the Panthers, who hold the eighth and final playoff
berth in the East. With three games in four nights, beginning
Friday, the Rangers could fall out of the race. But a hot streak
could put them right back into contention.
</P>
<P>
   The result gave Montreal a 4-0 record over the Rangers this
season. They won't meet again unless it is in the playoffs.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   As for Rangers and injuries, Wednesday night it was MacLean, who
has 20 goals, leaving in the first period with a ``burner'' in the
neck area. Eric Lacroix, recently acquired in a trade with Los
Angeles, opened a gash on his forehead when he was shoved from
behind into the Montreal crossbar by Turner Stevenson.
</P>
<P>
   The officials gave Stevenson a five-minute major penalty and the
Rangers scored a goal during the advantage to cut the Montreal
lead, briefly, to 3-1. Earlier, Stevenson had collided with MacLean
moments before MacLean left the game, but it was not clear if that
check caused the injury.
</P>
<P>
   MacLean left the Garden, but Lacroix returned for the third
period after taking 15 stitches.
</P>
<P>
   Already missing for the Rangers were two big defensemen, Jeff
Beukeboom and Peter Popovic. Beukeboom is recovering from his
second concussion of the season and Popovic has blood in his eye
from being hit with a puck. It is not known if MacLean, Beukeboom
or Popovic will be able to play on Friday night at the Garden
against Pittsburgh. Rich Brennan, who was called up from the
Hartford Wolf Pack, was making his Rangers debut as a defenseman.
</P>
<P>
   Richter gave up three goals on nine shots and left the game
after 5 minutes 32 seconds. It was the second consecutive game in
which he was pulled after giving up three early goals. It also
happened on Sunday in a 4-2 loss to Detroit at the Garden. Dan
Cloutier played in Nashville on Monday night, a 7-4 victory over
the Predators.
</P>
<P>
   Martin Rucinsky gave Montreal a 1-0 lead at 4:25 after a
clearing pass by Adam Graves was intercepted in the Rangers' zone.
Jonas Hoglund made it 2-0 at 4:43 by putting his own rebound past
Richter. The Canadiens got the puck after a turnover by defenseman
Brian Leetch. The captain lost it to Sergei Zholtok after a
miscommunication with Ulf Samuelsson.
</P>
<P>
   Montreal made it 3-0 at 5:32 on a goal by Shayne Corson, who
took the puck away from Samuelsson behind the Rangers' net and beat
Richter with a low shot on a wrap-around move.
</P>
<P>
   Mike Knuble of the Rangers cut the deficit to 3-1 by scoring on
the power play at 6:32 of the second period. Without a goal in 14
games and demoted from higher lines, Knuble got extra ice time
because of MacLean's injury. After a pass from Marc Savard, Knuble
got his 10th of the season when he one-timed a wrist shot from the
right-wing circle that beat goalie Jeff Hackett between the skates.
</P>
<P>
   Montreal went up by 4-1 at 8:40 on a goal by Vincent Damphousse,
who backhanded a shot from the slot with nobody covering him.
</P>
</TEXT>
