<SLUG> BC-NJ-HMO-400-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JUDGE WANTS NEW PLAN TO HELP PATIENTS IN FAILED HMO 
</HEADLINE>
  (rk) 
 By RONALD SMOTHERS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW BRUNSWICK, N.J._ A state judge sternly directed New Jersey
insurance regulators Wednesday to ``go back to the drawing board''
to insure continuity of health coverage for members of the
insolvent HIP Health Plans of New Jersey as the state moves toward
closing down the company by March 31.
</P>
<P>
   ``The problem with your plan is that it is no plan,'' Superior
Court Judge Jack L. Lintner in Middlesex County said as he rebuked
state officials and a deputy attorney general, Josh Lichtblau, for
giving him only verbal assurances that there would be no transition
problems for HIP's 165,000 policyholders. ``You are going to be
required to give me a complete plan by this Friday.''
</P>
<P>
   Lintner ticked off the shortcomings he found in the State
Department of Banking and Insurance's interim plan submitted
Wednesday for HIP, the state's fourth largest health maintenance
organization.
</P>
<P>
   He said the plan did not make clear which hospitals and which
doctors would agree to continue seeing HIP members at discounted
rates, set no procedures to guarantee continuity for patients with
ongoing treatment and had no mechanism to allow for quick
certification of HIP-employed doctors who want to move to other
HMOs.
</P>
<P>
   He ordered the state to create an ombudsman for patients,
provide for the orderly transfer of medical records, insure
prescription coverage and assist employers faced with finding new
plan options for their workers.
</P>
<P>
   Looking out over a courtroom packed with dark-suited lawyers
representing landlords of the 23 HIP centers, doctors and hospitals
owed money by HIP, HIP employees and some unions, Lintner said that
until now, not enough attention had been paid to patient care.
</P>
<P>
   ``You're all concerned about the money you are owed, and I'm not
concerned with that at this time,'' Lintner told the crowd.
</P>
<P>
   Just last week Lintner had seemed to give his blessing to the
state's plan on HIP when he refused to grant a special hearing to
consider the proposal by HIP Health Plans Inc., the New York parent
company, to keep the insurer functioning but scaled down.
</P>
<P>
   After then, the judge said, he had been deluged with motions
highlighting ``the predicament of the insured'': whether
policyholders would still be served in the transition period.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
