<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-NISSAN-SIDE-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
USC, UCLA GOLFERS SHOW TRUE COLORS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DAVE SHELBURNE  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Craig Stadler wore his cardinal and gold as proudly as he wore
the green jacket he earned at the 1982 Masters.
</P>
<P>
   But he says ``Nope'' when asked if much USC-UCLA rivalry carries
over onto the PGA Tour _ particularly when the tour returns to Los
Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   ``Not at all,'' said the burly, bushy-mustached man who was a
two-time All-American honors at USC two decades ago. ``You give
everybody a little needle once in a while when you can, but it's no
big thing.''
</P>
<P>
   On that point, however, the Walrus appears to be in a minority
as seven former Bruins and Trojans gather at Riviera Country Club
for this week's Nissan Open.
</P>
<P>
   ``Absolutely,'' said ex-Bruin Steve Pate when asked if the
mustachioed rivalry extends beyond college. ``Some things never
change.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh yeah, certainly,'' added Scott McCarron, another former
Bruin. ``Any time USC and UCLA are playing in anything, I'm always
rooting against USC, no question.''
</P>
<P>
   Scott Simpson, also a USC All-American, contends the rivalry
remains on tour, even though he calls it a ``friendly''
competition.
</P>
<P>
   ``We all get along really well,'' said Simpson, an NCAA champion
with the Trojans.
</P>
<P>
   ``Corey Pavin is one of my good friends, and I like Duffy
(Waldorf), and Steve Pate and Scott McCarron. They're all great
guys. We might have fun with each other, but there's no huge
rivalry.''
</P>
<P>
   Those four Bruins will join Stadler, Simpson and USC alum Dave
Stockton Jr. this week, and it might be difficult to pick a
favorite in the mustachioed rivalry.
</P>
<P>
   On the Bruins' side, Pavin is a two-time Nissan champion, 1995
U.S. Open champion and seems to have recovered from the hand injury
that contributed to his missing the Nissan cut at Valencia Country
Club last year.
</P>
<P>
   Pate was nipped in last month's Bob Hope Chrysler Classic by
David Duval's tour-record tying final round of 59 and is playing
well enough to qualify for next week's World Match Play
Championship.
</P>
<P>
   Waldorf knows and likes the course, which sets up well for his
left-to-right game. And McCarron entered the final round of the '97
Nissan one stroke behind eventual winner Nick Faldo.
</P>
<P>
   For the Trojans, their old guard is holding up remarkably well.
Stadler won the '96 Nissan at age 42, finishing a stroke ahead of
Simpson _ who finished seventh last week in a strong title defense
at the Buick Invitational at Torrey Pines.
</P>
<P>
   Stockton, Jr. brings USC golfing blue blood to Riviera's table.
The sixth-year tour player is the son of former Trojans
All-American Dave Stockton, who won the Nissan (then Los Angeles
Open) in '74 and won two PGA Championships.
</P>
<P>
   Whichever school's pennant flys figuratively highest in the
Riviera locker room come Sunday afternoon, it seems a good bet the
preceding days will produce their share of jibes.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yeah,'' said Pate, the Bruins' 1983 Pac-10 champion who
resides in Agoura Hills. ``But now that UCLA's a football school,
it seems they (Trojans) don't want to talk.''
</P>
<P>
   Listening, on the other hand, is sometimes unavoidable:
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm constantly reminded about our eight-game losing streak in
football,'' said Simpson. He has come to terms with sports'
shifting sands, thanks to USC coach Mike Gillespie's defending
College World Series champions.
</P>
<P>
   ``So I talk about baseball,'' Simpson said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
