<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-17 23:42 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9712 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-JASPER18-COX     02-17 0942
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JASPER18-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Jasper proceedings focus on suspect's tattoos, activities
 &HT;    By Denise Gamino
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   JASPER, Texas _ The image of racism dominated the Jasper County
courthouse Wednesday as a jury inside viewed striking photographs
of white-supremacy tattoos, and black activists showed up outside
to denounce prejudice.
</P>
<P>
   The buzz of a police helicopter passing overhead could be heard
often inside the courtroom during the second day of testimony in
the trial of the white man accused of choreographing last summer's
dragging death of James Byrd Jr., a black man.
</P>
<P>
   John William ``Bill'' King, 24, sat stone-faced as the
prosecutor put on a slide show of his tattoos photographed at close
range: a black man hanging from a tree, a baby Jesus with horns,
the words ``Aryan Pride'' etched several inches high, an
upside-down pentagram covering his armpit, a logo for the
white-supremacy Confederate Knights of America, and neo-Nazi
lightning bolts with an ``SS'' symbol, among others.
</P>
<P>
   One spectator who sat in the courtroom for more than an hour was
Quanell X, a black activist from Houston who arrived with four
comrades dressed in black military fatigues. He said he came to
``look that no-good devil who lynched our brother in his cold eyes
and let him know that never again will you lynch our people and get
away with it.''
</P>
<P>
   Clusters of law enforcement officers patrolled the courthouse
square in anticipation of the black activists' appearance. Last
summer, Quanell X and his followers tried to shout out and clash
with Ku Klux Klan members demonstrating at the Jasper County
courthouse a few weeks after Byrd's slaying.
</P>
<P>
   When Quanell X left the courthouse Wednesday, he said the three
men accused of killing Byrd should be given the death penalty.
</P>
<P>
   ``I pray by God's grace and permission that, if they're found
not guilty by some delusionary jury, I pray that we give them hell
from the womb to the tomb, from the cradle to the damn grave,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   King, who contends he was at home when Byrd was dragged to death
on a rural road outside Jasper in the early morning hours of June
7, could receive the death penalty or a life sentence if convicted.
</P>
<P>
   Also accused of fatally pulling Byrd behind a pickup for nearly
three miles are King's friends and Jasper roommates: Shawn Allen
Berry, 24, and Lawrence Russell Brewer, 31. Their trials have not
been scheduled.
</P>
<P>
   Jasper County District Attorney Guy James Gray on Wednesday also
showed the jury photos of the tattoos on Berry and Brewer.
</P>
<P>
   Berry, who owned the pickup that allegedly dragged Byrd, has a
tattoo of a skull with devil horns and the word ``Brotherhood''
inscribed above it. Brewer has tattoos similar to King's, such as
the words ``Aryan Pride'' and the Confederate Knights of America
logo.
</P>
<P>
   Gray argues that King was a racist who orchestrated Byrd's
murder to gain recognition for a new hate group he was forming in
Jasper. King's tattoos are proof of his hatred toward blacks, Gray
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The tattoos speak for themselves,'' he said after testimony
ended Wednesday. ``It's proof _ state of mind, hate, anger _ the
kind of thing in somebody's mind it takes to commit this kind of
act.''
</P>
<P>
   King's attorneys say the young man's tattoos prove nothing. ``I
don't think just the tattoos themselves make him a racist,'' said
court-appointed defense attorney C. Haden ``Sonny'' Cribbs Jr.
</P>
<P>
   King got most of his tattoos while in state prison on a burglary
charge.
</P>
<P>
   Testimony early in the day linked all three men to the pickup on
the night of Byrd's death and revealed that King may have occupied
himself that evening with romance and betrayal. He twice dodged his
pregnant girlfriend to have a three-hour tryst with a former lover
who was cheating on her common-law husband, according to testimony.
</P>
<P>
   The former lover, Keisha Adkins, told a jury she spent about
three hours with King in his apartment while Brewer turned away
King's girlfriend, who had come to the apartment twice to look for
him.
</P>
<P>
   Adkins testified that when she left the apartment about 1:45
a.m. on June 7, she saw King, Brewer and Berry drive away in
Berry's pickup.
</P>
<P>
   Adkins, her voice often wavering, also said she saw King's
cigarette lighter at his apartment the night of the dragging death.
The lighter is inscribed with his nickname, ``Possum.''
</P>
<P>
   Law officers told the jury a lighter with the word ``Possum'' on
it was found at the remote location where Byrd was allegedly beaten
before being chained to a pickup and dragged until he was beheaded.
</P>
<P>
   Offering a hint of their strategy, King's defense lawyers
challenged the manner in which detectives gathered evidence from
the dragging-death site and King's apartment. Under questioning,
detectives acknowledge they did not change gloves each time they
collected a new piece of evidence.
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutors say they have collected cigarette butts, beer
bottles, watches, the ``Possum'' lighter, shoes and other items
belonging to the three white men that link them to the bloody road
where Byrd was dragged.
</P>
<P>
   Gray, the prosecutor, said the defense was trying to raise ``an
O.J. theory'' that evidence had been contaminated, a reference to
the defense strategy in O.J. Simpson's murder trial.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm satisfied there has not been any contamination,'' Gray
said.
</P>
<P>
   Missing from court on Wednesday was King's father, who could be
heard moaning during some of the testimony on Tuesday. But more
than a dozen members of Byrd's family again occupied the front two
rows of the courtroom.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
