<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-17 23:46 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9717 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-DOG-POISONINGS-LADN     02-17 0482
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DOG-POISONINGS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
POLICE PROBE RASH OF L.A.-AREA DOG POISONINGS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
BY PHILLIP W. BROWNE  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES -- One dog is dead and three others seriously ill in
a second rash of area dog poisonings, leaving residents on edge and
police looking for the suspects, police said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Los Angeles police investigators said someone walked through a
neighborhood in the suburban, San Fernando Valley community of
Winnetka on Monday night, throwing ground beef patties laced with
rat poison into back yards.
</P>
<P>
   The attacks are identical to a series of dog poisonings in Eagle
Rock northeast of downtown Los Angeles last week, but authorities
believe the cases are unrelated, said Los Angeles police Officer
Richard Andert. In Eagle Rock, three dogs died and one was
critically injured. Police there still are looking for the suspect.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's just awful. I don't have any words to describe how I feel
about this person that you could print,'' said Winnetka resident
Karen Wagner, whose dogs, Jon and Ayla, ate the tainted meat. Both
survived.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's just sick and deranged. I hope they catch this person.''
</P>
<P>
   When caught, the person responsible could face felony charges of
cruelty to animals, which is punishable by imprisonment and fines.
</P>
<P>
   Madeline Bernstein, president of Los Angeles' Society for the
Prevention of Cruelty to Animals, said she's pleased that police
are taking these reports seriously.
</P>
<P>
   Someone who harms neighborhood animals is usually a local
resident with a problem who is afraid of dealing with it, she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are usually always people with a gripe. I know of many
cases where a person took a neighbor's cat or dog, took them to the
pound and had them euthanized,'' Bernstein said. ``There are
sometimes copycat crimes, but it's usually a person that can't deal
with a neighbor face to face.''
</P>
<P>
   On Monday night Wagner thought Jon was bringing a ball into the
house about 9 p.m., but when she took a better look she realized it
was a fist-size ball of meat. The meat was partly frozen, she said.
</P>
<P>
   Her husband, Kurt, took a better look at the meat and found
green pellets inside. By that point, Jon was going into a seizure.
They rushed both dogs to a critical care veterinarian.
</P>
<P>
   ``They pumped Jon's stomach and saved his life. We brought him
home (Wednesday) and he's resting,'' Wagner said.
</P>
<P>
   Wagner's neighbor, Christina Barbato, said Wednesday that she
was planning to have a neighborhood meeting with residents, Andert
and animal control officers.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is sick and it needs to stop. Neighbors need to be
aware,'' Barbato said.
</P>
<P>
   Andert said the best way to prevent a poisoning is to keep close
watch on your pets.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're trying to reach residents and make them aware of the
problem,'' Andert said.
</P>
<P>
   X X X &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
