<SLUG> BC-PROSECUTOR-DRUGS-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FORMER PROSECUTOR FACES FELONY DRUG CHARGES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By SCOTT SUNDE  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ Will Miller, a former prosecutor who put bad guys away
in New York and Seattle, now faces five felony drug charges and the
possibility of spending 10 years in prison.
</P>
<P>
   After officers battered down his front door Tuesday night, they
found syringes in an upstairs office, a little bit of
methamphetamine downstairs and Miller hiding in his attic.
</P>
<P>
   It was a stunning reversal for a man who seemed to have lived a
charmed life inside and outside a courtroom. He prosecuted crooks
in Brooklyn, Queens, then finally Seattle, winning promotions along
the way.
</P>
<P>
   Luck seemed on his side. Eight years ago, muggers shot Miller in
the head, but he was hardly scratched. Last year, Miller walked
into the King County Courthouse in Seattle only to have security
officers discover a drug pipe and a small amount of methamphetamine
in his briefcase.
</P>
<P>
   But prosecutors didn't charge Miller. The incident did force him
to resign as a deputy prosecutor in King County and go into private
practice.
</P>
<P>
   But two months after the Washington state attorney general's
office decided that it couldn't make a case against Miller, he
allegedly began selling methamphetamine to a undercover detective.
</P>
<P>
   Court documents filed Wednesday say he sold an ounce of
suspected methamphetamine three times this year for $1,000 each to
the undercover detective three times. Subsequent tests on the
suspected drugs showed that they contained amphetamine.
</P>
<P>
   The investigation culminated Tuesday night, when the detective
arranged to buy three ounces of methamphetamine.
</P>
<P>
   Officers with the King County Sheriff's Office battered down the
front door of Miller's home in Seattle's Crown Hill neighborhood.
Officers arrested Miller in his attic and searched the house. They
found a scale, several syringes and a small amount of
methamphetamine, according to court documents.
</P>
<P>
   A 28-year-old man, who court papers say was Miller's source for
drugs, also was arrested. The man has yet to be charged. But court
documents say he had gone to his car to get the drugs after the
undercover officer paid $2,400 for them.
</P>
<P>
   Miller was being held in a special unit of the King County Jail
Wednesday night. Prosecutors have asked that bail of $50,000 be
set, arguing that Miller ``is a flight risk and is a threat to the
community based on his drug trafficking.''
</P>
<P>
   What proved to be Miller's undoing was a former roommate who had
been his alibi in the courthouse incident. A King County detective
who had investigated the incident left a business card with the
roommate, identified in court documents as Jeff Vinson.
</P>
<P>
   Vinson later called the detective with information about Miller,
sparking the investigation, said Jerrell Wills, a spokesman for the
King County Sheriff's Office. ``He felt somehow betrayed,'' Wills
said.
</P>
<P>
   The alleged drug buys and arrest took place in Seattle. But
county sheriff's officers rather than Seattle police handled the
investigation because the sheriff's officers had worked with Vinson
last year as they investigated the courthouse incident, Wills said.
</P>
<P>
   The state attorney general's office, which took several months
to decide not to prosecute Miller last year, acted swiftly this
week. The office, which is handling the case to avoid any conflict
of interest involving local prosecutors, filed three charges of
delivering amphetamine to the undercover detective, one charge of
trying to deliver amphetamine and one charge of possession of
methamphetamine.
</P>
<P>
   Miller faces up to 10 years in prison if convicted and a fine of
$25,000.
</P>
<P>
   A conviction would be a reversal of fortune for Miller, once a
respected prosecutor in New York and Seattle.
</P>
<P>
   He joined the Brooklyn District Attorney's Office in 1988 and
became a prosecutor specializing in sex crimes. In 1991, Miller
found himself on the wrong side of a gun, when a bullet grazed his
temple during a mugging in Brooklyn, according to the Long Island
newspaper Newsday.
</P>
<P>
   Fellow prosecutors in Seattle say Miller kept a laminated copy
of a New York Post story on the shooting in his office. It
proclaimed him a ``miracle'' prosecutor.
</P>
<P>
   Late in 1991, the Queens district attorney's office hired
Miller, putting him in the special victims bureau. Miller also
volunteered as a liaison to the gay and lesbian community. A year
later, Miller handled a high-profile investigation of a Korean gang
suspected of crimes such as kidnapping, robbery and rape.
</P>
<P>
   He joined the King County prosecutor's office in November 1995,
first handling juvenile cases, then moving to a so-called ``trial
team'' where he prosecuted car thefts, burglaries and assaults.
</P>
<P>
   In New York, he was known as ``D. Willas Miller.'' In Seattle,
co-workers knew him as ``Will Miller.''
</P>
<P>
   By March of last year, Miller was supervising new prosecutors
working mostly misdemeanor cases in District Court. He was on his
way to supervise the prosecution of a drunken-driving case on March
2 when the pipe and other items were found in his briefcase.
</P>
<P>
   That incident resulted in the possession charge that was lodged
against Miller on Wednesday. In November, Greg Canova, chief
criminal prosecutor in the state attorney general's Office, said he
couldn't file charges over the incident and expect to win.
</P>
<P>
   Miller contended at the time that he didn't know the drug pipe
and drugs were in his briefcase and that they weren't his.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday, however, Canova said he has new evidence to support a
charge over the courthouse incident. He would not identify the new
evidence.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, Vinson told investigators that the pipe and a scale
found in the briefcase were his. He had said the pipe and scale
were in a plastic box that he had lent to an acquaintance, who
might have been a drug dealer.
</P>
<P>
   Vinson got the box back and put it in Miller's briefcase on
March 1. The two had an argument, and Vinson left, never telling
Miller about the box.
</P>
<P>
   Neighbors said they had little contact with Miller, who kept the
drapes closed on his little brick home.
</P>
<P>
   At least one neighbor, Gowri Shankar, suspected something
strange was going on at Miller's home. Monday at 11:15 p.m., a
young man dress in socks, pants and a T-shirt, knocked on Shankar's
door. The young man said he had been locked out of Miller's home
and asked to use the telephone.
</P>
<P>
   The next morning, Shankar introduced himself to Miller, who said
he had had an electrical fire. Shankar said he wondered aloud to
his wife whether the fire was the result of a methamphetamine lab
inside the house.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was always something going on there _ a lot of
activity,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But other neighbors said they saw little, until just after
supper time Tuesday night when they heard officers batter open
Miller's front door.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
