<SLUG> BC-BKC-NATIONAL-REPORT-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IOWA'S STRANGE SEASON NEARS END, OTHER NOTES
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By WENDELL BARNHOUSE 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
FORT WORTH, Texas _ One way or another, it will all be over in, oh,
about six weeks. Iowa's basketball Season of Strange will come to
an end and sighs of relief will be heard across the heartland. 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Last April, Iowa announced that coach Tom Davis was retiring _
after this season. Lame ducks don't make good coaches; Ralph
Willard announced he was stepping down after this season at Pitt,
and the Panthers haven't won since. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Both Davis and Iowa athletic director Bob Bowlsby denied last
April that Davis was being forced out. Davis said he was resigning,
and Bowlsby said the coach was retiring. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The coaching staff's one-and-done status could have far-reaching
effects. Iowa signed no players during the November early signing
period. The new coaching staff will have to start from Square One. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Bowlsby said that his decision not to extend Davis' contract was
because of shortcomings in recruiting, scheduling, academics and
attendance. Bowlsby also backed up his decision with these facts:
Iowa has not advanced beyond the second round of the NCAA
Tournament since 1988 and had not won a Big Ten championship under
Davis. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``He's what Iowa basketball has been for a long time,'' senior
guard Kent McCausland said of Davis. ``For all of a sudden to say
all these things and not renew his contract, I think that's maybe a
little unfair.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Bowlsby's seat heated up when Hayden Fry retired as football
coach and the school was not quick enough to hire former Iowa
player Bob Stoops, who was hired by Oklahoma. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   That coincided with the Hawkeyes' fast start _ they won 13 of
their first 14. Hawkeyes fans believe that Bowlsby was making a
mistake, and there were whispers of a grassroots campaign to save
Davis' job. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   And Bowlsby appeared to be getting thin skinned when he asked
ESPN to reassign analyst Steve Yoder after Yoder made remarks that
were critical of Bowlsby's decision. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The looming opening has made for a season of rumors. The mill
has ground out the following candidates: B.J. Armstrong, Fran
Fraschilla, Rick Majerus, John Calipari, Leonard Hamilton, Kevin
Stallings and Steve Alford. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   However, the Save Tom Davis talk has cooled along with Iowa's
winning ways. The Hawkeyes have lost six of nine, but they're still
probably in line for an NCAA Tournament bid, which would be a
fitting way for Davis to leave. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``It's just been crazy,'' junior guard Ryan Luehrsmann said
recently. ``You never know what you're going to hear. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``We just want to get the most out of it _ share a moment with
him, a laugh here and there, get yelled at one last time or
whatever. I'm just thankful, and so is everybody else, to have the
chance to play for a legend like him.'' &QL; 
Spotlight &QL; 
 &QL; 
Michigan State clicking &QL; 
with healthy point guard &QL; 
 &QL; 
Now that Mateen Cleaves is healthy, Michigan State has regained its
engine, its driving force. And the 23-4 Spartans appear headed for
the Big Ten Conference title and a probable No. 1 seed in the NCAA
Tournament. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Cleaves' well-being is crucial for Michigan State. His freshman
year, he was slowed by a back injury and extra weight. Last season
as a sophomore, Cleaves was in top shape, and he led the Spartans
to a 22-8 record and a Sweet 16 berth. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   This season, Cleaves was hobbled by ankle and shoulder injuries.
In the Great Eight Classic against Duke, Cleaves missed 14 shots.
Because their point guard was not on his game, the Spartans started
4-3. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   It was difficult for Cleaves, knowing that he was a
player-of-the-year candidate, but not being able to play at a high
level because his body wouldn't allow it. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Knowing how people are going to be aiming at you, it was hard
to get ready mentally because I knew I didn't put in the work to
play some of those early games,'' Cleaves said. ``It was killing me
because I knew I couldn't do some of the things I normally
would.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In his first 12 games, Cleaves averaged 11.6 points, 6.8 assists
and 4.4 turnovers. In his next seven games, he averaged 11.4
points, 6.9 assists and 3.0 turnovers. And even though his team
lost _ its last loss _ at Wisconsin in early January, Cleaves knew
he was back. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``I saw I could get to the basket, get around people and
finish,'' he said. &QL; 
 &QL; 
quick hits &QL; 
 &QL; 
Geographically challenged &QL; 
North is North and South is South and never mind that the NCAA
Tournament committee doesn't appear to know how to read a map. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Two first-round sites in this year's tournament are Indianapolis
and New Orleans. The trouble is, Indianapolis is in the ``South''
Region and New Orleans is in the ``Midwest''. Logical explanation,
please. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``We know how to read a map,'' chuckled Kentucky athletic
director C.M. Newton chairman of the tournament committee. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Jim Marchiony, NCAA media coordinator for men's basketball, said
that after the sites were selected, a problem arose with dates and
building availability that caused the committee to ignore geography
in favor of convenience. &QL; 
Clank, clank, clank &QL; 
The gang that couldn't shoot straight resides at Arkansas-Pine
Bluff. In their first season in the Southwestern Athletic
Conference, the Golden Lions are proving that shooting accuracy is
not their strong suit. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Arkansas-Pine Bluff is shooting 37.8 percent from the field,
26.5 percent from 3-point range and 58.4 percent on free throws.
That helps explain its 2-21 overall and 1-12 SWAC records. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Damon Horton, though, is on a roll. The junior point guard has
made 20 of its past 47 shots. He started the season missing 50 of
his first 58 shots, so now his shooting percentage is up to 26.7
percent. &QL; 
Tournament signs &QL; 
If you believe in fate and omens, here are two reasons to believe
that Duke and Michigan State, two of the nation's hottest teams,
are serious Final Four/national championship contenders: &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Duke, 25-1 going into last night's game at Florida State, is off
to the best start in school history. The previous best was 24-2,
accomplished by Final Four teams in 1962-63, 1985-86 and 1991-92
(the '92 team won the national championship). &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Michigan State is 13-0 at Breslin Center with one remaining home
game (Sunday against Wisconsin). If the Spartans go undefeated, it
will be the second time in 100 years that a Spartans team has been
perfect at home. The other time that happened was 1978-79, Michigan
State's national championship season. &QL; 
Quotebook &QL; 
Saint Louis coach Charlie Spoonhour on his team's deliberate
style: &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``We control tempo. We don't like to use the word slow. Recruits
might be listening.'' &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Undefeated in conference &QL; 
Through Tuesday's games, four teams _ Duke (Atlantic Coast),
Winthrop (Big South), College of Charleston (Southern) and Utah
(Western Athletic) _ were undefeated in conference play. A look at
teams undefeated in conference play the past five years and how
those teams fared in the NCAA Tournament: &QL; 
Year Team W-L Conf. Postseason &QL; 
1998 Princeton 13-0 Ivy Lost NCAA second round &QL; 
1998 TCU 14-0 WAC Lost NCAA first round &QL; 
1997 Princeton 14-0 Ivy Lost NCAA first round &QL; 
1997 Charleston 16-0 Trans America Lost NCAA second round &QL; 
1996 Wisconsin-Green Bay 16-0 Midwestern Lost NCAA first round &QL; 
1996 Kentucky 16-0 SEC National champions &QL; 
1996 Davidson 14-0 Southern Did not qualify &QL; 
1996 Texas Tech 14-0 SWC Lost NCAA regional semifinal &QL; 
1995 Pennsylvania 14-0 Ivy Lost NCAA first round &QL; 
1995 Xavier 14-0 Midwestern Lost NCAA first round &QL; 
1994 Missouri 14-0 Big Eight Lost regional final &QL; 
1994 Pennsylvania 14-0 Ivy Lost NCAA second round &QL; 
1994 Coppin State 16-0 Mid-Eastern Athletic Did not qualify &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
