<P>
   INDONESIA-TIMOR (Washington) _ For almost a quarter-century,
relations between Indonesia, the world's fourth most-populous
nation, and the United States _ as well as the rest of the outside
world _ have often stumbled over the fate of half of an
impoverished island so small and so remote that even many
Indonesians would have trouble finding it on a map. But with the
utterance of a few words by Indonesia's new president last week,
the territory, East Timor, suddenly appears to be on the brink of
independence. That has left the Clinton administration and other
governments puzzling over how to respond to Indonesia's turnaround.
By Philip Shenon.
