   &UR; BUSINESS DAY _ (Moved in ``f'' category)  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   SOROS-RUMORS (Undated) When legendary speculator George Soros
speaks, financial markets move. When financial markets tumble,
politicians and central bankers look to Soros for advice. And when
noted economist and columnist Paul Krugman suggested last week that
Soros had taken advantage of his privileged position and engaged in
a bit of insider trading, the global gossip mill began churning.
The problem, Krugman now admits, is that his charges aren't true.
By Timothy L. O'Brien.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Photo [NYT26) has been sent to NYT photo clients.)
</P>
<P>
   DELL-MARKETPLACE (New York) _ Daniel T. Niles wants to make one
thing clear: his nephew does not work at Dell Computer. That Niles,
who follows computer and semiconductor companies for BancBoston
Robertson Stephens, has an inside source at Dell is but one of the
rumors that was circulating on Wall Street Wednesday, one day after
Dell shocked Wall Street by reporting revenues that failed to meet
analysts' estimates. Dell's report was a surprise to everyone but
Niles and the clients of his firm, whom he told on Friday that
Dell's sales had slowed and that the company was unlikely to meet
the consensus estimates for revenues. By Edward Wyatt.
</P>
