increasingly entwined worlds of art and fashion. By Christopher
Mason
</P>
<P>
   IKEA-SPACE (New York) _ She's always organizing, but her house
is a mess. He leaves his running shoes all over the apartment. Her
heel-less pumps multiply on the closet floor. The children are
having turf wars over their toys. Disputes over space _ especially
the lack of it _ can turn a happy marriage into the bitter,
chandelier-swinging finale from the divorce film, ``War of the
Roses.'' With that in mind, on the eve of Valentine's Day, Ikea in
Elizabeth, N.J., brought together two psychotherapists and an
interior designer to help customers sort out, or maybe even shelve,
their issues. By Julie Iovine.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Photo [NYT15) has been sent to NYT photo clients.)
</P>
<P>
   QUILTS-DECODED (Undated) _ One scholar compared it to the
``Rosetta stone,'' said Jacqueline L. Tobin, the author, with
Raymond G. Dobard, of ``Hidden in Plain View,'' a new book that
makes a startling claim about quilts: that some quilts were
patterned as a code to direct escaping slaves. A quilt with
monkey-wrench pattern hung in a cabin window signaled slaves to
gather tools for the escape. Tumbling blocks indicated imminent
departure. The number and placement of knots represented dates. The
book, just published by Doubleday, has become a surprise hot
seller. The story of its origin is as intriguing as its theory. By
Phil Patton.
</P>
