<SLUG> BC-BKW-TCU-WAC-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TCU WOMEN AIM FOR FIRST WINNING DIVISION I SEASON
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JENNIFER FLOYD 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
FORT WORTH, Texas _ Flying into Colorado Springs, Colo., a couple
of weeks ago, coach Mike Petersen passed the time by flipping
through a flight magazine.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Way back, in a small article, a single line caught his
attention.
</P>
<P>
   ``It said: `Do you know what happens when you chase two
rabbits?' '' Petersen said. ``I thought that was a pretty good
thought, so when we're sitting in the team meeting, I said: `OK,
what happens if you try to chase two rabbits?'
</P>
<P>
   ``And Jill \RSutton\S says, `Oh, they both get away.
</P>
<P>
   ``And I said: `Where did you see that?'
</P>
<P>
   ``And she said: `I read the flight magazine, too.' ''
</P>
<P>
   A coach utters 457 phrases in a season trying to inspire
players. Petersen figures two, maybe four, actually do. But rabbits
did this time.
</P>
<P>
   Goals are no longer called goals around TCU, but rabbits. Horned
Frogs players have T-shirts, too, that read, ``Chasing one WAC-ky
wabbit at a time.''
</P>
<P>
   The one rabbit that is being chased now is Nevada-Las Vegas. In
theory, the rabbits are all supposed to be equal, but they aren't.
</P>
<P>
   This one is bigger.
</P>
<P>
   If TCU defeats UNLV tonight, it will be the Frogs' 14th victory
of the season and will clinch their first winning season since
becoming an NCAA Division I program in 1982. It would also mark the
first time the Frogs have won more than 13 games in a season.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would mean a lot because it's a big step for the program,''
TCU guard Amy Sutton said. ``I think we'd all like to be a part of
history.''
</P>
<P>
   They were almost there last season. TCU reached 13 victories on
Feb. 5, 1998. They never really came close to getting No. 14, going
0-7 to finish 13-15.
</P>
<P>
   Too many rabbits, not enough focus.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's different teams. I really don't want to get into that
because I promised this team that I wouldn't,'' Petersen said. ``So
I guess the one thing I would say is: The kids who were here last
year and went through the whole tailspin that we went through are
very focused on not going through it again.''
</P>
<P>
   The problems last year were touchy ones, and no one really much
wants to talk about what they were like.
</P>
<P>
   The best way to describe it might be by describing how they are
this year.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is almost like an eighth-grade slumber party,'' Amy Sutton
said. ``You know how you sometimes hear teams say: `We're all
friends on this team.' Only, it's not fake, and it doesn't end when
practice ends. We really are friends, well, until ... ''
</P>
<P>
   Until, it's ``room-war'' time.
</P>
<P>
   On TCU's last trip, it was twins Jill and Amy Sutton against
Karen Clayton and Sally Spencer. The rest of the players acted as
spies and room guards and instigators.
</P>
<P>
   The pranks and laughs were straight out of an all-girls,
sleep-over camp, including toilet-papering and short-sheeting and
key-changing.
</P>
<P>
   Petersen had to call a peace summit for fear his players would
be up all night giggling and be unprepared against Wyoming.
</P>
<P>
   It wasn't a problem.
</P>
<P>
   The Frogs defeated Wyoming for victory No. 13, bringing about
the rabbit with the No. 14 on its back.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not like we had never talked about it,'' Petersen said.
``When we sat down at the start of the season, we talked about here
is a number of goals and the first one after `we're going to get
better every day' was 14 wins.
</P>
<P>
   ``So I don't want to downplay it, but at the same time, if our
only goal is to win 14 games what are we going to do in those last
four games?''
</P>
<P>
   Three regular-season games remain after tonight and then, at
least, one more in the Western Athletic Conference tournament. The
Frogs have already beaten three of the four remaining teams on
their regular-season schedule, including UNLV.
</P>
<P>
   So the way Petersen has it figured, the Frogs could be looking
at 17 victories and then maybe a shot at a bid to the Women's
National Invitation Tournament.
</P>
<P>
   It's a thought that was so ludicrous a couple of years ago that
Petersen, the perpetual optimist, is even a little nervous in
saying it.
</P>
<P>
   The Horned Frogs had gone 91-287 in 14 seasons in Division I
before Petersen arrived for the 1996-97 season. SMU coach Rhonda
Rompola witnessed some of the lean years.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like night and day,'' Rompola said. ``It's a team that
when they step on the floor, no matter who they're playing, they
think they can win. You didn't get that feeling from their teams a
couple of years ago.''
</P>
<P>
   So when the Frogs step on the floor tonight, it will be with the
knowledge they can make history and the belief that this isn't the
last rabbit out there waiting to be chased.
</P>
<P>
   ``Fourteen is just one of the many things we're hoping to do,''
Amy Sutton said. ``I think we're ready to finish this season
strong.''
</P>
<P>
   One WAC-ky wabbit at a time.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
