<SLUG> BC-SCHOOL-REPORT-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PANEL: LOS ANGELES SCHOOL BOARD MUST CHANGE ITS WAYS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
BY DAVID R. BAKER  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES -- Laying blame for Los Angeles' battered
educational system squarely on the school board, a group of
high-profile civic leaders will issue a long-awaited report today
challenging the members to fundamentally change the way they work.
</P>
<P>
   ``The culture and operations of the board, as a whole, are
dysfunctional and undermine the efforts of even highly capable
people,'' reads the report by the Committee on Effective School
Governance.
</P>
<P>
   The board must cease micromanaging schools Superintendent Ruben
Zacarias, a persistent problem that undercuts his authority, spawns
endless meetings and distracts board members from more serious
issues, according to the report.
</P>
<P>
   The board should craft with Zacarias a cohesive, long-term plan
to raise student achievement, approve it by the end of the summer
and then let the superintendent implement it without interference.
</P>
<P>
   ``Give the power to the CEO and get out of his way,'' said
committee member Antonia Hernandez, president and general counsel
of the Mexican American Legal Defense and Educational Fund.
</P>
<P>
   The report will be released at a news conference this morning.
Committee members presented it Wednesday to Daily News editors and
reporters on the condition that they not discuss it with board
members or others before the news conference.
</P>
<P>
   The report marks the high-powered committee's entrance into the
fray of local education reform.
</P>
<P>
   With members drawn from some of the city's most prominent civic,
business and educational institutions -- including the Urban
League, Salomon Smith Barney and USC -- the committee was formed in
the fall to push for change in the mammoth Los Angeles Unified
School District but has taken no firm positions until now.
</P>
<P>
   Even before it announced its intentions, the group had the
attention of Board of Education members, who already were facing
efforts to break up the school district and Mayor Richard Riordan's
initiative to elect a new board majority. School board members
noted their close relationships with many people on the committee
and hoped the new group would become an ally rather than another
foe.
</P>
<P>
   The committee's report takes pains to avoid attacking individual
board members, saying that all seem well-intentioned. Committee
members said Wednesday that the district has made some progress in
improving education, with student test scores slowly rising.
</P>
<P>
   The committee also pointedly declined to back specific
candidates for the April school board elections, an idea discussed
in the fall.
</P>
<P>
   But the report still gives a bruising assessment of the board's
performance, saying it operates without a clear mission or
understanding of its role.
</P>
<P>
   ``The school board does not have an overall plan for student
achievement,'' said committee Co-Chairman Harold Williams,
president emeritus of the J. Paul Getty Trust. ``Its activities
aren't coherent, and it gets into things it shouldn't.''
</P>
<P>
   Specifically, the report says, the board second-guesses the
superintendent, interfering with his ability to run the district's
operations. Board members routinely intercede in such personnel
matters as transfers and promotions that should be handled by
Zacarias, it says.
</P>
<P>
   ``You hear it throughout the system -- you hear about
individuals being protected by school board members,'' Williams
said. ``That undermines accountability.''
</P>
<P>
   As perhaps the most glaring example of micromanagement, the
report criticizes the board's decision to reopen contract
negotiations with the district's unions over Zacarias' strong
objections.
</P>
<P>
   Board members also waste time, the report says, by reviewing any
construction expense greater than $50,000, a tiny fraction of the
district's $6.6 billion budget. Instead, the board should leave
such projects to district staffers and create a reliable,
independent auditing procedure to make sure they don't run awry.
</P>
<P>
   Although committee members praise the board for trying to
implement reforms, they say the board seems to make many
commitments without coordinating them.
</P>
<P>
   ``Without a strategic plan to guide priorities, schools are
often asked to pursue conflicting goals, such as expanding
libraries, labs, and parent centers, and implementing
state-mandated class-size reductions -- which require the same,
limited available space,'' the report says.
</P>
<P>
   To reverse the situation, the district needs a broad, three- to
five-year plan concentrating on a few achievable, measurable goals,
the report says. The board must give its superintendent the power
needed to implement that plan, including authority over collective
bargaining agreements and the ability to reconstitute failing
schools, the committee argues.
</P>
<P>
   Committee members said Wednesday that they wanted the school
board to begin work on such a plan in July -- after any new board
members elected in April join the panel -- and approve it within 60
days. The committee also will call on all school board candidates
to pledge to implement the report's reforms.
</P>
<P>
   ``Whoever is elected come July, we're going to be asking, Where
is the plan?'' Hernandez said.
</P>
<P>
   For its part, the committee will host a series of meetings with
parents, teachers and other community members seeking input on its
report. A final copy will be presented to the board in July.
</P>
<P>
   Williams said he did not know what the committee would do should
the school board ignore or fail to act on its recommendations. But
in light of growing public frustration over the state of Los
Angeles' schools, he hoped board members would see the need for
such radical change.
</P>
<P>
   ``Board members have to realize, this may be their last
chance,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   X X X &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
