<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-17 23:51 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9732 &Cx1f; tic-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MONTINI-COLUMN-AZR &LR;      02-17 0692
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MONTINI-COLUMN-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TO PC OR NOT TO PC IS THE QUESTION 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By E.J. MONTINI  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   a week since I got the hot ``tip'' about discrimination against
students at Shadow Mountain High School, and the young man on the
telephone wanted to know why I hadn't done anything about it.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was officially sanctioned,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know,'' he's told. ``I spoke to the principal about it.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's racism! Doesn't that bother you, man?'' he said, his
anguished voice rising in hope of unearthing some shred of human
decency and fair play.
</P>
<P>
   ``No,'' he was told.
</P>
<P>
   Several parents also called. And other students.
</P>
<P>
   It was bigotry, they all said, the kind of blatant bias based on
skin color that people like me are supposed to expose, to hold up
for public ridicule and condemnation.
</P>
<P>
   ``You would write about it if the situation were reversed,'' one
parent told me. ``And the TV people would be all over it, too. It
would be a BIG story all over the country. Can you imagine?''
</P>
<P>
   If the situation were reversed, the story would go something
like this:
</P>
<P>
   White students at Shadow Mountain High School were invited to
listen to a speech by a successful White man in connection with an
ongoing series of school-sanctioned programs celebrating White
History Month. Pizza was served at the event. No Black students
were invited.
</P>
<P>
   And, yeah, every hack in town, me included, would have jumped
it.
</P>
<P>
   But it didn't happen that way.
</P>
<P>
   It involved Black History Month.
</P>
<P>
   Administrators at overwhelmingly White Shadow Mountain arranged
for a principal at another high school, a successful
African-American man, to speak to Black students at the Shadow
Mountain. About 50 attended, Principal Connie Liddle told me. Free
pizza was served.
</P>
<P>
   The event was followed, almost immediately, by whining.
</P>
<P>
   ``It never occurred to me it would be taken that way,'' said
Principal Liddle. ``It was really very much of a surprise.''
</P>
<P>
   The principal's office took complaints. The newspaper. Talk
radio stations. From behind the high walls of their red-tiled
enclaves in north Phoenix, lily-white crusaders stormed forth,
armed with the swords of self-righteousness and the shields of
moral indignation.
</P>
<P>
   They believed the attention to Black History Month had gone too
far. It was political correctness in the extreme, they said, and
they were determined to fight it _ with even MORE political
correctness.
</P>
<P>
   Which would be silly if it weren't so unnecessary.
</P>
<P>
   For most kids, I'd guess the only thing worse than being
excluded from a Black History Month lecture _ or any speech about
history _ is being ``invited'' to such a lecture.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had calls from parents because the kids went home and said
it was unfair,'' Principal Liddle said. ``I've said to those
parents, `Apparently, I made a mistake.' Sometimes you do.
Sometimes you misjudge. If I erred, then I apologize.''
</P>
<P>
   Will administrators face the same problem on Cinco De Mayo? And
Columbus Day? And St. Patrick's Day?
</P>
<P>
   Will there be an uproar when non-members of the track team or
marching band or chess club aren't invited to a group meeting?
</P>
<P>
   ``I certainly will think twice before I do anything like that
again,'' Liddle said. ``All we can do is to try to enjoy each
other's differences, and to develop awareness as much as we can.''
</P>
<P>
   Speaking as a longtime White man, I might be able to provide
some insight into the expressed outrage.
</P>
<P>
   For the most part, we're a fair-minded, fair-skinned people. We
accept and even encourage minority groups who want to celebrate
their uniqueness.
</P>
<P>
   We've adapted to changes in public policy and personal conduct.
We've adjusted to alterations in language and lifestyles. But, even
we can be pushed too far, and in this case, I believe we we were.
</P>
<P>
   You can deny us our own special minority status, our own special
lingo, our own special history month. You can deny us access to any
lecture you want.
</P>
<P>
   But, when you start denying us free pizza . . . &QL; 
E.J. Montini can be reached at 444-8978 or at ed.montini(at)pni.com
via e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
